<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3228 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     03-21 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DON'T worry. Be happy. Whether Enron Field is only 90 percent
completed, or even 80, this diamond in the rough will be fit for
human occupancy. Not every nook and cranny may be painted or paved
or planted, but there will be baseball when the Yankees come to
town in the last days of March.
</P>
<P>
   The race to finish the ballpark at Union Station might even
offer a unique opportunity to demonstrate true Texas hospitality.
Remember those covered-dish suppers neighbors would bring to the
door when a family moved into a new home? This tradition is both
welcome and a way of easing the stress. The Astros deserve nothing
less.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of food, fans attending the opening of Enron Field may
wish to bring any heavy equipment or garden tool they happen to
have around the house _ a tractor, bulldozer, shovel, chainsaw,
hammer or pair of pliers.
</P>
<P>
   Upon further review, no additional contributions may be needed
from a sellout crowd of 42,500 fans. The voters showed they cared
three years ago by approving the funds that made the stadium
possible. Mi casa es su casa.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what you have been reading, hearing or seeing, there
is no cause for panic. The grass is looking lush. The roof opens
and closes, which is about all one can ask of a roof. The
concession stands will be serving and the players playing. There
will be baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Those with tickets in the left- or right-field boxes are advised
to bring a large glove. They may even want to consider renting a
spare outfielder. The seats are closer to the foul lines than any
these eyes have ever seen. Drayton McLane Jr. said he wanted an
intimate ballpark. He wanted the fans to see the action up close.
Drayton has kept his word, just short of selling seats behind
second base.
</P>
<P>
   Any minor inconvenience, such as being stuck in traffic
overnight, may be viewed as part of the opening experience. Go with
it. Not many stadiums or arenas have been built without a flaw or
early shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   You know about the Astrodome, which was perfect but for the fact
the fielders could not follow the ball in the daytime, with the
sun's glare reflected off the spidery ceiling. You know about the
problems in Seattle and Milwaukee, which do not lend themselves to
cheap jokes.
</P>
<P>
   So take Philadelphia, please. The night they opened the
Spectrum, part of the roof blew away. Just like that, the 76ers and
Flyers were playing in an outdoor arena.
</P>
<P>
   And when the first hockey game was played in Madison Square
Garden, some of the sight lines were so bad you needed a periscope
to see what was happening in the corners. Who designed this place,
the critics inquired, a German U-boat commander?
</P>
<P>
   When hockey came to Cleveland, they had to cancel opening night
because the ice machine didn't work. At least there was no slime in
the ice machine.
</P>
<P>
   But in all the history of stadium building, there was nothing to
equal the unending complaints about Candlestick Park. When the
general manager stopped by one afternoon to see how the
construction was going, he saw boxes and machinery flying through
the air and workers clinging to various beams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does the wind always blow like this?'' he asked one of the
workmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only between 1 and 5 in the afternoon,'' the laborer replied,
a time frame that did not bode well for day baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out the hill they leveled to fill in the parking lot
was what kept the winds from blowing when the site was first
surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   From the Candlestick press box, the writers discovered they
could see everything except home plate. The height of the
countertop and the placement of the chairs, which were bolted to
the floor, blocked any view of the batter, catcher and umpire.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the writers pestered the city to send out an engineer
to solve their plight. On the day he showed up, the Milwaukee
Braves were in town. When the engineer opened the door, what he saw
was the Braves' traveling secretary, 4-foot-2 Donald Davidson, the
original little big man, sitting on a stool, his legs dangling.
Donald had arrived early to update his stats. (Years later he
became a fixture with the Astros.)
</P>
<P>
   The engineer took one look, decided the writers had played a
tasteless trick at his expense, slammed the door and returned to
his office.
</P>
<P>
   If further encouragement is needed, there is the historic
example of Rice Stadium, with 70,000 seats, built at cost and in
nine months by Brown and Root, celebrating its 50th anniversary
this fall. They were still pouring concrete with three days to go.
The scoreboard was hooked up two hours before the kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the stadium would be ready, George Brown paused, then
uttered his famous line: ``Is it a day game or a night game?''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
