<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3229 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-LSU-HNS &LR;      03-21 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LSU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
LSU coach John Brady sounds like a man desperately seeking
attention when he blares, ``What's happened at LSU this year is the
greatest story in college basketball.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   After all, college basketball has produced no shortage of
inspiring, entertaining and courageous tales this season.
</P>
<P>
   But Brady's desire for a pat on the back is not unmerited. LSU
has undergone one of the top turnarounds in the country, going from
last place in its division in 1998-99 to a tie for first place in
the Southeastern Conference this season and, after wins over
Southeast Missouri State and Texas this past weekend, a trip to the
Sweet 16, the first for the Tigers since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, LSU went 12-15 and only 4-12 in SEC play. A year
later, the Tigers are 28-5, the second-most wins in school history.
Next up Thursday is Wisconsin at the NCAA Tournament's West
Regional in Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why I came to play for coach Brady,'' sophomore
sensation Stromile Swift said. ``I knew LSU had a good tradition,
and I believed in the coaches. I believed they would get good
players here. They have done an unbelievable job of bringing in
talent to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Swift, a McDonald's All-American in high school, was the big
coup for Brady's staff. The Shreveport native came to LSU despite
its probation for violations in recruiting Lester Earl, now at
Kansas, and its measly 9-18 record during Swift's senior season in
high school.
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't know about the probation matter, which has
limited the Tigers to nine scholarship players this season, with
only one scholarship to give for next year. But Swift said he
thought his arrival could help turn the team around.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, LSU posted six straight non-winning seasons before
this year's run. Four of those losing campaigns came under Dale
Brown, who coached the Tigers for 25 years, and two came under
Brady, who was a lowly 21-33 prior to this season's miraculous
turnaround. And many of those wins came against low-level
competition in non-conference play.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers were 6-26 in the SEC in Brady's first two seasons.
Tiger Town was not a happy place to be.
</P>
<P>
   But the turnaround has been swift. Only two of the Tigers'
starters _ senior center Jabari Smith and junior Brian Beshara _
were even on campus at the beginning of last season. Swift was
sitting out his first semester to get a qualifying American College
Test score, Torris Bright was in high school, and Lamont Roland was
in junior college.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have the Tigers turned things around, they have done it
against good competition. This year's squad has beaten seven teams
that were ranked in the Top 25, two more than LSU had ever
previously beaten in one season. A win over Oklahoma State in
December was the Tigers' first over a ranked opponent in 24 tries
dating to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And the Tigers handled the pressure of the NCAA Tournament quite
well, thank you. Southeast Missouri hung around long enough to
threaten an upset, but LSU made big plays down the stretch to claim
a 64-61 win.
</P>
<P>
   No. 5 seed Texas gave the fourth-seeded Tigers a scare as well,
sitting tied at 60 with three minutes to play. But LSU responded
with an inspired closing effort, highlighted by a sensational block
by Swift, to claim a 72-67 win.
</P>
<P>
   They have navigated previously uncharted waters with ease, and
according to Smith, the Tigers have seen enough to not be fazed by
any of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we've been stepping into the deep waters and all that
kind of water all year,'' Smith said. ``We're kind of used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 45-year-old Brady swam the waters at Samford, where he is
its all-time winningest coach, for six years before coming to LSU.
</P>
<P>
   Brady originally signed a five-year contract, but that was
extended an extra year following his first season. LSU athletic
director Joe Dean announced in February that he plans to seek
another extension and a hefty pay raise for Brady, who reportedly
ranks 10th in the SEC in pay, that will last through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Brady has us believing in ourselves,'' Smith said. ``We
had a different attitude coming in this year than we had last year.
We knew we were getting ready to make some noise toward the top of
the conference. A lot of other people didn't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a meteoric rise for the Tigers, who began the season
ranked No. 129 among Division I programs in the Jeff Sagarin
computer ratings. By January, LSU was in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until March before the Tigers moved into the top 10 of
the Associated Press poll, so Brady's suggestion that the media
were a bit sluggish in catching on to his Tigers' tale is accurate.
But LSU fans were a little slow in coming around as well.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful awaited the team's arrival from a win at Auburn,
which clinched a share of the SEC regular-season title. Nearly 200
were on hand in the wee hours Sunday, when the Tigers arrived from
a triumphant weekend in the first two rounds of the NCAA Tournament
at Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders how many will be on hand to pat Brady and his troops
on their backs next week, should LSU advance to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the LSU story is indeed one of the best in college
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
