<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3230 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAA-HNS &LR;      03-21 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
You saw this coming, right?
<TEXT>
<P>
   You saw Wisconsin over Arizona, North Carolina over Stanford,
Seton Hall over Temple, Miami over Ohio State, and Tulsa over
Cincinnati, right? (Actually, you should have seen Tulsa over
Cincinnati.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course you did. You also bought Microsoft when it was in the
teens and sold Procter &AMP; Gamble when it was still in triple digits.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of us, the back of that tear-stained NCAA
Tournament bracket that looked so promising Saturday morning will
make a good grocery list. Advil sales surged in Bracketville over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody will point to all the high seeds losing,'' said Ohio
State coach Jim O'Brien, whose No. 3 Buckeyes lost to No. 6 Miami
in the South, ``but what it tells me is there are so many good
teams out there. You look at the 32 teams left after the first
round, and it was probably as good a 32 teams in the history of the
Tournament. There were some tough, tough games in the second
round.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the effect of all the favorites winning on Thursday and
Friday was better second-round games. For the first time since the
64-team field was instituted in 1985, the top five seeds in all
four regions won in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   No high-seeded team got a second walkover. Of those 20 teams
seeded 1-5 that advanced in the first round, 12 were bounced by
Sunday night. On consecutive days, the one, two and three seeds
from the West and South regions were sent home.
</P>
<P>
   There are more No. 6 seeds around (Miami, Purdue and UCLA) than
No. 1 seeds (Duke and Michigan State). There are the same number of
10th-seeded teams (Gonzaga and Seton Hall) as No. 1 seeds.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1981, two No. 1 seeds _ Arizona and
Stanford _ failed to reach the Sweet 16. And Duke, the top overall
seed, barely survived Sunday against Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to complain about where we were seeded,'' said
Tulsa coach Bill Self, whose Golden Hurricane seemed way too low at
No. 7. ``What you have in college basketball is a situation where
there are a number of really good teams. On any day, under the
right circumstances, a seven can beat a two, an eight can beat a
one. I'm not sure there are that many upsets in this thing
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   You want parity? For the first time since 1985, when the
Tournament was expanded to 64 teams, there is at least one team
seeded one through eight still alive after two rounds.
Interestingly, this is the first time since 1996 that fewer than
three teams seeded 10-16 remain.
</P>
<P>
   Of the top 12 seeds in the Tournament, only five remain. That's
the fewest survivors among the top dozen since the current format
came into being in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Teams given up for dead _ like North Carolina, UCLA, Seton Hall
and Tennessee _ are alive. Teams that seemingly never had a shot _
like Wisconsin and Miami _ are ticking.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, then, this has to be the wildest Tournament ever. The
year with the most surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   Using a formula that adds up the seeds of teams advancing to the
Sweet 16, this year's total of 85 is only the fourth-highest since
1985. The wackiest year was 1985, when the total was 89. In 1990
and '99, the total was 88.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this year's high total interesting is that there are
so few double-digit seeds remaining. Only the two No. 10s are still
alive. There isn't much left at the top or the bottom _ merely a
ton of teams seeded in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of second-guessing, last year's Tournament should
have been a tip-off that the way to figure the bracket is to look
for strong, underrated teams seeded in the middle or high end. And
beware vulnerable teams among the top four seeds _ Stanford,
Maryland, Illinois and Cincinnati come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there should have been neon lights around No. 6
UCLA playing a vastly overrated No. 3 Maryland. Tulsa was seeded
too low at No. 7, and the Golden Hurricane was a good choice
against a Kenyon Martin-less No. 2 Cincinnati in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga wrongly got no respect from the Selection Committee for
either its NCAA showing last season or its regular-season effort
this year. The Zags at No. 10 were a good upset pick for a couple
of wins, especially since No. 2 St. John's had no inside presence.
</P>
<P>
   Both Tennessee (No. 4 South) and Florida (No. 5 East) had
success in the tough Southeastern Conference. Ditto LSU (No. 4
West). The committee sold the SEC way short in the seeding.
</P>
<P>
   The real surprises so far have been Seton Hall, Purdue, North
Carolina and Wisconsin. Of those teams, Wisconsin is the only real
Cinderella. Among those who have made it this far, the Badgers had
to be the team least likely to make the Sweet 16 when the brackets
were announced.
</P>
<P>
   For a team with no basketball history, the Badgers look almost
like a team from another era _ the 1950s, say. They play a
deliberate motion offense and tenacious defense. Their game is most
assuredly below the rim. You almost expect Gene Hackman to be
coaching instead of Dick Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   They finished sixth in the Big Ten, playing only .500 in the
conference. If Wisconsin takes out LSU, don't be surprised if it
advances to the Final Four. Talk about setting college basketball
back a couple of decades. Nothing wrong with the Badgers' style of
basketball _ if you're a purist.
</P>
<P>
   However, most people watching the games this time of year
aren't. You can rest assured that outside of Wisconsin fans and a
number of high school coaches who preach fundamentals, not many
people are pulling for the Badgers.
</P>
<P>
   Two points are clear after the carnage of top seeds over the
weekend. First, the Selection Committee doesn't have this seeding
business down to an exact science. For instance, did the committee
perhaps give the Pacific-10 a little too much credit?
</P>
<P>
   A case could have been made on Selection Sunday that neither
Arizona nor Stanford deserved a No. 1 seed _ Arizona because it was
without injured center Loren Woods; Stanford because it had lost
two of its final three games in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, both were seeded No. 1, and both were bounced. Parlay
those defeats with No. 7 seed Oregon's first-round loss to Seton
Hall, and it's clear the committee didn't have a handle on the
Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the whole seeding process might need an overhaul.
Perhaps there is too much reliance on the Ratings Percentage Index
and strength of schedule and too little on what is actually
happening on the court, especially in the final two weeks before
the Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious we can do better,'' said Duke coach Mike
Krzyzewski. ``I'm not blaming the people that do it. I think the
people that do it on the Selection Committee try to do the very
best possible job they can.''
</P>
<P>
   The second point that's clear? When filling out your
second-chance Sweet 16 bracket, it might be better to pick winners
based on what city you would rather live in.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
