<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3231 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BAGWELL-HN     03-21 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BAGWELL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ When talking about the Big Three who now reside
in the National League Central, it's understandable why Jeff
Bagwell gets overlooked.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark McGwire rewrote the record book, in the process redefining
the term power hitter, with his 70-home-run season for the St.
Louis Cardinals in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa hasn't been far behind Big Mac with
129 home runs the past two seasons while beating McGwire for the
1998 Most Valuable Player Award.
</P>
<P>
   And how many times have we seen Ken Griffey Jr. _ the newest
addition to the Power Company after his offseason acquisition by
the Cincinnati Reds _ pose as he follows through with his crisp,
perfect swing?
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   His home-run totals aren't as impressive, mostly the result of
playing his entire career in the pitcher-friendly Astrodome. He'll
also be the first to say he wrote the how-not-to book with his
unorthodox batting stance.
</P>
<P>
   Fans might crave the long ball, but across the board the Astros
superstar is on par with _ or slightly better than _ McGwire, Sosa
and Griffey in almost every other major offensive category:
</P>
<P>
   He has batted .304 each of the last two seasons, which happens
to be his career average.
</P>
<P>
   He has hit 20 or more home runs in each of the last seven
seasons, including 42 last season, one off his career high. He's
the only Astro to reach 40 homers in a season.
</P>
<P>
   He has driven in more than 110 runs five times, dating to his
MVP season in 1994, when he led the NL with 116 in a season cut
short by seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He became the first full-time first baseman to reach 30 home
runs and 30 stolen bases in a season in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven major-leaguers who have hit 40 homers and stolen 30
bases in a season, only Bagwell and Barry Bonds have done it more
than once.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more of a complete player. He has been one the quietest
highly productive players in baseball the last seven years,''
Astros hitting instructor Tom McCraw said. ``He hasn't busted 70
home runs, but he's sure been steady with 30 or 40 home runs,
stolen bases and runs scored. He has no reason to take a back seat
to Sosa or McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   Being in the background is fine with Bagwell, who has thrived in
a clubhouse of unassuming, hard-working players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself a `legitimate' power hitter,'' said
Bagwell, the Astros' all-time leader in home runs (263), RBIs
(961), extra-base hits (598) and walks (885).
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I hit for power, but I'm not like Mac and those guys who
are going to hit 10 home runs in a month. That's a lot of home
runs. I've hit (more than) 40 twice and 39 once, but it's hard to
maintain doing that. The legitimate power hitters are the guys who
hit the ball so far and are consistent with it. Those are the guys
who impress me.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Bagwell's teammates believe he would be included among
baseball's big bashers had he not played nearly a decade in the
Dome. Of Bagwell's 42 home runs last season, 30 came on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baggy would be hitting 50 for the last five years if we played
at any ballpark other than the Astrodome,'' teammate Craig Biggio
said. ``I'll take Jeff's numbers over any of those guys any given
day. That's not a knock on anybody, but I've played with the guy
and I know what he can do offensively and defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, 40-homer players are commonplace. The bar has been
raised, with Roger Maris' seemingly unreachable 61-homer plateau
shattered four times in the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Before '98, Sosa was recognized as a huge talent with big-time
pure home-run power, although not at the level he is today after
hitting 66 home runs two years ago and 63 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think his appeal is as glamorous,'' Astros manager
Larry Dierker said of Bagwell. ``I think 65 or 70 home runs brings
a certain element of grandeur.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1996-99, Bagwell has a higher batting average (.302) and
on-base percentage (.439) while playing more games than McGwire,
Sosa and Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   He is a lifetime .304 hitter, 37 points higher than Sosa (.267)
and 35 points higher than McGwire (.269). Bagwell's career on-base
percentage is .416. His Gold Glove defense at first base also
attracts attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question I have is how you get more consistent than what
he has been in his major-league career,'' McCraw said. ``He has
been as consistent a power hitter as anybody in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's teammates are also impressed with how he overcomes his
typically slow starts to still finish with a .300 average and more
than 40 home runs and 110 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you get a first baseman that hits 40 home runs
consistently the last five or seven years, that's something to talk
about,'' said pitcher Jose Lima. ``I've never seen anybody start
slow and still finish with 40 home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   McCraw recalls, however, telling Bagwell there wasn't much he
could do to help with his unusual batting style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `I don't know if I can help you with that, but
we're going to try and maybe we can work something out,''' McCraw
said. ``It's very unique, very different. It's something I've never
seen in 40 years of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said, ``He doesn't have a graceful swing. He bludgeons
the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell doesn't regret the lack of attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston usually does not get much attention,'' Bagwell said.
``I don't put myself in that realm anyway. People come to watch
Griffey, Sosa and McGwire. I'm not so sure people come to watch me
play, not to the magnitude of those guys. All their accolades and
all the publicity is well-deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
