<HEADLINE>
LEE'S SUMMIT PATHOLOGIST APOLOGIZES FOR IGNORING CONGRESSIONAL
SUBPOENA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the brink of a possible U.S. House vote to hold
him in contempt, Lee's Summit, Mo., pathologist Miles Jones has
apologized to Congress for ignoring a subpoena to testify about
fetal tissue marketing.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter, Jones also for the first time denied allegations
that he sold aborted fetal tissue and organs for a profit, in
violation of federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, whose fetal tissue business is under an FBI
investigation, said the last two weeks of scrutiny by the media and
members of Congress had ``resulted in significant personal and
professional ruination'' for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I now live in terror,'' Jones wrote in a letter
dated Friday and sent to Rep. Tom Bliley, a Virginian Republican
who is chairman of the House Committee on Commerce. Last week the
committee voted 34-0 to hold Jones in contempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please be assured that I had no intention of undermining the
authority of Congress and do not want my actions to represent any
more than a personal failure of judgment,'' Jones wrote. ``I take
full responsibility for my actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he would be willing now to appear before any
committee of Congress ``without hesitation.''
</P>
<P>
   That may not be enough to keep him from facing contempt action
in the House this week, said Steve Schmidt, spokesman for Bliley
and other Republicans who control the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee plans to move forward with contempt charges,''
Schmidt said. If the House votes for contempt, the Justice
Department would decide whether to prosecute.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 47, was served a subpoena March 1 to appear at the March
9 hearing of the health and environment subcommittee. He did not
respond to the subpoena or to numerous calls from staff regarding
the subpoena, Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Jones wrote: ``Unfortunately, my schedule was
completely filled, and I had patient care responsibilities during
the period requested by the subpoena. With limited time available,
I was unable to arrange for coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he would not seek a lawyer and would submit to the
will of Congress on the contempt proceedings. Jones has not
responded to numerous calls from The Kansas City Star for comment
on the subpoena and the fetal tissue investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Fetal tissue and organs can be donated and fees charged only for
reasonable facilities, staff and shipping costs.
</P>
<P>
   For about 10 weeks in 1998, Jones had a contract with
Comprehensive Health of Overland Park, Kan., the affiliated clinic
of Planned Parenthood of Kansas and Mid-Missouri, to extract tissue
from aborted fetuses. He has done business in many states.
</P>
<P>
   On March 8, in a hidden camera interview conducted by an ABC
News producer who posed as a potential investor in Jones' business,
Jones said he could make up to $50,000 a week and that a brain, a
liver or a kidney can bring ``what you can sell it for.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Jones said his secretly recorded comments on
national television ``have reinforced the opinion that I sold fetal
tissue for valuable consideration'' in conflict with the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing could be further from the truth,'' Jones wrote. But he
does not explain the numerous comments he made in the ABC
interview, shown on the 20//20 program, that the fetal tissue
business could be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in the letter that would ease the concerns on
the committee about the undercover work of 20//20,'' Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Johnson, a spokesman for the National Right to Life
Committee Inc., said a lot of unanswered questions remained about
Jones and his business.
</P>
<P>
   ``What strikes me is that these matters need to be investigated
with Dr. Jones under oath,'' Johnson said. ``The questions need to
be answered under the penalty of perjury.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
