<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT AND MCI WORLDCOM ADDRESS CRITICS OF PROPOSED MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sprint Corp and MCI WorldCom Inc. on Monday filed a joint reply
with federal regulators to address comments and petitions that were
submitted to deny their proposed merger.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen parties, including competitors, labor groups and
individuals, weighed in with formal comments on the deal during the
public comment period at the Federal Communications Commission. The
commission also received a slew of letters from individuals, small
businesses, consumer advocates _ even a church.
</P>
<P>
   Critics think the merger would create too much concentration in
the long-distance and Internet markets, allowing the new WorldCom
to control prices and quality of service.
</P>
<P>
   Many have urged regulators to deny the merger or subject it to
strict conditions, such as the forced sale of some businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In their filing, Sprint and MCI WorldCom focused on the
long-distance and Internet markets and tried to demonstrate that
``there's no basis to believe that the merger ... will jeopardize
vibrant competition in either sector,'' said Jonathan Sallet, chief
policy counsel for MCI WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Sallet and Vonya McCann, Sprint senior
vice president of federal external affairs, summarized the 150-page
filing and stressed points that they said were supported by
independent studies:
</P>
<P>
   - More than 98 percent of households nationwide are served by at
least three carriers that own their own network facilities, with
more than 90 percent being served by four or more such carriers.
</P>
<P>
   - More than a third of customers who switched from MCI WorldCom
or Sprint in a 12-month period switched to an emerging carrier
rather than to AT&AMP;T Corp., MCI WorldCom or Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   - More than a dozen emerging carriers provide the full panoply
of advanced voice and data services that large businesses need,
contrary to critics' claims that AT&AMP;T, Sprint and MCI WorldCom
dominate those markets.
</P>
<P>
   - The regional Bell companies intend _ when permitted by
regulators _ to enter the four states that account for more than
half the country's long-distance traffic. (Those states are
California, Texas, Florida and New York.) Reductions in
long-distance rates by the Bell companies would compel traditional
carriers to lower their rates further.
</P>
<P>
   - Fiberoptic capacity has doubled since 1995 and is still
increasing dramatically, allowing competitors easy access to the
Internet market and preventing any company from dominating the
market or controlling prices.
</P>
<P>
   - New technology allows Internet service providers to route
their traffic over the network providing the best service, which
would undermine the new WorldCom if it provided poor service.
</P>
<P>
   Sallet and McCann also said the new WorldCom would be
regulators' best hope for bringing a new, competitive
communications platform to American consumers in addition to their
phone and cable providers.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint and MCI WorldCom have invested heavily in fixed wireless
spectrum across the country, buying companies that used the
licenses to provide wireless cable television services.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy is to use that spectrum to deliver voice and
high-speed data services to consumers and businesses, particularly
in remote areas where landline services can be uneconomical.
</P>
<P>
   The companies hope to receive approval for their merger from the
Department of Justice, which examines the deal from an antitrust
perspective, in late spring. The FCC is expected to render a
decision in the second half of 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
