<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPBROWN-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
60'S RIGHTS LEADER IS ARRESTED IN DEATH OF SHERIFF'S DEPUTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: The following story is an added starter on The New York
Times front page.) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three days after he was accused of the shooting death
of a sheriff's deputy, the former civil rights leader who was known
as H. Rap Brown was arrested on Monday night in a rural Alabama
field after an exchange of gunfire in the small town of Whitehall,
police officials said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now a Muslim cleric known as Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, the
fugitive had been the subject of a nationwide manhunt since Friday,
when a Fulton County Sheriff's deputy said Al-Amin had shot him and
another deputy as they tried to serve him with an arrest warrant
Thursday night on minor charges.
</P>
<P>
   One of the deputies, Ricky Kinchen, died Friday afternoon after
receiving several gunshot wounds from a high-powered assault rifle.
Aldranon English, the deputy who identified Al-Amin, was still
hospitalized with lesser injuries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Monday night, Atlanta Police Chief
Beverly Harvard said that Al-Amin was captured by federal marshals,
FBI agents and deputies of the Lowndes County, Ala., sheriff's
department. Whitehall is a small town between Selma and
Montgomery. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In interviews broadcast on local television stations, Bill
Imfeld, an FBI agent based in Mobile, said that federal agents had
begun looking for Al-Amin in Whitehall all day after learning that
he had friends and associates there from his days of association
with the Black Panther party in the 1960s. After knocking on doors,
several agents were fired on near a house at about 5:30 p.m., and
then called in backup officers, Imfeld said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and local law enforcement agencies then flooded the area
with officers, helicopters and dogs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When the dogs were turned loose, they flushed out H. Rap
Brown, and he ran right into the arms of a waiting sheriff,''
Imfeld said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harvard said that several people in the Whitehall area were
detained on the possibility that they may have been harboring
Al-Amin as a fugitive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She said a handgun was found in the field where Al-Amin was
caught, but she did not know if it had been used in the Atlanta
shooting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officers did not find the assault rifle that had been used in
the shooting, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Sheriff Jacqueline Barrett described herself as
``ecstatic'' that Al-Amin had been caught before the funeral, which
is set for Tuesday, of her deputy.
</P>
<P>
   English, was extremely relieved that the suspect had been
caught, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight I can sleep,'' she quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin was in custody in the FBI office in Montgomery, Imfeld
said, adding that he would likely be charged on Tuesday and then
transported to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard would not comment on reports that the FBI may have
tracked down Al-Amin through the use of electronic wiretaps and
cellular phone transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin had been underground for several years in the 1960s and
1970s after being accused of inciting a riot and transporting a gun
across state lines while under indictment. FBI agents had feared he
might stay in hiding for some time because of his experience on the
run, and because of what they called a large network of supporters
across the country who could hide him.
</P>
<P>
   He disappeared after the Thursday night shooting, leaving behind
a bewildered flock of followers in the largely black Atlanta
neighborhood called the West End, who said Al-Amin had renounced
violence when he formed the mosque and began working with community
groups to clean up the area.
</P>
<P>
   A blood trail had been found from the site of the shooting to a
nearby vacant house, but authorities were unable to track him from
there.
</P>
</TEXT>
