A3236 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-NADER-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRO     03-21 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NADER-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SACRAMENTO, NADER SAYS OUTSIDER STATUS IS HIS STRENGTH
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SACRAMENTO _ Consumer activist and Green Party presidential
candidate Ralph Nader said Monday he is the only candidate left for
people who are disgruntled with the political system.
<P>
   The collapse of major-party candidates John McCain and Bill
Bradley, along with the disarray in the Reform Party, show that
there is room for another candidate, Nader told reporters before a
speech to the California Nurses Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the theme that unites both conservative and liberal
voters is that they are losing control rapidly over everything that
matters to them,'' Nader said. ``That's what we appeal to _ the
recovery of control so that we have a government of, by, and for
the people instead a government of Exxon, by General Motors and for
the Duponts.''
</P>
<P>
   America has been taken over by corporations that are only
concerned with the bottom line, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our democracy is being highjacked by giant corporations that
are controlling everything from government to the media, the
workplace, even exploiting childhood with commercial
entertainment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to show that there are a lot of solutions in this
country that are not being applied to serious problems,'' he said.
``And that can occur if we have stronger democracy and new
progressive political movement.''
</P>
<P>
   And Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush are
part of the problem, not a solution, Nader said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting a broad-based, progressive political movement
to end once and for all the limited choice Americans have between
Tweedle Dum Republican and Tweedle Dee Democrat, both in hock to
big corporate interests and money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nader said he plans to campaign across the country, hopes to
raise several million dollars and would like to qualify for federal
matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   In the state's March 7 open primary, Nader received 101,165
votes, or about 1 percent. There were 108,904 registered Green
Party members as of February 7, according to the Secretary of
State's office.
</P>
<P>
   Nader received less than 1 percent of the vote when he ran for
president in 1996. He spent less than $5,000 of his own money on
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to about 250 nurses, Nader said the country's health
care system is in shambles, and called for a universal system
similar to one in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``The HMOs are destabilizing themselves by their own greed, by
their manhandling of the professions in the medical and nursing
areas, and their abuse of consumers,'' he said. ``I think we are in
a real transition period here that gives us a great opportunity to
recast our health care system into a nonprofit mode and expand to
universal health care.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nader said he does not see either Gore or Bush taking on the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to have their fingers to the wind to see what
kind of public demand is out there,'' he said. ``Right now I see
piecemeal and complex proposals by two politicians who are afraid
to take on the big drug companies and the big HMOs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
