<SLUG> BC-BKC-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRITTY GONZAGA RULES OVER ITS IN-STATE BIG BROTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Can't imagine the Kingdome looking any worse next
Monday morning than my NCAA men's basketball tournament bracket
does now.
</P>
<P>
   But after stepping through the dust, broken concrete and twisted
re-bar of the bracket carnage, there is a rose: Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's been there for two years. That might qualify it
as a weed, at least in the eyes of Washington and Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of the college hoops world wants to pinch the
Zags' cheeks between thumb and forefinger and exclaim,
``wudgie-wudgie-wudgie!'' they are a mortifying embarrassment for
their state brethren in the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   Bad enough that a 4,000-student school in a second-tier
conference can beat the bejeezus out of the Huskies and Cougars,
then make madness from a No. 10 tourney perch.
</P>
<P>
   But doing it mostly with in-state kids ... well, the bag has yet
to be made big or thick enough to hide the chagrined faces of the
Huskies and Cougs.
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it, the state of Washington in the Pac-10
this season gave new meaning to the term subterranean. The Huskies
tied for eighth at 5-13 (10-20 overall) and the Cougs were last
(1-17, 6-22). Included in each season was a 10-point loss to the
Zags.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen victories between the state's high-profile jock
factories while the Zags are at 26 and counting must be a little
like Garth Brooks winning the Grammy for best new hip-hop artist.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga's small size, high tuition and academic standards and
remoteness (wait: I-90 does go through Spokane, so civilization is
reachable) would seem to be a recipe for Division I mediocrity.
Instead, the program flourishes while the Huskies and Cougars
languish.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason some smaller private schools can do well in
basketball is because there's no football program to drain athletic
department resources. St. John's, St. Bonaventure, Iona and Seton
Hall are among tourney teams this year that don't have campus
competition for the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest virtue for Gonzaga is it feeds well after the
big dogs eat, getting the most out of overlooked state kids. The
Pac-10 duo annually seems to lose a handful of elite players to
out-of-state programs, then keeps casting the net to California and
other national points where competition from basketball-serious
schools is more intense.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga, meanwhile, more than makes do with state leftovers.
Leading scorer Richie Frahm is from Battle Ground, near Vancouver.
Leading rebounder Casey Calvary is from Tacoma's Bellarmine.
Starting guard Mike Nilson, now injured, is from Seattle's
Shorecrest. Freshman forward Zach Gourde is from Vancouver's
Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Another four reserves are in-state, and floor leader Matt
Santangelo is from Portland. Next year, Prairie's Dan Dickau, a UW
transfer, figures to start at point guard.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies had six state players on the roster, but only
Ballard's Michael Johnson and Sammamish's Chris Walcott played a
lot, and Walcott was a walk-on.
</P>
<P>
   The state kids Washington missed on is a familiar story:
Stanford's Curtis Borchardt, Utah's Phil Cullen, USC's Brian
Scalabrine, San Jose State's Billy Landram and Oregon State's Jason
Heide, to name just a few double-figure scorers _ not to mention
struggling stars Jamal Crawford and Doug Wrenn, nor Arizona's
recent All-America guard, Jason Terry.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Huskies' collapse this year after consecutive
NCAA appearances, a historic trend has continued: In the past
half-century, Washington's nine tourney entries have coincided
exclusively with a quality 7-foot center.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1950s, it was Bob Houbregs. In 1976, it was James
Edwards. In the mid-80s, it was Christian Welp, ably aided by
Detlef Schrempf. And the previous two years, it was Todd
MacCulloch.
</P>
<P>
   Though it can be argued that a good big man will make any
Division I team a contender, the Huskies have never recruited well
enough to make it during the many ``short'' years between goliaths.
</P>
<P>
   That's a fact of life not only for current coach Bob Bender, but
predecessors Lynn Nance, Andy Russo and Marv Harshman. Without an
occasional sprinkling of galootism, the Huskies' tourney drought
probably would have gone back before TV shows starring Milton
Berle.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what would have happened had the Huskies not stumbled
onto the obscure MacCulloch, an ungainly, lightly recruited former
hockey player from Winnipeg. Every program gets lucky once in a
while, but Washington has shown little ability to flourish without
good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't a lack of in-state Division I talent _ nationally,
including UW, WSU, Gonzaga and Eastern Washington, 70 state kids
are playing at the top collegiate level this season.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, starting next year, will a bad gym be an excuse, because
Hec Ed's renovation should eliminate a big recruiting disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   Bender, who has demonstrated some strategic and recruiting
shortcomings, will definitely find his seat toasty next season. But
it can't be overlooked that Husky basketball mediocrity is almost
institutionalized. Whatever the causes of the UW travail, the rise
of Gonzaga has made the scrutiny more acute.
</P>
<P>
   Give Bender credit for a willingness to schedule the Zags every
year. But the results lately recall a mood 20 years ago, when the
Huskies were thrilled that another little Jesuit outfit, Seattle
University, gave up big-time basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Being given a can-o-whuppin' annually by the little brother
makes living in the state family real edgy.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
