r a BC-MTBE-KAN &LR;      03-21 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTBE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADMINISTRATION'S PURSUIT TO BAN GASOLINE ADDITIVE MAY BOOST
FARM INCOMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR, Knight Ridder Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The nation's breadbasket may ride a strong
economic boost from the Clinton administration's announcement
Monday that it will ban MTBE, the controversial gasoline additive.
</P>
<P>
   Although the additive cuts down on smog, officials said it has
caused widespread water pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious effect of the announcement will be an increased
demand for ethanol, the corn-derived fuel that could replace MTBE,
said Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could have a dramatic impact on farm programs and farm
income,'' Glickman told the press Monday at a joint conference with
EPA Adminstrator Carol Browner.
</P>
<P>
   First, they said, MTBE should be banned. Then Congress should
remove a Clean Air Act requirement that gasoline in areas with
serious air pollution contain at least 2 percent oxygen by weight.
Both MTBE and ethanol have been used to meet that requirement; they
both add oxygen to fuel to help it burn cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   Instead the Clinton administration wants to require a small
percentage of all gasoline to be made from renewable sources, such
as ethanol and other grain-derived fuels.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA proposed banning MTBE on its own, but the process could
take three years, Browner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Action by Congress is the fastest and best way to address the
problem,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of the nation's fuel is reformulated gasoline,
which includes more oxygen. Nearly 90 percent of that has MTBE,
used in 17 states and the District of Columbia. St. Louis is the
only area where the reformulated fuel is used in Missouri or
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE, actually, is in almost all gasoline, but in levels of only
3 percent to 8 percent. In reformulated gas, it's added by at least
twice those levels.
</P>
<P>
   Studies estimate thousands of community water wells in dozens of
states may be contaminated by MTBE, or methyl tertiarybutyl ether.
The problem is that MTBE is very soluble _ 30 times more so than
benzene, a common water contaminant related to gasoline. And MTBE
doesn't degrade as rapidly. All this makes cleaning up MTBE spills
more difficult and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The water pollution problem shouldn't be called a crisis,
Browner said, but it's a growing concern in many communities. Some
states, led by California, have already decided to ban the
additive. Missouri regulators had already said the fuel should not
be allowed here.
</P>
<P>
   The agricultural impact of today's announcement could reach
beyond corn growers, especially if the government requires the use
of more renewable fuels.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good news for our farmers, for our energy security and
for the environment,'' Glickman said.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri corn growers are happy to compete for the market, said
Gary Marshall, executive director of the Missouri Corn Growers
Association. But Marshall worries that partisan politics will
stymie the effort, especially because it is an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders said Monday that the Clinton administration's
turn toward ethanol was political and follows a Republican lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the timing of this looks political,'' said David
Israelite, director of political and governmental affairs for the
Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have pushed for some time to boost ethanol, said
Daryl Duwe, spokesman for the Missouri GOP. ``Farmers know who was
with them and who wasn't,'' he said. ``Republicans have been with
them for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall noted that just last week some Republicans introduced
legislation in Congress similar to the Clinton administration
proposal introduced Monday. ``There should be some common ground
here where we can craft some bipartisan solution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, on Monday, Missouri's four Republican House members
released a letter they sent to the administration in January urging
a commitment to ethanol. Rep. Jim Talent of Chesterfield, speaking
for those House members, said the administration's actions Monday
were clearly the right thing to do ``regardless of the motives.''
</P>
<P>
   As for consumers, the impact is less certain.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies had projected a ban of MTBE could increase
gasoline prices up to 5 cents a gallon. But Browner on Monday
predicted little impact on consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing the use of ethanol, Marshall added, could even reduce
gasoline prices. Corn prices, after all, are at an all-time low.
Federal tax incentives also boost ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   Ethanol is a steal right now,'' Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   For certain, ethanol has a major environmental advantage over
MTBE, Browner said, because it doesn't pose great water pollution
threats. But tests found that MTBE did more to reduce ozone than an
ethanol blend. The ethanol blend was more volatile, meaning
pollutants more easily waft into the air to form ozone, the main
ingredient of smog.
</P>
<P>
   But some oil companies have recently begun to produce fuel for
ethanol blends that isn't as volatile, Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw it happen in the last year in St. Louis,'' he said.
``And they did it at the same price or below.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, increasing the use of renewable fuels might increase
gasoline prices, said Steve Mahfood, director of the Missouri
Department of Natural Resources. But, in the long run, it should
help decrease prices.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City metropolitan area, regulators hope the oil
companies can design a special blend _ not reformulated gas _ that
would reduce the city's ozone levels. The best solution for
everyone, including consumers, would be a national fuel that
reduced air pollution, Mahfood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that the administration is finally stepping up to
the plate,'' Mahfood added. ``This is the right thing to do, and
it's about time that they did it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
