<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3239 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-TOBACCO-SETTLEMENT-SF     03-21 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SETTLEMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$1.72 MILLION AWARD ANOTHER BLOW TO TOBACCO COMPANIES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A jury here delivered a blow to the embattled
tobacco industry Monday, awarding $1.72 million to a woman who
developed lung cancer after smoking for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The award against Philip Morris Cos. Inc. and R.J. Reynolds
Corp., which is expected to increase with punitive damages, is the
first in favor of a smoker who took up the habit after 1965 when
the Surgeon General required warning labels on all cigarette
packages.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the latest in a handful of verdicts that have gone
against the reeling industry in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really reflects a total collapse of the industry's
ability to defend itself in court,'' said Richard Daynard, a
professor at Northwestern University and head of a research project
on the tobacco industry. Until Monday's verdict, he said, cigarette
companies were considered unbeatable in cases brought by those who
took up smoking after the warnings labels came out.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's verdict, a jury of seven men and five women found
that Philip Morris and R.J. Reynolds knew about the health hazards
of smoking and deliberately misled the public about those dangers.
After more than six days of deliberation, the jury awarded Leslie
Whiteley, a 40-year-old mother of four from Ventura County, $1.47
million for medical costs and pain and suffering. The panel awarded
her husband Leonard $250,000 for loss of companionship.
</P>
<P>
   The jury also found that the two tobacco giants had committed
fraud. The panel will go back to court to consider how much, if
anything, the companies should pay in punitive damages. The award
could far exceed the compensatory damages.
</P>
<P>
   Whiteley began smoking at age 13 while growing up in Ventura
County and didn't quit until 1998 when she was diagnosed with lung
cancer. During those 25 years, she smoked Marlboros and Camel Light
100's.
</P>
<P>
   The Ojai woman, who is married to a truck driver, sued Philip
Morris and R.J. Reynolds last year, claiming that she developed the
cancer from smoking cigarettes and from exposure to the asbestos
that her father picked up on his clothes at his workplace.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's verdict, the jury found that Metalclad Insulation
Corp., which Whiteley said supplied and installed the insulation at
her father's workplace, was not liable for any damages.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, lawyers for the tobacco companies said that
Whiteley, who smoked two packs of cigarettes a day, should shoulder
part of the blame because they said she smoked marijuana and
disregarded her doctor's warnings not to smoke during her four
pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she liked smoking and didn't want to quit,'' Philip
Morris attorney Chris Hardy told the jury during closing arguments.
He said that the industry should not be held responsible for her
illness because she had been exposed to the warning labels since
she began smoking.
</P>
<P>
   But the jury apparently was swayed by Whiteley's lawyer, Madelyn
Chaber, who said that the industry deliberately targeted its
addictive product to children and teenagers, including her client.
</P>
<P>
   The case is the first case brought by an individual smoker to go
to trial in California since a jury in San Francisco last year
awarded $51 million to Patricia Henley, a longtime smoker who had
sued Philip Morris after developing lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The judge later reduced the verdict to $26 million and the case
is now on appeal. A month after the verdict in favor of Henley,
Philip Morris suffered another defeat when a Portland, Ore. jury
awarded $81 million to the family of a Marlboro smoker. The judge
later slashed the verdict to $32 million. Recent verdicts in New
Jersey and Florida in favor of smokers have been tossed out in
appellate court and are winding their way through the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   The Whiteley case has been overshadowed by a class action
brought by smokers in Florida. Last year, the Miami jury found that
the nation's biggest cigarette makers had concealed from the public
the dangers of smoking. The industry is now facing what could be a
record-setting punitive damage award.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco jury returned the verdict after the close of
trading on the New York Stock Exchange, where Philip Morris shares
fell 1/8 to close at 19 15/16. Shares of R.J. Reynolds, based in
Winston-Salem, North Carolina, fell 5/16 to 16 1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
