<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3243 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-GILLNETS-MONTEREY-SFC     03-21 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILLNETS-MONTEREY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE SEA BIRDS, MAMMALS ENDANGERED BY FISHING PRACTICE IN  MONTEREY
BAY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Thousands of rare sea birds and hundreds of
marine mammals are being entangled and killed in fishing nets in
the Monterey Bay National Marine Sanctuary _ and it's all perfectly
legal.
</P>
<P>
   The carnage is caused by commercial fishing boats that lay gill
nets in the sanctuary to catch halibut. Populations of the esteemed
fish have surged off the Central Coast in recent years, leading to
a fishing industry boomlet.
</P>
<P>
   It is generally not illegal to fish either commercially or
recreationally in national marine sanctuaries, which were
established to protect marine resources. Evironmentalists are
increasingly pushing for greater fishing restrictions inside the
sanctuaries.
</P>
<P>
   Two wild species have proved particularly vulnerable to the gill
nets in the Monterey sanctuary: a deep-diving seabird known as the
common murre _ which is not particularly common _ and the harbor
porpoise. Sea otters, California sea lions, harbor seals, and
elephant seals have also been killed.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists with the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS),
the federal agency that manages the sanctuary, estimate that up to
2,500 murres and more than 100 porpoises may be killed by the gill
net fleet each year.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by the kills, NMFS began posting observers on some of
the halibut boats last April. Don Peterson, the coordinator of the
halibut gill net observer program for NMFS, said the agency is
empowered with enforcing the federal law aimed at protecting marine
mammals, the Marine Mammal Protection Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main concern is the porpoises,'' said Peterson, ``but
speaking as a private person, the murre take does seem high to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   William Sydeman, a marine ecologist and the director of marine
sciences at the Point Reyes Bird Observatory, said ``perhaps 12,000
to 15,000 murres have been killed (by gill nets) during the past
five years. That's very significant, because murre colonies (in the
area of the sanctuary) are very small.''
</P>
<P>
   Murre populations have also been diminished in recent years by
other factors, said Sydeman, most notably oil spills. In the early
1980s, there were about 600,000 murres living off the California
coast; now there are about 300,000.
</P>
<P>
   So many murres and porpoises may be dying, say some scientists,
that government efforts to bolster the flagging populations of
these species may be undermined.
</P>
<P>
   The state is spending $5 million to re-establish a murre colony
on Devil's Slide south of Pacifica. While the program has been
successful, many of the birds fly south after the nesting season to
forage in the Monterey sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ironies implicit in the situation. The first is
the abundance of the halibut, which is stimulating the gill net
fishery. Until a few years ago, halibut populations off Central
California were relatively small, due to pressure from trawl net
boats.
</P>
<P>
   But state regulations restricting the trawlers have brought the
halibut back, creating a small bonanza in the process. Up to a
dozen boats now set gill nets for the succulent fish, which can
reach forty pounds in weight and bring $2 to $4 a pound to the
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if a state law had not been passed that resulted
in a resurgence of halibut, murres and porpoises would not be
drowning in gill nets.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it is likely many of the afflicted murres are
beneficiaries of a costly government program calculated to revive
their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, a petroleum barge owned by the Apex Oil Co. leaked
about 25,000 gallons of oil as it travelled off the coast. Ten
thousand or more seabirds died as a result, and the company agreed
to pay $6.4 million to settle a suit brought by the federal and
state governments.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that money, explained Paul Kelly, a marine wildlife
biologist with the California Department of Fish and Game, is
devoted to re-establishing a murre colony on Devil's Slide south of
Pacifica.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the last 20 years, humans have pummeled murres on the
Central California Coast,'' said Kelly. ``We're using $5 million in
public funds to restore this valuable wildlife resource, and it's
being jeopardized by gill net drownings.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said his agency will continue to collect data through
next year, and then recommend possible policy changes. These could
include requiring gill netters to fish deeper water, where birds
and porpoises are fewer. Currently, gill net fishermen can fish in
water no shallower than 30 fathoms, depths that lie about three
miles from shore.
</P>
<P>
   Gill nets, which catch fish by ensnaring their gills with mesh,
are popular with commercial fishermen. Though gill nets are
associated with the killing of untargeted species, they are not
considered as environmentally destructive as drift nets and trawl
nets. They are not, however, as benign as hook-and-line.
</P>
<P>
   The agency may require fishermen to install ``pingers'' _
devices that attach to the nets, sonically alarming the mesh so
that the porpoises can avoid entrapment. The pingers also work well
to alert murres, said Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Zeke Grader, executive director of the Pacific Coast Federation
of Fishermen's Associations, a commercial fishing lobbying and
education group, said he was not aware that there were problems
with the Monterey gill net fishery.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first I've heard of it, but our approach has
always been that if there's a problem, we're going to fix it,''
said Grader. He noted that his organization has worked to reduce
wildlife mortality in other state fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike a lot of other industry organizations, we're not in
denial about these kinds of things,'' said Grader. ``We're going to
look into it. We don't want anyone gratuitously screwing with
fishermen, but we will do what's necessary to stop birds from being
killed _ we don't care whether they're endangered or if their
populations are healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said the gill net mortality is so high that it may be hard
for the fishery to justify operating in the sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tourism represents tremendous money in Monterey,'' he said.
``There is a huge economy based around people who go out to see
marine birds and cetaceans in their natural habitat. When you look
at the small number of boats involved in gill net fishing and
factor in the money expended on the murre restoration program and
the observer program, it doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson acknowledges that tourism is a huge business in
Monterey, but maintains the halibut fishery also contributes
substantially to the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, commercial halibut fishermen using all types of gear
_ including gill nets and hook-and-line _ landed 199,099 pounds of
halibut in the region between northern Big Sur and Moss Landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a very lucrative fishery for these guys,'' Peterson
said. ``During the summer, a boat can land 200 fish a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how it will ultimately be addressed, the Monterey
gill net problem points to a bigger issue: What activities are
appropriate for marine sanctuaries?
</P>
<P>
   Warner Chabot, West Coast director for the Center for Marine
Conservation, observed that each of the country's 12 marine
sanctuaries operate under different rules, but that fishing is
generally allowed in all of them.
</P>
<P>
   When the Monterey sanctuary was created in 1992, fishermen were
guaranteed that there would be no new regulations beyond those
already established by the California Department of Fish and Game
and the National Marine Fisheries Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without those guarantees, the fishermen would've withdrawn
their support, and the whole plan could've collapsed,'' Chabot
said.
</P>
<P>
   But a provision in the 1972 federal legislation that provides
for the creation of national marine sanctuaries requires a
re-evaluation of each sanctuary's management plan every five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it has been eight years since it was created, that
process has just begun for Monterey,'' Chabot observed. ``This is
an excellent opportunity to look at the management policies for all
the living resources there _ including fishing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 0032EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3245 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     03-21 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL EXECS LIKE TO SEE PEOPLE DRIVE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sure, gas prices are high, but you get more for
your money these days.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night at the Chevron at 24th and Geary in the Richmond,
Tom Sweeney reports, a saxophone player was accompanying motorists
who were singing the blues while pumping unleaded regular at $1.99
a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   There was no cover charge for the show, but there was a
two-gallon minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Al Cattalini was filling up at a station in Rohnert Park when he
was approached by a panhandler with an empty gas can. Brother, can
you spare a gallon?
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest thing: Canhandling.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the big boys at the oil companies really aren't milking us
like the last cow on the farm, but explain this:
</P>
<P>
   In Carmel, a home on the Pebble Beach golf course has been
rented for $1.2 million for the 10 days of the U.S. Open. My Carmel
spy, Daryl Glen, says his impeccable sources tell him the renter is
a big oil company.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the kicker: The oil boys aren't even going to use the
house, only the patio. That's $120,000 per day for a few people to
sit on a redwood deck and say, ``Hey now, is that Davis Love III?''
</P>
<P>
   SOMETHING ELSE scary about gas: I heard an expert on the radio
say that surplus gasoline can't be stored to carry us through times
of shortage, because gas goes bad.
</P>
<P>
   Can't you just drop some Rolaids down the tank?
</P>
<P>
   How do you know when gas has gone bad? Does it start to smell
good?
</P>
<P>
   If you get a tank of bad gas, in order to send it back, do you
have to go to the station attendant's booth and demand to speak to
the  &UR; sommelier? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I KNOW who really stole the Oscar statuettes.
</P>
<P>
   It's so obvious, you'll kick yourself.
</P>
<P>
   The shipment of trophies got ripped off from a loading dock in
Los Angeles last week and was found early Monday morning in a
Dumpster.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Fulgear, Dumpster diver by trade, made the find. Fulgear
said, ``My foot hit one. It was heavy and I opened it up. ...
Everybody knows who Oscar is.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hollywood does the movie version, Willie Fulgear will be
played by Willie Nelson. It will be a loose remake of ``The Maltese
Falcon,'' another suspense thriller that was much ado about a
statue.
</P>
<P>
   But whodunit? Well, the motive was jealousy. The Academy named
the award after him and then never gave him one. They treated him
like dirt. He is disgruntled by nature. He lives in a trash can.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, it was Sesame Street's Oscar the Grouch.
</P>
<P>
   A SAD STORY behind every sale at the car auction at SFO's
long-term parking lot. You leave your car there too long, they
seize it and auction it off.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Jacobs is a regular at the auctions, and last Thursday, a
young woman approached him before the bidding. She's a Cal student,
British accent, her car was being auctioned off, she was desperate
to get it back.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs told her the used VW would go for about a grand, maybe
$1,200. She was distraught. He told her, ``Try making an
announcement.'' So with dewy eye, she told her story to the 35
assembled bidders.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have to understand,'' Jacobs says, ``this is a
ruthless crowd. I go to a lot of auctions, and the group here is
the bottom-feeders.''
</P>
<P>
   Bidding starts, auctioneer asks opening bid of $25. Woman bids
$25. Crowd starts chanting, ``Sold! Sold! Sold!'' Nobody bids.
Woman buys back car for the price of a tank of gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it didn't hurt that she was pretty,'' Jacobs says.
</P>
<P>
   WHY JOHNNY can read: Because of people like Amanda Gerrie.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern California Children's Booksellers Assn.,
independent Bay Area booksellers, gave out its 18 literacy grants
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   One went to Gerrie, who works for the S.F. Department of Human
Services and has a caseload of about 100 families on public
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those families don't own book one, so the kids start
school with two strikes against 'em. Amanda will use her grant to
give books to kids on special occasions _ birthdays, holidays _ and
encourage parents to read with the children.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody said education is not filling the bucket, but lighting
the fire. So here's to a great bunch of pyromaniacs.
</P>
<P>
   JENNIFER LOPEZ brought Union Square to its knees Sunday. John
Konstin, prom-dress shopping with his daughter, saw Lopez in Saks
and then in Neiman-Marcus, shopping-bag-loaded like a pack mule.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer, remember, stunned the Grammys with a dress that was a
designer version of a hospital gown worn backwards. If Ms. Lopez
were to steal a phrase from cowboy poet Baxter Black, she might say
that dress ``exposed my expose.''
</P>
<P>
   Can you get dresses like that off the rack at Saks and Neiman?
If so, how come you don't see 'em around town?
</P>
<P>
   THE SPIN from new 49ers' owner Denise DeBartolo York's spokesguy
is that both parties walked away happy, but you can't bet (sorry,
bad word choice) that Eddie DeBartolo wasn't whistling a peppy tune
when he signed away his beloved 49ers to his sister Friday.
</P>
<P>
   She gets the team that Eddie built to greatness, then kissed
away in a sordid gambling mess. He gets a bunch of stuff worth a
lot of dough.
</P>
<P>
   I guess Denise declined Eddie's offer to flip a coin, double or
nothing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
