<SLUG> BC-HKN-MCHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISORS OR NO VISORS? THAT IS THE QUESTION IN NHL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As Toronto's Bryan Berard undergoes surgery today
in an attempt to regain some sight in his right eye, NHL players
are debating whether visors should become standard equipment with
every helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Berard would be playing today, and the Maple Leafs would be
trying to overtake New Jersey for the top spot in the Eastern
Conference, if he had been wearing a visor when Ottawa's Marian
Hossa inadvertently struck him with his stick following through on
a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto was streaking before the March 11 incident. It is 1-2
since and it will be difficult to make up five points on the Devils
with just 10 games to go. But the bigger issue now is whether
players can overcome a longstanding prejudice against the visor and
make the league a safer place.
</P>
<P>
   ``You listen to some guys and they still go, `Look at those
chicken Europeans putting the visors on.' What a bunch of
(bleep),'' Alexander Mogilny said after he was traded from
Vancouver to New Jersey. ``What are those guys going to tell
(Berard's) family? That he took one for the team? You protect
yourself first and you don't listen to what anyone else says. We're
talking about a man's eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of reasons players claim they don't wear them.
The puck often looks distorted when players stare down through
visors. They often fog up and get wet when players go into the
corners. Some players feel claustrophobic. And they often spend the
entire time between shifts cleaning the shield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went away from the visor because it bothered me a little
when I looked down at the puck,'' the Red Wings' Sergei Fedorov
told reporters in Detroit. ``It changes perception when you look
down to handle the puck. I want to see everything well and the
visor didn't give me a chance to have excellent vision. For guys
who work with the puck most of the game, it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   But it also is a macho thing. Fans and opposing players taunt
players who wear visors as if it is not manly to protect your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's Vincent Damphousse said he sometimes hears insults
from opponents because of his visor.
</P>
<P>
   ```You're a (bleep), you wear a shield.'`' Damphousse told the
Oakland Tribune. ``It's just the old attitude. I think it's
childish. It's probably like when guys first started wearing
helmets. I'd rather save my eyes. If I get my teeth knocked out, I
can still smile. If I get my eye knocked out, I can't see from one
side. If players are smart enough, they'll start wearing them if
they're smart enough to understand the importance of their eyes,
they'll start wearing them.''
</P>
<P>
   The league is littered with stories of eye injuries, but none as
gory as Berard's. It is likely he will never play again.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators' Chris Phillips, who plays on the same line as
Hossa, almost lost an eye two years ago when he took a puck in the
face. He's been wearing a visor ever since. Radek Bonk, the other
member of Hossa's line, also has put on a visor. ``Losing your
vision was definitely a scary thought,'' said Phillips. ``That's
why I still wear my visor. I learned the hard way. It took a puck
in the eye for me to learn a lesson to put it on. I feel safer with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's Joe Sakic played 11 years without a visor but started
wearing one this season after taking a stick in the eye. His new
teammate Ray Bourque has worn a visor since early in his 21-year
career after he was hit with a puck above his eye and was sidelined
for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said peer pressure prevents some players from wearing
visors. ``Especially kids who come in with something to prove,'' he
said recently. ``They don't want to come in with a visor. But some
guys just don't want to take the time to get used to them, too. The
sweat gets in there, and the fog. It takes some getting used to.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is similar to the 1979-80 season, when the NHL
mandated that every player coming into the league had to wear a
helmet. The ruling was grandfathered in, meaning if you didn't wear
a helmet, you didn't have to start. Now it is standard equipment.
Visors are mandatory in youth, junior and college hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Damphousse says there are products to apply to the visor to cut
down on fogging. He also thinks it's a bad rule that anyone wearing
a visor who initiates a fight gets an extra two-minute penalty. The
league says players with visors who start fights have an unfair
advantage and the rule isn't going to change.
</P>
<P>
   And some players think wearing visors makes players less
respectful of one another because there is no fear of injuring
someone's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to wear a shield and I bet I was cut seven or eight
times around the mouth by high sticks,'' Tampa Bay defenseman Paul
Mara said. ``Then I took it off, and I can't remember the last time
I was hit with a high stick.''
</P>
<P>
   ISLANDERS PULL DEAL
</P>
<P>
   A few hours before sending rookie center Ryan Johnson and
minor-league left winger Dwayne Hay to the Lightning for Mike
Sillinger, the Florida Panthers thought they had agreed to a
blockbuster deal that would have brought New York Islanders
defenseman Kenny Jonsson and leading scorer Mariusz Czerkawski to
South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Islanders general manager Mike Milbury and Panthers GM Bryan
Murray apparently had worked out a deal that would send Oleg Kvasha
and Ivan Novoseltsev to New York. But Islanders owner Ed Milstein
stepped in and killed the trade because he did not feel two
unproven prospects were worth the price of both Jonsson and
Czerkawski, who is having a career year.
</P>
<P>
   Murray isn't happy, especially after watching a three-for-three
deal featuring Jonsson, Jorgen Jonsson and Claude Lapointe derail
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury and Murray say talks can continue over the summer
because Jonsson and Czerkawski will be Group II free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury is concerned with Jonsson's history of concussions and
was looking to deal Czerkawski because if the forward gets five
more goals for 30, it would trigger an $800,000 bonus in his
contract. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Deputy Sports Editor Matt McHale covers the Kings for the Daily
News. The NHL column runs every Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 0041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
