r s BC-BKC-UCLA-IOWASTATE-LA     03-21 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-IOWASTATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIZER &AMP; CO. WILL BE PLENTY FOR UCLA TO HANDLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA can thank Dayton coach Oliver Purnell for its
latest predicament.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn, Central Connecticut State, the Big 12 and everyone else
Iowa State thrashed this season they can all thank Purnell, too.
</P>
<P>
   As the coach of the U.S. World University Games team (WUG) last
summer, Purnell cut Iowa State junior forward Marcus Fizer after
the final round of tryouts. That made Marcus mad. And when Marcus
got mad, Marcus hit the weight room.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State hasn't been the same since.
</P>
<P>
   Picked last in the Big 12 in preseason polls, the Cyclones won
their first conference title in 55 years and are 31-4 entering
Thursday's Sweet 16 showdown with UCLA at The Palace of Auburn
Hills (Mich.).
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcus has made our team,'' Cyclones coach Larry Eustachy
said. ``The (WUG failure) was a real motivator for him. He worked
real hard to make the team, then he slacked off. He got
comfortable. He got out of shape. (The experience) changed him.
He's just a lot more motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Fizer wasn't bad before he got mad. He was a McDonald's
All-American at Arcadia (La.) High and a first-team All-Big 12 pick
last year. But a Purnell-inspired summer has turned him into a
first-team All-American and leading contender for player of the
year awards.
</P>
<P>
   He added 17 pounds to his 6-foot-8 frame while dropping his body
fat dropped from 16 percent to 9. His bench press increased from
300 pounds to 350. His vertical jump improved two inches. He shot
hundreds of 3-pointers and has improved his percentage from 21.4
last year to 39 this year. He's quicker, stronger, more durable and
closer to unstoppable than any player in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``After (the WUG), coach Purnell and I talked, and there are no
hard feelings; he just chose other guys,'' Fizer said. ``Once that
was over, I just dedicated myself to Iowa State.''
</P>
<P>
   Fizer averages 23.2 points and has five 30-point games in the
last month. He's shooting 59 percent from the field and 72.5
percent from the foul line, where he spends most of his time. He
averages 7.8 rebounds a game. He's been double-teamed,
triple-teamed and zoned, and nothing's worked. He can overpower
defenders in the post or step outside and bury 3-pointers. In
talent and body type, he's strikingly similar to another Louisiana
power forward, Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could lock him in the locker room, that would be my first
choice,'' Kansas coach Roy Williams said when asked about defending
Fizer.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had more success against Fizer than any coach in the
Big 12, holding Fizer to 34 points in two games. But the Jayhawks
lost both because they couldn't score against the Cyclones'
ferocious defense (opponents shoot 41.6 percent) and because they
couldn't contain Fizer's supporting cast: undersized power forward
Stevie Johnson; shooting guard Michael Nurse, a third-team
all-conference selection; and point guard Jamaal Tinsley, the Big
12 newcomer of the year.
</P>
<P>
   A junior from Mt. San Jacinto Junior College, Tinsley has given
Iowa State the floor leadership required for March Madness
survival. He's a Brooklyn native with a flashy, slashing New York
City game. He's a superb penetrator who's averaging 19 points and
6.5 assists in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference-maker between them being an average team last
year and a great team this year is Jamaal Tinsley,'' Oklahoma coach
Kelvin Sampson said at the Big 12 tournament. ``Marcus Fizer is a
great, great player, don't get me wrong. But do you know why he's
stepped up his game? A lot of it has to do with Tinsley, who I
consider one of the top point guards in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear a lot about (Ohio State's) Scoonie Penn and (Michigan
State's) Mateen Cleaves, but Tinsley is right there with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the tournament began, few outside the Big 12 had ever
heard of Tinsley, Nurse or Johnson. That's because Iowa State is
the anti-UCLA. It was on national television once during the
regular season. It has never been to the Final Four. (UCLA has won
11 NCAA titles.) It has one McDonald's All-American, Fizer. (UCLA
has four.) Even the teams' makeup is different. The Cyclones have a
slew of no-name, overachieving junior college transfers, while UCLA
has none. The Cyclones have one starter over 6-4, Fizer, while UCLA
has four. They have an injury-depleted bench, while UCLA is healthy
and goes 11 deep.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the No.2 Cyclones might be the higher seed, but
they have a smaller margin for error Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA may be the most talented team, when you add depth, in the
country,'' Eustachy said. ``There's all kinds of areas they can
murder you.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State is a product of its coaches: Tim Floyd, who recruited
many of the players, including Fizer, before bolting for the
Chicago Bulls in 1998; and Eustachy, an Arcadia native who looks
like David Duchovny and coaches like Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Equal parts motivator and strategist, Eustachy turned an
undersized, modestly talented team that finished 15-15 last year
into the Big 12 champ and Final Four contender. With Fizer's help,
of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was the worst, and none of us wanted to go through
that again,'' Johnson said. ``We added Jamaal, and everything has
fit just right. We knew we weren't going to finish eighth or ninth.
When people asked if they thought we could make the NIT, we'd say,
`Yeah, blah, blah, blah.' But we knew we'd be better. Coach
Eustachy made us mentally tough, and when we saw how well Marcus
was playing, we knew no one would stop him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 0104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3251 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-CAVS-HNS &LR;      03-21 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-CAVS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
CLEVELAND _ The least the Cavaliers could have done is send those
who sat through this thing home with free chalupas. It was all the
smattering of friends, family and neighbors seemed to want anyway.
A 98-85 win over the worn-out Rockets on Monday did not seem to
interest them.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A five-game road trip weighed on the Rockets as if they were
sloshing their way through the Ohio mud. They hit the accelerator,
but the engines coughed and the tires spun with futility.
</P>
<P>
   For even the Cavaliers, the Rockets were mere road kill. Losers
of six straight themselves coming in, the Cavs rolled over the
Rockets as if they were a speed bump.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not satisfy. The 13,241 _ many cleverly disguised
as empty seats _ wanted their chalupas. And when the Cavaliers,
scoreless against the Rockets' drive-through defense in the final
two minutes, dropped the chalupa chance, they were booed.
</P>
<P>
   In a new indignity for the Rockets, a victory over them was
apparently not deemed worth Cleveland's cheers without the literal
greasing of the customers' palms.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a young team to be out nine days, four games in five days,
it's pretty tough,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``We're a
road-weary team right now, and that was about as ugly as it gets.
We couldn't make plays in the open court, and we couldn't shoot it,
and we turned it over.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have gone on, but there was little point. The more the
Rockets seemed to press to stay within range of one of the NBA's
worst offensive teams, the more they seemed to run themselves back
in a ditch.
</P>
<P>
   They held their last lead with 4{ minutes left in the third
quarter when Steve Francis scored six consecutive points to finally
offer some help for Walt Williams, who had scored the Rockets'
first 15 points of the second half. But both players seemed to wear
themselves out by the effort. No one came close to picking up the
slack.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Francis each finished with 17 points. But a day
after scoring 25 in Toronto, Shandon Anderson did not score at all
in 27 minutes. A day after scoring 12 points in 27 minutes, Hakeem
Olajuwon had two points, making one of five shots, in 16 minutes.
Even when the Rockets did not have to move to score, they misfired,
making just 12 of 23 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was tired,'' Francis said. ``Everybody was thinking
of going home. It shouldn't have been like that. I thought we had a
good chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely took a step backward tonight, because we didn't
play with much intensity, and we didn't make any shots. Our defense
was really lacking tonight, and it doesn't make a difference who
the team is, Cleveland or LA. We still didn't play that good. They
wanted to win. We wanted to win. But we didn't prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Rockets walked slowly out of the Gund Arena locker
room, the midnight charter never looking so good, it was not the
road that had them feeling so worn and beaten.
</P>
<P>
   The setback extended their losing streak to eight games, their
longest uninterrupted stretch of defeats since they began the
1982-83 season 0-10. The winless road trip was their worst since
another 0-5 trip in January 1973 _ before any of their current
guards were born.
</P>
<P>
   Since the All-Star break, the Rockets have gone 4-13. And no
matter how difficult the road might be, the losing has begun to
weigh on them more heavily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never going to get used to losing,'' guard Cuttino Mobley
said. ``I've never lost like this. I'm not a loser. I'm having a
lot of trouble with it. I don't know how to cope with it right now.
I don't like losing. Nobody likes to lose. But I take it real
personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Rockets had effective moments, they seemed out of
sync, almost haphazard offensively and slow defensively.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavs came in having made just 43.7 percent of their shots to
rank 24th in the league. But after shooting just 35 percent in the
first half, they made 55 percent in the second half, even with
Randy Wittman clearing his bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were tired,'' Cavaliers guard Bob Sura said of the
Rockets. ``We didn't feel like they were ready in the beginning,
and we took advantage of it in the second half and wore them down a
little bit with the fast break.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Cleveland wore them down a lot. The Cavaliers did not
play particularly well, but their most free-wheeling players, Andre
Miller and Sura, took over, combining for 28 points, including 23
in the second half. The Cavaliers rolled up 59 second-half points.
But even they did not seem too enthused with the rout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the prettiest of basketball games _ especially in
the first half, when I thought both teams struggled shooting the
ball,'' Wittman said. ``But for us, we'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the surge by Williams and Francis put the Rockets ahead,
the Cavaliers easily outscored them 26-10 over the next 10 minutes.
The Rockets made four of 12 shots in that stretch, committed five
turnovers and finally gave in and sat every starter with 7:41 left,
knowing they had nothing more to give.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had eight-day road trips before, but never with so many
games and not with two back-to-backs,'' Williams said. ``I was
tired out there. I was just trying to fight through it. Losing so
many games, we were just trying to fight through that, just trying
to win a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're losing like this, you just try to stay positive,
to think of positive things. It's hard to take. We have to keep
fighting. We have to get a win.''
</P>
<P>
   As the night moved closer to home, victory seemed further away.
But the Clippers are in town Thursday. And for the first time in
two weeks, so are the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, however, the best they could manage was to prevent a
run for the border.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
