<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW&AMP;NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
 (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED IT;  STORY ALSO MOVING IN
THE ``E'' CATEGORY) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``TRUE NORTH'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Kimberly Kafka (Dutton, $23.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The protagonist of Kafka's first novel is Bailey Lockhart, a
35-year-old woman who has fled a troubled past to find solace as a
medic and bush pilot in the remote wilderness of Alaska. She lives
alone in a cabin 80 miles upriver from the nearest community, a
Native village with which she stays in touch by radio. The book
opens when she agrees to fly two tourists _ they claim to be
looking for a ``wilderness adventure'' but are really searching
illegally for Alaskan gold _ from Anchorage to a des-R oR[6adgY
fivej%1M
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 0111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3257 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-EL-AMIN-ARREST-1STLED     03-21 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EL-AMIN-ARREST-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Al-Amin nabbed after shootout in Alabama
 &HT;    By Doug Payne
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, the former Black Panther wanted in last
week's shooting death of a Fulton County sheriff's deputy, was
captured Monday night in White Hall, Ala., after an exchange of
gunfire with federal marshals, law enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin, formerly known as H. Rap Brown, had been the subject of
a nationwide manhunt since Thursday night when two Fulton County
sheriff's deputies were shot while trying to serve an arrest
warrant in Atlanta's West End.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Richard Kinchen, 35, died of his wounds; Deputy Aldranon
English, 28, is recovering from his injuries at Grady Memorial
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's arrest was the result of information investigators
received soon after the deputies were shot, Atlanta Police Chief
Beverly Harvard said at a late-night press conference at City Hall
East.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin was located Monday afternoon at a house in White Hall,
between Selma and Montgomery. As federal authorities closed in
around 6:30 p.m., shots were fired, Harvard said.
</P>
<P>
   Lowndes County Sheriff Willie Vaughner said no one was injured
in the exchange of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin fled to some nearby woods, which were surrounded by law
enforcement authorities. With the help of tracking dogs from the
Alabama Department of Corrections, Al-Amin was flushed from the
woods and arrested without further incident, Harvard said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents took Al-Amin, who was wearing a white shirt, sweat
pants and sunglasses, into custody at the Montgomery Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard said a handgun was found in the woods after Al-Amin's
arrest. She said it is not known whether this gun was used in the
shooting earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Sheriff Jackie Barrett said Deputy English had
expressed relief about Al-Amin's arrest. ``He said, `Tonight I can
sleep.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted that it happened in this time frame,'' the
sheriff said, referring to today's funeral service for the slain
deputy. ``This will add a different air to the service. On a good
day this would be a difficult service, this will help us through a
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard said Al-Amin will be arraigned in Alabama on federal
charges of firing on federal agents. A warrant has been issued in
Atlanta charging him with murder and aggravated assault.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard said she does not know when Al-Amin will be returned to
Georgia. She would not elaborate on how investigators tracked him
to Alabama beyond saying that it was due to information they
received early in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Several other people were detained in White Hall, she said, ``as
it relates to the possibility of their harboring a person that we
had a warrant on.'' About six people were being questioned but were
not under arrest as of Monday evening, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard said she does not know what connection Al-Amin has to
the White Hall area in general or specifically to the house where
he was found.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin, as H. Rap Brown, was a field organizer for the Student
Nonviolent Coordinating Committee in Greene County, Ala., and
worked to register voters in Lowndes County, then a segregationist
and racist stronghold, in 1966 and 1967, according to historians.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Panther Party had roots in Lowndes County. The panther
was adopted as a symbol of black voting rights after a mass meeting
in the county more than 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The late civil rights activist Stokely Carmichael left Lowndes
County after that meeting and helped lead the Black Panther Party
to national prominence.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn University history professor J. Wayne Flynt said the
Black Panthers capitalized on the Rev. Martin Luther King's
Selma-to-Montgomery march, which passed through Lowndes County, and
organized people who may have regarded the Panthers as part of
King's movement.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Panther movement in Lowndes County today, Flynt
said, but Al-Amin would likely still have friends there. ``What I'd
think you'd find is people who were personal friends of Brown and
Carmichael.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard said she does not know how Al-Amin was able to travel
from Atlanta to Alabama. She said investigators still have not
found either the black Mercedes that was at the scene of Thursday
night's shootout on West End Place, or the .223-caliber assault
rifle that was used to shoot Deputies English and Kinchen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 0115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
