<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, March 21.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BANGLADESH-VILLAGE (Joypura, Bangladesh) _ Of all the distant
villages, in all the poor countries, in all the Third World,
President Bill Clinton was supposed to visit theirs. And sitting on
a cane stool under a 150-year-old banyan tree, he was to talk with
the peasants of Joypura. It was to be Clinton's rare chance to hear
from people of the Bangladeshi soil and, in turn, their opportunity
to rub elbows with a man of global power. But at the last minute,
the visit was canceled. Instead, buses with hundreds of villagers
were taken to Dhaka to meet Clinton, who became the first American
president to visit this populous, impoverished nation. By Barry
Bearak. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Map has been
sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-CULT (Kanungu, Uganda) _ The scene: The counting of
corpses comes to an end in this lush mountain village where
hundreds of followers of a doomsday cult died in an apocalyptic
inferno. The twisted remains of the dead, found after their
tin-roofed chapel was set ablaze Friday, were dumped into a mass
grave. What was left of the church was torn down, too, and tossed
into the ditch. By Henri E. Cauvin.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-ASSESS (Taipei) _ A news analysis on China-Taiwan
tensions: Is there any hope of reconciling Chen Shui-bian's and
Beijing's seemingly irreconcilable positions? By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-FORMOSA (Undated) _ A look at just when did Taiwan belong
to China, and for how long?
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-WELFARE (New York) _ A year and a half before New York's
welfare recipients exhaust their eligibility for federal benefits,
new state figures indicate that those who remain are perhaps the
most deeply mired in dependency the state has ever seen. By Raymond
Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-LABOR (Undated) _ Buoyed by contract at Boeing, the
AFL-CIO looks for its next targets in the ranks of white-collar
workers. A news analysis by Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GASOLINE-ADDITIVE _ The Clinton administration has decided to
phase out MTBE as a gasoline additive on grounds it poses a risk to
public health or the environment, government sources said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN-RATES (Washington) _ The Federal Reserve is all but
certain to raise its benchmark interest rate by another quarter of
a percentage point on Tuesday, to 6 percent. That much Alan
Greenspan has made clear in his public statements. What is less
clear is the central bank chairman's thinking about the forces that
are driving him to tighten monetary policy. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   RESTORATION-HARDWARE (Undated) _ As the Federal Reserve raises
interest rates and the housing market cools off, the stocks of all
manner of home products retailers have taken hits. But the woes of
Restoration Hardware have been particularly severe. Its share price
has plummeted from a high of $37 in July 1998 to $5 Monday, nearly
three-quarters less than the initial offering price of $19 in June
1998. What went wrong? By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos and graphic have been sent to NYT
photo/graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSTRATEGY-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ MicroStrategy Inc., whose
software helps businesses manage inventory, says it is revising
revenue and operating results for the last two years after changing
the way it accounts for software sales. Shares of MicroStrategy
plunged Monday. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   POETRY-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Increasingly, marketing departments
at companies nationwide are distributing books of poetry, hoping
that a few of their customers will appreciate it. Meanwhile, some
corporate executives _ apparently having had their fill of
consultants that promise to ``optimize'' or ``rationalize'' or
``compartmentalize'' _ are turning instead to poetry for
inspiration. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WAJDA-POLISH-FILM (Paris) _ Few movie directors have better
captured their country's yearning for freedom than the Polish
filmmaker Andrzej Wajda. Yet when freedom finally came to Poland a
decade ago, the audience for his movies evaporated. Now, at 75, his
latest movie he has just scored the biggest box office hit of his
long career. And at the Academy Awards ceremony this year, he will
receive an honorary Oscar in recognition of his life's work as a
director whose films, in the words of the academy's board of
governors, ``have given audiences around the world an artist's view
of history, democracy and freedom, and who in so doing has himself
become a symbol of courage and hope for millions of people in
post-war Europe.'' By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   LAVIN-THEATER (New York) _ Linda Lavin on her role in ``The
Allergist's Wife.'' By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-DR-LAURA (Undated) _ A Critic's Notebook: On Dr. Laura, soon
to be on TV as well as radio. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS-CITY-GIFT (Undated) _ The Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art in
Kansas City, Mo., has received a gift of 84 artworks, primarily
20th-century sculptures, from the foundation created by the Hall
family, the heirs of the founder of Hallmark Cards Inc. The
donation includes works by Isamu Noguchi, Claes Oldenburg,
Alexander Calder, Magdalena Abakanowicz, Mark di Suvero and George
Segal, among others, as well as 52 pieces by Henry Moore. It is
valued at more than $80 million, said Marc F. Wilson, the museum's
director. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   ROMANTICS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Romantics,'' by Pankaj
Mishra (Random House). Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
