<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEISENBERG-BOMB (Undated) _ Interest has been renewed in the
role of the German physicist Werner Heisenberg during World War II.
Did he deliberately keep the bomb out of German hands, staking out
a stand based on morality? Or was he inept? The new play
``Copenhagen'' dramatically presents possibilities, and survivor of
the era are holding a seminar. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-POLIO (Undated) _ Scientists in three laboratories in
the United States and Europe are gearing up to test samples of an
experimental polio vaccine stored for more than 40 years to
determine whether it might inadvertently have been the spark that
ignited the worldwide AIDS epidemic. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NUKE-WATER (Undated) - When the government conducted
underground nuclear tests in Nevada from 1956 to 1992, scientists
knew that groundwater beneath the site would become contaminated.
They believed that the underground water barely moved, and that
radioactive particles would be sealed into cavities or else
absorbed by underground rock. But studies in recent years have
found that radioactive particles like long-lived plutonium 239 can
travel with water, and that water is flowing more rapidly beneath
the site than was once believed. By Martin Forstenzer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GALDIKAS-ORANGUTANS (New York) _ A Conversation With Dr.
Birute Galdikas, who has extensively studied the habits and
examined the future of the endangered Indonesian orangutans. 1500
words w/photo. By Claudia Dreifus.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WEATHER-SATELLITE (Undated) _ The National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, which runs the nation's weather
satellites, is celebrating the 40th anniversary with releases of
historic photographs and a public conference on April 5 in
Washington on the past, present and future of the field. By William
J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPACE-FISHING (Undated) _ Throughout the space age, the
waters around Cape Canaveral in Florida have been off limits to
fishermen for reasons of security and safety. Though bad for local
fishermen, these closed waters turn out to have been a bonanza for
fish and even for anglers in nearby areas, new research shows. By
William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT2) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on
forests forest diversity, evolution of snakes with legs and studies
on new meteorite fragments.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-YOUNG-PATIENTS (Undated) _ The Cases column: A doctor learns
that even facing the worst circumstances and the most difficult
odds, young patients can sometime produce pleasant surprises. By
Howard Markel, M.D.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHILDREN-OBSESS (Undated) _ With early intervention,
medicine and counseling children with obsessive-compulsive
disorders often can be treated and overcome their more severe
obstacles, and sometimes even cured. By Annette Fuentes.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTHMA (Undated) _ In a startling discovery that could
radically alter the way asthma patients are monitored and treated,
doctors at the University of Virginia have found that the breath of
asthmatics who are having an attack is a thousand times more acidic
than normal. This increase in acidity, never before detected, may
be central to the disease process, the researchers said, and could
open a new avenue of research to explain the disease. By Sandra
Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-WEIGHTS (Undated) _ Lifting weights, just two or
three times a week, can reduce blood pressure, body fat levels and
improve glucose metabolism, according to an American Heart
Association survey. By Alisha Berger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health: Several
organizations are pushing for public recognition of the problems
association with post-traumatic stress disorder so more people can
be treatment. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
