<SLUG> BC-COYOTE-CHANGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTE RETOOLS TO PIONEER NEW MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  WESTLAKE VILLAGE, Calif. _ Coyote Network Systems Inc., which
began as a maker of telecommunications switching equipment, is
reinventing itself, complete with a new name, the company said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders at the Westlake Village company are being asked to
approve a new name, Quentra Networks Inc., to go with the new
identity.
</P>
<P>
   Company spokesman Tony Squeglia said the company wants to emerge
as a provider of Internet services through a specially designed
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is going through a transition period,'' he said.
``We believe there are a lot of people who are not comfortable with
adapting to a new type of technology like a PC.''
</P>
<P>
   The company took its new name, Quentra, from the word entrance
because its new service will allow customers an entrance to
services on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The future, according to Coyote, is being able to do online
shopping, bill paying, stock trading and other Internet services
through a telephone with a screen and keyboard and a port to insert
a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   The company is working on developing partnerships with credit
card companies and utilities it isn't naming yet. The partners
would allow their customers to use the phone and the service to pay
their bills or to receive special offers, Squeglia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we'll be the first to market these services,'' he
said. ``We're not creating anything new; the technology all
exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Vik Grover of Kaufman Bros LP, an investment bank, said
the movecould expand the market for Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   The company's sales and revenue models are untested, however,
and the service itself is so new it is difficult to say with
certainty how the company will perform, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a totally new company; they have had a lot of doubters of
the old management,'' Grover said. ``It's a work in process.''
</P>
<P>
   One marketing strategy might be to give away the phones to
customers who sign up for the service, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Squeglia said the company hopes to integrate the services of a
company it purchased in 1998, Inet, which provides international
long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes to begin launching the service by summer.
</P>
<P>
   It has some advantages over PC-based Internet access, Squeglia
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will always be on. You're always connected, so it's not a
question of having to boot up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is in discussions with digital subscriber line
companies to provide high-speed broadband Internet access, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
