r a BC-OSCARS-FOUND-LADN     03-21 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-FOUND-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCRAP COLLECTOR FINDS OSCARS; MAY GET $50,000 REWARD, ATTEND
AWARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Willie Fulgear came from Chicago to Los Angeles
some 40 years ago to find fame and fortune as a rock 'n' roll star.
</P>
<P>
   Now at 61, the junk salvager finally has found celebrity and
appears headed toward the Academy Awards and a $50,000 reward _
after finding 52 of the 55 stolen Oscar statuettes in a Koreatown
trash bin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to go, me and my son,'' Fulgear said Monday. ``I
think I earned it. I saved Oscar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My plan is to buy me a home. I'm going to put it in my son's
name so it will be his house. I'm 61 years old: I want to leave my
son something.''
</P>
<P>
   Academy of Motion Picture Arts &AMP; Sciences officials said they
hope to invite Fulgear to the awards ceremony Sunday as a way of
expressing their appreciation for his good deed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to wait until the Police Department completes its
investigation before we decide who we thank, acknowledge and
appreciate, but we'd certainly love to invite him,'' said academy
spokesman John Pavlik.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're feeling a little nervous yet. We're hoping to invite
him, but we want to be absolutely sure before we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said Fulgear deserves the reward, and they have arrested
two men they suspect stole the golden boys from a loading dock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thank him from the bottom of our hearts for coming
forward,'' Los Angeles police Detective Robert Rivera said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a Hollywood-perfect happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Fulgear found the Oscars, detectives announced on
Monday that they had solved the March 10 theft of the statuettes
from a Roadway Express shipping dock in Bell. And they have clues
about the whereabouts of the three other missing statuettes.
</P>
<P>
   Roadway dock worker Anthony Keith Hart, 38, of West Covina and
Roadway truck driver Lawrence Edward Ledent, 38, of Los Angeles
were arrested over the weekend on suspicion of grand theft, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   They were being held at Parker Center with bail for each set at
$100,000, and are expected to be arraigned in court this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought they could make some money off them,'' said Los
Angeles police Detective Marc Zavala.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime employees knew what was in the boxes they were
loading: Fifty-five unengraved Oscars, valued at a total of
$18,000, police said.
</P>
<P>
   But when the theft of filmdom's most coveted awards became an
international !ital!cause celebre!off!, the thieves wondered
whether they had made a blunder of ``Ishtar'' proportions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they knew they couldn't do anything with them and
everyone was looking at them, that's when they panicked,'' Zavala
said. ``They figured it was just a matter of time before somebody
would tell on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The men dumped the Oscars next to a green Dumpster behind a
supermarket at Venice Boulevard and Western Avenue near Koreatown,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Fulgear comes in.
</P>
<P>
   Once a rock 'n' roll musician who warmed up shows for big-name
acts in Chicago, Fulgear now makes his living recycling metal he
scavenges. ``In Jackson, Miss., I won the talent contest. I came in
third place, but that's still a winner,'' he recalled wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, he was going through trash bins looking for
boxes for his belongings because he and his son had been evicted.
He literally stumbled on the Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked over to the bin and my foot hit something heavy. I
picked it up and opened it. I didn't know what it was. I loaded it
into my car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was throwing them real fast into the trunk because I was
afraid somebody might come and take them. I'm a junk man, a scrap
man. I deal with metal and stuff. I thought it might be brass or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Unaware of what he had, Fulgear opened the cardboard boxes later
and found the 24-karat gold-plated symbols of Hollywood's dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The police _ and Academy _ were glad to get Fulgear's call, even
though three of the statuettes are missing.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera said detectives are investigating whether Hart or Ledent
might have kept the three missing Oscars for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the person who does have possession will do the
right thing, call the police and turn in the missing Oscars,''
Zavala said.
</P>
<P>
   Academy President Bob Rehme said another batch of Oscars was
made in case the missing ones were not located in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough for three years,'' he said. ``I think you can
rest assured this won't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Gerloff, security manager for Roadway Express, said the
company intends to pay the $50,000 reward once the investigation is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're anxious to pay the reward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Fulgear, the money couldn't come at a better time.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since he lost his job as a bakery mechanic in the mid-1980s
and the death of his wife shortly afterward, Fulgear has been alone
to raise his son, who is now 22.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Fulgear said his father helps everybody he comes across.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody is hungry, he gives them food,'' he said. ``That's
the way he is. He looks to help and please others more than
himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
