<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPBROWN-SHOOTING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
60'S RIGHTS LEADER IS ARRESTED IN DEATH OF SHERIFF'S DEPUTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Subs to provide addititional background material) (sw) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three days after he was accused of shooting to death
of a sheriff's deputy near downtown Atlanta, the former civil
rights leader who was known as H. Rap Brown was arrested on Monday
night in an Alabama field after an exchange of gunfire near the
small town of Whitehall, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Now a Muslim cleric known as Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, he had been
the subject of a nationwide manhunt since Friday, when a Fulton
County Sheriff's deputy identified Al-Amin as the man who had shot
him and another deputy while they tried to serve him with an arrest
warrant Thursday night on minor charges.
</P>
<P>
   One of the deputies, Ricky Kinchen, died Friday afternoon after
receiving several gunshot wounds from a high-powered assault rifle.
Aldranon English, the deputy who identified Al-Amin, was still
hospitalized on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Monday night, Atlanta Police Chief
Beverly Harvard said Al-Amin had been captured by federal marshals,
FBI agents, and deputies of the Lowndes County, Ala., sheriff's
department.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehall is a small town between Selma and Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews broadcast on local television stations, Bill
Imfeld, an FBI agent based in Mobile, Ala., said federal agents had
begun looking for Al-Amin in Whitehall all day after learning that
he had friends from the days when he associated with the Black
Panther party in the 1960s. After knocking on doors in the town,
several agents were fired on near a shed at about 5:30 p.m., and
then called in backup officers, Imfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and local law-enforcement agencies flooded the area with
officers, helicopters and dogs. Al-Amin had run into a field when
the dogs found him, Imfield said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the dogs were turned loose, they flushed out H. Rap
Brown, and he ran right into the arms of a waiting sheriff,''
Imfeld said. Al-Amin was arrested about 8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard said several people in the Whitehall area had been
detained on the possibility that they may have been harboring
Al-Amin as a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   She said that a handgun had been found in the field where
Al-Amin was caught, but she did not know if it had been used in the
Atlanta shooting. Officers did not find the assault rifle that had
been used in the shooting, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Sheriff Jacqueline Barrett described herself as
ecstatic that Al-Amin had been caught before the funeral, scheduled
for Tuesday, of Kinchen. English was extremely relieved the suspect
had been caught, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight I can sleep,'' she quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin was in custody in the FBI office in Montgomery, Imfeld
said, where he would probably be charged on Tuesday and then
transported to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard would not comment on reports that the FBI may have
tracked down Al-Amin through the use of electronic wiretaps and
cellular phone transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when he was stopped by a police officer in suburban
Atlanta while driving a car that turned out to be stolen, Al-Amin
claimed to be a police officer in Whitehall, and flashed a badge he
said was from the Whitehall police department. But he was unable to
name the chief of police there, and was charged with impersonating
an officer, among other violations.
</P>
<P>
   After he failed to show up in court, a warrant was issued for
his arrest, which the deputies were serving when they were shot.
</P>
<P>
   As H. Rap Brown, Al-Amin was one of the best-known and most
confrontational black militants of the 1960s and 1970s. He spent
several years underground after being accused of inciting a riot
and transporting a gun across state lines while under indictment.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged with inciting a riot in Cambridge, Md., in 1967
after he told a crowd of about 400, ``It's time for Cambridge to
explode, baby. Black folks built America, and if America don't come
around, we're going to burn America down.'' Afterward, Brown was
wounded and a police officer were wounded when gunfire broke out
between blacks and whites.
</P>
<P>
   A leader of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee in the
1960s, he was known for proclaiming that ``violence is as American
as cherry pie.''
</P>
<P>
   After serving five years behind bars in New York on a robbery
charge, he converted to Islam, changed his name and moved to
Atlanta in 1976, where he has lived in relative peace.
</P>
<P>
   He disappeared after the Thursday night shooting, leaving behind
a bewildered flock of followers in the largely black Atlanta
neighborhood called the West End, who said Al-Amin had renounced
violence when he formed the mosque and began working with community
groups to clean up the area.
</P>
<P>
   He was chosen to be the imam, or prayer leader, of his mosque,
and later became a prominent figure in Orthodox Muslim circles in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Before Monday's arrest, FBI agents had feared Al-Amin might stay
in hiding for some time because of his experience on the run, and
because of what they called a large network of supporters across
the country who could hide him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
