<HEADLINE>
L.A. SCHOOL CROWDING TO WORSEN AS CONVERSION PLAN DERAILS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID R. BAKER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A sweeping plan to ease overcrowding by converting
middle schools to high schools won't work at many campuses, Los
Angeles Unified officials said Monday, raising the specter that the
district's classroom shortage could worsen.
</P>
<P>
   While the school district hasn't ruled out the possibility of
converting some campuses, the idea has proved too complex and
unpopular with parents to work on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
   That means Los Angeles Unified will need to build even more
schools than previously planned, with estimates soaring from 100 to
150 and now even higher. The exact number has yet to be determined
but overcrowding at existing schools _ many of them already packed
with portable classrooms and operating on multitrack schedules _
will grow until the construction program gets into gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the magic bullet,'' school board member Caprice
Young said of the plan to convert middle schools. ``It isn't going
to save us.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the neighborhoods Young represents, North Hollywood, was
supposed to be the plan's first test. Last fall, Chief Operating
Officer Howard Miller proposed turning two North Hollywood middle
schools into high schools, rearranging seven elementaries to
include grades four through eight and building 11 small primary
centers to handle kindergarten through grade three.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, Miller said, would allow the district to house a
growing high school population without needing to find and buy the
large parcels of land required for a secondary school campus.
</P>
<P>
   But fierce opposition from parents and other complications
forced officials to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   At James Madison Middle School in North Hollywood, parents
complained about placing fourth-grade students on the campus with
much older children in grade eight. At Sun Valley Middle School,
district officials worried that a nearby landfill could cause
environmental problems if the school expanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always an option that depended on finding the right
locations and community input, and it turns out the community
opposition was considerable,'' Miller said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Without the changes _ or new high schools _ the eastern San
Fernando Valley will have about 5,620 more high school students
than existing campuses can handle by 2006. Miller said the
district's staff hopes to present, in the next few weeks, more
options for easing overcrowding in the area's schools.
</P>
<P>
   The district also encountered stiff resistance to its school
conversion plan in South Gate, where the school board's decision to
abandon a contaminated site for a future high school only
exacerbated a serious classroom shortage.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 parents attended one community meeting on the plan,
and most of those who spoke were critical of converting schools to
meet growing enrollment demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was overwhelmingly rejected by the parents,'' Assistant
Superintendent Gordon Wohlers said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the district has shifted its emphasis to finding
alternative sites for new South Gate schools. That policy will
apply to other schools as well.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, when Miller presents the school board with ways to
replace the now abandoned Belmont Learning Center downtown,
converting middle schools won't be one of them. The district needs
to construct 5,000 new classroom seats for students and Miller has
identified possible locations for 18,000 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Although board members and others initially praised the idea's
creativity, it has proved difficult to implement. Many middle
schools simply don't have the space needed for a comprehensive high
school, lacking adequate science labs or sports facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also posed instructional problems.
</P>
<P>
   Sol Bialeck, assistant principal of Madison Middle School,
worried that the changes would destroy middle schools by lumping
those grades in with others. Students at that age, Bialeck said,
are undergoing significant changes and need a school specifically
focused on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sacrifice educational soundness for the need
to have a building,'' Bialeck said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   District officials said the conversion idea remains a
possibility in places where it would make sense and that it is
still an option in North Hollywood. But it no longer appears to be
the kind of large-scale solution many had hoped it would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an alternative,'' Wohlers said, ``but it's an alternative
only when all other options have been exhausted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
