<HEADER>
A3268 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-HEAT-LADN     03-21 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-HEAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER LAKERS BEAT HEAT, EVEN JACKSON IMPRESSED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In a season in which the Lakers have made few
concessions to the powers of the NBA, their coach has made even
fewer concessions regarding his own team's awesome potential.
</P>
<P>
   Predict a championship? Never.
</P>
<P>
   Foreshadow even a finals appearance? No.
</P>
<P>
   But Phil Jackson is starting to give in. He has little choice.
</P>
<P>
   Especially after Monday night, when the Lakers overcame a
15-point deficit and used a dominant second half to put down the
Miami Heat 100-89 before 20,075 at American Airlines Arena. And
this, just 24 hours after the Lakers beat the New York Knicks at
Madison Square Garden _ as impressive a back-to-back set of
victories as there is.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making me a believer,'' Jackson said. ``This team is
really making me a believer.''
</P>
<P>
   He joins a growing legion. Jackson's team won 4 of 5 on this
road trip, has now won 22 of its last 23 games to improve its
league-best record to 56-12, and extended its lead over Portland to
five games.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers are winning converts at every turn, that must make
Shaquille O'Neal the Big Proselytizer. O'Neal led the Lakers with
28 points and 12 rebounds, but it was his four blocks of Alonzo
Mourning _ all in a four-minute span to open the third quarter _
that turned the game around.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had trailed 57-42, and O'Neal had been hampered by
three first-half fouls. But his defensive crush ignited a 22-2 run
that gave the Lakers a 64-59 lead and the momentum that carried
them to the win. O'Neal scored eight points in the run, while Kobe
Bryant added seven and finished with 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had to wake up,'' O'Neal said. ``I know I had to wake
up personally. I was tired in the first half, then I woke up,
somebody ticked me off, so I had to wake up.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal didn't identify the culprit, but Mourning was a good
candidate after scoring 19 points on 7-of-11 shooting in the first
half on his way to a 33-point night. More likely, it was the
officials who slapped O'Neal with the early fouls and later ejected
teammate Rick Fox for a verbal spat with referee Derek Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the source, O'Neal responded. The Lakers won the third
quarter 33-14 and never trailed again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaquille, with the effort defensively out of the gate, was
impressive,'' said Fox. ``He controlled the paint and got three or
four blocks in a row there. I think he set up a tone going down the
stretch, that there was not going to be the easy play in the paint.
That changes (the Heat's) confidence level on that side of the
court when they see their leader being controlled the way Shaquille
was controlling him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat was also battling through injuries _ P.J. Brown and
Otis Thorpe didn't dress, and Dan Majerle was hobbled and
ineffective. Yet it was the Lakers, perhaps battling some fatigue
playing their fourth road game in five days, who stumbled out of
the gate.
</P>
<P>
   They allowed the Heat to shot 56.4 percent in the first half
while falling to a 55-42 halftime deficit ``We did everything wrong
defensively in the first half,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were challenged at halftime as a basketball team to play
better basketball than we got mired into in the second quarter, ''
Jackson said. ``Shaquille came out and played a great defensive
quarter against Alonzo and just turned the momentum around in the
ballgame. ... And for a fourth game in five nights, that was a
terrific effort by these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The final piece was Glen Rice, the former Heat star who again
scorched his former team with 28 points on 7-of-15 shooting,
including 3 of 6 from the 3-point arc.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's no coincidence at all,'' said Rice, who scored 23
points when the Lakers beat the Heat in L.A. two weeks ago. ``I
just try and go out here and give my best performance. At times
they leave me open when they shouldn't. That's kind of hard to
believe at times, but I'm happy for it.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Jackson now believes his team has something special. His
team wonders what took so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a believer. The Big Believer,'' O'Neal
quipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we definitely have always been confident amongst
ourselves in this locker room, '' said Fox. ``But that's a nice
compliment coming from the coach, when you ... take it to another
level and prove to him in his mind that we're definitely
improving.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
