<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE HOPES THIS IS ONLY THE BEGINNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BOSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ The irony is that Jan van Breda Kolff's
Vanderbilt teams played a slow-down, grind-it-out style on offense.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly the same system that Pepperdine players resisted under
Lorenzo Romar.
</P>
<P>
   But van Breda Kolff never considered that type of game for the
Waves. At Vanderbilt, his team lacked depth and speed, two
necessities for a fast-paced, pressing system.
</P>
<P>
   He knew he wouldn't have that problem at Pepperdine, which says
a lot about van Breda Kolff. When he replaced Romar in April, he
looked at the Waves roster and crafted a plan to take advantage of
the team's quickness, size and depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, he let us play,'' point guard Tezale Archie said.
``It's a style that suits us best, being from the West Coast and
wanting to run. And the guys enjoy that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin Gibbs agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows what kind of difference (van Breda Kolff) has made,''
Gibbs said.
</P>
<P>
   Romar wanted the Waves to grind games to halfcourt sets and
pound the ball into the post. Two players Jelani Gardner and Gibbs
provided most of the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a good team, but it was like a slugfest,'' Archie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Transformed under van Breda Kolff, the Waves won a school-record
number of games (25-9) this season, won the regular-season West
Coast Conference championship, gained an at-large berth into the
NCAA Tournament and shocked Indiana 77-57 in the first round of the
East Regional.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine fell 75-67 to Oklahoma State in the second round
Sunday, but as disappointing as the loss was, the Waves made great
strides this year. The key now is taking advantage of the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of the foundation returns next year, including
leading scorer Brandon Armstrong (14.1), starting forward Kelvin
Gibbs (nine points, eight rebounds) and key reserves Craig Lewis
and David Lalazarian.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has NBA-type ability, is able to shoot from the
outside and get to the basket by beating his defender on drives. He
needs to get stronger and be more consistent, but his future is
bright.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs sacrificed offense this year to play a more versatile
role. Next year he'll get more scoring opportunities in the low
post, where his size and strength are a plus. Lewis and Lalazarian
came off the bench, and both are in line for starting jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves are also high on sophomore center Cedric Suitt (6-10)
and freshman forward Boomer Brazzle.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine's success in Buffalo created name recognition for the
program, and that awareness should increase its stature among high
school recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't really know much about Pepperdine outside of the
West Coast and California, other than when Ken Starr was on
(television) a lot,'' van Breda Kolff said. ``Now that we're on
national (television) and in the NCAAs winning games, maybe we can
do some recruiting in the regional areas of the West Coast, start
to get some kids from the East Coast and the Midwest. That will be
an exciting situation.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be holes to fill. Archie, who developed into a
trusted leader, graduates, as do starters Nick Sheppard and Tommie
Prince.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine hopes to minimize those losses with the players
coming back, plus two gifted recruits who the Waves secured in the
early signing period. Forwards Robert Turner (Anaheim Western High)
and Will Kimble (San Bernardino Pacific) are expected to make
immediate contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff envisions a consistently powerful program, the
type that can compete nationally every year. By adding players such
as Turner and Kimble, he may be on his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We signed two (recruits) early that are very good players and
we're involved with a few other excellent players,'' van Breda
Kolff said. ``I think they could really put us in the top 25 range.
If we can get those guys, hopefully we can be a powerhouse on the
West Coast.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
