<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WIZARDS-CLIPPERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIZARDS TROUNCE ODOM-LESS CLIPPERS, 105-93
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Clippers, who seem a bit light on heart,
courage and basketball smarts, thought they had a remedy:
</P>
<P>
   They scheduled a Monday night house call from the Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   Their next move should be suing for malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   Before 11,443 in the waiting room known as Staples Center, the
Clips were pronounced defeated, 105-93, by the 23-45 powerhouse
from Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers (14-54) rolled over against the Wizards by
following the standard format.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I see us winning,'' said Clippers interim coach
Jim Todd, ``is playing defense and shooting over 50 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The only place to see such activity may be the Psychic Hotline.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Todd's team had to play without one of its heroes;
this time it was rookie Lamar Odom (strained right calf). They also
had another cozy, first-quarter lead (23-15 at the 2:05 mark) that
was discarded so that they might spend the second half eating dust.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole key to everything was not having Lamar,'' Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   And the unexpected Washington depth.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers were served a second-quarter slice of humiliation
by the Wizards' bench, which produced a decisive 17-0 run.
Sub-Wizards Tracy Murray (9 points), Chris Whitney (9), Aaron
Williams (6), Richard Hamilton (4) and Don Reid (3) teamed up for
all 31 of Washington's points in that period. Reid, claimed off the
waiver wire from Detroit last week, finished the game with 15
points.
</P>
<P>
   Reid as secret weapon?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a new phrase used with my name,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Wizards' bench went berserk, the mighty Clippers
finished the second quarter with 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   The visiting team had a 55-39 advantage at the break.
</P>
<P>
   Tyrone Nesby scored 20 points to lead the home team. Maurice
Taylor, with less than a month remaining on his Clipper expiration
date, had 15 and 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   And it was almost fun for a moment or two.
</P>
<P>
   Nesby's lay-up at 9:40 of the first quarter made it 8-0
Clippers. His 3-point bomb made 23-15 at 2:05.
</P>
<P>
   But a 3 by Whitney at 9:40 of the second stanza finally pulled
Washington even at 31.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Clippers scored again, Washington led by a
dozen.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards' offense was paced by Mitch Richmond, who bagged 13
of his game-high 21 points in the third quarter. Washington pushed
its lead to 68-49 at 6:51 in that period, but the Clippers rallied
to trail 78-70 leading into round four.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Chilcutt scored 7 points off the bench in that quarter,
which was won by the Clips 31-23.
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't even bother teasing anyone with a fourth-quarter
rally, and Taylor limped to the locker room on a sprained left
ankle at slightly under 4 minutes before it was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just dug ourselves too deep of a hole,'' said Todd, whose
team had the decency to throw the dirt on itself.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: The Atlanta Tipoff Club selected Clippers assistant coach
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar as the Naismith College Basketball Player of
the 20th Century. Abdul-Jabbar, who led UCLA to three national
championships as Lew Alcindor, was chosen by a panel of coaches,
journalists and administrators. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 0210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
