<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3272 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     03-21 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA-MOSLEY A BIG GAMBLE FOR STAPLES CENTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I don't know Tim Leiweke from Tim Robbins or Tim
Conway, but I do know this much about the clean-cut,
youthful-looking, 42-year-old president of Staples Center: he isn't
fearful of taking a risk.
</P>
<P>
   He has plunged feet first into one of the more dangerous
businesses in America _ professional boxing _ quite aware that it
is a field littered with promotional corpses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sleeping very well at night these days,'' claims Leiweke,
the driving force behind bringing the Oscar De La Hoya-Sugar Shane
Mosley welterweight title fight to the new Los Angeles arena on
June 17.
</P>
<P>
   That's a surprising development for a guy who has guaranteed the
promoter of the event, Bob Arum, a minimum $5 million payoff, come
rain, shine or a lousy turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fight is going to do 8 million dollars at the box
office, and I think half of the tickets will be gone by the end of
the week,'' says Leiweke confidently. ``That means we already will
have pocketed $4 million. And I expect by fight time, all the
tickets will be gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a natural attraction for L.A. Two great fighters from
the area. You wouldn't believe how many ticket requests we've
already received from people in the entertainment industry. I
realize the risks involved. We could blow millions. But that won't
happen. Oscar's a great draw.''
</P>
<P>
   But is Oscar De La Hoya such a great draw since his fadeout
against Felix Trinidad?
</P>
<P>
   Was he ever a great draw at the box office without a Julio Cesar
Chavez, or Felix Trinidad as an opponent?
</P>
<P>
   Pay per view phenomenon, yes, but fistic aficionados haven't
exactly stormed the turnstiles to buy expensive tickets to watch
him fight. And many of those people who have sat in ringside seats
at his Las Vegas matches were high-rollers who had their tickets
purchased for them by the casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, De La Hoya did draw a huge crowd once in El Paso for his
three-round farce with Patrick Charpentier, but the tickets prices
were minimal and not faintly comparable to the $900, $700, $500,
$300, $100 and $50 price scale that Arum has established for De La
Hoya's debate with Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   Leiweke is oozing with unrestrained optimism, and that's
understandable in the wake of the stunning success his arena
already has enjoyed since its opening last October 17, with
sellouts being routine for the Lakers, as well as for the Grammy
Awards, Bruce Springsteen, the Eagles, Cher, Bette Midler, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to be the top entertainment venue in the
entertainment capital of the world,'' says Leiweke. ``We just feel
to reach that plateau you have to also get involved in boxing. We'd
like to have at least two major boxing shows a year.''
</P>
<P>
   That might turn out to be the case, but Tim Leiweke has to
realize that boxing is a sport that has a sacred history of leaving
brash newcomers with bright hopes disillusioned and drenched in red
ink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried a bit,'' says Leiweke.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is Bob Arum, a sly fiscal operator whose deal with
Staples also assures him of getting 75 percent of the gate receipts
after he banks the first $5 million from tickets sales and after
Staples takes out for its expenses that's expected to be in the $1
million range.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Leiweke might be right when he says half of the tickets
might be peddled by the weekend especially the 5,500 ones going for
$50 and $100 but getting rid of those next 10,000 might pose a
problem and make him and those people bankrolling him nervous.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt Staples will encounter too many obstacles getting rid of
the quality $900 tickets, but who in their right mind will fork out
$700, or $500, or even $300 to watch De La Hoya after his ignoble
retreat against Trinidad?
</P>
<P>
   Mosley is a quality fighter with exciting skills, and the former
lightweight champion figures to seriously challenge De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   But Mosley doesn't exactly have a passionate following like
Trinidad or Chavez, and there is still skepticism among many fight
fans about his moving up 12 pounds in such a brief time _ he began
fighting at 147 only last September _ to face someone the caliber
of De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   But who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Tim Leiweke knows something I don't know, and that there
are tons of people out there set to gobble up all those $700 and
$500 tickets to assure Staples Center of not suffering a severe
financial setback.
</P>
<P>
   The fighters certainly won't.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya is being guaranteed $8 million, and will get a
percentage of all the other various goodies connected to the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar's take could go as high as $20 million,'' said Bob
Arum's roly-poly mouthpiece, Bill (Bozo) Caplan.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley is being guaranteed $4.5 million, with a percentage of
the pay per view proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sugar Shane could wind up with $8 million,'' said Caplan.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if the fight turnout is as large as the fight press
conference turnout was Monday afternoon at Staples Center _ it had
to be the best-attended one I can recall in L.A. _ then Bob Arum
and Tim Leiweke might, incredibly, still be warm friends after the
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was on their best behavior at the event, and the
typical hyperbole by Bob Arum _ ``this is going to be the biggest
non-heavyweight pay per view show in boxing history'' _ left you
absolutely breathless with anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya was in prime rhetorical form, saying he would be in
the best shape of his life, saying he was not going to run away
from Mosley, saying he had a New Year's Day epiphany in which he
had come to his senses and would ``fight like I used to fight when
my best defense was my offense.''
</P>
<P>
   I've heard it all before, and you can be sure when the fight
starts against Mosley that ol' Oscar will do what he does best _
stick, move, attack once in a while and keep himself at a safe
distance to avoid as much as he can getting hit.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the fight would be a Alexis Arguello-Aaron Pryor-like
classic if De La Hoya doesn't retreat because Mosley certainly
won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm preparing for a war and I will go after Oscar,'' promises
Mosley, and I believe him.
</P>
<P>
   But I have a hard time believing that Staples Center will sell
out for this one, especially with the most reliable ticket buyers
in America _ the Las Vegas casinos _ staying on the sidelines. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 0238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
