<HEADER>
A3282 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-FEMALE-PUTIN-INDEPEND     03-21 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEMALE-PUTIN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAMFILOVA: RUSSIA'S FIRST WOMAN PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Russia's election: Sunday, March 26)   (This timely 775-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By HELEN WOMACK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ ``If only there was woman candidate we could vote for.
The men have made quite enough of a mess in this country with their
aggression, their drunkenness and their corruption. A woman could
hardly do any worse. I would give her a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The speaker was Pavel, a middle-aged man, talking about the
dearth of inspiring politicians in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   If he thought like that, imagine how the millions of
still-downtrodden Russian women felt after all the disappointments
of former President Boris Yeltsin's flawed rule.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this weekend's upcoming presidential elections, they do
have a woman for whom they can vote.
</P>
<P>
   Although, because of Chechnya and the way the establishment has
backed him, acting President Vladimir Putin has a huge advantage in
the election on March 26, it is inaccurate to say that voters are
deprived of choice.
</P>
<P>
   There are no fewer than 11 other candidates, among whom is the
first woman to run for the Russian presidency, the liberal reformer
and former social affairs minister, 46-year-old Ella Pamfilova.
</P>
<P>
   If she won the Kremlin, she would be the first woman to rule
Russia since the Empress Catherine the Great.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, on the eve of International Women's Day,
when Russian women receive token attention from their sexist men,
Pamfilova held a press conference to launch her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Elegant in black velvet in keeping with her soft image, avoiding
any suggestion of strident feminism, she called for ``capitalism
with a human face.'' In 1968 the doomed Czechoslovak leader,
Alexander Dubcek, sought to improve the imperfect system in his
country by advocating ``socialism with a human face.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the economy is important and we should not be thinking of
reversing privatization,'' Pamfilova said, ``but in the process of
market reform, we have not cared enough about human beings. This
has led to national degradation and a sense of hopelessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must invest in job creation, education and science so that
we can compete in the modern world. If we learn to respect
ourselves, others will respect us. But if our social decline
continues, no amount of military might will save us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all the resources we need to get up off our knees by
our own efforts. Russia is a rich country and we simply do not have
the right to live as poorly as we do now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   All of which would be music to the ears of doctors, teachers,
scientists, librarians and artists, the natural middle class
reduced to poverty in the Yeltsin years and the kind of people
Pamfilova sees as her constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Pamfilova, an electronic engineer, first entered politics in
1989 when the last Soviet leader, Mikhail Gorbachev, abolished the
monopoly of the Communist Party and allowed for the election of a
semi-democratic parliament that included some independent MPs.
</P>
<P>
   After Boris Yeltsin defeated the coup in August 1991, Pamfilova
joined his first reforming government as minister for social
affairs. Her personal struggle was always against ``the
indifference of bureaucrats'' and ``the unfairness of privileges,''
a battle that Yeltsin also fought in his early, energetic days.
</P>
<P>
   But while the now-retired Russian leader allowed power to
corrupt him, Pamfilova remained loyal to her ideals. Today she
lives in nothing more luxurious than a two-room apartment with her
husband, daughter, son-in-law and granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first war in Chechnya from 1994-1996 that prompted
Pamfilova to go into opposition against her president. She stayed
on in parliament, campaigning against deputies' rights to immunity
from prosecution and taking part last year in the unsuccessful
attempt to impeach Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Duma elections last December, she lost her seat as
the ``bears'' of the new Unity Party packed parliament to support
Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's first woman presidential candidate admitted that she
had virtually no chance of winning the election but said she had
reason to hope for third or fourth place, which might inspire
younger Russian women coming up behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Pavel said he would be voting for Pamfilova, at least in the
first round of the election. But the women of Russia, who should be
showing her solidarity, looked as if they would betray their
pioneering sister.
</P>
<P>
   They were all going weak at the knees about Putin, described by
one Russian actress as a ``real man.''
</P>
<P>
   On Women's Day, the acting president adopted his softest
``father of the nation'' tone of voice when he said that Russian
women were held back in many ways but had one advantage: ``their
absolute right to be protected by men.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this timely 775-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
