<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 04:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3313 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-INDIA-HITECH-BOOM-RES     03-21 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-HITECH-BOOM-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA'S HIGH-TECH BOOM IS GREAT SUCCESS STORY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Business, Technology Editors)   (RESENDING from Feb. 23 for Clinton-in-India coverage)  
  
 (This 475-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' general/technology news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By HAMISH MCRAE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Indian high-tech boom is one of the great under-publicized
stories of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   For many years the Indian subcontinent has produced talented
computer people who did, in general, head off to the developed
world to make their fortunes. Silicon Valley in California is
attracting upwards of 50,000 of them a year.
</P>
<P>
   True, there was an established software business in India,
located principally around Bangalore, but as recently as 1995
Indian software exports were only $300 million a year. This was
despite the fact that Indian programmers are paid less than half
the rate they would et in the U.S., and are of higher quality too.
</P>
<P>
   You can measure this by counting the errors made in lines of
code and apparently Indian programmers make only one-third as many
mistakes as their U.S. counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, however, the Indian high-technology
sector has moved up a gear. Last year Indian software exports were
nearly $3 billion _ ten times the level of four years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Four things account for this takeoff. Most obviously there is
the Internet, which has both increased demand for computer skills
and make people aware that they can buy such skills from anywhere
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   It has also given a simple online delivery mechanism for
software, which in theory existed before but in practice has become
much easier. Expect this to grow as demand for the Internet booms
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   By 2003 it looks as though there will be more Internet users in
Asia than in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Second, there was the Millennium Bug. Fixing it demanded vast
amounts of competent computer programming time. India could deliver
that in abundance and buyers have now discovered that the people
they thought they had brought in to fix problems could now help
them do much more than just that.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem proved a blessing, for it gave these people an
entree into companies that they would never have got into
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Third, there is the emergence of English as the default language
of the world. Other less developed countries can offer computer
skills, but frequently there is a language barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Few can offer the combination of English and technical
competence. As a result it is not just programmers that are in
demand: India is becoming a call-center, handling the nighttime
calls for a number of U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   This night shift does not just apply to voice traffic. The
development of a true 24-hour world economy has created a demand
for a computer night-shift.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. computer workload can be passed at the end of the
working day to Indian operators who can carry on the software
development _ or simply fix problems _ before America wakes up. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
