<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYSTERY-SADEND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sad end to photo mystery: Air Force officer died in cycle crash
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some stories have happy endings. This one doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Air Force Capt. George Ray Herren, whose Vietnam-era
photographs were published Monday in The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, is dead.
</P>
<P>
   The staff at the Atlanta History Center, who had just mounted a
display of the pictures, knew only that they were taken by an Air
Force captain named Herren. They had hoped the display would help
them find him.
</P>
<P>
   But Herren's widow and two grown daughters, all of whom live in
Atlanta, saw the newspaper story and contacted the History Center.
Herren survived his 1968-69 tour of duty in Vietnam but was killed
in a motorcycle accident in the Philippines in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Gue, a graduate student at Emory University, found the
cache of 300 or so negatives a month ago at a flea market in
southwest Atlanta and gave them to the History Center. The center
mounted the display because the photos show a side of life in
Vietnam that most people don't see: tourist-type pictures that
don't make magazine covers.
</P>
<P>
   Herren's widow, Mayme Herren, 57, said the negatives were stolen
from her home in 1995, along with her wedding ring and other
belongings. She has never remarried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost fainted,'' she said, when she saw Monday's newspaper.
``I knew immediately: `It's my husband.' It was a shock to see the
pictures in the paper. It was the last thing I was expecting to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Herren, a counselor at Fulton County's Price Middle School, said
her husband was killed while the couple was living in the
Philippines with their son and two daughters. Mrs. Herren and the
children returned to her hometown of Mobile, then moved to Atlanta
in 1973 so she could pursue graduate studies at the Atlanta
University Center. Her daughters, Theresa Herren, 28, and Lisa
Herren Blount, 29, also live in the Atlanta area. Theresa is a
district manager for Blockbuster, and Lisa works in human resources
for Sears. Son George Raymond Herren, 32, is an aeronautical
engineer in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Herren, a native of Nacogdoches, Texas, was a mechanical
engineer. After his tour of duty in Vietnam, the family moved to a
base in California, then to another in Minot, N.D., before he was
sent to the Philippines to fly support missions to and from
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have been 30 the year he was killed,'' Mayme Herren
said Monday. ``He's buried in the veterans' cemetery in San
Antonio.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Blount said she has no memories of her father, but she
remembers seeing some of the same photos in family albums.
</P>
<P>
   Family members plan to meet with History Center officials to
discuss the use of the pictures. For its exhibit, the center wants
to include more information about the man who took them, or whose
friends took pictures of him with his camera.
</P>
<P>
   Blount and Herren said they will try to ascertain where Gue got
the negatives, in hopes that the wedding ring might be found too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
