<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Patriotism and pineapples in WWII
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in America. Back then, or at least the
way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Helen Hynes
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   A couple of 5-pound sacks of sugar were among the most precious
household items that my husband and I brought to our furnished
apartment in Chicago when we were married in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Why the sugar? Well, the United States was at war and the
government had imposed a rationing system to ensure supplies for
the armed forces, and also to prevent hoarding.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the imposition of food rationing, I realize that it
was a unique event in the history of our country.
</P>
<P>
   We had all been accustomed to freedom of choice in the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Other countries suffering under the control of dictators might
have restrictions placed on their purchasing power, school
attendance, travel or religion, but never in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   We should have been indignant but we were not.
</P>
<P>
   The infamous bombing of Pearl Harbor on Dec. 7, 1941, had united
our people in such a passion of patriotism that we were almost glad
to have this way of showing our cooperation in the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   With everyone in the same boat, living under that rationing
system became sort of a game.
</P>
<P>
   Going to the market entailed a great deal of figuring because
suddenly there were two prices on most items: the money price and
the point price.
</P>
<P>
   If a can of fruit cost 16 points, it was too expensive. Instead,
you made the best of it with whatever fresh fruit was available.
</P>
<P>
   Butter was also scarce and expensive in ration points.
</P>
<P>
   Margarine had been available before the war but had not been
popular because it was white and looked like lard.
</P>
<P>
   The dairy industry had fought against this cheaper spread and
won to the extent that it could not be colored yellow by the
manufacturer to look like butter.
</P>
<P>
   However, in each package of margarine was a small capsule of
yellow food coloring that could be mixed in by the customer, and
the ration-free margarine quickly became acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   It was a chore that most of us hated, but we did it anyway:
dumping the margarine into a bowl, softening it up with a spoon,
then slowly working in the yellow coloring.
</P>
<P>
   But of all the food items rationed, meat proved the most
difficult for me, since I had grown up eating the best steaks and
roasts from my father's meat market.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, organ meats did not require points. A favorite meal was
boiled beef tongue with mustard sauce, boiled potatoes and spinach.
For leftovers we had cold tongue for sandwiches and beef broth as a
base for vegetable soup.
</P>
<P>
   Each week I would lay out my supply of meat stamps and then make
a shopping list of what I could afford.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, if we were having company, we would splurge and
have a roast, but not often.
</P>
<P>
   One poignant memory comes back to me.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1945 I gave birth to my first son and was kept in the
hospital for several days, suffering from a high fever.
</P>
<P>
   Great efforts were made to bring down the temperature. I was
given a series of shots and had to drink great quantities of water.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, late one night, a nurse announced that the fever had
broken and I could have something to eat.
</P>
<P>
   With that she produced a dish of canned pineapple, something I
had not been able to buy for probably three years.
</P>
<P>
   It was delicious!
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Helen Hynes lives in Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail, jmurray(AT)txucom.net. If your
article is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville
stories, visit http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
