<HEADER>
A3409 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0322-CO     03-21 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0322-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reach anyone no matter your location
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE COUNTY, Ga. _ It's late afternoon, that time of day in the
mountains where the sun seems to hang up for a moment just before
taking a nose-dive behind the nearest hill. The time when I like to
move out onto the deck of my rented cabin-on-stilts, and watch the
woods come alive - deer, raccoons, a possum or two, even an
occasional bear.
</P>
<P>
   But the night life will have to wait a bit. First, I need to pay
a visit to the country store down the road - the one that boils its
own peanuts and has three rocking chairs and a pay phone on the
front porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``No peanuts,'' the lady behind the counter tells me. ``Too
early in the season.'' I pick up some homemade peanut brittle
instead and head for the porch as the screen door slaps familiarly
behind me.
</P>
<P>
   For a minute I stand there in front of the phone, fishing in my
jeans pockets for the long distance calling card I'd slipped in
there earlier. I'm overdue to call my son and let him know I'm well
and happy, down here in the north Georgia mountains.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, I was neither.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven numbers I punched in, carefully following instructions on
the flip side of my card. Okay, fiber-optics, do your thing. Ring
me through to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, that doesn't happen. Instead, a recording tells me
I've done it all wrong and I should hang up and try again. I
express my feelings about this to a dead wire and start over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beep. Beep. Beep. We are sorry. We cannot complete your call
as dialed. Please hang up and try again.''
</P>
<P>
   All-ll right. I'm doing it again. Punch. Pause. Another beep
followed by a whole different set of instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Very deliberately, and with as little visible loss of patience
as I can muster, I prop my calling card on the windowsill and start
over.
</P>
<P>
   DIAL 0 + Area Code + Phone No. LISTEN for tone and AT&AMP;T. ENTER
Card Number. I do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beep. Beep. Beep.'' Now a different voice is reminding me I
must enter my card number AND my PIN number.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's a pin number?'' I catch myself shouting into the
receiver even though I know better than this. There are no humans
left to listen at the phone company. Then I remember how I used to
razz my mother for saying ``Thank you,'' to the time-of-day
recording. She'd remind me that good manners dictate polite
responses - even to a machine.
</P>
<P>
   So I thank the dead mouthpiece, hang up, and repeat the process.
This time, before I can punch in the ``Auth. Code'' which I have
decided may or may not be my PIN number, a voice says it's sorry,
but I've screwed up again and maybe I need to talk to an operator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I KNOW I NEED TO TALK TO AN OPERATOR!'' I yell, ashamed of
myself for being reduced to screaming at dead chrome things on
walls. ``I'd give my last bite of peanut brittle for an operator.
Just tell me how do I do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, there is no answer so I read the card again.
</P>
<P>
   ``DIAL 10 + ATT + 0 + Area Code + Phone No. then ENTER Card
Number after the tone and AT&AMP;T.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't work either. Now I'm shouting. ``I have just pushed
30 buttons in a row and you're telling me that's not good enough? I
demand to talk to a people!'' I'm beginning to draw a crowd. The
rockers are filled and it's SRO for the crazy lady on the phone
show.
</P>
<P>
   I decide to give it one more try and that's when this odd thing
happens. Somewhere around button 14, something sounding remarkably
like a human voice comes on the line and asks how he might help me.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned silence. He asks again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you a recording?'' I ask back. Silence. Finally, I demand
to know: ``Are you, or are you not, a real person?''
</P>
<P>
   His polite response? ``No ma'am. I'm the AT&AMP;T operator.''
</P>
<P>
   Ain't progress just grand?
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
