<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Timely tips for tax season
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three out of four American taxpayers expect to get
refunds from the Internal Revenue Service this year.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans think of that money as a forced savings plan, or
even as a sort of annual bonus from Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Another way of looking at it is this: Your refund was an
interest-free loan to the government. The IRS kept your money for
as much as a year, then gave it back without saying ``thank you''
or rewarding you _ as a bank would _ with an interest payment.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Gallup Poll showed that 46 percent of the 1,000
respondents believe that overpaying their taxes was a good thing
because it prevented them from spending the money as they went
along.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of them spent some or all of their refunds, mostly
for fun or travel. Somewhat larger percentages said they put refund
money into paying bills or savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   They moved the money along quickly, too. About a third spent or
saved their refunds within a week, and 69 percent had disposed of
the money within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   The refunds build up when employees have too much money withheld
for taxes from each paycheck. They get the money back the following
year, in refunds.
</P>
<P>
   That is not necessarily a bad thing. ``If you don't have any
other way of saving, it's a good idea,'' said John W. Masters, a
certified public accountant in Atlanta. ``The idea is that if you
have it taken out of your pay, you can't decide to spend it.
Frankly, that was my salvation as a younger person.''
</P>
<P>
   But if you have self-discipline, you're better off keeping and
saving the money by yourself. It's easy enough to arrange: Go to
the payroll department where you work and change the amount you
have withheld from your paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can call (800) 829-1040, ask the IRS to send you
Publication 919 or Publication 505, and figure it out yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can do just about anything you want, and it's OK as long
as it's enough to pay your taxes,'' Masters said. ``The real risk
is that you'll end up owing more than you withheld. It's a shock
having to come up with an extra $500 or $1,000 or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   For those with self-discipline, Masters suggests setting up a
direct deposit to a credit union or other financial institution.
The money comes out of your paycheck and marches into your savings
account automatically.
</P>
<P>
   You never get your hands on it, which is the same advantage you
get with too-generous withholding. You also get some interest
payments, which Uncle Sam does not provide.
</P>
<P>
   If you get a refund this year, here are some rewarding ways to
use the money:
</P>
<P>
   _ Invest it in a tax-deferred retirement account. The average
refund last year was $1,542. If you dropped that amount into an
individual retirement account and achieved an average annual return
of 10 percent, you would have $10,374 in 20 years or $26,907 in 30
years. It's a nice start on a retirement savings program.
</P>
<P>
   A Roth individual retirement account is probably the most
beneficial for younger investors.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to pay taxes now on the money you contribute, and
higher-income people could bump their heads on the income ceiling.
But you will owe no taxes at all when you start taking the money
out, assuming you meet certain minimal requirements.
</P>
<P>
   _ Save it for earlier goals. You might get a head start on
buying a house or paying for college for your children.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pay debts. That feels good, too, especially if you're knocking
off high-interest credit card bills.
</P>
<P>
   _ Start an emergency fund. That will feel really good if you
lose your job or run into some other disaster.
</P>
<P>
   _ Give some to charity. It's a case of feeling good by doing
good. You might also get a deduction on next year's taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it's a question of what makes you happiest. You can
reward yourself with a splurge right now, or you can do the
responsible thing and reward yourself later.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, you could split the money between current and future
goodies. That's what many of the Gallup Poll respondents did and it
is what I would do.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
