<HEADER>
A3412 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BELLY-DANCERS22-COX     03-21 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLY-DANCERS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Belly dancing moves women to accept their bodies
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By JoLee Hammer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Belly dancing is not your mother's two-step.
It's not even her Lambada.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's better because it's all about being a woman _ in
a way that Shania Twain can't touch. But she probably could learn a
few things on Friday nights when Melodee Huey teaches three classes
of women more than just how to slide their hips and crunch their
stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   She teaches them how to love themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started dancing, my stomach had not seen daylight since
1976,'' said Huey, a Mineola resident. ``Like most women I was
never, ever, ever comfortable with my body. I never was pleased
with it. I was always too short, too chubby, too, too, too
something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I began to belly dance, I started accepting my body and
understanding that I'm supposed to be round. I'm a woman,'' Huey
continued. ``It's nothing to be ashamed of. Even those that are
rounder than some have nothing to be ashamed of. Even those whose
hips are wider have nothing to be ashamed of.''
</P>
<P>
   Huey has been belly dancing for about six years. She began
teaching classes this winter at the Panther Park Community Center
in Longview through the city's parks and recreation department. The
course attracted more students than anticipated, and what was
originally supposed to be one class became three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't turn away a woman who wants to belly dance,'' Huey
said one night during class, as she begged for a break, explaining
that she already had taught two other classes that night.
</P>
<P>
   But Huey wasn't complaining. Her smile is almost a constant
fixture on her face as she dances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would really like to spend the rest of my healthy life
teaching, and as long as there are women who want to learn, and it
won't cost me money to teach, then I will continue to teach,'' Huey
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to see the challenge Huey faced as she stood before
the group of women who gathered the first night of class. The women
were excited. But some were stiff that first night, timidly copying
Huey as she demonstrated the ``isolation techniques'' that are the
root of belly dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Isolation techniques concentrate on moving specific parts of the
body while the rest of the body remains still. Rib cage slides move
the upper body from side to side at the waist, while the hips and
shoulders remain immobile. Figure eight hips make an ``8'' on the
floor or the wall, depending on how the hips are moved, while the
upper body doesn't move.
</P>
<P>
   Huey urges her students to be patient with themselves as they
learn the isolation techniques. She seems to read some of her
students' minds through the fear in their eyes that says ``my
mother told me not to move like this.''
</P>
<P>
   But the way Huey explains it, maybe our mothers should have. As
she explained at the beginning of class, belly dancing began as a
physical and spiritual preparation for childbirth thousands of
years ago. Several women would surround another who was in labor,
rolling their stomachs and breathing in a way that resembles
present-day Lamaze to help facilitate the birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just do what comes naturally with a smile,'' Huey said.
</P>
<P>
   Huey, who previously was a classical style dancer, knows some
are skeptical about belly dancing. She was one of those people. Her
husband's mother was a belly dancer, and he encouraged his wife to
learn also.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `Excuse me. I'm a dancer,' '' she said. ``I was
real snobby about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But it changed her life when she started. First, it made her a
lot busier, but Huey said it also increased her self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave me a sense of self that I had never quite been able to
get a handle on,'' Huey said. ``I haven't been real successful at a
lot of endeavors. I made good grades in school, but I didn't finish
(college). ... It's given me something that is really going to be a
part of my life for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like a rebirth,'' she added. ``I started
studying ancient history, other cultures, other religions, other
literature. ... I started sewing again, which I thought I would
never do. It was kind of like a Renaissance for me.''
</P>
<P>
   As the weeks of class progressed, it was easy to see that Huey's
lack of self-consciousness had rubbed off on her students. Some
made traditional belly dance costumes to wear to class. The
stiffness from the first class melted with each passing Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Huey showed infinite patience at each class, never laughing or
ridiculing students if their bodies weren't quite moving in the
right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to know that everybody dances at their own
level,'' she said. ``My goal as an instructor is not to produce
performers every time. My goal as an instructor is to produce women
who will belly dance. Everyone's on their own level, and you just
have to understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Huey still takes lessons herself, and is part of a performing
group called ``The Dream Harem'' that performs at Renaissance fairs
and other functions. They occasionally perform at Bernard's
Mediterranean Restaurant in Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best teacher is the perpetual student,'' she said. ``I
truly believe in all my heart that if you had three lifetimes to
spend studying (belly dance) you would never learn it all. It's a
living changing entity all its own. It's so ancient that there's
just so much to know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
