A3413 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-POISON-PREVENTION22-C     03-21 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POISON-PREVENTION22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Protection from poison
 &HT;    By Christine Moran
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ Child resistant doesn't mean childproof.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, more than a million children nationwide younger than
age 5 were exposed to potentially poisonous substances.
</P>
<P>
   The 39th annual observance of National Poison Prevention Week is
March 19-25. As always, the focus is prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education and awareness are the keys to prevention,'' said
Brenda Street, poison prevention coordinator for the Carolinas
Poison Center in Charlotte. ``If parents and child-care providers
know the dangers, they can prevent most injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   The home is supposed to be a safe haven. All too often it isn't.
The home poses many threats, especially for young children.
Household cleaners, cosmetics, medicines, pesticides and even some
plants are hazards found in almost all homes.
</P>
<P>
   The saying ``out of sight, out of mind'' is perfect when
referring to poison safety and children, said Karen Ramsey, Nash
County Health Department's health education supervisor. To
understand it best, she urges all parents to act like a child for
half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get down on the ground and start crawling,'' Ramsey said.
``Put yourself in your child's position. On your hands and knees,
make your way around your house like a child would and look for
potentially harmful substances, like plants or cleaners.''
</P>
<P>
   Children learn by exploring the world around them. They're
constantly touching and tasting everything they see. As a child's
mobility increases, so does their ability to reach for a dangerous
product.
</P>
<P>
   Children younger than 5 can't read. They rely on their senses to
help feed their curiosity. If something smells good, looks colorful
and resembles a piece of candy, they'll ingest it.
</P>
<P>
   So don't keep products unattended while using them, Street said.
And use child-resistant products whenever possible, but don't place
too much faith in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a label reads child resistant, it gives parents a false
sense of security,'' Street said. ``Everyday children break into
child-resistant containers. Parents still have to be cautious. It's
best to keep any potentially hazardous substances under lock and
key.''
</P>
<P>
   If a child ingests a potentially hazardous substance, Street
urges parents to call the poison center at (800) 848-6946 or (800)
84TOXIN. Certified specialists in poison prevention are on-hand 24
hours a day, seven days a week, ready to address any and all
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Oftentimes a certified poison prevention specialist will advise
a parent to feed their child activated charcoal, a substance which
can be bought at most pharmacies. Activated charcoal is specially
processed charcoal that is packaged in a fine power form. When
mixed with a liquid and ingested, the formula absorbs any foreign
chemicals in the body and passes them through one's system the
following day.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts warn parents against taking matters into their own
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents get scared and they want to do something, but all too
often they make the situation worse,'' said Cindy Hayes, supervisor
in children's health at Edgecombe County Health Department. ``Some
give their children milk. Others induce vomiting. But really no
action should be taken until you call for help first.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
