r l BC-PSYCHOLOGY-COLUMN22-C     03-21 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHOLOGY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Try simple steps to avoid road rage
 &HT;    By Hap LeCrone
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ A reader recently sent the following request:
``Dear. Dr. LeCrone: My husband is, generally speaking, a
reasonable acting and pleasant individual. However, when he gets
behind the wheel of the car he often ``snaps'' and turns into a
monster. The aggressive driving he displays is what is known as
``road rage.'' His personality changes so that if he feels in any
way violated by another driver or traffic condition he begins
swearing, grips the steering wheel until his knuckles become white
and would probably shoot someone if he had gun. This condition is
not good for his health, the other drivers or our family because
our life is literally in his hands. Do you have any suggestions
that might help him?''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Road Rage Passenger: St. Basil, a fourth century religious
figure, called anger a kind of temporary madness. Individuals
suffering from road rage are more likely to speed, tailgate, fail
to yield, weave in and out of traffic, pass on the right, make
improper lane changes, run stop signs and lights, make hand and
facial gestures, scream, honk and flash their lights. Perhaps the
worse thing you can do to a road rage prone individual is issue
them the universal sign of disdain, the middle finger salute.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the following behaviors can trigger road rage:
</P>
<P>
   _ Tailgating.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shining the high beam of headlights in their rear view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   _ Using the horn, especially in traffic or at stop lights.
</P>
<P>
   _ Changing lanes without signaling.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blocking a passing lane.
</P>
<P>
   Learning to manage anger, including road rage, is often a
difficult task. This is especially true if the individual feels
that his or her anger is warranted.
</P>
<P>
   In some instances, the most effective way to control this
problem is for the road rage-prone individual to take several
moments before starting the car and mentally rehearsing a set of
feelings and behaviors that don't include road rage. After taking
several deep breaths, the individual can imagine and verbalize (out
loud if necessary) the importance of driving safely in an often
inherently dangerous situation. Further, he can practice stating to
himself that rude and reckless drivers are nondiscriminating,
uncivilized individuals with impaired judgment and the temperament
of a severely annoyed rattlesnake. They can also remember that
inconveniences such as traffic jams and roads under construction
are no reason to endanger oneself or others by acting in an
impulsive fashion.
</P>
<P>
   By using this or a similar technique, your husband might
decrease his frequency of road rage and thus relieve your anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hap LeCrone is a Waco clinical psychologist. His column
appears in the Waco Tribune-Herald. If you have questions or topics
you would like Dr. LeCrone to discuss, write him 4555 Lake Shore
Drive, Waco, TX 76710 or e-mail him at hlecrone(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
