<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3415 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CRABGRASS22-COX     03-21 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRABGRASS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forsythia wasn't a sign to treat for crabgrass
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ One rule of thumb for crabgrass control is that
you should apply a pre-emergent crabgrass-control agent by the time
forsythia bushes start to bloom. That rule is out the window this
year, said Mark Webber of Mark Webber Landscaping Co.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the forsythia bushes in the area were full of their
bright-yellow flowers last week, but they bloomed at least a month
earlier than normal.
</P>
<P>
   Crabgrass seeds probably were germinating in the soil at the
same time the forsythias were blooming. But like many of the
premature blooms from last week, any crabgrass that sprouted
probably was killed by last weekend's cold snap.
</P>
<P>
   WAIT A WHILE BEFORE ATTACKING CRABGRASS
</P>
<P>
   Webber said the best time to apply a crabgrass agent is still
late March and early April, the same time crabgrass preventers are
applied in normal years.
</P>
<P>
   The bluegrass and fescue breeds most people prefer in their
lawns are perennial plants. They go dormant in cold weather, but
they revive and spread as the soil warms.
</P>
<P>
   Crabgrass is an annual plant. Crabgrass plants die in the late
fall and drop seeds that wait until spring to sprout.
</P>
<P>
   Crabgrass-control chemicals work by attacking the seeds as they
germinate so that the crabgrass doesn't get a chance to mature.
However, the chemicals don't stay in the soil very long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is to have the crabgrass agent on the ground while
the bulk of the germination is going on,'' Webber said. ``That
happens when the soil temperature goes up and stays up.''
</P>
<P>
   Before worrying about applying a crabgrass-control agent, you
should first be sure you have a crabgrass problem.
</P>
<P>
   A healthy lawn is covered with an even, dense growth of grass
plants where mostly grass blades rather than stems are visible.
</P>
<P>
   Crabgrass plants show lots of stem, and the stems and grass
blades tend to sprawl on the ground rather than growing upright.
</P>
<P>
   Crabgrass blades come to a point and are about a quarter-inch
wide. Large crabgrass, the most common variety, has fine hairs on
the tops of the grass blades. A mature crabgrass plant produces a
crest of fingerlike seed pods.
</P>
<P>
   In the height of summer, crabgrass may blend in with the rest of
the lawn. Except for its coarse, stemmy look, you might not notice
it.
</P>
<P>
   But with the first frost of fall, the crabgrass dies. That can
leave brown, bare spots in the places where crabgrass has displaced
perennial grass.
</P>
<P>
   If you have remnants of plants around your yard that fit the
crabgrass description, or if you have bare spots where grass was
growing last summer, applying a crabgrass-control chemical along
with your early spring fertilizer is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   HOW ARE YOUR EVERGREENS DOING?
</P>
<P>
   The odd warm spell we had in late February and early March isn't
the only unusual climatic condition our plants are dealing with,
Webber said. We're also in the midst of several years of
below-average rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   That's particularly hard on evergreen trees, Webber said.
``People are seeing needles dropping and limbs dying back, and the
problem is that 90 percent of the population doesn't call until the
plant is two-thirds dead, and that's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Liz Cramer, horticulturist for Siebenthaler Nurseries, said
people don't usually realize their evergreens are in trouble until
they're in bad shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look at Christmas trees,'' she said. ``They're cut down
in the fall, and they still can look healthy when you throw them
away in January.''
</P>
<P>
   Cramer said one sign of health that should be monitored is
budding _ the tips of limbs should have live buds.
</P>
<P>
   Also look for branches that are obviously dead and browning.
Look for excessive insect infestation and signs of fungus attacking
the wood.
</P>
<P>
   Webber and Cramer said most evergreens don't like either too
much water or too little. The stress of too little rainfall has
been building up in local trees for more than five years.
</P>
<P>
   Webber said tree owners should look for signs that their
evergreens are not flourishing and call in a professional if they
suspect trouble. ``If we catch the problems early enough, there are
often ways a tree can be saved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cramer said it's important to keep trees watered during drought
periods. Trees need about an inch of rainfall a week, and, when not
much rain is falling, the tree owner needs to step in.
</P>
<P>
   Lawn sprinklers that spray water in the air over a large area of
grass aren't best for trees. Trees need water on their roots, not
branches.
</P>
<P>
   A soaker hose or sprinkler hose placed on the ground under the
branches does the best job. Remember that the roots of the tree
usually spread out underground from the trunk of the tree to about
as far as the branches extend outward.
</P>
<P>
   A gradual, thorough soaking that moistens the first inch of soil
once a week is better than several lighter sprinklings several
times a week.
</P>
<P>
   If your evergreen has dead branches, but you don't want to call
in a professional arborist, Cramer said you shouldn't start cutting
the dead branches away immediately. Most evergreens aren't like
leaf-shedding trees, which usually tolerate late winter pruning
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait until late summer to remove dead branches, and think
before you cut,'' Cramer said. ``Branches on tree evergreens don't
grow back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
