r f BC-TESTDRIVE-HONDA22-COX     03-21 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-HONDA22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Honda S2000 roadster a fun, hot item
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Honda's high-profile S2000, an all-new and virtually
hand-built head-turner, comes with all the classic characteristics
of a real sports car. It's as quick as credit card debt, hangs on
like a bad reputation, is as noisy as a jackhammer and rides like a
pogo stick.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it's delightful. And that's why would-be buyers and
sellers are prompting inflated prices, with some classified ads
appearing in cities offering nearly new cars for as much as
$38,500.
</P>
<P>
   Bear in mind that this is a car base-priced at $32,000; the
tester with add-on floor mats totaled $32,477. Honda hopes the
market will perceive it as offering more performance than cheaper
performance convertibles (the Mazda Miata and Ford Mustang, for
example) and being a bargain compared with its performance peers
(Chevrolet's Corvette and Porsche's Boxster, for example).
</P>
<P>
   Early reviews give Honda execs grins akin to those of first-time
drivers. Automobile magazine calls the S2000 a ``tech-head's
dream,'' Consumer Guide says it's a ``bargain'' packed with
performance and Honda quality, and Road &AMP; Track finds it
``stylish'' and ``exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The drivetrain is superb. Honda found 240 horsepower in its
2.0-liter, four-cylinder engine _ quite an accomplishment for a
street-legal car _ and hooked it to a six-speed transmission that
requires only a flick of the wrist to shift. The problem is
avoiding premature shifts because the engine redlines at 9,000 rpm,
with peak power and torque at 7,500-8,500 rpm.
</P>
<P>
   Despite getting virtually everything right, Honda did manage to
include one bit of foppery: To crank the S2000, turn on the
column-mounted ignition switch to the right of the steering wheel,
then push the large red button reading ``engine start'' on the dash
to the left of the wheel. It reminds one of 1940s and '50s
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The interior is a comfy cocoon for two. Seats are body-fitting
hip to head, and controls can be finger-operated without really
taking a hand off the wheel. But the power cloth top (up or down in
about six seconds) and plastic rear window cut visibility. Drivers
who rest their arm on the wide center tunnel while cruising or
shifting gears may find the drink holder and storage hole
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   But the aggravations are minor in view of what the S2000
delivers.
</P>
<P>
   Purists may even forgive the digital speedometer and tachometer
arched across the speedo because of the ease and speed with which
they run up the scale.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 2000 Honda S2000 roadster
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $32,477 (base: $32,000, plus $415 delivery)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 2.0-liter four-cylinder engine with 16 valves (240
horsepower), six-speed manual transmission
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual air bags, anti-lock disc brakes, roll bars
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: floor mats, $62
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 20 mpg premium unleaded city, 26 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1109EST &QL; 
