<SLUG> BC-OSCARS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oscar nominees' talent shines through in previous performances
 &HT;    By Steve Uhler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gearing up for the annual ritual of the Oscars
is kind of like embarking on a new love affair: A lot of foreplay
and speculation, the Big Event itself, and, depending on the
outcome, either a satisfied smile or a morning-after headache.
</P>
<P>
   While you can't watch this year's nominated performances on
video or DVD yet, it's a perfect time to look back at some of the
nominees' earlier performances that helped get them to where they
are today. Here's a sampling:
</P>
<P>
   Best Actor nominee (``American Beauty'') Kevin Spacey is
arguably the most admired actor in movies, creating a gallery of
unforgettable characters, and he just keeps getting better. Savor
his breakthrough role as clubfooted chatterbox Verbal Kint in
1995's clever ``The Usual Suspects.'' It was a dream part, and the
versatile Spacey made the most of it in a tour-de-force
performance, winning him the Oscar that year for Best Supporting
Actor (where he memorably thanked Keyser Soze as he accepted the
award.)
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to remember a year in which Meryl Streep hasn't
received a Best Actress nomination (this year's is for ``Music of
the Heart''); her nominations are as ubiquitous as her dialects.
She's been nominated 12 times and won twice, as Best Supporting
Actress for her role as the conflicted mother who deserts her child
in ``Kramer vs. Kramer'' (1979), and Best Actress for her wrenching
performance as a Polish prisoner-of-war at Auschwitz who must
decide which of her two children will live in ``Sophie's Choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Best Actress nominee, Annette Bening has not had that
many high-impact, showcase roles. Her best performance is in Steven
Frears' gritty ``The Grifters'' (1990), where, as manipulative and
ambitious femme fatale Myra, she schemes to get boyfriend and
small-time con artist Roy (John Cusack) into the big leagues. It's
a great, eye-opening turn _ but inevitably upstaged by Angelica
Huston as Lily, Roy's seen-it-all, ``reformed'' mom. When Myra
introduces herself as ``Roy's friend,'' the savvy Lily looks her
down and smiles, ``Yes, I imagine you're lots of people's friend.''
And the claws are out.
</P>
<P>
   Best Actor nominee for ``The Straight Story,'' 79-year-old
Richard Farnsworth may not have the most high-profile acting career
but, after 53 years in the profession, he's had one of the most
enduring. He made his film debut in the Marx Brothers' 1937 classic
``A Day At The Races'' and has been going ever since. Farnsworth
finally achieved stardom in 1982 when he starred as ``The Grey
Fox,'' an over-the-hill gentleman bandit in 1901 who, after serving
33 years in San Quentin prison, is released into the 20th century _
where there are no stagecoaches to rob. It's an elegiac, wistful
performance in a wonderful film.
</P>
<P>
   The academy passed on Tom Cruise this year for Stanley Kubrick's
lethargic ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' but he did get a nod for his
supporting turn in ``Magnolia'' as sex guru Frank T.J. Mackey.
Cruise first gained attention as the entrepreneurial teen in 1990's
``Risky Business,'' but didn't get respect until his powerful
performance as hustler Charlie Babbitt, Dustin Hoffman's
self-centered brother, in ``Rain Man'' (1988). He was even better
as real-life veteran Ron Kovic in Oliver Stone's ``Born On The
Fourth of July'' (1989), convincingly evolving from patriotic teen
to embittered paraplegic activist.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Uhler writes about movies for the Austin
American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
