<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3422 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN22-COX     03-21 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For gun lobby, ounce of prevention is worth pound of blather
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The talking head of the Gun Owners Association
appeared cool, composed and not in need of medication.
</P>
<P>
   So why was he talking about pill bottles?
</P>
<P>
   Well, because they're suddenly relevant to gun control, that's
why. Here. The association has a position paper on it.
</P>
<P>
   Through its chromium-throated spokesman, the association was
voicing outrage over Smith &AMP; Wesson's agreement to sell external,
unremovable trigger locks with its handguns, among other
concessions to the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Safety measures like this won't make people safer, the gun lobby
says. As an example, it points to a Harvard University study
asserting that child-resistant medicine-bottle caps have resulted
in 3,500 additional poisonings of small children annually. Really?
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, parents let down their guard because of
child-safety caps, making the world less safe.
</P>
<P>
   Fascinating. Comparing apples to deer droppings, but
fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Apples: Show of hands, now. Who wishes, in the name of safety,
to ban the use of child-resistant medicine caps? (You can ask your
pharmacist that your pill bottles not have them. That's another
matter.) I didn't think many of you would ban child-proof caps. You
know they're worth having.
</P>
<P>
   Deer droppings: The gun lobby will peddle anything to stall
reasoned efforts to keep guns out of the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   At its root, the gun lobby's base argument against trigger locks
is that they are an impediment to split-second use. That might be
valid if every gun were locked every moment. But the definition of
a gun lock is that it can be unlocked. So one who doesn't want to
lock his or her gun wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   In gun locks, as with any other form of merchandise, you get
what you pay for. You can either get one that can be easily
compromised by a child, or one that baffles the owner.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Smith &AMP; Wesson is confident that the combination
trigger locks it plans will meet the test.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is a spurious argument that trigger locks are a
danger in and of themselves, just like that rhetorical flier on
medicine bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Just as one could leave his Smith &AMP; Wesson gun unlocked even
with its built-in gizmo, one could leave his pill bottles open so
as not to hassle with a child-proof cap. That person had better not
have children around in either case.
</P>
<P>
   Only because we have come to think of a handgun as something as
common as a cantaloupe do we have arguments about things like this.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine auto manufacturers disputing the need for keys to the
car. No argument. You are within your rights to leave the keys in
the ignition in the driveway, just as you would be with your
handgun unlocked on your nightstand even with a mandatory trigger
lock as the U.S. Senate would require.
</P>
<P>
   A lock's simple function is to give the owner control over who
uses something of value. If a gun owner chooses not to use a
trigger lock, he proceeds at his considerable risk if he has
children in the home.
</P>
<P>
   The gun lobby proceeds to do what it can to stall and ensnare
reasoned efforts to keep guns out of the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   It is fascinating these days to hear, as the National Rifle
Association's new No. 1 position, that the federal government isn't
doing enough to enforce the laws on the books. You'd almost think
it supported those laws, like Brady background checks for gun
sales. The fact is that the NRA fought Brady with all of its might.
And the only reason we needed Brady was to enforce laws that were
already on the books banning gun sales to felons, minors, illegal
aliens and others.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to keep up with the gun lobby. But don't stop trying.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
