<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3423 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BASS-LAKE22-COX     03-21 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASS-LAKE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    World-class bass lake's fish could all be dead in 2 years
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Lake Okeechobee has long been known as
one of the top bass lakes in the world, but some say soon that may
be nothing but a memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the conditions of the lake remain the same, in two years,
there will be no fish in the lake,'' said Steve Gornak, biologist
with the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission in
Okeechobee.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate crisis, he said, is caused by the abnormally high
water level of the lake _ 15.3 feet. ``There are supposed to be
periods of naturally high and naturally low levels of water. But
the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers is using the lake as a reservoir.
Their schedule for releasing the water is causing high water levels
even when they do release.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsh and lake-bottom vegetation crucial to the fish and
wildlife is being destroyed by wave action caused by the deeper
water, Gornak said. Young fish, nesting birds and wildlife are
beginning to disappear.
</P>
<P>
   The corps is responsible for maintaining the lake level. At a
recent meeting with lake residents, biologists and environmental
groups, the engineers agreed the lake was now being used as a
reservoir and said they would be lowering the level, but they
hedged on saying how much and when.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Gray, manager of the Audubon Society's Lake Okeechobee
sanctuaries, acknowledges the lake must be used for water storage
but, he said, ``it has to be managed with the lake's health in
mind. And while the current level is the single most important
threat to the health of the lake, it's not the only one.''
</P>
<P>
   Phosphorus levels in the lake are high, the result of runoff
from farms and dairies around the lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely in trouble,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Head of Okeechobee has organized a Friends of the Lake
organization, a nonprofit group dedicated to saving the lake. For
more information, call (863) 763-3568.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
