<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Sometimes a point seems so obvious you don't
realize it has gone mostly unrecognized until someone finally makes
it out loud. Thus with U.S. Education Secretary Richard Riley's
mention that in its immigrant population, the United States has a
potentially huge advantage over most other nations in an
internationalizing world. Riley has put the Clinton administration
_ and one hopes, beyond that, U.S. policy _ strongly behind a form
of bilingual education that mixes English-speaking students with
classmates reared in other tongues, with the objective of making
both sets fluent in both languages. (Teepen, Cox News Service.)
MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Here is my dilemma: In the past week, I
became the owner of one of those Palm mini-computers (maybe that's
the wrong noun but anything that whirs and remembers is a computer
to me.) I also got a new does-everything cellular telephone, on
which you even can play games. Not long ago, my wife bought a new
video camera; one that is digital and is supposed to interface
(that's another word for ``work with'') her desktop computer. I
must tell you that we are inundated with digital befuddlement.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE _ A couple of
5-pound sacks of sugar were among the most precious household items
that my husband and I brought to our furnished apartment in Chicago
when we were married in 1942. Looking back at the imposition of
food rationing, I realize that it was a unique event in the history
of our country. (Hynes, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
