<P>
   PERSONAL FINANCE
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Your tax refund was an interest-free loan to the
government. The IRS kept your money for as much as a year, then
gave it back without saying ``thank you'' or rewarding you _ as a
bank would _ with an interest payment. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   ROCKWELL _ His life has become something of a national joke, but
how good is Rick Rockwell, erstwhile marrying-multimillionaire, at
delivering a joke? We talk him up and check him out at the
Punchline. (Harris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY-SADEND _ The mystery about an Air Force officer shown in
a cache of Vietnam photos found b an Emory student doesn't have a
happy ending. The officer, a native of Nacogdoches, texas, was
killed in a cycle accident in the Philippines in 1972. (Hendrick,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POISON-PREVENTION _ ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ Child resistant doesn't
mean childproof. Last year, more than a million children nationwide
younger than age 5 were exposed to potentially poisonous
substances. The 39th annual observance of National Poison
Prevention Week is March 19-25. As always, the focus is prevention.
(Moran, Rocky Mount Telegram). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BELLY-DANCERS _ LONGVIEW, Texas _ Belly dancing is not your
mother's two-step. It's not even her Lambada. Actually, it's better
because it's all about being a woman _ in a way that Shania Twain
can't touch. But she probably could learn a few things on Friday
nights when Melodee Huey teaches three classes of women more than
just how to slide their hips and crunch their stomachs. She teaches
them how to love themselves. (Hammer, Longview News-Journal) MOVED.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   PSYCHOLOGY-COLUMN _ Dr. Hap LeCrone's weekly psychology column.
This week: Controlling road rage. (LeCrone, Waco Tribune-Herald).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-ROMEO _ Movie review of ``Romeo Must Die.'' (StMurray,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-MUSEUM _ HOUSTON _ As Atlanta's Woodruff Arts Center
collaborates on a master plan with Renzo Piano that will include,
probably in its first phase, an expansion for the High Museum of
Art, Houston's Museum of Fine Arts is opening its own Texas-sized
expansion Saturday March 25. On a press preview tour of the new
facility, we'll talk to MFA director Peter Marzio, Spanish
architect Rafael Moneo and others about the mission set for this
enormous building, and how that compares that with what the High
Museum is trying to do with its planned expansion. Michael Shapiro,
acting director at the High, has seen the Houston expansion and
comments for us. (Sabulis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40. WITH
PHOTO. (Handout art of the museum exterior and interior)
</P>
<P>
   WITH _ If You Go box.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM-SIDE _ List of other new art museums and spaces going up
in Texas building boom. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 5.
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS _ Oscar nominees' talent shines through in previous
performances. (Uhler, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   CRABGRASS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ One rule of thumb for crabgrass
control is that you should apply a pre-emergent crabgrass-control
agent by the time forsythia bushes start to bloom. That rule is out
the window this year, said Mark Webber of Mark Webber Landscaping
Co. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ A gardening column by Lee May. This Week: Lee
extols the pleasures of bamboo. Yes, bamboo. In all its
incarnations _ good, bad, lovely, reluctant, Lee says it is as much
a harbinger of spring as any of the flowers whose scents and petals
arrest beautifully. (May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, March 23.
</P>
<P>
   ORGANIC-GARDENS _ Gardeners can go the all-natural route to
growing their veggies. A look at organic gardening. (Moran, Rocky
Mount Telegram). 20. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   REMODEL-MAIN _ Home remodeling renovations that turned
nightmarish because of shoddy work by contractors, who gouge
homeowners with cost overruns or some who take the money and never
return to do the work. Some disputes are in arbitration, others in
litigation and a few even under criminal investigation so names of
contractors were not included. Story provides tips on how to find a
contractor, things to ask a potential contractor, contract writing
and general homeowner information. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, March 23.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: The Atlanta Journal-Constitution Home and Garden editors
asked readers to share their remodeling experiences. Here are three
responses that show what can happen when communication, competence
and commitment are at stake.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   REMODEL-COLLINS _ Bob and Joyce Collins an elderly East Point
couple talk about how their contractor required a 50 percent
deposit of $825 for a shower installation project. The contractor
returned to the couple's home, tore up the bathroom, left them a
set of 2x4s in the bathroom, but never returned to complete the
project. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, March 23.
</P>
<P>
   REMODEL-LIEVENS _ Not all home remodeling projects are
nightmares, there was at least one couple_Geert and Debra Lievens
of Garden Hills_ who had a positive experience with their
contractor from beginning to end. We find out what the Lievens did
to avoid any trouble. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, March 23.
</P>
<P>
   REMODEL-GOOD _ Rick and Vicki Good of Ormewood Park wanted to
upgrade their kitchen, add a bath and create a master suite. They
Goods interviewed several contractors and settled on one. But after
almost two years, their contractor has not finished the project and
the Goods are out more than $60,000. The contractor (who can't be
found) has placed a lien on the couple's home because they refused
to meet project payment schedules listed in their contract.
(Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, March 23.
</P>
<P>
   RESOURCE-LIST _ Homeowners resource list that includes phone
numbers, addresses and web sites for Atlanta area and national
agencies that provides consumer information on appliances,
remodeling, roofing, windows, heating systems, insulation, lighting
and more. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
