   Editors for publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service for
 &UR; WEDNESDAY, March 22  &LR; of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INDIA (New Delhi) _ Bill Clinton's day in India, where
he deplores new violence in Kashmir, issues a ``vision statement''
with Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee and visits the
Gandhi memorial. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-KASHMIR (New Delhi) _ Forty Sikh villagers in India's
disputed region of Kashmir were executed by gunmen Monday night.
Indian officials blamed militant groups supported by the Pakistani
government. (Summary from wires.) By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-HOLYLAND (Jerusalem) _ Pope John Paul II arrived in Israel
Tuesday on the first diplomatic visit ever by a pope to the Jewish
state, welcomed by warm words from political leaders, prayers and a
military fanfare. By Alessandra Stanley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POPE-HOLYLAND-BAPTISM (Wadi Kharrar) _ On the scene with pope as
he visited the site where Jordan says Jesus was baptized. By Joel
Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WESTBANK (Jerusalem) _ Israel made its long-delayed
withdrawal from 6.1 percent of West Bank, giving Palestinians full
control over 40 percent of the disputed area. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Israel-Palestinian peace talks
resume in Washington. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ The people of Kosovo risk
losing the goodwill and backing of the international community if
they do not put ethnic hatred aside, NATO Secretary-General George
Robertson said Tuesday in a report three days before the
anniversary of the start of the NATO campaign against Serbia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-WRITER (Bane) _ Five years after the writer Ken
Saro-Wiwa was executed by the military government, his remains are
still in an unmarked grave, intermingled with those of eight other
Ogoni men who were also hanged. Because of a dispute between the
author's family and the relatives of the eight men, a burial
scheduled by Saro-Wiwa's family for April 24 appears very unlikely
to take place. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES  &LR; _  &UR; General &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' news category)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ U.S. District Judge K. Michael Moore
dismissed the lawsuit aimed at keeping 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez in
the United States, saying only the U.S. attorney general can grant
asylum to the Cuban boy. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   TENN-EXECUTE (Nashville) _ Robert Glenn Coe is scheduled to die
by lethal injection, the first person put to death in Tennessee
since 1960. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-SAFETY (Undated) _ A coalition of major U.S. cities,
searching for a way prevent a drive to improve gun safety from
stalling, intend to use their combined buying power to try to force
the nation's gun manufacturers to follow the lead of Smith &AMP; Wesson
and sign onto last week's landmark pack that requires new handgun
safety devices. By Eric Lipton.
</P>
<P>
   ROMANIAN-PRIZEWINNER (New York) _ A profile of 17-year-old
Viviana Ioana Risca, a Romanian immigrant from suburban New York,
who won first prize and a $100,000 scholarship last week in the
Intel Science Talent Search for encrypting a secret message on a
DNA strand. By Robin Finn.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES _ Washington &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `w' news category)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TOBACCO (Washington) _ In a big victory for the cigarette
industry, the Supreme Court ruled 5-4 Tuesday that the government
does not have the authority to regulate tobacco as an addictive
drug. But the court also ruled that it is up to Congress to decide
how much regulation of tobacco the government should impose. In
recent years, federal, state and local lawmakers have placed more
and more restrictions on tobacco use, and there is no sign that
trend will change.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   FED-RATES (Washington) _ Federal Reserve policy makers are
widely expected to raise the target on the federal funds rate a
quarter point, the fifth such increase since June. (Announcement
scheduled for 2:15 p.m. EST.) By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   BARBIE-RIVALS (Undated) _ Just when Barbie has finished her
latest makeover _ a redesign of both doll and packaging _ along
comes Get Real Girl, hoping to give the 41-year-old icon who
controls the vast majority of the $2 billion fashion-doll market a
little run for her money. But Get Real Girl and other dolls that
challenge Barbie's world view face huge hurdles in winning over
children in a marketing-driven world. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MEXICO (Mexico City) _ The Internet is coming of age in
Mexico, thanks to a number of major Internet alliances designed to
exploit e-commerce opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   BMW-ROVER (London) _ Recriminations over BMW's sale of Rover
intensify. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   HIRING-PITFALLS (Undated) _ In today's tight job market, many
companies have not been diligent in checking the backgrounds and
work histories of the people they hire. That can spell trouble,
according to executive recruiters and people at companies that
specialize in background checks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   NAZIYEARS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``I Will Bear Witness,''
Volume II, is an even more striking, more emotionally vivid account
of the Nazi years than Volume I, in which Victor Klemperer covered
the years 1933 to 1941. Klemperer, a thoroughly assimilated,
patriotically German Jew who taught Romance Languages at the
Dresden Technical University, describes the worst years of the Nazi
era: the mass deportations of Jews, the stints of forced labor, the
near starvation, the allied bombings, the alternating episodes of
hope and depression. By Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``Fragments: Jerusalem''
Ron Havilio captures the history of Jerusalem, where he was born,
mixing it with the history of his own family, which traces its
history there for centuries. By Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLISH-PUDDINGS (Mickleton, England) _ English puddings _ that
fabulous array of soft, warm, sweet desserts that light up
childhood mealtimes and linger reassuringly decades later in the
memories of 50-somethings and 60-somethings _ have been undergoing
a renaissance of late. ``The rib-stickers especially,'' said Simon
Hopkinson, a leading English chef and food writer, ``are back in
fashion in a big way.'' By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `d' news category.)
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (New York) _ The weekly column: The members of the new
generation of New York wine bars are about more than just wine and
refreshingly free of pomposity. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `d' news category.)
