<P>
   &UR; Tuesday, March 21, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ People are often at their most
vulnerable during periods of uncertainty or rejection. Ask any job
hunter. Sometimes there will be hurt feelings no matter what you
do, but it's awfully easy to turn those feelings into anger and
bitterness if you come across as callous. Workers have been told
for decades not to burn their bridges, but employers need to
realize that the advice is just as significant for them. By DAVE
MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   3COM-CORP. (San Francisco) _ Remember Rockwell International
Corp.? U.S. Robotics? Ascend Communications? These were the firms
3Com Corp. bested in one of the Internet's first guerrilla wars,
waged over modem technology back in the mid-90s. For years, those
companies jockeyed for position in the growing market, competing
for the right to connect you to the burgeoning Internet. By ALAN T.
SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   IKEA (San Francisco) _ In last year's film, Fight Club, Edward
Norton's Everyman character flips through an Ikea catalog and
surveys the tasteful Euro-chic, assembly-required furniture that
fills his apartment. ``Like everyone else,'' he declares, ``I had
become a slave to the Ikea nesting instinct.'' Ikea  &Cx1f;  the store
that helped furnish both Ally McBeal and Jerry Seinfeld's
apartments and inspired an outing for the Simpson family _ has
arrived in pop culture. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DACHAU-ANNIVERSARY (San Francisco) _ It is not a date that comes
readily to mind. But it's as much a day of infamy as the 7th of
December, 1941. On March 22, 1933, a few miles north of Munich, the
German government opened Dachau, the first in a series of
concentration camps. It was followed immediately by Esterwegen and
Oranienburg. Before they were through, the Nazis built more than
1,000 camps throughout Europe and Russia. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WEIGHT-LOSS (Albany, N.Y.) _ If I had been alive during the
Renaissance, my excess girth would be considered beautiful. But
today those of us with a spare tire and a double chin are thought
of as, to put it politely, physically unattractive. But there are
ways to become more content with your body. For instance, has
losing some weight lowered your cholesterol level? Are you able to
manage eating habits now? By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-IDENTITY (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ The Internet has introduced
an unexpected element of whimsy to the world of college admissions.
In addition to ranks, scores, essays wishing for world peace and
deep thoughts about the millennium, colleges now learn that
applicants like to be called ``Sexwaxman,'' ``Shagm,''
``Ipitydafoo'' and ``Sellthekidsforfood.'' By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A readers asks, ``I planted fragrant
gladiolus (Acidanthera) several years ago, but only two have
bloomed. Where should I plant them, and in what kind of soil?''
Assorted Q&AMP;As. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KARAOKE-NIGHTS (Houston) _ Karaoke, that performing style of
music that allows everyday people to indulge their vocal fantasies,
just won't die. And amateur singers live for the few moments on
stage when they get to belt out a favorite tune. By CLIFFORD PUGH.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-AC-DC (Undated) _ Initially, AC DC's new album, ``Stiff
Upper Lip,'' is a letdown, but a second listen offers comfort in
the band's return to blues-based guitar roots. By MICHAEL D. CLARK.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-STAR-REVIEW (Undated) _ Charles M. Robinson's book ``The
Men Who Wear the Star'' is an admiring but dispassionate history of
the Texas Rangers. By BOB TUTT.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-WINE-WEEK (Undated) _ One of the great wines of the world
is vintage port, but it can get expensive. But you can get most of
the pleasure for a fraction of the cost with a vintage-character
port, such as the 1994 Taylor ``Late Bottled Vintage'' Port _ 4
stars _ with lush, cassis-and-chocolate undertones. By MICHAEL
LONSFORD. (For release Friday, March 24.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SURF-CAMP (Namotu Island, Fiji) _ Surf's up! And for
those who relish the thrill of riding the biggest waves, surf camps
now operate in tropical climates worldwide, from the South Pacific
to Mexico. All-inclusive packages make an international surfing
vacation more affordable than ever. By JOE DOGGETT. (Photo
available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SURF-TIPS (Undated) _ Tips for finding a surf camp from
Mexico to the South Pacific. By JOE DOGGETT. (Photo available on
NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Houston) _ Is it possible to have too many
choices? On a daily basis, we're so bombarded with two-for-one
offers and one-time-only specials that it's hard to tell which is
the real deal. The editor of the new ``Consumer Reports Best Travel
Deals 2000'' offers perspective. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Although some of my best friends
have them, I've never been much of a cat fan. With a handful of
exceptions, their ancient, inscrutable charms are nearly always
lost on me. Where others see an exotic and mysterious aloofness _
``They're descended from lions; they won't be OWNED!'' - I see a
selfish, ungrateful, narcissistic pain in the butt. By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH-DRINKING (San Rafael, Calif.) _ If Americans need
one-size-fits-all drinking advice based on the so-called ``French
Paradox,'' how about telling the truth? Drink like the French, die
like the French. By HILARY ABRAMSON.
</P>
<P>
   YUMMIES (San Francisco) _ We Americans have had our flappers,
our boomers, our hippies, our yippies, our yuppies. Now, as the
millennium dawns, it is altogether appropriate that our English
language respond to a new group for statisticians to ponder and
economists to dissect: those young multimillionaires running
dot-com businesses. How about ``Yummies?'' By ARLENE SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-AMERICANS (San Francisco) _ A short inscription
proposed for the National Japanese American Memorial in Washington,
D.C., is reopening half-century-old wounds. The words, written by a
Japanese American leader who died in 1991, are generating hundreds
of letters by Japanese Americans to federal authorities in a
last-minute effort to block the plan. By YURIKO NAGANO.
</P>
