r a BC-WIRED-FEATURES-$ADV26     03-21 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRED-FEATURES-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With WIRED-CITY. Moving in (a) national, (l) lifestyle and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, March 26.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIVABILITY AT DC RANCH: THEY'VE GOT IT WIRED
</P>
<P>
   Every house at the DC Ranch planned community north of Phoenix
has two 256K Internet connections that are always available without
dialing an access number. Every household can have up to six e-mail
addresses and one personal Web page. In addition, residents can
link to RanchNet, the community's private intranet, to access:
</P>
<P>
   _ A community directory. Neighbors list names and ages, whether
they have children, and their common hobbies and interests. With a
click, they can be contacted by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   _ Interest groups. Among the recent online sign-up sheets: a
book club, desert nature walks, music classes for children, an
exercise group, and a bridge club.
</P>
<P>
   _ A bulletin board. Residents can search for a baby-sitter; sell
extra tickets to an NBA game; seek advice on computers, cooking and
other hobbies, or express concerns about neighborhood security and
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   _ The community center: An online monthly calendar lists events
such as swimming lessons and CPR training. Residents can use the
link to reserve tennis courts and time at the gym.
</P>
<P>
   _ Group e-mail: The scout leader and soccer team parents can
bundle all associated families into one messaging group.
</P>
<P>
   _ School: When a community grade school opens in August 2001,
parents will be able to download homework assignments and check
report cards on line.
</P>
<P>
   _ Health care: An agreement with a local health-care provider
means residents soon will be able to use their computers to make
doctors' appointments and access health information.
</P>
<P>
   _ Retail: A commercial section of RanchNet now under development
will allow residents to make dinner reservations and order
groceries and prescriptions on line.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
