<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3466 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-AL-AMIN-MAIN-COX     03-21 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AL-AMIN-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Police search Ala. woods for gun used to kill deputy
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa and Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Law enforcement officers searched for a murder weapon today in a
wooded area near White Hall, Ala., where Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin was
arrested Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities were still trying to determine how Al-Amin, who is
charged in the shooting death of a Fulton County sheriff's deputy
and the wounding of a second deputy, got from Atlanta to White
Hall, said William Imfeld, special agent in charge of the FBI's
Mobile office.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin had been staying with a fellow Muslim in a rented house
in White Hall, said Lowndes County Sheriff Willie Vaughner.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin was being represented at his arraignment hearing today
in federal court in Montgomery by state Sen. Hank Sanders of Selma
and J.L. Chestnut, according to the U.S. Marshal's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Imfeld said three U.S. marshals were in White Hall looking for a
Toyota 4-Runner registered to Al-Amin at a White Hall address on
Monday when, at about 5:30 p.m. CST, they were fired upon by
.223-caliber rounds. The Fulton County deputies were shot with
rounds from a .223-caliber assault rifle.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, a 1985 Cadillac came by and picked up the
(unknown) shooter, drove down County Road 40 and pulled into a
house at 531 County Road,'' Imfeld said. Imfeld said he was not
sure why the car pulled in at that house.
</P>
<P>
   The car then circled around the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that very odd. We were looking to see if it was part
of a scheme, if he was with them, or if it gave them an opportunity
to draw attention away from where Al-Amin may have been,'' Imfeld
said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI set up a roadblock and arrested six occupants of the
Cadillac, two of them juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   Four were being held in federal custody in Montgomery today for
questioning for shooting at the marshals and possibly for harboring
Al-Amin, Imfeld said. The juveniles were released to their parents.
</P>
<P>
   About three hours after the marshals were initially shot at,
marshals were fired upon again, and Al-Amin was seen running into a
wooded area at the corner of White Hall Road and County Road 80,
Imfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughner said no one was injured in the exchange of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 law enforcement personnel, including dog teams, gave
chase and Al-Amin ``basically ran out of the woods into the arms of
a deputy,'' Imfeld said. ``Within seconds there were about two
dozen agents on him.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of White Hall said today he has known Al-Amin since
the 1960s , when he was known as Black Panther leader H. Rap Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor John Jackson said he and Al-Amin met in 1965 and were
members of the Lowndes County Freedom Organization, a nonviolent
Christian organization that tried to put black candidates on the
ballot. The organization used the Black Panther emblem as a symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``About a year ago, (Al-Amin) came in to try to start up a
mosque but there were not enough people,'' Jackson said. ``They
opened a restaurant. It is the only one in town that does not sell
alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said Al-Amin came to White Hall ``about every two or
three months,'' but added that the last time he saw him was in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said in the past he had Al-Amin talk to the children of
White Hall about the dangers of drugs and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been in the struggle for a long time but when someone
crosses the line, we have to deal with it,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents arrived in Lowndes County, Ala., about four days ago,
said Vaughner. They suspected Al-Amin might return to his activist
roots and knew that he had a vehicle registered in the area,
Vaughner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Panther Party's origins are in Lowndes County. The
animal was adopted as a symbol of black voting rights after a mass
meeting in the county more than 30 years ago. The late civil rights
activist Stokely Carmichael left Lowndes County after that meeting
and helped lead the Black Panther Party to national prominence.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin had been the subject of a nationwide manhunt since
Thursday night. Deputy Richard Kinchen, 35, and Deputy Aldranon
English, 28, were trying to serve a warrant on Al-Amin. Kinchen
died; English is recovering from his injuries at Grady Memorial
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's arrest was the result of information investigators
received soon after the deputies were shot, Atlanta Police Chief
Beverly Harvard said at a late night news conference at City Hall
East.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokeswoman Celeste Armstead agreed: ``It was unbelievable
cooperation between several agencies that worked hard to catch this
man.''
</P>
<P>
   After his arrest, FBI agents took Al-Amin, who was wearing a
white shirt, sweat pants and sunglasses, to the Montgomery Police
Department. He was fingerprinted and booked at the Montgomery City
Jail late Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard said a handgun was found in the woods after Al-Amin's
arrest. She said it is not known whether the gun was used in the
shooting earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Sheriff Jackie Barrett said English had expressed
relief about Al-Amin's arrest. ``He said, 'Tonight I can sleep.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted that it happened in this time frame,'' the
sheriff said, referring to today's funeral service for the slain
deputy. ``This will add a different air to the service. On a good
day this would be a difficult service, this will help us through a
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard said Al-Amin will be arraigned in Alabama on federal
charges of firing on federal agents. A warrant has been issued in
Atlanta charging him with murder and aggravated assault. He has
also been charged with unlawful flight to avoid prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard said she does not know when Al-Amin will be returned to
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Several other people were detained in White Hall, she said, ``as
it relates to the possibility of their harboring a person that we
had a warrant on.'' About six people were being questioned but were
not under arrest as of Monday night, she said.
</P>
<P>
   White Hall is a little country town located off State Highway
80. It does not have stop lights or sidewalks.There is a town hall
and church at the intersection of County Roads 23 and 30 and some
houses and general stores nearby in the town, which the mayor said
has a current population of about 1,800.
</P>
<P>
   Cox writers Doug Payne and Mike Morris contributed to this
article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
