<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-TOBACCO-NYT &LR;      03-21 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT CANNOT REGULATE TOBACCO AS DRUG, COURT RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a big victory for the cigarette industry, the
Supreme Court ruled 5-4 Tuesday that the government does not have
the authority to regulate tobacco as an addictive drug.
</P>
<P>
   The justices declared that the Food and Drug Administration had
reached beyond its authority in 1996, when it reversed its own
decades-old policy and moved to crack down on cigarette sales to
minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``By no means do we question the seriousness of the problem that
the FDA has sought to address,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote
for the court, acknowledging that the agency had shown that
``tobacco use, particularly among children and adolescents, poses
perhaps the single most significant threat to public health in the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   But, O'Connor concluded, Congress simply did not give the FDA
the authority it sought to exercise over tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations at issue in the case (Food and Drug
Administration vs. Brown and Williamson Tobacco Corp., No. 98-1152)
prohibit the sale of cigarettes or smokeless tobacco to people
under 18 and require retailers to check the identification of those
under the age of 27.
</P>
<P>
   But the court ruled Tuesday that it is up to Congress to decide
how much regulation of tobacco, and what kind, the government
should impose. In recent years, federal, state and local lawmakers
have placed more and more restrictions on tobacco use, and there is
no sign that that trend will change. But Tuesday's decision was
nonetheless a big disappointment for the Clinton administration,
which had embraced FDA regulations as its main anti-tobacco
initiative, and for the 40 states that sided with the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry had argued in part that, since the FDA had
concluded that cigarettes were dangerous, it logically ought to
move to ban them altogether _ assuming it was found to have
jurisdiction _ rather than regulate them.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. 4th Circuit Court of Appeals, in Richmond, sided with
the industry in a 2-1 ruling in August 1998. The appeal from that
case led to Tuesday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   When the high court heard arguments on Dec. 1, several justices
were openly skeptical of the government's arguments, partly because
for decades after it was created in 1938 the FDA maintained that it
had no authority to regulate smoking, and then switched its
position in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In December, O'Connor said regulating smoking ``just doesn't
fit'' within the agency's authority. Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist and Justice Antonin Scalia were similarly skeptical then,
so it was no surprise Tuesday that they joined O'Connor's decision,
as did Justices Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the lineup of dissenters was a small reminder that the
tribunal's rulings are not always predictable based on its members'
comments from the bench. In December, Justice David H. Souter also
seemed unconvinced by the government's arguments. But Tuesday, he
sided with the government in dissenting from the majority, along
with Justices John Paul Stevens, Stephen G. Breyer and Ruth Bader
Ginsburg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1303EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-POPE-HOLYLAND-590&AMP;ADD     03-21 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOLYLAND-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE ARRIVES IN ISRAEL ON PILGRIMAGE TO MIDDLE EAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also POPE-HOLYLAND-BAPTISM) 
(js) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Pope John Paul II arrived in Israel Tuesday on the
first diplomatic visit ever by a pope to the Jewish state,
appealing for peace in a region that has grappled with religious
and political conflicts for generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``May peace be God's gift to the land that he chose as his
own,'' the pope said in a brief speech. ``Shalom,'' he said in
conclusion, using the Hebrew word for peace.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech he praised Prime Minister Ehud Barak as ``a man of
peace'' and asked that Jews, Christians and Muslims come together
to settle their differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray that my visit will serve the cause,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pope was welcomed by warm words from political leaders,
prayers and a military fanfare as he arrived at Ben Gurion
International Airport aboard a Royal Jordanian Airlines plane
bearing the flags of Israel and the Vatican. With a large
delegation of dignitaries looking on, he descended the stairs from
the plane and kissed Israeli soil that was in a bowl held up to him
by three young boys _ one Jewish, one Christian and one Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the Holy Land,'' said Barak as he shook the pope's
hand.
</P>
<P>
   En route to Jerusalem, as his plane carried him over Palestinian
territories, the pope sent a telegram to the Palestinian leader,
Yasir Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``As my flight from Amman to Tel Aviv takes me over the
Palestinian autonomous areas, I greet your excellency,'' the pope's
message said. ``In eager anticipation of my visit to Bethlehem and
the Palestinian territories I ask Almighty God to bless the
Palestinian people and to strengthen in all the peoples of the
Middle East the resolve to bring about a just and stable peace in
the region.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope normally sends telegrams to heads of state when he
flies over their countries, but officials said it is rare for him
to send a message to a leader of a territory that is not a state.
</P>
<P>
   The pope is scheduled to visit Bethlehem in the Palestinian
territories on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   For John Paul, the trip to Israel fulfills one of the enduring
dreams of his 21-year papacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, on the 2000 anniversary of the birth of Jesus
Christ, it has been my strong personal desire to come here and to
pray,'' he said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The only other pope to visit Israel was Paul VI in 1964. But
that visit came at a time when Israel and the Vatican did not have
diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul established diplomatic ties with Israel in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The pope arrived in Jerusalem from Amman, Jordan, where he
celebrated Mass earlier Tuesday for an estimated 40,000 Jordanians
in a local sports stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Resplendent in red vestments and speaking under a yellow and
white awning, the 79-year-old pope told his congregation, many of
whom came from the small Christian community in Jordan and other
Arab countries, ``Your future lies in unity and solidarity.`
</P>
<P>
   The pope expressed the hope that the Roman Catholic Church would
use its resources to set unity and love as the ``supreme goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Judaism and Islam, he also called for a stronger
bond ``between the Christians and the other great religions which
flourish here'' in the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Jordan, the pope went by helicopter to Wadi
al-Kharrar on the east bank of the Jordan River, where some
Christian scholars believe that Jesus was baptized by John the
Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving in Jordan on Monday, the pope began his
pilgrimage in the Holy Land by praying on Mount Nebo in Jordan, the
site where the Bible says Moses first viewed the biblical Promised
Land.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   John Paul, who first mentioned his desire to make a spiritual
journey to the key biblical sites of Jordan, Israel and the
Palestinian-controlled territories in his maiden Christmas homily
in 1978, has battled his ill-health and the political turmoil of
the Middle East to make this journey in the year 2000, a Holy Year
for the Roman Catholic Church. He made a pilgrimage to Israel in
1963 when he was a bishop of Krakow, but had never been to Mount
Nebo.
</P>
<P>
   The trip, however personally important to the pope, also has
vast political and social significance to the region, and to
history.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul, who has often spoken on behalf of the Palestinians'
right to a homeland, will also tour a Palestinian refugee camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
