<HEADLINE>
AC/DC FILLS IN THE GAPS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  ``Stiff Upper Lip; AC/DC; Elektra'' 
 
By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The joy of listening to a new AC/DC album is in finding the
Aussie rock band's latest metal fantasy. The song that has the
requisite amount of Brian Johnson's grainy falsetto and enough of
Angus Young's guitar-rendered electrocution to be dubbed a
head-banging classic. The cut that you know will be Young's newest
song to duckwalk to on stage.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, then, the disappointment of not finding such a song on
the band's latest album, ``Stiff Upper Lip.'' Initially it's a
letdown, but a second listen offers comfort in the band's return to
blues-based guitar roots. AC/DC hasn't put together a collection of
songs this raw and unpolished in the 20 years since Bon Scott died
and Johnson took over vocal duties.
</P>
<P>
   For 27 years, AC/DC has assembly-line-produced the kind of grand
finale guitar romps that most arena bands hope for just once in a
career. Early on, it was ``Highway to Hell'' and ``Dirty Deeds Done
Dirt Cheap.'' Later, it peaked with ``You Shook Me All Night Long''
and ``Who Made Who'' in the early to mid-'80s. Even more recent
tracks like ``Thunderstruck'' and ``Shoot To Thrill'' have provided
the perfect platform for Young to scamper around naughtily in his
schoolboy short suits.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the Scott and Johnson years is what
filled the album space between manifestos. Almost all of AC/DC's
'90s catalog was chord-crunchers designed to swing a skull off its
neck pivot. In Scott's day, the band balanced the bombast with a
three-chord jam, like in ``The Jack'' or ``Let There Be Rock,''
that built slowly into an explosion. The formula allowed the band's
real T.N.T. to stand out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stiff Upper Lip'' has stripped away several layers of feedback
to allow that to happen again. Opening with the honky-tonk guitar
of the title track, Young's guitar is the primary voice throughout
the 12 songs. Whether it be the John Lee Hooker chord progressions
of ``Meltdown'' or the backyard swing and loose strings of
``Satellite Blues,'' Young provides the musical chorus that sticks
in the head while Johnson does the noodling with his voice.
</P>
<P>
   About the closest ``Stiff Upper Lip'' gets to a roof-raiser is
``Safe in New York City,'' which combines a beat built on cymbals
with Young's deft finger touches on guitar and Johnson's most
prominent falsetto whispers just begging to shriek. It's followed
closely by ``Can't Stand Still,'' featuring Young's trademarked
guitar rolls, the ones that sound like live wires dipped in water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold Me Back'' is unique in that it's nearly a ballad. Instead
of taking the opportunity to yowl on the change from chorus to
verse, the band takes the song title's advice. Nothing here will
probably ever be held up as AC/DC's finest, but they should sound
great in concert between the monster hits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Grade: B- &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
