<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAGRANT GLADIOLUS SAID TO THRIVE IN SOUTH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: I planted fragrant gladiolus (Acidanthera) several
years ago, but only two have bloomed. Where should I plant them,
and in what kind of soil?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Acidanthera bicolor'' or ``Gladiolus callianthus'' is
commonly called Abyssinian sword lily or peacock orchid and is
supposedly a good perennial for most regions of the South,
including coastal areas. This member of the iris family likes sun
and a well-draining garden soil. You can leave the corms in a
well-mulched bed during winter. When new growth appears, fertilize.
</P>
<P>
   But some gardeners prefer to dig the corms in fall after the
leaves have yellowed, allow them to dry, store at a cool
temperature in a dry material through winter, then replant in
spring. I have not grown this plant, but there are those who think
this process leads to better blooms.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would you please give information on primroses?
Fertilization, light requirements? Is this an indoor or outdoor
plant?
</P>
<P>
   The bottom leaves of my plants are turning yellow, and the green
leaves are starting to curl.
</P>
<P>
   A: Primroses are grown outdoors in beds or containers during the
cooler months. If you plant them in mid-to-late fall, they will
perform through spring. Primroses prefer partial or bright shade.
Best results come with an organically enriched, moist but
well-draining soil. Plants in afternoon sun during the recent
80-plus-degree days may not be as lush and green as those receiving
more shade. Heat and/or irregular watering can cause foliage to
curl. Overwatering and/or a poorly draining soil can also trigger
yellow leaves.
</P>
<P>
   There are three species of primroses used here: ``Primula
malacoides,'' which produces dense clusters of small pink, rose,
lavender or white flowers; ``P. obconica,'' which produces clusters
of larger pink, rose, lavender/blue and white flowers; and the ``P.
polyantha hybrids,'' which are available in pastels and striking
blues, reds and bright yellows with contrasting eyes. ``P.
obconica'' is a short-lived perennial; the other species are
annuals.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Three years ago I planted four dewberry bushes; one I believe
was `Cheyenne.'' How do I care for them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Blackberries tolerate various soil conditions but prefer a
well-draining, slightly acidic sandy loam.
</P>
<P>
   There are upright and trailing varieties of blackberries. Both
should be pruned after harvest.
</P>
<P>
   About the time older canes bear fruit, you should see new canes
developing. As the development occurs, remove all but five to seven
of the newer canes on each plant. On upright varieties, trim the
tips of these newer canes when they reach 4 feet. Trim tips of
trailing types when the new canes have reached the top of the
support. This will encourage them to branch. Keep your row of
berries in check by removing suckers.
</P>
<P>
   Apply a 3-1-2-ratio fertilizer just before flowering and after
harvest. Keep the weeds down and debris removed to help control
disease. Mulch helps.
</P>
<P>
   Blackberry varieties for this area include `Cheyenne,' `Brazos,'
`Choctaw' and `Comanche.'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, TX 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to each unpublished letter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
