<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING REAL DEAL CAN BE A CHALLENGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ I was visiting the other day with a friend who applied
an alarming perspective to travel at the start of a new century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm beginning to think that it's easier just to stay home,''
he said. ``When I get ready to arrange a vacation, I feel as if I'm
being tugged in every direction. There are so many new online
sites, so many confusing airline and hotel promotions, so many
special deals for kids or families or couples or seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's good to have all these options,'' he continued,
``but I get a headache trying to figure it all out. Planning a trip
used to be fun. Now, it's hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TOO MANY CHOICES? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible that we have too many choices today?
</P>
<P>
   I think back to the first time my wife and I decided to vacation
in Europe: There was no Internet. No plethora of free brochures or
reference books beyond the basic all-encompassing guides. No air
fare wars or hotel discounters. We naively approached a travel
agent, cried, ``Help!'' and relied completely on her expertise. She
must have served us well, too, because we were inspired to return
many times.
</P>
<P>
   Now, thousands of Web sites provide insight into attractions
from Africa to Antarctica; we can even click on a computer key and
see photos of hotel rooms in Amsterdam or Hong Kong, or join a chat
room and discuss where to shop or dine. Specialized guidebooks and
periodicals focus on almost every imaginable travel-related topic.
Tour packagers' glossy brochures appeal to increasingly varied
interests.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
INFORMATION OVERLOAD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And everywhere we turn, someone is bidding to sell us a low-cost
ticket to help make our vacation dreams a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost information overload,'' says Bette LaGow, managing
editor of ``Consumer Reports Best Travel Deals 2000'' (Consumer
Reports, $9.99).
</P>
<P>
   One result, as expressed by LaGow in a recent telephone
interview: ``On a daily basis, you are so bombarded with offers
that it's hard to decipher what the real deal is any more.''
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of adding to this ``information overload,'' LaGow
and other editors at Consumer Reports offer 360 pages of tips aimed
at helping travelers sort the wheat from the chaff. Topics covered
range from airfare know-how to home swaps, car rentals to health
and safety. One chapter is devoted to travel and the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web is a great place _ it's kind of like a new travel
agent _ but it's enormous,'' LaGow says. ``This book tries to show
people exactly what types of sites are out there.''
</P>
<P>
   LaGow reminds that self-planning online requires sound judgment.
``It's buyer beware,'' she says. ``There is fine print everywhere,
and that includes Web sites. Some of the low airfare sites, for
instance, are a lot better than others at disclosing fees. There
can be a processing fee from $4 to $25 for sending you a paper
ticket as opposed to an e-ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Be wary, LaGow says, of online auctions or other promotions
involving frequent-flier mileage. ``Many of these frequent-flier
miles are not transferable,'' she says. ``I would check directly
with the airline to make sure you're going to be able to use
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Other alleged ``super-duper deals'' aren't always what they seem
either. ``If you get a low price on a hotel and it turns out to be
15-20 miles from where you really want to be, requiring you to rent
a car, how good of a deal are you really getting?'' LaGow asks.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers who make transactions over the Internet should always
take precautions. Consider these indicators in helping avoid scams:
Look for a security symbol whenever you are asked for sensitive
information such as a credit card number; make certain you know a
company's address (and not just a post office box) and background;
and check for independent seals of approval from the Better
Business Bureau Online (www.bbbonline.org) or TRUSTe
(www.truste.org).
</P>
<P>
   Planning our travels should be enjoyable. But I believe _ and
hope _ my friend is wrong in theorizing that it's better to stay
home than to sort through the maze of alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   I get frustrated sometimes, too. And confused. That's why I give
``Consumer Reports Best Travel Deals 2000'' a prime location on my
bookshelf, just as I do Tom Parsons' ``Insider Travel Secrets''
(Best Fares, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   It's also why when confronted with so many choices, I take
solace in knowing that I can still cry out to my travel agent,
``Help!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3506 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-BOS &LR;      03-21 0956
