<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW TENNIS OASIS IN THE CALIFORNIA DESERT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIAN WELLS, Calif. _ No black armbands for promoter Charlie
Pasarell. So his three big attractions _ Anna Kournikova, Andre
Agassi, and Serena Williams _ were buried in the desert faster than
you could say Nathalie Dechy, Hicham Arazi, and Mary Pierce, the
mischief-makers who did the spadework. Not all the palm trees were
delivered on time, either, and the bottled water runs out now and
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped worrying about things like that a long time ago,''
said Pasarell, impresario of a tennis tournament, the Indian Wells
Masters, where his star this year was made of steel and concrete,
not flesh and blood. The matinee (and evening) idol, a spiffy new
park called the Indian Wells Tennis Garden, puts Pasarell and his
partners, Ray Moore and International Management Group, in a league
with the old Mongol champ of the 13th century, Kublai Khan.
</P>
<P>
   As you probably recall, the English poet Coleridge wrote: ``In
Xanadu did Kublai Khan a stately pleasure dome decree . . . a sunny
pleasure dome.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Indian Wells, on the outskirts of Palm Springs, may not
pass for Xanadu, it's a pretty good American approximation. The sun
streams relentlessly, toasting inhabitants and glistening off
encircling snow-kissed mountains. Kublai Khan would have approved
this pleasure pen, and enjoyed lazing among 16,100 patrons, viewing
sneaker-shod combatants in the main arena, an octagonal citadel
rising four levels and 48 rows above the hardcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Pro tennis has been a regular visitor to this desert since 1974,
and Pasarell the promoter at several locations for the last two
decades. The only problem he had at the last site was finding room
for more spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing well, selling out 11,000 seats at the Hyatt
Grand Champions, drawing 152,000 last year,'' said Pasarell. ``But
we needed more room, for courts, hospitality tents _ and
spectators. We came very close to moving to Las Vegas. But that
fell through, and I was pretty depressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came into my office soon after, and there was a note on the
desk from a realtor named Bill Culver, a very good tennis player,
suggesting the property, 189 acres, on which we've built a $77
million project. What a boost. Especially since I didn't want to
leave this area. We broke ground in November '98 _ and here we are.
And it won't be long before we have an additional 10,000-seat
stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Corretja and Lindsay Davenport were crowned the men's and
women's champs over the weekened when the Masters concluded at the
sparkling new facility, which began as a wasteland of cactus and
sagebrush. Years ago, gangsters such as Bugsy Siegel and Meyer
Lansky made the Vegas desert bloom with their gambling playground.
Now the gamesters _ Pasarell, Moore, IMG _ have planted their own
garden for gamboling racket-flappers, and are well on the way to
establishing the planet's prime tennis patch.
</P>
<P>
   In the US, Miami's Crandall Park, scene of the upcoming Ericsson
(nee Lipton) Open, has been the paragon, with a 14,000-seat
stadium. Now Pasarell and Moore are catching up with their pal and
former colleague of the courts, Butch Buchholz, who built Crandall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butch has encouraged us every step of the way, helping us not
to make mistakes,'' said Pasarell. ``He's got the ocean view on Key
Biscayne. We've got the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the US Tennis Association had neither Pasarell
nor Buchholz influencing the construction of monstrous Arthur Ashe
Stadium at Flushing Meadow three years ago. The overblown
23,000-seat arena offers a decent spectating experience only to
those in the highest-priced seats.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is more disappointed by that than Pasarell since Ashe,
his college roommate and teammate at UCLA, was his closest friend.
A statue of Ashe and numerous photos are prominently positioned in
Pasarell's office.
</P>
<P>
   The same architect, Gino Rossetti, did the three stadia
excellently, tailoring his work to differing demands. The USTA went
for greed in ordering too many seats (but too few, and at too great
a distance for ordinary pocketbooks). Buchholz and Pasarell went
for grace, gratifying their customers. Anything exceeding 16,000
seats defeats a true intimate tennis atmosphere, and there isn't a
bad location here.
</P>
<P>
   It may take players who've been around to create the right
setting for their game. Pasarell and Buchholz played Davis Cup for
the US, Moore for South Africa, where he had the style and chutzpah
to speak out against apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly this stadium would have been named for their friend,
Ashe, had the USTA not wisely chosen to honor an exemplary American
(rejecting an earlier decision to sell naming rights).
</P>
<P>
   That tasteless practice of hanging commercial names on
playgrounds was avoided, said Pasarell, ``because the city gave us
$2.5 million to call it the Indian Wells Tennis Garden. Unique, and
a nice feel, don't you think?'' Preferable to the Taco Bell
Ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller outer stadia are sunken for better viewing, and so are
the unusual practice courts. Pasarell noted, ``Fans love to watch
practice, and we'll make it easy for them with seating.''
</P>
<P>
   A rugged serve-and-volleyer, Pasarell was No. 1 in the US in
1967, and lost a US Amateur semifinal to champ Stan Smith two years
later at Longwood in Brookline, Mass. He has a golfer's memory _
virtually unheard of among tennis players _ and can replay every
point and match if you ask.
</P>
<P>
   His mind was also a storehouse for ideas, items and details he
would use _ as he has _ when he outbuilt Kublai Khan with his own
pleasure dome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
