<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAINING HOOPS ALL WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gus Johnson typifies the all-out effort by CBS in covering the
unpredictable, bracket-busting NCAA men's basketball tournament. Of
the six games he covered in Tucson, only one was a blowout and four
were decided by 6 points or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's first game of the West Regional was Purdue beating
Dayton by a point. He also called the startling Gonzaga win over
St. John's in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday night, Johnson said he was ``emotionally drained.''
But he caught a red-eye back to New York to do play-by-play for the
Knicks-Lakers game on Madison Square Garden Network radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest with you,'' Johnson said. ``By the end of the
Knicks game, I was out of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS's coverage of the first and second rounds was comprehensive
and outstanding, and while nitpickers have criticized the network
for not instantly interrupting some games with hotter contests, CBS
did everything but split the screen to provide viewers with
breaking game information.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's feature reports were excellent, too, particularly
the ``Road to the Final Four'' piece narrated by Greg Gumbel
Saturday. CBS caught Valparaiso coach Homer Drew telling his
players that the NCAA tournament was ``a whole lot of emotion and
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew is correct, and CBS captured the emotion without being
syrupy. Once known for being staid and conservative, CBS even used
music from Led Zepplin as background.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody needs a little Jimmy Page in their day,'' said
Gumbel, a rock-and-roll connoisseur.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other team, Gonzaga has been on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are stone cold killers,'' said Johnson. ``They definitely
can go to the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that Gonzaga has a great combination of perimeter
and inside players.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are hard basketball players and are pumped and ready to
go,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS analyst Clark Kellogg said he was not surprised by Gonzaga
and went so far as to say there weren't a lot of true upsets in the
tourney, even though lower seeds were beating higher seeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that much different between 3 seeds and 7 seeds,''
Kellogg explained. ``College basketball is much more balanced now,
which means more compelling, competitive games.''
</P>
<P>
   He said only three games were upsets: North Carolina beating
Stanford, Wisconsin beating Arizona, and Seton Hall beating Temple.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg predicts that the UCLA-Iowa State game will be one of
the most exciting in recent memory. Iowa State guard Jamal Tinsley,
said Kellogg, ``brings all of Brooklyn with him'' when he plays.
And UCLA smoked a good Maryland team by 30 points.
</P>
<P>
   In case anyone hasn't noticed, Kellogg likes to throw in a few
flavorful terms to spice up his analysis. His best one over the
weekend was ``equi-finality,'' loosely defined as a team's ability
to reach the Final Four in a number of different ways _ defense,
perimeter shooting, fast breaks, or inside-the-paint play.
</P>
<P>
   He used ``equi-finality'' during a break in the
Syracuse-Kentucky game as he was talking about the Wildcats'
multiple weapons. Unfortunately, Kentucky didn't use all of those
weapons and lost to Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next round
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's TV games are Michigan State-Syracuse at 7:38,
followed by UCLA-Iowa State around 9:55 p.m. Both will be called by
Verne Lundquist and Bill Raftery, with Armen Keteyian reporting.
Friday night's action starts with Duke-Florida at 7:38, followed by
Oklahoma State-Seton Hall. Jim Nantz and Billy Packer call those
games, with Bonnie Bernstein reporting . . . Ratings for NBC's big
Lakers-Knicks matchup Sunday were down 30 percent from the NBA
telecast on the same weekend last year. The Lakers' blowout earned
a 4 rating and 10 share, but last year's Lakers-Magic game pulled a
5.7 rating and 14 share. . . NBC's ratings for the Bay Hill Classic
were up 20 percent, with Tiger Woods winning yet again. NBC earned
a 5.3 rating and 11 share; last year's tournament pulled a 4.4
rating and 9 share.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
