<SLUG> BC-BOOK-STAR-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORY OF THE FAMED TEXAS RANGERS GIVES EXCITING LOOK AT HISTORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  ``The men who wear the star: The story of the Texas Rangers''; By
Charles M. Robinson III; Random House, $29.95.) 
 
By BOB TUTT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For decades after revolutionaries wrested Texas from Mexico, the
blood continued to flow. Warfare raged between Texans and American
Indians. Assorted feuds snuffed lives, as did battles against an
abundance of badmen.
</P>
<P>
   If all the blood staining this state's history were miraculously
recovered, our blood banks could forget about donors for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   Of necessity, this bloodshed must be an integral part of Charles
M. Robinson III's ``The Men Who Wear the Star: The Story of the
Texas Rangers.'' Blending admiration and dispassion, Robinson
offers a balanced view of the Rangers, who during their long
history have been lionized as heroes and served as lightning rods
for controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The first Rangers were like the Colonial minutemen who protected
people living on the American frontier and ultimately fought for
independence from the British.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Robinson writes, ``The Ranger was a unique frontiersman on
a unique frontier, for in all the annals of the American West there
was nothing quite like Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Its settlers, he explains, ``depended on the citizen-ranger far
more than on any soldier or sheriff, because he was one of them and
he knew the dangers they faced.''
</P>
<P>
   The most pressing danger came from Indian raids, especially by
Comanches and their Kiowa allies. Tribal braves strived to
demonstrate their manhood during designated annual raiding seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Empresario'' Stephen F. Austin introduced the Ranger concept
in Texas about 1823 to protect ``a colony beyond the pale of white
civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Republic of Texas emerged in 1836, it expanded Ranger
forces, offering rank-and-file members $25 a month plus 1,280 acres
of public land for each year they served. Their officers got higher
pay, with captains getting the most, $75 a month.
</P>
<P>
   These first Rangers served primarily in locally raised companies
rather than as a Texaswide corps. Robinson notes that as ``horsemen
and guerrilla fighters, the Texans and the Indians were about
evenly matched, and Indian fights often were inconclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the early Rangers were good guys, he writes. A few
Ranger companies actually turned out to be outlaw gangs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest early Rangers was Capt. John Coffee Hays,
better known as Jack Hays, a Tennessee native. His slight build and
boyish appearance made him look much younger than he was, but
Nelson Lee, who served under him, knew him as ``a lamb in peace''
but ``a lion in war.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his most famous feats (often embellished in the
retelling) was single-handedly holding off a Comanche band after
being separated from his men. He took refuge atop Enchanted Rock,
an immense granite dome near what is now Fredericksburg, and
escaped unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson says the average Ranger's life expectancy during this
pre-Civil War period was about two years. Awareness of their peril
seems to have spurred them to make the most of leisure time.
Topping their pleasures were drinking, cock fights and the favors
of women.
</P>
<P>
   Though often tending to be insubordinate, Rangers served
valiantly in the Mexican-American War, triggered by the United
States' annexation of Texas. Led by Jack Hays, Rangers helped
counter Mexican guerrillas who harassed U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
   During that war some Rangers ``gave the service a reputation for
brutality that still lingers,'' Robinson writes, but ``the fame of
the organization had spread. ... The Texas Rangers were becoming a
legend.''
</P>
<P>
   Indians continued to regard Texans as a people apart from other
Americans even after Texas formally entered the Union in 1846,
Robinson relates, and although they were at peace with the federal
government, they continued their raids in Texas. Things reached the
point that traveling outside Austin, the state's capital, could be
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   In 1849 the federal government agreed to bankroll formation of
three Ranger companies to deal with this Indian peril.
</P>
<P>
   Among those distinguishing themselves was another storied
Ranger, Capt. John Salmon Ford. He became known as Rip Ford because
he signed letters of condolence to families of deceased Rangers
``RIP (rest in peace)/ Ford.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1850s Ford would also notably serve in the so-called
Cortina War fought along the Mexican border against forces led by
Juan Cortina, a revolutionary who deplored what he saw as American
exploitation of Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   During the Civil War famed Ranger leaders such as Ford, Sul Ross
and Bill McCulloch gained added stature serving the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Ranger unit known as the Frontier Regiment worked
to protect Texans along the northern and western frontiers. The
state of Texas and the South could provide it scant if any support.
</P>
<P>
   Indian attacks in the closing days of 1863 and the year 1864
``were among the worst in the history of Texas,'' Robinson writes.
</P>
<P>
   He recounts how these problems continued during the upheaval of
the Reconstruction era before 14 companies of Rangers called
Frontier Forces and designated as auxiliaries of the U.S. Army took
the field against Indian raiders.
</P>
<P>
   These Texas Rangers, Robinson writes, ``were the men who created
the lasting image that has inspired so many motion pictures,
television series and pulp novels.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1874 the Legislature ``established the Rangers as a
permanent, professional statewide gendarmerie,'' he explains. ``The
era of the citizen Ranger was over. For the duration of their
enlistments the men of the Frontier Battalion had no occupation in
life save as Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time, he adds, the Rangers had civil police
powers. This ``brought them into closer touch with law-abiding
people,'' making them peace officers.
</P>
<P>
   Ranger Sgt. James B. Gillett would later observe, ``This new
work was less romantic than the old Indian warfare, but it was
every bit as dangerous and necessary in the building up of the fast
developing state.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Robinson explains, ``The Texas Rangers were now
subject to a discipline and organization that they had never before
known. ... Henceforth they would be professionals, obeying orders,
serving where ordered and when ordered.''
</P>
<P>
   In their future were such outlaws as elusive, shrewd John King
Fisher, described by one Ranger as ``the most perfect specimen of a
frontier dandy and desperado.''
</P>
<P>
   His base of operation was West Texas, and by the time he was 26
he claimed to have killed 26 men. He was running unopposed for
sheriff of Uvalde County when killed during a drunken brawl in a
San Antonio saloon.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably ``the champion desperado of the world'' was John Wesley
Hardin, a preacher's son known to have killed 27 men. He fled to
Florida, but Rangers tracked him down and returned him to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Using what Robinson describes as ``a finely tuned sense of
public relations,'' Hardin charmed the press and the public and
ultimately managed to be tried on only one murder charge. He
escaped being hanged when the jury found him guilty in the second
degree in the slaying of a deputy sheriff. He drew a 25-year
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Hardin was released and pardoned after serving almost 16 years
in prison and became a lawyer practicing in El Paso. Ultimately
another gunman, John Selman, cowardly murdered him by shooting him
in the back.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1880s, Robinson observes, Rangers had begun putting more
emphasis on employing due process of law rather than ``a rope or a
firearm'' to administer justice.
</P>
<P>
   But they regressed in the 20th century as revolution engulfed
Mexico and they had to deal with banditry along the border. In one
instance, Rangers seriously strained U.S.-Mexican relations by
callously dumping in brush country bodies of Mexicans they had
killed in a gun battle.
</P>
<P>
   The overall quality of the Rangers dipped when James E. ``Farmer
Jim'' Ferguson took office as governor in 1915 and allowed
patronage and cronyism to guide the filling of state jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Upheaval along the border gave Ferguson the opportunity to
create units of Special Rangers. In January 1918 some of these
Rangers massacred 15 Hispanic men and youths in Porvenir, a Big
Bend-area village. The lawmen coldbloodedly perpetrated this
slaughter despite not finding the evidence of banditry they sought.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year a patronage scandal led the Legislature to
impeach Ferguson, then oust him from office. The lawmakers also
abolished his Special Rangers and made provisions for citizens to
have redress for Ranger misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ferguson climbed back in the saddle in the 1920s when
his wife, Miriam ``Ma'' Ferguson, served two nonconsecutive terms
as governor. Robinson notes that ``one of her first acts was to
discharge the entire Ranger Service,'' then to commission 2,300
``special'' Rangers that included some who were convicted felons.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he writes, Rangers like Frank Hamer, who tracked
down the Bonnie and Clyde crime duo, ``managed to uphold the
integrity of the service.'' The Rangers were merged with the
Highway Patrol in 1935 to form the Texas Department of Public
Safety.
</P>
<P>
   But, sad to say, much blood still flows in Texas as it enters a
new century.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
