<HEADLINE>
MEN, WOMEN, VACATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's more proof (if you needed any) that women and men are
different. A survey by Hilton found that:
</P>
<P>
   --Seven out of 10 women say they get more pleasure out of
vacations than possessions. Only 55 percent of men say that.
</P>
<P>
   --On average, the longest vacation taken by men _ 19 days or so
_ is about two days more than the longest trip by women.
</P>
<P>
   --Nearly 20 percent of women want to renew contact with loved
ones while on vacation. Only 13 percent of men do.
</P>
<P>
   --Forty-seven percent of women feel they get to know themselves
again while on vacation. The figure for men is 42 percent. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: A recent trivia question on flags has inspired
another from a reader. What is the only country with a
monochromatic flag? And which country has a non-rectangular banner?
(Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: Halifax, the capital of Nova Scotia, derives its name
from an Old English term meaning a tress of holy hair. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``It is good to have an end to journey towards; but it is
the journey that matters, in the end'' _ Ursula K. Le Guin,
American novelist. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Event to remember: Mike the Headless Chicken Days, celebrated in
the western Colorado town of Fruta, honors a 1940s Wyandotte
rooster who is said to have lived two years without a head. This
year's festival, May 19-20, will feature chicken bingo, egg tosses,
polka dances, chicken joke contests, a microbrewery competition,
and a 5K Run-Like-A-Headless-Chicken Race. For more information
about Colorado events, visit www.colorado.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: In Ocean City, N.J., it is against the law to
slurp your soup at a restaurant. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Guess you'll just have to buy one: For those who have asked,
Guinness will not be holding its ``Win a Pub in Ireland'' contest
this year. After six years, it's giving the contest a rest. Last
year's competition drew more than 70,000 entries. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Museum of the month: The National Watch and Clock Museum in
Columbia, Pa., just keeps on ticking. Its hundreds of timepieces
cover the history of timekeeping from early nonmechanical devices
to today's atomic and radio-controlled clocks. There are German
musical clocks, a clock with 48 moving figures, and an 11-foot-tall
French statue clock. There are also exhibits on tools, art, and
models. The museum is at 514 Poplar St., Columbia, PA 17512-2130;
phone 717-684-8261, fax 717-684-0142, Web page
www.nawcc.org/museum/nawcc/nawmus.htm. Admission is charged.
</P>
<P>
   Zoom! The fastest passenger elevators in the world are the
express elevators to the 60th floor of the ``Sunshine 60'' building
in Tokyo. They travel 2,000 feet per minute _ that's 22.7 miles an
hour. (With thanks to Daytrips.com via faithful contributor Mike
Schuster of Foxborough.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Home, not-so-sweet home: The government of Romania is preparing to
give tourists a chance to stay in the home once occupied by the
brutal dictator Nicolas Ceausescu and his fur-loving wife, Elena.
The cost will be $3,000-$4,000 a night, but you'll be able to swim
in their mosaic-lined pool. (With thanks to world traveler Tom
Bross of Boston.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Candyland: Chicago, of all places, is the candy capital of the
world, according to the National Confectioners Association. The
candy industry employs 13,000 people at about 100 companies in the
Chicago area. Those people make $4 billion worth of candy every
year. Chicago's candy business got going in the 1800s because the
city was a transportation hub and manufacturing center, and milk
and corn syrup were readily available. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Libya's flag is monochromatic and Nepal's is
non-rectangular. (With thanks to Sheldon Cohen of Marblehead.)
</P>
</TEXT>
