<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3516 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-JUDO-FELTON-BOS &LR;      03-21 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-JUDO-FELTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATECOMER FALLS FOR JUDO WITH OLYMPIAN EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEEKONK, Mass. _ It was the fermented mare's milk that did it.
Joe Felton was sitting at a feast somewhere in Uzbekistan when
someone handed him a tumbler of the regional beverage _ just like
Trigger used to drink. ``That's when it hit me,'' Felton says.
``What the hell am I doing here? How did I get here?''
</P>
<P>
   He was an ex-Detroit Lion who'd been working as a personal
trainer down by the Rhode Island border. Now Felton's an ippon or
two away from Olympus, from getting a ticket to Sydney with the US
judo team at 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty much unheard of,'' says Jimmy Pedro, the world
champion from Lawrence who is favored to win the gold medal in the
lightweight class. ``For someone who started as late as Joe did,
it's almost impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Most judo players start hanging out at the dojo as children.
Felton didn't step onto the mat until he was 29, but got himself to
the world championships in just three years.
</P>
<P>
   Being a heavyweight _ Felton is 6 feet 2 inches, 280 pounds _
undoubtedly helped. There are so few of them in judo that a good
athlete with quick hands and feet, discipline and poise, and a
patient coach can become a contender in much less than a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Peter Contardo and Mike Nees were thinking when they
saw Felton walk into a pizza joint half a dozen years ago. ``Look
at the size of him,'' Contardo marveled to Nees. ``What do you
think? Wouldn't he make a great heavyweight?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever done judo?'' Nees asked Felton. He might as well have
said: ``Ever done jai alai?'' Though he lives in Fall River now,
Felton comes from Michigan, where most folks don't know judo from
Judas. ``It's either football or wrestling there,'' says Felton.
``That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Felton was an offensive guard from Saginaw, good enough to be
offered a full ride to Michigan from Bo Schembechler. But after
Felton tore up his knee and the Big Ten lost interest, he ended up
at Albion, a Division 3 school between Ann Arbor and Battle Creek
where he made small college All-America.
</P>
<P>
   When the NFL players went on strike in 1987, Felton went to the
cattle call for replacement players and found himself starting for
the Lions. Just like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father's a UAW member who works for GM,'' Felton says. ``I
said, Dad, I'm going to be a scab. He said, for $6,000 a week, I
don't care what you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Detroit fans, especially when the ersatz Lions beat
the Packers on the road in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``They loved us,'' Felton recalls. ``We were the Lions who were
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The scrapbook fantasy lasted three games, until the regulars
returned. So Felton played Arena Football with the New England
Steamrollers and Detroit Drive and wangled a few NFL tryouts, one
of them with the Patriots in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was cold, wintery, rainy and I was running 4.6s,'' he
remembers. ``My hamstring just bunched up on me, and that was
that.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Felton decided it was time to hang up the pads for
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been in and out of pro football and I was getting tired of
it,'' he says. ``So I took a couple of years and just goofed
around, figuring out what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Felton taught as a substitute in the Fall River schools. He ran
a center for juvenile delinquents. He did some personal training.
But except for some stay-in-shape powerlifting, he was out of
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Until Contardo and Nees persuaded Felton to drop by the dojo and
have a look.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you come here and you train and you do what you're supposed
to,'' Nees told him, ``I'll get you to the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   All Felton had to do was start from Page 1, work out two and
three times a day for a couple of years, go overseas for months at
a time _ and forget every instinct he'd had on a gridiron.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd always been trained to attack,' he says. ``In football,
you learn to be aggressive. In judo, you have to be passive.''
</P>
<P>
   Once his coaches got him to stop grappling with his rivals as if
they were defensive tackles, Felton progressed quickly. Unlike most
heavyweights, he's quick and mobile. And he approached the sport
with obsessive intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe lived at that dojo _ literally,'' says Contardo.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, Felton was dominating his coaches on the mat.
Once he won his first competition, it was time to cross some oceans
and take on the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing my Mom said when I was doing judo was: How
much are you getting paid?,'' says Felton, who now makes his living
installing car lifts in garages. ``I said, well, I sold my
motorcycle and my truck . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Felton went to Hungary, to England, to Germany, to France, to
Austria, to Poland, to the Czech Republic, to the Netherlands, to
the Scandinavian countries, to any place he could find training and
someone his size to fight. For a while, he was roughly as welcome
as scarlet fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a little animosity toward me,'' Felton says. ``There
still is.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody wanted to take on the American football player and
club him upside the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I wish I could just get them over here, get a helmet
on them, and go at it,'' Felton says.
</P>
<P>
   With the animosity, though, came fascination.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to a dojo in Japan, they just kept coming,''
Felton says. ``They all wanted to throw me.''
</P>
<P>
   They found out it wasn't all that easy. Though he still can't
count to 10 in Japanese, Felton knows the essential holds and
locks, the grappling and choking techniques and the dozens of
throws, from double outside reaps to ``rice bag'' reversals.
</P>
<P>
   What came more slowly was ``mat sense,'' knowing how to craft a
strategy for every minute of the match, how to maneuver and
manipulate an opponent _ and how to avoid being cat-and-moused
oneself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you screw up in football, you have the rest of the game to
recover,'' Felton says. ``In judo, if you make one mistake, you go
home.''
</P>
<P>
   His first world championships in 1997 was a one-day advanced
course that left Felton humbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was close each time,'' he recalls. ``But I'd make a stupid
mistake each time.''
</P>
<P>
   Felton had a return ticket last year, but after trashing his
knee in Japan, he decided to opt out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go and not be able to do anything,'' he
figured.
</P>
<P>
   The important thing is to make it to Olympus. To do that, Felton
needs to outpoint top rival Martin Boonzaayer, a Motorola engineer
and Mr. America runner-up, by the time the national championships
end in April.
</P>
<P>
   That means winning a medal at next month's Rotterdam Grand Prix
or British Open. That also means three sessions a week at the old
Masonic Hall on County Street, which Nees has transformed into a
roomy dojo.
</P>
<P>
   When Felton was missing for a while around the holidays, he got
a phone call from his sensei. ``Did you forget how to get here?''
Nees needled him. ``If you need a map, it's on my Web site
(www.mikesdojo.inpronet.com).''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese don't take Christmas off. And there'll be no
replacement players in Sydney. That was the whole point of Felton's
taking up judo in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do this so I could say I was a local champion,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Felton sold his wheels and bounced around bargain-basement
Europe and fought malodorous strangers and went passive-aggressive
so he could get to where he is now, a throw or three away from
Sydney. They don't drink mare's milk there. Just lager, mate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
