<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3517 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-SURF-CAMP-2TAK     03-21 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SURF-CAMP-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURF CAMPS: GREAT WAVES ARE WITHIN REACH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos available on NYT database) 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over third a in Mazatlan)  
 
By JOE DOGGETT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAMOTU ISLAND, Fiji _ A blue hill pushed across the open Pacific
toward the barrier reef. The wave rose with growing promise against
the abrupt bottom and transformed into a steepening wall as it
swept along the edge of the reef pass. Reflections of sunlit coral
ghosted through the clear trough, and the morning wind tore a
crackle of urgent spray from the crest.
</P>
<P>
   Magnificent isn't too strong a word to describe this mighty
force of nature _ at least not for the surfers who know these
moments best.
</P>
<P>
   Wyman Wade of Houston swung his 9-foot board and took three
powerful strokes to launch over the pitching ledge. The 43-year-old
Wade sprang to his feet, flexing in a crouch to absorb the drop.
The crest threw out and over, blasting with an avalanche of white
as the speeding board banked from the bottom and aimed like a spear
for the unbroken shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The surfer climbed and dropped, racing the peeling wave for 200
yards down the reef before pulling out amid a plume of spray into
the safety of the channel. Outside, beyond the dissipating foam
that charted the ride, another perfect blue wave was wrapping down
the reef. Gregg Pratka, in position, began scratching for the
takeoff while fellow Houstonians John Stavinoha and Chris Noon,
paddling out, yelled encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, the idea of a group of middle-aged
Americans riding a remote reef break in Fiji was inconceivable.
International surf exploration, still in its infancy, was the turf
of surf guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed on the beach and in the curl. Now surf
resorts _ or ``surf camps,'' although the rough-and-tumble
connotation doesn't always apply _ lure adventure-seeking travelers
to the South Pacific, Mexico, Central America and other spots
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   This global quest for the ``perfect wave'' gained steam in the
mid-1960s, when Bruce Brown's ``The Endless Summer'' (a documentary
about two surfers traveling in search of surf) inspired a
generation of wave riders to venture beyond the growing crowds in
California, Hawaii and Florida. The first ``secret spots'' on the
Pacific Coast were drive-to beaches in Mexico, such as Mazatlan and
San Blas. East Coast surfers found Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   During the '70s, the potential for world-class reefs and points
exploded as surfers took to the off-road jungles of Mexico, Central
America, Africa and Indonesia. Guarded word of fabulous breaks
filtered back _ Petacalco in Mexico, La Libertad in El Salvador,
Pavones in Costa Rica, Chicama in Peru, Uluwatu in Bali, Grajagan
in Java, Tavarua in Fiji, Jeffrey's Bay in South Africa. Exotic
blue-and-green images began appearing in surf magazines and films.
</P>
<P>
   Jungle waves tantalized urban surfers mired in the brown rubble
of crowded beach breaks, but these remote destinations were mostly
the domain of hard-core adventurers _ renegades and one-eyed jacks
toting battered single-fin pintails and tattered backpacks, willing
to eat dust and risk revolution for the sight of ``la punta
perfecta'' unreeling off some nameless malarial river mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Many failed in their crusade. A few died. But those who scored
expanded the horizon and changed surfing forever.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, a vagabond known as the Jackal was holding court on the
Mazatlan seawall. He overlooked Cannon's Point, the glossy
left-breaking wave that had started the wanderlust for thousands of
surfers who saw ``Stoner's Mexican Log,'' Ron Stoner's photo spread
in the November 1966 issue of Surfer magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackal was a ne'er-do-well, but he was experienced. He had a
case-hardened tan, and he had seen the beaches and ridden the waves
deep in the ``Centro'' jungles. When mighty Cannon's boomed on a
big south swell, he would take off on the sucking ledge behind the
boil, over the shallow rocks spiked with purple sea urchins. That
day the Jackal stared with knowing eyes, pointed a knuckly finger
and said, ``When you get back to the country club, tell 'em center
court ain't nowhere close.''
</P>
<P>
   As any serious surfer will agree, the Jackal was correct in his
assessment of center court, indeed all courts and courses. But time
has proved him wrong on the country-club mentality.
</P>
<P>
   The country club has come to the surf. Over the past decade, the
expansion of &UR;  &LR; surf camps at tropical destinations has had a
significant impact on surfing.
</P>
<P>
   A typical surf camp or resort near a classic break offers a
full-service package that includes airport pickup, lodging, meals
and transfers by boat or land vehicle to surf spots. Usually a
qualified water patrol remains on site while guests are in the
water.
</P>
<P>
   The cost (excluding air fare) of a week at an upscale surf
resort is about $1,000 _ cheap compared to similar packages at top
ski resorts or fishing lodges.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of having someone deliver a pina colada to your hot tub
or escort you to the surf might be scorned by dedicated off-road
explorers, but the established resorts are booked solid during peak
surf seasons. Some have long waiting lists. They appeal to
professionals and family-oriented surfers, people who lust for
adventure but cannot afford to spend weeks or months trailing off
in quest of ``secret spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Namotu Blue Water Sports Resort is a fine example of an upscale
wave-riding bivouac. It sits alone on Namotu Island, which is part
of the Mamanuca Island chain southwest of Fiji's main island, Viti
Levu. The resort was started in 1996 by a small partnership of
Australians and Hawaiians. The operation books through
California-based WaterWays Surf Adventures (motto: ``Offering
global surf relief for local surf anxiety'') and caters almost
entirely to surfers.
</P>
<P>
   Namotu is tiny, occupying three to five acres, depending on the
tide swing. The little outcrop lies inside the Malolo Barrier Reef,
several miles north of more famous Tavarua Island. The coral reef
catches open-ocean swells generated by storms in the Roaring
Forties south of Australia, and various passes allow the waves to
break with regimented control into deeper channels. The peeling
waves create excellent surfing conditions, especially under the
prevailing light to moderate ``side-off'' trade winds.
</P>
<P>
   The water over the South Seas reefs is clear as alcohol,
sparkling with gaudy corals and glittering fish, and the water
temperature averages about 78 degrees (similar to Hawaii's South
Shore/Waikiki area). Sunny days predominate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
