</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-RALPH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN'S SHEA RALPH IS STRONGER AFTER TWO KNEE SURGERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ The long road back from an anterior cruciate
ligament injury, as any athlete will tell you, is fraught with
physical and mental minefields. One wrong step and _ kaboom! _ you
can be thrown for a giant setback. But the journey back, as
grueling as it can be on the mind, body, and spirit, is extremely
rewarding in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Shea Ralph knows all too well the feelings of exasperation and
exhilaration that such a rehabilitation can evoke.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the University of Connecticut junior forward has
made the descent into that physical hell and ascent to complete
recovery twice. The first time she tore her right ACL was March 15,
1997, in the first NCAA tournament appearance of her dazzling
freshman season. It happened on a fast break with 12:31 left in the
first half of a 103-35 rout of Lehigh in the first round of the
Midwest Regional.
</P>
<P>
   After undergoing extensive rehabilitation that got her back on
the court that August, Ralph wound up sitting out the 1997-98
season as a medical redshirt when she reinjured the knee in
preseason workouts Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Going through that once is enough to make anyone wince. But
twice in the same year? It would seem a harsh sentence to impose on
any athlete's budding career.
</P>
<P>
   But Ralph's resolve to fight back was unwavering.
</P>
<P>
   Her sheer will and determination to overcome her injury and make
herself into a better player than when she arrived at Storrs,
Conn., four years ago as a highly-touted high school All-American
from Fayetteville, N.C., is the main reason the top-ranked and
top-seeded Huskies romped through the first two rounds of the NCAA
East Regional last weekend to clinch their seventh straight Sweet
16 appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Shea's case, her mindset once she came to Connecticut from
where she was in high school, the injury was probably the worst
thing that could've happened to her,'' said UConn coach Geno
Auriemma. ``She was just learning what it was to be part of a
really good team and what she had to do to be a part of that team.
Then the injury happened, and it forced her to become even more
self-directed: `I've got to do this for me. I've got to get back.
I've got to get my game back. I've got to get healthy.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So you keep going down that path where it's all about you and
what you're doing, and it kind of set her back a little bit. You
never know how a kid will respond to that. Some kids never come
back, and some kids come back better than they ever were. In her
case, she had to go through it again. The second time? Honestly, if
you would've told me that Shea would never play again at the level
that she was accustomed to playing, I would say that I wouldn't be
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that's how far I think she's had to come.''
</P>
<P>
   So which took a greater toll on her? The physical or mental
aspect of her rehab.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither was easy,'' Ralph said. ``The physical was the hardest
_ short term. It was the first thing I had to face. Mentally, I
didn't have to face anything but my rehab every day. The physical
part was harder for me in the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mental part took longer for me to overcome and I think if
you compare the two, the mental part was way, way harder, because
physically you can only do so much and it's guaranteed to pay off.
Mentally, you have to find the right thing and you don't even know
if it'll pay off or not.''
</P>
<P>
   All throughout her medical redshirt year, Ralph wrestled with
the same fears that most athletes do when rehabbing from a torn
ACL.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Will I be the same athlete? Will I be better after this?
Or worse off?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Ralph knew it would be a long road back to where she left off as
a freshman, when she averaged 11.4 points and 4.5 rebounds off the
bench and was recognized as Big East Rookie of the Year and
National Freshman of the Year by The Sporting News.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I did (worry) in the beginning. I think everybody
does,'' she said. ``I think it was part of the process that I
needed to go through to learn and to grow from what happened. So
there was a part of me that did worry, and I think that when I was
worrying and concerned about that I wasn't a player. I didn't play
well. I didn't even belong on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I overcame that, and I started to focus my energies
outward instead of inward, it all worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't until February of her sophomore season, when she
returned to the lineup after missing four games with a sprained
medial collateral ligament and dropped 36 points on Boston College
in her first collegiate start. Ralph went on to improve her scoring
average to 16.8 ppg after starting 11 of 30 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about two or three weeks after I started playing in
January that I put it all behind me and began to play,'' she said.
``Last year, there were relapses and whatnot, but I still had a lot
of learning to do because I wasn't very experienced and my role had
changed, and I had to get accustomed to it and I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I made some decisions over the summer in what I wanted to
do and what I wanted to be for this program and for my teammates.
It's just really worked out for me and I'm happy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because she is finally reaping the rewards of all her
hard work. She earned Big East Player of the Year honors after
starting all 31 regular-season games and leading the Huskies in
scoring (14.5 ppg). She recently was named to the Associated Press
All-America team along with UConn teammate Svetlana Abrosimova.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the journey has been physically to get her knee
back, I think mentally the jump has been even further,'' Auriemma
said. ``It's easy to go in the weight room and lift weights and
rehab and do all that. That's easy. To become better mentally and
to understand what the game is all about, that's hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``For her to have made that jump and not lost any aggression in
both the mental and physical part of her game is something really
special.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
