</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE READY TO THROW CONTRACT OVER TO HELP PATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Drew Bledsoe says he's not looking to break
the bank and is willing to restructure his contract to help make
the Patriots a better team.
</P>
<P>
   But Bledsoe, who took part in the first official day of strength
and conditioning workouts under new specialty coach Mike Woicik,
may be waiting for some time on that.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations began last year, but Patriots CEO Andy Wasynczuk
said Monday that no proposals from the Bledsoe side would benefit
the financial future of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Because Bledsoe's cap numbers are so high _ $8.66 million this
season and $9.3 million next season _ the Patriots are somewhat
handcuffed on signing free agents. Wasynczuk has restructured other
players' contracts _ pushing more payments into the future _ but he
fears doing that with a contract as large as Bledsoe's.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at restructuring, there's a certain amount you
do that is kind of affordable for your future,'' said Wasynczuk.
``It doesn't matter if you do it with your quarterback as long as
you can do it with a number of players. If you do it with everyone,
you're in San Francisco's shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, who has the most service time among current Patriots
(seven years), said, ``It's something we've talked about it and
there have been discussions. My cap number is high and it would
help the team if there were a renegotiation. I'm not going to hold
the team hostage for the very last dollar. The Patriots have been
very good to me and I know they will continue to be. At some point,
there needs to be something done so we can remain competitive in
the free agent market and re-sign our guys.''
</P>
<P>
   So why hasn't it been done?
</P>
<P>
   ``With the stadium, the coaching change, there have been things
going on,'' said Bledsoe. ``It's not something I'm concerned about.
At some point it needs to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the Patriots are holding off because they're
uncertain about their commitment to Bledsoe after a subpar season,
Wasynczuk said, ``The flip side is that, from our point of view,
that might be the best time to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said, ``When and if it gets done, it opens up a lot of
room for us. I'm open to it and I'm hoping it happens very
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   But apparently it won't. There may be more conversations on the
topic at the owners' meetings in Palm Beach, Fla., next week, if
Wasynczuk runs into Bledsoe's agent, Leigh Steinberg. Otherwise,
the Patriots are concentrating on other issues, such as trying to
get Tedy Bruschi and Bruce Armstrong re-signed.
</P>
<P>
   At 27 years old, and in the middle of a seven-year, $42 million
deal, Bledsoe can't believe he's the elder statesman on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here longer than the owner, longer than the coaching
staff (except for Dante Scarnecchia),'' he said. ``Only the
equipment guy and the two trainers have been here longer. I think
of myself as a kid, yet I have the longest tenure in the
organization. Time is short in this league. The first seven years
have gone by pretty quickly and I know that the rest of it is going
to go by quickly. I have to approach this year like it's my only
opportunity to make it to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   But first he must put last season behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the midway point, we felt we had something going,'' said
Bledsoe. ``To have it turn so dramatically, it was tough to deal
with. For me, it's easier to come back and easier to focus on
things I need to focus on. I feel everything outside of football is
about as good as I can make it. When I come here and focus on
football, I can do that clearly. I think I have a better
understanding of what I need to do to prepare for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he called 1999 ``the most disappointing season of my
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bledsoe, ``Teams started challenging us and gave us press
coverage down the field and we didn't react very favorably. We just
didn't make plays the second half and we turned it over. You don't
ever forget about it. You file it away as experience and you learn
from the bad plays. As far as the emotional part, yeah, I'm over
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback will soon sit down with new coach Bill Belichick
to determine what it was that it made it so difficult for him to
play the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll pick his brain on what he felt were my strengths and
weaknesses when he was playing me,'' said Bledsoe. ``I'm sure he'll
share those things with me.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has not reviewed his film from last season, but he
didn't think he had mechanical problems. He will be asked to
improve his footwork and mobility, but he is what he is _ one of
the last classic dropback passers in the NFL. It's an issue he
thinks about often, especially with the trend shifting toward
mobile quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can still get the job done,'' he said. ``I know I can
take this team to a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe will miss Ben Coates and, if he is not re-signed,
Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're on a short list of the best players who have ever
played for the Patriots,'' said Bledsoe. ``To see those guys depart
is very hard to take. The door is still open for Bruce and I hope
to do everything in my power to get him back here.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the offseason personnel losses _ and few additions _ he
still thinks the Patriots are a team to be reckoned with. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're naive, and that's what we do,'' said Bledsoe. ``If I had
to take the field with you guys, I'd be optimistic about it. It
might be unrealistic, but I'm going to be optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also know we have lost some guys. I know about the
character of this team, and we have enough talent that if we make
enough plays we can win. I believe that we can be very competitive
and with a couple of additions we can do some things.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coates is visiting with the Tennessee Titans Tuesday . . . Terry
Glenn wasn't seen at the first day of the strength program; agent
Jim Gould said Glenn was due to arrive Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
