u t BC-TRAVEL-SURF-CAMP-2NDT     03-21 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SURF-CAMP-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
NAMOTU ISLAND, Fiji: Sunny days predominate.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Namotu is ringed by three potentially world-class surf breaks _
Namotu Lefts, Swimming Pools and Wilkes. All can be observed from
the camp. Under favorable weather and swell conditions, Namotu is a
compact Fantasy Island, and the resort's package tour puts a week
within reach of wave-starved surfers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   After a 10-hour nonstop Air Pacific flight from Los Angeles to
Nadi on Viti Levu, the 16-man Texas contingent was met at dawn by
air-conditioned tour buses and transported to a shallow backwater
bay about an hour away for boat transfers to Namotu.
</P>
<P>
   Long, open, outboard-powered skiffs staffed by surf camps at
Namotu and Tavarua were well-suited for loading surfboard bags and
luggage. The run to the barrier reef took about 45 minutes.
Recurring lines of white beyond the growing specks of land assured
that the surf was up.
</P>
<P>
   Landing at Namotu International Dock and Wharf (otherwise known
as the leeward beach), the group was met by waving and singing
staff members. Necklaces of coral and shell were draped over each
arriving neck, and drinks were shuttled from the decked bar that
overlooks the barrier reef and the beautiful Namotu Lefts.
</P>
<P>
   The resort, managed by Australians Scotty and Mandy O'Connor,
can lodge groups of 16-20. Two bunkhouses are complemented by
several two- to four-bed thatched bungalows, or ``bures,'' with
private bathrooms and balconies. No air conditioning is available,
but most days it is not needed.
</P>
<P>
   Meals are served with South Seas flair and flare (as in flaming
torches) amid palm fronds and tapa cloth on the deck next to the
swimming pool and hot tub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, my wife would really like `roughing it' here,'' was the
refrain during Scotty O'Connor's orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The skiffs are used to transport surfers to the breaks and held
ready for unlimited transfers, a solid program that allows
leisurely sessions to suit individual schedules.
</P>
<P>
   The mood around the camp and kitchen was upbeat, highlighted by
a ``magiti,'' or feast. The feast included platters of grilled
fish, roasted pig and the kava-drinking ritual. To get off on the
right foot (a bare one, naturally), all guests are expected to
partake.
</P>
<P>
   Kava is a muddy, slightly narcotic liquid pounded from the root
of the pepper plant. It is served from a ``tanoa,'' a large wooden
bowl. The celebrants, male and female, wear wrap-around skirts
called ``sulus'' and sit in a circle on woven mats as the kava is
served in a ``bilo,'' a cup made from half a coconut shell.
</P>
<P>
   The proper technique requires clapping once, then taking the
full cup in both hands and bowing slightly to the server. The drink
is quaffed in one bold, mouth-numbing swallow; then you hand the
empty vessel to the server and clap three times.
</P>
<P>
   You do not want to trip over your trailing vestments and drop
the cup. The ceremony is an ancient custom, and the only thing
worse than getting drilled on a double-overhead Fijian wave is
choking on a kava cup and spewing the host.
</P>
<P>
   All this might sound contrived, but on a small South Seas
island, under the flicker of torches, against the concussion of the
black reef, with your face greasy and your lips numb, in the
company of proven comrades, it works pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   Not that surf resorts are without problems and controversies.
Regardless of venue, each tide is different, and a flat spell or a
contrary wind might wipe out several days, even an entire week _ a
soul-deadening prospect for the short-term Crusoe on a package
trip.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, the surf might be out of control,
dangerous for a casual participant. Surf camps are near serious
breaks, with the kind of waves that dedicated surfers are willing
to spend time and money to ride. It's easy to get in over your head
at a world-class spot, especially for the swelling ranks of the
sport's ``gray wave.'' Older surfers may have the resources, but
the perfect wave can prove too much for the imperfect wave rider.
</P>
<P>
   Middle-aged affluence might buy a gunned custom Fry pintail
surfboard, a first-class Air Pacific upgrade and a week at Namotu
Blue Water Sports Resort, but you are alone and stripped of all
pretense in the lineup to ride the waves. One of the truths of
surfing is that there are no timeouts and no penalty strokes, and
no gold card can bail you out if things start going horribly wrong
about midway down the face of a freight-train wave.
</P>
<P>
   Surf camps usually require waivers or disclaimers in case a
guest is jackhammered into the reef or speared by a board or
carried under in a rip. Reasonable levels of fitness and expertise
are expected; without them, you should stay home or remain a
noncombatant on the big days.
</P>
<P>
   One appealing aspect for graybeards is that the most consistent
spot here, Namotu Lefts, has a deeper reef under the surfing area.
This cushion provides a ``softer'' wave with more sloping face than
the terrifying Cloudbreak of nearby Tavarua. Namotu certainly is a
serious wave in the double-overhead class, but normally it is not
life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Spending a week on a small island rimmed by winding reef breaks
allows many opportunities for personal success and failure.
Highlights might include a huge, high-speed cutback on a bowling
peak at Namotu Lefts or an immaculate 100-yard trim on an overhead
right at Swimming Pools with the sun-sparkled curl pitching above
straining arms and streaming board during the entire run.
</P>
<P>
   Another pure moment might be a crushing wipeout _ too deep, too
steep, nowhere to go but down, tumbling across the shelving reef
and emerging bleeding and frightened, gasping and choking, to face
another pummel of whitewater and the realization that the clean
line of surfing can take you to the edge.
</P>
<P>
   One intriguing aspect of surfing in Fiji involves laws that
allow surf camps to control specific breaks _ a notion that is
offensive to some surfers. (The dusty Jackal would be appalled.)
</P>
<P>
   In most countries, the ocean beyond the tideline belongs to the
public; surfers have the right to ride waves near a camp without
being hassled or abused.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Fiji is unusual because the tribes of the
Mamanuca Islands have for generations owned fishing rights on reefs
rimming the islands. The case has been made that waves, like fish,
are associated with particular reef formations, so the inhabitants
of Namotu and Tavarua regulate access to some surf spots.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, full-service resorts are a positive step,
placing adventure travel and great surf within reliable reach of
thousands of surfers each year.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the country-club concept is working. And the perfect
wave is only a phone call away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
