<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN AT PEACE WITH HIS DECISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Something has changed with Mo Vaughn. Call it a
new attitude. Say that, after eight-plus seasons in baseball, he
has grown up and now fully understands the circumstances
surrounding his departure from the Red Sox after the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   He is no longer reticent to talk about it. Feeling like a kid
again, Vaughn says he can't wait to begin his second season with
the Anaheim Angels, who shelled out $80 million to sign him. During
negotiations with the Red Sox, Vaughn often claimed his decision
wasn't about money. But he never has said what the other
considerations were. In a recent interview, he came close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had put in seven years,'' said Vaughn. ``I knew I wasn't
going to do any better in Boston. I wasn't going to hit any higher.
I couldn't hit any more home runs. I couldn't drive in more runs.
The only place that I could go was down _ and I knew that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to play there. Don't get me wrong. I'm not wishing
anyone bad luck just because they put on a Red Sox uniform. But it
needs to be said it is hard to play there. So when my contract was
up, I knew it was time to go.''
</P>
<P>
   A slimmer and more mature Vaughn says he is ready for a second
season with the Angels. He is confident that he can improve on his
1999 season, when he hit just .281 with 33 home runs and 108 RBIs.
The ankle sprain he incurred on Opening Day and cost him 30 games
has healed, and he will be ready to face his old team come April 7
in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, 32, confessed it took him almost a year and a half to
put his feelings into focus. But now that he has, he should be a
better person and player. He has no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy now,'' he said. ``Happy with a new regime, new
coaches and a new manager. My family is happy and that's
important.''
</P>
<P>
   When he played for the Red Sox, Vaughn was a superstar of
enormous dimensions who had few private moments around here. But
after he signed with Anaheim, he still spent part of the offseason
in New England, and it was a wakeup call not being part of the Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   It bothered him that news of his charitable work slipped out of
sight. He noticed that Red Sox fans who had supported him in his
dispute with Dan Duquette began to question his professionalism.
That hurt. Even when he got media coverage, things like the Foxy
Lady and negative off-field incidents usually were mentioned. That
is just wrong, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should have lived somewhere else and not lived in New
England year round,'' said Vaughn. ``But I still have ties with the
foundation. I enjoy working and being with those kids. I have a
place in California now. Out here, nobody bothers you.''
</P>
<P>
   Happiness for Mo Vaughn has not come easy. The ankle injury
pretty much destroyed any chance he had of being ``The Savior'' in
Anaheim in 1999. The team, which some picked to win the American
League West or at least earn a wild-card berth because of Vaughn,
finished last in the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you saw the real Mo last year,'' said Gary
DiSarcina, the veteran Angels shortstop from Billerica, Mass. ``He
came into a whole new situation and got hurt right away. He wasn't
producing the way he thought he should. He was hands off and pretty
stiff. He was mostly looking in from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year is very different. He's very vocal and having fun.
Guys feed off that. When they see Mo having fun, it kind of relaxes
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be no more second-guessing himself about leaving
Boston, Vaughn insists. The decision was correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it first in 1998 when I walked off the field after I
hit a double off the wall in a playoff game,'' said Vaughn. ``The
more I thought about it, the more I got tired of people trying to
figure out what type of person I was or what I was doing off the
field. I realized I might have a real problem if I didn't continue
to go out and hit .320 and 40 bombs a year and drive in 140-plus
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my performance had deteriorated, I could understand. But I
was already doing the best I could. The only place I knew I could
go was down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Sox knew I played for the love of the game. But in
Boston they didn't evaluate me that way. They were evaluating me on
other things. After I signed with Anaheim, I knew I would never be
able to adequately explain any situations or my contract. I would
never be able to explain this or that. I would always wind up being
looked at in a negative light, and I didn't feel I deserved that.
</P>
<P>
   The West Coast lifestyle is a lot better than he thought it
would be. He lives in Newport, Calif., near his parents. He says he
feels as comfortable there as he does in Anaheim Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living there is really different than back East,'' said
Vaughn. ``Here there are so many more athletes. I hang out with
Shaq when I'm in LA. I hang with other guys like Charles Barkley .
. . a lot of guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been exposed to several new industries _ music and
movies. But I know who I am. I'm a baseball player. I'm not going
to be a rapper.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this realm, you can just be regular. You don't have
anything to hide or worry about because not everybody has their
eyes focused on you. Your're not an icon or a superstar. You're
just like they are. It's nice.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Red Sox reach the playoffs, said Vaughn, ``Don't be
surprised to find the Angels waiting for them.''
</P>
<P>
   An overhaul of the staff _ from manager Terry Collins down
through the scouts _ has Vaughn excited about the team's chances.
He already has become close with new manager Mike Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like two peas in a pod,'' said Vaughn. ``In Mike we have a guy
who understands what it takes to win. You look around and you have
a lot of talent. We could use some pitching, without a doubt. The
main thing is that we've got the right approach now. Nobody is
picking us. So we'll just sneak up on everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know all these guys yet. But I must have changed my
attitude and approach a whole lot _ to the point they ask me, `Why
weren't you like that last year?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
