<HEADLINE>
WHERE DID THE BIG BANG HAPPEN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Assuming that the Big Bang theory is correct, where in the
Universe did it occur? Specifically, how many light years was it
from the present milky way galaxy _ our Earth in particular. Are we
on an outer edge of the universe? What could be beyond the known
universe?
</P>
<P>
   B.L., Norfolk, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The tricky thing about the expansion of the universe is that
it's supposed to be an expansion of space itself, rather than an
expansion into a pre-existing space. Probably the best way to
visualize what's going on is by analogy and the best analogy of the
expansion of our three-dimensional universe is the two-dimensional
surface of a balloon as it gets inflated. Dots drawn on the balloon
all move away from each other and there is no center on the surface
_ every point moves away from every other. The total area of the
surface is finite, but there are no walls or edges.
</P>
<P>
   For our universe, the idea is pretty much the same. Everything
moves away from everything else and there is no center. The total
volume of the universe is finite, but there are no walls or edges.
Hard to understand? You bet. Einstein tried to fudge his equation
of gravity in order to describe a static universe with no
expansion. He thus missed predicting the expanding universe and
later called it the biggest scientific blunder of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Now what's beyond the universe? Well, by definition, the
universe is everything. In the balloon analogy, the inside of the
balloon is just something to help us imagine the expansion, but not
a part of the two-dimensional world of dots on the surface. In the
same way (again, it's tricky), our universe is supposed to be all
there is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
