r e BC-CARAVAN-LADN &LR;      03-21 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARAVAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CARAVAN' HAS ROOM TO RIDE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One beneficial effect of an Academy Award nomination is the
``Oscar bounce,'' the frequent jump in audience interest that this
year blessed ``American Beauty'' and ``The Cider House Rules''
following their respective wads of nominations.
</P>
<P>
   But another Oscar nominee, ``Caravan,'' is hoping for its own
sort of bounce with a different audience: a film distributor.
</P>
<P>
   Where the high-profile U.S. releases are merely counting the
extra millions rolling in from newly appreciative fans, the makers
of ``Caravan'' are trying to bring their film _ shot in one of the
world's most remote, and stunning, regions _ to American
theater-goers.
</P>
<P>
   Though 3 million people have already seen the film in France,
and it has done well in the few other countries where it has a
distribution deal, it somehow managed to get an Oscar nomination
with no U.S. theatrical outlet, one of only two such films this
year, according to its makers.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Frenchman Eric Valli, ``Caravan'' is the official
best foreign language film nominee of Nepal, where it was shot with
largely non-professional actors, based on the nearly two decades
Valli spent in the Himalayan highlands as a still photographer and
documentary maker.
</P>
<P>
   Valli uses his photographer's eye to capture image after
overwhelming image of the hard-scrabble village life in Dolpo, in
northwest Nepal. The film revolves around the periodic caravans
that set out on foot from the village for the 900-mile trip to more
fertile areas where they trade salt for grain.
</P>
<P>
   An old chief, Tinle, blames his son's death during a caravan on
Karma, his son's assistant and best friend. He fights Karma's
naming by village elders as the man to lead the next caravan.
</P>
<P>
   Karma in turn defies village traditions by starting the caravan
before the officially ordained day, taking most of the village's
yaks and young men in an effort to beat the looming winter storms.
</P>
<P>
   Tinle organizes a second caravan with some of the village's old
men, his daughter-in-law, grandson and second son, who is a monk,
and drives them hard to catch up. How the chiefs _ old, new and yet
to come _ deal with the arduous trip forms much of the film.
</P>
<P>
   The hard journey reflects the hard process of making the film
itself, Valli said. Just to get to Dolpo requires walking a crew
and equipment over three mountain ``passes'' that each are more
than 17,000 feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the highest inhabited part of the world,'' said Valli,
who lived there for two years. ``You cannot helicopter in, because
you would blow your brain out from the altitude. You would die of
edema. It's like some parts of America 200 years ago. It's a rough
life. We could compare Tinle to 'The Last of the Mohicans.'''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most astonishing shots are taken along a narrow
trail cut into a sheer rock face above a mountain lake. The scene
mirrors an experience Valli had a dozen years ago with a real
caravan, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a documentary. But it's very authentic,'' Valli
said. ``There are no special effects, other than the stars (in a
twilight scene) and the yak falling in (on the lake trail).
Otherwise, we're shooting what is very similar to their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   That included five weeks of shooting the film's climactic scenes
in snowstorms over one of the passes. For all those physical
challenges, Valli said his biggest challenge was getting his
17-member crew to interact comfortably with the villagers who
played all the film's roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Tinle since 1983,'' Valli said. ``We've been
roaming together for many, many years. But I knew if I couldn't
create the relationship that I had with the crew and my friends in
Dolpo, I couldn't bring back the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Valli said he was overwhelmed by the film's Oscar nomination,
though he had previously received one for a short documentary
called ``Shadow Hunters.''
</P>
<P>
   But Valli said he sees the current film as a fitting testament
to a way of life that he believes will soon disappear under the
onslaught of tourism and pressures of neighboring China.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be the only testimony about what was this part of this
world,'' Valli said. ``Nobody else is going to shoot a movie up
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, if only he can get someone to watch it in the United
States.
</P>
</TEXT>
