u k BC-AFRICA-AIDSORPHANS-$A     03-21 2995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-AIDSORPHANS-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE SADDEST FACE OF AFRICA'S BURGEONING AIDS CRISIS: ORPHANS
 &HT;    (2500&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With half-page color map-graphic.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., March 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MBARE, Zimbabwe _ In a wooden shed behind one of the tiny
cinderblock houses that line this district's narrow dirt roads,
12-year-old Nomsa Mwale struggles with her new role as mother.
</P>
<P>
   Nomsa's father died of AIDS in 1998. Six months ago, her mother
followed him, leaving the five children to make their way in a
world that offers little comfort and less hope.
</P>
<P>
   As she speaks, Nomsa stares vacantly away from the people who
have come to see her. She is thin and has a sweet, doe-like face.
With a tiny, wispy voice, she answers the questions about her
family's circumstance, but she does not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The first-born girl, it has fallen to her to care for older
brother Sibongile, 15, and the three younger children: Shonia, 10;
Garikai, 9; and Betina, 8.
</P>
<P>
   Their life is a frenzy of survival guided by little more than
the advice given by their mother as she prepared her children for
their journey without her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me to tell the boys not to go to people's houses
because if something is missing, they will blame them,'' Nomsa
says. ``She said, 'You need to feed the others but also you must
learn to take care of yourself.'''
</P>
<P>
   This was the best advice, because Nomsa has almost no one but
herself.
</P>
<P>
   The AIDS epidemic in Africa is an orphan-making machine,
striking down millions of men and women in their prime
child-rearing years. A recent United Nations report estimates that
Africa is home to more than 9 million children who have lost their
parents to AIDS. If nothing changes, this number is expected to
triple over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   In Zimbabwe, there are as many as 800,000 AIDS orphans. In one
rural school, 24 percent of its 946 students have lost their
parents to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   As international aid groups stagger under the weight of their
