and raise the children.
</P>
<P>
   They leave behind legions like Nomsa with little prospect of the
most basic emotional, physical or material necessities.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-by-8-foot shack occupied by Nomsa and her siblings is
surrounded by rusting lean-tos inhabited by tough-looking older
men. The children share a foul-smelling toilet and shower with the
men.
</P>
<P>
   When the children have food, usually a little something provided
by local charities, they cook on a one-burner stove. From time to
time the food is stolen by the lodgers, who pay Nomsa's uncle to
sleep in the hovels that surround the shed.
</P>
<P>
   The structures are behind a slovenly house owned by Nomsa's long
dead grandparents. The children have no legal rights to the
