<HEADLINE>
CITRIX LOOKING AT MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Citrix Systems Inc., a leader in the application service
provider market, is casting covetous glances at the region. Ed
Iacobucci, chief technology officer of Fort Lauderdale, Fla.-based
Citrix, says his firm is likely to establish a major presence here
in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seriously looking at Boston as a possible significant
expansion of the Citrix firm,'' Iacobucci said last week. ``We're
going to have some partnerships and probably some acquisitions in
the area.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason: Proximity to EMC Corp.'s Data General business unit,
and the remains of Digital Equipment Corp., now owned by Compaq
Computer Corp. Iacobucci said that Citrix works closely with both
these organizations. ``They've been some of our most significant
supporters of what we're trying to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Citrix makes software that lets companies run popular programs
on a central server computer, instead of on each individual
computer in the company. For instance, instead of giving each
worker a copy of Microsoft Corp.'s Excel spreadsheet program,
workers get a small Citrix client program. This client connects to
a Citrix server that runs the Microsoft program remotely. A single
server can provide Excel to dozens of workers in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Major companies such as Hewlett-Packard Co. and Oracle Corp.
have begun offering ASP services, and International Data Corp.
predicts there'll be a $2 billion ASP market by 2003. Iacobucci
thinks Citrix is well-placed to take part in the boom.
</P>
<P>
   The company now employs 1,200 workers, about half in Fort
Lauderdale. Iacobucci said his company will probably take on about
600 workers in the Boston area, many of them through acquisitions
of local firms.
</P>
<P>
   Which local firms? Wait and see, Iacobucci said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERVER SCARE
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new Stephen King ghost story, published last week on the
Internet, threw a nasty scare into the people at Glassbook Inc. in
Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Glassbook is one of the companies chosen to deliver electronic
versions of ``Riding the Bullet,'' the first King story to be
published exclusively on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Glassbook was supposed to provide hundreds of thousands of
electronic copies of the story to people with computers based on
Microsoft Corp.'s Windows operating systems. Amazon.com, the
Internet's biggest book dealer, relied on Glassbook to handle the
load.
</P>
<P>
   But the huge spike of demand for the book overwhelmed
Glassbook's servers, admitted Tom Diaz, Glassbook's vice president
of product development.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz said part of the problem was caused by some new software
his company is using to register the customers' downloads. He says
future electronic book rollouts should go more smoothly, but Diaz
admits mixed feelings about riding this particular bullet.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, we're very gratified to suddenly have tens
and tens of thousands of interested customers,'' he said. At the
same time, ``We're disappointed that . . . we've sent a lot of them
away feeling unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A REASON TO BE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now that Linux has proven there's demand for an operating system
to rival Microsoft Windows, BeOS is trying to step into the
limelight.
</P>
<P>
   BeOS has been floating around for years. But few have embraced
this operating system, despite its strong performance as a platform
for video applications.
</P>
<P>
   But now Be Inc. is getting more aggressive. The company is
copying a key Linux strategy by announcing a giveaway of a
Windows-compatible version of the software, beginning in late
March.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to prime the pump by building a sizable community of
Be users, similar to the millions who now use Linux.
</P>
<P>
   So how will Be make its money? By selling a version of the
operating system to makers of lightweight ``personal information
appliances.'' These are simple computers that just do one or two
things, like picking up e-mail from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp. has signed a licensing deal with Be, and
has been showing off prototypes of a cheap home data device that
will rely on a version of BeOS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
