<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-LEDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING THE LEDS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before too long, most of the traffic lights you stop at may not
be lights at all, but jumbo versions of the light-emitting diodes
you now commonly see in bedside digital alarm clocks and home
electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
   With a push from conservation-minded utilities, public works
departments and highway agencies around the United States are
increasingly swapping out red lights in traffic signals with diodes
that use up to 90 percent less electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred, in fact, are already in use around
Massachusetts. But they remain a small minority and, nationally,
transportation officials estimate that 92 percent of traffic
signals still use incandescent bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   The way to tell whether a signal is using a bulb or an LED is
that the diode looks like a collection of dots arranged in a circle
_ most commonly red, because red diodes are cheapest.
</P>
<P>
   Though the timing difference is slight, it will appear that the
LED turns on more quickly. The average human eye can perceive the
several hundredths of a second it takes an incandescent bulb to
reach full brightness, while an LED begins glowing almost
instantaneously.
</P>
<P>
   As the cost of producing diodes falls, a whole host of new
applications are emerging, including brake lights in cars, exit
sign lights in office buildings, airport runway beacons, and even
home lighting.
</P>
<P>
   LED technology has been around for a little over 40 years, but
the standard joke in photonics circles for years was that you could
get an LED in any color you wanted, as long as it was red. Only in
recent years have researchers developed ways to create a range of
colors through using materials such as indium, arsenic, gallium
nitride, and other semiconducting solids that glow when zapped with
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming a cost-effective and eye-pleasing way is worked out to
produce white light from LEDs, future-minded home designers dream
of creating houses where artificial light is generated by a single
``light plant,'' then spread out through LED fibers embedded like
stars in ceilings and walls.
</P>
<P>
   LEDs could create balanced low-shadow indoor light at much less
cost than incandescent or even fluorescent bulbs. Plus, it would
just look cool to have an LED-studded living-room ceiling that
looked like the sky on a clear January night.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, automotive designers have begun using LEDs instead of
hard-to-replace bulbs for middle rear brake lights and other car
lights. Some envision filling car interiors with diodes to
eliminate the need to ever replace lightbulbs.
</P>
<P>
   But to get to widespread use, the cost of LEDs still needs to
plunge considerably. Officials with the Consortium for Energy
Efficiency Inc., a Boston-based group that lobbies for more
efficient home and office appliances, think a stepped-up effort to
replace traffic signal lights with LEDs could not only save
millions of dollars in wasted energy but also serve as a
market-driving application for the technology to get its cost down
and credibility up.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, consortium officials estimate, at least $250 million
is spent each year on electricity for the country's estimated 3.1
million traffic signals. That is probably eight to nine times more
than necessary. A typical yellow light, for example, loses 80
percent of its light to filtering.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while the vast majority of energy used for an
incandescent bulb only generates heat, up to 98 percent of the
electricity put into a red LED emerges as light. And because
traffic signals run 24 hours a day, making them more efficient can
directly reduce the risk of power failures on hot summer afternoons
by cutting base load on power grids.
</P>
<P>
   One big hangup is the way most municipal and state governments
pay for traffic lights, through an annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   Over seven years, the cost of installing and operating a red LED
may be less than half the cost of an incandescent bulb. Utilities
such as NStar (parent of Boston Edison and Commonwealth Electric)
and the New England Electric System companies will give generous
rebates for buying the LEDs.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, leading manufacturers such as Dialight Corp. of
Manasquan, N.J., and Ecolux Inc. of Lachine, Quebec, have developed
diodes that can be installed in minutes by swapping out the light
bulb and its housing and splicing the power line into the back of
the LED. Diodes can last seven to 10 years, while the long-life
incandescent bulbs used in traffic signals typically must be
replaced every 12 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite some clear advantages, the $120 to $140 upfront
cost of a red LED (even with a utility rebate) _ and up to $275 for
a green _ makes buying a $2.50 incandescent every year look cheaper
when it's a question of just making it to the end of the fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get the word out that this is good
technology,'' said Thomas J. Coughlin Jr. of New England Electric.
``But there have been some shortcomings, mostly the price. In the
next year or two we are going to make a really concerted effort to
try to educate the market.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Peter J. Howe is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at howe(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
