<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3537 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-WEIGHT-LOSS-HNS &LR;      03-21 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEIGHT-LOSS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     YES, BIG IS BEAUTIFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If I had been alive during the Renaissance, my
excess girth would be considered beautiful. But today those of us
with a spare tire and a double chin are thought of as, to put it
politely, physically unattractive.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that's not all. Studies have shown that people
who are considered attractive are also more likely to get a job and
be considered smarter than those who are less pleasing to the eye.
Society even punishes those who are unattractive. They're less
likely to receive raises and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   The ideals about what is and what is not physically attractive
change over time. You can't fix what society says about your shape.
However, you can fix how you feel about yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are continually unhappy with your body, you'll be
carrying around a lot of baggage emotionally,'' said Drew Anderson,
assistant professor of psychology and co-director of a study
sponsored by the Albany Medical Center and the State University of
New York at Albany. The study is designed to measure weight loss on
cholesterol levels.
</P>
<P>
   After 18 weeks on LEARN, a weight-loss program based on behavior
modification, the 10 members of the group had varying levels of
success. We had learned in previous sessions that, now in our
middle ages, we'd most likely never return to the slim and trim
physiques of youth. With only two weeks to go in the study, we were
learning to accept things we couldn't change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being physically beautiful does not make you happy,'' Anderson
said. ``Happiness does not go with weight loss. We have to get
people to say, `I don't have to lose weight to be happier.'''
</P>
<P>
   One way to become more content with your body, Anderson said, is
to look for improvements in the overall quality of your life. For
instance, has the weight loss I have achieved lowered my
cholesterol level? Has starting an exercise regimen made me more
able to do things I enjoy? Am I better able to manage my eating
habits now that I know the difference between physical and
psychological hunger?
</P>
<P>
   Other ways to deal with body image problems include changing
your perception of yourself. Thomas Cash, a professor of psychology
at Old Dominion University in Norfolk, Va., and author of ``The
Body Image Workbook'' (New Harbinger Publications), advocates
retraining emotional reactions instead of trying to attack
perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ``Do people perceive themselves wrongly? Or do
they perceive themselves accurately and are they unhappy with it?''
Anderson asks the group.
</P>
<P>
   Learning to be happy with your body isn't easy. Begin by
spending some time with yourself. Ask yourself if you've avoided
social or interpersonal relationships because of your weight. Which
of your body parts do you like the least? Which do you think are
the most attractive? Develop a list of body parts from the least to
the most disturbing to you.
</P>
<P>
   Next, expose yourself to those body parts that upset you. Start
with the least upsetting and take a good look at yourself. Got cute
ankles? Go ahead. Look at 'em in the mirror, turn those toes so you
can see those beautiful ankles from all sides. Bend over and take a
picture of 'em. Bet Cindy Crawford doesn't have ankles that look
this good. Set a video camera on the floor and walk past it,
recording those gorgeous joints.
</P>
<P>
   Sound silly?
</P>
<P>
   It may even feel silly at first. But then do the same with your
next favorite part, and the next, and the next, until you're able
to look at your least attractive part with the same affection. The
goal is to accept the weight that you cannot lose.
</P>
<P>
   Once you're happy with your self-image, you'll be free to do
things out of choice, not out of fear. Imagine, buying a swimsuit
and being comfortable enough in it to go to the beach without a
wrap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1355EST &QL; 
