<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3539 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECHNO-GADGETS-BOS &LR;      03-21 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-GADGETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGING THE WORLD _ ONE COMPUTER AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If there's a hot phrase floating in Silicon
Valley these days, it's ``ubiquitous computing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the notion of having thousands of computers for every human
being on the planet. What's more, these computers all talk to one
another, organizing and making decisions on their humans' behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Intel Corp. cast its imprimatur on the topic by
hosting a three-day conference at the Hyatt Hotel on ubiquitous
computing. The Santa Clara, Calif., chipmaker invited about 350
scientists to envision a future in which billions of computers are
embedded into everyday objects. The underlying implication, of
course, is that many of those computers will have Intel inside.
</P>
<P>
   An often-used example of ubiquitous computing is the
computerized car that senses a crash, deploys an airbag, and
notifies the nearest police station of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   To demonstrate that it walks the talk, Intel provided hundreds
of laptops that scientists used to send messages to one another, to
set up group chats, or to comment on what was being presented, much
like the way grade school children pass around notes during class.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scientific luminaries from the University of
California at Berkeley, the Masssachusetts Institute of Technology,
AT&AMP;T, Xerox Corp., and other institutions paraded their research.
The audience heard about ``knowbots,'' ``silicon inchworm motors,''
and what it means to have a ``robot ecology'' where machines
amiably coexist with humans.
</P>
<P>
   Monika Woszczyna and Mike Schneider, scientists from
Carnegie-Mellon University in Pittsburgh, were impressed with the
presentation on ``Smart Dust,'' a project at Berkeley where
engineers are working to build computers no larger than a cubic
millimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was cool,'' said Schneider.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have millions of these little computers spread out,
all communicating and constantly updating people on weather
patterns or road conditions,'' Woszczyna agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Then Schneider added: ``But you could also see it being used by
the military to sense where people are walking.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, the conversation turned toward ethics. Do governments
have a responsibility to limit technology that can be used toward
destructive ends? Do scientists have an obligation to respect
people's privacy and safety when creating new technologies? Will
there be so many computers around that humans will become slaves to
their creations? Will these machines run amok?
</P>
<P>
   The questions were reminiscent of a ``Star Trek'' episode in
which millions of tiny computers organized a protest and demanded
better working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Such weighty issues were not in evidence downstairs in the
hotel's Pacific Concourse, where engineers showcased their latest
inventions for changing the world.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular, judged unscientifically by the size of the
crowds that gathered around the display, was Joseph Paradiso's
computerized shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Paradiso, a principal research scientist at MIT's Media
Laboratory and technology director for the Things That Think
Consortium at MIT, demonstrated how his shoe generates power each
time the wearer strikes the heel or bends the sole. The idea is to
help people-on-the-go power up their cellular phones, pagers, and
electronic organizers, literally without having to stop.
</P>
<P>
   But the shoe, like many other techno-delights here, were far
from making it on to store shelves. To generate enough power to
refuel a single cell phone battery, a person would have to walk
``about 500 hours,'' said Paradiso.
</P>
<P>
   One gadget closer to hitting the commercial road was the
wireless digital pen from Intel, set to be introduced next year for
less than $100. It writes ink, like any other pen. At the same
time, the pen translates what is being written into a nearby
computer and saves the words as typewritten characters.
</P>
<P>
   Other gadgets on display included a virtual reality contraption
from Columbia University, and a three-in-one verbal language
translator, navigation system, and travel guide from
Carnegie-Mellon.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stuff is interesting, but not practical,'' said Rob
Enderle, an analyst with the Giga Information Group in Santa Clara.
``You get the sense that it's technology for its own sake, as
opposed to identifying problems and then using technology to solve
them. There's so much technology coming at us so fast that it
creates more problems than it solves.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can be
reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1356EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3540 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECHNO-INCUBATOR-BOS &LR;      03-21 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-INCUBATOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWCOMERS JUMPING ON THE INCUBATOR BANDWAGON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The word ``incubator'' has a safe, warm, motherly ring. But
today's high-tech incubators are less about hatching eggs than fast
fortunes. And there are plenty of foxes trying to claw their way
into the hen house.
</P>
<P>
   Incubators _ first set up to finance and nurture new businesses
_ have become a booming industry. New ones are springing up every
day. Some are backed by venture capital firms. Others are rising
from the ashes of failed businesses as opportunists recast
themselves as investors in start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 100 incubators across the continent and some
have curious roots. Recent arrivals include a Nevada casino gaming
company, a New York plastics company, two Canadian gold-mining
concerns, and a New Jersey e-tailer whose IPO was a bust.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is silliness time,'' says Tom Crotty, a general partner
at Battery Ventures in Wellesley, Mass. ``All these guys are going
to try to be early-stage venture capitalists, and many of them have
no experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditional venture capitalists like Crotty see incubators as
competition. They prefer to get in on a hot idea early themselves,
before an incubator has pumped up the value of the company and
taken a huge ownership stake.
</P>
<P>
   But that bias aside, there are some unlikely companies jumping
into the incubator scene. Take Jackpot Enterprises Inc., a Las
Vegas gaming-machine company that this month changed its name to J
Net Enterprises and launched a $100 million venture fund.
</P>
<P>
   Jackpot couldn't put its betting machines in bars, restaurants,
and grocery stores outside of Nevada because of regulatory
restrictions. So it's selling that business and getting into
early-stage venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   J Net does boast some big-name executives and directors,
including the founders of online news site CBS Marketwatch.com,
Allan Tessler and Alan Hirschfield, who formerly ran Columbia
Pictures and 20th Century Fox. J Net also has bought a controlling
interest in a Manhattan venture firm Meister Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the brothers, Todd Meister, says: ``We call ourselves a
corporate incubator. We want to help branded companies migrate to
the online world.''
</P>
<P>
   The big question for J Net and other incubator newcomers: Are
people who failed with their last public company qualified to pick
and back new ventures?
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, the board of Touchstone Software Corp. of
North Andover voted to sell off its operating units, change its
name to Touchstone Capital Group, and become a B2B Internet
incubator. Its stock trades around $2.
</P>
<P>
   There's Jordex Resources, a Vancouver, British Columbia, company
that's giving up mining for Internet gold-digging: It's new name is
iTech Capital Corp. Another ex-mining company, Vengold, has changed
its name to itemus and declares on its Web site: ``Prepare for the
E-Dream team.''
</P>
<P>
   David Barry, senior editor of The Corporate Venturing Report in
Wellesley, warns against falling for quick make-overs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's clearly a lot of money out there,'' he says. ``But
who's behind the money? What's their background?''
</P>
<P>
   It's crucial that entrepreneurs know who they're dealing with.
No company with a decent idea should sell its soul for $500,000 and
a few desks and phones. As a guideline, venture capitalists say, a
young company these days can get $15 million and give up around
half its ownership stake. An incubator shouldn't get the same stake
for far less money and expertise.
</P>
<P>
   The new players are surely lulled by the success of incubator
pioneers like Silicon Valley's idealab, which launched eToys,
GoTo.com, and CarsDirect.com. Incubating has the appearance of easy
money, a way to get in on technology early, take it public, and
ride the bull market for Nasdaq stocks.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the opportunity to take the incubator itself public
_ perhaps the main driver for some entrants. It's hard to resist
the success of Andover's CMGI Inc. and Internet Capital Group of
Wayne, Pa., venture firms with hot public stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Capital Group last week kicked off an incubator of its
own, eColony. No small ambitions from the established player: It
aims to fund 100 B2B start-ups in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AnswerLogic lands $10m
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CMGI's (at)Ventures Technology Fund is betting $10 million on
AnswerLogic Inc. as a leader in self-help customer service on the
Web. The funding is a second round for the Washinton, D.C. company,
whose first round came from Novak Biddle Venture Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Online customer service is a hot issue. Says AnswerLogic chief
executive Paul Jacobs: ``It's a problem that's been building as
commerce on the Internet has increased.'' The company's software
lets consumers ask questions online in plain English.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IPO watch
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are some initial public offerings scheduled for this week:
</P>
<P>
   ACLARA BioSciences Inc., Mountain View, Calif., 9m shares,
priced $16-18, managed by Deutsche Bank Alex Brown, measuring,
photographic, optical; Blaze Software Inc., Mountain View, Calif.,
4m shares, priced $12-14, managed by Robertson Stephens, business
services and software; Caldera Systems Inc., Orem, Utah, 5m shares,
priced $10-12, managed by Robertson Stephens, business services and
software; eMachines Inc., Irvine, Calif., 20m shares, priced $8-10,
managed by Credit Suisse First Boston, industrial and commercial
machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Eprise Corp., Framingham, Mass., 4m shares, priced $8-10,
managed by Deutsche Bank Alex Brown, business services and
software; Etinuum Inc., Englewood, Colo., 4.5m shares, priced
$10-12, managed by Chase Bank Hambricht &AMP; Quist, business services
and software; ImageWare Systems Inc., San Diego, 1.9m units, priced
$8-10, managed by Paulson Investment Co., business services and
software; InSilicon Corp., San Jose, Calif., 3.5m shares, priced
$9-11, managed by Robertson Stephens, electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
   InterMune Pharmaceuticals Inc., Palo Alto, Calif., 5.5m shares,
priced $17-19, managed by Warburg Dillon Read, other services;
IntraBiotics Pharmaceuticals Inc., Mountain View, Calif., 7.5m
shares, priced $13-15, managed by Deutsche Bank Alex Brown,
chemicals and allied products; Iteris Inc., Anaheim, Calif., 4.3m
shares, priced $11-13, managed by Bear Stearns &AMP; Co., other
services; PartsBase.com Inc., Boca Raton, Fla., 3.5m shares, priced
$11-13, managed by Roth Capital, business services and software.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Laboratories Inc., Austin, Texas, 3.2m shares, priced
$21-23, managed by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, electronic
equipment; Snowball.com Inc., San Francisco, 6.25m shares, priced
$10-12, managed by Goldman Sachs, business services and software;
Stratus Services Group Inc., Manalapan, N.J., 1.3m shares, priced
at $6, managed by Hornblower &AMP; Weeks, business services and
software; Viasystems Group Inc., St. Louis, 40m shares, priced
$16-19, managed by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, electronic
equipment.
</P>
</TEXT>
