<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LEAP FOR URBAN HOUSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR;  _ Maybe you saw the number in a passing headline
_ $2 trillion. It was the successor to the number in another
headline six years ago _ $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   For a change, these huge sums don't refer to a big mess, like
the federal debt. They involve just about the only bright spot in
the housing picture. For at least half the country it is the
biggest economic issue next to income itself.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, Fannie Mae, the biggest financial services
corporation in the world that isn't a bank, announced a commitment
amid considerable skepticism to invest $1 trillion in housing that
matters most _ for 10 million families in underserved urban
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Fannie Mae's CEO, Frank Raines, announced that the
federally chartered institution will double that in this decade,
helping bring housing within reach of another 18 million families.
Within that commitment is another one aimed at a growing crisis in
American cities _ shrinking supply and exploding demand for
affordable rental housing.
</P>
<P>
   When you talk ``national housing policy,'' this level of action
merits far more attention than it gets. Since it went private more
than 30 years Fannie Mae has been at the center of the American
homeownership miracle. Because of its federal charter, it can raise
vast sums in credit markets on favorable terms. Using those funds
to buy mortgages from the outfits that issue them is the core of a
``secondary'' market that is essential to the rapid flow of loans
to homebuyers and apartment developers.
</P>
<P>
   What the first $1 trillion commitment under Raines's
predecessor, Jim Johnson, represented was a herculean effort to
push the envelope, using the leverage of the company's purchasing
power to influence changes for the better in lending patterns. In
practice that has meant lower down payments and other innovative
ways of getting working families of limited means through the front
door.
</P>
<P>
   With the new commitment, half of Fannie Mae's business will be
in underserved urban and rural communities and among low-income
families and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae's immensity and clout inevitably draw an unfair share
of sniping, a fact of life in a hothouse like Washington. Andrew
Cuomo's Department of Housing and Urban Delelopment is a
too-frequent offender. So, too, are sharpies in the banking
business who have hired lobbyists to try to break off high-margin,
high-interest-rate business. Fannie Mae's record, more than just
its power, has tended to keep the junior varsity wolves at bay.
</P>
<P>
   What ought to be of concern is the growing crisis in
affordability, especially for renters. The tip of this iceberg is
the scourge of homelessness, as well as the booming business done
by food banks to help families nearly starved by the expenditure of
excessive portions of their income for often-inadequate shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need partners,'' says Boston Mayor Tom Menino, who like
many of his colleagues focused on the problem in his State of the
City message this year. ``You can't begin to solve this problem
alone because of the amount of capital involved, but the state
governments and the federal government have stepped away from the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   With supply tight and rents exorbitant, responses like Menino's
are by definition small, however vigorous. His need for partners
can be filled in part by Fannie Mae. The company financed $50
billion in multifamily housing last year. It will raise that number
to $175 billion, serving 4 million renting families. It already is
the largest investor in federal low-income-housing tax credits and
local bonds that help finance multifamily housing. The company also
will expand the market for smaller properties (with up to 50 units)
and for owner-occupied buildings with two to four units that are
such a staple in older urban neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   This is an astonishingly bold set of ventures, but mayors like
Menino believe there remains an opening for more federal
initiative. Their focus is not on a new program but on tax policy,
specifically the reforms of 1986 that ended the special tax breaks
(via accelerated depreciation schedules) for real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with that law,'' says Menino, ``is that it hit
everything hard, especially affordable housing projects, and not
just the windfall that was going to commercial real estate.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right to suggest that the federal surplus should make
possible a targeted reincarnation of tax incentives for apartment
units that lower-income families can afford. It would be a natural
issue for Al Gore, given its equal relevance to close-in suburbs as
well as urban cores. And it would be natural for a conservative
like George W. Bush if he didn't plan to spend the surplus on
income tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae's new commitment makes two points. For more than a
decade its innovations have been a model for forward-looking
business behavior. And the company also serves as a gold-plated
yardstick by which to measure the inadequacy of nearly every other
public and private player.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
