<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3544 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-21 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAR MUZZLES THE SEARCH FOR TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ I prefer my law enforcement officials to be like German
shepherds _ smart, vigilant, and at times, fierce. Right now,
though, Boston Police Commissioner Paul Evans and Attorney General
Thomas Reilly are acting like a pair of French poodles _ prancing
around the muck that comes with their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year after a Boston police captain quietly revived
the investigation into the Boston Strangler murders, Evans and
Reilly have slammed the door shut, worried not in the least about
truth, but consumed by the fallout on their careers.
</P>
<P>
   And the truth is this: Few detectives who investigated the
Strangler case back in the early and mid-1960s believe that Albert
DeSalvo, the confessed killer of 13 women, murdered anyone at all.
DeSalvo was slain in Walpole State Prison in 1973 without having
been charged with even one of the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, according to detectives, lawyers, and people who
have studied it since, the spree was not the result of a lone
strangler, but rather one or two serial killers followed by several
copycat murderers who buried their deeds and their dead in the
raging headlines of the times.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation back then was phenomenally, fundamentally
flawed. Police departments in the municipalities where the murders
occurred did not share vital information. A politically motivated
task force was convened by an attorney general _ Edward Brooke _
who had his eye on higher office. The man in charge of the team,
John Bottomly, was widely described as an incompetent. And the
biggest proponent of DeSalvo's guilt was his own lawyer, F. Lee
Bailey, who was pushing for an insanity verdict in a string of
unrelated crimes.
</P>
<P>
   All of which becomes important now because of this simple,
logical conclusion: Someone, perhaps even several people, may have
gotten away with murder. They could very well be alive. And two of
the state's leading law enforcement officials _ Evans and Reilly _
don't particularly seem to care.
</P>
<P>
   When news first broke in this space last July that Captain Tim
Murray, head of the highly regarded Cold Case Squad, had taken aim
at the Strangler case, police brass dived for cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``A technical exercise,'' Evans described it. Others downplayed
it even further, ignoring the fact that detectives and lab
civilians had already accumulated a massive pile of old evidence
and had dozens more boxes to find. One police report indicated the
existence of cotton swabbings from a victim's midsection _ a DNA
jackpot, if they could be found.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the search for evidence was halted before the
difficult work ever began; the Cold Case Squad was temporarily
disbanded, and Murray was promoted out of the job.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Evans said he didn't want to cause any emotional pain
for the victim's families. But that excuse fell flat when families
of some of the dead pushed for a revived investigation. Relatives
of Mary Sullivan, the final victim, are so convinced DeSalvo wasn't
the killer that they recently offered to exhume her body for DNA
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're demanding answers, and we feel like we can't get help
from anyone,'' said her nephew, Casey Sherman. DeSalvo's family has
also offered to dig up his corpse.
</P>
<P>
   Police remain unbowed. ``We are not just going to jump into a
situation that leaves us with little hope and in some sense no hope
of completing an investigative effort,'' said Deputy Superintendent
Paul Farrahar, the head of the homicide unit.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's people are even more timid. ``It doesn't make sense for
an AG's office to get involved in homicides, and we don't do
that,'' said Gerard Leone, the head of the criminal division.
</P>
<P>
   But Leone ignores the fact that the attorney general got
involved in 1964 and may have fouled the investigation. Now the
trail of old evidence runs directly through Reilly's office, with
much of it leading to musty archives and the cellars of retired
state officials.
</P>
<P>
   So why the reticence? Evans and Reilly, two decent,
forward-thinking men, are loath to confront problems that preceded
them _ problems that may beget problems. And like a good lawyer,
they rarely ask questions in which the answers aren't preordained.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a reason there's no statute of limitations on
murder. It's a crime so heinous that neither time nor effort should
stand in the way of solving it. It's not their choice, but their
job to pursue the Strangler case. And when they do, Boston may come
to grips with another demon from its past.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
