<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3545 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CROWE-LADN &LR;      03-21 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROWE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE CROWE FLIES, SUCCESS FOLLOWS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a guy who specializes in coming off as mean as a Tasmanian
devil, Russell Crowe sure knows how to make friends.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the New Zealand-born, Australia-raised actor's
remarkable, ever-more-impressive chameleon abilities probably make
that easier than it would be for most people. After all, the
35-year-old Crowe was more than convincing as the whistleblowing
American scientist Jeffrey Wigand _ a man nearly 20 years the
actor's senior and some 50 pounds larger _ in ``The Insider,'' the
tobacco and media industry expose that's earned Crowe his first
Academy Award nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Wigand is an immensely paranoid and difficult
individual, whom Crowe captures in all of his furtive,
hair-trigger, depressive glory. Or that Crowe's last major U.S.
performance, as the ``L.A. Confidential'' cop whose uncontrollable
rages make the Rampart Division gang look like choirboys by
comparison. Or that in his next film, the May release
``Gladiator,'' he plays a Roman general turned Coliseum superstar
whose capacity for close-quarters killing is matched only by his
murderous hatred of the emperor.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood loves this guy. And in his rough-hewn, Down Under way,
Crowe humbly appreciates the current expressions of it.
</P>
<P>
   `I think I'm in a very privileged position,'' the deceptively
jocular, deeply committed actor says. ``A lot of people have had
long and stellar careers and have never been acknowledged by their
peers or critically in the way that I have been this year. So I
don't have a humorous or cynical viewpoint on it; I'm just very
thankful for the position that I'm in.''
</P>
<P>
   According to ``Gladiator'' director Ridley Scott, it's the movie
industry that should be thankful for someone of Crowe's talent and
screen charisma at this point in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russell is very inventive and experienced _ he's done quite a
few movies and some 30-odd plays, which is a lot of work at his age
_ but it's something else that you want,'' says Scott (``Alien,''
``Blade Runner,'' ``Thelma &AMP; Louise''). ``You can get a great actor
who disappears when you put him on screen; he sort of drops back as
opposed to comes right up. But Russell's got that burn, he's very
strong on screen. Some people say the camera loves him, but it's
not that, it's just him. In his age bracket, about the only other
male actor you can say that about today is Tom Cruise.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody is saying similarly complimentary things about Crowe _
these days. His ``Gladiator'' co-workers wax nostalgic about the
extra effort Crowe went to to make the grueling, five-month filming
of the picture on the Mediterranean island of Malta as fun as
possible _ hosting parties, renting boats for weekend sailing
excursions, printing up special T-shirts he'd hand out to cast and
crew members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humans are a funny creature, mate,'' Crowe says with a shrug.
``You can't just continuously demand from them effort without
showing them that they're appreciated, y'know? And I demanded that
everyone here remained completely involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But before he became the ideal collaborator, Crowe had a
reputation for impatience and not suffering fools.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that a young, developing actor like Russell
has to defend himself when he comes on the set and protect his
work,'' notes cinematographer Dante Spinotti, who shot Crowe's
first American film, ``The Quick and the Dead,'' as well as ``L.A.
Confidential'' and ``Insider.'' ``He needs everybody to concentrate
and pay attention to what they are doing. I think it's a very
positive feature for an actor, knowing what he wants to do and
where he wants to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowe certainly knows what he's about. He's been acting
professionally since early childhood _ and was destined for a
show-business career well before that. The grandson of a
cinematographer, Crowe grew up on film sets that his parents
catered meals for. He made his acting debut at age 6 on a
television series called ``Spy Force.'' And although there have
been several detours along the career path _ he still plays what he
claims is mediocre guitar for his 16-year-old band, Gruntland _
movie acting is clearly his lifeblood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movies, for me, are like the last circle in the concentric
spiral; I just always knew that this was my job,'' Crowe says.
``Now, I can't sit down and jam on a guitar with Eric Clapton with
any level of confidence. But I can jam with any actor who walks the
planet and know, with absolute confidence, that I will fulfill the
needs of my character.''
</P>
<P>
   This was proven by the extended ``Insider'' encounters between
Crowe and Al Pacino, perhaps the greatest living scene-stealer in
the acting universe. For the astonishing Wigand impersonation,
Crowe bleached his hair seven times, had to get his mouth around a
New York accent with Bluegrass inflections (since all of Wigand's
tobacco-related lingo was learned in Kentucky) and even went
through boxes and boxes of glasses before settling on the precisely
right style. Then there was gaining all those pounds _ and losing
them with alarming speed when he had to reach fighting weight for
``Gladiator'' right afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all of that and a thousand other painstaking steps,
Crowe was too nervous to watch his first portrayal of an actual
individual once director Michael Mann cut ``The Insider'' together.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I sat and watched that movie and I didn't see Jeff Wigand,
then I'd have been shown up, I couldn't do my gig,'' he explains.
``That's how I felt, so I kept making excuses to Michael about why
I couldn't make any of the screenings. He finally cornered me and I
had to watch it; and it was OK, because I did see Jeff Wigand in
there a couple of times, which was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowe's devotion to acting is matched only by his interest in _
are you ready? _ cattle. He runs 270 head of Angus beef on his
560-acre ranch in Australia, and can go on at mind-boggling length
about animal husbandry and the kinds of grass best-suited for
grazing in the arid environment.
</P>
<P>
   But there's not been much time for cow-punching lately. These
days, Crowe is hopping between Poland and Ecuador, filming the
romantic political thriller ``Proof of Life'' with Meg Ryan. After
recording a new album in Texas this summer and taking in the Sydney
Olympics, he starts up Jodie Foster's next directing effort,
``Flora Plum,'' in which he'll play a circus sideshow freak.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe admits that the workload has gotten to be a bit much. But
he probably wouldn't want it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish the madness would just calm down for a little while,
y'know?'' he acknowledges. ``However, having said that, it's my
choice to make films. It's the thing that I like to do. By rights,
I should be sleeping, but at the moment I'm making a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet another reason why Hollywood loves this guy. But will they
love him enough to hand him that Oscar statuette Sunday night? We
ask Crowe what he thinks his chances are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't go there, mate,'' he says. ``Sorry. I'm a great believer
in karma and I'm just going to live in the moment. I'm an Academy
Award-nominated actor for the rest of my career, regardless of what
happens or what junk I do. And put it this way: The worst that I
can come in is second.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
