<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MOUNTAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMOIR OF `COLORS' IS TINTED IN BEIGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
COLORS OF THE MOUNTAIN 
By Da Chen 
Random House. 310 pp. $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the curiosities of the American book-publishing scene is
the continuing interest in a genre best described as ``cultural
revolution memoirs,'' accounts of growing up in the People's
Republic of China during the 1960s and early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   These began appearing more than a dozen years ago, as China was
opening to the outside world, and young Chinese who had been swept
up in that turmoil _ or had taken an active part as Red Guards _
came to the West as graduate students.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those early accounts, published in the late 1980s and
early 1990s (among them Gao Yuan's ``Born Red'' and Jung Chang's
``Wild Swans'') have stood the test of time and hold permanent
places as important firsthand documents of Mao Zedong's chaotic
experiment in political engineering.
</P>
<P>
   But while the blood has run thin and most such memories have
lost their punch, still these memoirs keep appearing. Most come
from academic presses and quickly disappear from bookstore shelves
(rarely into the hands of book-buyers). Occasionally, however, a
major trade publisher brings one of them out, with a hefty advance
to the author and a promotional budget.
</P>
<P>
   Such is ``Colors of the Mountain'' by Da Chen.
</P>
<P>
   Chen is 37, the child of a small landlord family in Fujian
province (identified, in the curious practice of Anglicizing China
place names, as ``Yellow Stone Village''). The family seems to have
endured the years of the Cultural Revolution with relatively little
discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Chen himself endured some taunting from classmates but seems to
be a natural winner _ the brightest boy in town, the best at both
the violin and Ping-Pong. He won admission to the Beijing Language
Institute to study English, then came to the United States in 1985.
He studied at Union College in Lincoln, Neb., and Columbia
University Law School and then worked at a Wall Street law firm. He
now lives in upstate New York with his wife, a physician, and their
two children.
</P>
<P>
   And he has now written a book. The problem is not that ``Colors
of the Mountain'' is bad. It is that it is nowhere near what it
could have been.
</P>
<P>
   As a coming-of-age memoir, it is passable but too generic. There
is little sense of time or place. Absent the Chinese names of his
schoolmates _ and the very, very occasional reference to specific
political events _ it could describe a bright kid's growing up in
Somerville and getting into Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   For Da Chen, the turmoil of the Cultural Revolution seems to
have involved a lot of time spent sneaking cigarettes with his
buddies and fantasizing about girls.
</P>
<P>
   And the language is too often unnecessarily American-colloquial.
As he studies for the national entrance exam that will determine
his getting into college, Chen writes that without ``a scheme, a
method,'' he ``could easily kiss the books and my life good-bye and
say hello to the rice paddies.'' As for college men he'd read
about, ``all the girls dreamed about them (and) they kicked ass in
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, there are so many wasted opportunities in which
``Colors of the Mountain'' could have been so much more.
</P>
<P>
   After the death of Mao in 1976, his wife, Jiang Qing, and three
of her political allies were denounced as ``The Gang of Four'' and
arrested. The political fallout reaches into the furthest corners
of the country. After the local party chief flees to avoid arrest,
Yellow Stone Village puts on a play to celebrate the downfall of
the Gang of Four. Chen is cast as the writer and editor Yao Wenyuan
(misidentified in the text as ``Yiao''), and one of his schoolmates
as Madame Mao herself.
</P>
<P>
   We learn what Chen's costume was _ padded stomach and shoes
``two sizes too big'' _ and that his classmate ``would curl his
little finger as he held a cigarette, and push his boobs up once in
a while, whenever the sponges inside his dress dropped too low.''
</P>
<P>
   But what was the political and cultural context of all this?
Were such plays presented throughout China at that time? How did
this relate to the propaganda shows that were a fixture of the
Cultural Revolution? Was there a standard script? Who decided to
turn Madame Mao into a comic figure? Or was she turned into a evil
figure at the play's end? What a missed opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the real problem here is that as more and more Americans
visit China _ or even go there to study or to work _ China becomes
less exotic. To succeed in that context, memoirs such as this need
to offer more than passably told coming-of-age reminiscences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1403EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
