<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3550 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS &LR;      03-21 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO STRINGS, BUT THE GIRLS WILL SWOON ANYWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listen. Can you hear it?
</P>
<P>
   If you tune your ears just right, you'll hear the cacophonous
clamor of millions of teenage girls stampeding through record
stores to buy 'N Sync's just-released sophomore album _ as well as
the unholy groan and wail of millions convinced that anything by
any so-called ``boy band'' is yet another sign of the apocalypse.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting that 'N Sync's ``No Strings Attached'' will be
humongous _ perhaps equaling or even eclipsing the single-week 1.1
million sales record set by the rival boy band Backstreet Boys with
last year's ``Millennium '' _ is like predicting that rain will be
wet. But it's also a safe guess that those who hate boy bands will
greet this CD as if it were a compilation of Kenny G and John Tesh
performing the greatest hits of Wayne Newton.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, those who hate boy bands are just as passionate
as those who love them. It doesn't matter if it's 'N Sync,
Backstreet Boys, 98 Degrees, LFO, or whichever manufactured group
some producer will unleash on the world soon. Ever since pop groups
populated with cute, crooning, camera-ready cover boys began
dominating the charts, MTV, and Top 40 radio a few years ago, most
music and cultural critics have outdone themselves in finding new
ways to denounce the heavily produced, packaged pop that makes the
little girls swoon. Entertainment Weekly has referred to such
groups as wimps, and derided the music as laden with ``slurpy
harmonies and puppy-dog songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence, this message for all the critics _ get over it. They're
not for you.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured that Louis Pearlman, the Orlando-based businessman
who created Backstreet Boys and 'N Sync (and was subsequently sued
by both groups) didn't put these bands together thinking about how
they would appeal to middle-aged men like himself. This was all
about the ladies, preferrably those under voting age, who will
always scream and shriek at the sight of pretty young men singing
silly love songs.
</P>
<P>
   So long as there are teenage girls with hormones and allowances,
there will be boy bands. Singing groups who don't play instruments
or write their own songs, whose pleasant faces and pearly smiles
are as important as their performing talents, have been around
forever. From the Four Freshmen to the Osmonds, from New Edition to
New Kids on the Block, boy bands have always been a part of popular
music. (One could even argue that the Sex Pistols, manufactured and
manipulated by entrepreneur Malcolm McLaren, were a boy band,
albeit one with much ruder songs and even worse personal hygeine.)
</P>
<P>
   Boy bands of various stripes have coexisted alongside the
Beatles, Bob Dylan, and Public Enemy, but never have their
bubble-gum harmonies been greeted with such derision as they are
these days. Perhaps, that's because so many have deluded themselves
into believing such groups are personally responsible for
hip-checking rock off the charts in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, please. Somehow, I doubt that the same fans who were once
moshing to Smashing Pumpkins's ``Bullet with Butterfly Wings,'' are
now swooning to Backstreet Boys' ``Show Me the Meaning of Being
Lonely.'' Rock hasn't been undermined by boy bands as much as by
its own mediocrity, as evidenced by such wobbly recent albums as
Smashing Pumpkins's ``MACHINA/The Machines of God'' or Oasis's
``Standing on the Shoulder of Giants.'' Whatever their faults, at
least boy bands and their producers seem to understand what their
fans want, which is more than can be said for some rock groups who
are more interested in, at best, self-indulgence, and, at worse,
hackneyed songs that barely hint at what made the bands great in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   So, let's all leave boy bands alone already. They're harmless.
Let them enjoy whatever time they have left, for we all know such
groups have notoriously short shelf lives. (NKOTB, anyone?) They'll
be gone soon enough as such groups usually fizzle by their third
album, when their fans are finally old enough to know better. At
least while they're around, we won't have to hear about their
pulling knives or guns on anyone, and their fans are unlikely to
pummel one another or go wildin' through a concert.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, regardless of how anyone feels about boy bands, I think
most would agree they'd prefer to have their daughters listening to
Backstreet Boys's ``I Want It That Way,'' or 'N Sync's ``Bye Bye
Bye'' than Juvenile's ``Back That Ass Up'' or Limp Bizkit's ``Break
Stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
