<HEADLINE>
CHERRY BLOSSOM TIME IN GEORGIA, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the nation's capital and San Francisco may be known for
their cherry blossom festivals, Macon, Ga., claims to have more
beautiful Yoshino cherry trees than you can shake a stick at. More
than 236,000, to be exact. Macon's 18th annual Cherry Blossom
Festival is on through next Sunday with lots of events from parades
to ghost tours, a Japanese drum performance, and the Beach Boys.
For information, call 800-768-3400 (1).
</P>
<P>
   The annual Northern California Cherry Blossom Festival is both a
celebration of spring's arrival and of the rich Japanese culture
that is present in the San Francisco Bay area. The ancient samurai
were not only inspired by the blossoms in their poetry, but would
also willingly die in battle to defend their well being. It is out
of this passion that San Francisco's annual celebration was created
to honor the delicate flowers with viewing, parties, dance, song,
and sake. This year's festival will be held the weekends of April
8-9 and 15-16. The grand finale Cherry Blossom Parade will be held
April 16. For more information on the festival, call 415-563-2313
(for lodging, call 888-782-9673) or visit www.sfvisitor.org.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a National Park Service spokesman said peak
cherry blossom time is expected the week of March 19, 12 days ahead
of earlier forecasts. The annual Cherry Blossom Festival parade is
April 4.
</P>
<P>
   On the Eastern Shore of Virginia, Historic Garden Week's house
and garden visits are April 29. For information on bus tours call
757-787-3945.
</P>
<P>
   The 65th Annual Savannah Tour of Homes and Gardens is Thursday
through Sunday. Sponsored by the Episcopal Women of Christ Church
and Historic Savannah Foundation, the tour offers a rare
opportunity to appreciate the architecture, interiors, and gardens
of Savannah's National Landmark Historic District. For information,
call 912-234-8054.
</P>
<P>
   Beaufort and St. Helena Island, S.C., will have its 44th Annual
Spring Tours Friday and Saturday. Tours begin at St. Helena's
Episcopal Church, one of the oldest in continuous use in the United
States. For information, call 843-524-0363.
</P>
<P>
   St. Augustine, Fla., will have a Celebration of Spring March
29-April 2, which includes a Flower, Garden and Art Expo April 1-2.
For information, call 904-829-3295.
</P>
<P>
   While New England is famous for its hot lines for foliage
reports, Asheville, N.C., has a hot line for spring bloom reports.
The reports begin with early blooming of crocus and daffodil in
March through the display of flowering rhododendron in June.
Reports also include garden-oriented events, hiking suggestions,
and a guide to the region's most popular gardens. Call
800-280-0005.
</P>
<P>
   More than 250 of Virginia's outstanding homes, gardens, and
historic landmarks will have their welcome mat out for America's
Largest Open House, during Historic Garden Week in Virginia, April
22-30.
</P>
<P>
   Properties on the tour range from farmhouses to penthouses, from
stately 17th-century National Historic Landmark manors to new
millennium villas. Virginia's 67th annual Historic Garden Week is
the oldest and largest statewide house and garden tour event in the
nation. Three dozen tours are scheduled during the week, from the
Eastern Shore to the Shenandoah Valley. Prices range from $10 to
$25 per event. For a brochure, call 804-644-7776 or, on the Web,
visit www.VAGardenweek.org. A 200-page guidebook may be reserved by
sending a $5 donation payable to Historic Garden Week, 12 E.
Franklin St., Richmond, VA 23219. For information on touring and
staying in Virginia, call 804-786-4484, and for bed-and-breakfast
reservations, call 800-934-9184.
</P>
<P>
   Plymouth County, just an hour south of Boston, has spring garden
tours and more. The Shofuan Garden at the Art Complex Museum in
Duxbury includes a tea hut built in Kyoto, Japan. (Tea ceremonies
are held June through August; call 781-934-6634.) And at Plimoth
Plantation in Plymouth, a Rare Breeds and Heirloom Seeds Weekend is
May 27-28 (508-746-1620). For more ideas, call 800-231-1620 for a
Plymouth County Vacation Guide or visit www.plymouth-1620.com.
</P>
<P>
   In Holland, the Keukenhof Gardens in Lisse (an hour from
Amsterdam), world famous for the millions of tulips, narcissi,
hyacinths, and other bulb flowers will be open from Thursday
through May 21, and again from Aug. 3-Sept. 17, with begonias,
dahlias, lilies, and other varieties. For information, call the
Netherlands Board of Tourism at 888-464-6552 or visit
www.holland.com.
</P>
<P>
   And, in Monterey County, California, springtime is artichoke
time, where you can not only watch the harvest but feast on the
horny green globes at area restaurants. Castroville, the
``artichoke capital of the world,'' holds its annual Artichoke
Festival May 20-21. The festival is best known for crowning Marilyn
Monroe its first Artichoke Queen 41 years ago. For information on
the county, call 877-MONTEREY or visit www.GoMonterey.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Newburyport getaway
</P>
<P>
   Newburyport, known for its seafaring history and inns, offers a
getaway package that includes two nights' lodging at an inn or
bed-and-breakfast and a $25 gift certificate good at more than 65
local businesses. The package is $125 a person and is good through
April 30. Newburyport is about an hour north of Boston. For more
information, call the Newburyport Chamber of Commerce at
978-462-6680 or, on the Web, visit www.
</P>
<P>
   newburyportchamber.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel posters
</P>
<P>
   Boston's International Poster Gallery (205 Newbury St.) is
celebrating the freedom to explore the world in ``Bon Voyage!
Vintage Posters from the Golden Age of Travel 1900-1940'' beginning
Friday and continuing through April 30. The show includes posters
on rail and ocean travel and several from Thomas Cook, the
pioneering travel agent who helped create modern travel with such
innovations as a comprehensive ticketing system that simplified
travel. For more information, call 617-375-0076 or, on the Web,
visit www.internationalposter.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snowmobile tours
</P>
<P>
   Snowmobile resorts in Maine are planning on grooming their
trails and offering vacation packages through the first weekend in
April. Base depths on trails range from 1 1/2 to 2 1/2 feet. For
information, call 877-275-3363 or visit www.sledme.com. All that
snow promises a good spring runoff for the white-water rafting
season that begins May 1.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sales tax out
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani has ended the city's
sales tax of 8.25 percent on the purchase of clothing and footwear
items costing less than $110. During the past three years the city
has held seven sales-tax-free weeks, during which New York City
retailers saw sales increase as much as 77 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
