<SLUG> BC-3COM-CORP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     3COM SELLING PARTS OF MODEM BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Remember Rockwell International Corp., U.S.
Robotics and Ascend Communications?
</P>
<P>
   These were the companies the 3Com Corp. bested in one of the
Internet's first guerrilla wars, waged over modem technology in the
mid-1990s. For years, those companies jockeyed for position in the
growing market, competing for the right to connect you to the
burgeoning Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The winner, by most accounts, was 3Com, the Santa Clara-based
networking company. The victory was sealed in 1997 when 3Com
purchased rival U.S. Robotics for nearly $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, the Internet landscape has changed
dramatically, and 3Com's victory has proved bittersweet for the
2,700 employees whose jobs will be transferred or eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced Monday that it was selling its dial-up
modem business, which has struggled amid falling prices, as well as
its PC card business, to a new company formed by Accton Technology
of Taiwan and NatSteel Electronics of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   The moves will include laying off approximately 1,000 workers as
well as transferring approximately 1,700 current employees to the
new company, according to 3Com spokesman Mark Plungy.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, yet to be named, will be based in Mount
Prospect, Ill., where 3Com's current dial-up modem division is
centered.
</P>
<P>
   3Com employs 12,000 people in 48 countries. The company has
manufacturing plants in Ireland, Israel, Singapore, Santa Clara,
Foxboro, Mass., Chicago and Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes as part of a larger restructuring at 3Com
that includes the company's plans to leave the high-end networking
business, conceding that market primarily to Cisco Systems Inc. of
San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The 3Com announcement illustrates the blinding speed at which
the Internet, and the technology that drives it, is evolving.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Shimer, vice president and general manager of 3Com's
residential connectivity group, acknowledged pointed out the upside
of buying U.S. Robotics three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We accomplished a lot with the U.S. Robotics acquisition;
we've gained a presence in the consumer market, not only with the
modem but also with Palm,'' said Shimer, referring to the company's
Palm computing division, whose popular hand-held technology was
acquired in the U.S. Robotics deal and which was recently spun off
in a highly popular public stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now our question is focusing on the rapid growth in broadband,
with a focus on home networking,'' Shimer said.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, 3Com Chairman Eric Benhamou vowed to take a closer
look at the company's businesses, hoping to stem market share
losses in the fields of networking and computer connector cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will allow us to do what we do best,'' said Bruce
Claflin, president and chief operating officer of 3Com. ``We are
going to focus on the things that will increase our shareholder
value.''
</P>
<P>
   That focus will come in the consumer and small to mid-size
business markets. 3Com, the top worldwide manufacturer of cable
modems, will continue to invest heavily in high-speed Internet
access through cable and DSL hardware. It also will provide the
necessary connectivity to Internet service providers and
businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
