<HEADLINE>
MORE CHANCES TO SAIL THE GREAT LAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For five years, the US-flagged American Canadian Caribbean Line
has made calls from Chicago on Great Lakes cruises. Increased
passenger demand for unique lakes adventure cruises has resulted in
the line adding a whole summer of cruises from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Planned are several seven-day Lake Michigan circumnavigation
cruises in addition to others departing, arriving, or continuing
from Chicago to the Atlantic coast or mid-America.
</P>
<P>
   ACCL's Niagara Prince is the only cruise ship that can pass
beneath Chicago's bridges, allowing it to connect the Great Lakes
to the Mississippi and mid-America. The line, America's original
small-ship cruise line, is based in Warren, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   The 84-passenger Niagara Prince has unique features like bow
landings, allowing passengers to disembark onto remote islands and
beaches along lake shores that other cruise ships cannot do. Its
shallow draft makes a spectacular Great Lakes itinerary even better
by getting into rivers and inlets to exotic places.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call 800-556-7450 or visit
www.accl-smallships.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Irish festival &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking for more Irish fun? Norwegian Cruise Line's Norwegian
Majesty is planning a series of Irish theme cruises out of Boston
this fall. From Sept. 3 through Oct. 15, Irish entertainment,
dining, and activities will be featured on the weekly cruises to
St. George's, Bermuda. Among plans are a mini ``Riverdance''
production and the Irish Rovers, an authentic Irish duo from
Dublin, entertaining in the Royal Fireworks Lounge. At the Sun Deck
buffet, Irish stew, corned beef and cabbage, and Irish potatoes
will be offered, and whiskey tastings featuring a selection of 40
Scottish, Irish, Canadian, and US whiskeys, as well as Irish
stouts, lagers, and green draft beer will be on tap.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Iceland cruise &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new destination for Orient Line's Marco Polo this summer will
be Iceland. Also included on the July 14, 15-day sailing will be
Norway's fiords, and the Faroe and Shetland islands. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Foliage cruises &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may seem a bit early to think of foliage, but to see the
colorful scene from a riverboat, book now; these sailings sell out
fast.
</P>
<P>
   The authenic steam paddlewheelers Delta Queen, Mississippi
Queen, and American Queen will offer 14 foliage cruises leaving
from ports such as St. Louis, Cincinnati, and Nashville.
Itineraries range from three to seven nights. As with all cruises,
travel agents have details, or call the Delta Queen Steamboat Co.
at 800-543-1949.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cruise plus &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travelers age 50 or older looking to experience the greatest two
minutes in sports have the opportunity to take advantage of Saga
Holidays Two for One sale. Book a four-night cruise down the Ohio
River to the 126th running of the Kentucky Derby aboard the
legendary Delta Queen and receive a free seven-night holiday to
either Scottsdale, Ariz., or Bangkok. Prices begin at $2,999 a
person, including air fare. For details call 800-952-9590.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free air &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holland America Line is offering free round-trip air fare from
New York on seven- and 14-day spring and summer sailings of the MS
Maasdam from Barcelona and Stockholm. The sailings begin at $1,599
a person (double occupancy) and include free air, port charges, and
taxes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Veterans' reunion &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A reunion of veterans who served in the Pacific islands is
planned for September. The 28-day voyage departs San Francisco
Sept. 24. The cruise begins at $4,795 a person and is not limited
to veterans. For information, write to Joan Irvine Travel, 1600
West Coast Highway, Newport Beach, CA 92663; or telephone
949-640-7402.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   World cruise &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Cruises has announced plans for its 2001 world cruise.
The Jan. 21 to April 27 sailing will boast more countries visited
than any previous Crystal cruise. The sixth world cruise of the
Crystal Symphony will visit 38 exotic ports of call in 31
countries, including rarely visited destinations in Southeast Asia,
India, the Middle East, Africa, and the Canary Islands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Loyalty discounts &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new and innovative guest loyalty program for travelers who
sail on the six lines belonging to World's Leading Cruise Lines _
Carnival, Holland America, Windstar, Seabourn, Cunard, and Costa _
is now available.
</P>
<P>
   The program, called Vacation Interchange Privileges, provides
the same discount benefits accorded to members of each line's past
program.
</P>
<P>
   For example, guests who sail on Seabourn, Windstar, or Cunard
will not only have access to discounts offered through past-guest
programs of the Seabourn Club, Windstar Foremast Club, and Cunard
World Club, but also savings available through any of the six WLCL
member lines' repeat-passenger programs. All the cruise line
members of the WLCL are owned by Carnival.
</P>
<P>
   Savings of up to 50 percent are offered on select sailings of
Carnival, Costa, and Windstar. The discounts on Holland America are
up to 35 percent and those on Cunard, up to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the discount, a traveler simply books a cruise through any
travel agent, who then informs the cruise line reservations agent
of the past-guest status at the time of bookings and, with the
initial deposit, supplies proof of the prior WLCL cruise. Other
restrictions may apply.
</P>
<P>
   The World's Leading Cruise Lines has a Web site, www.
</P>
<P>
   leaderships.com, that provides information and a gateway to the
Web sites of the participating lines.
</P>
</TEXT>
