<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDEST CITIES STILL HAVE IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Suppose you're just starting out in your working life, trying
to get your bearings. You wonder where to go to seek your fortune.
You want to go where the pinnacles are the highest, where the
ascent is most fierce.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of the Los Angeles Times last week by Chicago's
Tribune Co. offers certain clues about the new geography of
American opinion-making.
</P>
<P>
   The most important nodes are New York, Chicago, and,
paradoxically, Los Angeles _ the largest city, the Second City and,
once again, the Third.
</P>
<P>
   The other American cities of international importance _
Washington D.C., Boston, Miami, San Francisco and, possibly,
Seattle _ are world centers in certain fields. But they do not rank
in the first tier of cities in which the formation of opinion takes
place.
</P>
<P>
   I should explain that I am using a highly subjective set of
yardsticks in which education, finance, and media industries carry
roughly equal weight, and the capacity to absorb the latest streams
of immigration counts heavily as well. This back-of-the-envelope
exercise is in the spirit of Jane Jacobs' notion of cities as
places where the real gains arise from diversity. It owes as much
to Michael Porter's characterization of cities by the clusters of
types of enterprises they contain.
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident that New York and Chicago remain on top at the
beginning of the 21st century. They are where the stock exchanges
and money markets are. Money, news, and fashion go together as a
rule.
</P>
<P>
   New York is obviously still the financial and cultural capital
of the United States _ perhaps the world. But only in the last few
years has it become a formidable power in Internet publishing,
though ``Silicon Alley'' constitutes only a thin slice of
Manhattan. Universities in its orbit _ Columbia, New York
University, and Yale _ have suffered since the late 1960s but once
again are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago, in contrast, may be said to have been university-led.
Economic reformers from around the world trained at the University
of Chicago; Milton Friedman may be better known than Al Capone or
even Michael Jordan (in certain quarters). Its financial markets
rival those of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for a glimpse into what enabled the Tribune Co. to make
it to the top, you need look no further than the resume of chief
executive John W. Madigan. He passed through the accounting firm of
Arthur Andersen &AMP; Co. and the investment banking firms of Paine
Webber, Jackson and Curtis, and Salomon Brothers on his way to the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is the more surprising story. Its traditional
corporate establishment is in eclipse: Lockheed, Rockwell
International, and Unocal recently have been sold. And the
University of California at Los Angeles is a good university but
not great. But Los Angeles has unrivaled vitality and a lock on one
industry that ensures that the world will continue to share its
secrets. Los Angeles has the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is the anomaly here, since it is the seat of the
national government. But it is more acted upon then acting. The
Washington Post is the most distinguished private institution in
that town. There is little finance aside from government funders
and the local universities _ Georgetown, George Washington,
American and George Mason _ are still second-rate. Only the Johns
Hopkins University in nearby Baltimore is top-notch.
</P>
<P>
   Where does that leave Boston and San Francisco? Definitely
connected to the cities of the first tier and strong rivals in
certain respects. Both derive their power from world leadership in
science and technology. Strong educational and financial
institutions are the key.
</P>
<P>
   Miami and Seattle occupy similar niches, although their
respective bases are slimmer. Miami derives its importance from
being North America's portal to South America and the Caribbean.
Seattle has all the earmarks of a high-tech nursery, though it is
starting from far behind.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to rob a dozen other US cities of their
significance. Atlanta, Phoenix, Cincinnati, Denver, St. Louis,
Portland, Pittsburgh, Dallas, Detroit, to name an obvious few, are
thriving. But the hierarchy is well-established, and here, as in
Europe, the oldest cities tend to remain at the top.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
