<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADVxx-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DYSFUNCTION RULES ON TV, AT HOME  
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dysfunctional families are hot on television this year.
</P>
<P>
   On Fox, which is to dysfunctionality what Shakespeare was to
rhymed couplets, there's ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' ``King of the
Hill,'' ``The Simpsons,'' ``Family Guy'' and ``Titus.'' ``Married
... With Children'' has, sadly, been discontinued but, happily, can
still be seen in reruns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?'' broke new ground in
the genre in the sense that it actually created a real
dysfunctional family right there on (more or less) live TV. The
disappointment was that the couple split up almost immediately,
denying us, the viewers, the pleasure of watching their
dysfunctionality come to ``full flower'' by having kids and raising
them dysfunctionally and possibly, 20 years down the line, giving
rise to the sequel, Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire's Evil
Spawn?
</P>
<P>
   These shows have got to be confusing and maybe even a little
embarrassing to non-dysfunctional families who wonder why their
domestic situation is not like those portrayed on television.
Although they'd never admit it, even to themselves, what these
families want to know is how they can be dysfunctional, too.
</P>
<P>
   As someone who has more than a little expertise in the subject,
allow me to say, first, that dysfunctionality is not something you
can achieve overnight. Some people may think that dysfunctionality
is just a fancy name for ``doing nothing'' but it really takes a
lot of dedication and hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Since we're on the subject, let's begin with a discussion of TV.
No. 1, there is no such thing as too many TVs. Try to have at least
on TV in every room in your house, including the bathrooms and
laundry room. Having a lot of TVs reduces the chances that two or
more family members will be in the same room watching the same TV
at the same time. (There was some chilling talk, early on, that the
show ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire'' had brought back to life,
vampire-like, the concept of ``family viewing.'' While it is true
that some otherwise dysfunctional families did watch the first few
shows together, the novelty quickly wore off, partly because of
Regis Philbin's grating personality and partly because of the
difficulty of the questions.)
</P>
<P>
   Mealtime is unquestionably the best time to watch TV. All meals,
including Thanksgiving and Christmas dinners, are to be eaten in
front of the TV, preferably alone in one's room. If unforeseen
circumstances, such as a broken TV, result in two or more family
members watching TV in the same room, remember the cardinal rule:
Nothing you have to say is as important as what is being said on
TV. Some non-orthodox dysfunctional families permit talking during
the commercials, but I consider this a dangerous precedent. If you
let the kids tell you about their day during a commercial, the next
thing you know they are interrupting Drew Carey.
</P>
<P>
   Needless interruptions, of course, are not limited to children
whining about their high fevers. Since dysfunctional families watch
TV during all their free time (another advantage: dysfunctional
families have a lot more free time than non-dysfunctional
families), distractions are bound to occur. Before turning on the
set, it's a good idea to unplug the telephone and cut the wires to
the doorbell. Some families close their windows so they won't be
disturbed by chirping birds or rustling leaves, but I find that
this can be overcome simply to turning up the volume.
</P>
<P>
   Once you master the basics of doing nothing but watching TV and
never talking to one another, you'll find that the other elements
of the dysfunctional family quickly fall into place. The house will
start to fall apart. The yard will take on that wild, unkempt look
that one normally associates with Tarzan movies. An oil refinery
will be built next door and your property value will actually
increase. Jesse Ventura is elected president and your only worry is
that he will make fewer guest appearances on Saturday night
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   It is only when you have reached the Zen-like state of total
obliviousness that you can begin to think of yourself (and,
hopefully, the rest of your family) as dysfunctional.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what happens, always remember: Dysfunctionality is
not just a passing fad; it's a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
