<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ALZHEIMERS22-COX     03-21 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALZHEIMERS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REAGAN'S DAUGHTER URGES MORE FUNDING FOR ALZHEIMER'S RESEARCH
 &HT;    Eds: Cox state information follows 5th graf.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Being a former president doesn't mean you won't get
Alzheimer's disease. And being a glamorous former first lady
doesn't mean you won't suffer the heartache and exhaustion of
caring for an Alzheimer's patient.
</P>
<P>
   That's the message Maureen Reagan, daughter of former President
Reagan, brought a Senate panel Tuesday in urging lawmakers to boost
spending for Alzheimer's research by $100 million next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This disease is a thief that sneaks into the brain and robs a
family of everything that is dear to them,'' Reagan told the Senate
Appropriations subcommittee on labor, health and education. ``We
must be the last generation of American families to deal without
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan said her father, who turned 89 last month, ``is
wonderful, (but) the disease just gets worse.'' She said her father
``is comfortable'' with her, even though he does not recognize her.
</P>
<P>
   About 4 million Americans suffer from Alzheimer's, a
degenerative disease of the brain associated with aging. It
afflicts about one in 10 persons aged 65 and about half of those
over 85. At present rates, the number of Alzheimer's patients will
double within 30 years and increase to 14 million by the middle of
the century.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin Cox state information)
</P>
<P>
   Florida is expected to have the second highest number of
Alzheimer's patients by 2025, after California, an increase from
nearly 400,000 to about 713,000.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Alzheimer's patients in Colorado is expected to
more than double by 2025, from nearly 61,300 to about 140,000.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Alzheimer's patients in Georgia is expected to
nearly double by 2025, from roughly 103,000 to nearly 200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio is expected to have the sixth highest number of Alzheimer's
patients by 2025, an increase from more than 212,500 to about
308,600.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina is expected to have the eighth highest number of
Alzheimer's patients by 2025, an increase from more than 132,000 to
about 253,000.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is expected to have the third highest number of
Alzheimer's patients by 2025, after California and Florida _ an
increase from nearly 281,000 to about 552,000.
</P>
<P>
   (End Cox state information)
</P>
<P>
   Such an increase will put enormous strains on the nation's
health care system, the Medicare program, and millions of families
called upon to care for their aging relatives, said Stephen
McConnell, vice president of the Alzheimer's Association.
</P>
<P>
   Alzheimer's costs the United States an estimated $100 billion a
year in medical costs and lost wages. In 30 years, that total could
exceed $375 billion a year, McConnell said. Delaying the onset of
Alzheimer's by five years could save an estimated $50 billion a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare bears much of the federal cost of Alzheimer's disease.
Although Medicare does not pay for long-term care or prescription
drugs, studies have shown that Alzheimer's patients have additional
health problems that cost Medicare roughly $7,700 annually,
compared to $4,500 for non-Alzheimer's patients.
</P>
<P>
   Research offers the possibility not only of alleviating the
symptoms of Alzheimer's, but substantially delaying or even
preventing the onset of the disease in most people, said Dr. Steven
DeKosky, chairman of the Medical and Scientific Advisory Council of
the Alzheimer's Association.
</P>
<P>
   But DeKosky warned the panel that research projects take years
to conduct, and pursuing them in sequence would take too long to
offer promise to the baby boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we stack them end to end, we'll be in the middle of the
epidemic before we complete our research,'' DeKosky said.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., and Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, the
subcommittee's chairman and ranking Democrat, pledged to support a
$100 million boost in Alzheimer's research to $566 million. That's
$75 million more than President Clinton has asked for in his
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin said lawmakers worried about Medicare's financial
security should support increased Alzheimer's research.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could just postpone the onset of Alzheimer's by five
years, Medicare will be secure for the next 50 years,'' Harkin
said. ``If we can postpone the onset of Alzheimer's for 10 years,
Medicare will be safe for 100 years. If you want to save Medicare,
put your money in research for Alzheimer's disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
