<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, March 22:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INDIA (New Delhi) _ President Clinton, in India,
deplores the new violence in Kashmir, issues ``Vision Statement''
with Indian prime minister, pays homage at the Gandhi Memorial. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-KASHMIR (New Delhi) _ On the massacre in Kashmir. By Celia
W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   Related stories as needed.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-HOLYLAND (Jerusalem) _ Pope John Paul II celebrates Mass in
Jordan, then goes on to Tel Aviv and Jerusalem. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   POPE-HOLYLAND-BAPTISM (Wadi Kharrar) _ Feature from the site
where Jordan says Jesus was baptized. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WESTBANK (Dateline to kum) _ Israel finally makes a
long-delayed withdrawal from the 6.1-percent chunk of the West
Bank, which means the Palestinians now have full control over 40
percent of the West Bank. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Israeli-Palestinian talks resume in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-ELECT (Taipei) _ Developments in the aftermath of the
election; the stock market soars. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Beijing) _ Interview with Richard Holbrooke, the
U.S. envoy to the U.N., who has just completed talks with Chinese
leaders. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ The people of Kosovo risk losing the
good will and backing of the international community if they do not
put ethnic hatred aside, NATO Secretary-General George Robertson
said Tuesday in a report three days ahead of the anniversary of the
start of the NATO campaign against Serbia. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-WRITER (Bane) _ Five years after the writer Ken
Saro-Wiwa was executed by the military government, his remains are
still in an unmarked grave, intermingled with those of eight other
Ogoni men who were also hanged. Because of a dispute between the
author's family and the relatives of the eight men, a burial
scheduled by Saro-Wiwa's family for April 24 appears very unlikely
to take place. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TOBACCO (Washington) _ Supreme Court rules, 5-4, that the
FDA cannot regulate tobacco. The majority says tobacco is a huge
public health problem, but it is not covered under the authority
given by Congress to the regulators. For decades the FDA had said
it did not have authority to regulate tobacco, but it reversed its
view in 1996, saying there was new evidence that cigarettes were
dangerous and that the industry was manipulating nicotine levels.
By Linda Greenhouse. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TOBACCO-NEXT (Undated) _ In some ways, the Supreme
Court's decision clears the decks for the government and industry
to reach a negotiated settlement or for Congress to weigh in on
tobacco regulation. By Barry Meier. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-LOANS (Washington) _ A federal panel designed to offer
subsidized loans to independent gas and oil companies whose
business suffered when prices were low has received nearly two
dozen applications for loans, the Department of Commerce says. The
program, created by Congress last summer, would offer guarantees on
private loans totaling as much as $500 million for qualifying oil
and natural gas producers and small oil-field service companies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ U.S. District Judge K. Michael Moore
dismissed the lawsuit aimed at keeping 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez in
the United States, saying that only the U.S. attorney general can
grant asylum to the Cuban boy. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   RAPBROWN-SHOOTING (Atlanta) _ Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin,
apprehended Monday night in Lowndes County, Ala., where, as H. Rap
Brown, he was active during the '60s as leader of the Student
Nonviolent Coordinating Committee, is arraigned on unlawful flight
charges. Meanwhile in Atlanta, a funeral is held for the sheriff's
deputy he is accused of killing. By David Firestone. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT1,2.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-SAFETY (Undated) _ A coalition of major American cities,
searching for a way prevent a drive to improve gun safety from
stalling, intend to use their combined buying power to try to force
the nation's gun manufacturers to follow the lead of Smith &AMP; Wesson
and sign onto last week's landmark pact that requires new handgun
safety devices. Atlanta, Miami, Detroit and nearly a dozen other
major cities are scheduled to announce their effort Wednesday
morning in Washington. By Eric Lipton and James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3, of police recruits in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   TENN-EXECUTE (Nashville) _ At midnight Tuesday, Robert Glenn Coe
is scheduled to die by lethal injection, the first person put to
death in Tennessee since 1960. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-SENATE (Washington) _ Sen. John McCain's back in the
Senate. He makes a speech on the floor of the chamber and attends a
weekly luncheon. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Brief items from the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FED-RATES (Washington) _ Federal Reserve policy makers raise a
key interest rate a quarter point, the fifth such increase since
June. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-FUEL-BRITAIN (Washington) _ From simmering tanks of
high-level nuclear waste in Washington State to plutonium laced
with chemical poisons in Idaho and production of radioactive gases
in South Carolina, the nuclear weapons program has festering
technical and environmental problems like no one else in the
country. With no easy way to solve them, the Energy Department has
gone to one of the few entities in the world with experience as
broad as its own: British Nuclear Fuels, part of the nuclear power
and weapons agency of the British government, now spun off into a
government-owned company. But as BNFL prepares to tackle the
American problems, an embarrassing problem has surfaced back home.
British government inspectors report that for months, employees who
were supposed to be performing a final measurement check on fuel
pellets bound for Japanese reactors were instead simply copying
numbers from previous shipments. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The U.S. trade deficit surged 13.8
percent in January to a record $28 billion, much higher than
forecasts. Rising oil prices helped push January imports up 1.7
percent to a record $112.1 billion during January. A $6.9 billion
deficit in petroleum products alone was the largest since the
government started tracking those numbers in 1989. By Robert D.
Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   USAIRWAYS-UNION (Undated) _ What's at stake as a showdown looms
between US Airways and its flight attendants' union. The union has
said it will select random routes with impromptu walkouts to cause
maximum chaos. The airline says it will respond by shutting down
the entire system. Both sides are talking, but the deadline is
12:01 a.m. Saturday. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TAX (Dallas) _ Developments on last day of hearings by
the advisory commission on Internet taxation. By David Cay
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks are mixed in mid-afternoon trading.
At 2:20 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was up 79 points,
the S&AMP;P 500 was up 7 points and the Nasdaq composite index, which
tumbled nearly 3 percent in the first half hour, is down 45 points.
Treasury prices were slightly higher. European stock markets were
lower: London was down 0.14 percent and Frankfurt down 0.99
percent. The Nikkei closed up 0.18 percent; the Hang Seng, down
0.20 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   AHP-BASF (Undated) _ American Home Products sells its
agricultural business, Cyanamid, for $3.8 billion, a higher price
than expected, to BASF, ridding itself of an obstacle to its
efforts to find a merger partner as well as giving it more cash to
help settle fen-phen litigation.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-EARNINGS (New York) _ Goldman Sachs says first-quarter
earnings rose 67 percent, to $1.76 a share, higher than estimates
of $1.48. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Nancy
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MEXICO (Mexico City) _ A look at how the Internet is
coming of age in Mexico, pegged to a number of major Internet
alliances to exploit e-commerce opportunities, including a
partnership to be announced Tuesday between Televisa and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   BMW-ROVER (London) _ Recriminations over BMW's sale of Rover
intensify. Germany warns Britain that it risks foreign
disinvestment. Rover dealers demand compensation for snazzing up
their showrooms at BMW's request. Unions plan a mass rally April 1
to protest the sale to the Alchemy Partners investment firm. And a
rich Birmingham city councilman says he is planning a rival offer.
By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ECON (London) _ Looking at the governments new budget
and what it says about the British economy. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANAGEMENT PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOTCOM-MANAGE (Undated) _ A feature by Wenda Harris Millard,
executive vice president of DoubleClick.
</P>
<P>
   HIRING-PITFALLS (Undated) _ In today's tight job market, many
companies have not been diligent in checking the backgrounds and
work histories of the people they hire. That can spell trouble,
according to executive recruiters and people at companies that
specialize in background checks. Some companies, especially
Internet start-ups desperate to fill large numbers of openings,
openly acknowledge that they lack the time and resources to verify
all the information that job seekers submit. Even recruiters of
senior-level managers acknowledge that the frantic competition for
talent can blind them to danger signs. ``Now, if a bird flies, you
go for it,'' said Peter Crist, vice chairman of Korn/Ferry
International, the global executive-recruiting firm. ``What happens
is, in a high-velocity market like this, it becomes more
mistake-prone.'' By Charles Butler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties'' and Paul Krugman's ``Reckonings.''
</P>
