<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3583 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-IKEA-HNS &LR;      03-21 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IKEA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FANS AWAIT ARRIVAL OF SWEDISH RETAILER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EMERYVILLE, Calif. _ Ikea and its blond wood, affordable home
furnishings arrives in Northern California on April 12 with the
opening of a $46 million, 274,000-square-foot store in Emeryville.
</P>
<P>
   To the uninitiated, Ikea is a really big furniture store with
some very cool stuff. But to its followers, it goes to a much
deeper place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a cult. I don't know what it is about it,'' said
Laura Knerler, a Novato resident who has taken trips down to
Southern California on the auspices of visiting friends, but
acknowledging the true draw was Ikea.
</P>
<P>
   Knerler was first introduced to the store in suburban
Pittsburgh, where her in-laws live: ``All of a sudden, going to
visit was a treat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Emeryville store, the size of five football fields located
in a can't-miss location off Interstate 80 at the I-580 interchange
and painted in the can't-miss blue and yellow colors of the Swedish
flag, is expected to be wildly successful in this market.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, people in the San Francisco tend to respect the
stereotypical Swedish sensibilities of Volvos, massages and
unfailing political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   But to Ikea fans, none of this really matters. What matters is
the product.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good, cheap, modern design stuff,'' said Denise Alvidrez,
25, of San Francisco. ``Out here, you can find a lot of witty,
clever products, but they're priced like witty, clever products.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvidrez has been limited to stocking up on all the Ikea items
she can fit into a suitcase when she visits her or her boyfriend's
families near Los Angeles and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a junkie. I can't wait until it opens,'' she said of the
Emeryville store. ``I'm getting these under-the-bed drawers I've
been eyeing for a year. They're nothing you can lug on a plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Ikeaites have been known to drive many hours to get to the
nearest store.
</P>
<P>
   When David Brix, a computer graphic designer-illustrator who
lives in Oakland, broke off a long-term relationship, he had to set
up his own apartment in a hurry. So he flew to Los Angeles,
borrowed a friend's truck and filled it with Ikea furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to start from scratch,'' he said. ``I had no living
furniture, no dining room. I didn't have anything. It was the first
time I had my own place.''
</P>
<P>
   Ikea spokeswoman Marty Marston is at a bit of a loss to explain
why Ikea fuels such passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing quite like us. You can buy virtually anything
you need to live in a house, other than the appliances,'' she said,
``and we're somewhat hip.''
</P>
<P>
   The depth of merchandise can only be compared with, say, a Sears
store. But the style is more like a Scandinavian Designs with a
little Crate &AMP; Barrel or Pottery Barn thrown in. The prices add a
touch of Target, a store that recently shot up on the hipster
meter.
</P>
<P>
   It has everything from kitchenware and lighting fixtures to
office furniture. Whimsical designs such as a lamp shaped like a
lightbulb to inflatable animal chairs set it apart.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Ikea able to sell a solid-wood twin-frame bed for $79
or a kitchen cabinetry set (including the cabinet, countertop and
handles) for $645 is that everything is flat-packed and sold
unassembled (except upholstery products).
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept is you do a little, we do a little and together we
say a lot,'' said Michael O'Rourke, manager of the Emeryville
store, which will be the country's third largest Ikea store,
eclipsed only by those in Chicago and Elizabeth, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at efficiencies on the factory floor and that, in
turn, leads to a lot of innovations in what we produce,'' O'Rourke
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because the Emeryville Ikea is the company's first store in
Northern California, the opening is expected to draw huge crowds
(the company is bringing in 100 employees from other stores to help
in the opening rush).
</P>
<P>
   George Rosenbaum, chief executive of Leo J. Shapiro &AMP;
Associates, a Chicago-based market research firm specializing in
retail, said Ikea encourages this fanatical following.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image of this great merchant entrepreneur coming out of
the deep, black forests of Scandinavia with affordable,
do-it-yourself furniture in styles and designs that will make your
life comfortable while meeting the approval of friends and family
is kind of seductive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since a store cannot survive on fanaticism alone, Rosenbaum said
Ikea manages to draw $60 million to $70 million in sales per store
in a year by becoming the ``Volkswagen of furniture stores.''
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco will be a very good market for Ikea,'' he said.
``A lot of people pay so much for housing they have no money left
for furniture. Yet they want nice quality stuff. Ikea is a good
solution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
