<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3604 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-21 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NO WARM AND FUZZY FEELINGS FOR FELINES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Although some of my best friends have them, I've
never been much of a cat fan.
</P>
<P>
   With a handful of exceptions, their ancient, inscrutable charms
are nearly always lost on me. Where others see an exotic and
mysterious aloofness _ ``They're descended from lions; they won't
be OWNED!'' _ I see a selfish, ungrateful, narcissistic pain in the
butt.
</P>
<P>
   I know this attitude is pedestrian and lacking in soul (I have
been told it is pedestrian and lacking in soul), but give me a
tail-wagging, jump-up-on-you, slurpy-tongued dog anytime.
</P>
<P>
   A cat comes and rubs up against you when it wants something to
eat or is bored and has no other option. If your dog had its way,
you two would be joined at the hip.
</P>
<P>
   A dog wants to be with you just because you exist. Toss in a few
luxuries like regular food, petting and playing fetch with a tennis
ball, and you see where that ``man's best friend'' stuff comes
from.
</P>
<P>
   Also ``dog'' is ``god'' spelled backwards, something I don't
think is a coincidence. Dog, god. Anyway you spell it, it means
unconditional love.
</P>
<P>
   I've been ruminating on all this because my neighborhood has
gotten lousy with cats.
</P>
<P>
   Not the skinny, skittish feral kind that skulk around for food,
then scurry away to their version of a homeless person's cardboard
box under a freeway.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about privileged and pampered cats, the kind with
collars (though rarely ID tags) and well-tended fur. Cats with
homes from which they roam. And roam and roam and roam.
</P>
<P>
   Where do they roam?
</P>
<P>
   Into my back yard and onto my deck. Or, when (silly me) I open
my French doors to let in light and air, they roam into my home.
</P>
<P>
   As of the most recent count, I have lost three flower pots to
the privileged cats that roam from home. One pot, a white ceramic
bucket with blue and green flowers, had been with me since 1981 and
had survived three moves and an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   But what is sentimental value to a cat?
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being the main transfer point for all north-south
and east-west cat traffic, my deck has become the feline Club Med
of the neighborhood. It is the place everybody heads to loll in the
sun, scratch their claws on wood and _ yum, yum _ conceive
hairballs by licking themselves all over.
</P>
<P>
   In no time at all, the hairball babies gestate, grow and get
delivered (in all their slimy glory) back onto the deck or down in
the yard in my flower beds. Often, they are deposited right next to
another little clump of waste that comes from kitty's opposite end.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the fights.
</P>
<P>
   Both combatants screech and keen. The sound of bodies slamming
against wood fills the air, something I especially appreciate at 3
a.m. Fur literally flies.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, my only weapon is a garden hose, which I use when I
happen to be home and not dead asleep, to break up the brawls.
</P>
<P>
   (One of my cat-keeping neighbors actually endeared himself to me
a few weeks ago when he shouted across the fence: ``That cat in the
back is mine; aim your hose at him!'')
</P>
<P>
   But I don't like the violent and vengeful way I feel with my
water hose gun in hand. I hate that I love to see the cats freeze,
then rocket away in fear of their lives. It disturbs me that I
thoroughly enjoy blasting the little bastards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you get a big dog?'' several friends have asked.
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason is because I'm not home enough to be a good
dog owner. Unconditional love or no, I don't believe it's fair to
leave your best friend unattended for 10 or 12 hours at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, a dog should be free to run around its own yard. So
much for my flower beds and rose bushes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could always fight fire with fire,'' one pal suggested.
``Get your own cat.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about unclear on the concept. I'd rather fight fire with a
fire hose.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
