<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-KASHMIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACRE OF SIKHS IN KASHMIR COINCIDES WITH CLINTON VISIT TO
INDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-INDIA) 
(js) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The first day of President Clinton's visit to
India Tuesday was haunted by a horrific atrocity committed Monday
night in Kashmir, the disputed Himalayan territory that is at the
nub of half a century of conflict between India and Pakistan _ one
that the Americans fear could be a nuclear flashpoint between them.
</P>
<P>
   Just after dinnertime Monday, a band of armed men entered two
neighboring Sikh villages, summoned the male residents from their
mud huts and small brick homes, then slaughtered 39 of them in a
hail of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   No one has claimed responsibility for the massacre, the first
ever committed against the minority Sikhs in the past decade of
fighting in Kashmir. But both India and the militant groups that
have been battling in Kashmir say they assume the attack was timed
to coincide with the first visit by a U.S. president to India in 22
years on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has said he hoped he could help ease tensions over
Kashmir by visiting both India and Pakistan, condemned the attack,
while cautioning that it will be hard to draw any conclusions about
it until the identity of the killers is known.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly share your outrage and heartbreak over last
night's brutal attack in Kashmir,'' he said Tuesday at a joint
press conference with India's prime minister, Atal Behari Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, this latest twist in the cycle of violence has the
Indians pointing an accusing finger at Pakistan _ and the Islamic
militant groups Pakistan supports in Kashmir _ while Pakistan
denies complicity and the militant groups charge Indian security
forces with committing the massacre to discredit them in the eyes
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   According to police and residents of the small Sikh village of
Chati Singhpura, a band of armed men, dressed in Indian army
uniforms, entered their village and the adjacent village of Karewa
Singhpur at about 9 Monday night. The army put the number of gunmen
at about 20, while the police in Srinagar estimated a posse of 40.
</P>
<P>
   The male residents of the villages, which are about 40 miles
south of the summer capital of Srinagar, were asked to step outside
their homes. They filed out unsuspectingly. Sikhs had never before
been targets of violence in the years that predominantly Hindu
India has battled a Pakistan-backed insurgency in predominantly
Muslim Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers said that a tall, polite man who identified himself as
the commanding officer assured the villagers that all they needed
to do was show their identification cards, a process that would
take just 10 or 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed they were security men searching for militants,''
said one of the villagers, Surinder Kour.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the gunmen opened fire, killing 35 villagers on the
spot. Four more died later of their wounds. ``They were shot at
point blank range, said Ashok Bhan, inspector general of police in
the Kashmir zone.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, the village was a pitiable scene. Women and
children, sobbing and beating their chests, gathered round the
bullet-pocked bodies of their menfolk, scattered and askew near the
Sikh temple.
</P>
<P>
   Angry and sorrowful, the villagers on Tuesday did not seem sure
whom to blame. Some accused the Indian army, others suspected the
militants, and still others said they simply did not know who had
done it.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Brajesh Mishra, national security adviser to India's prime
minister, said Tuesday that India had evidence that two militant
groups _ Lashkar-e-Toiba and Hezbul Mujahedeen _ had jointly
carried out the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``These outfits are supported by the government of Pakistan,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee and his home minister, Lal Krishna Advani, painted the
attack as part of strategy planned by Islamic militants engaged in
a holy war against India to ethnically cleanse Kashmir of other
faiths. They first targeted Hindus and have now moved on to Sikhs,
Advani said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee also depicted it as part of a concerted effort to
undermine any movement toward peace and stability in South Asia
generally and Kashmir in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a deliberate design to foment trouble, to encourage
killings, mass murders, to sabotage any attempt to bring about
normalcy in this part of the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Pakistani officials condemned the attack and denied any part in
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would very much like a very thorough inquiry or
investigation to be conducted into this incident so that it is not
exploited for purposes of propaganda in order to deflect attention
from the Indian repression in Kashmir,'' Pakistan's foreign
minister, Abdul Sattar, told reporters in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Hezbul Mujahedeen also denied any
involvement in the attack. ``It is a deliberate attempt by the
Indian secret agency by which it wants to tarnish the 55-year
freedom movement as a terrorist movement,'' said Sayed Salahuddin,
the group's leader, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said they had no independent evidence of who
killed the Sikh men. Tuesday morning, when the Indian and U.S.
delegations met, the Indians seemed to know little and had not been
shown any additional evidence later in the day, the Americans said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
