<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3636 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-TEMPLE-SCROLL-NYTSF &LR;      03-21 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEMPLE-SCROLL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TEMPLE SCROLL' IS USED TO ATTACK JUDAEO-CHRISTIAN HERITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By NEIL ALTMAN  
 c.2000 NEIL ALTMAN  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by N.Y. Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Anti-Semitism, which is no stranger to skinheads or
intellectuals, has found a subtler breeding ground. It has gained
respectability within the intellectual elite involved in Dead Sea
Scroll research and biblical criticism.
</P>
<P>
   In an attack on Judaism and the Bible, some Dead Sea Scroll
scholars have used the Temple Scroll to suggest that Jews took a
direct hand in the crucifixion of Jesus, thus reopening an old
wound that the Roman Catholic Church has sought to close in recent
years. These scholars have asserted in recent years that the Temple
Scroll should become the sixth book of Moses and a new book of the
Bible, equal to the Torah, the foundation of all Jewish law.
</P>
<P>
   Although many questions still swirl around the true age of the
Dead Sea Scrolls and who produced them, mainline scroll scholars
say most of the biblical texts and commentaries were written in
pre-Christian times and hidden in caves in about 68 AD where they
lay untouched until 1947.
</P>
<P>
   The Temple Scroll, so named because it speaks of rebuilding the
Jewish temple in Jerusalem, reportedly was found in the 11th
scroll-bearing cave overlooking the Dead Sea in 1956. But it didn't
surface until the Six-Day War in 1967, when Israeli soldiers
liberated it from a Palestinian dealer who had been keeping it in a
shoe box under the floor of his home in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The dealer was later paid $105,000 for what turned out to be the
largest of the Dead Sea Scrolls, measuring 26 feet long and 9 to 10
inches high in its original form.
</P>
<P>
   Reconstructing part of the text of the Temple Scroll, some
scholars have taken the Hebrew verb ``to hang'' and have claimed
the word actually denotes crucifixion, despite contrary statements
from such leading Hebraists as Joseph Baumgarten of Baltimore
Hebrew University.
</P>
<P>
   One of these scholars wrote in the Journal of Jewish Studies
that Jews borrowed the practice of crucifixion from the Romans, and
``naturalized'' it into Jewish law.
</P>
<P>
   Another took the next step, reviving the old libel that the Jews
killed Jesus. He wrote that crucifixion in Judaism of the first
century (BC) could be regarded as a ``divine commandment'' and as a
legal penalty for high treason and blasphemy. ``One can no longer
argue that the fact of Jesus' crucifixion excludes Jewish
participation in his trial and death....'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Baumgarten, who is a member of the current Dead Sea Scroll team,
flatly states that the word in question does not mean ``to
crucify.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Baumgarten, the former graduate chairman of religious
studies at Boston University, Howard Kee, agreed that the Hebrew
means ``to hang,'' or ``to suspend'' but does not mean ``to
crucify.''
</P>
<P>
   He also took issue with those scholars who say Jews adopted
crucifixion from the Romans and made it part of their law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence that the Jews practiced crucifixion at
the time of Christ,'' Kee said.
</P>
<P>
   According to biblical and rabbinic law, the only Jewish means of
execution were stoning, burning, decapitation, and strangulation --
not crucifixion, which was a Roman method.
</P>
<P>
   Scroll scholars do not dispute that the Romans crucified Jesus,
yet by the mistranslation of the Temple Scroll, Jews again are made
culpable for his death, not just by consent, but by method as well.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing this new attack on Jews and Judaism, Jewish scholars
scoffed at the suggestion that crucifixion was a divine
commandment, regarding it as historical fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Breitbart, senior researcher at the Simon Wiesenthal
Center in Los Angeles, said in an interview: ``One, Jewish courts
never crucified. Two, Jewish courts many years before (the death of
Jesus) lost their power to inflict capital punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a few accounts of hanging from before the Roman
conquest of Palestine, but, Breitbart said, ``when the hanging from
a rope was done, it was done after the death of the guilty party
... to display justice, not at all as a method of death.
</P>
<P>
   ``So shame on them (the scholars) for their lack of
scholarship,'' he said. ``Or, if they knew this, shame on them for
perpetrating an agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Many biblical critics loathe the Bible, which shows up in their
animus toward Jesus, Jewry and the State of Israel. Since their
discovery in 1947, the Dead Sea Scrolls have become a major weapon
in such attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Hershel Shanks, in ``Understanding the Dead Sea Scrolls,''
states, ``For years the issue of anti-Semitism has lurked beneath
the surface of the Scrolls.''
</P>
<P>
   The virulent anti-Semitic views of John Strugnell, former head
of the scrolls team, were revealed in a 1990 interview with an
Israeli correspondent in which he referred to Judaism as ``a
horrible religion'' and said ``the occupation of Jerusalem -- and
maybe of the whole state (of Israel) -- is founded on a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite those statements, Strugnell was allowed to stay on the
team, though not as its leader.
</P>
<P>
   Randall Price, in his expose, ``Secrets of the Dead Sea
Scrolls,'' revealed that the views of a number of other scroll
scholars were also anti-Semitic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most members of the original Scroll Team had anti-Semitic
sentiments and openly aligned themselves with the Arab cause even
after the 1967 Six-Day War,'' Price wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Examples of this anti-Semitism,'' he wrote, ``include Patrick
Skehan's refusal to publish his completed volume in the DJD
(Discoveries in the Judean Desert) series of scroll photos under
Israeli auspices. Price also notes ``Roland deVaux's decision to
discontinue as the leading Scroll Archaeologist his work at the
Ecole Biblique in protest of `Israel occupation.' At the time,
these attitudes temporarily shut down work on the Scrolls.''
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on Price's revelations, Yitzchok Adlerstein, director
of the Jewish Studies Institute of the Yeshiva of Los Angeles,
said, ``Dead Sea Scroll studies in particular show bias of epic
proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Edward F. Jaworowski, chairman of classical studies at Villanova
University, commented in a 1993 letter concerning Dead Sea Scroll
studies that there are ``indeed serious issues at stake here of
anti-Semitism and anti-Christianity, not to mention valid
scholarship and personal and professional integrity.''
``Unfortunately,'' he continued, ``I agree that until the scrolls
can be turned over to a more legitimate board whose intentions are
beyond question, we'll never know the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Anti-Defamation League is weighing in. Emily Greytak,
assistant director of the Philadelphia ADL, has prepared a report
after a month-and-a-half long investigation based on this article
and other documentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reviewed this material and are forwarding it to our
national Office on Interreligious Affairs,'' she said in a Dec. 9,
1999 letter. ``We are confident that they will be handled
appropriately by our ADL colleagues.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Given the bias of many liberal scholars, is it any wonder that
Jews were barred from the scroll team until 1985? Or that Israel's
right to exist was in question?
</P>
<P>
   While conservative evangelical scholars saw the rebirth of
Israel as the beginning fulfillment of many biblical prophecies,
many liberal biblical scholars expressed disdain.
</P>
<P>
   Christianity also came under direct attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early days (of Scroll research,) much of the
controversy involved the extent to which Christianity would be `cut
down to size' by the contents of the scrolls,'' Shanks wrote.
</P>
<P>
   John Allegro, one of the original eight members of the Scroll
team, is quoted in Shanks' book as telling a colleague, ``By the
time I've finished there won't be any Church left.''
</P>
<P>
   Price further tells us, ``John Allegro, the agnostic, spent the
rest of his life trying to find ways to subvert the Christian
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Even to this day, scholars use the scrolls to discredit the
Bible and the validity of Judaism and Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Neil Altman is a Philadelphia-based writer who specializes in
the Dead Sea Scrolls.)
</P>
</TEXT>
