<SLUG> BC-CONDOMS-TAX-FREE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDOMS ADDED TO LIST OF SALES TAX EXEMPTIONS IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander has managed
to find a tax cut that Gov. George W. Bush, a fellow Republican,
probably won't brag about:
</P>
<P>
   Starting April 1, Texans will pay no sales tax on condoms.
</P>
<P>
   Prophylactics, which can be used to prevent pregnancy and
venereal disease, were included by the state's chief financial
officer among over-the-counter health items in Bush's 1999
initiative to give Texas families a break on some of life's
necessities.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, the presumptive GOP presidential nominee, never wanted
condoms included in the package. In fact, when he proposed the tax
cut during his 1998 re-election campaign, he stated that it would
not apply to sex-related items and birth control products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comptroller decided to include those products that the
U.S. Food and Drug Administration certifies as having a medicinal,
treatment or preventative effect on disease and illness,''
explained Sheila Clancy, a spokeswoman for the comptroller's
office. ``And condoms have been proven effective for preventing
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bush spokesman reiterated on Monday that the governor had no
intention of including condoms among sales-tax exemptions, but
would go along with Rylander's interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sounds like a bureaucratic, technical thing,'' said Mike
Jones of the governor's media office. ``Apparently the FDA has
found that these products have health benefits, and our law
basically uses the FDA's guidelines. I'm not an expert on what the
FDA calls medicine, but we'll follow the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathie Adams, president of the conservative Texas Eagle Forum,
said equating condoms with cough syrup and antacids is outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am surprised, and very disappointed'' by the ruling, Adams
said. ``We are more concerned about protecting children than we are
about protecting those who would promote promiscuity. And that's
what those products do.''
</P>
<P>
   But others applauded the move as an appropriate one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about public health policy at this point,''
said Peggy Romberg of the Texas Family Planning Association. ``It
seems to me that it would be inconsistent with good public health
policy to separate out those products which are effective in
preventing the spread of HIV, hepatitis and other diseases. That's
the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Other exempt items include over-the-counter products for
allergies, nausea, hemorrhoids, rheumatism, asthma, colds, sunburn,
constipation, headaches and dandruff; anti-microbial products;
antiperspirants (but not products labeled ``deodorant'');
anti-vomiting products and vomiting inducements; blood fortifiers;
medicated dental products; ear care and eye care items; sedatives
and sleep aids; stimulants; vitamins; minerals; and wound treatment
products.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, see the comptroller's Web site,
www.windows.state.tx.us.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
