<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BMW-ROVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH LABOR UNIONS TO PROTEST JOB LOSSES FROM BMW'S SALE OF
ROVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ An increasingly bitter dispute between Germany and
Britain over BMW's sale of the money-losing Rover Group threatened
to spill onto the streets when British labor unions Tuesday called
a huge demonstration on April 1 to protest thousands of expected
job losses from the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement coincided with remarks by a senior German
official that Britain's reputation as a haven for foreign
investment could be jeopardized by the government's criticism of
BMW's keeping secret the talks that led to the sale agreement.
</P>
<P>
   After a six-year investment, BMW announced last week that it was
selling Rover's main car production plant at Longbridge near
Birmingham to Alchemy Partners, a British investment group. BMW
also said it would sell Rover's profitable Land Rover sport utility
vehicle division to Ford Motor Co. for $2.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Alchemy said it planned to phase out Rover cars _ one of the
last British mass-market nameplates _ and focus on new models
bearing the MG name.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the BMW-Alchemy deal have not been disclosed, but
executives close to the talks said the investment group was likely
to pay up to $80 million for a debt-free balance-sheet worth more
than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The British government and labor unions have appealed for
alternative offers that would safeguard jobs. Under the present
deal, thousands of the 9,000 jobs at the rambling Longbridge plant
would be lost as it is transformed into a niche car producer. The
job losses would be likely to extend into smaller supply companies
in Britain's West Midlands automaking region.
</P>
<P>
   John Hemmings, a wealthy e-commerce and Internet businessman
with political ambitions in the region, said he was trying to
assemble a consortium to make a counterbid. But, he said, ``it will
be very difficult to get anything together'' because of Alchemy's
lead.
</P>
<P>
   In trading in Frankfurt on Tuesday, BMW rose 3.75 percent on
speculation that the Munich-based company could be vulnerable to a
takeover by Volkswagen, Ford and General Motors. But Thomas Gauly,
a spokesman for the Quandt family of Germany, BMW's dominant
shareholder, dismissed the speculation. He also denied a report in
a German news magazine that Joachim Milberg, BMW's chief executive,
was about to be replaced because of the involvement with Rover.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, Prime Minister Tony Blair's spokesman said Blair was
furious that BMW had not consulted his government in the talks,
echoing similar displeasure in Germany when Britain's Vodafone
AirTouch began a hostile bid for Germany's Mannesmann late last
year. BMW responded by criticizing Britain for allowing the pound
to rise so high against the mark that it made Rovers too expensive
to sell abroad.
</P>
<P>
   British unions, meanwhile, are calling for a boycott of BMW
cars, and anti-German sentiment is filling the mass-circulation
news media. On BBC radio Tuesday, Germany's ambassador in Britain,
Hans Friedrich von Ploetz, warned that Britain's reaction to the
deal could ruin its reputation as a magnet for foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Byers, Britain's trade and industry minister, who has
accused BMW of lying about Rover, plans talks with BMW in Munich on
Thursday, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Woodley, the chief negotiator for the Transport and General
Workers Union, who has also held talks with BMW executives, said
Tuesday that labor organizers had had a very favorable response to
their call for a protest march on April 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no exaggeration to say that this campaign is now a
battle for Britain and British manufacturing,'' he said, ``and it
has struck a chord with the British people.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1553EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
