<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: about it.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jakob the Liar &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In another ``upbeat'' Holocaust movie, a Polish restaurateur
(Robin Williams) decides he'll cheer up his fellow concentration
camp inmates by pretending he has a radio and is hearing news of
imminent liberation. That gives Williams a chance to do his Winston
Churchill imitation, but it also opens the floodgates for a rush of
strained good spirits that rob the tale of credibility.
</P>
<P>
   In this Holocaust story, an Anne Frank look-alike (Hannah Taylor
Gordon) may just live happily ever after. And, Janet Maslin wrote
in The New York Times, ``the film anticipates all laughter and
emotion in ways that make it its own worst enemy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77; DVD, $27.95. 114 minutes.
Closed captioned. PG-13. Release date: March 21. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Endurance &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A bombastic score of East African folk music doesn't help an
excruciatingly dull film about the Ethiopian long-distance runner
Haile Gebrselassie. Much happy trotting through the fields and
scenes from races is augmented with a fictionalized re-creation of
his youth, which counts for little because little is subtitled.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly the film meant well, but interest flags in a film
that resembles a 1950s National Geographic spread, and ``its
mixture of biographical hype and social studies quickly curdles''
(Stephen Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. . $104.16. 83 minutes. G. Closed captioned. Release date:
March 21. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B. Monkey &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Washing the clown-wig-red dye out of her hair, B. (for Beatrice)
Monkey (Asia Argento) signals to her live-in partners in crime
(Rupert Everett and Jonathan Rhys Meyers) that she's ready for
other things in life. Soon she has traded in her wayward ways for
crazed domesticity with a schoolteacher (Jared Harris), who lives
on a junky little houseboat.
</P>
<P>
   But old habits interfere when a former pal reappears, bringing
more trouble to a character who has been ``either written or
directed to be a little too aware of her charming quirkiness''
(Anita Gates). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 90 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: March 21. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Adventures of Sebastian Cole &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coping with an extended family situation rearranged by divorce,
a bright, energetic 17-year-old (Adrian Grenier) learns that his
stepfather, Hank (Clark Gregg), has decided to undergo sexual
reassignment and become a woman. Once again the family is
shattered, with hurt and enraged relatives scattering from England
to California.
</P>
<P>
   After some dislocation of his own, Sebastian settles down with
Hank, now Henrietta, resuming his tortured adolescence and capping
a performance by Grenier that ``beautifully captures his
character's precarious balance of naivete and bravado,
self-destructiveness and self-invention'' (Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Paramount. $64.10; DVD, $29.99. 100 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: March 21. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE UNPLEASANTNESS AT THE BELLONA CLUB. Who died first _ General
Fentiman or his rich sister, Lady Dorland? It's another case for
Lord Peter Wimsey (Ian Carmichael) of the BBC and '70s
``Masterpiece Theater'' series. Acorn Media. $59.95; four
cassettes. 180 minutes. Information: (800) 474-2277. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE AFFAIRS OF ANATOL and two other silent films from Kino.
Based on a play by Arthur Schnitzler (whose ``Traumnovelle''
inspired ``Eyes Wide Shut''), Cecil B. DeMille's ``Affairs of
Anatol'' (1921, 117 minutes) stars Gloria Swanson and Wallace Reid
as a wealthy philanderer drawn to the bordello of Satan Synne, the
queen of Jazz Age perversion.
</P>
<P>
   In D.W. Griffith's BATTLE OF THE SEXES (1928, 88 minutes), a
real estate baron (Jean Hersholt) bolts home and wife for a flapper
(Phyllis Haver) and a trip to the financial cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   Appendicitis and peritonitis felled Rudolph Valentino after THE
