<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3653 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN23-CO     03-21 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Of effluence and affluence
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ We're having a big stink about our paper mill,
more so than normally.
</P>
<P>
   The mill is asking state regulators to allow more leeway in its
discharge of effluent into the creek that leads into the Angelina
River that feeds Lake Sam Rayburn.
</P>
<P>
   Some people who worry about the environment are opposed to what
they consider an undue amount of pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The paper mill, however, says its scientific studies show the
concern is unwarranted. Most of our civic leaders _ a busload
traveled to Austin this week to support the mill at hearings _
point to the company payroll as a mainstay in the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   What would we do, they say, without the paper mill?
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask me. It was already here when I was born.
</P>
<P>
   Folks back then weren't bothered so much about the environment.
The smell of the paper mill, they used to say, was the smell of
money.
</P>
<P>
   A writer for Harper's magazine, who got lost and somehow ended
up here for a night or two, described it somewhat differently in an
article in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Rotten egg puke, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As I recall the magazine article, he told an old-timer he was
talking with, ``If I lived here, I'd blow that place up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir,'' the local replied. ``If you lived here, you'd work
there.''
</P>
<P>
   I worked there myself, in an indirect way, as did most everybody
in town.
</P>
<P>
   The paycheck I drew as a cub reporter at the newspaper came from
the same folks who owned the paper mill, and most everything else
in town _ the TV station, the biggest bank, the sawmill and any
number of elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   I can't remember anybody ever telling us we couldn't use the
word ``pollution'' in the newspaper. But we didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the paper mill has changed ownership more than once
since then, as have the newspaper, TV station, banks and any number
of elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   The sawmill, by the way, closed.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to imagine that folks used to ask: What would we ever do
without the sawmill?
</P>
<P>
   No reason to think that'll happen with the paper mill. There's a
$230 million modernization plan in the works, assuming the state
OKs more lenient environmental standards.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you know what modernization means _ more machinery,
less people. But what jobs are eliminated, the company says, will
be mostly through attrition.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the mill effluent can't be all that bad.
</P>
<P>
   I remember, years ago, the PR guy who conducted plant tours
would drink a cup of the stuff being discharged into the creek, all
but smacking his lips, to demonstrate for visitors how safe it was.
</P>
<P>
   I remember, too, that a young man on one of the tours with his
college group lingered behind the others and, before anyone could
stop him, took a big swig of it himself.
</P>
<P>
   As the story goes, the paper mill ended up hiring a private
detective to shadow the student around campus for a number of
weeks, just to make sure there were no delayed, ill effects. Last
anybody knew, he was doing just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Here's to the paper mill, whence our blessings flow. Drink up,
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
