<HEADER>
A3655 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-ELECT-NYT &LR;      03-21 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN RECOVERS AFTER ELECTION TURMOIL  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Defying analysts who predicted that the victory
of the opposition leader in Taiwan's presidential election would
scare off investors, the stock market here roared back on Tuesday.
Taipei's exchange jumped 5.5 percent, more than making up for its
2.6 percent loss on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders were comforted that the victory of the opposition
leader, Chen Shui-bian, did not noticeably ratchet up tension
between Taiwan and China, despite strident warnings from Beijing
about Chen's past advocacy of Taiwanese independence. And while the
defeated Nationalist Party was still in turmoil, the violent street
protests that followed the vote also subsided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chen has come out with a number of conciliatory statements
toward China,'' said Peter Kurz, the director of research at
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   Like most analysts, Kurz had predicted that the market would
plunge by its daily limit of 3.5 percent for several days before
hitting bottom. Fears of a crash grew on Sunday, when angry members
of the Nationalist Party besieged its headquarters in central
Taipei, demanding the resignation of the party's chairman,
President Lee Teng-hui, for his role in the defeat.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, hours before the market opened, Minister of
Finance Paul Chiu cut the limit on single-day price declines to 3.5
percent, from 7 percent. But on Tuesday, as Taipei basked under
glorious blue skies rare for this time of the year, those fears
seemed wholly unwarranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three issues that were worrying people _ a victory by
Chen, reprisals by China, and the collapse of the ruling party _
all settled down,'' Kurz said.
</P>
<P>
   In another soothing gesture, Taiwan's parliament approved direct
trade links between three outlying islands and mainland China. The
move is largely symbolic, since fishing boats and fruit vendors
from the islands _ Quemoy, Matsu, and Penghu _ already travel
freely to and from the mainland. But it added to the perception
that Taiwan and China were not hurtling toward a confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   As the leader of the Democratic Progressive Party, Chen has
battled the perception that he is less friendly to business than
the long-ruling Nationalist Party. That stems from his party's
roots as an opposition movement which drew its support from outside
the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Yet several analysts predicted Chen would work hard to win over
business people, and might be more accommodating in some areas than
Lee. Apart from Tuesday's gesture, Lee has refused to allow direct
trade, transportation, or communications links between Taiwan and
China. He has also imposed strict limits on investment in the
mainland by Taiwanese companies.
</P>
<P>
   In his victory speech on Saturday, Chen said he was willing to
lift those restrictions and negotiate direct links, provided it can
be done without compromising Taiwan's security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expanding trade is mutually beneficial,'' said Chen Pi-chao, a
former national security adviser to Lee who is now advising Chen.
``If we or they try to use trade to score points, it's not in the
best interest of either side.''
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's new leader has tried to woo foreign investors by
pledging to accelerate the lifting of restrictions on foreign
ownership here. Chen said he would allow outsiders to own 100
percent of local companies by June rather than by the end of the
year as had been earlier contemplated.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's economy played only a peripheral role in the campaign,
which was dominated by issues with China and charges of corruption
in politics. Chen's campaign manager, Chiou I-jen, acknowledged on
Monday that the incoming administration lacked experts on the
economy. He said Chen was assembling a task force of scholars and
other experts to help formulate policies.
</P>
<P>
   But with Taiwan rebounding briskly from the Asian economic
crisis, Chiou suggested that President-elect Chen had no plans for
radical changes. ``The situation of Taiwan's economy is fine,'' he
said, adding that even firms with ties to the Nationalist Party
``will want to continue investing in Taiwan.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts here noted that although Chen himself is a prosperous
lawyer who has represented some of Taiwan's largest corporations.
Several captains of industry endorsed Chen in the final week of the
campaign -- votes of confidence that proved crucial in swaying
voters who might have harbored doubts about his intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old impression was that Chen was anti-business,'' said
Paul Hsu, a leading corporate lawyer. ``But now the businessmen are
powerful enough that Chen needs them more than they need Chen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
