<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3662 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-FRAZZLED-PARENT-TEX     03-21 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAZZLED-PARENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SONIC DIED, GUILT LIVED ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some pets, like Old Yeller, become true best friends, and when
they die, we grieve but know our lives were enriched by the love we
shared.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the story with Sonic the Hedgehog.
</P>
<P>
   Sonic's death was all about guilt.
</P>
<P>
   The night I came home and found my son's pet dead, lying on his
side with his mouth half-filled with some loose shavings from his
cage, I cried. It was 9 at night, and I had just gotten home from
the office. I was tired, and the kids were at their dad's for the
night.
</P>
<P>
   I sat at the dining room table for two hours, drinking three
glasses of pinot noir and reusing the same pathetic tissue.
Finally, I picked up the phone and called a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonic's dead,'' I sniffed, which brought the anxious reponse
of ``Who?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonic. Jack's hedgehog,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   My friend was silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry,'' he said, finally. ``I didn't know you cared.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just it,'' I said, keenly irritated with his density.
``I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   I did care about Sonic once. And so did my son. When we first
got our little exotic pet four years ago, Jack took him out each
day to play with him, just as the pet-store owner had suggested.
</P>
<P>
   As the months passed, Sonic overcame his natural tendency to be
scared of humans and would unfold himself from the prickly hissing
ball that was his defense position. Sonic would run around the
floor in front of Jack. While it wasn't exactly playing, it was
entertaining. They both seemed so happy.
</P>
<P>
   When Sonic was about a year old, I noticed his spines were
beginning to fall out and his skin looked rough and red. I found
him a specialty vet _ two cities away _ who told me Sonic had
mites. Every day, twice a day for a month, I coaxed Sonic out of
his hissing ball and somehow compelled him to swallow a drop of
medicine. I Florence Nightengaled him back to health. I was happy.
</P>
<P>
   That was light-years ago.
</P>
<P>
   I cried when Sonic died because I didn't know what to do with
the corpse.
</P>
<P>
   Throw it in the trash? It wouldn't get picked up for four days.
Bury it in the back yard? What if the neighboring cat dug the thing
up? And what was I going to tell the kids the next day when they
came back home?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I hit upon an answer: the vet across the street. The
clinic opened early. I'd take Sonic there. I put Sonic's cage in
the garage and slept well that night, not knowing what lay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The vet rushed to the door to help me with the cumbersome cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have we here?'' he asked with a wide grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' I said, ``I'm afraid it's a dead hedgehog.'' I waited
nervously for him to ask how I had the nerve to dump this horrid
problem squarely on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the good doctor looked sad. He opened the cage and with
his bare hands, began stroking Sonic's face, exposing a nasty
infection on his ear I hadn't noticed before. I began to feel like
a pet abuser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor baby,'' he murmured. ``Poor, poor thing.''
</P>
<P>
   I tried to look sad, too, but I felt nothing. Except guilt. I
knew Sonic had been losing weight. I knew he had been dehydrated. I
knew he was disoriented because he began running on his wheel in
the daytime instead of at 3 in the morning as was his usual
behavior. I explained all this to the vet. What I couldn't explain
was why I hadn't done a thing.
</P>
<P>
   To cover my shame, I stammered something about how I just wanted
this taken care of before the kids got home from school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aah, there's children,'' he said. He touched my arm in
sympathy. ``Please, wait here.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling increasingly uncomfortable (I am a horrible, horrible
animal-neglecting person with no feelings whatsoever), I watched
while the vet rummaged through cabinets. Finally, he handed me the
literature he sought: ``Death of the Family Pet: Losing a Family
Friend'' the cover read.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I guess you'll want this cage back for your next pet,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Next pet?
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, that's OK,'' I said, looking at the cage and noting with
sudden shock that the still-afixed price tag read $70. How
different life was back before I was divorced, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand,'' the vet nodded, not understanding at all. And
how could he? He was a saint. I was the fallen, clearly beyond
rehabilitation. I had to get out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll clean this out right now,'' he said, misinterpreting my
anxiety and offering comfort that could only make me feel worse.
``And then I'll call around to some local schools. I'm sure there's
a classroom that could use this for their pet.''
Epilogue &QC;
</P>
<P>
   When I told the kids about Sonic's death the next day, Jack had
tears in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry, Sweetie,'' I said, thinking that this was all my
fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all my fault,'' said Jack. ``Do you understand, Mom? I
just feel so guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   This I understood. And reprobate that I am, I could offer real
comfort to my son.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1612EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
