<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3665 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-INDIA-CLINTON-0322-CO     03-21 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-CLINTON-0322-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S.-INDIA TALKS STUMBLE ON KEY ISSUES OF KASHMIR, NUCLEAR
WEAPONS PROGRAM
 &HT;    (850&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With INDIA-PROTEST-0322.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ President Clinton and Indian Prime Minister
Atal Bihari Vajpayee clashed Tuesday over two critical security
issues, as India's leader rejected Clinton's appeal for early talks
with Pakistan over the fate of Kashmir and insisted on India's
right to bear nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee's responses appeared to thwart Clinton's central aims
in coming here: to defuse tensions between Pakistan and India; and
to try to roll back a nuclear arms race between the South Asian
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Both issues were unexpectedly inflamed after unidentified gunmen
massacred 40 people Monday night in Kashmir, the Himalayan state at
the root of Indo-Pakistani friction.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee implicitly blamed Pakistan for sponsoring the attack _
and other terrorist acts that have bedeviled Kashmir for years.
Referring to such attacks, Vajpayee warned darkly in a news
conference that, ``We have the means and the will to eliminate this
menace.'' He declined, when pressed for further explanation, to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Vajpayee hailed their summit here as the
long-overdue opening of a new chapter in relations between the
United States and India, a democratic nation of 1 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's attack, however, assured that differences over U.S. and
Indian policies concerning nuclear arms and Pakistan would overtake
the broader message of Indo-American partnership Clinton had hoped
would be sent by his visit here, the first by a U.S. president in
22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged India to abandon its nuclear arms program, and
Vajpayee flatly refused. After a meeting and lunch with Clinton,
Vajpayee told reporters, ``I've explained to President Clinton the
reasons that compel us to maintain a minimum nuclear deterrent.''
</P>
<P>
   India conducted a series of nuclear test explosions in May 1998.
Pakistan quickly followed with its own tests, adding the threat of
a nuclear exchange to the highly charged rivalry between
subcontinental neighbors that have fought three wars over Kashmir
since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pressed India on the need to enter into a diplomatic
dialogue with Pakistan _ which he has offered to help mediate _
over Kashmir, divided into sections of Indian and Pakistani control
by the fragile cease-fire boundary known as the line of control.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee spurned that proposal as well, saying that ``problems
between countries of the region should be resolved peacefully by
the concerned countries themselves.'' There has been virtually no
diplomatic contact for months, analysts say, between Pakistan and
India and tensions between them are near a 30-year high.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's message was muddled, moreover, when he appeared to
hand Vajpayee an excused absence from such talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some way must be found to renew the dialogue,'' Clinton said.
``But you cannot expect a dialogue to go forward unless there is an
absence of violence and a respect for the line of control.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders made their remarks during a joint news conference
following a bilateral meeting here in India's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Even as India hardened its positions and escalated its rhetoric,
this country's president took the unusual step of publicly
lecturing Clinton for suggesting that tensions between India and
Pakistan, home to the world's third-largest and eighth-largest
armies, respectively, have raised the risk of war between the
world's two newest nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been suggested that the Indian subcontinent is the most
dangerous place in the world today, and Kashmir is a nuclear
flashpoint,'' India's president, Kocheril Raman Narayanan, said in
a prepared toast to Clinton at a state dinner Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``These alarmist descriptions will only encourage those who want
to break the peace and indulge in terrorism and violence,''
Narayanan said, as Clinton, his guest of honor, looked on from his
seat directly across a long banquet table from his host.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding a similar theme earlier, Vajpayee said talk of possible
war in the region was overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is not so bad as it is made out to be,''
Vajpayee said. ``There are differences. There have been clashes.
There is the problem of cross-country terrorism. Innocent people
are being killed. But there is not threat of any war . . . and
nobody should think in those terms in this subcontinent.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not respond directly to the remarks, which appeared
to target comments he made to members of the clergy during a March
9 White House event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most dangerous place in the world today, I think you could
argue, is the Indian subcontinent and the line of control in
Kashmir,'' Clinton told the religious leaders at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called line of control is the fragile cease-fire boundary
agreed to by India and Pakistan following fighting in 1971 over
control of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The province is under the formal authority of India. Portions of
it, though, are actually controlled by Pakistan, which has never
accepted India's sovereignty over the predominantly Muslim region
and has supported repeated incursions into Kashmir by separatist
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The 40 people massacred Monday night were Sikhs, an
ethno-religious group that combines elements of Hinduism and Islam.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said U.S. officials had
made no judgment as to who was responsible for the killings, which
vied all day Tuesday with Clinton's state visit for air time on
Indian television.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee, though, laid the blame on Pakistan. Clinton plans to
journey on Saturday to the Pakistani capital of Islamabad to meet
with Chief Army Gen. Pervez Musharraf, who overthrew the elected
government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif last October.
</P>
<P>
   Without specifically naming Pakistan, Vajpayee said that
``whenever there are chances of both countries coming together . .
. there is a deliberate design to foment trouble, to encourage
killing, mass murders, to sabotage any attempt to bring about
normalcy in this part of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Vajpayee, ``This policy is not going to pay, and I hope
this question will be discussed by the president in Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials tried to play down the rhetorical skirmishes that
dominated what was billed as a day of new directions and diplomacy
for U.S. relations with India, the second most populous nation on
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Independent analysts had cautioned, also, that any progress in
easing Indo-Pakistani relations or trimming India's nuclear sails
would likely come from behind the scenes diplomacy and might not be
publicly visible for months.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Vajpayee did manage to sign a joint communique,
calling for regular consultations between the two governments on a
host of shared issues ranging from terrorism control to
environmental protection and economic development.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
