<HEADER>
A3670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      03-21 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT A BAD WAY TO OPEN A MUSSEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many years ago in Barcelona, I saw mussels and clams
cooked ``a la plancha'' _ on a thick slab of hot metal much like
the griddles used by short-order cooks. The technique involved
tossing handfuls of the shellfish onto the hot grill, then scooping
them off as soon as they had opened up.
</P>
<P>
   It's a common preparation in Spain and throughout the
Mediterranean, and the results are memorable: the plump, firm
mussels are filled with their own natural flavors as well as a
certain smokiness picked up as their juices burn on the hot
surface.
</P>
<P>
   It never occurred to me to try to duplicate this dish at home
until I tasted the ``black skillet'' mussels at the Black Cat, a
restaurant in the North Beach neighborhood of San Francisco. In
some ways, the chef, Reed Hearon, has improved on the Mediterranean
staple. His mussels are presented in the same skillet in which they
cooked, so their juices _ cooked dry and stuck to the pan _ come
with them. Hearon serves the mussels with drawn butter; the idea is
to dip the mussel meat into the butter, then rub it on the surface
of the pan, where it picks up more of the smoky flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The technique seemed perfect for home cooking, but I was a
little worried: what seems simple in a chef's hands doesn't always
work for the rest of us. Maybe, I thought, Hearon uses a 700-degree
oven to make all of this happen. But when I called him, he was
encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fun dish,'' he said, ``and one I do at home all the
time. It works great on either gas or electric stoves, and all you
need is a heavy skillet.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor, he added, need the skillet be all that hot _ when a few
drops of water dance across its surface, it's ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any hotter than that and you run the risk of incinerating the
mussel shells,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   On no account should the pan become white-hot. Beyond that, he
said, it's just a matter of keeping the mussels in a single layer
and taking them off the heat as soon as the juices evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   I was still suspicious, but when I gave it a try I was stunned
and delighted: there were no problems. The mussels started opening
on contact with the skillet, the juices ran out and evaporated, and
the dish was done in about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   I served it with drawn butter the first time, but abandoned that
once I realized how delicious the mussels are with no more than
salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Hearon was right about this dish.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best kind of cooking,'' he said. ``One in which
you start with a great product and don't mess it up.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLACK SKILLET MUSSELS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Reed Hearon &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds mussels, washed and debearded
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat a large cast-iron or heavy steel skillet over high heat
about 5 minutes, or until drops of water dance across the surface.
Add mussels in one layer. (Your pan may hold more or less than 1{
pounds; use as many as will fit comfortably.)
</P>
<P>
   2. Cook mussels, shaking pan occasionally, until they begin to
open. Meanwhile, in a small pan over low heat, melt butter if
you're using it. When all mussels are open and their juices have
evaporated in the hot pan, about 10 minutes, remove from heat,
sprinkle with salt and pepper and serve immediately in pan with
butter for dipping.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
