<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-HOTEL-SUIT22-1STLD-CO     03-21 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTEL-SUIT22-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ADAM'S MARK HOTEL CHAIN SETTLES TWO DISCRIMINATION LAWSUITS
 &HT;    Eds: Adjusts wording in 2nd graf.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Adam's Mark hotel chain has agreed to pay $8
million and implement non-discrimination policies to settle two
lawsuits, Attorney General Janet Reno announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's Mark admitted no wrongdoing in an agreement ending a
class-action lawsuit filed by African-American plaintiffs and
joined by the state of Florida, but will pay $4.4 million to guests
and visitors at the chain's Daytona Beach hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The case began after five African American college students said
the hotel them _ but not white guests _ wear bright orange
wristbands to get into the hotel during last spring's Black College
Reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's Mark will also pay $1.5 million to four historically
black colleges in Florida for scholarships and internships in hotel
and hospitality management. It also agreed to pay $112,000 to the
four schools _ Florida A&AMP;M University, Bethune-Cookman College,
Edward Waters College and Florida Memorial College _ to coordinate
and promote the annual Black College Reunion over the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Another $1.75 million will go for attorney fees, and about
$250,000 to administer the payments to members of the class.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the five students who brought the original suit will get
$25,000. Another 1,200 guests and an undetermined numbers of their
visitors will also share in the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate suit, the Justice Department alleged that the
chain violated the Civil Rights Act by charging black customers
higher prices than whites and segregating them in less desirable
rooms in a corporate pattern of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's Mark agreed to revise its policies to prevent bias and to
attract minority customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under today's settlement with the Justice Department, the
21-unit hotel chain has agreed to adopt a comprehensive plan which
will ensure that every hotel will be operated in a
nondiscriminatory fashion,'' said Reno. ``It will create an
effective method for investigating and resolving complaints. It
will retain an independent monitor to ensure that the chain is
complying with the agreement, and it will employ strategies to
attract minority customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hotel officials said Adam's Mark is ready to move ahead ``now
that this lawsuit is behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While Adams Mark is committed to equality and has never
intentionally done anything wrong, we apologize for any actions
that may have made any of our guests feel uncomfortable or
unwelcome,'' said Fred Kummer, the company's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adam's Mark chose to do the right thing,'' said Florida
Attorney General Bob Butterworth, who announced the settlement with
Reno.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will stay in effect for four years and calls for
Adam's Mark to hire an outside monitor _ Project Equality of Kansas
City, Mo. _ to ensure compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, Project Equality will investigate any
complaints filed by Adam's Mark guests, design and monitor a
non-discrimination training program for hotel employees, and
establish a marketing plan with the hotel to attract African
American guests.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement is still subject to court approval.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's Mark, based in St. Louis, owns hotels in 13 states. The
cities it serves include Atlanta; Grand Junction, Colo.; Dallas;
Houston; San Antonio; Clearwater Beach, Fla.; Orlando; Columbus,
Ohio; Charlotte, N.C., and Winston-Salem, N.C. The chain is
building what the company says will be the largest hotel in
Jacksonville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
