   UNDATED: For years, my friend had no kitchen stove _ but she did
have a small child and a husband who expected to eat. ``How on
earth do you get away with having no cook stove?'' I asked. ``It's
easy,'' she said. ``You've got to have a coffeepot, a toaster and a
hot plate. For breakfast you have coffee, toast, boiled eggs or
cereal.'' She counted the items off on her fingers. ``Lunch doesn't
count because no one is home. At night you eat refrigerator food _
that is, sandwich stuff _ or you go out,'' she declared, dusting
her hands together as if to remove excess flour. I've taken a page
from my friend's book _ and another from the restaurant guide, but
that's another essay. I've got a range top, an outdoor grill, a
microwave, a coffeepot, a toaster oven and a Crock-Pot. Who needs
more? By MARY ROGERS. &QL; 
