<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3690 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE23-COX     03-21 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bamboo's tender shoots making dramatic leaps
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, March 23.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Walking through the garden the other day, I knew
spring had sprung. Playing off one another in a symphony of sights
and sounds were, among others, daffodil, iris, quince, saucer
magnolia, lenten rose, flowering almond, azalea, cherry, Scotch
broom. And bamboo.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, bamboo. In all its incarnations _ good, bad, lovely,
reluctant, it is as much a harbinger of this soft season as any of
the flowers whose scents and petals arrest beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, whenever I go to the garden this time of year, I search
for the first shoots springing from the golden bamboo and the
black. The gray, too. Those were the first I planted 11 years ago
for their gentle whistling, rustling, swaying in soft breezes,
their bent-doubleness during ice storms and blowdowns. (About 5
feet tall when I planted them, some now reach 20 feet. Some bamboo
growers cultivate timber canes 50 feet tall.) Over the years I have
planted and admired bamboo that zigs and zags, bamboo with swollen
canes, spotted canes, some with swollen joints. Weeping bamboo,
bamboo with leaves like palms.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered plantings under windows and those away from the house
have brought much drama and movement to the garden. Through windows
and doors, the mobile canes entertain and intrigue endlessly,
bringing the outdoors inside, integrating house and garden.
Outside, in the garden, those same canes create a tropical,
mystical tour, transporting all who appreciate them.
</P>
<P>
   While bamboo's lacy leaves always lend an evergreen air to the
bleakest winter day, it is this time of year that the plant seems
most lively, as its tender shoots jump from the ground, epitomizing
primeval.
</P>
<P>
   And I do mean jump. Turn your head for a day or so, and those
6-inch shoots reach your waist. This kudzu-like reality makes
bamboo growers pay close attention to what's going on in the
corners and shadows of the garden. As I welcome the shoots to spots
where I want them, I also diligently break them off at about 6
inches when they shoot up where I don't want them. For more than a
decade this has worked just fine, despite friends who shake their
heads, pitying any fool who grows bamboo.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, I have felt foolish many times as I watched dwarf
bamboo try to take over my garden; it's not for nothing it is
called a ground cover. Unlike the canes, this low-growing, plastic
grass catches no breeze, emits no sounds and gives no sway. It just
eats up space, choking out other plants. Beauty is its sole asset.
</P>
<P>
   So, about four years ago, I cut it back, dug it out and hoped to
kill it. For months, I patrolled the garden with pruners, snipping
each sprig that pushed up, eventually wearing out a pair of the
cutters. Patience and mindless warfare eventually paid off; last
spring was the first that did not bring a revival of the plastic
grass. Still, I keep a sharp eye _ and even sharper pruners.
</P>
<P>
   Never, ever planting dwarf bamboo (except in containers) is just
one lesson I've learned since I began loving the reeds. Another is,
like many allegedly fast-spreading plants, canes never grow fast
and far if you want them to.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, I put in several clumps of canes at the cabin in
McCaysville, Ga., hoping to cover a large area with a forest of
reeds, seeking those sounds and sights that flow through the open
windows and doors. I'm still waiting for the clumps to produce
their first new canes.
</P>
<P>
   With this fertile season, hope surges again. Like fresh new
shoots untamed.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay (at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1630EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3691 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-REMODEL-COLLINS23-COX     03-21 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMODEL-COLLINS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Contractor showers owners with problems
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, March 23.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bob and Joyce Collins just wanted a shower. What they
got was $800 worth of damage to their bathroom _ and major bruises
to their egos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were way too sophisticated to be taken, but at
this point we're feeling like stupid senior citizens,'' Joyce says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The job: Like many people their age _ she's 66 and he's 68 _
the East Point, Ga., residents had found it difficult in recent
years to get in and out of the bathtub. They decided that
installing a shower would help the situation. ``We've never really
had a shower in our home of nearly 50 years and were so happy to
finally get one,'' Joyce says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The hire: The Collinses were excited to get a referral for a
remodeler who was young. ``When you get our age, everyone you know
out there is retiring,'' she
</P>
<P>
   says.
</P>
<P>
   The contractor met with the couple on Nov. 20, told them he'd
been in business for 15 years, showed them a portfolio of bathrooms
he'd completed and offered a contract, which they signed. He
required a 50 percent deposit _ $825 _ before beginning the work
and agreed to start two days later.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The rub: The couple paid the deposit, but the contractor
failed to show up that Monday. He came on Tuesday and began ripping
out the bathroom wall, bagging the debris and drilling holes in the
tile floor, where he mounted a two-by-four.
</P>
<P>
   Upon leaving, the contractor told the Collinses he would not be
back for a week. When that time passed, he left a message on their
answering machine saying he couldn't make it back for yet another
week. When that appointment came and went, the couple left repeated
messages for him, none of which were returned.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The fallout: ``He left a large open hole the full length of
the shower area where you can see the ground, feel cold air and
entertain roaches; and without any insulation the (nearby) airport
sounded as if the landing strips were in our toilet,'' Joyce says.
``What he did consists of nothing. He did harm to our bathroom, not
improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The resolution: The couple filed a complaint against the
contractor with the Better Business Bureau. The contractor later
``pleaded ignorant about the whole thing,'' explaining that he'd
left his business in the hands of a partner who had not followed
through. The contractor has made no attempt to resolve the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Collinses have since hired another contractor from a
friend's referral. ``He built us a beautiful shower,'' she says.
``It's just gorgeous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The lesson: The couple has their shower but are left drained
from disappointment _ in mankind.
</P>
<P>
   The contractor had instantly won the Collinses' trust with his
sad stories about a dying mother and other family tragedies. ``We
believed this boy,'' Joyce says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always dealt honestly with people and cannot understand
how anyone can do this kind of evil to a couple who treated him
kindly. What really bothers me is that if he just got into a jam
and needed our money, why didn't he just come to us and tell us the
truth?''
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
