<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3694 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-REMODEL-GOOD23-COX     03-21 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMODEL-GOOD23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Couple's dream of better home becomes nightmare
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, March. 23.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Rick and Vicki Good thought they'd taken every
precaution to protect themselves from unscrupulous contractors.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly two years after starting a remodeling job that should
have taken three months, the Atlanta residents are out nearly
$60,000 and left with such shoddy work that the kitchen sink fell
out of the counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were doing all the right things _ had four or
five bids, picked the second most expensive contractor (they say
you get what you pay for), checked references, called the Better
Business Bureau,'' Vicki Good says. ``The man could sell ice cubes
to Eskimos, as the saying goes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The job: The Goods wanted to upgrade their kitchen, add a
bathroom and create a master suite. They contacted some of
Atlanta's most reputable remodelers, two of whom ``flat refused to
come south of Ponce,'' she says, preferring to work in more upscale
neighborhoods such as Virginia-Highland and Morningside.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The hire: The couple turned to newspaper ads and, after
talking to several contractors, hired one whom a neighbor had
recommended. Vicki cut back on her hours as a physician's assistant
at Grady Memorial Hospital so she could keep an eye on the project.
(Rick Good, 39, is a flight paramedic.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The rub: Their contract, signed in May 1998, required a 50
percent deposit upfront, which Vicki questioned but was told was
necessary to cover material costs. Though their check was cashed
two days later, the contractor didn't begin work for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Their tiny, solitary bathroom became Grand Central Station for
the couple, their three dogs and work crews. ``Ever try washing
dishes in the tub?'' asks Vicki, 37. ``Imagine doing this for five
months between showers.''
</P>
<P>
   Cabinets didn't arrive until August and weren't installed until
late October.
</P>
<P>
   The Goods became suspicious when they asked to see the building
permit, which their contract stated the contractor would secure.
``I was told I would be a fool to want to permit the work,'' Vicki
says, because that would require city inspections. When she halted
the work, her relationship with the contractor became so hostile
that they were forced to communicate by notes.
</P>
<P>
   The permits eventually were secured, but the contractor returned
to the project only a few times over the next five months, leaving
what she calls incompetent and inexperienced workers to finish the
job. ``By July, he had basically washed his hands of us, as he had
gotten 80 percent of his money out of me,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The contactor finally agreed to add a completion date to the
contract: Dec. 14, 1998 _ eight months after work began _ with
financial penalties for each day the job went over.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The fallout: While some items on her ``punch list'' were
completed, the quality, Vicki says, was horrible: drywall with
exposed nail heads, broken trim work, walls painted without being
primed, damage to a deck and a new heating and air-conditioning
system, and the undermounted sink that fell out after a couple of
months of use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole miserable experience pushed me to the edge when, on
Dec. 23, we failed the electrical inspection for the second time
and the city gave us five days to remedy the faults, as they
created a fire hazard,'' Vicki says. ``Our power was to be turned
off!''
</P>
<P>
   The Goods fired the contractor and hired another to correct the
problems. But the next week, a worker delivered a final bill with a
letter in which the first contractor threatened to sue if the
couple didn't pay him. The Goods hired a lawyer and, in March 1999,
learned that the contractor had gotten a lien placed on their house
for failure to pay.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The resolution: Because their lawyer estimated that a court
battle would cost them $15,000, the Goods filed a complaint with
the Better Business Bureau, hoping its arbitration process would
resolve the issues. But because the BBB has no authority to enforce
an arbitrator's decision, that process left the couple even more
frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki contacted the consumer fraud division of the Fulton County
solicitor's office, which is investigating. Even a criminal
conviction, however, would do nothing to get the project completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we could afford to sue, he has no assets, so there's
nothing to go after,'' Vicki says. ``I am unable to sell my house,
as his lien would have to be paid, and I am not willing to reward
him for his bad behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The fiasco has cost the couple nearly $60,000, she says, and the
contractors they've contacted about finishing the job aren't
interested in correcting someone else's mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The lesson: The Goods realize they made mistakes, especially
in failing to check out references. ``I should have gone to work
sites and followed him around,'' Vicki says. They also now know
they should never have agreed to a 50 percent deposit and that
their contract should have stipulated work deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, a year and a half later, I am still dealing with the
aftermath of this experience,'' she says, ``and wondering what else
is going to fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
