<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3695 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-REMODEL-LIEVENS23-COX     03-21 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMODEL-LIEVENS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Planning gets the job done without hassles
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, March 23.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tales of renovation horror are so common that many homeowners
would rather sell than take on a project.
</P>
<P>
   Geert and Debra Lievens had heard plenty, but because they loved
their house, their neighborhood and its schools, they decided to go
for it. ``We were dreading it, but we had long since outgrown our
home and needed the additional space badly,'' she says. ``Buying a
new home was out of the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Deciding to renovate didn't eliminate their fears. But they were
able to conquer them by educating themselves. The result is that
their project was completed ahead of schedule, to their desire and
without hassle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living through a renovation is tiring, stressful, dirty and
intrusive,'' said Debra, who works in marketing from her Garden
Hills home. ``For most of us, it also represents a huge financial
commitment and, hopefully, a good long-term investment. All the
more reason to get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The job: She and her husband, an engineer, wanted a master
suite, a small second office, a sitting area and carport. A steep
slope in the back yard and complicated roof lines presented
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The hire: ``My husband and I had countless discussions about
the pros, the cons, the process, the results and, of course, the
money that would be involved,'' Debra says. They considered several
local design/build firms before hiring Sawhorse Inc., which had
already done two smaller projects for them. The latest would
involve adding some 800 square feet to their 2,100-square-foot
home.
</P>
<P>
   Before they first hired the company, the couple checked out its
references. ``Unexpected things would be inevitable, but I wanted
to know how the remodeler dealt with them, how they manage the
process, how they follow up on things,'' Debra says. ``When you're
talking about a big chunk of money and that much disruption in your
home, you want someone you can trust.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The rub: There wasn't any _ something the Lievenses attribute
to taking their time, planning and communicating with their
remodeler. ``I had about five years to salivate over what I wanted,
and we spent a lot of time talking with them about how we'd use
every aspect of the renovation,'' Debra says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The fallout: The inevitable bumps occurred, most caused by
weather delays, but they were dealt with promptly, Debra says.
While the construction schedule in their contract called for four
months of work, the couple and their two kids braced for six. To
their delight, the project was completed five weeks early, on
budget and with results that exceeded their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The lessons: The Lievenses believe their project was
successful for several reasons _ they checked out the stability,
the design skills and the construction results of the firms they
considered. They also talked to references about how the companies
dealt with unforeseen developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a little luck, a positive attitude, the right team of
professionals and a common vision,'' she says, ``it is possible to
get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1631EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3697 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS &LR;      03-21 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     GOP SUMMIT URGED TO REPAIR BUSH-McCAIN SPLIT  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Winner George W. Bush and loser John McCain are
imperiling Republicans' chances of retaking the White House unless
the rivals for the GOP presidential nomination quickly hold a
summit signaling unity, GOP pollster Frank Luntz warned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Luntz, saying the candidates' post-primary coolness threatens to
drive independents into the arms of Vice President Al Gore, said
both Bush, the two-term Texas governor, and McCain, the three-term
senator from Arizona, shared responsibility for the stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that McCain has not endorsed Bush up to this point is
a real problem for the Republicans,'' cautioned Luntz, the pollster
who helped Texas billionaire Ross Perot fashion a reform message in
1992 that enabled the Reform party candidate to capture 19 percent
of the popular vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of seeing a bridge built between McCain and Bush, you
see sniping going back and forth,'' added Luntz, who also helped
then-Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., draft the 1994 campaign manifesto
``Contract with America'' that helped the GOP win control of the
House and Senate for the first time in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Luntz spoke with reporters shortly before McCain returned to the
Senate floor for the first time since losing the GOP nomination to
Bush in hard-fought Republican presidential primaries that left a
bitter after-taste among many McCain supporters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain continued to withhold public endorsement of Bush's
candidacy and vowed to continue his populist quest for campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to do what I can, working with my congressional
colleagues, Republicans and Democrats, to help bring about the
changes to the practices and institutions of our democracy that
they want and deserve,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with CBS News broadcast later Tuesday, McCain
said that he would support the GOP presidential nominee but left
the scope of his support for Bush ambiguous, saying: ``Exactly how
that happens and under what circumstances _ and my degree of
enthusiasm _ obviously are questions that are yet to be resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Luntz, urging Bush and McCain to move quickly to public
rapprochement, said that without quickly forging unity between Bush
and McCain, the GOP could lose the White House for the third time
in three elections and relinquish control of the House after only
six years.
</P>
<P>
   With that much at stake, Luntz said, two former GOP party
leaders who are now lobbyists in Washington could serve as
intermediaries to overcome the GOP split _ former Republican
Chairman Haley Barbour, a Bush supporter, and former Rep. Vin
Weber, R-Minn., who worked for McCain's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Republican leader needs to look John McCain in the face
and say, `You will elect Al Gore if you don't make amends with
George Bush,''' Luntz said. ``And somebody needs to look George
Bush straight in the eye and say, `Stop fighting over Michigan and
find the big picture.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has criticized the McCain campaign's ``Catholic voter
alert'' telephone calls in the Michigan primary in which callers
reminded voters that Bush had addressed Bob Jones University in
Greenville, S.C., where the founder has expressed anti-Catholic
views.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and his campaign staff are ``playing with fire'' by
withholding public support for Bush, Luntz said. Continued
criticism of Bush inflames McCain supporters' ``fires of
hostility'' toward Bush, Luntz said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush is at fault, as well, Luntz said, for refusing to reach
out to McCain. Bush ought to ``put a bear hug around McCain'' and
travel with him across the nation to set the stage for the pair to
sweep into the GOP convention in Philadelphia in July as a unified
team determined to reclaim the White House for the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's reluctance to make concessions to highlight McCain's
reform agenda ``makes no sense,'' Luntz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not suggesting that you kow tow,'' Luntz said.
``Everything in this town is up for grabs in six months. And if the
stakes are that high why play around? Why not reach out, and agree
to disagree but at least stop sniping at each other in public?''
</P>
<P>
   Unless Bush and McCain move quickly, Luntz said, Gore can
strengthen his appeal to the independent minded voters who lost
their candidate when McCain stopped campaigning following setbacks
in the 13 GOP primary contests on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is busily trumpeting reform-style rhetoric in a naked bid
to win McCain supporters and could pick up independent voters by
selecting Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why Bush has to solidify these independent and
conservative Democrats now,'' Luntz added. ``Because if you throw
Lieberman into the mix, then the race is up for grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Luntz said the swing vote in the 2000 presidential election will
be the ``McCain middle'' _ voters who backed McCain in the GOP
primaries, Bill Clinton in 1996 and Ross Perot in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   To win the White House, Bush needs to win over two-thirds of the
bloc to boost the GOP share of the vote from 45 percent to 55
percent. But if Gore can capture the swing constituency as Clinton
did in 1996, Luntz said, ``Gore becomes president.''
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
