   FED-RATES (Washington) _ The Federal Reserve clamped down a bit
more on the economy and the stock market on Tuesday, raising its
benchmark interest rate by a quarter of a percentage point in an
attempt to prevent an outbreak of inflation. The move was no
surprise to economists and investors, who had heard repeated hints
over the last month from Alan Greenspan, the central bank's
chairman, that he intended to continue with his policy of raising
rates in small, steady steps until he sees signs that the
supercharged economy is throttling back. Stock prices were up on
the news, with the Dow Jones industrial average gaining about 200
points for the day. The Nasdaq index was up 90 points. By Richard
