<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3710 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-KITCHEN-WARES-ART-NYT     03-21 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-WARES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADE FOR CREPES, BUT IDEAL FOR EVERYTHING ELSE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Years ago, I was given a crepe pan. It was a
hand-me-down, and it looked like one. I've grown to love it. And
I've used it for lots of things _ sauteing mushrooms, searing duck,
simmering onions. About the only thing I haven't used it for is
crepes.
</P>
<P>
   It has an unusually elegant shape, a slender-handled, shallow
pan that lies like an open palm. It is a little thinner than a
regular saute pan. Made of dense steel, it holds heat very well and
like cast iron is great for browning. And when it is a seasoned
hand-me-down, it acts like a nonstick pan.
</P>
<P>
   The shallow cooking surface also traps less moisture in the pan,
which is why it is perfect for crepes. When the batter hits the
pan, it immediately begins cooking and puffing and developing a
scattering of tiny rings on the surface where air bubbles form.
</P>
<P>
   But those design features also make it ideal for cooking many
other foods. Though I've used my crepe pan liberally already, last
week I tested to see what limits the pan might have. There were
none.
</P>
<P>
   It worked beautifully with shellfish like scallops and rock
shrimp, which need to be seared with lightning speed, so that they
brown without overcooking. The pan's surface, seven and a half
inches across, is the perfect size for searing scallops for four
people. And the sides of the pan are in perfect proportion to the
tiny pieces of shellfish. Rather than steaming or stewing or simply
burning as they would in a high pot, they began browning
immediately and their juices vaporized instantly.
</P>
<P>
   The pan had the same effect on a thin fillet of shad. The fish
cooked halfway through and browned well in about one minute. When I
turned it, the gently sloping, shallow sides had another advantage.
It was much easier to get at the fillet with a spatula.
</P>
<P>
   This was especially helpful when I made a thin omelet. Turning
it took no effort, no wrestling with a hot, heavy pan. The crepe
pan feels like a badminton racket compared with many saute pans.
</P>
<P>
   The crepe pan really charmed me though, when I treated it like a
shallow gratin dish. Often, gratin recipes require you to begin on
the stove, then transfer the dish to the oven. This can be a
difficult maneuver with a small-handled dish, potholders and a hot
oven.
</P>
<P>
   Also, gratin dishes tend to be deep, and I don't always want
potato gratins or fruit crumbles that are more than an inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   In my crepe pan, I made a potato tart, slicing the potatoes as
thin as subway tokens and layering them in circles over the base of
the pan. I made just two layers and browned the bottom on the
stove, then finished the tart in the oven. Beginning over the stove
browned and crisped the potatoes. All I had to do was grab the long
handle to swing the pan into the oven.
</P>
<P>
   The real test came when the potatoes were done. I had to invert
the tart onto a plate so that the golden-browned surface, with its
carefully arranged layers of potato, would be on top. With a deep
pan or gratin dish, you must invert the pan and hope the tart stays
intact as it falls onto the plate. But with the crepe pan, the
potato tart simply shifted from pan to plate.
</P>
<P>
   A tarte Tatin benefited from this pan, too. Again, the handle
made it much easier to move around, and the depth of the pan
imposed a natural limit on the thickness of the tart. I had to cut
the apples smaller, but the resulting tart came out just as
beautifully caramelized as the classic.
</P>
<P>
   I then made a Provencal tart with eggplant, tomatoes and
zucchini. This time, I made just a single layer, alternating very
thin slices of the vegetables, and standing them up so they just
reached the rim of the pan. I wanted each serving to be like a thin
slice of terrine.
</P>
<P>
   I started the tart on the stove, then finished it in the oven.
The vegetables wilted and the liquid cooked off; they were like a
concentrate of their former selves. The tart was soft-looking and
browned on the edges like a rustic dish emerging from a
wood-burning oven. I could not think of a single reason to transfer
them to a serving dish. They seemed to belong in that old crepe pan
of mine.
</P>
<P>
   The crepe pan has a diminutive relative, the blini pan, which is
about four inches in diameter. It is also a gem. The pan happens to
be the perfect size for individual servings, and like the crepe
pan, this sturdy, wee pan can also become part of the presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Neither pan is a big investment. They are possibly the cheapest
pans in a cookware store. The De Buyer nine-inch steel crepe pan is
$14.98, the De Buyer four-inch steel blini pan is $6.98, both at
Zabar's, 2245 Broadway (80th Street); (212) 787-2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THIN POTATO TART &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   8 baby Yukon Gold potatoes (8 to 10 ounces), washed and sliced
thin
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Place a 9-inch crepe pan over
medium-low heat. Add 1 tablespoon butter and olive oil. When butter
foams, layer potatoes: place one slice in center of pan, then lay
slices overlapping one another, in circles, until you reach edge of
pan. Season generously with salt.
</P>
<P>
   2. On second layer, simply cover first layer in any arrangement
(you may not need all the slices). Season with salt and pepper. Dot
with remaining butter.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cook on stove top until potatoes are browned on bottom.
Adjust heat if necessary; potatoes should not stew or burn. Press
on potatoes with a spatula to compress lightly. Cover pan with foil
and transfer to oven. After 5 minutes remove foil. When potatoes
are cooked through and crisp on the edges, about 10 minutes more,
remove from oven.
</P>
<P>
   4. Carefully run a thin spatula around the edge of the pan to
loosen. Place a heatproof serving plate on top of pan. Holding the
pan with one hand and the plate with the other, carefully invert
pan. Lift pan slowly, peeking to see if any potatoes are stuck. If
so, gently loosen with spatula and place where they belong.
Sprinkle tart with salt and pepper, and serve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
