<SLUG> BC-CENSUS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CENSUS ADS ARE WORKING, POLL SHOWS
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The advertising campaign to promote the 2000 census
is working, according to a poll released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Census Director Kenneth Prewitt said the poll shows that more
than 90 percent of Americans were familiar with the process even
before census forms reached their homes, and three of four
Americans were ready to mail back their questionnaires.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Prewitt said the actual count is
proceeding well, with 7.3 million forms already processed. Forms
have been sent to 120 million households in the once-a-decade head
count.
</P>
<P>
   The visibility of the census took another leap Tuesday when it
became an issue in the presidential race. At an appearance in New
York, Vice President Al Gore criticized Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas for failing to support the use of population estimates to
bolster traditionally undercounted minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats support the practice of statistical sampling to
achieve what demographers believe is a more accurate census, while
Republicans oppose the statistical method. Many people believe that
most of the uncounted are poor and minority people, who tend to
vote for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The political debate will not cast a shadow over the Census
Bureau's efforts to convince Americans to participate, Prewitt said
in a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The national advertising campaign and grassroots effort to
promote the census is so strong ``that our message will swamp other
messages,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the Census Bureau has used paid advertising
to promote the head count, a $167 million campaign that includes
prime-time television.
</P>
<P>
   The poll results showed that 25 percent of Americans had seen a
census TV commercial at least 10 times, and 75 percent were aware
that the census determines the distribution of federal money to
state and local governments, a key theme of the ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted in early March by InterSurvey and
financed by a consortium of non-profit foundations. The final poll
results assessing the promotional campaign will be released in
early April.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN/USA Today poll by Gallup in late February showed that 74
percent of Americans were aware of the census and that 37 percent
had seen the television ads.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
