<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS TRANSFER PORTION OF WEST BANK TO PALESTINIAN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: a  map  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALHOUL, West Bank _ In this quiet town near Hebron, a newspaper
danced in the wind down the main street Tuesday morning, an elderly
man in a red-checked kaffiyeh rode his donkey and a few teenagers
whizzed along on bicycles. There was no air of expectation, no
feeling that a long-awaited moment had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, this was the day that Halhoul, after 33 years
under Israeli occupation, was to become fully Palestinian, give or
take a few acres. On the other, Halhoul had heard that promise
before, and the residents had decorated and un-decorated their
streets so many times that they were not going to hoist the flags
until the first Palestinian police jeep pulled into town.
</P>
<P>
   But indeed, Halhoul was ``liberated'' Tuesday, in the words of
the Palestinians. With about 20,000 residents, it was one of the
largest towns that Israel transferred to Palestinian control. After
a two-month delay that froze peace negotiations entirely, the
long-awaited handover of 6.1 percent of the West Bank _ or 132
square miles _ took place quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Later, peace talks resumed in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The transfer did not include Arab towns adjacent to Jerusalem,
for which the Palestinians had been pushing. It consisted of a
hodgepodge of areas throughout the West Bank, near Hebron, Nablus,
Jericho, Ramallah and Bethlehem. As of Tuesday, some 43 percent of
the West Bank, and most of the Palestinian population, lies under
Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   As in Halhoul, most of the transfer involved territory that has
been under mixed control and has now become fully Palestinian.
About 1 percent of the West Bank moved from total Israeli to total
Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Beituniya, a village near Ramallah, Palestinian police rode
into town firing their rifles in joy. But in Halhoul, the
Palestinian forces did not arrive, and no Israeli soldiers pulled
out, since they had been stationed at a regional command post. So
the big moment lacked a sense of reality. Municipal officials, who
were confused, could not even get any Palestinian Authority
officials on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of this moment _ 4:30 p.m. _ nobody has informed the
municipality what's happening,'' said Deputy Mayor Mohammed Mashal.
``On several occasions in the past, we prepared ourselves for
celebrations and _ nothing. This time, we are waiting for them to
arrive, hopefully tomorrow, in order to express our feelings of
liberation.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Halhoul, which connects to Hebron by a bridge, now creates a
land block of Palestinian territorial contiguity, one of the goals
of Yasir Arafat, the Palestinian leader. But the highway under the
bridge remains in Israeli hands, which means that a few acres of
precious land did not get transferred.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are a little disappointed,'' said Walid Aburayyan, 32.
``But, look, it will be a joy to have them out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear why the Palestinian Authority did not make a
concerted effort to plan celebrations for the handover, as they
have in the past. It is possible that Palestinian officials are
just too busy preparing for Pope John Paul II's day in Bethlehem on
Wednesday. It is possible that they did not want to call attention
to what they failed to get from the Israelis _ villages abutting
Jerusalem. It is possible that they were inept at milking the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Ala, the speaker of the Palestinian legislature, suggested
that they were focused on what lies ahead. ``What happened was an
achievement,'' he said. ``But we were supposed to get this land for
some time now. The most important thing is what comes next: the
third redeployment and the final status negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   There was limited protest from Jewish settlers Tuesday, some of
whom have complained that the withdrawal endangers them by placing
more responsibility for West Bank security on the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Ephraim Sneeh, Israel's deputy defense minister, has said that
he thinks their fear is unwarranted, especially given new and
effective cooperation between Israelis and Palestinians in cracking
down on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time that Arafat's guns were aimed, they were aimed
at Hamas terrorists,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
