<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3716 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX     03-21 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARRO TO SHARE ART, SKILLS AT EVENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The last time Jerry Diaz performed for Fort
Worth audiences, he had them standing in the aisles applauding his
skill with a horse and a rope. This weekend, his act will be more
subdued, but no less engaging.
</P>
<P>
   He is a featured speaker at Horse-O-Rama, a three-day equine
program offered by the Texas Agricultural Extension Service of
Tarrant County.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year we are targeting the Hispanic audience,'' said John
South of the extension service. ``We know there is a lot of
interest in horses among the Hispanic community.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz is a fourth generation ``charro'' _ a precursor to, and
faint relative of, the American rodeo cowboy. He is devoted to his
craft and a spokesman for thousands of Hispanic horsemen who enjoy
celebrating their past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional skills of the ``charro'' are very important to
me,'' Diaz explained on his last visit. ``I feel very lucky to be
able to take these skills and put them in front of so many
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz received standing ovations during his 1997 Stock Show
performances, something unusual for rodeo specialty acts. The
tributes were as much for his bearing as his talents. He looked
regal in his ``traje de charro,'' a snug, wheat-colored uniform
made of gabardine, and his broad-brimmed sombrero.
</P>
<P>
   He later explained to a San Antonio newspaper: ``It's about
being well-mounted so it looks like it's all one _ you, the horse,
the outfit and the heart. It's very romantic controlling the horse
and at the same time doing it with pride, honor and beauty. That's
the discipline of the horsemanship.''
</P>
<P>
   His great-grandfather was a horseman in Spain. His grandfather
settled in Mexico, in the state of Jalisco near Guadalajara, around
the turn of the century. He was a respected horseman but lost
everything in the Mexican Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz's father, Pepe, went to Mexico City to train horses for the
government, becoming the personal trainer for Mexico's president,
Lazaro Cardenas. In the late 1930s, Pepe Diaz crossed the border
into Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Diaz was born in 1960, northwest of San Antonio. By the
age of 2 or 3, he earned nickels and dimes by standing on the backs
of horses and singing. At 5, he made his first professional
performance at a local rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has devoted himself to the art and skills of the
``charro''. He was named 1998 Specialty Act of the Year by the
Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association; he performed at the
Olympics in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, he will forgo the arena and spotlight in exchange
for a classroom setting at the Will Rogers Equestrian Center where
he can tell his Fort Worth audience about the lariat _ ``la
reata.'' He'll explain the development of chaps (''chaparreras)''
and spurs ``(espuelas).'' He'll follow the evolution of the
``vaquero'', the ``charro'' and eventually the cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   Other speakers will discuss the development of the horse over
the past 2,000 years. ``We'll go back to the Roman Empire, then to
the New World,'' South said. ``We want this to be a real learning
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Other educational presentations include a cavalry re-enactment,
sessions on cutting, roping and dressage. There will also be an
all-breed horse show and classes on equine health and nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 14th annual Horse-O-Rama and the largest. South said
the program has grown along with horse ownership in Tarrant County.
It is estimated that horses represent an $80 million industry in
the county based just on keep and maintenance. Figuring in the
annual shows that come to Fort Worth _ the Stock Show, the NCHA
Futurity and the APHA World Show among them _ the economic impact
soars to more than $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   For more information and a complete Horse-O-Rama schedule, call
the agricultural extension service at (817) 884-1946.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
