<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3717 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-LUNTZ22-COX     03-21 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-LUNTZ22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH SHOULD COURT McCAIN, GOP POLLSTER SAYS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After analyzing research from three Republican
primary states, Republican pollster Frank Luntz offered some
unsolicited advice Tuesday to Gov. George W. Bush: Wrap John McCain
in a ``bear hug'' and don't let go.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush does not win two-thirds of the McCain vote in the
general election, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee
will lose the White House to Vice President Al Gore, Luntz warned.
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast with reporters, Luntz reviewed his findings from
focus groups of McCain voters in New Hampshire, South Carolina and
New York, concluding that these independent-minded voters are the
``swing vote'' in this year's presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   Bush can't afford to wait until the GOP convention in late July
to make peace with McCain, Luntz said. ``Bush needs to bear-hug
McCain now and take him with him so that McCain and Bush share the
platform and speak out together.''
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain, a veteran senator from Arizona, has made it
clear he is not interested in being the Texas governor's running
mate, Luntz said Bush should try to convince him to join the
Republican ticket.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Gore is already reaching out to McCain voters the
way President Clinton did to Ross Perot voters in 1992. But the
Bush camp is criticizing McCain the way Republican Party leaders
did Perot in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``History is repeating itself,'' said Luntz, who was a pollster
for Perot before the Texas billionaire halted his independent White
House bid in 1992. Perot eventually re-entered the 1992 race, but
by then, much of the enthusiasm for Perot's candidacy had shifted
to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Luntz said he has been puzzled by Bush's unwillingness to make
any overtures to McCain. He compared Bush's attitude to the
disastrous position taken by former House Speaker Newt Gingrich
following the Republican takeover of Congress in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to see an analogy? Gingrich '94,'' said Luntz, the
pollster behind Gingrich's ``Contract With America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The man destroyed himself hours out of the box by talking
about how irrelevant Bill Clinton was, how the Republicans now ran
Washington and basically flexing his political muscle to the point
of offending the American people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Luntz suggested that such GOP notables as former party chairman
Haley Barbour and former congressman Vin Weber meet privately with
Bush and McCain to make peace within the party.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
