<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3722 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NAZIYEARS-BOOK-REVIEW     03-21 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAZIYEARS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I WILL BEAR WITNESS': A VICTIM'S SANG-FROID IN COLD-BLOODED
TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one of the first entries of his diaries of 1942 to 1945,
Victor Klemperer tells of riding the tram in Dresden and being told
by a young man _ ``very clean-cut face, cold gray eyes'' _ to get
off at the next stop. He is taken to the Gestapo, where he is
humiliated and insulted and told to keep off the tram from now on,
or else. Klemperer's last entry, three and a half years and a
lifetime of anguish later, is a simple declarative sentence about
his return on foot to the house that he and his wife, Eva, had
bought outside Dresden before the war broke out.
</P>
<P>
   In between are the years of terror and deprivation, the daily
torment of survival as a Jew in Nazi Germany. ``I Will Bear
Witness,'' Volume II, translated and abridged by Martin Chalmers,
is an even more striking, more emotionally vivid account of the
Nazi years than Volume I, which covered the years 1933 to 1941.
</P>
<P>
   The first volume, published in the United States in 1998, was a
kind of grim prelude, one in which Klemperer, a thoroughly
assimilated, patriotic German Jew who taught Romance languages at
the Dresden Technical University, described the slow, terrifying
collapse of his country into barbarism. This second volume treats
the worst years of the Nazi era: the mass deportations of Jews, the
stints of forced labor, the near-starvation, the Allied bombings,
the alternating stages of hope and depression as the German war
effort weakened and recovered over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the Klemperer diaries stand as an unparalleled
and intimate record from the innards of the beast. What makes them
unparalleled is the thunderous accumulation of the small details
that escape standard historical accounts _ the psychology of
wearing the yellow star, the effort to face Gestapo interrogations
with courage, the anti-Semitic taunts of children on the street,
the ban on having clothes washed in ``Aryan'' laundries. Then, at
the very end, comes what is perhaps the most remarkable part in
this monumental two-volume work. It is Klemperer's account of the
phantasmagorical few weeks before and after the German surrender,
when he and his wife, in a grim, necessary bid to survive,
underwent a harrowing Odyssean journey through the physical and
spiritual wreckage of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Klemperer was born in Landsberg an der Warthe, now Gorzow
Wielkopolski in Poland, in 1881, the son of a rabbi who soon took
his family to Berlin. He studied philosophy, philology and Romance
languages in Munich, Geneva, Paris and Berlin and embarked on an
academic career, the early highlight of which was a two-volume
study of Montesquieu. He married a non-Jew and became a Protestant,
which is what gave him the ``privileged'' status that saved his
life during the war.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Klemperer remained in Dresden, which became part
of East Germany, and resumed his career as a professor and a
scholar. He died in Dresden in 1960. His diaries, which were at one
time believed lost, were published in Germany in 1996, to enormous
public interest and acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the events and themes crowded into this second volume
illustrate the absurdist deformations that the Nazi regime imposed
on those in Germany who clung to a shred of decency. ``Don't say
that we treated you well,'' his Aryan anti-Nazi supervisor warns
him during the winter when Klemperer, 60 years old and suffering
from angina pectoris, is made to shovel snow for eight or nine
hours a day. ``Rather say we were bad; otherwise we'll be in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, Klemperer notes with a kind of resigned outrage that
Jews have been banned from buying flowers. The Jews are prohibited
from entering the railway station. They are not allowed to use
their bicycles to make visits on Sundays. ``I only go out on the
street if it is absolutely necessary,'' Klemperer writes in May
1942.
</P>
<P>
   The diaries record the full range of human responses to
circumstances of great duress, including acts of kindness by
ordinary Germans that make Klemperer reject the view, common among
his friends, that the entire country and culture is anti-Semitic.
In 1942, Klemperer is approached by two gray-haired women on the
street. They shake his hand. ``You know why,'' one of them says,
and rushes off. A friend named Frau Pick in 1943 is summoned to the
Gestapo, which she knows means almost certain deportation. ``She
had had a good life, and now it was over,'' she says calmly, and
then kills herself.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1943, Klemperer is given a cigarette packet full of
teeth so that one can be used to replace a missing one for his
wife. ``Secret teeth from the Jewish cemetery,'' he writes. ``It
sounds as gruesome as a fairy tale, but it is crazy enough even in
reality.'' Then the ``Aryan'' trustee of his weekend house in the
Dresden suburbs, a man named Richter, offers to hide Klemperer and
his wife if the order comes for him to be deported. When Richter
himself is arrested, he instructs his secretary to give Klemperer
some money. ``That in his desperate situation the man has thought
of us!'' Klemperer exclaims.
</P>
<P>
   Klemperer is continually astonished at the amazing reach of
Germany's anti-Semitic paranoia, to the point that when the Allied
invasion in Normandy takes place, the headline in the Dresdener
Zeitung is ``Jews in Normandy.'' Klemperer takes hope from the
landing and in Soviet advances on the Eastern front, but at the
same time he records the slow disappearance of Dresden's remaining
Jews. He does what amounts to slave labor in a factory, and one day
without warning three Jewish men are taken out and, it is reported,
shot. ``A moment ago I was in constant contact with these three
people, and now they are buried. And tomorrow my fate may be the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1945, with the war almost over, Dresden was firebombed by the
Allies with devastating results, but for Klemperer, whose
description of the attack is densely vivid, it is a reprieve. The
next day it appeared that the ``privileged'' Jews were going to be
deported. But the chaos of the bombing saved him, though it also
sent him and Eva on a desperate journey from town to town that
didn't end until several weeks after the German surrender.
</P>
<P>
   There is an enormous amount to read in this volume, but it is
difficult to put down. Not least of its elements is Klemperer's own
expressed awareness that, if the diary were to be discovered in one
of the many routine police searches that were carried out, it would
surely mean his death. ``But I shall go on writing,'' Klemperer
says on May 27, 1942. ``That is my heroism. I will bear witness,
precise witness.''
</P>
<P>
   Not just witness, but precise witness, a German trait. And in
this instance, rare, illuminating and priceless.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `I WILL BEAR WITNESS
</P>
<P>
   A Diary of the Nazi Years, 1942-1945'
</P>
<P>
   By Victor Klemperer
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. Translated and with a preface by Martin Chalmers.
556 pages. Random House. $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds., fyi, a retrospective on the career of Bruce Chatwin, the
subject of a new biography by Nicholas Shakespeare, is available
from The New York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com/books) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
