<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3724 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SOUR-ORANGE-ART-NYT &LR;      03-21 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUR-ORANGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAGICAL MYSTERY ORANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By MATT LEE and TED LEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the surface, it is not one of nature's most
beautiful creations: a bumpy, blotchy thick skin encasing a pale,
seedy yellow pulp.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of a sour orange is revealed in the kitchen, where it
is every bit as appealing as a lemon or a lime, but with a spicy,
flowery fragrance like no other citrus. It can adapt to a wide
range of cuisines, melding savory and sweet flavors and perking
them up with an exotic, fruity tang.
</P>
<P>
   At Chicama in the Flatiron district in Manhattan, Douglas
Rodriguez uses sour orange juice in traditional Ecuadorean ceviches
and for marinating suckling pig. Marc Murphy pairs Seville orange
chutney with vanilla custard at La Fourchette on the Upper East
Side. And at Eight Mile Creek in SoHo, Ken Addington bathes tuna in
sour orange juice and fish sauce before searing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a greener, wilder, almost salty citrus flavor,''
Addington said.
</P>
<P>
   While it may be new to New York chefs, the sour orange has been
used for generations in Latin America and the Caribbean in mojo,
the thin cooking sauce of sour orange juice, oil and garlic that is
prized for marinating stewed pork but also makes its way into
dishes from salad dressings to ceviches.
</P>
<P>
   The sour orange, originally native to Asia, is now grown in the
tropics and along the Gulf Coast, where it is considered wild and
almost valueless _ a nuisance when it unloads its bounty on the
lawn. Along the Mediterranean, where its cousin the Seville orange
grows, the rind is used in marmalades and candies.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, sour oranges can be found for about three for $1 at
some supermarkets and bodegas (they're often labeled ``naranja
agria''). Specialty markets like Gourmet Garage, Agata and
Valentina and Grace's Marketplace also carry them.
</P>
<P>
   We first bought sour oranges at a C-Town on Upper Broadway, and
they quickly became a magical presence in our kitchen, inspiring
weeks of experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   We went substitution-wild, replacing the lemon in our favorite
recipes with sour orange. Dressing a roast chicken with sour orange
gave the bird a subtle, fruity lift. A sour orange hollandaise we
made with two teaspoons of the juice had a more pronounced orange
flavor, especially when we tossed in a pinch of the zest.
</P>
<P>
   Our first attempt to revitalize the Key lime pie was a triumph.
Our second attempt was even better, with a tablespoon of navel
orange zest added for appearance's sake. Sour orange zest, which
contains most of the aromatic oils, with notes of gardenia blossoms
and honey, is an unfortunate yellow-gray color.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by a bottled sour orange sauce, we infused
fresh-squeezed sour orange juice with fresh herbs and used the
liquid as we do balsamic vinegar, to deglaze pans and in salad
dressings. The mixtures are fun to concoct, and we discovered that
grassy, floral herbs like oregano, cilantro, thyme, and tarragon
best complement the juice.
</P>
<P>
   Now we keep three strengths on hand. The spiciest, made from
cilantro, slices of raw onion, garlic and serrano chile, makes a
knockout mojo. The next, a supercharged infusion of tarragon, can
be sprinkled over stewed greens like kale and chard for an elegant
top note. A third version, made with thyme and garlic, lends itself
to whisking with olive oil for a tropical vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   And the drinks! Perhaps the most satisfying way to experience
the sour orange _ the way that best reveals its distinction from a
lemon or a lime _ is in a cocktail. A pony of sour orange juice
dresses down a same-old gin and tonic.
</P>
<P>
   A mojito made with sour orange juice instead of lime is
transformed. And that mojito, modified into sour orange mojito
sorbet, has become our new favorite dessert, one that conjures warm
summer breezes even if it's still chilly outdoors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOUR ORANGE PIE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: About 1 hour, plus 2 hours' freezing  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the crust: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups fine graham cracker crumbs
</P>
<P>
   \ cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   } cup butter, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   Butter for greasing pie pan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the filling: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 14-ounce can sweetened condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   5 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   { cup plus 1 tablespoon strained sour orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sour orange zest
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons sweet orange zest
</P>
<P>
   1 pint whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   Mint sprigs for garnish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a bowl, combine cracker
crumbs and sugar; add melted butter and mix thoroughly. Grease the
bottom of an 8-inch pie pan and press mixture firmly into it,
creating an even layer on bottom and sides. Bake 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. As crust bakes, whisk condensed milk, cream and yolks
together in a nonreactive bowl. Mix in sour orange juice and both
zests, reserving { tablespoon sweet zest.
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove crust from oven, set on a rack and cool 10 minutes.
Reduce oven temperature to 325. Stir pie filling once to distribute
zest, then pour into crust.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bake pie 14 minutes or until filling is set. Cool half an
hour before placing in freezer for at least two hours. Just before
serving, whip cream; spread on top, sprinkle with remaining zest
and garnish with mint.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPICY SOUR ORANGE SAUCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5 sprigs cilantro
</P>
<P>
   5 sprigs mint
</P>
<P>
   1 quart sour orange juice, strained
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, smashed
</P>
<P>
   1 serrano chile, roasted, peeled, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   1 chipotle pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 slice large yellow onion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place cilantro and mint on a cutting board and roll a rolling
pin over them once, to slightly bruise them and release their oils.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pour juice into a quart Mason jar. Add sprigs and remaining
ingredients. Steep two days in the refrigerator before using as a
marinade for pork, chicken or fish. Sauce keeps two weeks,
refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About a quart.
</P>
<P>
   Variations: Add 4 sprigs of tarragon to a quart of strained sour
orange juice. Or add 2 smashed cloves of garlic and 4 sprigs of
thyme to a quart of strained juice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOUR ORANGE MOJITO SORBET &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes plus 3 hours' chilling and freezing &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces dark rum
</P>
<P>
   { cup mint, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1} cup fresh sour orange juice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small saucepan over a low flame, heat rum slowly for
several minutes to evaporate some of the alcohol. Do not boil.
</P>
<P>
   2. Using a mortar and pestle, mix mint with sugar until it is a
paste. In a medium bowl, combine mint mixture with juice, 1\ cups
water and the rum. Cover and chill three hours. Pour mixture into
ice cream maker and freeze according to manufacturer's
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
