<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3728 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-YOUCANSAY-REVIEW-N     03-21 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-YOUCANSAY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`YOU CAN'T SAY THAT!: SPEAK FREELY BUT NOT ABOUT THOSE THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Broadcast notes appear at end of review. Time, channel
are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thursday night, John Stossel, ABC's scourge of the
left, goes after what he considers constraints on free speech in
the claimed interests of civility. ``You Can't Say That!'' wanders
a bit with asides on Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's attempts to stop
marches and exhibits by groups he finds offensive, on efforts in
Congress to outlaw flag burning and on mainstream television's
restrictions on profanity, before it gets down to Stossel's real
subject: current tendencies on the once-permissive left to crack
down on what it deems racism or sexism.
</P>
<P>
   Stossel recalls a celebrated incident in which Miller beer fired
an employee for telling a female colleague a joke he had heard on
``Seinfeld,'' a show that the company sponsored. The woman
complained that she was offended. The point here is that
corporations are so frightened of being sued for sexual harassment
that they bow to charges, however slight or unsubstantiated.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Miller explains, ``Once you've stepped over the
line that the other person believes is offensive, you have to
acknowledge it and back off.'' Otherwise, since offensiveness is
often treated by juries as being in the eye of the beholder, the
company risks having to pay substantial damages.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges have caved in, too, says Stossel. He tells of an
English professor at the State University of New York who was fired
for allowing rude words to be used in a writing exercise. A law
teacher at the University of California at Los Angeles asserts that
sexual harassment laws are forcing employers to become speech
police: ``These are the jokes you can't tell, these are the
opinions you can't express, these are the words you can't use.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview that sounds like the stuff of a Nichols and May
routine, Stossel talks with a company consultant who earns her fees
giving employees ``sensitivity training,'' which she says means
``Don't talk about body parts, don't give people sexual attention
of any kind, whether you think they want it or not.'' Stossel
comments, ``People now compete to see who can be most offended,''
adding that the policy at many schools is ``to ban words that the
`sensitive' would consider offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   On the political front, Ward Connerly, a conservative campaigner
against racial preferences, tells of repeatedly being shouted down
by university audiences. In answer to Stossel's question ``Who gave
you that power to decide for everybody?,'' a student at Columbia
University says, ``I'm taking the power by going out and
protesting: `Racist, get off my campus!'''
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of making his case, Stossel sometimes loads it.
But this time out he forces viewers to ponder whether tolerance for
certain unpopular views, be it in offices or on campuses, is
becoming an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `YOU CAN'T SAY THAT! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's Happening to Free Speech With John Stossel'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 10 p.m. ET, Thursday on ABC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A production of ABC News. Victor Neufeld, executive producer;
Roger Goodman, director; Martin Phillips, senior producer; Brian
Ellis and Mark Golden, producers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1715EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3730 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-THENCAMEYOU-REVIEW     03-21 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-THENCAMEYOU-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THEN CAME YOU': ROOM SERVICE? ONE ROMANCE, PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review) 
(jt) 
 By ANITA GATES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The best television series, it seems, come from
somebody's personal experience or vision. Like Linwood Boomer's
growing up as the smart one in a rowdy four-boy household, which
turned into ``Malcolm in the Middle.'' Or whatever it is that
inspired Chris Carter to create ``The X-Files,'' about FBI agents,
conspiracies and extraterrestrials.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, viewers of the premiere of ABC's ``Then Came
You'' will see a personal experience of Betsy Thomas, a creator and
a co-executive producer of the show. After her divorce, Thomas
moved into the Chateau Marmont in Los Angeles and fell in love with
her room service waiter. And that's exactly what happens to the
show's heroine, Billie (Susan Floyd), a book editor with great
hair. This, however, seems to be a case of life at its most
sitcomish to begin with. When it's officially turned into comedy,
the fact that it's real doesn't make it original.
</P>
<P>
   In the first episode, Billie, who is 33, is in her hotel room
celebrating her coming divorce. Just as her best female friend and
her best gay male friend are suggesting friends of theirs she
should go out with, room service arrives in the person of Aidan
(Thomas Newton). Banter begins. Billie learns that both she and
Aidan went to Northwestern. ``When did you graduate?'' she asks. He
answers, ``May.''
</P>
<P>
   Their first date happens almost by accident. That's the kind of
man she needs, Billie says to her friends, laughing. ``He's funny.
He's educated. He brings me things.'' And, Aidan quickly adds, ``He
gets off at midnight.'' Then there's the equivalent of the
happy-dating montage, this one to establish that the couple are
having, as another character later summarizes, ``seven days of
mind-bending sex.'' The rest is equally obvious. Billie announces
that she's a changed woman. (``Until I met you, I was the kind of
person who wouldn't go swimming until 30 minutes after I ate.'')
She worries that he can't afford to take her to dinner, and he's
offended. Her soon-to-be-ex-husband ridicules the relationship.
(``Is that what you meant when you said you wanted children?'')
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad that Thomas and her co-creator, Jeff Strauss, have
made so many predictable choices. And that Floyd, while attractive
and personable, is so unconvincing as a woman fresh from a loveless
marriage who needs an awakening. The series also has a laugh track
that goes wild over lines like ``Wow, that was _ thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, Newton has considerable charm. And there is a
lot of real humor to be mined from the older-woman-younger-man
relationship. When Billie explains that she doesn't want to turn
into Robinson, Aidan says _ you guessed it _ ``Who?''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THEN CAME YOU'
</P>
<P>
   ABC, Wednesday night at 8:30 ET.
</P>
<P>
   A production of Jeff Strauss Productions in association with
Twentieth Century Fox Television. Jeff Strauss, executive producer;
Betsy Thomas and Barton Dean, co-executive producers; Jay Kleckner,
producer.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Susan Floyd (Billie), Thomas Newton (Aidan), Miriam Shor
(Cheryl), Desmond Askew (Ed) and Colin Ferguson (Lewis). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1718EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3738 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WIRED-CITY-$ADV26-COX     03-21 1637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRED-CITY-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WIRED COMMUNITY USES NETWORK TO BRING NEIGHBORS TOGETHER
 &HT;    980&AMP;adds. With WIRED-FEATURES. Moving in (a) national, (l)
lifestyle and (f) financial categories for release Sunday, March
26.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ A stay-at-home mom, Kathy Verschoor sits
down daily at the family computer to stay in touch with her
toddler's play group, scan upcoming events at the nearby community
center and keep up on neighborhood concerns.
</P>
<P>
   But Verschoor is no nerd. She knew little about computers and
the Internet until she and her husband, Scott, moved last year to
DC Ranch, a high-tech housing development taking shape in the
desert foothills on the northern fringes of Phoenix's urban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a tool, and it helps people get to know each
other quicker and better,'' said Verschoor.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the personal-computing boom, real-estate developers and
architects across the country are collaborating on new
neighborhoods that feature high-speed connections marrying the
Internet, television and telephone services.
</P>
<P>
   DC Ranch, with 200 homes occupied and another 6,000 slated for
construction, has made high-speed Internet connections a standard
feature of the houses it sells. Its quiet, cactus-studded streets
and upscale homes are wired with fiber optics and coaxial cable to
provide each household with at least two high-speed, ready-to-surf
Internet connections, six e-mail addresses, and digital TV and
telephones _ all for $50 a month.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not intended as an exclusive haven for the pocket
protector crowd. The Arizona developers, DMB Associates, have taken
their technology a step further by encouraging the suburbanites to
use their computers to build personal relationships.
</P>
<P>
   RanchNet, a password-protected internal community network, lets
residents find neighbors with common hobbies, organize Scout
meetings, sound off about neighborhood security and reserve tennis
courts at the community center. Soon, they'll also be able to
download their children's homework assignments, make medical
appointments, and order groceries on line.
</P>
<P>
   Few, if any, American communities will offer residents more
computerized power to organize their lives and save time.
</P>
<P>
   Will the spread of such technology turn America into a wired
wasteland?
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by Stanford University researchers warned that
people who use the Internet as little as five hours a week were
less likely to have face-to-face contact with friends and family,
and were at risk of shutting themselves off from society.
</P>
<P>
   DC Ranch residents challenge that notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in a neighborhood where you knew all your neighbors.
But that was the '50s and '60s. Well, this is the same,'' said
Verschoor, 41. ``I want to be known to my neighbors, and the system
helps us do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Both DC Ranch and Celebration, a similar trail-blazing community
developed by Disney near Orlando, try to integrate the Internet
into a movement that architects and planners have dubbed New
Urbanism or simply TND _ traditional neighborhood design. The goal
is to achieve a friendly community of small neighborhoods linked by
front porches, sidewalks, bike paths and small parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes a community-building tool that allows neighbors to
build relationships more quickly,'' said Brent Herrington,
community manager of DC Ranch, who came to the Arizona project from
Celebration. ``This is intended to be a catalyst to get people out
of the house, not simply cocooning in front of the computer
screen.''
</P>
<P>
   While DC Ranch is aimed partly at telecommuters, more residents
are mere casual users of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   On the private RanchNet intranet, e-mail addresses consist of
first name, followed by a dot, then last name.
</P>
<P>
   An online community directory lets families publish their names,
children's ages, hobbies and other biographical information. Since
every resident is a newcomer, the intention is to encourage
contacts for activities beyond the computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   Among some of the items and topics posted recently on the
community's chat site: ``Upset about pool closing ... Need a dog
sitter ...Spring baseball tickets for sale ...Pokemon trading card
party.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Verschoors' 2-year-old daughter Sarah eventually heads
off to the new public elementary school being built at the edge of
DC Ranch, they will be able to check her grades on line and
download her homework. Already there's a parents' group meeting
regularly at the community center and keeping in touch through
RanchNet.
</P>
<P>
   The high-speed connections and community system have changed the
way telecommuters Ed and Judy Bott work and play.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, in their 40s and childless, moved to DC Ranch last
year from Redmond, Wash., home of Microsoft Corp. He is an author
of books on computers and software. She is a public-relations
consultant to several Silicon Valley dot-com companies. They were
lured by the Arizona sunshine and the ability to seamlessly work
via the Net with clients hundreds or thousands of miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology was a deal-breaker for us. If it didn't have
high-speed connections, we weren't interested,'' Ed Bott said of
their decision to buy at DC Ranch. ``Here, we're ahead of the
curve, and that's where we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But the technology of DC Ranch offered an unexpected dividend.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our first three months in this community we met more
neighbors than we did in three years in Redmond,'' he said. They
use RanchNet to keep in touch with the community's exercise club
and to sign up for nature walks into the nearby desert mountains.
</P>
<P>
   With one house and two fast Internet connections, they sometimes
find themselves e-mailing one another from their home offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really geeky,'' admitted Judy Bott. ``As crazy as it
sounds, because we live in the same house sending e-mails is really
polite, because when you're both working you don't want to
interrupt the other by casually dropping in.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Only a tiny fraction of American homes have high-speed Internet
connections. At the end of 1999, 36 million of the more than 102
million U.S. households had Internet connections, but only about
1.35 million were high-speed coaxial cable connections and fewer
than 600,000 were the upgraded phone lines known as DSL, according
to International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers are rising rapidly, though. The concept of
pre-wired high-speed access is being replicated across the country,
from Atlanta's hot condominium market to apartment building
renovations in New York to golf communities in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it has become routine. We ask every client, 'Do you want
this wired?' `` said Eric Seugling, project manager for Brock Green
Architects and Planners in Atlanta, which is working on two wired
condo projects, the 130-unit Studio Plex on Auburn and the 120-unit
New Loft condominiums in Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   North of Austin, Texas, the Avery Ranch master planned community
has signed a deal with ClearWorks.net to provide digital Internet,
video and telephone services to 2,000 single-family homes and 2,000
multi-family units.
</P>
<P>
   At DC Ranch, the telephone, TV and Internet services are
supplied by US West. The services are bundled, meaning one monthly
bill and unique features. For instance, the telephone's caller ID
system can be set to display on a TV or computer screen. The
integration also means that houses can be automated. Security
systems, climate control, lights and music can be controlled by a
computer or a switch panel on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Such houses are not cheap. Prices start at just under $300,000
and extend beyond $1 million for a custom-built home on an adjacent
golf course.
</P>
<P>
   One developer in Florida is planning a similar Internet
community with more affordable homes in the range of $113,000 to
$170,000. Houses at the development near Port St. Lucie, called St.
James Golf Club, will be interconnected like the ones at DC Ranch
and Celebration, said developer Paul Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a basic yearning to return to classic neighborhoods,
and that is what fuels these designs,'' said Rhodes. ``Do people
want it? We're going to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   So far, the experiment has worked at DC Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   For Scott Verschoor, a business consultant whose office is a
45-minute commute to downtown Phoenix, the high-speed Internet
connection from home often saves him a long drive when work
requires his attention on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   As a tool, the community's Web site is sometimes as simple as
this: ``You know, you forget people's names and you don't want to
be rude,'' he says. ``Sometimes we go in just to find out the names
of the neighbors we met a few weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Architects and developers like the potentially lucrative idea of
making fast Internet connections as integral to the family home as
the telephone and cable TV are today. New homes are being designed
using standards once reserved for commercial office buildings, with
features like advanced and easily upgradable wiring and reinforced
roofs to accommodate satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developers are simply awakening to what telecommunications and
retail companies have realized at every phase of the Internet's
evolution _ that people simply like to communicate with each
other,'' said Stephen Doheny-Farina, author of the 1997 book ``The
Wired Neighborhood'' and a professor of technical communications at
Clarkson University in Potsdam, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they are selling are people-to-people connections,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
