polite, because when you're both working you don't want to
interrupt the other by casually dropping in.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Only a tiny fraction of American homes have high-speed Internet
connections. At the end of 1999, 36 million of the more than 102
million U.S. households had Internet connections, but only about
1.35 million were high-speed coaxial cable connections and fewer
than 600,000 were the upgraded phone lines known as DSL, according
to International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers are rising rapidly, though. The concept of
pre-wired high-speed access is being replicated across the country,
from Atlanta's hot condominium market to apartment building
renovations in New York to golf communities in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it has become routine. We ask every client, 'Do you want
this wired?' `` said Eric Seugling, project manager for Brock Green
Architects and Planners in Atlanta, which is working on two wired
condo projects, the 130-unit Studio Plex on Auburn and the 120-unit
New Loft condominiums in Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   North of Austin, Texas, the Avery Ranch master planned community
has signed a deal with ClearWorks.net to provide digital Internet,
video and telephone services to 2,000 single-family homes and 2,000
multi-family units.
</P>
<P>
   At DC Ranch, the telephone, TV and Internet services are
supplied by US West. The services are bundled, meaning one monthly
bill and unique features. For instance, the telephone's caller ID
system can be set to display on a TV or computer screen. The
integration also means that houses can be automated. Security
systems, climate control, lights and music can be controlled by a
computer or a switch panel on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Such houses are not cheap. Prices start at just under $300,000
and extend beyond $1 million for a custom-built home on an adjacent
golf course.
</P>
<P>
   One developer in Florida is planning a similar Internet
community with more affordable homes in the range of $113,000 to
$170,000. Houses at the development near Port St. Lucie, called St.
James Golf Club, will be interconnected like the ones at DC Ranch
and Celebration, said developer Paul Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a basic yearning to return to classic neighborhoods,
and that is what fuels these designs,'' said Rhodes. ``Do people
want it? We're going to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   So far, the experiment has worked at DC Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   For Scott Verschoor, a business consultant whose office is a
45-minute commute to downtown Phoenix, the high-speed Internet
connection from home often saves him a long drive when work
requires his attention on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   As a tool, the community's Web site is sometimes as simple as
this: ``You know, you forget people's names and you don't want to
be rude,'' he says. ``Sometimes we go in just to find out the names
of the neighbors we met a few weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Architects and developers like the potentially lucrative idea of
making fast Internet connections as integral to the family home as
the telephone and cable TV are today. New homes are being designed
using standards once reserved for commercial office buildings, with
features like advanced and easily upgradable wiring and reinforced
roofs to accommodate satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developers are simply awakening to what telecommunications and
retail companies have realized at every phase of the Internet's
evolution _ that people simply like to communicate with each
other,'' said Stephen Doheny-Farina, author of the 1997 book ``The
Wired Neighborhood'' and a professor of technical communications at
Clarkson University in Potsdam, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they are selling are people-to-people connections,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
