<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3743 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER22-COX     03-21 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: New leader in wallet weight
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   His record-shattering treasury drained by his campaign's $2
million-a-week advertising binge, George W. Bush for the first time
trails Democratic rival Al Gore in available campaign cash. Bush's
latest spending report shows he began March with just $7.5 million
_ one-tenth of the $73.9 million war chest he had amassed while
vanquishing a tougher-than-expected Arizona Sen. John McCain. In
contrast, Gore's spending slowed over the last two months along
with the waning threat from Bill Bradley. Gore, according to his
aides, had $4.1 million in the bank on March 1 and expects to
receive $7.3 million in federal matching funds in the next few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   POLLS OPEN, BUT DO VOTERS CARE?
</P>
<P>
   Illinois voters were going to the polls Tuesday for the mostly
irrelevant Democratic presidential primary. But with the
presidential nominations largely decided and no interesting
statewide contests on the ballot, a low turnout was expected. But
both Al Gore and George W. Bush will be watching for any indication
of how the crucial battleground state will swing in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   BACK TO HIS SENATE JOB
</P>
<P>
   John McCain made a low-key return to the Senate floor Tuesday,
and in his first Senate speech since suspending his presidential
bid earlier this month, thanked his supporters and promised to
press ahead on the reform issues he advocated. He chose to take on
the Clinton administration's Kosovo policy, but didn't mention his
signature issue: campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   TRYING TO EXPAND THE BASE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is appealing to John McCain's backers and reaching out
to Bill Bradley's top aides for support in November. ``John McCain
was right, and George W. Bush was wrong,'' Gore told a college
crowd in Springfield, Ill. After another campaign stop and
fund-raising luncheon Tuesday in New York, Gore was headed to New
Jersey, Bradley's home state. Gore planned to meet at a Bergen
County restaurant with Bradley campaign chairman Doug Berman and
other area Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   HIDE AND GO SEEK
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore criticized George W. Bush on Tuesday for not supporting
a census that would include estimates of undercounted populations.
``I want to say to Governor Bush, if you really believe that every
American counts, it's time to stand up to the operatives in your
own party and support a census that counts every American,'' Gore
said. Democrats want the U.S. Census Bureau to use sampling to
reach its final population count. The Republican Party is opposed
to sampling. Some analysts say Republicans believe undercounted
minorities would boost Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   CHARACTER ISSUE AGAINST CLINTONS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush will use the revelations of the Democrats' 1996
campaign financing strategy to raise questions about Al Gore's
character, and Rudy Giuliani will follow the same road in his New
York Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton, the Boston Globe
reported Tuesday. The Globe quoted Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer as
saying that Bush wanted to run an issues-oriented campaign, but a
president could not achieve his goals ``if you don't first restore
honor and integrity to the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   CONSERVATIVE PARTY DISTANCING
</P>
<P>
   In a move that could shake up New York's Senate race, the
powerful leader of the state Conservative Party said Tuesday he is
on the verge of backing a candidate other than Rudy Giuliani.
Giuliani is a Republican, and no GOP candidate has won statewide
office in the state in more than a quarter-century without
Conservative Party backing. Conservative Party Chairman Michael
Long refused to identify his possible alternative Senate candidate,
other than to say ``people will recognize the name.'' Long has
insisted that Giuliani, an abortion rights supporter, back a ban on
what critics call ``partial-birth abortion.'' Giuliani has refused
to do that.
</P>
<P>
   IF DRIVERS , WHY NOT . . .
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani, under attack from Senate rival Hillary Rodham
Clinton for taking money from gun interests, says he favors a
sweeping licensing system for firearm owners. At a community forum
in upstate in Watertown, one resident reminded the New York City
mayor that many people in the region firmly believe in the
constitutional right to bear arms. Said Giuliani: ``I do not think
the government should cut off the right to bear arms.''
Nonetheless, he said his position for many years has been that just
as a motorist must have a license, gun owners should be required to
have one as well.
</P>
<P>
   DO AS YOGI SAID
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader, the Green Party candidate for president, said
for-profit HMOs are ``destabilizing themselves by their own greed''
and that consumers, nurses and doctors should take advantage of
looming changes in the medical system to force creation of
universal health care. ``As Yogi Berra said, `When you reach a fork
in the road, take it,' '' he told the California Nurses
Association. He said he doubts Al Gore or George W. Bush would push
for ``sound medical plans for every American.''
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING IS AMMO FOR HILLARY
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton has been reluctant to criticize Rudy
Giuliani in their New York Senate race. Until recently, she rarely
even mentioned him by name. But she is now criticizing the New York
City mayor over his handling of a fatal police shooting, saying he
had ``hunkered down, taken sides and further divided this city.''
Patrick Dorismond, 26, was killed last week during an attempted
drug sting outside a midtown Manhattan bar. Dorismond, who was
black, was unarmed. Giuliani said there ``was no indication'' that
the shooting ``had anything to do with race.''
</P>
<P>
   REFORM PARTY STIRRINGS IN MINNESOTA
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month after Gov. Jesse Ventura led the Minnesota
Reform Party out of the national organization amid growing unrest
and growing party support for Pat Buchanan, other activists want to
re-establish the party in the state. Cedric Scofield, the
Midwestern regional representative for the national Reform Party,
said that a founding convention has been scheduled for April 7 in
Minneapolis to write a party charter and elect delegates to the
national convention.
</P>
<P>
   RUSH-ING TO STAY IN CONGRESS
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bobby Rush (D-Ill.), who ran unsuccessfully for mayor of
Chicago last year against Richard M. Daley, now faces a strong
challenge as he tries to keep his seat in Congress. Rush, a former
Black Panther leader who left the Chicago City Council for Congress
in 1992, is facing three Democratic opponents in today's Illinois
primary, including Barack Obama, a state senator, a civil rights
lawyer and first black president of the Harvard Law Review. The
other two candidates in the race are state Sen. Donne Trotter and
George Roby, a retired police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE VOTING: GOOD OR BAD?
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles Times analysis concluded that ``many people
believe that online voting is inevitable and that it will increase
voter participation. But an Industry Standard article is not so
optimistic, saying online voting may just increase the ``digital
divide.'' Meanwhile, a Harvard study says that voter interest in
the presidential campaign has dropped sharply since the March 7
primaries sealed both parties' nominations.
</P>
<P>
   VOTERS' CHOICE FOR VP
</P>
<P>
   A new independent Zogby Poll shows that 23 percent of likely
Democratic voters think that Bill Bradley should be chosen as Al
Gore's running mate, followed by former Sen. George Mitchell of
Maine, at 13 percent. On the other side, Elizabeth Dole is the
choice of 29 percent likely Republican voters, followed by John
McCain at 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
