<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BALLROOM-DANCE-NYT &LR;      03-21 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLROOM-DANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURN THE RUG? NO! BURN THE FLOOR! IT'S DANCE FEVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The idea was born at Elton John's 50th birthday party
three years ago at Hammersmith Ballroom in London and grew into
something that, well, let's put it this way: Nobody's grandparents
danced quite this way on their wedding night.
</P>
<P>
   Take traditional ballroom dancing, add a pinch of heavy metal
and a dash of professional wrestling and you begin to have some
sense of Burn the Floor, a stage presentation of dancing
flamboyance that played to sold-out audiences in Australia and
Europe last year and is coming to the United States this week.
</P>
<P>
   The show is beginning its American tour in Denver on Wednesday
and will reach 11 cities in seven weeks, with stops including the
Universal Amphitheater in Los Angeles from March 29 to 31 and Radio
City Music Hall in Manhattan on April 5 and 6.
</P>
<P>
   This is traditional ballroom dancing at warp speed, and audience
members of a certain age might not want to try this at home. The
show's two acts consist of 22 couples in various dress (and
undress) interpreting ballroom-style dances at a frenzied and
sultry pace to create an entirely new dance form, a little like
what might have happened had George Ballanchine ever collaborated
with Michael Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken ballroom dancing to another level,'' said Harley
Medcalf, the show's Australian-born creator and producer, whose
inspiration came from the entertainment that John gave the 600
guests at his birthday party: a swirl of couples performing
traditional and Latin ballroom dances, slightly stylized.
</P>
<P>
   The guests were amazed, Medcalf said, adding: ``I was completely
captivated by the rawness, the sensuality of it. I had always
thought ballroom dancing was stiff.''
</P>
<P>
   And if this was exciting, he remembered thinking, what about
energizing the presentation a few degrees more?
</P>
<P>
   Through nonstop activity over the next 18 months, Medcalf
brought together many of the creative artists he had worked with in
a 20-year career of concert and touring productions that starred,
among others, John, Kenny G, Michael Crawford, Meat Loaf and Boyz
II Men.
</P>
<P>
   They included Mark Fisher, a set designer who worked with the
Rolling Stones and Pink Floyd, and Patrick Woodroffe, a lighting
director who worked with the Stones and with Medcalf when he was
promoting Michael Flatley's ``Lord of the Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   More challenging, or so Medcalf thought, was finding the
dancers. He did not realize how eager the best of them would be to
drop everything to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Ballroom dancing is wildly popular around the world, but
nonetheless a cult activity that rewards the best dancers little
more than some respect from their peers. In most Western countries,
including the United States, there are competitions every weekend,
and even national champions in a variety of categories.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of couples compete every year. But generally there are
no audiences watching, only judges and other dancers. So not many
people know who won the 1998 and 1999 United States American Style
Nine Dance Championship. (Answer: Clive Phillips and his sister,
Karen McDonald, two of the dancers in Burn the Floor.)
</P>
<P>
   For the world's best ballroom dancers, though, titles are not
enough. Sometimes they come with reasonable pay, supplementing
annual income that almost always includes teaching. Most top
ballroom dancers could not eat if they did not teach, and almost
all the dancers in Burn the Floor have been national champions and
continue to teach.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Phillips and McDonald earned $80,000 in prize money
and from shows in addition to what they earned teaching at their
studio, Dance New York on West 54th Street.
</P>
<P>
   But the best ballroom dancers have always wanted more, and until
Medcalf invited a few of them into the Burn the Floor ensemble,
there were few other outlets to accommodate the kind of artistic
expression forbidden in tightly defined competitions.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, Phillips and others say they are pioneers,
presenting a show that finally gives ballroom dancing, at least
this ultra-version, the public exposure that could lead to more
shows of its kind and draw more people into dance studios for
lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, we have an avenue to release our artistic
side,'' Jason Gilkison, artistic director and an ensemble member,
said, comparing the strictures of competitions with the free form
of Burn the Floor. ``It's incredibly fun, and what makes my job so
easy is that all the dancers in the show are so passionate about
what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Passion is ever present and at times borders on the steamy. Hips
get a big workout in this show. The 10 dances may not be recognized
by those who are unfamiliar with Burn the Floor: waltz, cha-cha,
samba, rumba, jitterbug, salsa, tango, lindy, jive and swing. The
sultry quality of each number is amplified by costumes, music and
lighting to fit the mood.
</P>
<P>
   Romance as unifying theme was always the idea Medcalf intended
to convey. In that sense at least, Burn the Floor clings closely to
its Ginger Rogers-Fred Astaire roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always what I come back to: ballroom dancing was always
about here, the heart and romance and beauty,'' said Medcalf, his
hand pressed to his chest. ``Now, it's just big, brassy and loud.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
