   w/INDIA-PROTEST _ NEW DELHI, India - Police fired water cannons
to subdue angry crowds protesting President Clinton's visit in the
heart of the Indian capital Tuesday afternoon. Despite tight
security throughout the city, the protesters, carrying anti-U.S.
signs and chanting ``Bill Clinton, go home,'' marched about a mile
to the American Center, where they tried to break through police
barricades. Most of the protesters were affiliated with the
Communist Party India. Tuesday's protest was one of several that
have been held in New Delhi over the last few days. But the
protests have failed to deter a group of Indian community leaders
from across the United States, who traveled back to their homeland
to promote Indo-U.S. ties during Clinton's trip. ``The protesters
have a lack of understanding of the modern world and the free
enterprise system,'' said Atlantan Antony Thaliath, vice president
of the National Federation of Indian-American Associations. (Basu,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
