u i BC-IRAQ-U.S.-460&AMP;ADD-NYT     03-21 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO PROPOSE INCREASE IN IRAQI EXPENDITURES ON OIL INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United States will propose doubling the
sums Iraq may spend on spare parts for its decrepit oil industry,
neglected during almost 10 years of sanctions, diplomats said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under a U.S.-sponsored resolution to be circulated for
discussion among Security Council members in the next day or two,
Iraq would be permitted to raise up to $600 million every six
months _ $1.2 billion a year _ instead of the current $300 million
every six months.
</P>
<P>
   The money is raised through the oil for food program, which
allows Iraq to sell oil to meet the needs of its civilians. The
increase was recommended by Secretary-General Kofi Annan in a
report to the council this month because the sanctions have left
the equipment in such poor shape.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, generally expected to be voted on by the council on
Friday unless there are unforeseen objections, is being introduced
as members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
prepare to meet in Vienna next week to discuss the possibility of
increasing oil production so that record high prices will decline.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has oil reserves second only to Saudi Arabia's, experts
say. Since December, the Iraqis have been permitted to sell as much
oil as they wish under the U.N.-supervised program. Some of the
proceeds pay for goods needed by civilians, who have been living
under sanctions since 1990, and for public services like water and
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday an official Iraqi newspaper attacked oil-exporting
countries thought to be willing to increase production to ease
costs for the United States and other countries. ``The United
States policy of blackmail must be rejected,'' said the paper,
Al-Jumhuriya, which as with all Iraqi papers is government
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Iraq has been straining its pumping and pipeline operations
to take advantage of the higher prices, although it cannot sustain
such a high level of activity for long, Annan's report said. It
described Iraqi oil installations as hazards to the safety of
workers and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The report was based on a technical survey of the industry
requested by the council in December and carried out in January by
an independent group of oil experts from Saybolt International BV
of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats are not concerned that allowing Iraq to double the
money spent on spare parts for oil production will cut into the
food, medicine or other purchases for the population, because with
oil prices high income is also up; if more oil is pumped, more
civilian goods can be imported. Over the last three years, Iraq has
earned $20 billion in supervised oil sales, with a third of that
going to pay compensation to victims of Iraq's 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   However, even with more money, Iraq says that it cannot upgrade
its oil industry effectively as long as the United States and, to a
lesser extent, Britain, block critical contracts for oil spare
parts or other related equipment in the Security Council sanctions
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials say that these contracts must be carefully
scrutinized, because Iraq appears to want to channel some new
equipment into refineries, when under the current program it is
allowed to sell only crude oil abroad. They say they fear that
refined petroleum products will earn more money for smugglers and
benefit President Saddam Hussein, his family and supporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
