<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3774 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     03-21 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF SHORT TRIPS AND LONG MEMORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hey guys, I'm going out to run some errands. Come ride with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems like a nice invitation, doesn't it? I mean if I was
just sitting around watching TV for the umpteenth hour because I
have no money and no transportation, and someone invited me to go
somewhere _ anywhere _ I'd jump at the chance. But then, I'm not a
teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers, especially those who are barely 13, have to be
persuaded or coerced into going out into public with their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a younger sibling is included in these invitations, but for
the most part, he's going to follow his anointed leader, the Grand
Poobah of Indifference.
</P>
<P>
   So, in response to my gracious invitation, the Poobah says,
``Where are you going?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I've just got to run by a couple of stores and take care
of a few things,'' I reply as I check my to-do list and plot the
speediest route to completing my tasks. ``Come on, we'll have fun.
I'll buy you a drink at the convenience store.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thirsty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine, we'll skip the drink. Just come along for the ride.
You've been cooped up in here all day watching reruns. You need
some fresh air and sunshine. I won't be gone long.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But where are you going exactly?'' the Poobah asks,
emphasizing the word exactly as if he's cross-examining someone on
the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, I'm going to the mall to get my watchband repaired. Then,
I've got to run by the cleaners, and I need to pick up a few things
from the grocery store. We won't be gone long. Put your shoes on
and come on. It's not like you have some pressing engagement. And
I'll make sure the answering machine is on so you won't miss any of
your urgent calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, my sons start to put their shoes on.
</P>
<P>
   The Poobah's disciple pipes in now, ``But Mom, how long will we
be gone? Dragon Ball Z comes on at four.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm so exasperated now that I'm sorry I even invited them to go
along. It wasn't always like this, you know. When they were
younger, I couldn't move without one of them trying to tag along.
They'd come running like puppies every time they heard keys jingle.
</P>
<P>
   These are the same boys that used to follow me to the bathroom
and stick their fingers under the locked door even though I begged
and pleaded with them to go away.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I have to become a travel agent and extol the virtues of
our interesting and exciting destinations before they'll agree to
get into the car with me. Or, I just put my foot down and say,
``Let's go, now!'' But then I've got to deal with their attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   The performances kids give us from their ``developmental
stages'' are not always entertaining, are they? I'm told that there
is good news and bad news about our young actors. The good news is
that they eventually move on to another stage. The bad news is
that, quite often, the new drama is even more confusing.
</P>
<P>
   Oh well.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we get into the car. We ride into the sunset. I sing, I
tell jokes, I get them to laugh and talk and we have fun.
</P>
<P>
   On the way home, I smile. I'm pleased with myself and the fact
that we've spent quality, productive, fun time together. As we pull
into the driveway; however, I'm exhausted and looking forward to
kicking off my shoes and taking a load off.
</P>
<P>
   I'm about to turn off the ignition when the Poobah says, ``What
about my drink?''
</P>
<P>
   I think I'm ready for the final curtain on this stage.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is an Arlington, Texas, dentist. Write
her in care of the Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington,
TX 76013, or leave a message for her at (817) 548-5564. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
