<SLUG> BC-FILM-`ROMEO'-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIAL-ARTS `ROMEO AND JULIET' A TRAGEDY, ALL RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best scene in ``Romeo Must Die'' doesn't have much to do
with the rest of the movie. Lead character Han (Jet Li), who
recently escaped from a Hong Kong prison to avenge the Oakland-area
death of his brother, gets talked into a pickup game of football.
Han learns the rules the hard way, falling victim to bone-crunching
tackles, before discovering that the person with the ball is the
one who gets hit. So on his next run, he tosses the ball to
opposing players, knocks the stuffing out of them, gets the ball
back and repeats the process until he gets a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The scene has a comic edge, highlighted by Li's light-speed
martial arts stunts, which comprise moves you'll never see on NFL
on Fox. Li has an even neater trick, though. Somehow, he drains all
the intelligence from his face till he looks so naive and boyish
that you don't suspect the violence within. He's always coiled and
ready to strike _ it's the movie that unravels around him.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as a ``martial-arts/hip-hop Romeo and Juliet,'' ``Romeo
Must Die'' isn't a romance; it's more of a buddy movie, pairing Li
with R&AMP;B star Aaliyah, who makes her feature-film debut as Trish, a
mobster's daughter who hooks up with Han when she eludes her
bodyguard and pops into a cab that Han has just stolen. The
potential for sparks is there, but never explored; instead, the
overstuffed script by Eric Bernt and John Jarrell deals with family
honor (leading to some really hoary dialogue), mob battles for
waterfront property and a deal to find a home for Oakland's latest
football team.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad more isn't made of Li's and Aaliyah's characters,
because both actors share a mischievous arrogance that makes
``Romeo'' fun to watch for a while. But because there are so many
characters, the movie is constantly steering away from the things
we want to see: any developing romance between Li and Aaliyah, and
Li in top tail-kicking form.
</P>
<P>
   Li does get to see some action _ according to the press notes,
it's eight fights, but who's counting? _ the best of which comes
during the aforementioned football game and other scenes in which
Li uses such unconventional weapons as a fire hose and Aaliyah
herself. But in between, there are a lot of been-there, done-that
situations, enlivened somewhat by some sharp supporting turns by
Delroy Lindo as Trish's father, Isaiah Washington as his
trigger-happy sidekick, rapper DMX as a club owner and Anthony
Anderson as Trish's ineffectual bodyguard.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Romeo and Juliet connection, well, a lot of people
die, but director Andrzej Bartkowiak, a longtime cinematographer
making his directorial debut, fails to provide the movie with any
sense of encroaching doom. He's content merely to move from fight
to fight, in scenes so pedestrian it's like the action scenes were
filmed by another director. Romeo Must Die had potential; if
there's any tragedy involved, it's that Bartkowiak and the
scriptwriters didn't know how to fulfill it.
</P>
<P>
   Romeo Must Die is rated R for violence, profanity and brief
nudity.
Romeo Must Die 21/2 out of 5. Director: Andrzej Bartkowiak Stars:
Jet Li, Aaliyah Length: 118 min. Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
