<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TECHNOLOGY PROVES THAT LESS IS MORE  
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gasoline prices are high, and the trend may continue. At least
there's an offsetting trend that will continue, too: electronic
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Electronic products cost less and do more,'' said Jim Barry,
spokesman for the Consumer Electronics Association. The trade group
used to have ``Manufacturing'' in its name, but dropped it within
the past year because some companies _ like DirecTV, for instance _
supply a service rather than manufacture goods.
</P>
<P>
   High-definition television costs more than a gallon of gasoline,
but the price is coming down at a faster rate than gasoline is
going up. The HDTV that cost $10,000 when it was first introduced
about two years ago has been slashed in half _ with some units
going for $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, Barry said the trend has been to make
products smaller. The brick-size cellular phone from yesteryear has
been reduced to nearly the size of a matchbox _ and has far more
features than the larger model.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could make it even smaller,'' said Barry, ``but that
would just mean people would lose them. I keep this one in a belt
clip. I'm afraid that if I put it in my pocket, it would wind up at
the dry cleaners.''
</P>
<P>
   CD players are smaller and lighter _ barely much larger than the
CDs themselves. Sony has just come out with one that doesn't skip,
no matter how much jarring it gets.
</P>
<P>
   Televisions are pocketsize _ and are color, not just black and
white like they used to be. Products get longer play time from
batteries.
</P>
<P>
   What's going to be the hot new electronic product?
</P>
<P>
   Barry's answer provides some insight into why the trade
association he represents no longer is called the Consumer
Electronics Manufacturing Association. Remember at the beginning of
the column when I pointed out that CEA represents more than
manufacturers?
</P>
<P>
   The hot news in electronics in the coming year will be wireless
technology, said Barry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hooking up two computers in the home used to mean either
running cables through walls or draping them behind desks or over
chairs,'' he said. ``There's one method that uses telephone lines
in the house to connect two computers in different rooms.'' But
transfer rates using that method aren't as high as they are with
cable hookups.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless transmitters can send signals through walls and floors.
They're becoming easier to install and cheap enough so that hooking
up two computers wirelessly doesn't cost much more than doing so
with wires.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, wireless will replace wires that connect things to
computers. Printers, scanners, external disk drives and other
devices may work as well without wires as they do now with them.
And rather than wonder where to plug things in, users could justturn them on and let the computer find the new device and set it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Barry brings home the point by pulling out a Palm VII from his
coat pocket.
</P>
<P>
   It's a personal information manager (about $450) that keeps
track of addresses, phone numbers and appointments. This one costs
about $200 more than the Palm IIIx, which has many of the same
features. The extra price is for wireless.
</P>
<P>
   Barry flips up an antenna and the Palm automatically connects
with a wireless network. Within a minute, he has stock quotes,
access to e-mail, and can read news and articles from Web pages on
the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Barry said it may seem like new technology is making old
technology obsolete. But what it's doing is making new technology
more desirable. The computer that's 10 years old will still do word
processing. The wired telephone can still make telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``What becomes obsolete,'' said Barry, ``is the language used
with the technology. If you say, `He sat by the telephone,' and a
teen-ager hears that, he might wonder why anyone waiting for a
telephone call would sit by the telephone. He'd think, `Why not
just take the telephone with you?' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be contacted by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. The
Ledger is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
