<SLUG> BC-FOODNEWS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Food, nutrition and health studies bombard us, but
the seemingly endless information is often as confusing as it is
enlightening. With Food in the News, The Chronicle's Food staff
aims to change that. This round-up column will make practical sense
of the latest nutrition-related studies _ as well as offering
offbeat but tantalizing snippets of other food news to put on your
plate. &HT;     
 FOOD IN THE NEWS: National Organic Standards Should Become Law by 
 Summer   By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Except for a few details, Bay Area organic farmers
like the federal government's newest effort to create a national
standard for organic food.
<P>
   The Clinton administration announced revised rules that define
and regulate what can and can't be labeled organic food earlier
this month. The 600 pages of regulations, written by the U.S.
Department of Agriculture after years of public wrangling, now face
another public comment period that ends in July. The rules could
become law by early fall, but it might take another 18 months
before consumers will see any effect.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the first set of USDA organic rules was hit with
heavy protest, in particular because they allowed irradiated foods
and the use of genetically modified ingredients. The new version
prohibits use of those sorts of ingredients and also bans the use
of sewage sludge as fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   States can choose to have the federal government enforce the
rules. In states like California, which has a strong organic
certification system, the federal government would need to approve
existing programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, it's has been extremely well received. Everyone's
relieved it's a tighter rule,'' says Michael Straus of Beyond
Organic, a Marin-based public relations consultant to the
agricultural and environmental communities. ``At this point, it
gets down to the nitty gritty of production. The rules are so tight
that there is some concern that standards might be too tough for
some farmers to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Straus says, farmers who want to use composting
manure from a dairy farm will need to figure out if the cows were
fed organic grain. But the dairy farms might not have a tracking
system in place to determine if the feed meets the new organic
standard.
</P>
<P>
   To review the new rules and find out how to offer comment, click
on the Web site,  &LR; www.ams.usda.gov/nop &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; One Banana, Two Banana &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Administrators at the University of California at Riverside are
learning that Internet-driven urban myths die hard.
</P>
<P>
   In late January, someone on campus received a mysterious e-mail
reporting that shipments of bananas from Costa Rica were infected
with necrotizing  &LR; fasciitis &LR; , a flesh-eating bacteria. Eating an
infected banana, according to the e-mail, would cause an infection
that could eat skin at a rate of two to three centimeters per hour.
Amputation was likely, death possible, the e-mail said.
</P>
<P>
   Although administrators still don't know exactly how it
happened, the e-mail was sent off campus with the name and
telephone number of the assistant to the dean of the College of
Natural and Agricultural Sciences. The e-mail was so widely
circulated that at one point last month, more than 50 inquires a
day poured into the campus, says UC Riverside spokeswoman Kathy
Barton.
</P>
<P>
   Things got so bad that Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta issued a press release calling it a hoax and
noting that although the disease does exist, it is not transmitted
by bananas.
</P>
<P>
   The college is still fielding inquiries. Callers to the number
on the e-mail hear a recorded message setting the record straight
and are asked to tell anyone they might have forwarded the message
to that the whole thing is a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the recording: ``Please note we do not do research on
bananas at the University of California at Riverside.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Soy What? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Students scoping out the cafeteria line will have a new choice
on April 10, when USDA rules go into effect that allow soy burgers
and other soy products to be swapped for meat.
</P>
<P>
   Under previous rules, soy could only be used as an additive. The
idea is to help limit the fat in school lunch menus, USDA officials
say. The rule applies to any school or child-care center that
offers federally subsidized meals.
</P>
<P>
   Whether students will actually choose a soy burger over a beef
burger remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be well received, though there is a question
in my mind whether it's the parents wanting it or the kids,'' says
Cindy Schneider, a child nutrition consultant for the state
Department of Education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
