<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: Sauvignon Epiphany Comes to a Wine Writer   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Anyone reading this column with any regularity
knows of my occasional ranting about the generally sad state of
California Chardonnay and Sauvignon Blanc. More about Chardonnay
later, but now I'd like to tell you about a Sauvignon epiphany.
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm a red wine drinker, but when white wine is a better choice
with my meal, then it needs to be crisp and fresh, with flavor that
echoes a grape and not a tree. Above all, the wine must go with a
wide range of dishes. To me, Sauvignon Blanc best fills that order.
I like the crisp citrusy freshness of New Zealand and South Africa
Sauvignons, and the mineral qualities of French Sauvignons from
Bordeaux and the Loire Valley.
</P>
<P>
   California Sauvignon Blanc is another matter. Sweeping
generalizations, of course, are never fair, since there usually are
exceptions to any criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, I wrote a grumpy commentary on California
Sauvignon Blanc and received a nice letter from Bob Travers of
Mayacamas, along with a six-pack of Mayacamas Sauvignon Blancs.
Travers is too nice a guy to say right out, ``Get a life, Boyd!''
so he just suggested that I might enjoy the six Mayacamas
Sauvignons, from 1993 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Jack and Mary Taylor established Mayacamas high above the Napa
Valley, on the remote slopes of Mount Veeder, in 1941. Bob and
Elinor Travers bought the property in 1968 and hired winemaker Bob
Sessions, who now is with Hanzell. Mayacamas always has been known
as a Cabernet Sauvignon house and, as Travers points out,
``although we made a little Chenin Blanc in the 1960s, Chardonnay
was our only white wine for a decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayacamas produced its first Sauvignon Blanc in 1977 when the
varietal was virtually unknown in California. During the 1980s,
Travers used a little Semillon in the blend, but today the 600 to
800 cases of wine are all Sauvignon Blanc from mountain vineyards
around the winery. Mayacamas may be the only winery in the United
States to produce a mountain-grown Sauvignon Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   Travers says the gravelly, rocky soils in the mountain vineyard
give the wine a ``steely character,'' a distinguishing feature of
true Sauvignon Blanc. ``I like the grassy-sage character, but when
it's just barely there,'' says Travers.
</P>
<P>
   To that I say amen, and note that the appealing mineral-steely
flavor with just a light grassy note often is missing from many
California Sauvignons that lean more to floral characteristics,
even with a little sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   I tasted the six Mayacamas Sauvignon Blancs together and found
the 1997 and 1995 especially attractive, both with juicy grapefruit
and subtle herbal flavors, great texture and crisp acidity. The
1998 (currently available at $18) is more citrus and melon but,
with another year of bottle age, has the potential to develop the
crisp slightly grassy-herbal style that is so appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Mayacamas Sauvignon Blanc is available in limited supply in the
Bay Area, but you'll have to shop around.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Woe Is Chardonnay &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There are probably more than a thousand Chardonnays produced by
the 700 bonded wineries in California, and most lack inspiration
and the appeal to encourage the drinker to have a second glass.
Although Chardonnay remains the favorite white wine of America's
wine drinkers, far too many of them are ``cookie cutter'' wines
that look, smell and taste remarkably similar.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Chronicle's Wine Selections recommends nine 1997 Sonoma
Chardonnays from a group of 33 wines tasted. Our five tasters,
including myself, failed to give a unanimous endorsement to any
wine, feeling they were mostly one-dimensional, too oaky and
alcoholic and too pricey for quality offered. Perhaps the general
attitude of the tasters was summed up best by one Chardonnay-loving
panelist: ``After tasting these wines, I may have to reassess my
position on Chardonnay.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Zin Fest 2000 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Zin lover, there's still time to make it over to the
Lark Creek Inn, 234 Magnolia Ave. in Larkspur, for Zin Fest 2000, a
celebration of American food with America's own red wine. Chefs
Bradley Ogden and Jeremy Sewall will be cooking up Zin-friendly
foods such as Zinfandel-braised Lamb Shank with Garlic Potato Puree
and Spring Vegetables. Ravenswood Zinfandel will be poured tonight,
Hendry Wines on March 23, Scherrer on the 24th and Biale on March
25. The tasting menu is $69 per person, with an optional wine
pairing for a $28 supplement. For reservations, call Lark Creek Inn
at (415) 924-7766.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Basics &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Merlot is fast becoming one of America's most popular red wines,
but it isn't without controversy. Once a blending grape in Bordeaux
that stood in the shadow of Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot is more
widely planted there now than Cabernet. The shift is mainly due to
changing worldwide tastes for softer consumer-friendly red wines.
</P>
<P>
   Merlot from the best Pomerol chateaus, such as Petrus, will age
for 30 years, producing an elegant wine with great depth. But
so-called New World Merlots, especially from California, are softer
and rounder.
</P>
<P>
   Merlot is grown in all of California's main wine regions and
does well in Eastern Washington, Southern Oregon and New York's
Long Island. Popular Merlots also are available from Chile and
Northern Italy. New Zealand Merlots and Merlot-Cabernet blends from
Hawkes Bay are the latest finds from the Southern Hemisphere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1813EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3781 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-BOOKHERB-SFCHRON &LR;      03-21 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKHERB-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 COOK'S BOOKS: Chef Promotes Herbs With Every Course   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  If you have always thought of a tossed green salad
as something that you, well, just toss together, ``The Herbfarm
Cookbook'' might impart some shocking news. But then again, it
might also prove an epiphany.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reading how chef/author Jerry Traunfeld describes the creation
of the Herbfarm Garden Salad _ from gathering the ingredients, leaf
by leaf and blossom by blossom, in the kitchen gardens surrounding
his celebrated restaurant in the Cascade foothills near Seattle, to
the individualized dressing of each and every component and the
final ritualized assembly _ you may finally fathom why your salads
seem ordinary when compared with creations of fine restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   However, while extolling the virtues of growing your own herbs,
Traunfeld doesn't dismiss the urban dweller or the cook with a
permanent brown thumb. With care, he writes, any good market today
can yield the essentials for cooking with herbs, including making
his signature salad.
</P>
<P>
   He insists that the density of the dressing must be matched to
the character of the greens _ thick, strong-tasting leaves like
radicchio or kale need a robust coating, delicate young butter
lettuce or m &LR; a &LR; che ``only the slightest whisper of vinaigrette.''
</P>
<P>
   Traunfeld, a transplanted New Yorker who got his formal training
at the California Culinary Academy, uses herbs in each of the nine
courses that make up the menu at the restaurant where he is
executive chef, and he mirrors this dedication in the book. Yet he
and his editors wisely chose not to intimidate home cooks with
forbiddingly complex restaurant preparations.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many of the dishes in the handsomely illustrated book
have appealing simplicity and purity of flavors: Lettuce and
Tarragon Soup has only eight ingredients and can be mostly made two
days in advance. Fresh tomato and herb salad is just that _
perfectly ripe tomatoes and a handful of assorted herbs dressed
with wine and balsamic vinegars and olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   His fish fillets  &LR; en papillote &LR;  detail five herb/flavor
variations and are a breeze to make. One of the easiest versions is
also one of the most intriguing: The fish packets are seasoned with
sliced shallot, fresh tarragon leaves and grapefruit sections and
zest.
</P>
<P>
   Traunfeld's lavender shortbread, made with only flour, butter,
sugar and lavender blossoms, is superb _ definitely a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   Salsas, sauces and other enhancements abound in this innovative
book, and so does down-to-earth advice. Traunfeld grows herbs for
his own household in a small urban yard, so he is not addicted to
grandiose garden schemes. His advice on planning and planting an
herb garden, on the varieties to select and the pitfalls to avoid
are as solid as his detailed charts and descriptions of herbs as
common as parsley and as arcane as Good King Henry (chenopodium).
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``The Herbfarm Cookbook,'' by Jerry Traunfeld (Scribner, 448 &LR; 
 &LR; pages; botanical watercolors by Louise Smith, illustrations by &LR; 
 &LR; Elayne Sears and color photography by Jonelle Weaver, $40). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LAVENDER SHORTBREAD
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces unsalted butter, chilled
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons fresh lavender buds, or 2 teaspoons dried
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour (9 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes before you begin the dough, remove the butter
from the refrigerator. Place the lavender buds in a clean spice
mill with 1/4 cup of the sugar and grind until fine, or grind the
lavender with all the sugar in a blender or small food processor.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the lavender-sugar to the bowl of a heavy-duty electric
mixer fitted with a paddle, add the remaining sugar if you used a
spice mill, and the butter. Beat on low speed until the mixture is
smooth; do not beat it until fluffy. Add all the flour at once and
continue to mix on low speed just until it forms a cohesive dough.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the dough out onto a lightly floured surface, press it
firmly into a smooth rectangular block with no cracks and dust it
lightly with more flour. Using a rolling pin, roll it into a 12 x
9-inch rectangle, 1/4 inch thick, rotating the dough a quarter turn
each time you roll to make sure it is not sticking to the work
surface. You can also roll the dough out between sheets of plastic
wrap or parchment paper. Using a straight edge and a pastry wheel
or chef's knife, cut the dough into 2 x 11/2-inch bars, or cut out
other shapes with cookie cutters. Using a spatula, transfer the
cookies to a baking sheet lined with parchment paper, leaving
1/2-inch space between them. Refrigerate the cookies 30 minutes to
allow the dough to rest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Preheat the oven to 300 degrees. Bake the cookies until they
are colored lightly like sand, not browned, 22 to 25 minutes. Lift
one with a spatula to check the color of the underside; it should
be just a shade darker than the top. Let the cookies cool
completely on the pan (they are soft while hot). Stack the cooled
cookies in an airtight container and store at room temperature for
up to 1 week.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 24 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Substitutions:  &LR; In place of lavender, add 4 teaspoons finely
chopped fresh rosemary, thyme, lemon thyme, or 2 teaspoons dried
fennel or anise seeds, or 1/2 teaspoon green cardamom seeds,
grinding the seeds with the sugar as directed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER COOKIE: &LR;   &LR; 120 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 12 g carbohydrate,
8 &LR;   &LR; g fat (5 g saturated), 21 mg cholesterol, 1 mg sodium, 0
fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
