 CHRON  
 Bay Area Food Professionals Reap Kudos   c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  San Francisco chefs, restaurateurs, vintners,
cookbook authors and local media have captured a wealth of this
year's James Beard Foundation nominations, which are considered the
Academy Awards of food.
<TEXT>
<P>
   San Francisco's Zuni Cafe, owned by Judy Rodgers and Vince
Calcagno, is one of five national nominees for top restaurant of
the year. The award goes to a restaurant in business at least 10
years that is considered a national standard-bearer in food,
atmosphere and service. Gary Danko, also in San Francisco, is
nominated for best new restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   In the regional categories, the nominees for Best Chef in
California are all from San Francisco: Traci des Jardins,
Jardini &LR; e &LR; re; Nancy Oakes, Boulevard; Reed Hearon, Rose Pistola and
Black Cat; Michael Mina, Aqua; and Judy Rodgers, Zuni.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Morgan and David Hughes of Level design in Calistoga are
nominated for outstanding restaurant graphics for Bouchon in
Yountville.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area dominated the wine and spirits categories, taking
four of the five nominations for wine and spirits professional of
the year: Evan Goldstein of Sterling School of Service and
Hospitality in Calistoga; Kermit Lynch of Kermit Lynch Wine
Merchants in Berkeley; Fritz Maytag of Anchor Brewing Co. in San
Francisco; and Helen Turley of Marcassin Winery in St. Helena.
Rubicon restaurant, in San Francisco, and its wine director, Larry
Stone, are nominated for the outstanding wine service award.
</P>
<P>
   In the cookbook arena, Bay Area author and Chronicle columnist
Marion Cunningham received a nomination in the General category for
``Learning to Cook With Marion Cunningham.'' Other local nominees
include Beth Hensperger for ``The Bread Bible;'' Thomas Keller for
``The French Laundry Cookbook;'' Michael Chiarello and Penelope
Wisner for ``The Tra Vigne Cookbook;'' and noted artisan Alan Scott
for ``The Bread Builders.''
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area newspapers also swept the Beard journalism nominations.
The San Francisco Chronicle received a total of six nominations for
feature stories, restaurant reviews and nutrition coverage. The
weekly San Francisco Bay Guardian and the Metro in Santa Cruz each
received one nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
