<SLUG> BC-BESTPASTA-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods. 
 
 Cooking Pasta Ahead   By Noel Advincula  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Whether you are planning your meal ahead of time
or just storing some left over pasta, how it's cooked and stored
does affect its quality.
<TEXT>
<P>
   We chose the readily available De Cecco brand of dried
spaghetti, cooked it  &LR; al dente &LR;  according to package directions,
and refrigerated it overnight. Before serving, we tossed it with a
jarred marinara sauce (1/2 cup per 1/2 pound cooked spaghetti) and
reheated it in a microwave. We did not re-store the pasta after it
had been coated with the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Our first test was to determine how best to prepare pasta that
would be stored. The pasta that was cooked and drained but not
rinsed was gluey and tacky when reheated. On the other hand, the
pasta that was cooked, drained, then rinsed with cold water,
drained again and tossed with 1 teaspoon of olive oil produced a
firmer texture that met the Food department's approval.
</P>
<P>
   We also tried a batch that was stored immediately after cooking,
without sufficiently draining the excess water. The pasta looked
swollen the next day and was no longer  &LR; al dente &LR;  after being
reheated.
</P>
<P>
   The next step was determining the best storage medium for the
pasta. We found out that there was not much difference in flavor
and texture between the pasta that was stored in plastic
self-sealing bags versus being packed into small plastic containers
or spacious plastic containers.
</P>
<P>
   We also tested the storage life of the cooked pasta. We left the
pasta in plastic bags in the refrigerator for two days, three days
and six days. Most testers couldn't tell the difference between the
three. That's good news for people who like to make them in huge
batches and have it for dinner throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we compared freshly cooked pasta with pasta that had
been cooked, held overnight and reheated in the microwave the next
day with sauce. Here there was a major difference. The reheated
pasta was duller, heavier and less  &LR; al dente &LR;  than the freshly
cooked version.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Even though freshly cooked pasta is best, if pasta is cooked and
stored properly it can be OK. Draining the water right away and
quickly rinsing the pasta with cold water to stop the cooking
process is an absolute must. Lightly oiling the pasta before
storing it in an airtight roomy plastic bag or container will
prevent the pasta from clumping. The pasta will keep up to six days
in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   We all think of how easy it is to cook pasta, but for the people
who want an easier way to make a quick meal, this is a very good
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   If you are planning to consume the pasta throughout the week,
undercook the pasta so that it is firmer than  &LR; al dente &LR; . That way
the texture should be right when it is added to the sauce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1815EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
