<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3787 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-WORKING-SFCHRON &LR;      03-21 1544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute Main
Dish takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast &AMP; Fresh
gives you dinner in about 20 minutes. 
 
 THE WORKING COOK: `Working Cook' Takes on a New Meaning  By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Puttanesca sauce may well be the original working
cook recipe. Among the theories behind its name (which means ``of
the harlot''), is that it was a quick meal for working girls to
prepare between ``engagements.''
<P>
   Others say the name derives from the sauce's many colors _ deep
red tomatoes, purplish olives, green parsley, bright red chiles _
reminiscent of the eye-catching colors worn by ladies of the night,
according to Arthur Schwartz in ``Naples at Table'' (HarperCollins,
1998).
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the etymology, the name seems appropriate for such a
spicy, zesty sauce. Served with linguine, it makes a very easy
meal, especially since the only fresh ingredient is parsley;
everything else comes straight out of the pantry.
</P>
<P>
   This week's other quick recipe, Salmon with Leeks &AMP; Bok Choy, is
a colorful display of Easter-egg colors like the pink-orange fish
and spring-green leeks. Seasoning the vegetables with rice vinegar
and lemon zest gives them a pickled flavor that suits the richness
of roasted salmon. Though the bok choy should be wilted, be careful
not to overcook it or it will lose its delicate, juicy crunch.
</P>
<P>
   Weekend cooks should like the Now &AMP; Later recipe, Black Bean
Enchiladas with Chipotle Sauce. This vegetarian entree calls for
many steps, but the end result is a wonderful dish with a lot of
complex flavors.
</P>
<P>
   As the main filling for the enchiladas, black beans are simmered
with orange juice, which lightens up their dark, earthy taste. Sour
cream and cheese enrich the beans, and a lively sauce of
oven-roasted tomatoes and chipotle peppers tops off the dish.
</P>
<P>
   If you get tired of cooking, ask family members or dinner guests
to help you assemble the enchiladas. After all, a working cook
should work only so much.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FAST &AMP; FRESH dinner in about 20 minutes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SALMON WITH LEEKS &AMP; BOK CHOY
</P>
<P>
   Serve this dish with steamed medium-grain rice.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 leek (about 1/2 pound)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Pinch hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound baby bok choy
</P>
<P>
   4 salmon fillets, 6 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black sesame seeds (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler. Line a baking sheet (one that will fit
under your broiler) with foil and grease it lightly with butter.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the stem on, slice the leek in half lengthwise and clean
thoroughly under running water. Remove stem and slice the leek
across the grain into very thin strips until you reach the dark
green part.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a large skillet. Add the red pepper flakes
and stir for a few seconds over medium-low heat. Add the leek and
saute over medium heat, stirring occasionally, until soft, 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Slice the bok choy widthwise into 1/4-inch strips, discarding
stems. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Season the salmon fillets with salt and pepper. Place on the
baking sheet. Broil until golden-orange on top but still rare in
the middle, about 8 minutes (10 minutes for medium).
</P>
<P>
   After the leeks have cooked, add the bok choy, vinegar and lemon
zest. Season with salt. Cover and wilt 2 minutes, stirring once.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the vegetables and their juice in shallow soup bowls and
top with salmon. Sprinkle with sesame seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 380 calories, &LR;   &LR; 35 g protein, 5 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 24 g fat (8 g saturated), 128 mg cholesterol, 144 mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NOW &AMP; LATER dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BLACK BEAN ENCHILADAS WITH ROASTED TOMATO-CHIPOTLE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   This vegetarian dish freezes remarkably well. Cool completely,
then cover tightly to freeze. Defrost slowly in the refrigerator.
After reheating, add dollops of sour cream and sprinkle with
cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dried black beans, soaked overnight and drained
</P>
<P>
   about 4 tablespoons salt
</P>
<P>
   51/2 pounds Roma tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil + 1/2 cup oil to fry tortillas
</P>
<P>
   4 onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried oregano, preferably Mexican
</P>
<P>
   1 cup freshly squeezed orange juice
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup minced cilantro + cilantro for garnish
</P>
<P>
   2 cups low-salt vegetable stock or water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon pureed canned chipotles in adobo sauce, seeds
removed (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons adobo sauce (from the can of chipotles)
</P>
<P>
   24 super-size corn tortillas (see note)
</P>
<P>
   20 ounces dry Mexican cheese, such as queso anejo or queso seco
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Place the beans in a large stockpot and cover with twice the
volume of water. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat and simmer until
the beans are just tender, about 25 minutes. Add 2 tablespoons salt
to the water and simmer until beans are cooked through but still
firm, about 10 minutes. Drain, reserving 2 cups of the cooking
liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cut the tomatoes in half. Place cut-side up on a
baking sheet lined with aluminum foil; sprinkle with salt and
pepper. Place in oven and roast for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 3 tablespoons oil in another large stockpot. Add the onion
and saute for 5 minutes over medium-low heat. Add the garlic and
oregano and saute for 10 minutes. Set aside half of the mixture.
</P>
<P>
   When the beans are cooked, return to the pot with the reserved
cooking liquid, the orange juice, half of the onion mixture and 2
teaspoons salt. Simmer for 25 minutes, stirring occasionally, until
most of the liquid has evaporated. Stir in 2/3 cup cilantro. Remove
from heat.
</P>
<P>
   When the tomatoes are cooked, add them to the remaining onion
mixture, along with the stock, chipotle, adobo sauce and 2
teaspoons salt. Bring to a boil, remove from heat and cover for 10
minutes to allow flavors to blend. Run through a food mill or puree
in a processor.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the 1/2 cup oil in a large skillet and place over
medium-high heat. When the oil is hot, fry the tortillas for a few
seconds on each side, until slightly crisp. Fold and drain on paper
towels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble:  &LR; Reduce the oven temperature to 350 degrees.
Crumble the cheese, setting aside 1/2 cup for the top. Spread a
thick layer of chipotle sauce in 2 large casserole dishes. Dip a
tortilla in the sauce to coat. Add a few tablespoons of the black
beans, a sprinkle of cheese and a few small dollops of sour cream
down the middle of the tortilla. Roll up the tortilla and place
seam-side down in one of the casseroles. Repeat, filling each
casserole with 12 enchiladas. Spread the remaining sauce over the
enchiladas, then sprinkle with the reserved cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve garnished with cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Canned  &UR; chipotle peppers  &LR; in adobo sauce are available
in the Latino foods aisle of many supermarkets, while Mexican-style
 &UR; cheese  &LR; is also widely available, refrigerated. Most grocery stores
now carry only ``super-size'' corn  &UR; tortillas.  &LR; Use 3 or 4 extra if
using regular-size corn tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER ENCHILADA: &LR;   &LR; 345 calories, &LR;   &LR; 15 g protein, 45 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 14 g fat (6 g saturated), 26 mg cholesterol, 680 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 10 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
30-MINUTE MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   LINGUINE WITH PUTTANESCA SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   6 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   5 small anchovy fillets
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry-cured black olives
</P>
<P>
   1 (28-ounce) can whole tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound linguine pasta
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried oregano leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons small capers, drained
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Large handful Italian parsley, trimmed (about 1/3 cup minced)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Start a pot of liberally salted water boiling for the pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the garlic and thinly slice. Remove spines from the
anchovies, if necessary, and leave whole (ignore the tiny pin
bones). Pit the olives and coarsely chop.
</P>
<P>
   Place the tomatoes and half their juice in a large bowl. Using
your hands, squeeze to break them up into small pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Begin cooking the pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large skillet. Add the red pepper flakes,
oregano and garlic and saute until just golden, about 1 minute. Add
the anchovy fillets and mash with a spoon until they dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   Add the tomatoes, capers and olives to the sauce, plus a
grinding of black pepper. Simmer steadily for 7 minutes, then
adjust seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   While the sauce cooks, mince the parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Drain pasta and return it to its pot. Add the sauce and simmer
over low heat, stirring for 1 minute, to incorporate. Stir in most
of the parsley. Sprinkle the remaining parsley over each serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 605 calories, &LR;   &LR; 18 g protein, 96 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 17 g fat (2 g saturated), 7 mg cholesterol, 634 mg
sodium, 2 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1816EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
