<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3788 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SECRET-UDON-SFCHRON &LR;      03-21 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-UDON-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: O Chame's Noodles Are O So Good   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  David Vardy has a unique personal vision of
East-West cooking at O Chame in Berkeley. While he wouldn't claim
to be a Japanese chef, his sensibilities are as traditional as his
top-level Tokyo counterparts.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At his restaurant, he has become known for his noodle dishes,
and what he creates is superior to any of the noodle houses in San
Francisco's Japantown. The broth, made with dried bonito tuna
flakes and seaweed, has a subtle smokiness that pairs well with
myriad toppings.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular combinations is the fleshy udon noodles
with smoked trout. The bland noodles, the peppery daikon sprouts,
and the flaky smoked fish combine for a bracing and restorative
combination.
</P>
<P>
   At the restaurant, the large udon (wheat) and the more delicate
soba (buckwheat) noodles are served in large potter bowls,
shimmering in the bonito-based broth. Combinations include shrimp
with wakame seaweed; grilled chicken breast with spinach; and beef
with burdock root and carrots.
</P>
<P>
   The room has a similar cross-cultural orientation, and it
translates into a peaceful setting that is soothing after a long
day. The focal point of the room is an Oriental carpet at the
entrance, centered under a long table that holds a vase with an
arrangement of grasses and blooms, platters of wonderful cookies,
and a few baked goods.
</P>
<P>
   The terra-cotta-colored stucco walls are subtly etched with a
dragon and other Asian scenes. The Japanese country feel is further
enhanced with the straight-back rough wood chairs and a round
window inset with bamboo.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; O Chame, 1830 Fourth St. (near Hearst), Berkeley; (510) &LR; 
 &LR; 841-8783. Lunch, dinner Monday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Simmering the seaweed. &LR;  Kombu, or kelp seaweed, gives the
water a silken texture by releasing a sticky substance with the
consistency of aloe. If boiled, this texture will be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Simmering the bonito. &LR;  Much like a French fumet, the fish
flakes should not be boiled. The water needs to be brought to a
simmer and immediately removed from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Cooking the noodles. &LR;  The noodles are cooked like pasta, but
you don't want them to be al dente. They should be cooked through
and tender. Do not put any salt or oil in the water during cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
UDON NOODLE SOUP WITH SMOKED TROUT
</P>
<P>
   This traditional Japanese noodle dish is versatile. A number of
toppings, including grilled chicken, shrimp or thinly sliced beef,
may be substituted for the trout. Other julienned vegetables such
as daikon, carrots or cabbage also may be added. All the
ingredients, except the smoked trout, are readily available at
Japanese grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   1 piece (about 3 x 4 inches) dried dashi kombu (kelp)
</P>
<P>
   3.5 ounces shaved dried bonito flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup mirin
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Japanese soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   3/4 tablespoon sea salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dried udon noodles
</P>
<P>
   4 smoked trout fillets
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch daikon radish sprouts (about 4 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the water and dashi kombu in a 8- to 10-quart pot. Set
over medium-low heat and slowly heat the water until almost ready
to boil, about 50 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Using tongs, remove the dashi kombu and discard. Add the bonito
flakes and bring to a simmer over medium heat, skimming any scum
that forms on the surface. Do not boil. Immediately remove from
heat and let stand for 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the broth through a cheesecloth-lined sieve or a
fine-mesh sieve, pushing hard on the bonito to release all the
liquid. Discard the bonito.
</P>
<P>
   Return the strained liquid to the pot and add the mirin, soy
sauce and salt. Bring to a simmer and cook for 2 minutes to blend
the flavors. Add more salt, if needed. The stock may be used
immediately or refrigerated and reheated when needed.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, cook the udon in a large pot of boiling
unsalted water until tender, about 12 to 15 minutes. Drain. Rinse
with cold water.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the noodles among serving bowls. Top with the trout
fillets (either whole or cut into bite-size pieces), daikon sprouts
and scallions. Gently pour 11/2 to 2 cups hot broth over each bowl
of noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 720 calories, &LR;   &LR; 35 g protein, 68 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 35 g fat (7 g saturated), 65 mg cholesterol, 2,970
mg sodium, 6 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1817EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
