<SLUG> BC-SUPPORTING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 And the Best Supporting Flavors Are . . . Spices herbs, coffee  and
citrus boost the star power of the whole production   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  If the food world awarded Oscars to ingredients,
Best Supporting Flavor would be a critical category.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a good movie, a good dish depends just as much on its
supporting cast as it does on its star. Supporting flavors make
food interesting, bite after bite, giving a dish fullness and extra
verve. A whisper of vanilla boosts the flavor of chocolate; a
grating of nutmeg adds nuance to a cream sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Just like actors, supporting flavors can be leads as well.
Vanilla, for example, is as versatile as Kevin Spacey. He's
nominated this year for Best Actor in ``American Beauty'' but he's
tops at smaller roles, too, like his Oscar-winning Best Supporting
role in ``The Usual Suspects'' in 1995. Just like Spacey, vanilla
enhances the whole, no matter the size of the particular part.
</P>
<P>
   More exotic ingredients, like star anise and lavender, are
reminiscent of Angelina Jolie, nominated for Best Supporting
Actress in ``Girl, Interrupted'' _ an intense, mysterious
undercurrent.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are flavors that fit into the ``Jim Carrey
category.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrey has been overlooked for his work in films like ``The
Truman Show'' and was left out again this year for ``Man on the
Moon.'' Chile peppers and cloves are the food world equivalent _
because they can take a dish over the top unless they are used
judiciously, they may not be considered a best supporting
ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   The key to getting the most out of these ingredients is knowing
how they work in supporting roles. Cooks assume the roles of
directors, learning where and when to coax and combine
performances.
</P>
<P>
   So, with Oscars taking center stage on Sunday, here our our
nominees for Best Supporting Flavors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VANILLA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No ingredient has as wide a range as vanilla. Vanilla brings out
the best in a chocolate chip cookie, but it also has a magical
effect on lobster bisque, where it intensifies the sweetness of the
shellfish. It also brings out shrimp's sweet flavors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FENNEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The licorice notes of fennel do the same thing for seafood
dishes, which is what makes it so important for bouillabaisse.
Whether you use fresh fennel or fennel seeds, the effect is similar
_ the fish will taste sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MINT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mint is also a candidate. It's no secret why so many cuisines
pair lamb and mint. The herb cuts through the rich flavors and
fattiness of the meat plus it adds a refreshing herbal note to the
entire dish.
</P>
<P>
   Mint can also work in salad. Throw whole leaves in with baby
greens dressed with a tart lemon vinaigrette and it adds a yet
another layer of flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITRUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Citrus fruits garner an out-of-left field nomination because
they're more often used as the star. But they're the kamikaze of
supporting ingredients _ when used in the right amount, they
sacrifice their own flavor for the benefit of the overall dish.
</P>
<P>
   Squeeze a lemon on a piece of fish and it's not the lemon you
taste but rather a tingling tartness that aligns with the fish's
inherent flavor, cutting its natural oils.
</P>
<P>
   And citrus isn't just for fish. Chef Paul Bertolli of Oliveto in
Oakland serves his breaded lamb chops with lemon wedges, but not
just as a garnish. A few drops of the juice permeates the oil
flavors and crispiness of the crust, lending the dish a fresher
flavor. It does the same for  &LR; Wiener &LR;   &LR; schnitzel &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COFFEE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Coffee seems an unlikely supporting ingredient nominee, but when
used correctly it can embolden the flavor of beef stew or braised
lamb shanks. It also makes chocolate taste more chocolate-y.
Recipes for chocolate desserts often call for a bit of espresso
powder to push the flavor up a notch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STAR ANISE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Star anise has been playing in the Asian cooking arena for
hundreds of years, but can add an intriguing supporting note to a
wide variety of dishes. Throw a couple pieces in a pot of white
beans and watch diners try to figure out what accounts for the
elusive flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Star anise also adds an intriguing fragrance to soups and
desserts, particularly those made with fruit. Pastry chef and
cookbook author David Lebovitz uses it in poached pears along with
cinnamon sticks and black pepper. It's a marvelous combination.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAVENDER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Then there's lavender, the floral back note to herbes de
Provence. Combined in small quantities with lemon, garlic and other
herbs, the dried buds offer an almost indescribable flavor. Chefs
at Cafe La Haye in Sonoma use lavender with black pepper on a filet
mignon, and the meat is magnificent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHILES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Chile peppers are one of those ingredients thought to be fit
only for starring performances. They're so powerful they tend to
obliterate everything else. But, just like a good director, a
knowledgeable cook can use the tiniest amount to add unexpected
heat to dishes like chocolate ice cream. It's a surprising
combination, but it can work.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLACK PEPPER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Along the same lines, a few grinds of black pepper over apple
pie filling before the pie is baked adds a tingling sensation to
each bite. The pepper makes the apples taste more exciting.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLOVES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Cloves, too, can overshadow all else. Use too much and short
ribs braised in wine and tomato sauce taste like they should be
served for Christmas breakfast, but in small quantities _ 1/2
teaspoon in a humongous pot _ the sauce gets a sweet, fragrant and
mysterious quality.
</P>
<P>
   So while Hollywood turns the spotlight on its stars on Sunday,
let's give a round of applause today to supporting ingredients.
They're showcased in the accompanying recipes that will also let
you polish your ``director's'' skills so you can get the most out
of ingredients that may not be at the top of the casting call.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MUSSELS IN COCONUT BROTH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A squeeze of lime juice added just before serving significantly
brightens the flavors of the broth.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 (14-ounce) can unsweetened coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-ounce) bottle clam juice
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 stalks lemongrass, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1-inch knob fresh ginger, cut into 4 slices
</P>
<P>
   Salt and white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds mussels, scrubbed and debearded
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the coconut milk, clam juice, onion, lemongrass, garlic
and ginger in a heavy large saucepan. Simmer 15 minutes to blend
flavors. Strain.
</P>
<P>
   Return the broth to the saucepan. Season with salt and white
pepper. Bring to a boil. Add the mussels. Cover and simmer until
the mussels open, about 5 minutes. Remove from heat. Discard any
mussels that do not open.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the mussels among serving bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Add the lime juice to the broth. Adjust seasonings if necessary.
Pour over mussels and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 as an appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 165 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 3 g carbohydrate,
15 &LR;   &LR; g fat (13 g saturated), 25 mg cholesterol, 198 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; RHUBARB &AMP; DRIED FRUIT COMPOTE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Star anise adds a haunting fragrance and elusive flavor to this
versatile fruit compote. Use as a topping for ice cream or
breakfast waffles, or as a condiment with roasted pork tenderloin.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   13/4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   4 strips orange peel, each about 3x1 inches (orange part only)
</P>
<P>
   2 whole star anise
</P>
<P>
   1 cup tart dried fruit (such as dried cranberries and cherries)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sweet dried fruit (such as apricots, pears and peaches),
cut into 1/2-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup currants
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped candied ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 cup 1/2-inch pieces of fresh rhubarb
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the water, sugar, lemon juice, orange peel and star
anise in a heavy medium saucepan. Stir over medium heat until the
sugar dissolves. Add all of the dried fruit and the candied ginger.
Simmer 10 minutes. Add the rhubarb and simmer until it is tender
and the liquid is a syrupy consistency, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 30 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 8 g carbohydrate,
0 &LR;   &LR; fat, 0 cholesterol, 0 sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ROAST LAMB WITH MINT PESTO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Fresh mint cuts the richness of the lamb and pairs well with the
garlic. Try this as a sandwich on a split baguette with crumbled
feta cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   31/2- to 4-pound boneless leg of lamb, rolled and tied
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon + 1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dried marjoram
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup (packed) fresh mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup toasted pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Make small slits all over the lamb. Insert garlic into each
slit. Rub the lamb with 1 tablespoon olive oil and the marjoram.
Season generously with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Place the lamb in a roasting pan. Roast 20 minutes. Reduce oven
temperature to 375 degrees. Continue roasting until the lamb
registers 130 on a thermometer inserted into the thickest part of
the meat, about 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the lamb to a cutting board. Tent with foil and let
stand 15 minutes before carving.
</P>
<P>
   Process the mint leaves and sugar in a processor until the mint
is finely chopped. Add the lemon juice and pine nuts and process
until the nuts are chopped. With the processor running, gradually
add the remaining 1/4 cup oil and process until the mixture is
completely emulsified. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Slice the lamb. Arrange on a platter. Drizzle with the mint
pesto.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 645 calories, &LR;   &LR; 74 g protein, 3 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 36 g fat (11 g saturated), 237 mg cholesterol, 184 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; GRILLED LAVENDER CHICKEN ON ARUGULA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Lavender adds an unusual floral flavor to the chicken and lemon.
Arugula works as a bitter counterpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dried lavender blossoms
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coarse salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coarsely cracked black pepper + pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon + 1/2 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 boneless chicken half-breasts, with skin
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey (preferably lavender honey)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh tarragon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   4 cups arugula
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the lavender, lemon zest, salt and pepper in a mortar
and pestle and grind to a fine powder. Stir in the 1 tablespoon oil
to form a paste. Smear the paste on both sides of the chicken,
smearing some under the skin. Cover and refrigerate at least 1 hour
and up to 4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a barbecue (medium-high heat; alternately you may cook
the chicken on a grill pan on top of the stove).
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the lemon juice, honey, tarragon and mustard in a
small bowl. Gradually whisk in 1/2 cup olive oil. Season with salt
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Grill the chicken until cooked through, about 4 minutes per
side. Transfer to a cutting board.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the arugula with the dressing. Divide among serving plates.
Cut the chicken crosswise into 1-inch strips. Arrange on the
arugula. Drizzle with any remaining dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 550 calories, &LR;   &LR; 31 g protein, 8 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 44 g fat (8 g saturated), 92 mg cholesterol, 649 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WINE-BRAISED SHORT RIBS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Just a tiny amount of ground cloves adds a tingly sensation to
this dish. Resist the temptation to use more, which quickly takes
the cloves from a supporting role to an overacting position.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds beef short ribs
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   All-purpose flour for coating
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   21/2 cups dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   1 (141/2-ounce) can tomato puree
</P>
<P>
   1 (141/2-ounce) can beef broth
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   Hot buttered noodles
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat 2 tablespoons of the oil in a large Dutch oven over
medium-high heat. Season the ribs with salt and pepper. Coat with
flour, shaking off the excess. Working in batches, add the ribs to
the Dutch oven and cook until brown on all sides, about 10 minutes
per batch. Using tongs, transfer the ribs to a platter. Pour off
any fat in the Dutch oven.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining 2 tablespoons oil in the same Dutch oven over
medium-high heat. Add the onion and saute until beginning to brown,
about 8 minutes. Add the garlic and stir 2 minutes. Add the tomato
paste and cloves and stir 2 minutes. Add the wine and bring to a
boil, scraping up any browned bits. Boil until the liquid is
reduced by half, about 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the tomato puree, broth and bay leaves. Return the ribs to
the Dutch oven. Bring to a boil. Reduce the heat, cover and simmer
until the ribs are very tender, about 2 hours. Adjust the seasoning
with salt and pepper if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Place the noodles on a platter. Top with the short ribs. Pour
the sauce over and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 1,185 calories, &LR;   &LR; 103 g protein, 20 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 65 g fat (25 g saturated), 295 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 219
mg sodium, 3 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CHOCOLATE ESPRESSO COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   Espresso powder kicks up the chocolate flavor to an intense
level. The batter on these is a bit thin, but the cookies don't
spread out too much. The recipe works just as well as brownies,
baked in a 9-inch square glass baking dish for about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces bittersweet chocolate, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup golden brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon instant espresso powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup semisweet chocolate chips or toasted walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Line baking sheets with
parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Mix the flour, salt and baking powder in a small bowl. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place the chocolate and butter in a heavy small saucepan over
low heat. Stir until melted and smooth. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the eggs, sugar, brown sugar, vanilla and espresso powder
in a large bowl until well blended. Stir in the warm chocolate
mixture until combined. Stir in the dry ingredients, then the
chocolate chips or nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Drop the batter by heaping tablespoonfuls onto the prepared
baking sheets. Bake until the tops of the cookies crack and cookies
are softly set, about 12 minutes. Transfer the baking sheets to
racks. Cool 5 minutes. Transfer the cookies to racks and cool
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 30 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER COOKIE: &LR;   &LR; 130 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 12 g carbohydrate,
9 &LR;   &LR; g fat (6 g saturated), 22 mg cholesterol, 45 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; VANILLA SHRIMP WITH AVOCADO TARRAGON DIP
</P>
<P>
   This is Chronicle Food Editor Michael Bauer's recipe. He uses
vanilla to bring out the sweetness of the shellfish, and red pepper
flakes to punch up the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   24 ounces large shrimp, peeled with tails attached
</P>
<P>
   2 cups white wine (such as Chenin Blanc, Gewurztraminer or
Sauvignon Blanc)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 1 lemon, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Generous 1/2 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons finely chopped fresh tarragon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Avocado Dipping Sauce (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Rinse the shrimp in cold water and drain. Combine the wine,
orange juice, lemon zest, lemon juice, vanilla, pepper flakes,
tarragon, salt, pepper, garlic and 1/2 tablespoon of the oil in a
large bowl or heavy-duty gallon-size plastic storage bag. Add the
shrimp and stir to coat. Marinate for up to 6 hours in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the shrimp well. Heat 1/2 tablespoon oil in a heavy large
skillet over high heat until almost smoking. Working in batches,
add the shrimp to the skillet, season to taste with salt, and saute
until the shrimp curl and turn bright pink. Transfer to a serving
bowl. Repeat with remaining shrimp using more oil for each batch.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with Avocado Dipping Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10 as an appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING (without dip): &LR;   &LR; 75 calories, &LR;   &LR; 11 g protein, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 3 g fat (0 saturated), 84 mg cholesterol, 82 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 0 fiber.  &UR; Note: &LR;  The calories and other nutrients &LR; 
 &LR; absorbed from marinades vary and are difficult to estimate. &LR; 
 &LR; Therefore, this analysis does not include the marinade. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AVOCADO DIP
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe avocado, pitted and peeled
</P>
<P>
   Finely chopped zest and juice of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped fresh tarragon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 to 1/2 teaspoon ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 drops Tabasco
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Mash the avocado in a bowl until smooth. Stir in the remaining
ingredients. Cover and chill.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 20 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 1 g carbohydrate,
2 &LR;   &LR; g fat (0 saturated), 0 cholesterol, 68 mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
