<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3794 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-POPE-HOLOCAUST-0322-C     03-21 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOLOCAUST-0322-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOLOCAUST SURVIVORS LOOK FORWARD TO SEEING THEIR CHILDHOOD
FRIEND: THE POPE
 &HT;    (600&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-POPE-0322.
 &HT;    By DOUGLAS BELKIN 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In this land of distorted perceptions, it's not
surprising that a small group of people believe they are at least
partially responsible for the pilgrimage Pope John Paul II is
making this week.
</P>
<P>
   But the two dozen Holocaust survivors and their relatives _ who
will meet the pontiff at Yad Vashem, the Holocaust Memorial in
Israel, on Thursday _ may actually have a point.
</P>
<P>
   They knew the Pope as a boy, they say, when his impressions of
Jews were formed. And they contend that the relationships the young
Karol Wojtyla built with them and their families prepared the
foundation for the attitudes that have propelled John Paul II to
try and close the gap between Jews and gentiles throughout his
papacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has made some enormous steps toward the Jewish
people,'' said Meir Gorsky, an oral surgeon whose father grew up
with the future pope. ``And I think a lot of that comes from the
fact that he has a lot of Jewish friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in Wadowice, Poland, the small town located in the
Carpathian foothills 30 miles southwest of Krakow where Wojtyla
spent the first 18 years of his life, Jews and gentiles lived in
the same buildings, attended the same schools and played on the
same athletic fields. As a young man, Wojtyla even attended
synagogue to hear a famous cantor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He simply loved Jews and loved listening to Jewish chanting,''
said Joseph Bienenstock, an 80-year-old retired watchmaker who grew
up next door to the pope. ``There are no people like him. Not just
his position, I mean as a human being. He has been able to address
all of the
</P>
<P>
   Catholics in the world to stop anti-Semitism and remove the
notion that we are responsible for the crucifixion of Jesus. No
Pope has declared this in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Wojtyla was 19 when the Nazis invaded Poland in 1939, and not
long after virtually every Jew in the small town disappeared. Some
fled; others were deported to death camps. More than 3 million
Polish Jews were murdered by the war's end.
</P>
<P>
   Among them were 42 of the 47 members of the family of Meir Lau,
the chief Ashkenazi rabbi of Israel. As a boy, Wojtyla often saw
Lau's grandfather walking to synagogue surrounded by his children
and grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul's friendships with Jews are important, Lau said, but
the empathy he has demonstrated as a result of those friendships
toward Jews is even more so.
</P>
<P>
   What has most impressed Lau about John Paul was a decision the
pontiff made 44 years ago when he was still a young priest.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, a Jewish couple gave their 2-year-old boy
to Catholic neighbors for safe-keeping immediately before the Nazis
deported them, Lau said. The parents asked their neighbors to send
the boy to relatives in America if they did not return.
</P>
<P>
   But four years later, after it became clear that the parents
were dead, the neighbors decided to adopt the child. They brought
him to the local parish to have him baptized, but their priest,
after learning of the circumstances surrounding the adoption,
refused their request. Instead he urged the couple to send the boy
to his relatives in America.
</P>
<P>
   That priest, Lau said, was Father Karol Wojtyla.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, John Paul's visit to Israel is not without
controversy. Some in the Jewish community have criticized the
pontiff for not mentioning the Holocaust specifically during his
apology a week ago Sunday. Others have complained he has not
demanded the removal of several crosses at Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most divisive is the Vatican's move to consider Pope
Pius XII for beatification. Many believe anti-Semitism motivated
Pius_relative reticence during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can and here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But supporters point to the things John Paul II has done, often
away from the public eye, to take the measure of the man. For
instance, years after the war, when he was a young bishop, Wojtyla
was visiting Wadowice when he came across the grave of
Bienenstock's younger brother in the Jewish cemetery. The cemetery
caretaker told the bishop Nazis had beaten Bienenstock to death.
His grave marker was a simple inscription on a piece of tin. The
bishop, who knew the Bienenstock family well, paid to have it
replaced with a marble tombstone.
</P>
<P>
   Jews who know the pope say these experiences have shaped him,
and by extension, his papacy and the contemporary Catholic church.
He has reached out to Jews at hundreds of occasions throughout his
career, said Rabbi David Rosen, the Jerusalem director of the
Anti-Defamation League.
</P>
<P>
   When he remembers those who died in the Holocaust, he does not
remember faceless victims, but friends and classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they lived in Wadowice, my father used to play the piano
and the pope used to sing,'' said Meir Gorsky. ``I don't think you
just forget things like that. They shape you, they are a part of
who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
