<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3798 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GUN-ENFORCEMENT22-COX     03-21 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-ENFORCEMENT22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR NRA, ENFORCEMENT OF GUN LAWS IS THE CENTRAL ISSUE
 &HT;    640&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Rifle Association, criticized for its
harsh rhetoric and hard-line opposition to gun-control, is fighting
back by focusing on a popular message _ enforcing gun laws already
on the books.
</P>
<P>
   The theme resonates in NRA President Charlton Heston's defiant
ads on television, in public remarks by other officials and
supporters, and in multiple essays and press releases on the
group's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the polls I've seen, going back years and years, indicate
that Americans expect and want enforcement of laws that prohibit
felons from carrying guns, prohibit drug dealers from carrying
guns, prohibit violent felons from even trying to get them,'' said
NRA spokesman Bill Powers. ``And yet those laws are never enforced
or hardly ever enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   Powers said that the NRA has pushed the issue for several years.
Now, he said, it ``has reached a broader spotlight and is being
discussed at the national level,'' and that is a ``positive thing
for all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and gun-control advocates have pounded the NRA
for opposing gun-show restrictions and other bills in Congress, and
for criticizing last week's agreement by gun maker Smith and Wesson
to provide trigger locks with every gun it ships.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some moderate Republicans such as Gov. George
Pataki of New York and former President Gerald Ford have said the
GOP should accept some gun restrictions that the NRA has
steadfastly rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The group's response has been to emphasize its enforcement
message, which enjoys broad public support, according to polls by
conservative groups and the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But the message hit a sour note recently when NRA Executive Vice
President Wayne LaPierre said on a television talk show that
Clinton is ``willing to accept a certain level of killing to
further his political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Even leading Republicans criticized that comment.
</P>
<P>
   The party's expected presidential nominee, Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, said LaPierre went too far. Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois,
chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, said ``it's an extreme
statement'' and not ``terribly helpful to trying to reach a
consensus on a very difficult issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But LaPierre has not backed down from his stance, and Heston
also defended it, telling NBC's Maria Shriver on Monday: ``You guys
owe Wayne an apology. He was right and you guys were wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Heston refused to discuss the comment further, focusing instead
on the case of Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, previously known as H. Rap
Brown, who was captured Monday as a suspect in the shooting death
of Fulton County, Ga., Sheriff's Deputy Ricky Kinchen.
</P>
<P>
   Other NRA officials have followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a deputy sheriff in Atlanta dead today because the
charges against H. Rap Brown with respect to felony possession
charges were dropped,'' Powers said. ``He should be in the middle
of a 10-year sentence in a federal prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials involved in Al-Amin's 1995 gun case said Monday that
it disintegrated because a key witness in a related charge recanted
his story.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocates say the NRA's stress on the enforcement
issue is hypocritical because the group has opposed bills in
Congress that would strengthen enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   A group of Democratic lawmakers Tuesday introduced a measure
that would pay for 1,000 new local, state and federal prosecutors,
500 ATF agents and inspectors, local anti-gun media campaigns and
other programs. It would also increase ATF inspections of firearms
dealers and improve record-keeping of domestic violence offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said that the NRA should support
the bill if they are serious about enforcement. But he added: ``I
wouldn't hold my breath.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is pushing for laws to require safety locks on all
handguns, ban imports of large-capacity ammunition clips, and
require 72-hour background checks for buyers at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate have passed separate versions of a bill
that includes gun control measures but have not found a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, who is a leading gun control advocate in the Senate,
said that he wouldn't be surprised if Bush ``calls up (Senate
Majority Leader) Trent Lott and calls up (House Speaker) Dennis
Hastert and says: 'Hey, get me off the hook. Let this bill pass.'
``
</P>
<P>
   Bush will be faced with an important decision sometime this
year, Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can either break free of the NRA and help his party break
free of the NRA or he will lose a good percentage of swing voters,
many of whom ... tend to be suburban women.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has challenged Congress to pass some gun control
measures before April 20, the anniversary of the Columbine High
School massacre in Littleton, Colo. Two Columbine students used
high-powered guns to murder 12 students and a teacher before
killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso's e-mail address is eunicem(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
