<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3801 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-INDIA-PROTEST-COX     03-21 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PROTEST-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Police clash with Clinton protesters in India
</P>
<P>
   By Moni Basu
</P>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, INDIA _ Police fired water canons Tuesday afternoon
to subdue angry crowds protesting President Clinton's visit in the
heart of the Indian capital.
</P>
<P>
   Despite tight security throughout the city, the protesters,
carrying anti-U.S. signs and chanting ``Bill Clinton, go home,''
marched about a mile to the American Center, where they tried to
break through police barricades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want Clinton to interfere in India's matters,'' said
Chandrani Chatterji, a graduate student at Jawaharlal Nehru
University. ``Every time the Americans go somewhere to talk, they
end up getting involved. We don't need America to solve our
problems for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 350 protesters were affiliated with the Communist
Party India (Marxist), which opposes the growth of foreign
investments in India. It is generally believed that if Clinton's
visit achieves nothing else, it will at least succeed in forging
new trade links between the world's two largest democracies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think that the result of the Clinton trip will
mean more unemployment and hard times for Indians,'' said Suraj Dev
Singh, another graduate student at JNU. ``More privatization will
mean more foreign multinationals, which are basically interested
only in their own pound of flesh.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's protest was one of several that have been held in New
Delhi over the last few days. On Sunday, the day the president
arrived in the subcontinent, anti-U.S. demonstrators burned him in
effigy. Singh said the protests are designed to let the world know
that not all Indians support the ruling Bharatiya Janata Party's
friendly overtures toward the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's trip reflects the spineless attitude of the BJP
government when it comes to the United States,'' said protester
T.K. Rajlakshmi, a journalist with a leading English-language
weekly magazine called ``Frontline.'' ``One one hand, they shout
nationalist slogans. On the other hand, they don't hesitate to
sponsor a complete sellout of the country,'' she said brushing back
hair soaking wet from the water canons.
</P>
<P>
   Although the demonstration threatened to turn violent with
protesters hurling stones, riot police were unfazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are doing what they are expected to do,'' said Ramesh
Rana, a senior police officer. ``It is nothing but meaningless
party politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's demonstration did not cut much ice with U.S.
officials, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demonstrations are a fact of life here. They aren't unusual at
all,'' said embassy spokeswoman Elizabeth Corwin.
</P>
<P>
   Also undeterred were a group of Indian community leaders from
across the United States, who traveled back to their homeland to
promote Indo-U.S. ties during Clinton's South Asia sojourn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The protesters have a lack of understanding of the modern
world and the free enterprise system,'' said Atlantan Antony
Thaliath, vice president of the National Federation of
Indian-American Associations. ``It's an old-fashioned way of
blindly protesting. They don't know what they are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFIA's Subash Razdan, also from Atlanta, said 14 members of
his organization met with Clinton in New Delhi on Sunday night.
Razdan, a native of the war-torn Kashmir region, said he is banking
on the president to help ease tensions between nuclear powers India
and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him we have enough confidence and faith in him that he
will go back with a (peace) treaty in his hands,'' Razdan said. ``I
am very hopeful that he will help bring permanent peace in Kashmir.
We are waiting for him to get the Nobel Peace Prize.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
