<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTERNET-TAXES22-COX     03-21 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TAXES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMISSION FAILS TO REACH COMPROMISE ON INTERNET SALES TAXES
 &HT;    720&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Long hours of closed-door negotiations Tuesday failed
to produce a compromise that would allow a federal commission to
make a formal recommendation to Congress on Internet sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The inability of the 19 members of the Advisory Commission on
Electronic Commerce to agree on language that could win a
``supermajority'' of 13 votes means Congress will not get the clear
direction it had sought on taxing electronic transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's two-day meeting here was its last scheduled
session. It was supposed to issue its recommendations by April 21.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the commission did vote 11-8 to urge Congress to
extend the current moratorium on new Internet sales through 2006,
ban Internet access taxes, repeal a federal 3 percent
telecommunications excise tax, and grant tax exemptions for sales
taxes on goods that can be ``digitized,'' such as records and
books. But that vote was short of the two-thirds requirement.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioners will continue to teleconference in coming
weeks to see if they can find language on which 13 of them can
agree.
</P>
<P>
   But the panel's chairman, Gov. James Gilmore, R-Va., said he is
still committed to sending Congress a majority report if a 13-vote
consensus is not reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we made a great deal of progress,'' he said. ``We're
going to present a wonderful majority report to Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's failure to accomplish its mission in Dallas suggests
just how difficult the sales tax issue will be for lawmakers, who
most likely will take it up next year. ``What we're reporting back
(to Congress) is, you know, this is a tough issue,'' said Stan
Sokul, a commission member and consultant to the Association of
Interactive Media.
</P>
<P>
   The inability to form a supermajority also demonstrated the
growing political clout of traditional retailers, who are angry
about the current situation.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, retailers must collect sales taxes from
customers only in states in which they have a physical presence, or
a ``nexus'' in legal terminology. That means an Internet retailer
without storefronts doesn't have to collect taxes on items shipped
out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional merchants, including powerful companies such as
Wal-Mart and Circuit City, say they want a ``level playing field''
on which all retailers share the same tax collection
responsibilities whether they are operating in a store, on line or
by phone or mail order.
</P>
<P>
   Most state and local government officials agree, saying public
coffers can't afford to lose sales tax revenues as more commerce
shifts to online companies. Sales taxes generate about a third of
all state revenues, or about $150 billion annually, and typically
are used to pay for schools, police, roads and other basic
services.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study at the University of Tennessee forecast that at
the rate electronic commerce is growing, states could be losing
$10.8 billion annually by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Although most Americans are now aware of the rapid growth of
electronic commerce, that was not the case in 1998. When Congress
created the commission that year, it was widely expected that the
group would urge lawmakers to keep cyberspace free of the
responsibility to collect and remit out-of-state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many observers believe the Republican-led Congress
stacked the commission to make sure that would be the outcome. For
example, the six business representatives were all chosen from
companies with significant online operations: America Online, AT&AMP;T,
Gateway, MCI WorldCom, Charles Schwab and Time Warner. No
traditional retailer had a voice.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gilmore, a staunch opponent of Internet taxes, was
made chair of the commission.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, the ``level playing field'' argument has
been gaining adherents, even among many conservatives who fear
lawmakers might look to income and property taxes to make up for
lost sales tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the effort to put online and traditional retailers
on equal footing admit, however, that sales taxes as they are
structured today are too complicated. The nation has more than
30,000 taxing jurisdictions, imposing a bewildering array of rates
and rules.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Michael Leavitt, R-Utah, a commission member who leads the
``level playing field'' forces, said states must begin to simplify
and coordinate their tax laws to prepare for the borderless
Internet age.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Back in Washington, the commission's failure to reach a
supermajority vote prompted Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., to introduce
legislation to extend the current moratorium on new Internet taxes
through 2006. The current ban is set to expire in October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   That move may also suggest that Leavitt's supporters are gaining
strength. McCain earlier had introduced a bill to impose a
permanent ban on Internet sales taxes, but his new bill merely
extends the moratorium. In a statement, McCain said he has ``become
convinced that we need more time to determine how state and local
governments will be affected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to consider ... how to ensure a level playing field
for all venues of commerce,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Tuesday it would support an extension of
the moratorium while the ``nexus'' issues get sorted out.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
