<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3808 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-DACHAU-ANNIVERSARY-HN     03-21 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DACHAU-ANNIVERSARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOOK TRACES THE ROOTS OF THE HOLOCAUST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in ``a'' and ``l'' categories)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It is not a date that comes readily to mind. But
it is as much a day of infamy as the 7th of December, 1941.
</P>
<P>
   On March 22, 1933, a few miles north of Munich, the German
government opened Dachau, the first in a series of concentration
camps. It was followed immediately by Esterwegen and Oranienburg.
Before they were through, the Nazis built more than 1,000 camps
throughout Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are well known by now: The Nazis killed 6 million
Jews, almost one-third of the world's Jewish population. They also
tried to wipe out the Sinti and Roma gypsy tribes, Soviet prisoners
of war, homosexuals, Freemasons, Jehovah's Witnesses, the
handicapped, the mentally disabled, and political and religious
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   No book yet written covers the subject as comprehensively as
``The Holocaust Chronicle,'' a not-for-profit, 765-page volume from
Publications International of Lincolnwood, Ill. The book, published
by Louis Weber with contributions from a number of professors,
describes the history of the Holocaust year by year, starting with
Germany's economic troubles after World War I and ending in 1999
with Holocaust survivors applying for their share of a $1.25
billion settlement with Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holocaust Chronicle'' (which is being sold in lots of six
books for $100), offers an 80,000-word time line and a forward from
Dr. Michael Berenbaum, project director of the Holocaust Memorial
Museum, that says, in part, ``What does the Holocaust have to do
with our world? ... Sadly, students today do not have to ask
whether what they are studying is relevant. The images of Bosnia,
Rwanda and Kosovo are embedded in their consciousness, more deeply
engraved in their being than images of Cambodia and Biafra from two
decades ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holocaust Chronicle'' traces the tragedies at the end of
World War I _ an estimated 250,000 Germans starved in 1918 _ to May
1996, when mental patients' brains, kept in formaldehyde for more
than 50 years after being experimented on by the Nazis, finally
were buried in Hamburg. It is an 80-year saga that is still
unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   In 1923, inflation led to an exchange rate of four billion marks
to one dollar, paving the way for such groups as the German Workers
Party (later to become Adolf Hitler's National Socialists) to gain
power by finding scapegoats in and outside Germany. Evidence of his
anti-Semitism can be found as early as a letter Hitler wrote in
1919, while he was still in the army.
</P>
<P>
   In it, he talks of Jews as ``the racial tuberculosis of the
people'' and calls for ``the removal of the Jews altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitler, an Austrian who didn't become a German citizen until
Feb. 25, 1932, claimed 37 percent of the vote in Germany's national
elections that year. Once he was named chancellor in January 1933,
the country's freedoms deteriorated rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   After fire gutted the Reichstag in February, all 100 communists
elected to the German parliament were linked to the crime and
arrested. Within a month Dachau opened. By the end of the year
there were 50 concentration camps in Germany, dealing with more
than 30,000 inmates: Jews, communists, socialists and
``undesirables.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 1, the government called for Germans to boycott the
businesses of Germany's 565,000 Jews. On April 21, the kosher
method of slaughtering meat was forbidden. On April 25, public
schools were given non-Aryan quotas, cutting the number of Jewish
students allowed to 5 percent. In 1934, the same year Hitler was
voted the title of ``Fuhrer'' by the German people, the same year
all Jewish holidays were removed from the German calendar, the
government officially accepted the argument that Christ was not a
Jew, but a Nordic warrior put to death by the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuremberg Laws of 1935 decreed Jews were no longer citizens
but ``subjects'' of Germany. Marriage and extramarital relations
between Jews and people of ``German or related blood'' were
forbidden, Jewish civil servants were required to retire, and it
became illegal for Jews to fly the flag or display the Reich colors
of red, black and white. The definition of ``Jew'' was given as
someone with three Jewish grandparents, while those with two Jewish
grandparents, without a Jewish spouse, were labeled ``Mischlinge,''
a distinction that lost importance over time.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,400 anti-Semitic laws were passed in Germany between
1933 and 1939. Few freedoms were left by the time of Kristallnacht
on Nov. 9-10, 1938, a Nazi rampage that left 267 burned synagogues,
91 Jews dead and 30,000 more sent to concentration camps. All of
this came before the opening of World War II in 1939, when attacks
on European Jewry began in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The introduction to ``The Holocaust Chronicle'' acknowledges
that the subject ``invites a certain numbness of response. The mind
wants to shut down, turn itself off. And then you realize that
millions of individuals were killed. One death at a time _ an end
to a mortal existence for a person like you ... to express this
reality in a comprehensible way has been one goal of this book.''
</P>
<P>
   The liberation of the concentration camps began March 21, 1945,
nearly 12 years to the day from the opening of Dachau. Russian
troops found 200 women alive in the camp at Pruszez, Poland, out of
an original total of 1,100. On April 15, British troops reached
Bergen-Belsen, finding 60,000 survivors and 27,000 unburied corpses
(typhus would claim about 500 inmates a day for 10 days following
liberation). On April 29, the camp at Dachau, which started it all,
was liberated by American soldiers, who found 32,000 inmates and 50
railroad cars piled with corpses. The Americans rounded up 123 Nazi
guards and executed them.
</P>
<P>
   One day later, on April 30, Hitler and his bride, Eva Braun,
committed suicide in a Berlin bunker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
