<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3809 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-SMOKING-HNS &LR;      03-21 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-SMOKING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT REJECTS CLINTON PLAN TO REGULATE TOBACCO AS DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday rejected the Clinton
administration's plan to regulate cigarettes as drugs, ending the
federal government's main anti-smoking initiative.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-4 ruling, the court said U.S. Food and Drug
Administration officials overreached four years ago when they
claimed they had power over cigarettes and smokeless tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that Congress never intended for the FDA to
regulate the tobacco industry,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote
for the court.
</P>
<P>
   However, O'Connor stressed that the court's decision was not
meant to downplay the deadly consequences of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``By no means do we question the seriousness of the problem that
the FDA has sought to address,'' she wrote. ``The agency has amply
demonstrated that tobacco use, particularly among children and
adolescents, poses perhaps the single most significant threat to
public health in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco industry officials praised the decision, saying any
regulation of cigarettes should be left to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business and industry throughout the nation ought to breathe a
sigh of relief,'' said Mark Smith, spokesman for the Brown &AMP;
Williamson Tobacco Corp. ``The highest court in the land has
confirmed that a federal agency cannot on its own go beyond its
limits of authority set by Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican
presidential nominee, also agreed with the court's ruling and said
that ``decisions about tobacco regulation should be made by
Congress and state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-smoking groups said they would now focus on legislative
remedies. ``This ruling will put tremendous pressure on Congress,
especially during an election year, to ensure that nicotine does
not remain the only totally unregulated drug,'' said John F.
Banzhaf of Action on Smoking and Health, a Washington-based
anti-smoking group.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and several Democratic lawmakers urged
passage of legislation giving the FDA jurisdiction over tobacco,
but Republican leaders quickly opposed the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said of the FDA, ``I
don't think they do a very good job with what they're doing and
don't need any more responsibilities.'' House Majority Leader Dick
Armey, R-Texas, added, ``I'm not anxious to extend the power and
authority to the FDA.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the agency, tobacco use is the nation's leading
cause of premature death, resulting in more than 400,000 annually.
The agency also has found that people who reach age 18 without
smoking are unlikely to start.
</P>
<P>
   To help reduce the number of minor smokers, the FDA in 1996
entered the tobacco-regulation arena. Until then, the tobacco
industry was regulated primarily through congressional mandates
such as warning labels, a ban on TV ads and tobacco sales to
minors, and rules protecting nonsmokers from secondhand smoke in
confined places like airplanes and elevators.
</P>
<P>
   When the FDA wrote its rules aimed at curbing teen smoking, it
sought to keep vending machines out of places frequented by
youngsters and to ban billboard and magazine advertising aimed at
young viewers.
</P>
<P>
   But the tobacco industry, which feared that such control
eventually would result in a ban on cigarettes, challenged the
regulations. It argued that the FDA, from its establishment under
the federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act of 1938 until the mid-1990s
had rejected jurisdiction over tobacco and that Congress had never
granted the agency the authority to impose such restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, a federal appeals court in Richmond, Va., agreed
with the industry and struck down the regulations.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Supreme Court affirmed that decision, saying it
did not see how cigarettes could be classified in the same category
as a drug that is sold to prevent diseases or cure illnesses, which
was what the Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act was designed to cover.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said the FDA has concluded that cigarettes are unsafe
and dangerous. As a result, she said, federal law ``would require
the FDA to remove them from the market entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``The inescapable conclusion is that there is no room
for tobacco products within the (federal law's) regulatory scheme.
If they cannot be used safely for any therapeutic purpose, and yet
they cannot be banned, they simply do not fit (under the Food, Drug
and Cosmetic Act).''
</P>
<P>
   In her opinion, O'Connor was joined by Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist and Justices Anthony M. Kennedy, Antonin Scalia and
Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Stephen G. Breyer, John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter
and Ruth Bader Ginsburg dissented.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer, writing for the dissenters, said he did not believe the
1938 law would require a ban on cigarettes. He said the statute
allowed the FDA to seek a ``number of remedies'' other than barring
the sale of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer added that cigarettes have ``mood-stabilizing effects
through the interaction of the chemical nicotine and the cells of
the central nervous system.''
</P>
<P>
   The Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act defines a drug as a substance,
other than food, ``intended to affect the structure or any function
of the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Breyer said tobacco does fall under the FDA's jurisdiction
because cigarette manufacturers were aware of the effect of
nicotine on the body and ``intended'' to exploit that effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Far more than most, this particular drug and device risks the
life-threatening harms that administrative regulation seeks to
rectify,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite Tuesday's ruling, anti-tobacco forces have been winning
on other fronts. In several legal settlements with the states, the
major tobacco firms have agreed to pay $246 billion to cover
smoking-related health costs. The Justice Department has brought a
similar federal lawsuit against the tobacco firms, and several
class-action suits are pending in state courts. The nation's
largest cigarette-maker, Philip Morris Co., acknowledged last
October that smoking is addictive and causes cancer. The
third-biggest company, Brown &AMP; Williamson, said in April 1999 that
smokers ``are taking significant health risks.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, a Philip Morris Co. executive said the company was
willing to discuss some government regulation of the tobacco
industry, but that the firm still opposes the FDA's effort to
regulate tobacco as a drug.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department had no immediate reaction to the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, most tobacco stocks gained ground after the
ruling. Philip Morris was up 43 cents at $20.37 in early afternoon
trading on the New York Stock Exchange, where R.J. Reynolds Tobacco
was up 43 cents at $16.93, and Loews, which owns Lorillard, was up
$1.75 at $46.75. But the U.S. shares of British American Tobacco,
which owns Brown &AMP; Williamson, were down 62 cents at $9.62.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
