A3810 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-SMOKING-FDA-HNS     03-21 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-SMOKING-FDA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FDA WIELDS A BIG STICK OVER MANY PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Food and Drug Administration does not have the
authority to regulate tobacco as an addictive drug, the Supreme
Court ruled Tuesday, but the agency still has sweeping power over
what is manufactured, sold and eaten in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Those products include corn, Viagra, cosmetics, animal
antibiotics, pacemakers, breast implants and CD players.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA, which is one of the nation's oldest consumer-protection
agencies, traces its genesis to a 1848 law requiring the inspection
of foreign-made drugs imported into the country. The agency's
authority has grown considerably since then.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is responsible for monitoring the manufacture,
import, transport, storage, and sale of $1 trillion worth of goods
annually. It has some 1,100 investigators and inspectors who police
15,000 facilities a year as part of the regulatory oversight over
95,000 U.S. businesses.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 9,000 employees in 157 cities, the core of the
FDA is its scientific firepower: 2,100 scientists, including 900
chemists and 300 microbiologists.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FDA, about 3,000 products a year are deemed
unfit for consumers and are withdrawn from the marketplace, either
by voluntarily or by court-ordered seizure.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has different regulatory powers depending on the
product. For example, with drugs and medical devices, it has fairly
broad authority to assess whether a new product should be allowed
on the market. It relies on the manufacturers to provide studies
that prove the product meets the stringent threshold of being
``safe and effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the medical devices area, the FDA has different
regulation standards depending on the product's risk to the public.
For example, devices that are life-supporting, life-sustaining or
surgically put in the human body, such as pacemakers and breast
implants, must receive agency approval before they can be marketed.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA has power over the food supply. Its scientists regularly
test whether pesticide residue and other harmful agents are present
in unhealthy amounts. It sets labeling standards to let consumers
assess the nutritional value of foods. And the agency ensures that
the drugs given to animals _ especially those animals that wind up
in the food supply _ are safe for humans.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA is a key federal player in policing the nation's blood
supply. Investigators examine blood bank operations for
contaminants and poor record-keeping.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmetics also come under FDA's umbrella. However, the FDA is
only able to regulate them after they go on the market. But the
agency can order unsafe cosmetics removed from the market.
</P>
<P>
   Products that emit radiation are the FDA's responsibility. These
include medical products such as X-Ray machines and consumer
products such as microwave ovens, sunlamps and CD and DVD players.
The FDA helps set federal standards for the amount of radiation
that is safe and can order unsafe products removed from the market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1839EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
