u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      03-21 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, March 22 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INDIA (New Delhi, India) _ The United States and India
agreed to open a new relationship after what President Clinton
termed more than two decades of neglect. But in a series of
encounters between the countries' leaders, the opening chapter
proved to be spiked with surprises. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TOBACCO (Washington) _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday dealt
a sharp if not entirely unexpected blow to the Clinton
administration's effort to curb smoking, ruling 5-4 that the Food
and Drug Administration had never received authority from Congress
to regulate tobacco products. The decision, rejecting rules
proposed by the agency in 1995 to restrict the marketing of
cigarettes to children and teen-agers, hands the question of
national tobacco regulation back to Congress. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: an early version of this story has moved; the
1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   FED-RATES (Washington) _ The Federal Reserve clamped down a bit
more on the economy and the stock market on Tuesday, raising its
benchmark interest rate by a quarter of a percentage point in an
attempt to prevent an outbreak of inflation. The move was no
surprise to economists and investors, who had heard repeated hints
over the last month from Alan Greenspan, the central bank's
chairman, that he intended to continue with his policy of raising
rates in small, steady steps until he sees signs that the
supercharged economy is throttling back. Stock prices were up on
the news, with the Dow Jones industrial average gaining about 200
points for the day. The Nasdaq index was up 90 points. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DORISMOND-GIULIANI (New York) _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said
Tuesday that Hillary Rodham Clinton was engaged in a psychological
process called projection when she accused him of polarizing New
York City after the fatal police shooting of another unarmed black
man. ``It means accusing someone of what you're doing. That is
precisely what Mrs. Clinton is doing,'' he said. The mayor also
aggressively stepped up his attacks on Patrick Dorismond, the man
killed by police during an altercation on Thursday night, by
suggesting that Mr. Dorismond's previous behavior _ including a
fight with his girlfriend earlier this month _ may have contributed
to his death. By Elizabeth Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PUTIN (Moscow) _ Will the real Vladimir Putin stand up,
please? With five days left before the Russian presidential
election, perhaps the most striking observation about the vote is
that virtually no one - not rival politicians, not foreign
observers, not scholars of Russian politics and government _ can
say with certainty where Putin plans to take the nation. To an
amazing degree, he remains a blank slate, a vessel in which almost
any Russian faction can pour its dreams and hopes. By Michael
Wines.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ A federal judge on Tuesday refused to block
efforts to return 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez to Cuba, saying only
the U.S. attorney general can grant political asylum to keep the
boy in the United States. U.S. District Judge K. Michael Moore's
50-page ruling dismissed the lawsuit filed by Elian's great-uncle
Lazaro Gonzalez, who wants to keep Elian against the wishes of the
boy's father in Cuba. (Summary from wires) By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   ARTIST-LAWSUIT (Undated) _ A major art gallery is accused of
looting the estate of a prominent artist. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-HOLYLAND (Jerusalem) _ Saying he felt deep emotion setting
foot in Israel, ``the land where God chose to pitch his tent,''
Pope John Paul arrived in Tel Aviv on Tuesday, and was instantly
given a taste of the kind of fierce political intensity that will
vein his long-awaited religious pilgrimage to the Holy Land. The
Israeli president, Ezer Weizman, welcomed the first pope to visit
Israel in 36 years, with a blunt, at times defensive speech that
instantly bore into some of the key issues dividing the Vatican and
the Israeli government. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
