<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3813 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MCCAIN-RETURNS-HNS &LR;      03-21 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-RETURNS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     McCAIN RETURNS TO QUIET WELCOME IN SENATE  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain made his first Senate speech
Tuesday after losing his maverick bid for the Republican
presidential nomination, talking about Kosovo to a throng of
tourists and reporters and columnists but virtually no other
senators.
</P>
<P>
   McCain used his much-anticipated return to call for retaining
U.S. peacekeeping troops in Kosovo. He made only a passing
reference to campaign finance reform, the theme that had fueled his
presidential campaign when he repeatedly charged that Congress has
been corrupted by special interest money.
</P>
<P>
   After McCain wrapped up his 15-minute speech by thanking the
American people for ``their consideration of my candidacy,'' only
Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nevada, the No. 2 Democrat, came over to chat
with him.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said later he hadn't alerted his colleagues about his
plans to speak on the Senate floor because he wanted it to be ``a
normal occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Larry Craig of Idaho, the No. 4 Republican, said he didn't
go because he had expected McCain to speak after lunch. McCain's
fellow Arizona Republican, Sen. Jon Kyl, explained that he wasn't
there because he didn't have enough notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like there was any intention to snub him,'' Kyl said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said he didn't know McCain was ready
to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have come back and listened if somebody had told me,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The stillness on the Senate floor was in marked contrast to the
cheering mob of tourists who flocked around McCain as he walked
from his office to the Senate floor, greeting him like a rock star
and telling him that they loved him.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate press gallery was packed with reporters and
columnists in such quantities not seen since President Clinton's
impeachment trial last year.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the chamber, reporters, who asked how it felt to come
back to the Senate, swarmed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrible, I hated it, depressing,'' McCain joked. ``I'd much
rather be on the `Straight Talk Express,''' the name he gave to the
bus he used during his campaign for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   McCain marched into the regular Tuesday lunch meeting of
Republican senators flanked by his four Senate Republican
supporters _ Fred Thompson of Tennessee, Mike DeWine of Ohio, Chuck
Hagel of Nebraska and Kyl. Later, McCain said he had received a
standing ovation after giving a short speech to say that he was
glad to be back.
</P>
<P>
   McCain told reporters that he would continue to press for
campaign finance reform, no matter whom he offends.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also said he plans to campaign for candidates who are
committed to his agenda, but then softened his stance, saying he
would help those willing to negotiate on his goal of banning soft
money, the unregulated contributions to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   McCain threw a jab at Vice President Al Gore, saying that if the
putative Democratic presidential nominee intends to embrace
campaign finance reform as he says, he must launch a complete
investigation into alleged abuses in the 1996 Clinton-Gore
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Craig described the Tuesday luncheon as ``a fairly modest
gathering, welcoming back a returning son.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig added he didn't think a lot of hoopla was appropriate.
``He won a couple of primaries,'' Craig said. ``That does not a
president make.''
</P>
<P>
   He then added sharp words for McCain: ``Anyone in this body who
runs around saying there is corruption (in the Senate) deserves
shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, told reporters he would have ``a
good relationship'' with McCain now that he is back.
</P>
<P>
   ``John doesn't bother me,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of sad to see him come back because I think I'm the
meanest man in town right now,'' said Stevens, well-known for his
gruff manner.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, said he had welcomed McCain back
into the fold by sending him ``a nice message for him and his
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said Republicans
have already mended fences with McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already put those planks back on the fence and we're on
about our business,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address Judy(at) hearstdc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
