<HEADER>
A3815 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-GOODY-BEAT-AZR &LR;      03-21 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-BEAT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE CAMERA TRICKS, `BEAT' WORTH A LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - You get the idea that there is much to admire in `The
Beat,'' UPN's new cop show, but it's hard to tell _ the one-hour
drama switches film stock and camera angles so often it makes
watching it lIKe TryINg tO rEAd ThE eNd Of tHiS sEnTeNCE.
</P>
<P>
   It's death by stylized filmmaking. One minute, we're watching
film, the format shows like `ER ''and `Judging Amy'' use. The next
thing you know, we're looking at grainy videotape, the kind of
thing employed by shows such as ``Cops.'' Show-offy camera angles
only add to the effect.
</P>
<P>
   Patrons with sensitive stomachs are encouraged not to enjoy this
ride.
</P>
<P>
   Like UPN's recent, unfortunate ``Secret Agent Man,'' ``The
Beat'' is something of a departure for the network _ none of the
action takes place inside a wrestling ring. Instead, it takes place
on the streets of New York City, arguably a reasonable facsimile.
The show follows the lives, both personal and professional, of
young cops Zane Marinelli (Mark Ruffalo) and Mike Dorigan (Derek
Cecil).
</P>
<P>
   And it comes from a top-shelf production team: The executive
producers are Tom Fontana and Barry Levinson (who wrote and
directed, respectively, the first episode), who have teamed up on
great shows, such as ``Homicide.''
</P>
<P>
   (One Fontana-Levinson quibble: Their presence means a cameo by
Richard Belzer as Detective Munch, who sighs, ``I'm nostalgic for a
good homicide'' at a crime scene. We get it, guys. We're sorry NBC
canceled your show, too. Now move on.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Beat'' is one of those cop shows that allows itself to
become mired in the minutiae of the job. Fights over who gets stuck
with the paperwork are common; at one point, our heroes argue about
what you call the dot on an ``i.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Beat's'' emphasis on the small details of its characters'
lives is a nice, if occasionally annoying, change. Dorigan has
recently gotten engaged to his med-school girlfriend and worries
about losing his youthful independence; Marinelli's romantic life
is a little more, shall we say, interesting.
</P>
<P>
   The first three episodes set an intriguing tone and do something
that seems to happen more and more rarely on series television _
make you wonder what'll happen next. Despite the heavy-handed
production techniques, ``The Beat'' is worth a try.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't forget the Dramamine. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
