<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3817 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-POPE-0322-1ST     03-21 1398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-POPE-0322-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: in 11th graf, for clarification, changes ' ... to come
here.' to ' ... to come to Israel.'
 &HT;    POPE MAKES HISTORIC ARRIVAL IN ISRAEL
 &HT;    (900&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With POPE-HOLOCAUST-0322.
 &HT;    EDs: John Paul II became pope in October 1978.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV, Israel _ On a pilgrimage aimed at sweeping aside
ancient animosities, Pope John Paul II Tuesday became the first
pontiff to make an official visit to the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   The Pope arrived at Ben Gurion International Airport in a Royal
Jordanian airliner, which had carried him from Amman, Jordan across
the desert and the Jordan River. Upon landing, Israeli and Vatican
flags were mounted in the cockpit windows of the Arab airliner.
</P>
<P>
   He kissed a golden bowl of earth held before him by three
children: one Muslim; one Jewish; and one Christian. They were from
the area of Nazareth, an Israeli city and the land of Christ's
youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the Holy Land,'' Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
told the Pope while shaking his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of Israel's top officials were lined on the red
carpet to greet the leader of the world's one billion Catholics.
Some were quick to use the event to stress Israel's control over
this disputed city of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The frail-looking 79-year-old pontiff moved slowly, but steadily
as he exited his airplane and stood for a 30-minute welcoming
ceremony under gray skies and a drizzle in mid-50s temperatures.
His arrival was met with the fanfare of the Israeli army's
orchestra and color guard.
</P>
<P>
   For the Pope, the trip is a deeply spiritual visit to the land
of Jesus Christ. He has declared 2000 a ``Holy Year.'' This trip is
the highlight of the church's ``purification of memory'' as it
starts the third millennium since Christ's birth.
</P>
<P>
   The trip may also be the most celebrated moment of his 22-year
papacy. This millennial push for reconciliation could determine his
historical legacy.
</P>
<P>
   The Pope is scheduled to spend five nights and six days in
Israel and the West Bank lands controlled by the Palestinian
Authority. On Wednesday, he goes to Palestinian-controlled
Bethlehem to hold a Mass near the birthplace of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   The Pope said he arrived with ``profound emotion'' and noted
that ``many things have changed'' in relations between Catholics
and the Jews. It is a history scarred by the violence of the
Medieval crusades, the oppression of the Inquisition and the
silence of many Catholics during the Nazi Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   He is only the second Roman Catholic pope to come to Israel. The
Vatican did not establish diplomatic relations with Israel until
1994, in part out of concern for Christians living in Arab
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The previous papal visitor, Pope Paul VI in 1964, only spent 11
hours in the country and refused to publicly say the word
``Israel'' or recognize the country's existence.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, John Paul II mentioned Israel four times in his
short airport remarks. He asked for better relations between
Muslims, Jews and Christians and between the competing _ sometimes
fighting _ Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``World opinion follows with close attention the peace process,
which finds all the peoples of the region involved in the difficult
search for a lasting peace with justice for all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My journey therefore is a pilgrimage in a spirit of humble
gratitude and hope, to the origins of our religious history. It is
a tribute to the three religious traditions which co-exist in this
land,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He finished his comments with, ``Shalom,'' the Hebrew word for
greetings and peace. The Pope was then driven to an awaiting
helicopter that took him to Jerusalem, where he will spend his
nights in the Vatican's delegation building.
</P>
<P>
   His last trip here was in 1963, as the Bishop of Krakow. He
would later write about it as an ``unforgettable experience.''
</P>
<P>
   This trip will take him to the most sacred places in
Christianity. In addition to the site of Christ's birth, his
schedule will take him later in the week to the traditional
locations of Christ's crucifixion and his Sermon on the Mount.
</P>
<P>
   He will deliver a Mass for an expected 100,000 people
overlooking the Sea of Galilee and visit the Western Wall, sacred
to Jews, and the Dome of the Rock, sacred to Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40,000 Catholics from around the world are arriving on
their own simultaneous pilgrimages.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout it all, the Pope will be enclosed in heavy security.
About 22,000 Israeli police and soldiers will be on duty during
``Operation Old Friend,'' in the Israeli portions of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The visit is fraught with the potential for political
controversy. Both Israelis and Palestinians seek symbolic
vindication in the papal visit.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leaders this week asked the Pope to advocate that
Israel share control over Jerusalem. Israel captured the eastern
portion of the city in 1967, and claims sole control. Most other
governments say its status is up for negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials Monday ordered the Palestinians to lower a
balloon flown in Jerusalem that dangled the Palestinian and Vatican
flags. Other squabbles have developed over everything from whether
Palestinian officials will be allowed to accompany the Pope to
certain sites, whether Israel should handle security in eastern
Jerusalem and even whether the Pope's stand-by ambulance should
carry the Star of David.
</P>
<P>
   Some extremist Jews have called the Pope and anti-Semitic
``pagan.'' Some Muslims have said they seek apologies from the Pope
for the Crusades, which past popes ordered in an attempt to conquer
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Local Christians, about 180,000 Arabs in Israel and the
Palestinian areas, hope the Pope's visit will bolster their
minority status here. But, many of them also hope he will speak out
for Palestinian rights.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The pope will make two high-profile, non-religious stops during
his trip. Wednesday, he will visit the Dheisheh Refugee Camp in
Palestinian-controlled Bethlehem. The 52-year-old camp is home to
about 10,000 Muslims with origins mostly in towns now controlled by
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, he will visit Jerusalem's Yad Vashem Holocaust
memorial museum, where he will meet Jewish survivors from his own
hometown in Poland. Though the Pope has expressed regret for the
inaction of some Catholics in the face of the Holocaust, some Jews
feel he has not gone far enough in his apologies.
</P>
<P>
   In his welcoming remarks, Israeli President Ezer Weizman
credited the Pope for his efforts to reconcile relations with Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appreciate your Holiness' contribution to condemning
anti-Semitism by labeling it as a sin against God and humanity and
by the request for forgiveness for deeds carried out in the past by
representatives of the Church against the Jewish people,'' Weizman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman also took the opportunity to remind the pope of Israel's
positions on key issues, calling Jerusalem the ``capital and source
of pride of the state of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert met the Pope's helicopter in
Jerusalem and said the symbolism of the pontiff's landing was
important. ``In my opinion we emphasized what we wanted to
emphasize and he let us do this,'' Olmert said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerusalem arrival culminated a long day for the pontiff.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, the Pope led a Mass before tens of thousands of
worshippers in an Amman sports stadium. He also visited a site in
Jordan that some archeologists say could be where John the Baptist
baptized Christ. That site presents competition to an Israeli site
long seen as the place of Christ's baptism.
</P>
<P>
   The busy day may have proved tiring for the Pope, who trembles
with the symptoms typical of Parkinson's disease. On his early
evening arrival in Israel, he gave a half wave upon exiting the
airplane and braved the breezes that almost blew off his white
skullcap.
</P>
<P>
   But, the site of the white-robed elder clearly energized those
who greeted him, shook his hand and smiled excitedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an historic moment and will be remembered in the
future,'' said Daphna Bar-Sade, the 11-year-old Jewish girl who
helped carry the bowl of soil the pope kissed. ``He looked fine for
his age.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
