<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHELSEA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN INDIA, CHELSEA CLINTON IS LOW-KEY STAND-IN FOR FIRST LADY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CLINTON-INDIA) 
(bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ With her mother campaigning in New York,
Chelsea Clinton stepped into the role of substitute first lady on
Tuesday. Dressed in a gray dress and jacket, she drove with her
father to the formal arrival ceremony at the presidential palace
and, a few steps behind President Clinton, shook hands with the
dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   She then took part in the president's homage to Mahatma Gandhi.
Both walked around the Gandhi bier scattering red rose petals from
a basket. Standing at a respectful distance, she watched as he
planted a flowering magnolia in the gardens of the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Clinton's role in India has been underplayed by the White
House. There have been no press statements of where she has gone,
or what she has done, and reporters have been discouraged from
asking. In part, she is reacquainting herself with a country that
made a big impression on her when she came in 1995 with her mother.
Then she visited clinics and rode an elephant.
</P>
<P>
   This time some sun is also locked into the schedule. On Monday,
she did not go to Bangladesh with the president but instead flew
with her grandmother, Dorothy Rodham, to a traditional palace in
Jodhpur, where she watched the annual festivity of Holi. This is an
Indian ritual that encourages people to splash colors on one
another. The brief account of her trip to Jodhpur in the newspaper
The Hindu said that she did not ``play'' Holi. And the accompanying
photograph of her leaving the palace showed her T-shirt splatter
free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
