<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3819 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-HOMEDEPOT-FLOORING-CO     03-21 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEDEPOT-FLOORING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot to test flooring store
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Depot said it will begin testing a freestanding flooring
store this summer in metro Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The 40,000-square-foot specialty store is the latest in a string
of growth concepts by the Atlanta-based home improvement retailer.
The name and exact location of the test store should be announced
within two weeks, said Pedro Mendiguren, vice president of
strategic business development.
</P>
<P>
   Floor-covering products have been widely successful for Home
Depot. With a steady expansion of flooring products beginning in
1996, the retailer quickly muscled past other chains as the top
seller in that sector.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's regular warehouse stores focus on lower price
points. Rugs and carpeting at the Expo stores carry a heftier price
tag.
</P>
<P>
   The new store, Mendiguren said, will sell roughly 15,000
flooring products with about 25 percent overlap of merchandise at
its existing locations. The retailer plans to hire about 30 to 35
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The store is going to cross the whole pricing range, from
entry points all the way up, although we won't sell some of the
(higher-end products) found in Expo,'' he said. Products will
include carpet, ceramic tile, laminates, wood and vinyl surfaces.
In addition, the store will sell window blinds and wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot, which operates more than 950 stores, has been
looking for growth outside its traditional warehouse store format
as it tries to double in size. The retailer has begun a national
rollout of Expo, its higher-priced decor chain. Last year, it
launched the Villager's Hardware chain in New Jersey, where it will
test four small-store formats.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer said it chose metro Dallas for the floor-covering
store because it has about 25 to 30 Home Depot stores and three
Expos in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a one-store test to understand how the flooring store
would affect and take market share from Home Depot and Expo
stores,'' Mendiguren said. Home Depot doesn't plan any changes to
the flooring selection inside its existing stores because of the
test, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The $30 billion flooring industry represents a fragmented
hodgepodge of home centers, retail chains and independent showroom
dealers. Even as the top-selling flooring retailer, Home Depot
holds just a fraction of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flooring business is ripe for a company like Home Depot,
which could bring some pricing credibility to the industry,'' said
analyst Wayne Hood of Prudential Securities. ``This business is
driven by rampant promotions _ 40 percent off one day, 60 percent
the next, and so on. It's very confusing for the customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hood said that Home Depot has a chance to build stronger
relationships with its floor product vendors, particularly Shaw
Industries, the largest carpet maker.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot stopped carrying Shaw's products in 1996, when the
Dalton-based manufacturer began buying retail flooring stores. Shaw
was blacklisted for several years but regained shelf space at Home
Depot after it sold its retail chain to Kennesaw-based Maxim Group,
which recently changed its name to Flooring America.
</P>
<P>
   The digestion of the unprofitable Shaw stores has been a
struggle for Flooring America, though. The franchise operates about
1,000 stores, including 300 company-owned locations. Company
executives declined to comment on Tuesday about Home Depot's
specialty concept.
</P>
<P>
   While it's too early to gauge the competitive impact of Home
Depot's venture, some observers said that independents have been
holding their own in the flooring industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle has been, can a store the size of Home Depot
provide the service an independent retailer can?'' said Frank
O'Neill, publisher and editor of Floor Focus magazine. ``The
independents have discovered that they can move their stores near
Home Depot locations and do very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
