<HEADER>
A3824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-NATO-420&AMP;ADD-N     03-21 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO SECRETARY-GENERAL DEFENDS MISSION IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ One year after NATO began its 78-day
bombardment of Kosovo, the alliance's secretary-general issued a
report Tuesday highlighting what he said were the unsung
accomplishments of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the United States ad its NATO allies have been
fighting among themselves over how to keep a deteriorating
situation in the Serbian province of Kosovo from spinning out of
control.
</P>
<P>
   And critics of the NATO campaign have said that the bombing had
resolved little and exacerbated ethnic tensions while destroying
large parts of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia is the larger of the two republics remaining in
Yugoslavia, and the bombing came as Yugoslavia refused to withdraw
troops it massed in Kosovo in response to an Albanian rebel
movement.
</P>
<P>
   In his personal report, titled ``Kosovo One Year On,'' the
secretary-general, Lord Robertson, appeared to be trying to
pre-empt a harsh review of the NATO offensive when tensions between
Serbs and the majority Albanians in Kosovo are rising again.
</P>
<P>
   He said the difficulties of the present situation should not
obscure the successes of the mission so far, including the
resettling of 1.3 million refugees, the reopening of hundreds of
schools and a drastic reduction in crime.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1999, the report said, there were 50 killings a week in
Kosovo. Today, there are about five a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is much too early to claim a complete success,'' Lord
Robertson said at a news conference at NATO headquarters in
Brussels. ``But it is also far too early to have claimed that we
failed. No one can be satisfied with the situation in Kosovo today
but it's wrong to say that nothing is going right.''
</P>
<P>
   The 20-page report, issued three days before the anniversary of
the day when the first bombs were dropped on Kosovo, said that NATO
force there has cleared mines or unexploded ordnance from more than
16,000 houses, 1,165 schools and almost 1,250 miles of roads. They
have also distributed over one million roofing tiles, 18,000 stoves
and 4,000 truckloads of firewood to Kosovo homes and villages.
</P>
<P>
   More than 43,000 people have received medical treatment at NATO
clinics in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Pentagon officials have grown increasingly worried
about the potential for renewed fighting in Kosovo, particularly by
Kosovo Albanian fighters using the relative security of NATO's
peacekeeping zones to carry out strikes against Serbs in Serbia,
just across the southeastern border of Kosovo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last week, the State Department's spokesman, James P. Rubin, met
with former leaders of the Kosovo Liberation Army, the rebel group,
including Hashim Thaci and Ramush Hajradinaj, as well as
representatives of Albanian fighters from the Presevo Valley in
Serbia, to warn against such attacks. A day later, U.S. troops
raided five villages along the border, seizing weapons, ammunition
and uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, NATO and Pentagon officials have been encouraged by
the willingness of Thaci and other Albanian officials to seek a
halt to cross-border raids. However, they said the NATO force in
Kosovo was not negotiating any agreement with the Albanians to end
the strikes in exchange for an easing of crackdowns like the one
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gotten some positive responses in words,'' the
Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said. ``What we need to see is
a positive response in actions, and only time will tell whether
they got the message and they're acting on it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Prague on Tuesday, the NATO commander, Gen. Wesley Clark of
the United States, rejected the contention that little had been
resolved in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of violence has come down remarkably, and what
remains is primarily organized crime and family violence,'' the
general said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the idea that there is a situation in Kosovo now ``that
resembles the situation before the air strikes is absolutely
incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   The general said that before the air strikes, the Serbs had
conducted a systematic government-sponsored campaign of
intimidation, repression and selective elimination of Kosovo
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said that there is still a high incidence of crime in the
ethnically divided city of Kosovska Mitrovica and other places in
Kosovo, but that it is lower than the crime rate in Moscow, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the NATO peacekeepers had been successful in
cutting off some of the supply lines to Kosovo Albanian
``extremists'' who were trying to stir up fighting in southern
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Robertson said that much work remains to be done and that
Kosovo is still in need of many resources, including funding for
U.N. projects.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``With inadequate money for the basic building blocks of
government _ wages for teachers, railway and municipal workers,
judges and prosecutors, for example,'' how can the U.N. entity
re-establishing civilian authorities ``establish an effective civil
administration, and exert the will of the international
community?'' he said. ``It is in the international community's
interest to provide the necessary resources, both personnel _ and
particularly police _ and funds to overcome the existing
shortfalls. Government, including NATO governments, must do more in
this respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeeping force is currently made up of 30,000 troops
from NATO countries and 7,000 from nonmember nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international community cannot leave the Kosovo job half
done,'' he said. ``This is a mission possible, but it's going to
call for patience, perseverance and resources.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
