<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, March 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Periods of snow will persist in parts of the southern Rockies as
a slow-moving storm center drifts east through southern New Mexico.
As the disturbance encounters humid air, strong thunderstorms will
erupt later Wednesday over parts of West and Central Texas.
Otherwise, clouds and scattered showers will prevail over the
southern and central Plains.
</P>
<P>
   The storm that brought locally heavy rain and some
high-elevation snow to the Middle Atlantic states will drift off
the Carolina coast. Patchy light rain will linger from southern
Virginia to the Middle Atlantic coast. Farther north, clouds will
be slow to break near the eastern Great Lakes and central
Appalachians, but high pressure will result in ample sunshine over
New England
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, after some early clouds. most of the Southeast and
Ohio Valley will be mild and dry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DENVER ICE
</P>
<P>
   As residents of the Denver area waited for a spring snowstorm to
arrive Monday, the roads unexpectedly became glazed with ice. Early
in the day, the temperature several thousand feet above the ground
where precipitation was forming hovered around freezing. A light
mix of snow and rain began to fall into a shallow layer of
sub-freezing air near the ground. The raindrops froze on contact
with the cold surface. As the storm strengthened later in the day,
rising currents of air lowered temperatures at cloud level,
changing the icy mixture to just snow. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
