<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3833 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-21 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH VERSUS GOP CONGRESS? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There were two sharply different Republican
reactions to a National Rifle Association official's incredible
accusation that President Clinton has ``blood on his hands'' for
failing to enforce current weak, under-funded gun control laws.
</P>
<P>
   Both responses were driven by politics, and they represented the
first important break between Texas Gov. George W. Bush and
congressional Republican leaders since he sewed up the GOP
presidential nomination on March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sensibly rebuked NRA Executive Vice President Wayne
LaPierre as having ``gone too far.'' Bush observed that there are
``ways to debate the issue without casting aspersions on the
president like that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the right stand to take, both morally and politically. As
Bush tries to shake his right-wing image and move to the
philosophical middle, he does not want to be seen as a tool of the
NRA. As governor he opposed gun control proposals but now he
gingerly suggests he might go for some modest reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Republican congressional leaders, however, made no move to
similarly distance themselves from LaPierre's nutty outburst. They
reacted as though charging the president with being an accessory to
murder was just another commonplace insult that Clinton richly
deserved.
</P>
<P>
   Their hearts are with the NRA and the lavish contributions it
pours into their campaigns, not with a president they despise and
failed to dump. Even so, they could have behaved with a little
decency.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee chairman Henry Hide was a picture of
tolerance, benignly calling LaPierre's statement ``extreme'' but
justifying it on grounds that ``it's a free country. People can say
what they want to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Legally, of course, people can indeed do that. But sane
discourse and malicious criminal accusations are different things
and require different responses from responsible officials.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde acknowledged that LaPierre was ``not helpful'' as Congress
struggles to find a compromise on safety locks and other gun issues
that are stalled in a congressional conference committee. ``Not
helpful'' is putting it mildly.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay was simply crass. He saw nothing
wrong with LaPierre's claim that Clinton accepted killings ``to
further his political agenda.'' DeLay blamed the fuss on a media
double standard, whining that he too had been accused of complicity
in murder _ by NRA foes _ ``but the press never picked up on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he added, ``We're covering up the real problem (of
violence) here we're talking about words they are not as important
as people who want to constantly zero in on one sentence here, one
sentence there.''
</P>
<P>
   Interpretation: It's only a word game, so who cares what is
said? Who cares that gun law enforcement is basically a state
rather than a federal responsibility?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the real problem is that there are too many guns too
readily available to too many unstable people of any age. President
Clinton himself acknowledged the need for more federal prosecutions
in his State of the Union address, proposing the hiring of more
agents and giving them tougher enforcement tools. The RNA, natch,
has opposed any more money for such efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The gun control issue will be a hot one in the fall presidential
campaign, and the split between Bush and his GOP congressional
allies could prove damaging.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier policy difference had surfaced between the candidate
who must run a national race attracting non-Republican votes and
conservative legislators who must run local races. Before it was
clear that Bush would be the nominee, GOP congressional leaders
rejected as too costly the centerpiece of his campaign, a massive
tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Instead they proposed a smaller one of their own that would not
decimate Social Security revenues. It was tailored along the lines
of a rival tax plan proposed by Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and congressional Republicans will be together on the major
goal of defeating Vice President Al Gore, but too much disagreement
on policy issues can be distracting and create the impression of a
party in chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.C. Watts Jr., chairman of the House Republican
Conference, says a new GOP poll indicates Bush may not be much help
to GOP congressional candidates. ``We can't rely on the
presidential nominee,'' Watts says. ``There's no coattails at this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   A lack of coattails encourages the exercise of a whole lot of
independence by those who would otherwise bow to the will of the
coat-wearer. Bush will have his hands full keeping his troops
marching in lock-step.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
