<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MEXICO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT JOINS VENTURE TO CREATE WEB PORTAL IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By DAN FINEREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The richest man in the world, Bill Gates, joined
forces Tuesday with the richest man in Latin America, Carlos Slim
Helu, in a battle to dominate the Internet in the region by
creating a portal site that combines the expertise of the Microsoft
Corp. with the communications reach of Telefonos de Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The portal site, called t1msn.com, began with 6 million users,
said Gates, Microsoft's co-founder and chairman. Latin American
subscribers to Prodigy, the Internet service of Telefonos de
Mexico, or Telmex, and to Microsoft's msn.com are automatically
channeled to the new portal, except in Portuguese-speaking Brazil.
Gates said that the Web explorer program on all personal computers
with Microsoft operating software that are sold in Latin America
will have t1msn as the first port of entry to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth opportunities we have in Latin America are stronger
than anywhere,'' Gates said in announcing the venture with Slim at
a Latin America Internet conference in Miami. Slim controls Telmex,
the formerly state-owned phone company that is now his flagship
business.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, with trips and stumbles, the Internet is coming of
age in Mexico. And with that, the battle for cyberspace supremacy
has begun.
</P>
<P>
   Grupo Televisa, the world's largest Spanish-language
broadcaster, has teamed up with USWeb/CKS, the global leader in
World Wide Web site construction, to take on the portal partnership
of Telmex and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   At first, there was talk that Televisa might join with the
Telmex venture rather than challenge it, and Televisa's president,
Emilio Azcarraga Jean, has not ruled out the possibility of joining
with Telmex in the future. With Microsoft and Telmex searching for
the best news and entertainment for the portal site, the
possibility of t1msn's contracting the services of the Televisa Web
venture is high.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Telmex officials are counting on their well-established
customer base in Mexico and infrastructure in the region, combined
with Microsoft's name and skills to give its portal a competitive
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the chief editor of Televisa's new portal, Ramon
Alberto Garza, has said that the site will build on the broadcast
empire's experience in traditional journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, Slim is in a strong position. The Mexican
billionaire already owns 24 percent of Televisa's holding company
Televicentro SA.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Televisa's efforts, Slim said Tuesday that he saw his
main opponent in the country's second-largest Internet service
provider, Terra Networks Mexico SA, which is backed by Telefonica
of Spain, the biggest telecommunications provider in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Slim has made it clear that he wants to battle to the top of the
Spanish-speaking Internet market. In May 1998 he took over the
Prodigy Services Corp., then a lagging Internet service provider in
the United States, and quickly turned it into the largest Internet
provider in Mexico. In January he bought a controlling share of
CompUSA, the largest personal computer retailing chain in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   To get more Mexicans online, Telmex is selling its clients
computers on affordable monthly installments charged to the
customers' telephone bills. The deal includes free Internet access
provided by Prodigy.
</P>
<P>
   But Slim is still hindered by the country's telephone network _
10.8 million lines for nearly 100 million people. Telmex has
announced plans to install 10 million new phone lines this year,
and it will promote its Internet services to every new subscriber.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
