<HEADER>
A3838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.NYT &LR;      03-21 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEIJING SEES TAIWAN AS MAIN ISSUE IN U.S.-CHINESE TIES, SAYS
HOLBROOKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. envoy to the United
Nations, concluded two days of talks here Tuesday with Chinese
officials on issues ranging from the world forum's economic
restructuring to its role in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But Chinese officials quickly turned the discussion to Taiwan,
where on Saturday a candidate whom Beijing opposed for his
longstanding promotion of the island's independence won the
presidency and ended more than a half century of Nationalist rule.
</P>
<P>
   China considers Taiwan a renegade province that must be reunited
with the mainland, and has threatened to use force to block its
formal independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese made it clear to us that the central issue in
Sino-U.S. relations from their point of view was Taiwan,'' said
Holbrooke, who was joined on the trip by Stanley Roth, the State
Department's top official on East Asia. He said the national
security adviser, Sandy Berger, would arrive in Beijing next week
for more talks.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks leading up to the Taiwan election, China's top
leaders mounted a menacing propaganda campaign against Chen
Shui-bian, whose Democratic Progressive Party's platform supports
independence for Taiwan. Chen himself has backed away from that
position, arguing that a formal declaration would be unnecessary,
given Taiwan's de facto independence.
</P>
<P>
   But since Chen's election, Beijing's reaction has been more
muted, and Holbrooke on Tuesday praised the ``cautious and prudent
approach that the Chinese emphasized in their discussions'' with
his delegation.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Chinese officials were appreciative that President
Clinton had reaffirmed Washington's longstanding position that
Taiwan and the mainland are part of ``one China.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, Chen and Chinese President Jiang Zemin have floated
trial balloons in their own media concerning the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, Jiang said that Taiwan must accept that it is an
inseparable part of one China as a pre-requisite for negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In Taiwan, Chen told reporters said he wanted to renew talks
with the mainland and was willing to discuss the principle of ``One
China,'' but not as a starting point for discussions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1905EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
