<P>
   DOTCOM-MANAGE (Undated) _ A feature by Wenda Harris Millard,
executive vice president of DoubleClick.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   HIRING-PITFALLS (Undated) _ In today's tight job market, many
companies have not been diligent in checking the backgrounds and
work histories of the people they hire. That can spell trouble,
according to executive recruiters and people at companies that
specialize in background checks. Some companies, especially
Internet start-ups desperate to fill large numbers of openings,
openly acknowledge that they lack the time and resources to verify
all the information that job seekers submit. Even recruiters of
senior-level managers acknowledge that the frantic competition for
talent can blind them to danger signs. ``Now, if a bird flies, you
go for it,'' said Peter Crist, vice chairman of Korn/Ferry
International, the global executive-recruiting firm. ``What happens
is, in a high-velocity market like this, it becomes more
mistake-prone.'' By Charles Butler.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
