<SLUG> BC-FILM-ROMEO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ROMEO': TOO FEW STUNTS, TOO MUCH TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Romeo Must Die. Directed by Andrzej Bartkowiak. Written by Eric
Bernt and John Jarrell. Cast: Jet Li, Aaliyah, Delroy Lindo,
Russell Wong, Isaiah Washington. Warner Bros. 110 minutes. Rated R
for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   The current wisdom in Hollywood is that audiences are bored
stiff with mindless action movies that offer nothing but a string
of explosions and karate kicks. The new look in action is a film
like ``The Matrix,'' which gives us not just mayhem but a certain
depth of character, an intriguing story premise and
state-of-the-art special effects.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese martial-arts star Jet Li's latest Hollywood movie,
``Romeo Must Die'' _ which advertises itself as being ``from the
producer of `The Matrix''' (Joel Silver) _ has this new look: it
has more characters than ``War and Peace,'' it borrows its plot
from Shakespeare and it throws in special effects in its chopsocky
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   But, this time, it doesn't quite work. The film's handful of
action sequences are terrific, but the script is simply not
substantial enough to support the bewildering plot, nor is Li actor
(or movie-star presence) enough to carry it. After a while, it
seems excruciatingly talky, and you find yourself nodding off in
the lengthy spaces between body blows.
</P>
<P>
   The story is a wink at ``Romeo and Juliet'' (or, more properly,
``West Side Story''), set against a gang war that breaks out
between an African American mob and a Chinese mob when a business
tycoon decides to buy up _ as the site of a new NFL football
stadium _ the Oakland waterfront they share as their joint turf.
</P>
<P>
   When the youngest son of the Chinese Godfather is murdered, his
older brother (Li) escapes from a Hong Kong prison, sneaks into the
U.S., inserts himself in the midst of the war and, in the process,
gradually falls for the beautiful daughter (Aaliyah) of the black
leader (Delroy Lindo).
</P>
<P>
   As befits the first directorial effort of noted cinematographer
Andrzej Bartkowiak (``Speed,'' ``Terms of Endearment''), it's an
ambitious movie. And a fair share of it works, including most of
the action, a wall-to-wall hip-hop score, some of the comedy relief
from Anthony Anderson (of TV's ``Hang Time''), and the performances
of the always-reliable Lindo and of newcomer Aaliyah, a
recording-star-turned-actress who is, by far, the brightest thing
in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the fight scenes are amazingly few and far
between, the special effects (X-rays of crunching bones in the
midst of the action) are low-impact and silly, the plot is
near-impossible to follow and star Li's limitations as an actor are
constantly calling attention to themselves. In fact, when not
kicking butt, he's kind of a blank spot in the center of the
screen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1918EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
