<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS, ISRAELIS MEET TO DISCUSS `FINAL STATUS' PEACE
ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Se also ISRAEL-WESTBANK, POPE-HOLYLAND)  
(jt) 
 By NEIL A LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With much of the Middle East focused on President
Clinton's upcoming meeting in Geneva with President Hafez Assad of
Syria, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators Tuesday quietly began
conferring here on a separate but equally critical series of
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli and Palestinian negotiators are working against a
September 13 target date to reach agreement on some of the most
difficult issues in any settlement between the two sides. The
negotiations, which are expected to last about a week and are
taking place at Bolling Air Force Base on the edge of the nation's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   They involve what diplomats have called the ``final status''
issues, including defining the Palestinian territories, Jewish
settlements, the identity of Jerusalem, water rights, refugees and
Palestinian statehood.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect this process to take a substantial amount of time to
overcome differences on these profound issues and therefore we
don't expect there to be early breakthroughs,'' said the State
Department spokesman, James P. Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the high-profile and ultimately unsuccessful negotiations
between Syria and Israel that took place under American auspices in
January in West Virginia, the new Israeli-Palestinian round is
expected to attract little attention. One reason, said an American
diplomat, is that both Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright are out of the country, visiting South Asia. Clinton is to
meet the Syrian president on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that, ``The goal is for it to be a serious
brainstorming session where the parties can really talk about the
issues in a more free-flowing fashion than they have been able to
do to date.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Tuesday to the Young Leadership Conference of the
United Jewish Communities, Rubin said that the administration
wanted the current round of talks to take place ``at a site away
from the limelight, away from the media where the two sides can
talk and we can talk to them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said in the speech that time is running short.
</P>
<P>
   ``But think of the potential results,'' he said. ``If this were
achieved, we know that the Palestinian-Israeli conflict is at the
core of the Middle East problem. And if we could resolve this core
issue, once and for all, it would make a profound difference to the
lives of not only the Palestinians and the Israelis but Israel's
entire role in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1922EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0265 </DOCNO>
