u f BC-CITIGROUP-APPOINT-NYT     03-21 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIGROUP-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIBANK FILLS TWO IMPORTANT EXECUTIVE POSITIONS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Moving to fill two high-profile positions that were
recently vacated, Citigroup, the nation's largest financial
services concern, appointed a new chief financial officer and a new
chairman of its consumer and commercial banking unit Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup said that Todd Thomson, who previously ran the
company's private banking arm, will immediately begin serving as
the chief financial officer, replacing Heidi G. Miller, who left
Citigroup last month for the chief financial officer's post at
Priceline.com, an Internet commerce company.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup also said that Victor J. Menezes will succeed John S.
Reed as chairman and chief executive of Citibank, the company's
consumer and commercial banking arm. Menezes, who will continue as
co-head of Citigroup's investment banking unit, will succeed Reed
on April 18, after the company's annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, 61, surprised the banking industry last month when he
announced that he would retire as co-chief executive of Citigroup
after the annual meeting. Reed's retirement plans, which will leave
Sanford I. Weill, 66, as sole chief executive of Citigroup,
generated wide-ranging speculation about who will emerge as Weill's
eventual successor.
</P>
<P>
   Weill declined to comment Tuesday about the succession issue,
but praised the abilities of Thomson and Menezes. While Thompson
and Menezes are also well-regarded by banking analysts, neither of
the executives are considered strong candidates to succeed Weill
when he retires. Weill has suggested that he might retire in two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a major reshuffling of the chairs,'' said Michael
Mayo, a banking analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston, of the job
changes at Citigroup. ``Rather, it's a fine-tuning of the existing
structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Although analysts consider Menezes, 50, to be an extremely
capable manager they say he lacks the charisma and stature needed
to run a company as sprawling, influential, and complex as
Citigroup. Thompson, who is only 39, is a relative newcomer to
Citigroup, having joined the company just two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup also said Tuesday that it plans to buy all of the
outstanding shares of its insurance unit, Travelers Property
Casualty, that it does not already own _ a move some analysts
believe could signal Citigroup's intention to expand its insurance
operations through acquisitions. Such an expansion would be made
much easier once Citigroup controls all of Travelers' shares.
Citigroup currently owns about 85 percent of Travelers' stock and
said it will purchase the remaining Travelers stock for $41.50 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   In heavy trading on the New York Stock Exchange Tuesday,
Citigroup's shares rose $1.875, or 3.3 percent, to $58.0625, on a
generally good day for most bank stocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1922EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NIGERIA-WRITER-ART-2T     03-21 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-WRITER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNREST STALKS NIGERIAN HERO BEYOND THE GRAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANE, Nigeria _ ``I'm not happy, I'm not a happy man,'' said Jim
Beeson Wiwa, 94, standing in a field here where he hopes to build a
monument for the son whose remains he has yet to recover.
</P>
<P>
   His son, the celebrated author Ken Saro-Wiwa, was hanged nearly
five years ago by Nigeria's military rulers, whom he had criticized
fiercely and fearlessly. His executioners dumped his body in an
unmarked, common grave in the eastern city of Port Harcourt.
Nigerians knew the grave lay not too far from the prison where he
had been killed, though the government kept its exact location a
secret.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected death of the dictator, Gen. Sani Abacha, in June
1998 led the way to greater openness in Nigeria. The newly elected
president, Olusegun Obasanjo, who had narrowly escaped death
himself during three years in Abacha's prisons, immediately gave
Saro-Wiwa's family permission to exhume the body for a proper
funeral. But that was not the end of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Saro-Wiwa's remains are still in the unmarked grave,
intermingled with those of eight other Ogoni men who were also
hanged. Because of a dispute between the author's family and the
relatives of the eight men, a burial scheduled by Saro-Wiwa's
family for April 24 appears very unlikely to take place.
</P>
<P>
   When the government yielded, Saro-Wiwa's Ogoni people _ who sit
on billions of dollars in oil reserves but have remained
desperately poor, like the rest of the people in the Niger Delta _
rejoiced. Their champion would finally be buried in a ceremony
befitting a man who had become a martyr in the struggle for
democracy, along with others like the late opposition leader,
Moshood K.O. Abiola.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Here in the writer's hometown, a village of mud houses about an
hour's drive from Port Harcourt, his father and his mother, Wiidu,
showed a visitor the field where they plan to bury their son. Wiwa
waved his cane at the acres of trees he wants cleared for the
memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Abacha died, they took his body to Kano,'' Wiwa said,
mentioning the general's hometown. ``When Abiola died, they took
him to Yorubaland. Why should they not give me my own son to bring
to Bane?''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time that divisions have afflicted the Ogoni
people, or the organization that Saro-Wiwa founded in 1990, the
Movement for the Survival of the Ogoni People, known as Mosop. In
many ways, those divisions are a microcosm of those among the 7
million people of the oil-producing Niger Delta, in the southern
part of the country. The delta residents have shared the same
complaints against Nigeria's federal government but have been
hopelessly unable to unite behind them.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Under Abacha, security forces simply crushed any unrest in the
delta. The lands inhabited by half a million Ogoni were occupied
for years by soldiers, who attacked their villages, killing men,
raping women and burning down homes. The troops left Ogoniland a
few months after Abacha's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, there is no harassment now,'' said Des Alonale
Laka, an official with the organization. ``But what Mosop stands
for we have not achieved yet.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo has pledged to help achieve the goals of developing the
delta. The region produces almost all of Nigeria's crude oil. But
successive military governments dominated by northerners have kept
it severely underdeveloped, with few roads and almost no
electricity and running water.
</P>
<P>
   The rulers apparently believed that an impoverished and divided
delta would be less likely to press for secession, a constant worry
in a country with as many as 400 ethnic groups. In this vacuum,
European and U.S. oil companies became virtual states within a
state.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, the elected government's main effort has been a
Niger Delta development bill that has been finding its way slowly
through the national legislature. The bill would set up a committee
responsible for building up the region, putting in more money than
the delta has ever received.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the people of the delta, especially its young men,
have grown restive. A few months ago, in a town called Odi, some
youths from another ethnic group, the Ijaw, killed 12 police
officers. Obasanjo responded by sending in troops, who destroyed
Odi and killed dozens of its residents; he later approved $50
million worth of emergency projects.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Saro-Wiwa, a playwright, television producer and poet, was the
Niger Delta's most passionate and forceful voice. He demanded that
it receive a bigger share of the country's oil revenues, which had
filled the pockets of Nigeria's rulers for decades. He accused
Royal Dutch Shell, which pumped the oil in Ogoniland and half of
Nigeria's, of destroying the environment and supporting the
military in suppressing the delta people _ charges that Shell has
denied over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with growing protests and vandalism, Shell shuttered its
operations in Ogoniland in 1993 and has not been back since. In
1994, after four moderate Ogoni chiefs were killed by a mob,
Saro-Wiwa and other Ogoni men were indicted on murder charges,
which they denied. A kangaroo court convicted him and eight others
a year later. Despite international calls for clemency, the Abacha
government ordered them executed in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The executions marked a turning point for Nigeria, which became
isolated from the world and slid deeper into a morass from which it
is still trying to raise itself.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks after Obasanjo was inaugurated as president
last May, Owens Wiwa, the author's younger brother, met the new
president in the capital, Abuja.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Obasanjo gave an executive order that the bodies of
the Ogoni men should be given back to their families,'' Owens said
in a telephone interview from Toronto, where he still lives in
exile. ``Normally, in Nigeria, if you are hanged for murder, the
body is kept by the government. But everyone knows that they were
innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the new openness, divisions have persisted among the
Ogoni. This time the dispute seems to center on the control over
the Movement for the Survival of the Ogoni People, pitting
Saro-Wiwa's family against the organization's leadership, headed by
its president, Ledum Mtee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It adds a dent not only to the movement,'' Mtee said of the
squabble, ``but also to the sacrifice that Ken and the others
made.''
</P>
<P>
   The fighting spilled over into the burial plans. Owens Wiwa
wanted to have the remains of his brother and the other eight Ogoni
men exhumed. American pathologists had been set to travel to
Nigeria last month to conduct tests to determine the identities of
the remains in the common grave.
</P>
<P>
   But the families of the other eight, who are close to the
group's leadership, protested.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not consulted,'' said Lucky Dobee, whose older
brother, Saturday Dobee, was hanged with the author. ``They said
that the corpses would be given to the individual families. Where
are we to keep the corpses? No shelter. No money.''
</P>
<P>
   The families had been informed and offered help from Ken
Saro-Wiwa's family, Owens Wiwa said, accusing the organization's
leadership of creating divisions so that it could have full control
over the burial.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson Poromon, a Methodist bishop who was appointed by the
organization to lead a burial committee for the Ogoni men, shook
his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The men did not die for their families _ they died for
Ogoni,'' Poromon said. ``We are not happy about this. But we are
seeing how we can resolve this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
