<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAT SCORES ARE NO GAUGE FOR LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he was applying to college, Bill Bradley scored a 485 on
the verbal portion of his SAT's, the intellectual equivalent of a
night of air balls on the basketball court. George W. Bush, often
portrayed as a cerebral lightweight, registered a gentleman's 566 _
hardly enough to predict that he would one day be the Republican
nominee for leader of the free world.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one has shown that intellectual prowess is a
prerequisite for the presidency. With some voters, it might be a
liability, as it was for Adlai E. Stevenson, who was maligned as an
egghead in his race against Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the scores by Bradley and Bush seem to offer two more
pieces of evidence that the SAT is not an exceptional predictor of
success.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley graduated from Princeton with honors, became a Rhodes
Scholar and went on to become a U.S. States senator. When he
dropped out of the presidential race, he did so with a graceful
allusion to Proust's ``Remembrance of Things Past.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's acceptance to Yale may have been helped by his ancestry
and connections, but he has still done what many consider a
credible job running Texas, winning laurels for his leadership in
education.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity between these men's accomplishments and their
scores provides ammunition for the perennial assault on the SAT.
One of the loudest shots came last fall with ``The Big Test: The
Secret History of the American Meritocracy'' (Farrar, Straus and
Giroux) by Nicholas Lemann. It argued that the SAT replaced an
aristocracy of wealth and breeding with an equally distorted one
purportedly based on academic talent, generating a new elite that
undermined equal opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one could ask, what is so bad about trying to replace
an aristocracy with a meritocracy? We would hardly want our best
law firms and science laboratories run by mediocre students just as
few of us would pay $100 a ticket to see a minor league team play
in Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that the SAT has real flaws. It can be
coached, giving moneyed students an advantage. It underrepresents
some groups (though others, like Jews and Asian-Americans, would
say it opened once-closed doors for them). It is best at predicting
only first-year college grades. It is an excruciating,
time-consuming exercise. And, if Lemann is right, it helps select
an elite more focused on money and power than public service.
</P>
<P>
   The reason colleges do not get rid of the SAT, however, is that
we live in a country obsessed with local educational control. There
is no national curriculum, nor are there national standards.
Selective colleges have no yardstick to discriminate between a B
average in a pampered, competitive high school larded with Advanced
Placement courses and an A at a high school in the Badlands of
South Dakota that does not offer physics. Colleges need the SAT to
help them unearth a promising student at that unsung Dakota high
school.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if there were no SAT, colleges would have to
invent something like it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it has been a long time since the SAT's were seen as
accurate indexes of talent like batting averages. In the last
generation, colleges, pushing for racially diverse and well-rounded
student bodies, have purposefully searched for other ways of
deciphering the mystery of what an application really says about
the flesh-and-blood student behind it.
</P>
<P>
   The best colleges are so selective that they end up having
students with extremely high SAT's. But that is not the same thing
as saying they choose the students based on their SAT's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turn down lots of students with very high SAT's, and we
admit some students with very low SAT's.'' said George Rupp,
Columbia's president. ``There's no cutoff point.''
</P>
<P>
   But universities like Columbia insist upon an SAT as part of an
application because it helps them gauge the worth of more
subjective factors like grades and teacher recommendations. At the
same time, it helps them screen out high-grade students who do not
have the vocabulary or cannot do the abstract reasoning needed for
complex courses in literature or philosophy ( Bradley being a
striking anomaly).
</P>
<P>
   ``People who make quite low SAT's would have difficulty dealing
with complicated questions in class,'' said John A. Blackburn, dean
of admissions at the University of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there are many colleges that, preoccupied with their
ratings in U.S. News &AMP; World Report, place far too much weight on
SAT scores and reject promising students who might have been
worthwhile gambles. The best colleges, though, are mindful that if
they selected students largely based on their SAT's, they would not
have as lively, offbeat and engaging a flock of students, maybe not
even the kind of students who might one day be good at running the
country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1931EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
