<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3856 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JERUSALEM-FILM-REVIEW     03-21 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERUSALEM-FILM-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FRAGMENTS: JERUSALEM': A LONG LOOK AT ISRAEL AND AT HIS WIFE'S
TOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to New York Times photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
(Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ron Havilio had a lovely idea. Capture the history of
Jerusalem, where he was born in 1950, on film, mixing it with the
history of his own family, which traces its history there for
centuries. The resulting work is ``Fragments: Jerusalem,'' a
six-hour film being shown at the New Directors/New Films series
Wednesday through April 6. It is worthy and ambitious but somewhat
soporific.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fragments: Jerusalem'' is divided into seven sections ranging
from 34 to 66 minutes each. It begins with ``Mamila,'' a look at
the neighborhood of that name outside the Old City walls, and ends
with ``Abba (Father),'' the story of the filmmaker's father, who
joined the Haganah underground, struggling for the creation of a
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Havilio, who also lived in Paris, Istanbul and Africa (his
father was at one point Israel's consul general) while growing up,
had some wonderful raw material for a film or mini-series, but that
is exactly what it remains. ``Fragments: Jerusalem'' desperately
needs shaping and focusing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the division into seven sections, the story has no
apparent structure. Havilio, who narrates the English version
(there are English subtitles when the subject on screen speaks
Hebrew or French), often switches from a historical narrative about
his homeland to home movies, largely of his wife and his daughters.
</P>
<P>
   This could have worked, but the connections between subjects are
often unclear. At one point, Havilio films his wife wiggling her
toes.
</P>
<P>
   There are some very pretty pictures of Jerusalem, past and
present, in the film. The snowstorm in Chapter 5 is particularly
gorgeous. The scenes with ancient structures in their contemporary
surroundings as cars whiz by, contrasted with earlier photographs
or sketches, work nicely. But it takes more than 16-millimeter
travelogue photography, stream of consciousness and good intentions
to make a meaningful documentary, and that is all ``Fragments:
Jerusalem'' has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `FRAGMENTS: JERUSALEM'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ron Havilio; written (original in Hebrew, English
version of the narration has some English subtitles) by Havilio;
director of photography, Havilio; edited by Tor Ben Mayor and Yael
Perlov; produced by Ron and Jacqueline Havilio; released by New
Yorker Films. At the Walter Reade Theater at Lincoln Center.
Running time: six hours, shown in two segments. This film is not
rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
