<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS REBOUND BROADLY DESPITE FED'S RATE HIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also FED-MARKETPLACE and FED-RATES) 
(bl) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices staged a broad, strong rally Tuesday
even though the Federal Reserve Board raised short-term interest
rates and gave every indication it was prepared to do so again in
about two months.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's decision to raise the overnight federal funds rate, to
6 percent from 5.75 percent, had been widely anticipated. Indeed,
some traders said there had been a concern that the central bank
might have done something more dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something of a relief rally,'' said Bob Gasser, head
of U.S. equity trading at J.P. Morgan Securities. ``But the
implications of the move won't be known for about six weeks, when
minutes from the meeting are published.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the old- and new-economy companies posted strong gains, and
the leading market indexes all registered gains of 2 percent or
more.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed at 10,907.34, up 227.10,
or 2.13 percent. Since March 14, the blue chip index has gained
more than 1,000 points. Still, so far this year the Dow is down a
bit more than 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 30 stocks that make up the Dow, 21 posted price gains,
while only eight fell in value.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 37.24, or 2.6
percent, to 1,493.87, its first record of the year. In addition to
General Electric, technology companies like Cisco Systems, which
gained 6 47/64, to 140 55/64, and Yahoo, which jumped 19 47/64, to
191}, helped to push the index higher. For the first time this
year, the S&AMP;P is now higher than it was at the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, which was down by more than 100
points early in the session, staged a turnaround and gained 101.68,
or 2.2 percent, to 4,711.68. And the Wilshire 5000 index rose
292.98, or 2.1 percent, to 14,346.22.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume was brisk, but not hectic.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, 1 billion shares changed hands.
Volume on the Nasdaq stock market was 1.7 billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, the reversal in the Internet and technology
stocks that trade on the Nasdaq halted what has been the second
major correction that market has experienced so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This selloff has not been a panic,'' said Robert E. Turner,
chairman and chief investment officer at Turner Investment
Partners, a Berwyn, Pa. firm that has $10 billion under management,
much of it in technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big correction, but nothing more than that. It gives
everyone a better chance to evaluate what is out there, and
presents good opportunities to buy the better stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The rise in General Electric's stock price came after the
company announced that its first quarter profits will ``modestly
exceed'' Wall Street consensus estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Bank and financial-services stocks had a good day. Analysts have
been saying that bank stocks, which have fallen sharply since the
Fed began raising interest rates in late June, would begin to rally
when it appeared the central bank might be about finished pushing
them up.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P Major Regional Bank index gained 5.2 percent Tuesday.
Wells Fargo rose 1|, to 39 9/16. Mellon Financial was up 1|, to
32{. And Fleet Boston Financial rose 2 to 34[.
</P>
<P>
   Among financial service stocks, Goldman Sachs gained 4 13/16, to
118\, after the investment bank posted first quarter results that
were much better than expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
