<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-POLITICS-ART-2     03-21 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES(1000)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRACY AND INDEPENDENCE STILL BEDEVIL TAIWAN'S NATIVE
DISSIDENTS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT27-28 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Even Tuesday night, three days after an
opposition candidate was elected president, ending more than 50
years of Nationalist rule, Hsieh Tsung-min could barely contain his
elation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream has come true,'' said Hsieh, 64, an early hero of the
democracy and independence movement on this island, to which Chiang
Kai-shek's Nationalist forces fled from mainland China in 1949
after their defeat by the Communists. The Nationalists imposed
martial law and a dictatorship on the native Taiwanese population;
it was lifted only in the late 1980s, by Chiang's son and
successor, Chiang Ching-kuo.
</P>
<P>
   But meanwhile, native dissidents like Hsieh fought a hard battle
for civil rights in what was often called the Taiwan independence
movement. Convicted of treason in 1964 for drafting a ``Declaration
for the Taiwanese People,'' he spent a total of 11 and a half
torture-filled years in prison, went into exile in the United
States and then returned here in 1990 to join the offspring of his
cause, the Democratic Progressive Party _ the party of Sunday's
victor, Chen Shui-bian.
</P>
<P>
   Today Hsieh is not bothered by President-elect Chen's
backtracking on the need to declare Taiwan's independence,
backtracking aimed at broadening the party's election appeal and
avoiding a military blitz from the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy has really come to Taiwan,'' Hsieh said, ``and in
Taiwan, democracy means independence. But we must be practical and
careful in our dealings with China.''
</P>
<P>
   Another hero of the native Taiwanese cause said Tuesday that he,
too, was happy about Chen's election, but only up to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chen Shui-bian's victory is a great step, but I feel my wish
has been compromised,'' said Koo Kwang-ming, 74, who spent decades
in exile in Japan promoting his Taiwan Independence Union, while
under indictment at home for treason. Chiang Kai-shek, like his
arch-rival Mao Tse-tung on the mainland, allowed no dissent from
the view that Taiwan was a Chinese province, even as the two
leaders disagreed whether Beijing or Taipei was China's rightful
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing for us to do is to declare independence before
China becomes too strong,'' Koo said. ``Democracy is possible
anywhere, but if you forget you are a son of this land, then
democracy becomes meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Hsieh and Koo fought for the native-born Taiwanese against
their Nationalist rulers. But in their contrasting approaches _
Hsieh stressing democracy and willing to relax on formal
independence, Koo a die-hard advocate of a Taiwan Republic _ are
the roots of a continuing debate.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Taiwan's peculiar history, the issues of democracy
and independence have been intertwined, and differences in emphasis
have from the beginning bedeviled the newly emergent Democratic
Progressive Party.
</P>
<P>
   To many abroad, it is simply known as Taiwan's pro-independence
party. And that is an important strand in its makeup.
</P>
<P>
   But the emergence of this Taiwanese opposition party in the
mid-1980s _ even before martial law was lifted in 1987 _ was driven
more by the quest for democracy and ethnic justice than for legal
independence from the mainland, said Sherry Rigger, an expert on
Taiwan politics at Davidson College in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   During the just-concluded election campaign, Chen spent much of
his time not promoting independence but trying to convince voters,
and foreign governments, that he was realistic and would not
provoke a crisis with Beijing. Ethnic Taiwanese with strongly
pro-independence views were certain to vote for him in any case,
but Chen's main plank was the fight against the dirty money and
politics of the encrusted Nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   For the last decade, the Democratic Progressive Party has been
riven by internal struggles between hard-core promoters of
independence and pragmatists like Chen, who knew that regardless of
personal preferences, the party had to align itself with the
mainstream electorate on cross-strait relations in order to win
national office.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys have consistently shown that the vast majority of voters
want to keep things as they are now, with Taiwan sovereign in
practice if not in name, and that only a small fraction wants the
government to openly defy Beijing with a declaration of
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strong independence position was a kind of phase that
people went through,'' Rigger said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After the Nationalists lifted martial law, moved toward
democracy and made the native Taiwanese Lee Teng-hui the national
leader, the young opposition party groped for a message, Rigger
said. In the first direct presidential election, in 1996, it put up
a candidate some here call the godfather of independence, Peng
Ming-min, who was Hsieh's law professor and had also been
imprisoned in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Peng failed miserably, picking up just 21 percent of the vote.
In the aftermath, pragmatists like Chen steered the party toward
domestic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Fervent independence advocates _ with funds from the wealthy
Koo, who had previously bankrolled the Democratic Progressives _
split off to form the small Taiwan Independence Party.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in the latest sign that party moderates want to
minimize friction with the mainland, a legislator proposed formally
altering the party's basic statement of principles to remove its
provocative calls for rewriting the constitution and declaring a
Republic of Taiwan. Instead, the legislator suggested, it should
assert Taiwan's status as a ``sovereign independent country.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Chen will risk a contentious debate over the party's
charter is unclear, and, in any case, even the revised formulation
would remain objectionable in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   But the airing of such a proposal shows how far the Democratic
Progressives have converged with the Nationalists on cross-strait
policy _ leaving the situation dangerous but not, perhaps, as
immediately explosive as many feared.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Since his victory on Saturday, with 39 percent of the vote in a
three-way race, Chen has gone out of his way to avoid baiting
China.
</P>
<P>
   This week, there was some grumbling from independence supporters
within the leadership of the Democratic Progressives, as well as
among partial allies like Koo. But Chen and his aides know that his
most pressing immediate task, assuming that he can avoid fanning
the flames with China, is to find qualified people to run the
government and to patch together a coalition in the legislature,
which remains dominated by the Nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Koo, for his part, does not directly criticize Chen for watering
down calls for independence. ``He was a lot better than the other
two candidates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he still insists that Taiwan ought to declare independence
while it has the chance. ``Do you really think China would
attack?'' he asked. ``They would lose their external trade, and the
first thing to collapse would be the Communist Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Hsieh, by contrast, says there is no point in taking chances.
``We have to take China very seriously,'' he said. Even in his 1964
manifesto, which is celebrated as a landmark in the Taiwan
independence movement, he never actually used the word
``independence,'' he said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can wait,'' he said. And anyway, he said, ``how could a
country have a free election for a president, as we just did, and
still be considered part of Communist China?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1940EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
