<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3866 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-MAG-REVIEWS-AZR &LR;      03-21 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAG-REVIEWS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGAZINE REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED
 IT; ALSO MOVING IN THE ``E'' CATEGORY) 
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Muller's quick looks at some current magazine issues and a
popular website:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``CONSUMER REPORTS'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ladies and gentlemen, start your engines! It's time for this
magazine's most-stolen issue _ rating the cars. This one is kept
locked in the public library's hermetically sealed bunker, only to
be checked out with three forms of ID, a blood sample and a
security deposit including, but not limited to, your first born. Of
course, this issue is well worth the trouble, rating every vehicle
from the Audi TT (isn't that cute?) to the Volvo S80 (less boxier
than ever!). Arizona drivers, of course, will skip straight to the
Sports Utility Vehicle section (we counted 45 SUV models alone),
even if the most rugged terrain they ever traverse is the ABCO
parking lot. The magazine goes high-tech this time around, rating
the car Web sites, from CarsDirect (www.carsdirect.com), which
allows you to ``build your own car'' (actually, just add extras),
to Kelley Blue Book (www.kbb.com), which pegs resale prices for
used cars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``DISCOVER'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's definitely Science Lite, but the April issue includes a
couple of interesting pieces. The cover story details the discovery
of ancient Roman ships near the Leaning Tower of Pisa, in the
Tuscany region of Italy. Researchers have found the remnants of at
least 17 ships dating from around 200 B.C. to A.D. 500 and yielding
a number of artifacts, including incense burners, oil lamps, fish
hooks, sewing needles and numerous amphorae _ large earthen jars
used to transport goods around the Mediterranean. There's also an
interesting story on the world's ``deadliest carnivore'' a
half-mongoose, half-cloud leopard called a fossa, which lives in
Madagascar and apparently spends much of its food budget on Lemur
Helper. Our intrepid explorers actually manage to catch one of
these slick dudes, and then pass the tranquilized cat around for
polaroids. Way to be ecosensitive, dude.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ``GOLF'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a strong message emanating from this magazine, and that
message is: ``We want to sell you some really expensive golf
clubs!'' Or a luxury car. Or both. Still, this issue includes some
interesting features, including an 18-hole ``course'' on everything
from repairing divots to teaching your kids to play. Of course,
like most articles in the magazine, some of these helpful hints
double as ads _ many of the ``solutions'' involve buying cool stuff
or going to a ritzy resort. If you really want to ruin your swing,
consult some of the technical-sounding instructions in the back,
with lines like ``the upper spine is farther from the target than
the lower spine.'' Uh huh. And the ball is rolling through the
desert. There is also a fun feature that names the nation's 10 best
public courses. Arizona made the list, with Apache Stronghold in
San Carlos. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``THE NEW YORKER'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Includes one of those great articles that keep you coming back
for more _ a feature story on the top writer for ``The Simpsons,''
a former ``Harvard Lampoon'' staffer named George Meyer. It is
Meyer who writes many of the lines that are quoted from the wildly
successful series. Even his fellow writers stand pretty much in awe
of him. ``I would rather make George Meyer laugh than win an
Emmy,'' a colleague notes. Meyer, who traces his comedic roots back
to ``Mad'' magazine, culled his craft working for David Letterman
and Lorne Michaels. Writer David Owen does a nice job drawing Meyer
out, getting him to describe a less-than-idyllic childhood filled
with way too much television. There is also a well-done piece by
political correspondent Joe Klein which notes that John McCain
spent much more time adopting a posture of indignance than actually
explaining his positions. He says McCain plowed his jet into the
George W. Bush aircraft carrier, crippling both campaigns. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEBSITE REVIEW: www.yesterland.com  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there are things that just work better on the Web.
Yesterland is one of them. With an astounding commitment to detail,
the site chronicles Disneyland attractions that have closed over
the years, complete with pictures and narrative histories.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about nostalgia. All those rides that you remember from
childhood are here: the campy Submarine Voyage (``helmsman, steer
clear of the teetering columns!''), the Old Matterhorn (pre-1978)
and the Skyway to Tomorrowland/Fantasyland
</P>
<P>
   (those old buckets that hang on the wire, closed in 1994).
</P>
<P>
   There is a piece on the old PeopleMover (presented by Goodyear,
closed in 1995), which pushed guests around with motors installed
in the track, taking them through Tomorrowland's indoor attractions
and above its outdoor attractions. And don't forget Rocket to the
Moon, a ``D'' ticket that later became Mission to Mars, until it
closed in 1992. Today, it's a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   How deep does this site go? It even includes a long feature on
the old parking lot, which has been closed to make way for a new
slate of rides and other attractions. The article notes that those
who arrived early could park in the ``convenient Bambi section,''
but those who came late ``could be way back in Thumper or Winnie
the Pooh.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1945EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3867 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      03-21 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW&AMP;NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
 (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED
 IT;  STORY ALSO MOVING IN THE ``L''
 CATEGORY) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``TRUE NORTH'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Kimberly Kafka (Dutton, $23.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The protagonist of Kafka's first novel is Bailey Lockhart, a
35-year-old woman who has fled a troubled past to find solace as a
medic and bush pilot in the remote wilderness of Alaska. She lives
alone in a cabin 80 miles upriver from the nearest community, a
Native village with which she stays in touch by radio. The book
opens when she agrees to fly two tourists _ they claim to be
looking for a ``wilderness adventure'' but are really searching
illegally for Alaskan gold _ from Anchorage to a deserted lodge
five miles upriver from her camp. Add to this the romantic
attentions of Kash, a Native leader and realistic man who is trying
to look after the interests of his people, as well as the despair
and animosity felt toward Whites by many residents in the village,
and you have a pretty interesting look at major issues in Alaska
today. The plot lags a bit during the characters' seemingly endless
travels up and down the river, but Kash is appealing, Bailey is
strong and utterly capable, and their wilderness lives make for
good reading. Kafka, who is a wilderness emergency medical
technician, lives in Alaska and Wisconsin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE PENGUIN BOOK OF IRISH FICTION'' &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Colm Toibin (Viking, $40) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toibin begins this anthology with a challenge: ``If you want to
read about the vagaries of the human heart,'' he says, ``or the
fleeting nature of love or time, read Goethe's lyrics; but if you
want to know about the unreliable nature of narrative in a time of
landlords, read Maria Edgeworth. If you want to know how love can
lead to marriage, read Jane Austen; but if you want to delve into
the secret and dark unconscious of an embattled ruling class, read
Bram Stoker, Charles Maturin and Joseph Sheridan Le Fanu.'' Such is
Irish fiction, a territory in which, to paraphrase Maria Edgeworth,
reality is too strong, passion too violent, the world too feverish
to look upon without the disguising balm of language. Toibin has
assembled fiction from the time of Jonathan Swift to that of Emma
Donoghue, who was born a mere 31 years ago. Included are broad
selections from James Joyce, as well as excerpts from Roddy Doyle's
``The Snapper,'' Edna O'Brien's ``The Country Girls,'' Oscar
Wilde's ``The Picture of Dorian Gray,'' John Banville's ``The Book
of Evidence,'' Iris Murdoch's ``The Red and the Green'' and many
others.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``A CONSPIRACY OF PAPER'' &QL; 
 &UR; By David Liss (Random House, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Weaver is a man who performs work of a ``delicate
nature'' on behalf of rich and illustrious men, clients who are
driven to insult him but whose barbs Weaver shrugs off ``as a bear
tosses off the dogs sent to bait it in Hockley-in-the-Hole.''
Weaver is the consummate outsider: He is a former boxer who now
works as a private investigator, of sorts; a brainy, brawling
thug-for-hire. He is also a Jew, which distances him further from
the men he serves. More important, he is the tremendously appealing
narrator of this first novel, one of the best to come along in
years. Set in 18th-century London, ``Conspiracy'' takes Weaver into
a complex case that begins when he learns that the seemingly
accidental death of his father, a stock-jobber to whom Weaver had
not spoken in 10 years, was really a murder. Weaver's work becomes
personal then, and he throws himself into an investigation that
goes deep into the world of British finance and into the dark
territory of the city's criminal elite. It's great entertainment,
which Liss serves up with intelligence, historical accuracy and
rip-roaring ambition. Enjoy.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``JANE GOODALL: 40 YEARS AT GOMBE'' &QL; 
 &UR; (ST&AMP;C, $29.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We had a conversation recently with a man of a certain age, who
told us that the consensus among men of his generation is that Jane
Goodall was, as he put it, ``a babe.'' We confess we had never
heard that word applied to Goodall (and we imagine that she would
be amused to know of it), but we were reminded of the sentiment as
we looked at the early photographs in this book. They are personal
memories for so many people, these images of a barefoot, slender
young woman in shorts, long hair tied back, her attention given
over wholly to the intelligent animals that she would study all her
life. Her first article on the chimpanzees of the Gombe Stream Game
Reserve in Tanzania appeared in ``National Geographic''in 1963, and
it was not long before everyone knew who Goodall was. Today, she is
66 and travels constantly on a public relations mission to preserve
and enhance the lives of the creatures she came to love. This book
is a reminder of what a great combination youth, daring and
commitment can be. And he's right: She was something to see.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 1946EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0277 </DOCNO>
