<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: `TITUS'; `HARSH REALM'; `MILLIONAIRE'; ANCHORS AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Titus,' Emperor Of Mondays  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It has been a much better year to start up a dot-com than a
sitcom _ unless you're the Fox network.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time since the start of 2000, Fox has brought on
a new comedy to near-spectacular ratings, with the debut of
``Titus'' on Fox on Monday night proving to be the most popular
thing on the network since Darva met Rick and thought she was
marrying a rich guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titus'' pulled in more than 14 million viewers, scoring the
highest rating for any show premiere on a Monday night in the
network's history. That success comes on the heels of the showing
for ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' which moved to Sunday nights in
January and immediately established itself as the first comedy to
reach hit status this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titus'' is not all the way there yet, because it has to prove
that the viewers who tried it once will come back a second time.
But as Sandy Grushow, the chairman of Fox Entertainment put it,
``You'd certainly rather get out of the blocks like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the key to success was finding the right week to
introduce ``Titus,'' which mainly meant avoiding a week when ABC
would use ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' on Monday. But
``Titus'' was especially well scheduled, going against a weak movie
about Playboy bunnies on ABC, the ratings-challenged ``Freaks and
Geeks'' on NBC and the loudly flopping ``Grapevine'' on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titus'' was able to join ``Malcolm in the Middle'' as the only
new comedy on any network this season to even give a hint that it
might be a hit. Almost no other comedy anywhere else has made much
of an impression this season, with NBC suffering an especially long
drought in trying to find something to work with its hit comedies
on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is trying two new entries this Thursday, a family sitcom
called ``Daddio'' and a police comedy called ``Battery Park.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Titus'' and ``Malcolm'' are also the only two comedies this
season to expand on the audience of the established comedy leading
into it. For ``Titus'' that was ``That '70s Show,'' which has grown
into a solid performer for Fox at 8 p.m. on Mondays. ``Titus''
improved on the lead-in for that series by about 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One thing ``Titus'' has in common with ``Malcolm'' is that both
are based on the personal experiences of their creators. But in the
case of ``Titus'' the personal experiences of the star, Christopher
Titus, are considerably more grim than the largely goofy family
experiences being explored by Linwood Bloomer, the creator and
producer of ``Malcolm.''
</P>
<P>
   For Grushow, success for ``Titus'' would be especially valuable
in what has mainly been a struggling year for the network. ``If we
can count on this as another piece of the puzzle, we have a lot
more flexibility in building our schedule for next season,''
Grushow said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Carter
</P>
<P>
   `Realm' Reincarnated
</P>
<P>
   Five months after it was canceled by Fox, Chris Carter's ``Harsh
Realm'' will return to television Friday night on the FX cable
network. That must represent sweet vindication for Carter, creator
of Fox's very successful ``X-Files.'' Though the ``Harsh Realm''
debut on Oct. 8 was watched by 7.5 million viewers, only 3.7
million tuned in to watch its third episode.
</P>
<P>
   The show, starring Scott Bairstow and D.B. Sweeney, was canceled
days later. At the time, Carter had fully completed 9 shows of a
13-show order.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellation was rather abrupt for Carter, whose ``X-Files''
is often credited with helping make the Fox network prominent. He
made his displeasure public, attributing the series' rocky start to
poor promotion by Fox. ``I think they have big problems, and we
were part of a bigger effort to clean house,'' Carter was quoted in
The Hollywood Reporter as saying at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday he said: ``I was excited about the show. I think the
stars were great and I know, because I've seen the nine episodes,
it deserved a shot and it could have held its own.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter further needled Fox in February by inserting a little of
``Harsh Realm'' into an ``X-Files'' episode. (A man whose daughter
is being abducted from her bedroom is shown watching ``Harsh
Realm'' in his living room and muttering to himself, ``This is
great!'')
</P>
<P>
   The ever-expanding cable dial is allowing ``Harsh Realm'' to
live on after its network death. FX, Fox TV's sister network in 45
million homes, will run the show every Friday for the next nine
weeks. The first three episodes will be the same first three that
ran on the Fox broadcast network. The next sixwill begin April 14.
</P>
<P>
   FX executives said they expect the show to fit nicely within
their programming schedule, which is built partly around reruns of
Carter's ``X-Files'' and ``Millennium,'' said a network spokesman,
John Solberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a degree it's original programming for us,'' Solberg said.
``While three episodes aired on Fox, we've got six hours of
never-before-seen product from one of the premier producers of
television there is in Chris Carter.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he was pleased, too. ``It's just a nice opportunity
to take what I think is good, hard work _ stress the `good' _ and
let it be seen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, of course, has other things to worry about, like whether
his ``X-Files'' will live for another season on Fox. He said
negotiations were taking place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice because I'm writing episode 20 right now of
22,'' he said. ``If we're going to wrap this series up, I feel that
it would be best to do it with foreknowledge of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``X-Files'' doesn't survive after this year, Carter will have
another shot at the Fox broadcast schedule with his pilot ``The
Lone Gunmen,'' which centers on three peripheral ``X-Files''
characters. It has been mentioned as a possible replacement of
``X-Files.'' But then, so was ``Harsh Realm.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jim Rutenberg
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Who Wants to Be ...
</P>
<P>
   To take full advantage of its association with the Oscar special
Sunday night, ABC is adding a special edition of ``Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire'' on Friday night at 8: a show devoted to questions
about movies.
</P>
<P>
   The show is a stand-alone; the contestants from the regular
editions of the show will not carry over to this one. Every
contestant on Friday's show, which was taped last week, qualified
by answering only movie questions.
</P>
<P>
   One more note about the worldwide phenomenon of ``Millionaire,''
which is now on the air in more than 70 countries: four of the
candidates running for president in Russia turned up as contestants
in the Russian edition of ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates, who did not include the current Russian leader,
Vladimir Putin, who happened to be meeting with Prime Minister Tony
Blair of Britain at the time, were on the show to help raise their
profiles.
</P>
<P>
   The show is a hit in Russia as well (of course) drawing about 30
million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Carter
</P>
<P>
   Those Frequent Fliers
</P>
<P>
   With Pope John Paul II in Israel, President Clinton in India and
the Russian elections approaching, the network news anchors are
building up their frequent-flier miles.
</P>
<P>
   CBS's Dan Rather flew to Russia on Thursday, returned to New
York on Sunday, and headed to Washington on Monday morning to
interview John McCain for ``60 Minutes II,'' only to return to New
York later that day for Monday night's edition of ``Evening News.''
</P>
<P>
   At 11 P.M. Monday he boarded a plane for Tel Aviv. He may head
to Russia later in the week, a CBS spokeswoman said. Peter Jennings
arrived in New Delhi on Sunday night, the only anchor to go there
for President Clinton's visit. He was to depart Tuesday night for
Jerusalem, where he is to stay through Saturday before leaving for
Clinton's meeting with the Syrian leader, Hafez Assad, in Geneva on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Tyndall, publisher of The Tyndall Report, which monitors
network television news, said this was the most traveling that the
Big Three news anchors had done since the summer of 1997, when both
Mother Teresa and Diana, Princess of Wales, died.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday, Jennings was expected to arrive home in New York
on Monday night (Ted Koppel will be covering the Russian elections
for ABC from Moscow, where he has been since Thursday.) Tom Brokaw
of NBC flew to Israel on Monday. He was planning to stay there
through Thursday before heading to Moscow to cover the elections,
which start on Friday. It is unclear when he will return.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jim Rutenberg
</P>
</TEXT>
