r i BC-POPE-ARAFAT-TEX     03-21 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-ARAFAT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD'S MOST PROMINENT INTERFAITH COUPLE TO GREET POPE
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: This subs for budgeted POPE-JORDAN) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ When Pope John Paul II celebrates Mass in Bethlehem
on Wednesday, one of the world's most prominent interfaith couples,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and his wife, Suha, will be among
those greeting him.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Arafat, a Muslim, and Suha, a Greek Orthodox
Christian, at a Mass in Manger Square near the site traditionally
recognized as Jesus' birthplace reflects the mix of faiths that the
pope will encounter during his historic Holy Land pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   The Arafats will greet John Paul when he arrives by helicopter
in Bethlehem and present him mother of pearl depictions of the 14
stations of the cross, the traditional scenes of Jesus' march to
his crucifixion, one of Arafat's chief advisers said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see the pope as a great Christian leader who is seeking
peace,'' adviser Ibrahim Kandalaft said.
</P>
<P>
   Kandalaft, a Greek Orthodox Christian, said Arafat and his wife
attended three Christmas Masses for three different denominations
last year: Catholic, Greek Orthodox and Armenian Chrof.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Arafat) respects Christianity,'' said Kandalaft, whose
family was among Palestinian Christians uprooted from their homes
in the 1967 war when Israel took over both east and west Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Christian groups invited to the Mass are Greek
Orthodox, Latin Catholic, Armenian, Syrian Orthodox, Syrian
Catholic, Ethiopian Orthodox, marionite and Coptic, Kandalaft said.
</P>
<P>
   Government figures quoted in The Jerusalem Post this week
identify 130,000 Christians in Israel, about 2.1 percent of the
population. About 50,000 more live in the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, 143,000 Christians lived in Israel and the surrounding
territories, representing 7 percent of the population. Since the
Israeli victory in the 1967 war, the percentage of Christians has
declined in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is the subject of an ongoing debate. A position paper
by the Anti-Defamation League blames the growing Muslim population,
in part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear of reprisal has led Christians to be silent about Islamic
extremist harassment, destruction of property and, in some
instances, physical attacks,'' the league said.
</P>
<P>
   Kandalaft, on the other hand, blames ``atrocities of the Israeli
occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither side blames the Christian departure on any single
factor.
</P>
<P>
   The Anti-Defamation League paper acknowledges that the 1967 war
contributed to the emigration of Christians. And Kandalaft said
social and economic factors have also prompted many Christians to
move to other countries, particularly the United States _ where
they believe they can make a better living _ Australia, Canada and
Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, religious leaders in Jordan, the first stop on the
pope's visit, reported the pullout of Christians for various
economic and social reasons. Despite government policies for equal
treatment, some Christians believe they are discriminated against
in the workplace and seek better conditions elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the ancient Christian community is ever-present, and
Christian pilgrims from throughout the world flood holy sites in
Jordan, Israel and the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his arrival in Jerusalem yesterday, John Paul called for
dialogue among Muslims, Christians and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   He received a warm welcome, even from Christians whose
denominations don't recognize him as their official leader.
</P>
<P>
   Issa Odes, 62, a shop owner in the Christian quarter of the Old
City of Jerusalem, said he is delighted that John Paul is coming to
the ancient city.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good man. He's an old man,'' said Odes, a Greek
Orthodox Christian. ``He doesn't hurt anybody. He talks well. We
respect him.''
</P>
<P>
   Michel Abuald, a Latin Catholic shopkeeper, concurs with others,
hoping that the pope's attempt to promote harmony bears fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Christians are not unhappy in Jerusalem, even if we are a
minority,'' Abuald said. ``But we will be happier if there is peace
between Israel and the Palestinians.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
