<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3878 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FED-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      03-21 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: INVESTORS SEE RATE HIKE AS NECESSARY MEDICINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also FED-RATES and MARKET) 
(bl) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The no-surprises Federal Reserve Board gave investors just what
they were expecting Tuesday: a one-quarter point increase in
short-term interest rates. The full-of-surprises stock market
delivered a smashing gain on the news, with two of the broadest
indexes closing at new highs.
</P>
<P>
   Before the midafternoon announcement that the Fed had pushed the
federal funds rate to 6 percent, stocks had been adrift. After the
news, they took off, with the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index
rising 2.56 percent to end the day at a record of 1,493.87. The
Wilshire 5000 index, which represents the entire stock market and
is reportedly monitored by Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan, closed at a
high of 14,345.88, up 2 percent on the day. The Nasdaq rose 2.21
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists said the market's reaction reflected two things.
First, investors were relieved that the Fed had not chosen to be
more aggressive and raise rates by one-half point. In addition,
investors seemed to greet the one-quarter point rise as medicine
the Fed must administer to keep the long economic expansion
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conventional wisdom is rate hikes are bad for the stock
market,'' said Jay Mueller, economics strategist at Strong Capital
Management in Milwaukee. ``But I think the market recognizes that
good monetary policy means you sometimes have to raise rates. The
Fed had to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, given that the Fed is almost as concerned about
excessive speculation in the stock market today as it is about a
resurgence in inflation, the blistering moves in stocks probably
disappointed Greenspan. The gains also indicate, to some, that the
central bank is a spectator rather than an actor in the drama
playing out in the financial market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed's just not in control,'' said Stephen S. Roach, chief
economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``The economy is surging
at a rate that is clearly excessive, and while there's been some
rather frenetic rotation in the stock market, wealth creation is
still open-ended. The Fed, in my view, is staying incremental with
a very blunt instrument, the fed funds rate, that is inappropriate
for dealing with the problems that it's facing.''
</P>
<P>
   Other tools available to the Fed that might cool things down
include raising the initial amount of money that investors must put
up to buy stocks on borrowed money _ known as the margin
requirement _ or increasing the amount of reserves that banks must
have on hand as a percent of their deposits. A higher reserve
requirement means less money will be available for loans, which
would slow economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Even as stock investors celebrated the Fed's vigilance against
inflation, their enthusiasm made it more likely that the central
bank will push through additional rate increases this year. Rising
stock prices, said William Dudley, chief U.S. economist at Goldman
Sachs, make it harder for monetary policy to bring the economy back
down to earth. ``The financial markets are not doing a lot of
tightening for the Fed,'' Dudley said. ``The logical conclusion is
that the Fed will have to do more than people anticipate.''
Currently, the Wall Street consensus is that the Fed will raise
rates another one-half point and be done with it, a view Dudley
considers too optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   For now, most investors applaud Greenspan's incremental moves
even in the face of a rapidly growing economy. Stefan D. Abrams,
chief investment officer for asset allocation at Trust Co. of the
West, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``The only explanation of why the Fed is moving so gingerly with
these quarter-point moves is that either they see the signs of a
slowdown already evident in the shape of the yield curve, the price
of oil, the leveling of single-family housing starts, or they
believe that the lag is long between the beginning of a monetary
tightening and its showing up in the real economy. Greenspan thinks
he's on a glide path here to a soft landing and he doesn't need to
take more aggressive steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest beneficiaries of Tuesday's move were some of
the old investor favorites: General Electric rose $10.50 to
$151.4375 and Microsoft advanced $5.375 to $102.75. Even bank
stocks rallied, which is not normally the case when rates rise
because such increases are a drag on profits. The Philadelphia Bank
stock index rose 4.4 percent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even the bond market reacted favorably to the rate increase.
Prices rose across the board, pushing down yields on the 30-year
bond to 5.97 percent from 6 percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech stocks continued to decline Tuesday with the American
Stock Exchange biotech index falling 2.3 percent. It is down more
than 35 percent from its peak of two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's big move in stocks did not surprise Dudley, who
pointed out that historically, Fed tightening episodes have not
been all bad for equities. ``On average, since the 1960s, the stock
market has gone up when the Fed tightens because the Fed usually
tightens when the economy is strong,'' he said. ``What ends up
stopping bull markets is inflation because that causes the Fed to
shift to a truly hostile stance. Stock markets fear inflation, not
Fed tightening per se.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
