<HEADER>
A3879 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AOL-CITYSITES22-COX     03-21 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-CITYSITES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL becomes latest to offer local content to wireless devices
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you want local information online, you no longer
need a computer to do it.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, the Microsoft Network and AccessAtlanta all have
``Internet everywhere'' products that will deliver local news,
sports and entertainment to almost any electronic device you can
imagine.
</P>
<P>
   The newest entry into the wireless fray is AOL's Digital City.
AOL announced a nationwide rollout Tuesday of what it called
Digital City 2000. The service will be available in 200 markets
nationwide _ up from 60 _ and will also be accessible via wireless
hand-held devices as part of an initiative called ``Local
Everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest entry into a market analysts say is exploding.
Local information provided in many forms will be a lucrative niche
for ``city sites'' that put information at consumers' fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have been predicting for years that the online market
for local goods and services would eventually explode and bring in
millions in advertising from local retailers and service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Communications predicts that by 2002, 54 percent of the
$7.7 billion spent on online advertising will be spent locally,
making local content one of the fastest-growing online categories.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Leonsis, president of AOL Interactive Properties, said in an
interview Tuesday that total availability in every U.S. market on a
variety of electronic devices is the goal of Digital City 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He also said it represented an evolution from previous
incarnations of Digital City and its goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as AOL developed from a community-based business to a
media business to a part of your daily life, Digital City is
evolving the same way. It's convenience in a box,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Digital City will offer local entertainment, dining, resource
guides and directory services provided in conjunction with 200
content partners such as MoviePhone, MapQuest and Knight Ridder.
</P>
<P>
   No huge advertising blitz is planned. Digital City hopes word of
mouth will bring users to its sites.
</P>
<P>
   In many major markets, several players are vying to gain the
most users. New entrants, like Digital City, face
already-established Web sites with dedicated content developers,
designers and programmers, as well as partnerships with local media
outlets. For example, Boston has the vast resources of The Boston
Globe and media partners across the city to make Boston.com one of
the largest and most popular local sites in the city.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Digital City faces AccessAtlanta, the top-rated city
site in the country. According to Media Metrix's fourth-quarter
report, AccessAtlanta ranked 11th in the Atlanta market, ahead of
such nationally known sites as Excite, eBay and ZDNet. In Atlanta,
Digital City ranked 48th on the list of 100 sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a mistake to say we don't worry about Digital
City,'' says AccessAtlanta General Manager George deGolian. ``We
look at them every single day. We are always working to make sure
we are strongly differentiated from them and serving that local
market as best as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   AccessAtlanta and Digital City will also compete with a new
offering from the Microsoft Network called MSN Mobile, which
delivers a selection of MSN services including news, stocks, travel
and Web browsing on cellular phones and pagers. MSN's wireless
service does not offer local content, having sold its ``Sidewalk''
service to Ticketmaster/CitySearch in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Like Digital City and the Microsoft Network, AccessAtlanta has
its own wireless service called ``AccessAtlanta Everywhere,''
available on cellular phones, pagers and personal digital
assistants. Marketing manager Rhonda McClendon says the service has
been up in Atlanta for two weeks and is free to users with
Web-enabled electronic devices.
</P>
<P>
   So far there are roughly 3,500 users of AccessAtlanta Anywhere.
About 2,900 have signed up for e-mail alerts in categories that
interest them. Areas currently offered include local news, sports,
weather, traffic, entertainment calendars, movie times and severe
weather alerts.
</P>
<P>
   According to deGolian, AccessAtlanta's offering, unlike some
wireless services, can be customized to suit the needs, interests
or even different devices users might have.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cool thing you can do with it is customize to have e-mail
updates, traffic reports or other information whenever you want.
It's also possible for users of multiple appliances to have one
type of information sent to a pager and another to a cell phone,
even if you have devices from several providers,'' deGolian said.
``It's a broader strategy that ties into our content strategy of
broad distribution of locally focused content.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at things that were most useful to people on the
go,'' deGolian said. ``By definition, if you are wireless that
means you are not locked to your computer. If you are in your car,
traffic and weather updates make sense, movies make sense. You want
to check movie showtimes.''
</P>
<P>
   AccessAtlanta is hoping users who have made its Web site so
successful will also take advantage of the company's local wireless
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Whiteside, chief operating officer of Cox Interactive
Media, which operates AccessAtlanta, says the combination of
localized content and national content like search, chat and
shopping has propelled CIM's 26 city sites ahead of their
competition. (Cox Interactive Media is a subsidiary of Cox
Enterprises, parent company of The Atlanta Journal Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   He also credits the success to having staffers in each city
working on each site.
</P>
<P>
   Digital City, by contrast, uses a ``hub'' approach, where
content developers are based in one location and feed content to
nearby cities and towns. Digital City could not say how many
staffers were working on the Digital City Atlanta site or if there
were plans to increase its number of locally based employees.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
