<HEADLINE>
COLONIAL AIMS AT GOLDEN BEAR FOR SHOOTOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tiger trackers, for a third consecutive year, will be shut out
at the MasterCard Colonial. But those who venture to Fort Worth,
Texas, might find even more exotic game roaming between the gallery
ropes, if circumstances unfold kindly for the guys in plaid jackets
during the next eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Dare we suggest it: Golden Bear cleat marks at Colonial? For the
first time since 1983?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's far from a given. And, in a best-case scenario, we're
probably talking about Jack Nicklaus playing in a Tuesday shootout
rather than the actual tournament. But the possibility exists,
thanks to the presence of Nicklaus' son, Gary, as a rookie on the
PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, 60, has expressed a desire to attend as many events as
possible in which Gary competes this season. Gary Nicklaus, the No.
139 player on this week's money list ($46,020), can secure a spot
in the Colonial field by climbing into the Top 80 money winners by
May 7 or by receiving an exemption from tournament officials.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say Gary lands an invitation for the May 18-21 event in
Fort Worth. His father, as the 1982 Colonial champ, has a lifetime
exemption into the field and a standing invitation to take part in
the pretournament champions' dinner.
</P>
<P>
   With Jack's own event, the Memorial Tournament, looming one week
after Colonial on the PGA Tour calendar, no one on the tournament
committee expects the elder Nicklaus to exercise his option to
compete at ``Hogan's Alley.'' But a trip to the champion's dinner
would not be out of the question. And, if that happens, why not a
spot in Tuesday's shootout?
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, that might be the best possible thing we could
hope for,'' said Phil Thomas, Colonial tournament chairman. ``If we
could get Jack down here to play in a shootout, what more could you
ask for?''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas confirmed that discussions are ongoing about ways to
incorporate Senior Tour players into the Colonial shootout but said
it would be premature to characterize any fresh twists as final.
But the possibilities seem limitless.
</P>
<P>
   What about a shootout filled with father-son tandems, with the
Nicklaus duo taking on the possible pairings of Bob Duval-David
Duval, Al Geiberger-Brent Geiberger and Dave Stockton-Dave
Stockton, Jr. in a best-ball competition? What about a little
five-on-five contest, with Senior Tour rookie Tom Kite _ already a
Colonial commitment _ joining the four elder statesmen mentioned
above against five flat bellies from the PGA Tour in a team event?
What about grouping players in a four-team competition, with sides
based on birthday decades (Guys born in the 1940s play together,
guys born in the '50s play together, and so forth)?
</P>
<P>
   Without question, there is precedent for mixing Senior Tour and
PGA Tour players in an exhibition format. A few years back, the
Houston Open held a Tuesday long-drive contest between John Daly
and Jim Dent, the longest hitters on the two tours. It drew more
than 10,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus' presence at Colonial, no doubt, would spin the
turnstiles on an otherwise quiet Tuesday during tournament week.
With Tiger Woods headed to Germany that week to defend a European
Tour title, it would create some pretournament buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the Golden Bear's expanded playing schedule in 2000, a
Colonial cameo might not be that far-fetched. Nicklaus plans to
play in all four major championships on both tours. He said Gary's
weekly presence at PGA Tour events ``renewed my interest in playing
a few more times on the regular tour. I want to be part of what
he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Colonial officials stressed that Gary Nicklaus would not be
given an exemption ahead of a more deserving player simply to
enhance the opportunity to entice his father to Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be a bordering situation ... where we'd say,
`We'll do this, Jack, if you'll do that,' '' Thomas said. ``If Gary
earns his way in, we'd love to have them both. If something comes
up with Gary, we'd certainly go after Jack.''
</P>
<P>
   TIGER'S LATEST WEAPON: KNOCKDOWN, 9-IRON SHOT HELPING WOODS THIS
SEASON
</P>
<P>
   A two-week break from the PGA Tour rigors could not cool Tiger
Woods' hot streak. With Sunday's victory at the Bay Hill
Invitational, Woods has won seven of his past 10 starts at tour
events. He has finished second on two other occasions. Woods,
preparing for The Players Championship that begins Thursday, said
much of the credit for his fast start to the 2000 season can be
traced to a shot he perfected during the off-season: a knockdown,
9-iron that allows him to limit the spin on approach shots.
</P>
<P>
   The shot is especially effective on California courses, where
players usually find soft greens covered with poa-annua grass in
January and February. Such a combination tends to make wedge shots
spin back farther than normal after impact. Hence, the need for the
knockdown 9-iron. Woods leaned on the shot heavily during the
``West Coast Swing,'' when he won twice and finished second once
while becoming the first golfer in 52 years to record victories in
six consecutive tour starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the ultimate for me, right there, to be able to hit
that shot,'' Woods said. ``At times, I've surprised myself ...
because I'd never been able to hit it in competition before. That's
something I'm very proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   HAAS SEEKS AGENT
</P>
<P>
   Hunter Haas, the nation's No. 1-ranked amateur golfer, has begun
interviewing agents in preparation for turning professional this
season. A recent session with agent Jim Lehman, brother of PGA Tour
player Tom Lehman, led to Haas setting up a Monday practice round
during Masters week with Tom Lehman, Larry Mize and Tim Herron.
</P>
<P>
   Haas, a 23-year-old from Fort Worth, also has held discussions
with International Management Group, whose clients include Tiger
Woods, Arnold Palmer and David Duval. Haas plans to join Palmer for
a Tuesday practice round at Augusta National Golf Club, where the
Southwest High School graduate is scheduled to make his Masters
debut April 6-9. Haas is in the Masters field because of his
victory at the 1999 U.S. Public Links Championship. SUPPORTING
SOLHEIM
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, PGA Tour officials were embroiled in a bitter
lawsuit with Karsten Solheim, creator of Ping golf clubs, for
bringing square-grooved irons to professional golf events. Now,
they're pushing for his inclusion in the World Golf Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Finchem, PGA Tour commissioner, said his organization
supports the stance of LPGA commissioner Ty Votaw, who is urging
Hall of Fame voters to induct Solheim in its 2001 class for
lifetime achievement. Tour officials dropped their legal challenge
to Ping clubs in 1993 and mended fences with Solheim under the
direction of Finchem, who became commissioner on June 1, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Solheim, who died in February at age 88, was a longtime sponsor
of multiple LPGA events. In 1990, he created the Solheim Cup, the
women's equivalent of the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim Finchem and I both believe that Karsten is most deserving
of induction,'' Votaw said. ``Both of our organizations are in
complete support of his candidacy.'' PEERS PICK KANE
</P>
<P>
   Lorie Kane, a fifth-year participant on the LPGA Tour, has been
selected as the 2000 winner of The William and Mousie Powell Award.
Given annually by fellow players, the award recognizes the LPGA
player who, in the opinion of her playing peers, ``best exemplifies
the spirit, ideals and values of the LPGA'' through her behavior
and deeds.
</P>
<P>
   Kane, 35, will become the 15th recipient of the Powell Award on
Thursday at The Nabisco Championship in Rancho Mirage, Calif. A
winner of more than $1.8 million since joining the tour in 1996,
Kane has nine second-place finishes but still seeks her first
career LPGA victory. RECRUITING TRIP
</P>
<P>
   Tournament officials from both the MasterCard Colonial and GTE
Byron Nelson Classic have been evident during practice rounds this
week at The Players Championship, trying to secure commitments for
their events. The Colonial contingent includes tournament chairman
Phil Thomas, club president Steve Sykes, past club president Clark
Martin and former tournament chairman Floyd Wade. Byron Nelson, the
tournament's namesake, is among the glad-handers for the Nelson
event.
LPGA GOLDEN MOMENTS
</P>
<P>
   ``To commemorate the LPGA Tour's 50th anniversary, the
\Star-Telegram'' will feature a significant moment in tour history
each week during the 2000 season.'' OCT. 13, 1963
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Wright carved out an indelible spot in history, in more
ways than one, by holding off Louise Suggs, Mary Lena Faulk and
Mary Mills to win the LPGA Championship at Stardust Country Club in
Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was Wright's 13th of the season, a tour record. It
also was her fourth title at the LPGA Championship, the most by any
player. In 37 years, neither mark has been eclipsed by subsequent
LPGA tourists.
TIPS FROM THE PROS
</P>
<P>
   ``During the golf season, the ''Star-Telegram'' will feature
occasional tips from professional golf instructors based in Tarrant
County. Today's tip is from Dana Bellenger, director of instruction
at the Academy at Water Chase in Fort Worth. Bellenger also tutors
players on the PGA and Buy.com tours.'' CHIPPING FROM THIN LIES
</P>
<P>
   With the spring growing season not yet in full swing, local
fairways have more bare patches than normal. That creates extra
challenges when chipping. But you can stick it close to the hole
just as easily off bare ground as a lush lie if you remember two
simple tips: Keep your chest in front of the ball and keep your
legs still.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, you play a chip shot off your right toe. If you're
hitting off dirt or hardpan, be sure to put the ball farther back
in your stance to assure solid contact. The key alignment rule to
remember is ``Make sure the buttons on your shirt are in front of
the ball.'' The biggest problem people have with this shot is
failing to keep their chest in front of the ball so you can strike
with a descending blow.
</P>
<P>
   Get the proper alignment: ball behind your chest, heel of the
club slightly raised, grip off the left pocket. Then, keep your
lower body quiet and your wrists very firm. The tendency on a bad
lie is to try and help get the ball in the air by dipping your
knees or moving your legs to scoop the ball. You don't need to do
that. This is an arm and shoulders shot. There is no weight shift,
so body movement is not needed or desired.
</P>
<P>
   Once in position, take a short, firm swing and let the club do
the work. You'll find yourself saving strokes from the dirt. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
