<HEADLINE>
ABC GOT IT RIGHT THE FIRST TIME IN PULLING `THEN CAME YOU' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dusty TV archives brim with stories of successful mid- and
late-season launches. ``The Simpsons'' premiered in January. So did
``All in the Family.'' NBC gave ``Dateline NBC'' a March send-off.
``Dallas'' was an April experiment that surpassed all expectations.
</P>
<P>
   So the producers of ``Then Came You,'' premiering Wednesday
night on ABC, have every reason to think that late is better than
never, no?
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Came You'' is like every unspectacular sitcom you've ever
seen. Or never seen. And for it to catch on would be (a) a miracle,
(b) a travesty and (c) a sign that the apocalypse is near.
</P>
<P>
   Originally penciled in as one of the network's entries last
fall, ``Then Came You'' was pulled at the last minute because (a)
it isn't very good, (b) it isn't very original, and (c) ABC
realized it in time. Putting it on in March isn't so much a sign of
confidence as it is a sign of diffidence.
</P>
<P>
   The premise _ yet another revisitation of the mismatched-lovers
theme from ``Romeo and Juliet'' _ already gets plenty of attention
on the ABC comedies ``Dharma and Greg'' and ``Spin City,'' so to
merit a second look ``Then Came You'' would have to be pretty darn
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   It's not. It is exceedingly mediocre, borrowing from so many
comedies that have gone before that it could be the poster child
for this season's popular refrain: What's wrong with the
traditional sitcom?
</P>
<P>
   Susan Floyd plays a well-heeled divorced woman in her 30s who
falls in love with a hotel waiter 10 years her junior, played by
Thomas Newton. Both have sidekicks, re-creating the ``Will &AMP;
Grace'' vibe without the gay overtones or the hilarious
scene-stealing of Megan Mullally and Sean Hayes. Her sidekick
(Miriam Shor) seems to be doing her best impression of Jennifer
Aniston's Rachel from ``Friends.'' His (Desmond Askew) is
``Seinfeld's'' Kramer with an English accent.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the series is based on the experiences of one of the
show's creators, Betsy Thomas, who actually got divorced in her 30s
and fell in love with a young room-service waiter when she was
living in a Los Angeles hotel after moving out of her house.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of being rooted in fact, ``Then Came You'' seems
more to be relying on the fiction that viewers will swallow
anything that's delivered with a laugh track.
</P>
<P>
   `Freaks and Geeks' canceled
</P>
<P>
   If you saw Monday's episode of ``Freaks and Geeks,'' the one
where Lindsay (Linda Cardellini) tries pot and Bill (Martin Starr)
almost dies from eating peanuts, cherish it. It's the last episode
that will air on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The network informed the producers that the remaining episodes
of ``Freaks and Geeks'' will not air. They will be replaced by
editions of ``Dateline NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   On the production company's Web site, www.freaksandgeeks.com,
executive producer Judd Apatow said: ``I'm afraid to say the end
has come. NBC is dropping the show immediately and replacing it
with `Dateline.' They have agreed to allow another network to run
the last six episodes, and possibly the second season, if someone
is interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a late-season pickup is indeed unlikely, but co-executive
producer Paul Feig said discussions are taking place.
</P>
<P>
   Widely praised for its accurate depiction of high school life in
1980, ``Freaks and Geeks'' never attracted a large audience. Of
course, NBC never kept it on the air longer than four weeks at a
time. After debuting on Saturday nights last fall, the show moved
in January to Mondays at 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had great hopes for Monday,'' Feig said, ``but we never
really got the promotion we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Came You. Half-hour comedy about a woman who falls in love
with a man 10 years younger than she. Starring Susan Floyd, Thomas
Newtown, Miriam Shor and Desmond Askew. Series premiere Wednesday
night on ABC. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
