<HEADLINE>
ZUBOV SIGNS 5-YEAR, $25 MILLION DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Dallas Stars locked up their three-time
All-Star defenseman Sergei Zubov through the 2004-05 season
Tuesday, signing him to a five-year deal worth $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov, the only Stars player to play in all 73 games this
season, ranks second in the NHL in ice time among defensemen,
averaging 29 minutes, 10 seconds a game. His 41 points rank 12th
and his 32 assists tie him for 10th among defensemen in statistics
before last night's games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really exciting for myself and my family. We've spent
four years over here; so far it's just a great time with the
team,'' Zubov said. ``I've been more concentrating on just playing
hockey, but it's great to get back with one of the best teams
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have all four of their top defensemen signed to
long-term deals.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars acquired Zubov, 29, in a trade with Pittsburgh for
Kevin Hatcher on July 22, 1996. The Moscow native's career
blossomed after he came to Dallas. He was selected for his third
consecutive World All-Star team this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings his great skill with him, and his performance has
been so consistent,'' general manager Bob Gainey said. `` ... From
a personality point of view and just a balance, he's provided us
with a real element we needed.'' CARBONNEAU A GO?
</P>
<P>
   Guy Carbonneau is working on finding a comfort zone with a soft
playing cast around his fractured right wrist. He was cautiously
optimistic Tuesday that he will play Friday against Chicago. Coach
Ken Hitchcock, who misses his checking center and penalty killer,
was more definitive on his return.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in, he's playing,'' Hitchcock said. ``Our opinion is he's
a practice player on Wednesday and Thursday and if he looks as good
as he did (Tuesday) then we'll move him up to be a player on
Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau said his wrist feels sore, and he still has some
concerns about his effectiveness on faceoffs, wrist shots and
stickhandling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can do a lot of stuff out there,'' Carbonneau said. ``I can
hit the puck pretty hard. It's sore, but if I want to try a wrist
shot or stick handle a little bit then I have problems.'' THORNTON
REVIEW COMING
</P>
<P>
   Bob Gainey said he expects to have a conference call Wednesday
with winger Scott Thornton and NHL executive vice president and
director of hockey operations Colin Campbell to review Thornton's
hit Sunday on San Jose's Marco Sturm.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton's hit was ruled a match penalty for attempting to
injure when he boarded Sturm and landed a forearm to his face.
Thornton's hit was in retaliation after Sturm wrestled him to the
ice moments earlier. A match penalty is automatically reviewed by
the league, which can levy a suspension. MARSHALL SAYS HE'S READY
</P>
<P>
   Winger Grant Marshall said his right groin is as good as it gets
for now, and he's ready to play again on Friday. Ken Hitchcock,
however, isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's ready to be evaluated, there's a difference,'' Hitchcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a frustrating season for Marshall, who has played in
only 37 games because of two injured groins. This comes after his
breakout season last season, when he played in all 82 games and was
rewarded with a three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to get back,'' Marshall said. ``What's more
frustrating than anything is you want to play hard and honor that
contract, then you get hurt all year. That's very frustrating, but
I can't dwell on it.'' SLOAN SKATES, WON'T RUSH
</P>
<P>
   Winger Blake Sloan looked strong and agile Tuesday as he
returned to the ice to test his fractured ankle. His return to the
lineup is still likely a week or more away. He will wear the
red-cross jersey at Wednesday's practice, meaning he will
participate in all drills, but without any contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't tested it,'' Sloan said. ``I want to see if I
can drive off it with someone hanging on me, things like that.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
