   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-SMOKING (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rejects the
Clinton administration's plan to regulate cigarettes as drugs,
ending the federal government's main anti-smoking initiative. In a
5-4 ruling, the court says Food and Drug Administration regulators
overreached three years ago when they claimed power over cigarettes
and smokeless tobacco. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-SMOKING-FDA (Washington) _ The Food and Drug
Administration does not have the authority to regulate tobacco as
an addictive drug, the Supreme Court rules, but the agency still
has sweeping power over what is manufactured, sold and eaten in the
United States. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
