</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington)_ When a leader of the National Rifle
Association accused President Clinton of tolerating murders in
hopes of getting tougher gun control laws, George W. Bush
responsibly disagreed. But Republican congressional leaders, who
depend on NRA contributions, reacted as though the charge was no
big deal. It was the first break between Bush and his congressional
troops since he sewed up the nomination, but it is unlikely to be
the last. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
