<HEADER>
A3902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ROMEO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     03-21 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROMEO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIP-HOP JOINS MARTIAL ARTS BUT LETS PLOT MUSCLE IN
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who wants to be a millionaire? Almost every character in ``Romeo
Must Die,'' the first English-language starring vehicle for the
Hong Kong action star Jet Li. There's Isaak (Delroy Lindo), who is
waging an intimidation campaign against waterfront business owners
so he can buy up their properties, like that of Silk (DMX), whose
club may end up as the last standing opposition to Isaak's
ambition. Mac (Isaiah Washington), Isaak's bad-tempered right-hand
man, pushes around the people clinging to their shops and
businesses while dreaming of his own day in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's scrambling to get paid. There are only two honorable
people in the undercooked picture, Trish (Aaliyah), Isaak's
daughter, and Han (Li), a Hong Kong cop doing time in a Chinese
prison; he took a rap so that his brother and father could slip out
of the country. When word that his little brother has been killed
gets back to Han, he stages an escape so daring that even the
prison's guards are shaking their heads in disbelief, and he makes
his way to the United States to investigate his brother's death. He
kicks the story into gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romeo,'' which doesn't really include a Romeo and has only the
most fleeting reference to Shakespeare, is the first movie that
looks as if it was cast from the rap magazine The Source due to its
relatively chaste marriage of hip-hop and kung fu. In fact, there's
barely a shot in the movie that wouldn't make a great magazine
cover. The movie is overly dutiful in dragging itself through the
exercise of playing out its plot elements, ignoring the chief
lesson of its Hong Kong antecedents: extend the martial gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   If the Academy ever decides to give out Oscars for sheer
physical exertion, the other contenders will have to line up behind
Li. His mastery of the martial art known as wushu made Li a star
years ago to the fans of Hong Kong movies, with their exhilarating
blur of stunts and minimal-to-the-point-of-confusion story lines.
For the first half-hour or so, ``Romeo'' is very smart about giving
Li little dialogue since his command of English doesn't match his
grasp of hand-to-hand combat. Li is a comical presence because of
his Bruce-Lee-on-a-key-chain size. Even the willowy Aaliyah seems
to have a couple of inches on him, so his bouts with the SUV-size
thugs who snort vengefully into his hairline are jokey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romeo'' is a come-on, with cooing hip-hop songs popping up
whenever Aaliyah, who's a natural, glides across the screen. The
picture was conceived as a spotlight dance for Aaliyah and Li, but
they have so little chemistry together you'd think they're putting
out a fire instead of shooting off sparks. Li's filmography
includes the revered ``Fist of Legend,'' a picture whose
awe-inspiring assemblage of flying feet and soaring fists was the
basis of the mano-a-mano choreography of ``The Matrix,'' and he's
much better when he bursts into hyperactivity than when batting
around coy badinage.
</P>
<P>
   When the action gets serious and a fatal blow is struck, there's
a cut to a computer-animated version of viscera taking the impact.
All in the name of good taste, of course. Unfortunately, it's
Western technology that gets in the way of Eastern thrill-seeking
workouts, and since Li does all of his own stunts, it's a peculiar
annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the snarling come-hither of Bruce Lee and his
imitators, Li's round face takes on a beatific serenity before he
goes to work on one of his Cinemascope beatdowns. Those are more
dramatic than the rest of the picture, but they're chopped together
like a ransom note, all slivers and pieces. You catch Li in
bite-size chunks instead of the family-style helpings in his other
work, like the bravura punches and stag's leaps of the ``Once Upon
a Time in China'' series, films that raised the deadly swift Li to
a myth. (They're worth seeking out, no matter what part of town you
have to get to to rent them.)
</P>
<P>
   The camera prowls into each shot as if it's searching for an
opponent to throw down against; the movie itself seems to be
spoiling for a fight, though it doesn't have the attention span to
concentrate on the battles it does have. Li beats up his foes the
old-fashioned way: one at a time. Dreary as it is, ``Romeo'' is
bound to be a hit, thanks to its well-selected and wall-to-wall
hip-hop soundtrack _ particularly good songs by Timbaland and, yes,
Aaliyah _ that's so pervasive ``Romeo'' might as well be a musical.
DMX emerges as a star in the scattered proceedings. He establishes
so much audience rapport in his brief time onscreen that the film
suffers from his absence. DMX showed star power in ``Belly,'' his
debut, and he clearly takes acting seriously. More seriously than
``Romeo'' regards the able Jet Li. Sadly, if this movie was a
fight, they'd have stopped it.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``ROMEO MUST DIE''
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Andrzej Bartkowiak; written by Eric Bernt and John
Jarrell, based on a story by Mitchell Kapner; director of
photography, Glen MacPherson; edited by Derek G. Brechin; music by
Stanley Clarke and Timbaland; production designer, Michael Bolton;
produced by Joel Silver and Jim Van Wyck; released by Warner
Brothers. Running time: 110 minutes. This film is rated R. It has
extended scenes of Li's action choreography and violence, strong
language and gunplay.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Jet Li (Han Sing), Aaliyah (Trish O'Day), Isaiah
Washington (Mac), Russell Wong (Kai Sing), DMX (Silk) and Delroy
Lindo (Isaak O'Day).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
