<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE BARS GROW UP, POSING A QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two decades ago, New York had plenty of wine bars. Evolving out
of the wine boom of the 1970s, they were often equipped with
complicated wine-storing machinery and took themselves quite
seriously, with daunting lists, coat-and-tie stuffiness and an
attitude toward food that was either dismissive or overly reverent.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years about 20 places calling themselves wine
bars have opened in New York, some to considerable acclaim, and
none could be more different from those dinosaurs. They range in
style from the bright and lively Bateau Ivre in midtown to the dark
and romantic Tasting Room in the East Village and the casually chic
Bandol on the Upper East Side. Wine is still important, but the
pomposity is nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   What most of them share is an easygoing ambience, late hours,
decent but not elaborate food, plenty of wine _ and a
live-and-let-live approach to drinking it. In other words, just
about what everyone wants in a restaurant. These new wine bars are
also mostly French, or aspire to be.
</P>
<P>
   What they don't do, singularly or collectively, is answer a
question that's been nagging me _ slightly _ since the first
outbreak of the trend: just what is a wine bar, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Even established restaurants are getting caught up in the new
enthusiasm for wine bars. Raju Mirchandani converted his uptown Bar
and Books into Ivre, and the people who have run Etats-Unis on the
Upper East Side for nine years have opened a separate wine bar
under the same name across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Etats-Unis has one of the more intriguing wine lists among the
new bars. I particularly liked the German, Alsatian and Austrian
offerings, if only because some are available in half bottles. A
half bottle of Zind-Humbrecht's gewuerztraminer at $15 is a
remarkable buy. Etats-Unis also has some interesting old-vine
Beaujolais.
</P>
<P>
   Le Bateau Ivre bills itself as a ``bistro a vins'' and as ``New
York City's first true French wine bar.'' It's very French,
actually, but don't be fooled: the French didn't invent the wine
bar, the English did. For years, the most authentic wine bars in
Paris were Steven Spurrier's Blue Fox and Mark Williamson's Willi's
Wine Bar.
</P>
<P>
   The French quickly caught on, and signs heralding ``bistro a
vins'' and ``bar au vins'' began popping up everywhere in Paris.
But the French have always taken their wine for granted, and even
cafe owners who had better selections than others rarely advertised
it.
</P>
<P>
   The British, who have always been serious about their wines,
were the first to open pubs more oriented toward the grape than
flat, warm beer. It's no accident that one of the first wine bars
in this country was the London Wine Bar in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The new wine bars offer remarkable selections of wine, whether
they are eclectic like Etats-Unis, all Italian like Enoteca I
Trulli, or French like Bateau Ivre and L'Ivre. I doubt that there
are many restaurants in the world that offer the choices to be
found in these ambitious little restaurants. What's more, there
can't be places more conducive than these for learning more about
wine.
</P>
<P>
   Le Bateau Ivre, which takes its name from a poem by Rimbaud _
his picture is on the wall _ is actually a pocket-size brasserie,
even with its 250 wines, most of which are available by the glass.
Its fans show up for the charcuterie and fresh seafood and good
beer as much as for the wine. But this is one of the few places in
New York to suggest pairing its oysters with breathtaking, acidic
gros plant from the western Loire. The writer Jacqueline Friedrich
calls gros plant ``a rude wine made from a rude grape (folle
blanche).'' I like to think of it as muscadet's evil twin.
</P>
<P>
   Le Bateau Ivre has, if not a twin, a younger sibling called
L'Ivre, an elegantly paneled remake of the Bar and Books at
Lexington Avenue and 73rd Street. On a recent cold, rainy night, a
glass of wine by the fire at L'Ivre felt like New York at its best.
The librarylike back room, with its book-filled shelves, has been
changed hardly at all, justifying the double-entendre name: ivre,
aside from meaning intoxicated, comes from Bateau Ivre and L'Ivre
(a play on livre, which of course means book). L'Ivre draws on Le
Bateau Ivre's formidable wine collection and offers a similar but
more limited menu of bistro dishes: coq au vin, boeuf bourguignon,
open-face sandwiches, -croques-monsieur and oysters.
</P>
<P>
   Like L'Ivre, the Morrell Wine Bar and Cafe in Rockefeller Center
has plenty of backup if its wine supply runs short. It is obviously
joined at the hip to the Morrell Wine Shop next door. This is a
no-nonsense little enterprise with around 100 wines by the glass
and a brief but thoughtful menu for the busy people who dash around
Rockefeller Center. Roast chicken is the partner of choice for most
wines, and Michael Haimowitz's version here will highlight any of
the 2,000 or so wines the Morrells sell next door. Well, maybe not
the Chateau d'Yquem.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most ambitious wine program among the newcomers is
at the Tasting Room, where Colin and Renee Alevras offer some 300
wines by the bottle, all of them American. The by-the-glass list is
relatively short _ a dozen or so _ but it changes almost every
night so that, as Alevras put it, ``we can work our way through the
list with our guests.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Not many wine lists, even in California, offer Ridge Vineyards'
alicante, three different single-vineyard zinfandels from Cline
Cellars in Contra Costa County, three roussannes, two marsannes and
an Oregon muscadet.
</P>
<P>
   The Tasting Room lives up to its name with a menu designed for
wine tasting. Each dish is offered as a taste or to share. The
current ``Almost Spring'' selections include roasted skate at $10
for a taste and $18 to share. A taste of foie gras ravioli is $10;
a share $20.
</P>
<P>
   Bandol is like so many of New York's putative wine bars: really
a restaurant with more than a passing interest in wine. The chef,
James Baron, is proud of his steak frites and his lamb shank, but
he will happily serve you something light merely to go with your
wine. For me it was thinly sliced foie gras and beautifully sauteed
sea scallops, both served on mixed greens. They were ideal with a
good Brouilly. There's a good selection by the glass, too.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose this is as good a place as any to own up to the fact
that while I love a good wine bar, I'm not a great fan of wine by
the glass. To get to know and enjoy a wine, you need more than a
glass of it and you need to share it with someone. That requires a
bottle.
</P>
<P>
   The one instance when a single glass of a wine makes sense is in
a comparative tasting, and for me, one of the few places where that
kind of tasting is neither boring nor pretentious is Enoteca I
Trulli, the wine bar attached to I Trulli, Nicola Marzovilla's
southern Italian restaurant on East 27th Street. Bucking the trend
to French-oriented wine bars, Enoteca I Trulli sells only Italian
wines and has become a showcase for little-known and reasonably
priced wines from Puglia, Campania, Abruzzi and Sicily. For
tasters, a flight of three wines _ two ounces of each _ goes for
$8.75 to $23.25.
</P>
<P>
   While just about anything from I Trulli's kitchen is available
in the Enoteca, there is a special, lighter menu to satisfy those
who are more or less serious about tasting wines. Rather severe
when it first opened, Enoteca has become a warm, laid-back little
place, a bit like the old cliched Greenwich Village joints with
candles in Chianti bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, are any of these places genuine wine bars? Is there such
a thing? I don't think so. A wine bar, after all, is whatever the
owner wants it to be. I think anyplace that is serious about its
wine list and offers a place to drink wine without having to buy a
full meal is entitled to be called a wine bar. The Oyster Bar in
Grand Central Terminal has a magnificent list of mostly white
wines, and an oyster stew at the counter qualifies anyone to drink
them. Danny Meyer's Union Square Cafe, Gramercy Tavern and Eleven
Madison Park all offer interesting wines by the glass to anyone who
sits at the bar; it isn't even necessary to eat anything.
</P>
<P>
   The Bubble Lounge and Flute downtown offer dozens of Champagnes
and sparkling wines by the glass. Veritas, in the Flatiron
district, offers some of the most expensive wines in the world,
mostly French, some by the glass. The Tonic in Chelsea is a
restaurant and an old-fashioned tavern under one roof, with several
dozen wines available at the bar by the glass. Does that make it a
wine bar? Should it?
</P>
<P>
   The French have been trying to define what constitutes a bistro
since some Russian invaders coined the term more than a century
ago. If they can't figure out ``bistro,'' I'm not going to lose any
sleep over ``wine bar.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   These are some of New York City's newest wine bars:
</P>
<P>
   BANDOL 181 E. 78th St.; (212) 744-1800.
</P>
<P>
   LE BATEAU IVRE 230 E. 51st St.; (212) 583-0579.
</P>
<P>
   ENOTECA I TRULLI 122 E. 27th St.; (212) 481-7372.
</P>
<P>
   ETATS-UNIS 396 E. 81st St.; (212) 517-8826.
</P>
<P>
   L'IVRE 1020 Lexington Ave.; (212) 717-3902.
</P>
<P>
   MORRELL WINE BAR AND CAFE 1 Rockefeller Plaza; (212) 262-7700.
</P>
<P>
   TASTING ROOM 72 E. First St.; (212) 358-7831.
</P>
</TEXT>
