<HEADLINE>
PUTIN'S PLANS AFTER THE ELECTION REMAIN A MYSTERY
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take to follow.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As Russia ambles toward a second presidential election
almost surreal in its absence of sturm, drang or even
garden-variety suspense, perhaps its most amazing aspect is that
nobody yet has a clear notion of what the front-runner in the race
_ if it can be called a race _ will actually do if elected.
</P>
<P>
   That front-runner, of course, is Vladimir Putin, Russia's acting
president and the anointed successor to President Boris Yeltsin.
With but five days to the vote, Putin's name recognition is no
problem: His spare visage is plastered on every newspaper and
television screen and extolled by local kingpins in regions many
time zones away.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond manifestoes on the Internet and in Moscow newspapers,
extolling a mostly democratic regime adhering to somewhat
capitalistic rules, there is great doubt, even among experts, as to
where Putin plans to take the world's biggest nation. Some of his
few notable actions, in fact, point to a leader with a talent for
rhetoric, but considerably less intuition for the intricacies of
democratic checks and balances or Western politics.
</P>
<P>
   Russians pining for a pro-Western leader, for example, cheered
early this month when Putin met with NATO's secretary-general and
publicly raised the prospect that Russia would someday join the
organization. But anti-Westerners cheered a few days later, when he
said Russia not only has no hope of joining NATO, but doesn't want
NATO on its borders, either.
</P>
<P>
   Free-marketeers have banked on Putin's fervent paeans to
Western-style economics _ except during his frequent digressions,
such as last weeks' endorsement of a ban on most food imports to
prop up domestic producers.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have been heartened by Putin's written commitment to
political and social freedoms. And authoritarians must be equally
heartened by a string of draconian government pronouncements, such
as a recent promise to punish media outlets that publish interviews
with Chechen rebel leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Such studious inscrutability seems so far to be Putin's
hallmark. The Russian firm Garant, which keeps a database of
government actions, tracked 1,000 of Putin's official decisions as
president during January and February. More than half were
classified; more than 100 others were minor personnel changes and
political appointments. The remainder, the company concluded,
betrayed little if anything about his attitude toward the nation's
competing interests.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview published in mid-March, reporters for the
newspaper Kommersant asked Putin whether the rumors were true that
he would become his own man upon his formal election, proposing
bold policies that would ``change everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin was forthright, in his own vague way. ``I won't tell
you,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, some broad and reassuring _ to Westerners
_ suggestions of the future Putin course. His work as a business
liaison in St. Petersburg five years ago showed his comfort with
the capitalist system.
</P>
<P>
   And Western business interests generally praise his recognition
_ on paper, at least _ of the importance of free trade and open
markets. In particular, Putin has regularly argued that foreign
investment is essential to Russian economic growth. The nation
cannot advance, he has said, on the meager amount of capital that
domestic businesses generate.
</P>
<P>
   He also has made it clear that his Russia is in _ if not of _
the West. Putin has accepted European and U.S. overtures to end the
East-West estrangement brought about by the war in Kosovo. And
while it has continued to develop Russian alliances with China and
Iran, the Putin Kremlin has not dismissed outright the Western
concerns about human rights and the spread of weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Putin talks convincingly of the need for a strong state and for
laws that apply equally to everyone. His manifestoes, on the
Internet and in Russian newspapers, speak of a society distinctly
Russian in its reliance on a strong state, but European in its
guarantees of freedom and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond those generalities, however, even experts disagree over
what sort of Russia Putin would build as president.
</P>
<P>
   His brief public career offers few clues. Putin's first
substantive job came in 1998, as head of the FSB, Russia's domestic
successor to the KGB. It was a sensitive post for Putin, who said
this month that he resigned the KGB in 1990 after learning that the
agency was leading a coup against the Soviet leader, Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
</P>
<P>
   The coup, he said, convinced him that communism and the Soviet
machine were going nowhere. But it remains unclear what ideology,
if any, replaced Putin's officially mandated commitment to Marxism.
</P>
<P>
   Some reports, obliquely denied by Putin, suggest that he cleaned
house when he became head of the FSB, purging the agency of its
Soviet-era holdovers. Publicly, he has defended the agency as a
guarantor of order and, for better or worse, a talented executor of
commands from higher-ups.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
