<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3911 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JOFFREY-DANCE-REVIEW-     03-21 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOFFREY-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LES PRESAGES': THE JOFFREY MAKES A COMEBACK IN CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mcd) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Mankind battles Fate with a capital `F' in ``Les
Presages,'' the epic ballet by Leonide Massine that the Joffrey
Ballet of Chicago has just performed so magnificently as part of
its season here.
</P>
<P>
   As Tchaikovsky's Fifth Symphony rumbled to its climax, as
happiness vanquished evil and temptation onstage, Massine's famed
allegorical vision of 1933 became suddenly a metaphor for the
Joffrey's own triumphant battle for survival.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after severe financial problems pointed to the
possible demise of one of America's most popular ballet troupes,
its move from New York (including a legal reorganization and name
change from Joffrey Ballet to Joffrey Ballet of Chicago) is a
lesson in determined rescue strategy.
</P>
<P>
   When the Joffrey took over rented studios and offices in
downtown Chicago in October 1995, its $9 million budget had been
cut to $5 million and its dancers reduced to 30 from 40. It had
repeatedly canceled seasons in New York, where it has not been seen
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Things look very different now. On the artistic side, not only
performances but a rehearsal of George Balanchine's ``Square
Dance'' over the weekend reveal an amazing new perfection in
classical style. Gerald Arpino, the Joffrey's artistic director,
beams when asked if he and his ballet masters (Mark Goldweber,
Cameron Basden and Charthel Arthur) have recently concentrated on
toe work. But true to form, this is the Gerald Arpino whose
choreography has always been more concerned with spirit than steps.
No, he suggests, technique is not the only goal. ``I want them to
dance from the inside,'' he said, pointing to his heart.
</P>
<P>
   With typical Joffrey gumption and considerable help from an
expanding group of supporters in Chicago with high-powered civic
connections, the company has not only survived but acquired a
presence here that it never had in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago has embraced the Joffrey,'' said Lois Weisberg, the
city's cultural affairs commissioner, noting that several factors
worked in the company's favor. Bereft of a world-class ballet
company that would match the reputation of its major arts
institutions, the business and arts communities here have been
energetic on the company's behalf. The Joffrey's new chairman is C.
Steven McMillan, the president and chief operating officer of the
Sara Lee Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The troupe was also familiar to Chicago, having picked up a
following since it began performing here in 1957. ``They were held
in high esteem,'' Weisberg said. ``They were not perceived as
interlopers. It was not Joffrey Ballet of New York but Joffrey
Ballet of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard M. Daley attends performances and ``is extremely
interested in the Joffrey,'' Weisberg added. ``He knew its
reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest at the top helps. The Joffrey is about to acquire a
building in the downtown Loop area, a gift from Commonwealth
Edison, a utilities company. The $20 million renovation for
studios, offices and retail space is expected to receive some help
from the city through its tax-increment financing program, in which
the city provides incentive money for development in anticipation
of being repaid with increased real estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Joffrey's good luck to arrive in this revitalized
theater district in the Loop just as other arts organizations
(including the Goodman Theater) also move in, along with a
potential audience drawn by apartments recently converted from
offices and factories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Chicagoan,'' Arpino, a longtime resident of Greenwich
Village, said with a straight face and then added convincingly, ``I
gave up my apartment in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Once dependent on touring, the Joffrey has identified itself
with Chicago by working to increase its presence here. The
company's budget has climbed back to over $9 million with no
deficits. In New York the Joffrey could afford an orchestra at City
Center, but even this weekend at the landmark Auditorium Theater
the music was, for economic reasons, on tape. Nonetheless, the
company's five-week ``Nutcracker'' season employs an orchestra and
last winter brought in $2.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company performs in the Chicago area for 10 of its 37 work
weeks, which include rehearsal. There is also a concerted outreach
program with middle schools in the city. Since 1997 the company has
had a summer residency in Telluride, Colo., and resumed
international touring, with stops in Egypt, Turkey and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Despite significant progress, Arpino has no immediate plans to
come to New York. While the company is still rebuilding, intense
scrutiny might not help. ``What has happened is a miracle,'' he
said. ``We're a legend now, and I'm holding back. In New York, we
would be expected to be what we once were.''
</P>
<P>
   These remarks seem to imply that the company is not at full
strength in terms of repertory, number of dancers and finances. All
true, which makes the high artistic level of the dancing and
production values during the weekend's performances all the more
surprising. In addition to ``Les Presages,'' which was a major
Joffrey revival in 1993-94, the program included its well-known
staging of ``L'Apres-Midi d'un Faune'' by Vaslav Nijinsky and the
company premiere of Balanchine's ``Prodigal Son.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   What Arpino really means is what the company's staff and
supporters here all insist upon: that the Joffrey Ballet of Chicago
is a new company, and its reason for being is to maintain the
continuity of vision of the Joffrey Ballet, founded in 1956 by
Arpino and Robert Joffrey, who died in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to do in 10 years what other organizations do in
40,'' said Bruce Sagan, a regional newspaper publisher and
businessman who has been president of the Steppenwolf Theater
Company and has been prominent in supporting cultural groups in
Chicago for decades. ``The first thing was to survive,'' Sagan
said. ``That meant we couldn't run deficits and that means you have
to make choices and set priorities. I too would like an orchestra
with performances, but that will come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The effort so far has gone into controlling the cost of
everything so that Gerry Arpino can rebuild the repertory and get
new dancers,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 few in the dance world would have bet on the Joffrey's
future. The troupe was deeply in debt (with a deficit of $1.6
million), and it was perceived as a touring company based in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Jack R. Lemmon, executive director of the Joffrey Ballet of
Chicago, credits the New York board of the former company with a
strategic decision. ``The company needed to reinvent itself,'' he
said. ``It was a touring company that occasionally performed in its
home city. Now it is a resident company in Chicago that still does
national and international touring.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ballet Theater and New York City Ballet, with which it had
been ranked, the Joffrey had its home in New York. But whether New
York could support all three companies was a question. The company
did, however, have board members from Chicago and the Midwest and
it was this group that advocated a reorganized entity in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   On the artistic side, the turnaround has been even more
significant. Predictions were dire after the 1993 Joffrey premiere
of ``Billboards,'' a rock ballet to music by the Artist (still
Prince at the time).
</P>
<P>
   Arpino remains unapologetic for ``Billboards,'' and despite the
occasional scorn of critics, the ballet is credited in large part
with saving the company and keeping its dancers performing.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, the repertory picture has changed. In addition to the
return of Arpino's own works and of 20th-century classics
previously performed by the Joffrey, there have been premieres by
Laura Dean and young choreographers like Randy Duncan, formerly a
dancer in the Joseph Holmes Company.
</P>
<P>
   This fall there was also the company premiere of ``Frankie and
Johnny,'' a landmark 1938 work by Ruth Page and Bentley Stone,
pioneers of American ballet in Chicago in the 1930's and 40's.
Other firsts for the company that Arpino plans to present are
Antony Tudor's ``Lilac Garden'' and Martha Graham's ``Appalachian
Spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Arpino admits that ``in the first year here, when we had to
survive, I let the styles go down.'' But a visit with the three
former leading Joffrey dancers who have served as ballet masters in
the last two or three years does much to explain why the company's
32 dancers now look so stylish and technically strong. Eleven are
from the former company, with Deborah Dawn the senior ballerina and
best known. But some who were relatively new to the company in
1994, like Calvin Kitten, Davis Robertson and Maia Wilkins, among
others, have developed into strong and striking dancers.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight Thursday and Friday was certainly ``Les
Presages.'' Basden's staging, based on the original Joffrey revival
by Tatiana Leskova, does a fabulous job of making a historical
curiosity come alive to modern audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The ballet's interest lies less in its allegorical duel between
a generic hero and a gnomic Fate figure than in the movement
choruses that Massine borrowed from German modern dance in the
1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Basden does wonders not only in featuring the women's strong toe
work, but also in the clarity she has achieved in the swiftly
moving contrapuntal patterns.
</P>
<P>
   But now, as was not true before, the soloists in each movement
give Massine's once-surprising Neo-Classical choreography a
forceful projection. They included Wilkins, Dawn, Domingo Rubio and
Leticia Oliveira, and alternating as Fate, Robertson and Guoping
Wang.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prodigal Son,'' although familiar at City Ballet and other
companies, is atypical Balanchine, his last experiment in a
Constructivist style. Kitten is too pure a classical dancer to
adjust immediately to its grotesque aspects. But by his second
performance Friday, he made his very young rebel persuasive.
Trinity Hamilton also did better as the Siren on the second night,
preserving her marvelous loose-hipped cool.
</P>
<P>
   When the Joffrey revived ``Faune'' in 1979, its minimalism and
potent sensuality were mesmerizing. Against an approximation of
Leon Bakst's woodland backdrop, lighted brilliantly by Kevin
Dreyer, the Faune still eats his grapes, scares off seven nymphs
and satisfies himself with a celebrated autoerotic climax. A new
literalism crept into Robertson's performance at the end on
Thursday. On Friday, it was markedly toned down by Rubio. Both were
marvelously intense. As in the good old days, a program at the
Joffrey was unlike any other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
