<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SEARCH-ENGINES-NYTR     03-21 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEARCH-ENGINES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LADIES AND GENTLEMEN, START YOUR SEARCH ENGINES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DWAYNE FATHERREE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lumping all of the online search sites under one generic label
is like saying sharks and guppies are both fish. Although
technically correct, you wouldn't want to mistake one for the
other.
</P>
<P>
   A search engine by definition is a script or tool that lets
users search information, sift and parse it. In colloquial use, it
is a portal site through which Web users can surf the Web, finding
sites or pages that may or may not contain information they want.
</P>
<P>
   Different portals use different criteria to index sites, some
automatically, others by hand. Some basic knowledge of portal
design can make your next trip on the Web less frustrating, because
you'll be able to tailor your searches.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you never want to mention the phrase search engine
to a Yahoo! employee. Because Yahoo is indexed by people, not
machines, it is known as a Web directory. Teams of editors review
sites and decide which ones should be classified where.
</P>
<P>
   Although this process can put the most relevant sites for a
search term closer to your fingertips, it also means that not as
many sites can be indexed as readily. LookSmart and Google are
other examples of directory sites.
</P>
<P>
   For Web site operators, human indexing also means that you can't
improve your site's ranking by simply changing the content. A
reviewer will have to revisit and rejudge your site.
</P>
<P>
   My own experience has been that indexed sites are good for
``quick hit'' information like contact phone numbers, general
background on a subject or even links to more detailed sites. They
are not updated as quickly as automated sites.
</P>
<P>
   Automated sites are truly search engines, so you can call them
that with impunity. Like directory sites, they also have their
glitches. Most build Web indices by ``spidering'' sites, meaning
that an automated browser physically clicks through pages and ranks
them based on the content. Lycos, Infoseek, AltaVista and HotBot
are all examples of automated sites.
</P>
<P>
   Spiders rank sites in different ways. First, they can read the
meta tag information in the head of the site pages. Those tags give
thumbnail information on the site content, which the spider uses to
determine the relevancy of that site to a submitted request.
</P>
<P>
   Some less-than-scrupulous Web designers exploit this method of
indexing, loading their pages with meta tags unrelated to the site
in order to get higher search rankings. That explains why your
search for baby carriages can turn up links to Wicked Wanda's
Painatorium or some other porn site. Most automated directories
will block sites from the index for misuse of tags information if
the staff becomes aware of problems.
</P>
<P>
   Spiders also can read the first several hundred characters of a
page to determine content. Unfortunately, sites that use graphics
rather than text are less likely to be accurately indexed in this
way.
</P>
<P>
   The upside of automated sites is that those spiders go just
about everywhere, whether an editor tells it to or not. If you are
trying to do an exhaustive search on a topic, you will probably
find more sources through an automated search site. The level of
relevance, however, can be spotty.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to find what you want is to make sure you ask the
question as precisely as possible. Using a plus or minus symbol
directly before a search term will force most engines to either
include or exclude sites containing that term. For phrase searches,
enclose your search term in double quotes. This way most search
engines will search for that string of words, not just any
appearance of any word in your search.
</P>
<P>
   This comes in handy if you are searching for, say, fresh cod
fingers. If you type it without quotes, you'll get hits from sites
that contain any one of those three words, no matter if the site is
for fresh flowers or Billy Bob's premium codpieces. With quotes,
the results are dramatically more focused.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as the technology that drives the Web progresses,
these rules will become obsolete. At Ask Jeeves (www.ask.com), the
software will parse a question and return the most likely results
based on its interpretation of what you are looking for. Other
sites, like MetaCrawler or Dogpile, use an interface to send your
search to multiple search sites at once and report the results back
to you.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how advanced things get, one basic rule still holds.
If you speak clearly and ask nicely, you'll get whatever you want.
The same thing works for people, too.
</P>
<P>
   (Dwayne Fatherree edits newscoast.com, the Web site of the
Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune, which is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
