</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AL-AMIN-FUNERAL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amid tears for slain officer exists plea to forgive suspected
killer
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fulton County sheriff's Deputy Ricky Kinchen ``loved
good church,'' his pastor said, and the nearly three-hour ceremony
Tuesday _ proclaimed a homegoing instead of a funeral _ would have
surely made him rapturous.
</P>
<P>
   Three thousand people, most of them in the uniforms of police
and sheriff's departments from the metro area and around the state,
filled the huge sanctuary and balcony of Jackson Memorial Baptist
Church for the ceremony. There was singing, shouting, screaming,
and cheering as well as crying for the 36-year-old officer, shot
down Thursday night when he and his partner tried to serve an
arrest warrant for minor charges. The mood was lightened
considerably by the arrest Monday night of Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin,
the former H. Rap Brown, the man charged with killing Kinchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to forgive him,'' cried the Rev. Michael J. Gray,
pastor of Kinchen's small church, referring to Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no,'' the congregation rumbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' rejoined the preacher. ``He got a price to pay,
but you gotta forgive him!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We loved him like a brother,'' said Maj. Michael Cooke, chief
of the warrant service division, where Kinchen worked the
4-to-midnight shift with Deputy Aldranon English, who was seriously
wounded in the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``God sent down a transmission to Ricky Kinchen Thursday
night,'' Cooke said. `` `Your watch is over,' He said. `You can go
Code 8 (the sheriff's radio code for going out of service or end of
shift) and be in service with the Lord for eternity.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Antonio Sewell, a Fulton County deputy, opened the
service with a rich baritone rendering of ``I Won't Complain'' that
brought many of the mourners, uniformed and civilian, to their
feet. One elderly man leaped up and down, waving his program in one
hand and his cane in the other.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Gray's roaring, fist-waving eulogy that set the tone.
``Ricky was a dedicated man to God,'' he said as he warmed up. ``A
lot of people in our church didn't know he was a deputy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray said he talked with God after the shooting ``and I asked
him why, why him, why now. And I think He answered me.'' America
has strayed from religion, Gray roared, and ``He said, `I'm gonna
use Ricky to get the attention of this nation!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police motorcycle officers led a five-minute-long
motorcade from Turner Field to the church just outside Interstate
285. Kinchen's casket, draped with a U.S. flag, was brought to the
church at 10 a.m. under an escort of sheriffs' cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time we lose an officer, whether it's from our department
or another department, it's like losing a family member,'' said
Cobb County police officer Brody Staud, who recalled the deaths
last summer of two Cobb County officers during a hostage standoff.
``It hurts every time it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   It will take time to ease the hurt, but many deputies said they
took comfort in the arrest of Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps a lot,'' DeKalb County Sheriff's Major Nancy
Villalpando said of the news. ``Knowing he's not out there injuring
or hurting anyone else definitely helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Sheriff Jackie Barrett said, ``Ricky's badge,
Badge 1008, will be retired from service, and I will now present
his badge to his family.'' The diminutive sheriff walked down from
behind the altar and handed the badge to Sherese Kinchen, the
deputy's widow.
</P>
<P>
   Sherese Kinchen seemed to hold up well during the ceremony. As
she emerged from the church behind the casket, a lone piper
somewhere out of sight playing ``Amazing Grace,'' she appeared
gaunt and worn, her two daughters clinging to her knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has a wonderful deputy standing guard in heaven,'' said
Mayor Bill Campbell. ``Each time we see our loved ones go out the
door, we should hug them tightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writers Alfred Charles, David
Pendered and Dan Chapman contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
