<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3917 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-HOUSTON-MUSEUM22-COX     03-21 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-MUSEUM22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Huge addition to the Museum of Fine Arts/Houston might be a
model for High's expansion
 &HT;    By Tom Sabulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If it were a movie, it might be called ``Giant.''
</P>
<P>
   Opening Saturday, the new Audrey Jones Beck Building, built as
an expansion of the Museum of Fine Arts/Houston, is the biggest
project in a stampede of Texas construction that will result in
$750 million of new museums in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   But the Beck building, named for a benefactor who donated a
trove of impressionist and post-impressionist paintings, has its
own significance, as well. It stresses enormous, functional size _
a total of 192,447 square feet, with 84,400 devoted to galleries, a
number that moves the MFAH, in terms of exhibition space, from 30th
to sixth-largest museum in the country. (The High Museum of Art in
Midtown Atlanta and its downtown Folk Art and Photography Galleries
have combined exhibition space of nearly 40,000 square feet.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a powerhouse, a very muscular demonstration,''
says Michael Shapiro, the High's acting director, referring to the
new museum. Shapiro has made a few visits to the Beck building,
while under construction, with local curators and patrons. One of
them, he said, described the Beck building as ``Texas big.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowds may be as large.
</P>
<P>
   MFAH director Peter Marzio expects annual attendance to leap
from 1.3 million to 2 million in the Beck's first year, a figure
that could put his institution among the Top 5 art museums in the
country, rivaling such national destinations as the Art Institute
of Chicago and the Museum of Modern Art in New York _ but still far
behind the two national leaders, the Metropolitan Museum of Art in
Manhattan and the National Gallery of Art in Washington, which
attract nearly 5 million people a year, according to recent figures
from the American Association of Museums. (An Atlanta comparison:
The High Museum drew 475,225 in fiscal year 1999.)
</P>
<P>
   As the High Museum awaits a final master plan that may well lead
to a major expansion, its leaders have looked at Houston and the
Beck building, the biggest addition to the Sunbelt's museum
landscape in years, for lessons in what they want to do. And what
they don't want.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the to-do list, of course: raise money. The key to the
formidable $85 million Beck building is a wall of cool, blond
Indiana limestone almost 30 feet high and 60 feet long. It has
3,600 letters on it, each 7 inches to 8 inches tall, spelling out
the names of 170 major donors. A gift of at least $100,000 ensured
a donor's name would be engraved in perpetuity in this slab of
philanthropy which represents a spirited commitment, and yet
nothing unusual, in this city of big money and equally big arts
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the individuals, foundations and corporations carved
into this donor wall have gallery spaces named for them. The
smallest cost $300,000; the largest $10 million. And since donors
were asked to endow those spaces for maintenance, as well as
construction, the Beck building campaign has reached a total of
$127 million.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Spanish architect Rafael Moneo, the Beck building is
another milestone in the American museum building boom, a trend
that has been percolating for decades but seems to be accelerating,
heated by the strong economy and mega shows that set attendance
records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bilbao is probably a turning point,'' says Shapiro, referring
to the audacious Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao, Spain, whose 1997
opening entranced the art world. ``A city was transformed in the
world imagination on the basis of a single building. It fed this
sense that there's a kind of convergence between civic ambition and
architectural ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 600 museums _ art, history, science and others _ have
been built since 1970. Name almost any city large (Cincinnati,
Milwaukee, New York) or small (Davenport, Iowa; San Angelo, Texas),
and a new art museum has recently opened there or is in the works.
In Atlanta, the Woodruff Arts Center has hired Italian architect
Renzo Piano to redesign its Midtown campus, which includes the
High.
</P>
<P>
   But the Beck is responsible for ``radical'' innovations, says
Marzio, and museum insiders elsewhere have taken note. To reserve
as much space as possible to display its collections of European
and American art, the MFAH purchased two buildings nearby for
administrative offices and storage/conservation space.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the crowds coming, Marzio's team made a more
controversial move. It opened its arms to the automobile: A covered
drive dominates its main entrance. Pushed to its property line
limit, the Beck building can be viewed as anti-pedestrian, a blocky
container of stone (Indiana limestone again) connected by tunnels
under public streets to a parking garage/visitors' center, on one
side, and the original museum on the other side. (At least the
tunnel between the two museums is filled by James Turrell's
delightful installation ``The Light Inside,'' a neon and halide
light projection that plays with your sense of perception as you
walk through it.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to respect the reality of the automobile,'' Marzio
explains. ``It was a matter of trying a multiple approach to the
museum, which did not tell the car it was unwanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Architect Moneo, 62, says it was an opportunity to address ``how
cars are able to live together with buildings,'' a crucial
consideration in any sprawling city but especially in a
metropolitan area of more than 4 million people whose mass transit
relies primarily on buses, with no subway or light rail.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the approach to the new museum feels like a fine art
drive-through seems a minor point when one considers the needs it
fills as an art repository and what Marzio calls an ``intensely
public'' gathering place. Certainly, anyone who's had to
painstakingly steer through packed Picasso and Rockwell shows isn't
going to gripe about the broad avenues of oak (for the permanent
collection) and terrazzo (for changing exhibits) running through
these galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, the High's expansion would not be as large as the
MFAH's. And Shapiro makes clear the Atlanta museum is emphasizing a
more understated design that focuses on natural elements. Architect
Piano already has revealed his suggestion for a large cut-through
garden at the center. And the Woodruff's desire to cater to
pedestrians in its next phase is well-documented.
</P>
<P>
   Curious Atlantans will want to look at another Houston jewel,
the Menil Collection, also designed by Piano _ and run by Ned
Rifkin, the former High director who left in January _ for a bigger
clue as to what the Woodruff expansion might bring. The Menil's
softer, more contemplative nature is something High leaders are
seeking to complement Richard Meier's original building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a wonderful modernist sculptural statement on
Peachtree Street,'' Shapiro says, referring to Meier's creation.
``We don't need a Bilbao-type statement; it would give you
indigestion. We need something that is welcoming. That is calm.
That is gracious. And we're looking at something that's much more
open to nature (than the Beck).''
</P>
<P>
   He says the High is seeking something ``kind of in-between'' the
Beck building's dynamism and the ``more spiritual and tranquil
atmosphere of the Menil.''
</P>
<P>
   Rifkin hails the Beck building as ``a testament to the strength
of Houston's commitment to the vitality of this city's growth and
development in the visual arts.''
</P>
<P>
   But he looks ahead with a competitive eye. ``Whereas the MFA
Houston is a point of entry for so many,'' he says, ``the Menil
Collection will become a true oasis for contemplation and
meditation of the finest art available to the people of Houston and
visitors to this city. It is where art can be seen to greatest
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sabulis writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
