<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AHP-BASF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALE OF AMERICAN CYANAMID GIVES AMERICAN HOME CASH TO SHOP FOR A
PARTNER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Germany)   By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Home Products Corp. said Tuesday that it had agreed
to sell its struggling agricultural business to BASF, the German
chemicals giant, for $3.8 billion in cash _ a move that added to
Wall Street speculation that the drug company will try again to
find a corporate mate.
</P>
<P>
   But John R. Stafford, chairman and chief executive of American
Home, said in an interview Tuesday that the company, which has
failed to complete three proposed mergers in the last two years,
was not looking for another partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no conversations going on, no plans and no need,''
Stafford said. ``We've made it on our own since 1926. We're in a
better position now than we've been in sometime in terms of our
pipeline and balance sheet. There is no question that we can
compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors have flown on Wall Street about possible partners for
American Home ever since late last year when Pfizer upset the
company's plans to merge with Warner-Lambert. Pfizer began a
hostile takeover of Warner on Nov. 4, just hours after
Warner-Lambert agreed to buy American Home for $70 billion in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pfizer won the battle for Warner-Lambert, American Home
walked away with $1.8 billion as a settlement for the break-up.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the agreement with BASF would add $3.8 billion more
to that stash of cash. Under the proposal, BASF will also assume
about $100 million of debt held by American Home's agricultural
business, known as American Cyanamid. American Home has been trying
since last year to sell its agricultural operations, which have
been hurt recently by the downturn in crop prices and by
competition from Monsanto.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase would make BASF the fourth-largest agricultural
company in the world and greatly increase its presence in the
United States. Several large companies _ Bayer AG and Dow Chemical
_ were also competing to buy American Cyanamid.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Tuesday that American Home could use the money to
attempt another merger with a competitor or to buy a smaller drug
company. The money will also help settle thousands of lawsuits now
pending against American Home filed by people who said they were
harmed by the company's diet drug combination, fen-phen.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford said that the company planned to use some of the money
to strengthen its biotechnology operations. American Home owns 54
percent of Immunix, a biotechnology company in Seattle, which is
selling Enbrel, a drug for rheumatoid arthritis. Stafford said
American Home would soon invest $1 billion in a plant in Ireland to
make Enbrel and other drugs developed through genetic engineering.
</P>
<P>
   The companies most often mentioned as the next potential
partners for American Home are Novartis and Pharmacia, the proposed
name of a company formed by the pending merger between Pharmacia &AMP;
Upjohn and Monsanto.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all part of the general gossip in the business,'' said
Neil Sweig, an analyst at Ryan, Beck and Co.
</P>
<P>
   Novartis, a Swiss company, has applied to list its shares on the
New York Stock Exchange, a move that would allow it use stock,
rather than cash, to buy an American company. By buying American
Home, Novartis could greatly increase its share of America's drug
market, where companies can charge higher prices for drugs than
elsewhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also speculate that American Home could link up with
Pharmacia because Fred Hassan, the company's chairman, once worked
for Stafford as American Home's No. 2 executive.
</P>
<P>
   But Stafford said he was talking to neither Novartis or
Pharmacia.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, American Cyanamid's sales of herbicide
have foundered because of competition from Roundup, the herbicide
made by Monsanto. In the mid-1990s, Monsanto began selling seeds
that had been genetically engineered to resist Roundup, allowing
farmers to spray the weedkiller over their fields without harming
the crops. Farmers have quickly snatched up the genetically
engineered seeds that save them both time and money.
</P>
<P>
   BASF is buying American Cyanamid amid a growing international
controversy over the genetically engineered seeds that could now
turn around in Cyanamid's favor. Some farmers are now questioning
whether to plant the seeds because of the growing unease among
consumers over the safety of the foods and crops harvested from
them. Some analysts think that Cyanamid's herbicide sales could
rebound as a result.
</P>
<P>
   By selling American Cyanamid, American Home will be able to
focus on selling drugs, a business with much higher profit margins
than agricultural chemicals and seeds. American Home, based in
Madison, N.J., sells Premarin, the hormone-replacement therapy for
women, which is one of the most prescribed drugs in the country.
The company also has a myriad of new drugs, including Sonata, a
sleep aid, and Prevnar, a vaccine for infants. The company also
makes over-the-counter products like Advil and Centrum vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say that American Home must soon find a partner
because Stafford has indicated that he plans to retire in the next
few years. But Stafford said Tuesday that he had no immediate plans
to step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 62 and in good health,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2016EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
