<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3921 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUM     03-21 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUMN-ADV26-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV26 
 EVERYDAY ETHICS 
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26 AND THEREAFTER.
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by EVERYDAY ETHICS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By RANDY COHEN 
 c.2000 Randy Cohen 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I Want My MP3
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a college student who listens to music I download from
the Internet. This is probably illegal and in a sense it is
stealing. Can I continue to do it, just as many ethical people
jaywalk? Or is this akin to walking into a store and stealing
something?
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous, New Jersey
</P>
<P>
   A. To download music from the Net illegally is theft, depriving
songwriters, performers, music publishers and record companies of
payment for their work. I over Elton John's head and swatting him
with a stick until he sings ``Candle in the Wind'' (or stops
singing it, depending on your taste), but it is dishonest, and you
should not do it.
</P>
<P>
   Your temptation is understandable. In a perverse kind of social
progress, the Internet makes it easy to steal songs right in your
own home, while you're still in your pajamas. You might almost make
a case that it is unethical of Time Warner, say, to tantalize
honest music lovers beyond human endurance. This is a ticklish line
of reasoning, however, perilously close to blaming the victim. That
is, even if I sashay around town in a sport coat made of $100
bills, your robbing me is unethical. Unethical, but understandable.
</P>
<P>
   Yours is an intriguing sort of mischief, less likely to be
deterred by calls for individual rectitude than by technological
innovation. What stops many people from photocopying a book and
giving it to a pal is not integrity but logistics; it's easier and
inexpensive to buy your friend a paperback copy. Similarly,
technologies are or will soon be in place to encrypt music so that
it can't be stolen easily and that make it convenient to pay for
just the songs you want.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be all kinds of new ways to legally download music
_ by single cut, or for a limited number of plays, or for a limited
amount of time,'' Marc Morgenstern has told me. He runs new media
activities for ASCAP, an organization that protects publishers' and
songwriters' rights and collects their royalties. ''We're going on
the assumption that people want to be good, and we're looking for
ways to help make it easy for them to do the right thing.'' In
fact, ASCAP seems less interested in helping people be good than in
making it impossible for them to be bad. But if that system means
its songwriters can make a living and college students can walk in
the sun once again, that's not such a terrible thing.
</P>
<P>
   Q. In a medical study in which patients received regular blood
transfusions, one blood donor was found to have Creutzfeldt-Jakob
(''mad cow'') disease. As there is no current evidence that the
disease is transmitted by blood, none of the patients were told
about the diagnosis. The researchers reasoned that the mental
anguish provoked by the remote possibility that a patient might be
infected by the donor was not worth disclosure. Did they make the
right choice?
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Griesar, Portland
</P>
<P>
   A. They made the wrong choice _ a condescending and
paternalistic one. If I were a patient, I'd prefer to know as much
as I could about my treatment and its possible risks. As an adult,
I am capable of understanding what it means for a risk to be small
and a danger remote. And so, unless I've specifically instructed my
doctor to withhold certain information, he ought not to do so. That
said, knowing that many doctors have an honorable intention to
minimize a patient's anxiety, I must be assertive and solicit
information from my doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have ethical questions that you need answered? Send them
to ethicist &LR; nytimes.com, or Everyday Ethics, New York Times
Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th floor, New York, N.Y. 10168.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on EVERYDAY
ETHICS and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
