u a BC-TENN-EXECUTE-NYT &LR;      03-21 0292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TENN-EXECUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT LIFTS STAY OF EXECUTION FOR CHILD KILLER IN
TENNESSEE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ A federal appeals court Tuesday lifted a stay of
execution for a child killer in Tennessee, making it possible that
the state could carry out its first execution in 40 years early
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a federal judge must decide the last issue on
appeal, whether the killer, Robert Glen Coe, 43, is mentally
competent and whether state courts properly considered his mental
state. Coe was convicted of kidnapping, raping and murdering
8-year-old Cary Ann Medlin in Greenfield in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Judge John Nixon of U.S. District Court in Nashville stayed
Coe's execution on Monday so the defense could pursue appeals. But
the 6th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals in Cincinnati Tuesday vacated
the stay and sent the case to another federal judge to decide the
competency issues. A separate appeal is before the U.S. Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Coe is scheduled to be executed by lethal injection at 1 a.m. on
Thursday at the Riverbend Maximum Security Prison in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee is the only Southern state that has yet to resume
executions since the U.S. Supreme Court re-instated the death
penalty in 1976. The South leads the nation in the number of
executions, with the 216 carried out by Virginia and Texas
accounting for about a third of the 623 executions in the United
States since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   While no death sentences have been carried out in Tennessee, the
state's juries have not been reluctant to impose them. There are 97
people on the state's death row, which makes it the 12th largest in
the nation, according to the Death Penalty Information Center in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
