<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3923 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-21 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
  
 
 SURVIVOR OF PRINCESS DIANA CRASH DEFENDS HIMSELF 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In September 1997, immediately after the death of  &UR; Princess &LR; 
 &UR; Diana &LR; , the only survivor of the crash was praised by  &UR; Mohamed &LR; 
 &UR; al-Fayed &LR; , father of Diana's lover, fellow victim  &UR; Dodi &LR; 
 &UR; al-Fayed &LR; . Also killed was driver &UR; Henri Paul &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The passenger who lived was bodyguard  &UR; Trevor Rees-Jones &LR; .
Al-Fayed brought Rees-Jones' mother and stepfather to Paris, put
them up in his palatial apartment and ferried them to and from the
hospital in his limousine. When he launched his own investigation
into the British ``conspiracy'' he believed responsible for the
crash _ he refused to place any blame on drunken driver Paul, whom
he had hired _ it became clear to Rees-Jones and his parents that
their agreement with and support of his point of view was expected.
</P>
<P>
   But Rees-Jones, whose head was battered in the accident, could
hardly remember the details al-Fayed expected him to provide as
evidence for his theory. When he refused to ``remember'' facts that
would corroborate the bereaved father's version of the story,
al-Fayed turned on him, blaming the deaths on the bodyguard's lack
of professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   All this was intensely painful to Rees-Jones, perhaps even more
so than recovering from blows that broke every bone in his face,
pushed his nose flat into his face and his eyes an inch and a half
farther apart than they'd been before. ``Everyone deserves a right
to reply,'' he told Personals in describing his reasons for writing
``The Bodyguard's Story'' (Warner; $25.95). ``Certain accusations
have been thrown at us in the media. This is our right.''
</P>
<P>
   There was much publicity early on, for example, about Rees-Jones
allegedly wearing a seat belt while Di and Dodi weren't. This was
considered unprofessional for a bodyguard, who is supposed to have
freedom to move around in a vehicle. Rees-Jones couldn't remember
whether he'd been belted.
</P>
<P>
   But when French investigators determined that he was not belted,
published news accounts tended to overlook the finding. This book,
he said, will set the record straight.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, he said, he has ``two years' worth of legal bills to
pay'' as the investigation of the case, with a possibility of
criminal charges being leveled, worked its way through the French
courts. Rees-Jones wouldn't say how much advance he received for
the book, but he did say he was deeply in debt to his French
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The French legal team introduced Rees-Jones to New York agent
 &UR; Michael Carlisle &LR; , who in turn suggested that he tell his story to
 &UR; Moira Johnston &LR; , who lives in the Napa Valley and is the respected
author of several investigatory books, including ``Spectral
Evidence,'' an exploration of memory and truth in the Ramona sexual
assault case.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the book were kept secret for fear al-Fayed would
launch legal action to stop its publication. (He sued
unsuccessfully in London, where portions of the book were published
in newspaper excerpts, in early March.) The manuscript was edited
behind closed doors; Rees-Jones, Johnston, Carlisle and the
publishers maintained deep confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   The author, speaking by phone on Monday, March 20, from New
York, where he was doing a slew of media interviews, said he was
determined to get his story across unhindered and therefore would
refuse to sell rights to TV or the movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing this in the way of drawing a line under the
accident,'' he said. ``This is what I know, and this is what I'm
prepared to say. I don't want to pass it over to anyone else, I
want to put it behind me. If it became a movie or TV show, there
would always be somebody else's angle on it, and I wouldn't be
happy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _Playboy.com is auctioning a pair of slippers purchased at
Neiman Marcus in 1992 and worn on the actual size 10 feet of  &UR; Hugh &LR; 
 &UR; Hefner &LR; . They are signed ``in silver paint pen'' by Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Alice Waters &LR;  has been named the University of California at
Berkeley Alumna of the Year, in honor of which she has released a
new commemorative recipe for braised duck legs.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _A survey taken by AccuWeather.com found that people are four
times as likely to watch a comedy on TV on rainy days; talk shows
rule on foggy days; drama is tops when the sky is clear.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _Paying due respect to Yom Kippur, organizers of the October 9
Columbus Day parade in New York have agreed that marching bands
won't play when they pass Temple Emanu-el on Fifth Avenue, reports
the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
