<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3927 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CLINTON-INDIA-NYT &LR;      03-21 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS TO BUILD NEW RELATIONSHIP WITH INDIA
</HEADLINE>
   (See also INDIA-KASHMIR) 
(sw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The United States and India opened what they
called an era ``of new beginnings'' on Tuesday in an effort to
rebuild a relationship that President Clinton said had been
neglected for more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   But a series of encounters, including a sharp rebuke of the
president on Tuesday night, showed that the opening chapter was
spiked with surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Against a backdrop of a massacre of about 40 Indian Sikhs in the
Indian held part of Kashmir just before Clinton's official visit,
the Indian prime minister, Atal Behari Vajpayee, and the president
signed what they called a ``vision statement.'' It defined their
common interests while pointing out that they disagreed on India's
possession of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   After talks with Vajpayee, Clinton said that the two countries'
relationship was ``too important to ever fall into disrepair
again.'' Thus, the two countries said the joint statement was a
device to lay the foundation of an American-Indian relationship
without letting precise issues slow the process.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of the day, the tensions inherent in forging an
Indo-American friendship surfaced when India's president, Kircheril
Raman Narayanan, rebuked the president in a toast at a state dinner
on Tuesday night. Standing before Clinton at a long banquet table,
Narayanan scolded Clinton for his description of the Indian
subcontinent ``as the most dangerous place in the world today.''
The president has publicly used that term twice in the past two
months to describe a situation where India and Pakistan, two
neighboring countries, have nuclear weapons and are also at the
edge of a conflict in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   But Narayanan, in a rare display of blunt talk at a black-tie
diplomatic affair, said that this description was ``alarmist.''
``It has been suggested that the Indian subcontinent is the most
dangerous place in the world today and Kashmir is a nuclear flash
point,'' the Indian president said. ``These alarmist descriptions
will only encourage those who want to break the peace and indulge
in terrorism and violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not reply to the chiding, choosing in his toast to
stick to his theme of friendship. The president's day began here
with a formal review of Indian armed forces assembled in the
courtyard of the colonial-era presidential palace, Rashtrapati
Bhavan, and then moved on to a wreath-laying ceremony at the
memorial to Mahatma Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
   The president then drove through roads, swept clear of people to
Hyderbad House, a former princely residence, for his meeting with
Vajpayee, the prime minister. Vajpayee, the 72-year-old
white-haired leader of the Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata
Party, and Clinton had not met before.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Indian leader is not considered an easy
conversationalist, there was some uncertainty among administration
officials about how the talks would proceed. Afterward, an
administration official said that the ``tone was good but it would
be misleading to say that there was a brisk and free flow of
ideas.'' The measured atmospherics in the encounter with the prime
minister combined with the sharp comments by the Indian president
seemed to underline the difficulty of Clinton's undertaking to
improve the Indian-American relationship without having the United
States appear to be a superpower that was lecturing.
</P>
<P>
   From the time India first tested nuclear weapons in May 1998,
Washington has tried to convince the government here that its
maintaining a nuclear deterrent was not helpful to peace in the
region. But India, striving to be more than just a regional power,
sees its nuclear weapons as the right of an emerging major power
that is a neighbor not only to Pakistan but also to China.
</P>
<P>
   At the ceremony marking the signing of the ``vision statement'',
Vaypayee warned that India had limited tolerance for the violence
in Kashmir, which it accuses Pakistan of masterminding. ``We have
the means and the will to eliminate this menace,'' the prime
minister said.
</P>
<P>
   The statement itself included a summary of the differences on
nuclear weapons. It said in part: ``The United States believes
India should forego nuclear weapons. India believes that it needs
to maintain a credible minimum nuclear deterrent in keeping with
its own assessment of its security needs.'' It went on:
``Nonetheless, India and the U.S. are prepared to work together to
prevent the proliferation of nuclear weapons and their means of
delivery. To this end, we will persist with and build upon the
productive bilateral dialogue already under way.''
</P>
<P>
   In elaborating on the statement at the appearance with Clinton,
the Indian prime minister said he had repeated in their private
meeting India's commitment not to conduct further nuclear explosive
tests and not to be the first to use nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In replying, Clinton recognized that India was not close to
signing the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty, a position that
Washington has been urging on the government without success since
the 1998 test. The president said he hoped that the ``democratic
process'' in India would lead to the eventual signing and
ratification of the treaty in India, just he added, ``like I hope
the democratic process will ultimately produce a ratification of
the test ban treaty in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The killings in Kashmir Monday night, which American officials
said appeared designed by Pakistani-backed insurgents to draw
Washington into a mediation of the dispute between India and
Pakistan, presented Clinton with an opportunity to stress his
prepared message of restraint between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made clear before coming here that he was not planning
to mediate the Kashmir dispute _ a roll that the Indians reject but
which the Pakistanis want.
</P>
<P>
   But Indian officials interpreted a statement by Clinton as an
embrace of their position that Pakistan must stop infiltrating
Kashmir with militant fighters before talks can start. Clinton
sounded as though he was saying just this when, in his joint
appearance with Vajpayee, he said that talks between India and
Pakistan could not be expected ``unless there is an absence of
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials quickly tried to clarify Clinton's intent,
saying that because the United States was not a party to any talks
between India and Pakistan, it could not set any preconditions.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior administration official said that the Indians
should take heart from the message of support'' that Clinton
delivered against the violence in Kashmir.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
