<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SOUTHWEST-MUSIC-850-T     03-21 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHWEST-MUSIC-850-TRIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S GOT THE SOUND? BABY MOGULS AND TECHIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANN POWERS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``It's chaos out there right now,'' said Tim
Quirk on Saturday afternoon, briefly retreating from the
barbecue-munching crowd at Fat Tuesday's, one of many patio-style
beer joints here. Quirk wasn't just making the usual observation
about South by Southwest, the music, film and multimedia conference
that concluded Tuesday. He was addressing a particular kind of
chaos: the free-for-all over music on the Internet that enthralled
this year's convention-goers as intensely as it has the industry in
general.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been this giddy since the needle dropped on the
first Clash record,'' said Quirk, a managing editor at Listen.com,
the online music directory that helped sponsor this year's festival
and was host of the Fat Tuesday's bash, where the underground pop
bands Beulah, Polara and Saltine played sparkling sets. ``I
understood how this was going to revolutionize the music
business,'' he added. ``I wanted front-row seats at the revolution,
and they gave me a gun!''
</P>
<P>
   Quirk exemplifies one aspect of Web music's new school: the
devotee drawn to a Web job by high hopes and opportunity. He was a
freelance writer and stay-at-home dad when he learned about
Listen.com through a press release and called to see if any jobs
were available. He had never worked in an office before. Now here
he was, staying at the Four Seasons, a member of an establishment
that seems to be superseding the one he had battled as a member of
a punk band.
</P>
<P>
   The enormous influence of Web music on the music segment of
South by Southwest exposed the ferocious effects of new technology
on the record business. On one level, the festival proceeded as
usual, with sentimental favorites like Steve Earle and Patti Smith
and newcomers like Beachwood Sparks and Fu Manchu garnering buzz
from eager audiences. Shelby Lynne worked her hard country charm at
the Austin Music Hall; Japanese rock fans bopped to Puffy at the
Park Avenue. The hip-hop contenders Dead Prez freestyled at Stubbs,
while the Mekons, those adored indie rock veterans, closed the
festival at Antones.
</P>
<P>
   But the thrill of the new wasn't with the musicians. It belonged
to the techies and entrepreneurs who spoke on packed panels,
sponsored lavish parties and displayed their wares at a trade show
overflowing with free goods. Promoting Internet radio stations,
entertainment guides, online stores and multiservice sites, these
networking demons were the week's real rock stars, riding a wave of
hype and vision.
</P>
<P>
   On panels where they squared off with established executives and
in private conversations that were half sales pitch, half
manifesto, the Web rockers held the festival's spark. Idealists
like Quirk championed the independence that downloadable music
offers artists and fans in allowing them to sidestep the music
industry's protective gates. Industry veterans clued into the
shifting landscape debated how those gates might be adapted so that
the music will still generate profit. Still others, more baby
moguls than music maniacs, had smelled the money in a transforming
arena and sought to position themselves in its flow.
</P>
<P>
   The Web rockers have laid claim to the music's old-fashioned
outlaw spirit. Some are in fact engaged in lawsuits with the
Recording Industry of America, which is trying to rein in
technologies that supposedly promote piracy. The RIA has
specifically accused two major companies, MyMP3.com and
Napster.com, of copyright infringement for advancing the
distribution of music over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the accused companies avoided discussing the
lawsuits, but many of their peers defended them with
countercultural arguments. Napster, a file-swapping community
connected by software designed by two 19-year-old MIT students,
particularly seemed to entrance Web rockers. Napster allows members
access to one another's MP3 collections, theoretically eliminating
the need to purchase CD's altogether.
</P>
<P>
   In the opinion of some, this finally frees music from ``the
Man.'' Detractors reminded defenders that Napster doesn't pay
artist royalties. Web rockers argued that a system of artist
remuneration is evolving. It's hypocritical, they said, to act as
if the current system is the best for artists when low royalty
rates have always been a source of shame. Better to think of how
the changing technology is redefining the ``product'' itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two streams of thought here,'' said Ben Fong-Torres,
a longtime rock journalist who is now the editor of the MyPlay.com
site. ``One is the griping, and that has turned old. The second is
the dot-com world, along with the younger artists. There's
excitement about what it's doing, but some people are running
scared.''
</P>
<P>
   John Parres, a member of the Artists Management Group and
co-founder of Pho, a popular e-mail list connecting
music-technology aficionados, artists and managers, expressed
satisfaction at the nervousness of industry veterans. ``The record
labels have had the upper hand,'' he said. ``Many of the people in
Pho have been on the short end of the stick. We realize the system
is broken.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sexy leather and spiky hair wasn't in evidence at Friday's Pho
gathering, held, as the group's regional conclaves always are, over
bowls of the Vietnamese soup for which it is named. Excitement was
generated by the flow of ideas and the sense that someone in the
room might have the key to the new Napster, the next thing to make
music freer and, of course, more profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Rock 'n' roll careers have always been equal parts hustle and
revolt, tainted by the sins of payola and artist exploitation but
blessed by the serendipity of getting paid to make noise. The most
alluring Internet entrepreneurs project a similar recklessness. It
can be hard to work that pose when you're designing
office-management platforms, but it's the easiest thing in the
world when your service brings the latest Limp Bizkit track to
rabid fans.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Web rockers were eager to point out, the latest tracks by
artists that fans might otherwise never hear. Joe Fleischer, who
recently left his influential ``Wheels and Deals'' column at the
trade publication Hits to become a vice president at MP3.com,
shared what is becoming an axiom in the world of Web music: that
the person served best by all this innovation is the ``middle-class
artist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the North by Northwest festival in Portland, Ore.,
last year,'' he said during an impromptu Web site demonstration,
one of 50 per day he said he had given to interested executives.
``Nobody from the industry had come. But all the bands were there.
And I realized there was this middle class of artists emerging _
bands that had been dropped, bands that were never going to be on
the radio _ and going to the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Trachtenberg, a director of creative content for
Emusic.com, echoed Fleischer's sentiments in explaining what he had
accomplished at South by Southwest. ``I just licensed Daniel
Johnston's catalog, and I had dinner with Mojo Nixon last night,
started working out a deal with him,'' he said. ``I saw the Mooney
Suzuki three times.'' Trachtenberg was as delighted to know these
obscure artists as an old-style music-business type might have been
to hang out with the Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   This focus on the new and the small is smart business that has
the advantage of appearing principled. Web rockers will probably
abdicate some of their openness, not to mention their endlessly
reiterated concern for fans, once their nascent business models
jell. But they're starting with a powerful stance. They're a little
ruthless, very arrogant and full of joy, which is how legendary
record men like Jerry Wexler and Sam Phillips were when they began.
</P>
<P>
   But Wexler had Aretha Franklin, and Phillips had Elvis. South by
Southwest demonstrated that even as technology offers countless new
pop thrills, music itself is in a circling pattern, with plenty to
enjoy but few surprises. Perhaps the Web rockers will really be
stars when they find some new voices to champion. That's when all
this hoopla will really feel like rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
