<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HIRING-PITFALLS-NYT &LR;      03-21 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIRING-PITFALLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYERS LAMENT HIRING IN HASTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ga., Mass., N.J.)   (Eds., spelling Allied Domecq is CQ) 
 (DW) 
 By CHARLES BUTLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Companies that dawdle in hiring promising candidates may lose
them to the competition, but Margie Mosher does not care. She has
learned her lesson, and nobody gets a job at Allied Domecq Quick
Service Restaurants until a thorough background check is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Mosher, working in Randolph, Mass., is the personnel manager at
that division of Allied Domecq, the British holding company for
food retailers like Dunkin' Donuts and Baskin-Robbins. She recalls
that a company manager who urgently needed to fill a position last
year presented her with a ``phenomenal resume.'' On it, the
candidate listed graduate and undergraduate degrees from a noted
school, a professional accreditation helpful for financial work and
the skills required for the Allied Domecq job opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met this individual, and he had all the answers,'' Mosher
said. ``He had the experience and the credentials.'' The company
was ``within minutes'' of hiring him, she added, when she received
a background report from an outside firm that left her in shock.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate had no graduate degree, had been stripped of his
accreditation and even had a criminal record. ``The only thing we
didn't find was a bad driving record,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Domecq may have averted a hiring disaster, but in today's
tight job market, a lot of companies do not show the same sort of
diligence. That can spell trouble, according to executive
recruiters and people at companies that specialize in background
checks.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, especially Internet start-ups desperate to fill
large numbers of openings, openly acknowledge that they lack the
time and resources to verify all the information that job seekers
submit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been sloppy, but it has gotten even sloppier,''
Ed Dunn, a former corporate vice president for human resources at
the Whirlpool Corp. and now a consultant, said of corporate
procedures for checking on job candidates' backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Samer Hamadeh, chief executive of Vault.com, a Web site for job
seekers that provides information on careers and companies, says
that although he requires full background and reference checks on
applicants for senior executive positions, he is less demanding for
lower-level openings. ``What we do is make the offer, but then tell
them it is contingent on a background check,'' Hamadeh said.
</P>
<P>
   Even recruiters of senior-level managers confess that the
frantic competition for talent can blind them to danger signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if a bird flies, you go for it,'' said Peter Crist, vice
chairman of Korn/Ferry International, the global executive
recruiting firm. ``What happens is, in a high-velocity market like
this, it becomes more mistake prone.''
</P>
<P>
   To guard against laxness, Crist has begun checking references
before he calls the applicant about a position; previously, the
process of checking the references would not begin until an
executive became a serious candidate for a job.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced hiring managers know the dangers of letting down
their guard. In a 1998 survey by the Society for Human Resource
Management, 90 percent of human resources professionals said they
had encountered candidates who had falsified the lengths they had
held previous jobs and the salaries they had earned, while 78
percent in the survey said they had come across applicants who had
lied about their college degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Even little lies can derail a job hunter's chances if they are
detected, corporate managers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you lied about something that doesn't really matter, for
example, your degree, why wouldn't you lie about something else?''
Mosher asked.
</P>
<P>
   For employers, the failure to ferret out the fabrications can
create enormous headaches. Recently, James Mulvaney, the director
of research for forensics and litigation at the accounting firm
KPMG LLP, did background checks on employees at a New Jersey car
dealership where millions of dollars was missing. The stolen money
was later traced to a sales manager who, Mulvaney discovered, had
spent six years in Rahway State Prison for robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Mulvaney, a former investigative reporter for Newsday, The Daily
News and The Orange County Register, where he supervised a staff
that won a Pulitzer Prize in 1996 for a series of articles on fraud
by fertility doctors, remembers wanting to ask the dealership's
managers: ``What were you guys thinking? Did you look at his resume
and notice that there were six years missing?''
</P>
<P>
   Companies that conduct pre-employment background checks for
employers say business has increased in recent years as smaller
concerns have parceled out work they used to try to do themselves.
Aided by Web-based search tools, the firms say, they can usually
investigate a candidate's job history, credit rating and criminal
record within 48 hours for costs ranging from $15 to $90.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for example, Powerpay.com, which provides payroll
service for small businesses, began offering clients access through
its Web site to ChoicePoint Inc., one of the country's largest
pre-employment screeners.
</P>
<P>
   Mosher has used Business Directions Inc., of Atlanta, for
background searches on Allied Domecq job applicants. In the case of
the candidate with a bogus degree, a credit check by Business
Directions disclosed a former residence and employer not listed on
his application. That discrepancy prompted Business Directions to
dig deeper, uncovering his criminal record along the way.
</P>
<P>
   A mandatory background-check policy can annoy managers who are
itching to snag a hot prospect before a competing offer arises. But
Mosher urges personnel managers not to be swayed by them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take offense because they think you are questioning their
personal judgment,'' she said. ``And to put things into
perspective, we don't get these types of bad reports all that
often. But when you run into a situation where there is a glitch,
we're glad we found out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If some companies are relaxing the vigilance in the current
economic boom, others are being extra cautious.
</P>
<P>
   OnTarget Inc., a sales training company in Atlanta, requires
that no job offer can be made until a candidate's background check
is completed and at least two references have been called.
</P>
<P>
   To further help keep disreputable applicants at bay, the company
now offers OnTarget employees as many as three cash bonuses if an
applicant they recommend is hired and stays with the company a full
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an employee knows of a good co-worker from a past life and
that worker comes aboard, we're happy to pay a fee to the
employee,'' said Marianne Haskins, the director of human resources.
``Then you have the personal recommendation of someone you know and
trust.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
