<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3936 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AL-AMIN-ALA-TIES22-CO     03-21 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AL-AMIN-ALA-TIES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suspect known as friendly visitor in Ala. town where he was
captured
 &HT;    By Bill Osinski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE HALL, Ala. _ The rural crossroads town where Jamil
Abdullah Al-Amin's run from the law ended Monday is only a few
miles from the scene of perhaps his greatest triumph.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday, it was the good times that most people around here
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Favor, an elderly man who'd just caught himself a snapping
turtle for dinner, said he remembered Al-Amin well; they worked
together in the local civil rights movement in the 1960s when
Al-Amin was known as H. Rap Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a lot of friends around here, because he stayed out
here and worked with us,'' Favor said. ``I was real surprised when
I heard he had done a shooting. Rap Brown was a nice guy, but he
didn't take no fooling.''
</P>
<P>
   Favor and other Alabama friends and acquaintances of Al-Amin
expressed disbelief that he could have been involved in last week's
shooting of two Fulton County sheriff's deputies in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they recalled the dangerous days of the civil rights
movement, when a young Al-Amin came to Lowndes County, Ala., and
was a key figure in the struggle to gain the vote for
disenfranchised black people.
</P>
<P>
   The scene of Al-Amin's capture is about five miles from where
Brown and other leaders of the Lowndes County Christian Movement
for Human Rights in the 1960s set up a tent city where they
conducted an historic registration drive for a county where
virtually no blacks were on the voter rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came down here (after the shooting) simply because he had
friends down here,'' said John Hulett, county probate judge. In
1970, Hulett was elected Lowndes County sheriff, the first black to
hold that office; he largely attributed that victory to the
voter-registration efforts led by Al-Amin and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met him in 1965, when he first came to Lowndes,'' said
Hulett, now 72. ``He was level-headed, a good fund-raiser, and
motivated to get people registered.'' After the voter registration
drives, roads, schools and housing improved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been able to step up because of what we were able
to do together. It cost us some lives, but at the same times, we
were able to make some progress,'' Hulett said.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Al-Amin continued to visit. Hulett saw him
two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really surprised something like this could happen. It got
to me. The idea that he would be involved in this is hard to
believe,'' Hulett said.
</P>
<P>
   White Hall Mayor John Jackson, another comrade of Al-Amin's
during the 1960s, said the Al-Amin he knew was not a violent man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always known him to be peaceful,'' Jackson said. ``Now, I
hadn't seen him in a long time, but he never appeared to be
violent.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin was an auxiliary police officer in White Hall. Jackson,
who issued the credentials, explained that such badges are given to
civilians who would then assist the town's small police force at
events such as parades or football games. The badges do not allow
auxiliary officers to carry guns or to make arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Among the charges in the warrants that the Fulton deputies tried
to serve on Al-Amin was impersonation of a police officer. He is
accused of using his Alabama auxiliary police badge in the incident
that led to the charge.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson knew that Al-Amin, whom he still calls Rap Brown, had
run afoul of the law, including a 1973 conviction for armed robbery
in New York. However, he thought his friend had mellowed after
converting to Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was on the scene Monday night when Al-Amin was arrested
near White Hall's town hall. ``It looked like he had changed his
life in the right direction. It was such a shock, because most
people around here knew him as quiet and smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin maintained his connections to the Lowndes County black
leaders whom he helped gain political office. Mostly, they said, he
stopped by for brief visits while he was going to or coming from
Selma, where he would usually stay overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Outwardly, White Hall has changed little since the old days.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it is still little more than a country crossroads.
Clustered around the main intersection of the town's business
district are a supermarket, a bait and tackle shop, a gift shop and
the Bismillah Cafe. There is a small town hall and a branch library
in a trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks make up about three-fourths of the county's population of
about 13,000 residents, most of whom live below the poverty level.
The 1994 average household income for the county was $12,195, about
$5,500 less than the Alabama average.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the White Hall Supermarket, employee Sharon Barefield
said she had seen Al-Amin several times, but she knew nothing of
his past life as Rap Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know he was in the Panther movement. He used to come
in here and just chit-chat, talk about nothing, then he would
leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin had a connection to the people who ran the Bismillah
Cafe, which has been closed for the past four months. The manager
was Sahid Abdul Salaam, a friend of Al-Amin's. Salaam was the
leader of a small Muslim community in White Hall. He and several
relatives were taken in for questioning following Al-Amin's arrest;
but they were released Tuesday with no charges filed against them.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a man named Sharif Al-Malik moved with his family
into the back of the restaurant. They planned to re-open it.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Al-Malik said he spoke with Al-Amin about two weeks
ago, and they discussed preparing a celebration for area Muslims
who were returning from a pilgrimage to Mecca, Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was talking to me about slaughtering some goats for the
pilgrimage. He was asking me where we could get goats from,''
Al-Malik said.
</P>
<P>
   After the reports of the shooting in Atlanta, Al-Amin's friends
in White Hall were worried for his safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful they didn't kill him,'' Al-Malik said. ``I think
it was a witch hunt. They don't know who shot these police
officers. They put it on him, because they were serving the warrant
on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other nationally known civil rights leaders who
passed through Lowndes County rarely, if ever, returned. Al-Amin
came back in peaceful times, and last week, when he was on the run
from the law.
</P>
<P>
   Amilcar Shabazz, a professor of American Studies at the
University of Alabama, said Al-Amin must have considered White Hall
a safe haven.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think brother Al-Amin was trying to move into a direction
where he felt he could find safety and invisibility, until he could
figure out what his next move would be,'' Shabazz said.
</P>
<P>
   Hiding out in Lowndes County made sense, given Al-Amin's
historical and philosophical connections to the region, said Rose
Gladney, a professor at the University of Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``His philosophy is standing up to unjust authority,'' Gladney
said. Al-Amin may have come back to White Hall as a place to make
his last stand, she said. ``Sometimes, that's the thing you do,
rather than submit.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writers Dana Tofig, Steve
Visser and Ernie Suggs contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
