<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3937 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-TOBACCO-HNS &LR;      03-21 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-TOBACCO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVIDED JUSTICES RULE GOVERNMENT CANNOT REGULATE TOBACCO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A sharply divided Supreme Court on Tuesday ruled
that federal drug officials cannot control the manufacture or sale
of cigarettes, dealing a blow to President Clinton's effort to
regulate the product and handing a victory to the
multibillion-dollar tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   In its 5-4 decision, the court called cigarettes the United
States' most deadly consumer good but said Congress had not given
the U.S. Food and Drug Administration the legal authority to
regulate them.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton expressed disappointment with the court's
decision, which invalidated a host of FDA regulations aimed at
limiting teen-agers' access to cigarettes. He urged federal
lawmakers to take action in light of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are to protect our children from the harms of tobacco,
Congress must now enact provisions of the FDA rule,'' Clinton said
in a statement from New Delhi, India. ``I believe that by working
together across party lines we can protect our children and save
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But history is not on the president's side. Legislation to give
federal regulators authority over tobacco failed as recently as
1998, and a subsequent effort would appear to face a similar fate.
A leading Republican lawmaker rejected Clinton's call for
congressional action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I oppose legislation that would expand the bureaucratic reach
of the very agencies so intent on circumventing the role of
Congress on important matters of public policy,'' said House
Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas. ``Of course, we must continue to
address the problems of youth smoking, and I applaud the efforts of
parents, teachers and others to discourage the illegal use of
tobacco products.''
</P>
<P>
   The high court's ruling spared the largely unregulated tobacco
industry from the specter of FDA officials who would have had the
authority to ban cigarettes or at least limit the amount of
nicotine, a carcinogenic stimulant, permitted in the products.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law now imposes only minor demands on tobacco companies,
such as requiring them to put warning labels on their products and
encouraging retailers not to sell cigarettes to minors. States, by
contrast, have no authority to regulate the manufacture of
cigarettes but generally do prohibit retailers from selling them to
children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, retailers who sell tobacco to a minor face
fines of up to $500 for a first offense and up to $1,000 for
subsequent violations. Children convicted of using or possessing
tobacco may be required to take a tobacco-education course or pay
of fine of between $125 and $250. Teens who do not attend the
required course could have their driver's licenses suspended.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 FDA regulations, the agency's first ever effort to
control tobacco, would have prohibited the sale of cigarettes and
smokeless tobacco to anyone younger than 18, required retailers to
check the identification of would-be tobacco buyers younger than 27
and restricted vending-machine sales of cigarettes and smokeless
tobacco to adult-only locations. Enforcement of the now defunct
rules had been suspended pending the high court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Major cigarette makers Philip Morris and Brown &AMP; Williamson
Tobacco Corp., which challenged the FDA's authority, hailed the
court's ruling and offered to work with the federal government to
keep tobacco away from children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We opposed the FDA rule because regulation of cigarettes as
(drugs) was inappropriate and could have led to prohibition,'' said
Philip Morris, whose cigarette brands include Marlboro.
</P>
<P>
   ``But federal regulation of cigarettes as cigarettes, dealing
with youth smoking while respecting an adult's right to smoke,
makes sense for smokers and manufacturers alike,'' the New
York-based company added. ``We are ready and eager to engage in a
useful, positive discussion on these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris, Brown &AMP; Williamson and other tobacco companies
lobbied hard to defeat the 1998 legislation that would have given
the federal government broad power to regulate tobacco products and
prohibited advertising aimed at youngsters. The legislation, which
was defeated by massive opposition from conservative Senate
Republicans, also would have raised cigarette taxes by $1.10 per
pack.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the past failure, Senate Democrats were quick to pick up
the president's call for tobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The responsibility is now squarely on Congress to grant FDA
the authority it needs to regulate tobacco,'' said Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision has no effect on the Clinton
administration's pending multibillion-dollar lawsuit against the
industry, alleging that the companies defrauded the government by
withholding from until the 1990s what they knew in the 1950s to be
the truth of cigarettes' health hazards. The industry said it will
fight the lawsuit, arguing that the government knew of smoking's
dangers as far back as the early 1960s when lawmakers ordered
warning labels to be placed on cigarette packages.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's decision also has no impact on the $206 billion
the industry agreed to pay 46 states in November 1998 to settle
their lawsuits seeking compensation for the costs of treating
residents with smoking-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400,000 people die annually in the United States from
tobacco-related illnesses, including cancer, respiratory problems
and heart disease. The death toll from tobacco is higher than that
from AIDS, car accidents, alcohol, homicides, illegal drugs,
suicides and fires combined, according to the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also said that nearly 80 percent of the 400,000
smokers who die each year began smoking when they were children.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the court said Congress, rather than giving FDA
tobacco authority, has in fact passed laws to protect the industry.
Citing the 1998 legislative failure, the court added that Congress
has expressly rejected legislation that called for FDA oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress, for better or for worse, has created a distinct
regulatory scheme for tobacco products, squarely rejected proposals
to give the FDA jurisdiction over tobacco,and repeatedly acted to
preclude any agency from exercising significant policymaking
authority in the area,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote in the
court's majority option.
</P>
<P>
   Joining O'Connor's decision were Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy and
Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   In a sharp public sign of disagreement, Justice Stephen G.
Breyer took the extraordinary step of reading portions of his
dissent from the bench. Justices take this symbolic action only
when they have the most profound objection to the majority view.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer assailed his colleagues for carving out a cigarette
exception to the FDA's statutory authority to regulate drugs that
have profound effects on the human body. Breyer said cigarettes
should be subject to FDA regulation because their nicotine
component acts as a stimulant and appetite suppressant in the same
manner as do drugs that the agency oversees.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Breyer's dissent were Justices John Paul Stevens, David
H. Souter and Ruth Bader Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
