<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3938 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-POPE-HOLYLAND-1STLD-W     03-21 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOLYLAND-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE ARRIVES IN ISRAEL AND GETS A TASTE OF MIDEAST POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS throughout to recast, add details, quotes, background;
no pickup; adds art note and photo numbers; subs overline.) 
 (See also POPE-HOLYLAND-BAPTISM, POPE-HOLYLAND-PALS) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT6 and NYT26 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Pope John Paul II opened the first official visit by
a pope to Israel on Tuesday, declaring after he landed in Tel Aviv
that he felt ``deep emotion'' on setting foot ``in the land where
God chose to pitch his tent.'' Immediately on his arrival, he was
also given a taste of the fierce politics that are likely to vein
his long-awaited pilgrimage to the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   The outspoken Israeli president, Ezer Weizman, welcomed the pope
with a blunt, at times defensive speech that instantly bore into
one of the issues dividing the Vatican and the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are arriving this evening in Jerusalem, the capital of the
State of Israel, the heart of the Jewish world, which is also a
holy site for Christianity and Islam,'' Weizman told the frail
79-year-old pope.
</P>
<P>
   The pope listened, hunched under an umbrella beneath a light
drizzle in Tel Aviv, after a military band played ``Jerusalem of
Gold,'' a song that celebrates the return of Jewish holy sites
after the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerusalem is the city of eternity, a city that has been
reunified,'' Weizman said.
</P>
<P>
   Like most states, the Vatican has never recognized Jerusalem as
Israel's capital, and has argued that it should be granted
``internationally recognized'' status as a holy city. A top Vatican
diplomat recently angered Israeli officials by saying East
Jerusalem, the part of the city seized by Israel in the 1967
Arab-Israeli war, was ``illegally occupied.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli viewpoint was driven home even more directly Tuesday
night when the pope's helicopter arrived at a heliport in East
Jerusalem. Jerusalem's mayor, Ehud Olmert, greeted him there,
saying ``Welcome to the eternal capital of Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Abu Ala, speaker of the Palestinian legislature, watched the
helicopter's arrival on television, and said he was stunned and
appalled by Olmert's unscripted presence in East Jerusalem, whose
final status remains to be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   The pope arrived in Israel from Jordan, where Tuesday morning he
held a Mass for 40,000 people in Amman, and prayed on the eastern
bank of the Jordan River at Wadi al Kharrar, one of the sites held
to be the place where Jesus was baptized by John the Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   The import of John Paul's visit to Israel, the first by a pope
officially as a head of state, was underscored by the welcome he
received at Ben Gurion International Airport. He was greeted by
Weizman, Prime Minister Ehud Barak and several Cabinet ministers _
though no ultra-Orthodox government minister attended.
</P>
<P>
   A few rabbis joined a contingent of Muslim clerics and
representatives of all Christian faiths, including Greek Orthodox.
But neither of Israel's two chief rabbis was present. A Foreign
Ministry official said they were attending prayer services for the
eve of Purim, the holiday celebrating Jewish survival.
</P>
<P>
   Three children from Jesus' boyhood town of Nazareth _ one
Jewish, one Muslim and one Christian _ were on hand on the tarmac
as the pope arrived in a Jordanian Airlines jet, which was fitted
with Israeli and Vatican flags after landing. The pope's white
skullcap blew off in the strong wind, and he raised a trembling
hand in the air in a wave before kissing a pot of Israeli soil
offered by the children. When he finished his speech, delivered in
English, he saluted his hosts with the Hebrew word ``shalom,'' or
peace.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul showed no sign of being taken aback by Israeli
officials' public broaching of a sensitive political topic usually
left to diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
   He has long dreamed of leading a Holy Year pilgrimage to the
sites where Jesus lived and died. But in his remarks at the Tel
Aviv airport, he also raised a larger mission in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing Weizman as a ``peacemaker,'' the pope said, ``We all
know how urgent is the need for peace and justice, not for Israel
alone but for the entire region.'' He said the world closely
followed ``the peace process which finds all the peoples of the
region involved in the difficult search for a lasting peace with
justice for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Weizman did not suggest that Israel needed help in resolving
territorial disputes. ``From the very outset, our hand has been
outstretched in peace to our Arab neighbors,'' he told the pope.
</P>
<P>
   The pope hopes to use his visit to Israel to promote interfaith
reconciliation and lend his moral authority to the quest for peace.
But his unique international stature is equally coveted by
Israelis, who want him to reinforce their sovereign rights, and by
Palestinians, who hope his visits to Palestinian leaders and a
Palestinian refugee camp on Wednesday will lend legitimacy to their
cause.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship with Israel, however, is more complex, clouded
by Jewish memories of centuries of anti-Semitism and charges that
the Catholic Church failed to speak out sufficiently against the
Holocaust during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   When Pope Paul VI visited the Holy Land in 1964, he was
gratefully received by Israeli officials of the time, who welcomed
those early, pioneering efforts toward reconciliation between Jews
and Catholics. But few Israelis have forgotten that Pope Paul spent
only 12 hours in their country, and pointedly never referred to it
as Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican and Israel established diplomatic relations in 1994.
The pope, who has on several occasions apologized for some
Catholics' failure to protect Jews during the Holocaust and
repeated that regret this month in a sweeping apology for the
historic sins of his church, wants to use his visit to heal
lingering wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, saying the Vatican's diplomatic recognition of
Israel ``set a seal on efforts to open an era of dialogue,'' the
pope urged continued progress. ``With new-found openness toward one
another, Christians and Jews together must make courageous efforts
to remove all forms of prejudice,'' he said Tuesday night. ``We
must strive always and everywhere to present the true face of the
Jews and Judaism, as likewise of Christians and Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   Weizman, who mentioned the Holocaust twice in his remarks, said
he ``appreciated'' the pope's ``request for forgiveness for deeds
carried out in the past by representatives of the church against
the Jewish people.'' Saying he was mindful of how the church's
teaching has shifted to recognize ``the Jewish people as it defines
itself,'' the Israeli president said it was now ``important for the
men and women in the church to also become familiar with the modern
Israeli reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israel John Paul glimpsed Tuesday night is radically
different from the one he explored in 1963, when he went on a
pilgrimage there as a bishop from Cracow. In a letter he wrote to
fellow Polish bishops describing his trip, he focused on the
religious sites he toured, painstakingly describing shrines and
churches few of his colleagues in Communist Poland could visit
themselves. But the political strains of the time did not entirely
escape his notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's Jerusalem is divided between Jews and Arabs, and the
Jews do not have access to the Wailing Wall,'' he wrote then. ``All
the temple area belongs to the Muslims.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
