<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DOTCOM-MANAGE-ART-NYT     03-21 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOTCOM-MANAGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPLESS IN CYBERSPACE
</HEADLINE>
   ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(Eds: Wenda Harris Millard is the executive vice president of
DoubleClick, a company that tracks consumers' use of the Internet.)
(mcd) 
 By WENDA HARRIS MILLARD with JULIE DUNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was 9 years old, I was the founding editor, publisher,
circulation director and finance director for the Archer Lane
Scoop, in Lynnfield, Mass. It was your classic neighborhood
newsletter. My biggest scoop was interviewing a neighbor on the
one-year anniversary of her son's death by suffocation in a
snowbank. She wouldn't talk to me after that. I learned early on
what it was like to get doors slammed in your face.
</P>
<P>
   I moved to New York the day after I graduated from Trinity
College. I'm a Bostonian, and I hadn't spent much time in the city.
I moved in with a woman who I was working with and her husband.
They had a palatial Park Avenue apartment; I really lucked out. I
kept trying to move out, to places like Hell's Kitchen, but they
wouldn't let me. I stayed there for four months.
</P>
<P>
   I spent 21 years in the magazine publishing business. I'm a
great lover of print. But four years ago I had an epiphany: What
should I do with the rest of my life?
</P>
<P>
   When I first heard of DoubleClick, which places advertising and
tracks consumers' use of the Internet, I thought: ``I'm too old for
that stuff. I'm totally overdressed, and I don't want to work with
geeks.'' The first discussion we had, it was like speaking to
someone in a foreign language. I'm not even sure why we ever even
had a second meeting. I was the 14th employee.
</P>
<P>
   The first week after I came over, I must have got calls from 50
friends in traditional media worried that I had had a nervous
breakdown or was losing my mind. The hysterical thing is that
within a year, all 50 had called back and asked me for a job.
</P>
<P>
   I am a media junkie. This is what I eat for breakfast and snack
on at midnight. There hasn't been a new medium in 50 years, and the
Internet is beyond a medium _ it's a marketplace. So the idea of
being right smack in the middle of inventing a new medium, how much
better could it get?
</P>
<P>
   My children have always been involved in my career. The night I
brought home the DoubleClick offer, that was it. My 6-year-old
said, ``Oh, Mommy, I would be so proud if you got better on the
computer.'' My 8-year-old son said, ``Oh, man, do you know how cool
you'd be at school?''
</P>
<P>
   We have nine computers at home for four people. My kids
constantly amaze me, it's so intuitive for them. My daughter,
Leigh, just got a blueberry I-Mac. My son, Ben, wakes up in the
morning and says, ``I just put my mind into the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people fight about religion. My husband and I fight about
whether the kids are going to be raised Mac or PC. He's a creative,
a TV director, very quiet. We've been married for 16 years, and I
still think he's the nicest person in the whole world. But our
house is definitely full of large personalities.
</P>
<P>
   I took six weeks off with my first child and three weeks off
with my second. I have never not worked. It's always been part of
the deal. I got here first, and I invited them to join me.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, I was the first female publisher to take my
baby to the office. The idea of taking months off just wasn't an
option. It wasn't part of the executive suite as it often is now.
My son was at his first black-tie event when he was 3 weeks old; I
had him in one of those one-piece tuxedo suits.
</P>
<P>
   In my early 40s, I am working as hard as anyone in their early
20's can imagine working, even if they are a workaholic.
</P>
<P>
   I laugh a lot, and I'm an extremely people-oriented person. But
I am deadly serious about business. I don't sleep. I really resent
that sleeping isn't optional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3942 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-2NDTAKE-     03-21 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
MOSCOW: from higher-ups.
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than a few experts view Putin's KGB heritage as a harbinger
of an authoritarian crackdown during his presidency. As prime
minister and later as acting president, he has imported to his
inner circle former KGB officials who are widely criticized by
human rights advocates, including a deputy FSB director widely
attacked for persecuting dissidents under Soviet rule.
</P>
<P>
   A penchant for order and centralized control seems one of the
few clear hallmarks of Putin's governing philosophy. Both as prime
minister and as acting president, he tightened the financial screws
on Russia's independent-minded regions. Some reports indicate that
the government is calling in overdue loans against regional
governments that have not fully toed the Kremlin line.
</P>
<P>
   The English-language newspaper Moscow Times, in this week's
edition, suggested that Putin's months atop the FSB gave him access
to enough compromising material to keep Russia's notoriously
corrupt governors in line for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Putin also has beefed up the KGB presence in the military, where
spies have traditionally had the role of keeping tabs on dissident
factions and tamping down potential military resistance to
government policies.
</P>
<P>
   Former KGB officials also have a limited, though important role
in Kremlin affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at what he's doing, not what he's saying, then
it's clear he's trying to surround himself with members of his KGB
team,'' said Nikolai Petrov, a scholar at the Carnegie Endowment
for International Peace who is convinced that Russia under Putin is
headed for some softened form of dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``And unfortunately, the majority of people in the country are
ready to give him almost all the achievements of democracy to get
stability, and security, and certain guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   Petrov says the issue now is whether Putin's free-market, albeit
hands-on, style will prove better than the free-market-chaotic bent
of Yeltsin's years in power.
</P>
<P>
   Otto Latsis, a leading political commentator with the daily
newspaper Novaya Izvestiya, agreed that the question boils down to
one of approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that's apparent,'' he said, ``is that this is a
person who's competent. We always had problems with that, in the
Brezhnev era and in the Yeltsin era as well. They wanted to do
good, but they didn't know how. With Putin its clear he is
competent. He understands how.''
</P>
<P>
   But does he want to do good?
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Latsis sighed, ``is not apparent at this moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0324 </DOCNO>
