<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3947 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-COURT-TOBACCO-BOS &LR;      03-21 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-TOBACCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA NOT A REGULATOR OF TOBACCO, HIGH COURT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a major defeat for both the Clinton
administration and antismoking groups, the Supreme Court said
Tuesday that the Food and Drug Administration does not have the
right to regulate tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The high court said the agency was caught in an unwinnable
Catch-22: The FDA wants to limit the sale and marketing of tobacco
to reduce smoking, especially among children. But if tobacco is as
deadly and addictive as the government contends, the Supreme Court
said, the FDA would have no choice but to ban tobacco entirely,
making the issue of regulation moot.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 ruling throws out a series of rules the FDA issued in
1996 making it harder for minors to purchase tobacco illegally and
prohibiting tobacco companies from marketing to children and
teenagers. Many states, including Massachusetts, have laws on
selling cigarettes to minors that are not affected by the high
court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the majority, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor
acknowledged that tobacco ``poses perhaps the single most
significant threat to public health in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said the FDA had not proved it had the legal authority
to restrict the sale and marketing of tobacco, ``no matter how
important, conspicuous and controversial the issue, and regardless
of how likely the public is to hold the Executive Branch
politically accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry celebrated the ruling while antismoking
advocates in Congress vowed to pass legislation giving the FDA the
authority to control tobacco, a substance the government says kills
400,000 Americans a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Tuesday's) ruling is a setback,'' said Matthew Myers of the
National Center for Tobacco-Free Kids. ``But we think it's equally
significant in that the Supreme Court has said that tobacco is the
most serious public health hazard that faces our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision was a big win for the tobacco industry, which has
been hit with costly lawsuits and aggressive efforts by the federal
and state governments to control how and where the companies can
sell their product. In a negotiated settlement in 1998, the
industry agreed to pay $246 billion to 46 states, which sued to
recover the public health costs of tobacco-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Joining O'Connor's opinion were Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist and justices Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy, and
Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting were justices Stephen G. Breyer, John Paul Stevens,
David H. Souter, and Ruth Bader Ginsburg. Writing for the four,
Breyer said the 1938 federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act's ``basic
purpose _ the protection of public health _ supports the inclusion
of cigarettes within its scope.''
</P>
<P>
   In arguing the case decided Tuesday, the tobacco industry did
not try to convince the high court that tobacco is healthful.
Instead, the industry's lawyers said the FDA _ charged with
determining whether drugs, food, and medical devices are ``safe and
effective'' _ had no business regulating the sale and marketing of
a substance the agency believes is deadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is going to argue that these products are safe,'' said
Charles Blixt, executive vice president and general counsel for the
R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. But if the FDA were to get involved in
regulating tobacco, he said, it would have to ban it, a politically
and financially explosive idea that neither side of the debate
believes is feasible, given the nation's long history with tobacco
growing and use.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone in Congress intended that an unelected
bureaucrat should make the decision to ban cigarettes,'' Blixt
said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, traveling in India, called on Congress to
pass the Frist-McCain bill, which would impose many of the rules
the FDA issued in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are to protect our children from the harms of tobacco,
Congress must now enact the provisions of the FDA rule,'' Clinton
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate came close to passing a sweeping tobacco control bill
in 1998, which included a provision allowing the FDA explicitly to
control tobacco. But the measure was filibustered by the
Republican-led chamber, and the Senate failed by two votes to stop
the filibuster, so the bill died.
</P>
<P>
   However, since the FDA element of the bill was the least
controversial part of the measure, tobacco-control advocates
believe it could pass as a stand-alone bill. ``The solid groundwork
for legislation has already been laid,'' said Senator Edward M.
Kennedy, a leader on antismoking legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate majority leader Trent Lott of Mississippi said he
does not support giving the FDA authority to regulate tobacco. ``I
don't think they do a very good job with what they're doing,'' he
said Tuesday. House majority leader Dick Armey of Texas, said,
``I'm not anxious to extend the power and authority to the FDA.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco industry officials said they were ready to accept some
restrictions on the sale and marketing of cigarettes. What makes
the industry nervous is the government's insistence that tobacco is
an addictive drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a product that has a known and inherent risk to it,''
Blixt said. But ``I don't agree that cigarettes are drugs,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies are already operating under a series of
restrictions meant to curtail sales to minors, said Mark Berlind,
senior assistant general counsel for Philip Morris. ``We certainly
don't think cigarettes should be marketed to children,'' he said,
adding that the industry has no problem supporting laws meant to
ensure tobacco is not sold to minors.
</P>
<P>
   But smoking foes point out that 3,000 youngsters begin smoking
every day, and a good portion of them will continue to smoke. Young
people are now being tempted with ``bidi'' cigarettes, which look
like marijuana joints and come in vanilla and strawberry flavors,
said John Banzhof, a law professor at George Washington University
and the executive vice president of the Washington-based Action on
Smoking and Health.
</P>
<P>
   The flavored cigarettes ``are training wheels for kid smokers,''
Banzhof said.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts last year adopted the disputed FDA rules into its
consumer protection law. The regulations require persons under 27
to show identification before buying tobacco, demand that vendors
keep tobacco products behind the counter, and limit advertising of
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The rules are facing a court challenge, although the legal
issues are different than the ones considered in Tuesday's ruling,
said Gregory Connolly, director of the Department of Public
Health's tobacco control program. The state won in a lower federal
court, and the matter is now under appeal by the tobacco industry,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other states are taking a close look now'' at incorporating
the rules into their consumer and public health statutes, Connolly
said. ``We believe in states' rights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
