<SLUG> BC-NETTAX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET TAX COMMISSION FAILS TO REACH `SUPERMAJORITY' CONSENSUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ANDREA AHLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The congressional commission on Internet taxation
failed to reach a compromise in its final meeting on Tuesday,
instead sending Congress a report that does not have the support of
a two-thirds ``supermajority'' of the panel.
</P>
<P>
   The report will include a proposal put forth by business members
of the commission to continue the existing moratorium on Internet
taxes for five years.
</P>
<P>
   The Advisory Commission for Electronic Commerce, which met in
Dallas for the past two days, left the door open to continue
discussions towards a consensus proposal and might vote on any
compromises in a teleconference that will be held in the next few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission's chairman, Virginia Gov. Jim Gilmore, said
it is ``very unlikely'' that there will be any new developments by
April 21, when the commission submits its report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can't get a consensus,'' Gilmore said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission _ 19 commissioners including business executives
and federal, state and local government officials _ had convened to
vote on taxation proposals it would submit in its congressional
report. In order for a proposal to be included as a recommendation
to Congress, the proposal needed to be backed by a 13-vote
``supermajority.''
</P>
<P>
   Several commissioners said they were disappointed that they
could not reach a consensus after late-night and early-morning
backroom meetings in Dallas this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is frustrating when you come so close to reach an
impasse,'' said commissioner David Pottruck, president and chief
executive of Charles Schwab &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional report will include two recommendations that
received a supermajority vote. The commissioners agreed that
Congress should pay attention to privacy implications of Internet
taxation, and that Congress should enact legislation to make
Internet access and personal computers widely available to the
public, particularly lower-income families.
</P>
<P>
   The report also will include the proposal put forth by the
industry leaders on the commission, which received a majority vote
on Monday but not two-thirds support. That proposal advocates a
five-year extension of the current moratorium on any new Internet
taxes, and simplifying the current sales tax system with uniform
tax forms and one tax rate per state.
</P>
<P>
   The business executives' proposal was not supported by some of
the state and local government officials on the commission, because
it too clearly defined which Internet sellers must charge sales
taxes and exempted certain Internet goods and services from taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Remote sellers _ such as online or catalog retailers _ must
charge a state sales tax only if they have a physical presence,
such as corporate offices or distribution warehouses, in that
particular state.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Amazon.com does not have to charge its Texas
customers sales tax, because it has no offices or warehouses in
Texas. But Amazon.com does have to charge sales tax to its
Washington customers, because it has several offices in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Compromise talks between the business executive commissioners
and the government commissioners fell apart when the two sides
could not agree on the definition of physical presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, they were not willing to compromise at all,'' said
Commissioner Dean Andal, chairman of the California Board of
Equalization.
</P>
<P>
   Four proposed clarifications on the definition of physical
presence said municipalities should not be able to tax remote
sellers if:
</P>
<P>
   _The seller's customer is located in that state.
</P>
<P>
   _A seller has an agreement with another company that has a
physical presence in that state.
</P>
<P>
   _Repair or warranty services on products sold by the remote
seller cannot be taxed if the seller does not have a physical
presence in that state.
</P>
<P>
   _An agreement between a seller and another business in that
state that allows a consumer to return products to a physical
location in that state.
</P>
<P>
   By preventing municipalities from taxing on those goods and
services, government officials said it would create an unlevel
playing field for traditional bricks-and-mortar retailers. The
proposal is ``loaded full of special favors'' benefiting the
business leaders on the commission, commissioner and Dallas Mayor
Ron Kirk said.
</P>
<P>
   Utah Gov. Michael Leavitt said the provisions in the business
caucus proposal would affect $20 billion to $25 billion in state
and local taxes per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically the (provisions) would say anything on the Internet
won't be taxed, and you'd find Internet registers in every store,''
Leavitt said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he and the other commissioners agreed with the
business proposal on all other points.
</P>
<P>
   Several commissioners criticized the three federal government
representatives on the commission, accusing them of preventing a
possible two-thirds majority-backing on any proposal by abstaining
from voting.
</P>
<P>
   The government officials said the Clinton administration had
hoped the commission would reach a consensus, but is pleased that
the commissioners agree on several key issues such as the
simplification of the tax system and the repeal of the 3 percent
federal excise tax on telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done everything we can to narrow those differences,''
Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart Eizenstat said.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2050EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3950 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-WONDERLAND-ART-2ND     03-21 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WONDERLAND-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: made accessible.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the patients in the series were inspired by the kinds of
people Berg saw at Bellevue _ although he and the psychiatrists,
who have seen several episodes, said there were no breaches of
confidentiality. Patients in the opening show range from a Wall
Street broker who had tried to kill himself to a young man who bit
off his mother's thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said that the story lines are realistic, but that
situations are sometimes unrealistically condensed because of time
strictures.
</P>
<P>
   As would be expected, the plots also involve the personal lives
of the doctors. One of them is fighting for custody of his small
sons; another is struggling with single parenthood. A third is a
womanizer, inside and outside the hospital. ( Berg said that ABC
raised more objections to a brief but steamy sex scene between the
doctor and a girlfriend in the opening episode than to the violent
behavior of the patients.)
</P>
<P>
   Berg, who does not act in the new show, made his feature film
writing and directing debut in 1998 with ``Very Bad Things,'' a
violent comedy with Cameron Diaz and Christian Slater. Casting
``Wonderland'' presented an unusual hazard, Berg said. It seems
that many of the actors who sought roles as patients had seen
Dustin Hoffman in ``Rain Man'' way too many times.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he said, many of those who were selected, often from
the New York stage, knew something about mental illness because,
through friends or family members, they had been touched by it.
</P>
<P>
   The cast includes Martin Donovan (``The Opposite of Sex''),
whose character is based loosely on Berger. Donovan said that
everyone on the show understood the pitfalls of turning it into
something overwrought and not truthful, of turning the patients
into monsters. ``There's no moralizing here,'' he said. ``These
doctors have tremendous compassion for the patients and passion for
the work. Their job is to get at what makes these people tick and
what has gone wrong _ is it chemical, is it treatable, how severe
is it, are they, in fact, ill or faking it?''
</P>
<P>
   Berger, who has worked at Bellevue for 23 years, owns up to
being stirred by the show. ``Every time I see the pilot, I don't
know, it sounds corny, but I get chills when, after the patient has
been so obstructionist and agitated and against treatment, I hear
him say, `I've got this problem; you think you can help me?' I feel
like hugging him.'' Berg, the actors and producers are, not
surprisingly, apprehensive about facing ``E.R.'' One reason for the
unenviable time slot is that ABC's schedule revolves around the
ever-present ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' and only a handful
of hours are available. And, for their part, the producers are
convinced that ``E.R.'' may be getting a little tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it's a difficult time slot for us, but so many people
say they don't watch `E.R.' anymore,'' said Tony Krantz, the chief
executive of Imagine Television, which is producing the show along
with Touchstone Television. ``These people who watched `E.R.' might
be interested in checking the 21st-century version of a medical
show.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg said that nearly every ``Wonderland'' episode presented to
ABC executives has provoked friction with the network. ``We keep
getting calls saying, `it's just too intense, too disturbing, can
you take the edge off?' Every show. `Tone this down. Ease back.
Don't let this patient get too upset.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, Berg has few complaints. ``It's an odd
marriage,'' he said. ``Walt Disney and a show about the insane: we
aren't necessarily the most obvious of bedfellows.''
</P>
<P>
   Braun, at ABC, put it another way: ``We feel we have a unique
program _ very fresh and very risky. Are there concerns? Yes. Are
we proud of it? Yes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
