<HEADLINE>
INDIA, US SIGN MULTIFACETED PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI _ After a half century of misunderstanding and
mistrust, the United States and India Tuesday signed an agreement
hailed as a historic and overdue beginning of a strategic,
economic, and scientific partnership between the world's most
powerful democracy and its most populous one.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was overshadowed, however, by an overnight
massacre of at least 35 members of the minority Sikh religion in
the Indian-controlled part of Kashmir, a Himalayan territory
claimed by both India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The Hindu majority nation of India has long blamed Kashmir's
problems on state-sponsored terrorism by the Muslim state of
Pakistan. Pakistan Tuesday decried the latest attack and denied any
links to it. Shortly after the statement was signed, news emerged
of a grenade and rocket attack Tuesday on five security officials
in Indian-held Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The brutal Monday night massacre of Sikhs _ the first targeting
of a minority community in a decade-long Muslim insurgency that has
claimed as many as 25,000 lives _ focused attention on a tinderbox
region that sparked two of India and Pakistan's three wars. The
simmering conflict escalated last summer with incursions into
Indian-held Kashmir from bases in Pakistan, nearly provoking
another war between the nuclear powers. President Clinton recently
called this ``the most dangerous place in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, however, Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee
assured Clinton ``there is no threat of any war. India is committed
to peaceful means.'' But Vajpayee added that ``we have the means
and the will to eliminate this menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton denounced the killings of civilians in Kashmir, and
called for an end to armed hostilities; mutual respect of a
UN-established boundary that divides Kashmir; a renewal of talks,
and a recognition by both sides that there can be no military
solution to the territorial dispute. He also said he would convey
that message to Pakistan's military leader, Gen. Pervez Musharraf _
the man seen as the architect of Pakistan's apparent escalation of
hostilities in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders' statements came hours after Clinton was treated
to a 21-gun salute, with two dozen turbaned cavalry officers
parading on horseback in the shadow of the sun-baked, sandstone
domes of India's presidential palace. Clinton and his daughter
Chelsea also visited the simple, black marble memorial for Mohandas
K. Gandhi, the father of India's independence movement. The two
walked to the memorial hand-in-hand and barefoot as a sign of
respect, silently laying a wreath of white flowers and scattering
rose petals on the grave.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Indian hosts have given the capital a facelift for his
visit, sandblasting entire neighborhoods of Delhi's notorious
grime, repainting streets, and decorating traffic circles with
planted flowers and garlands of marigolds, the most auspicious
flower for India. Long-dry fountains have been turned on, and
beggars and cows who wander the streets of major Indian cities
freely have been rounded up and tucked out of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton needs to keep coming back now so we can keep enjoying
this new city,'' joked Kabir Sandhu, 32, a chauffeur.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's and Vajpayee's statement established regular bilateral
summits, dialogue on security and non-proliferation, joint
counter-terrorism efforts, commercial, trade and economic dialogue,
and a science and technology forum.
</P>
<P>
   The deal came on the first day of the first visit in 22 years by
a US president, exceeding India's expectations of what could be
accomplished in a short visit by the leader of the world's only
superpower _ a nation that New Delhi feels has unfairly given
India's giant democracy short shrift in favor of Pakistan, its
neighbor who has spent half its history under military rule.
</P>
<P>
   The apprehension between the two sides is a legacy of the Cold
War, an era when India headed the non-aligned nations movement and
refused to take sides with Washington, which began aiding Pakistan
as a buffer against communism. India, socialist in its economic
planning and unable to forge economic ties with Washington without
strategic ones, tilted toward Moscow for trade and aid.
</P>
<P>
   For both sides, this visit is a chance to start again. India
wants recognition as an important player on the world stage, and to
a chance to convey security concerns over Pakistan and China, with
whom India has fought four border wars since 1947. The United
States wants restraint and non-proliferation by the world's two
newest nuclear powers in New Delhi and Islamabad; peaceful
resolution of Kashmir; and deals with the fast-growing economy with
one of the world's largest middle-classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have neglected this relationship for more than two
decades,'' Clinton said. ``It is too important to ever fall into
disrepair again.''
</P>
<P>
   New Delhi hoped the visit would ``signal India's coming of age
in international politics as a player of some strength, and as a
possible ally for the US in securing the stability of Asia if there
are problems with China,'' said Amitabh Mattoo, a political
scientist at Jawaharlal Nehru University in New Delhi. ``That has
been accomplished today. In terms of signals and institutional
messages, it's been a very good trip already.''
</P>
<P>
   US administration officials acknowledged no concrete progress
had been made on getting India to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty. Some Indian analysts said Clinton had tacitly acknowledged
India's need for a minimum credible nuclear deterrent _ a
conclusion Washington officially denies. Vajpayee meanwhile vowed
``a firm committment not to conduct further nuclear tests, not to
engage in a nuclear arms race, and not to be the first to use
nuclear weapons against any country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
