<HEADER>
A3955 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-CLINTON-INDIA-HNS &LR;      03-21 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INDIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN LEADER CHASTISES CLINTON OVER NUCLEAR COMMENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Despite new ethnic slaughter in Kashmir and
India's refusal to make significant concessions in its nuclear
weapons program, India's head of state sternly took President
Clinton to task Tuesday night for repeatedly calling South Asia
``the most dangerous place in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner he hosted in honor of the visiting U.S. leader,
Indian President K.R. Narayanan took the diplomatically unusual
step of drawing a bead on some of his guest's recent comments and
blasting away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been suggested that the Indian subcontinent is the most
dangerous place in the world and that Kashmir is a nuclear flash
point,'' Narayanan said. ``These alarmist descriptions will only
encourage those who want to break the peace and indulge in terror
and violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not reply directly or immediately. A senior
administration official, arguing that Indian leaders resent
official U.S. commentary on their regional disputes, said later:
``It doesn't faze us.''
</P>
<P>
   Narayanan referred to public comments by Clinton made in
Washington in February and earlier this month. On March 9, Clinton,
addressing representatives of the U.S. religious community, spoke
of ethnic and religious conflicts around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most dangerous place in the world today, I think you could
argue, is the Indian subcontinent and the line of control in
Kashmir,'' Clinton said, basically repeating a sentiment he
expressed at the National Prayer Breakfast on Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Narayanan's caustic comments in what was called the
banquet's ``toast,'' Clinton saw his description brutally borne
out. The opening of his state visit was marred by a bloody eruption
in the Kashmir dispute and India's intransigence on nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Clinton, the first U.S. president to visit India in 22
years, hailed ``a day of new beginnings'' in relations between the
world's two most populous democracies, he had to pause to condemn
the massacre of 40 Sikh men Monday night in the Indian-held region
of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The mountainous enclave is claimed by India and Pakistan and has
sparked two rounds of open warfare between the regional powers
since their independence from Britain. The line of control, of
which Clinton spoke, is basically the Indian-Pakistani cease-fire
from a 1971 accord that momentarily tamped down the sectarian
territorial dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The violence must end,'' Clinton said during a joint news
conference with Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee. ``This
should be a time for restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who will visit Pakistan briefly Saturday at the end of
his weeklong trip to South Asia, called for ``renewed lines of
communication'' between the two nations. The two sides have not
held talks on Kashmir in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   India said it ``has the evidence'' that the killings were the
work of two militant Islamic groups, one of which is based in
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee, leader of a Hindu nationalist government, said the
``brutal massacre'' was ``further evidence of the ethnic cleansing
that has been under way for a decade.'' He said it was laughable to
cloak ``ethnic terrorism in the guise of jihad,'' the Islamic
notion of holy war.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan and separatist leaders in Kashmir condemned the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Sheik Abdul Rashid of the All Parties Hurriyat Conference, in a
telephone interview from Kashmir, said the killings were ``a
planned attack to divert the attention'' of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing to gain from such massacres,'' Rashid said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one analyst suggested that the killings possibly point
to Pakistan losing whatever control it may have had over the
Islamic militants in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to say that the (Pakistani intelligence agency) is the
tail that wags the dog,'' said Rear Admiral Uday Bhaskar, deputy
director of the independent Institute for Defense Studies. ``But I
think we've reached a point where the tail has been severed from
the dog and these militant groups are acting of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the assault in Kashmir and India's steadfast
refusal to abandon its nuclear weapons program dominated a
Clinton-Vajpayee news conference following the leaders' meeting at
Hyderabad House.
</P>
<P>
   At the daytime news conference, Vajpayee offered a less direct
criticism of the U.S. view that India and Pakistan could be edging
toward open conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no threat of any war,'' Vajpayee said. ``We do not
think in terms of war, and nobody should think in those terms in
the subcontinent.'' But the prime minister, speaking of what he
views as Pakistani-inspired violence in Kashmir, said: ``We have
the means and the will to eliminate this menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was to speak to the Indian Parliament, where leftists
may seek to disrupt Clinton's speech or walk out. As Clinton and
Vajpayee started their talks, about 2,000 members of left-wing
political parties marched on New Delhi's American Center.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said that Clinton, in
speaking to Indian lawmakers, would praise the nation's spirited
democracy and call for greater trade and development.
</P>
<P>
   The nuclear issue, in the background in subcontinental relations
for years, emerged into the headlines in May 1998. First India and
then Pakistan conducted nuclear weapons tests, explicitly conceding
their membership in an exclusive international club.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee sought to cloak his pro-arms position in the most
soothing language, but the bottom line was unmistakable: India
feels compelled ``to maintain a minimum nuclear deterrent.''
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister said he reaffirmed to Clinton his nation's
commitment not to conduct additional nuclear tests as well as to
eschew an arms race or first use of the weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Although Albright, in a speech in Washington before the trip,
said the United States would not accept the nuclear status quo, the
two nations' widely differing views were enshrined in a ``vision''
statement signed by Clinton and Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
   The document said that although the two nations share the
ultimate goal of nuclear disarmament, ``we have not always agreed
on how to reach this common goal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States believes India should forgo nuclear
weapons,'' the statement said. ``India believes that it needs to
maintain a credible minimum nuclear deterrent in keeping with its
own assessment of its security needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton even took the step of lifting an economic sanction
invoked against India two years following its nuclear test. Clinton
allowed resumption of a U.S.-funded project to help reform India's
financial markets, a program valued at $25 million over four years.
</P>
<P>
   In the news conference, Clinton called for renewal of
Indian-Pakistani contacts, but said: ``You cannot expect a dialogue
to go forward unless there is an absence of violence and a respect
for the line of control.''
</P>
<P>
   After the speech to Parliament, Clinton begins a three-day tour
that combines sightseeing and meetings with a cross section of
Indian society. He was to fly from New Delhi to Agra for his first
look at the Taj Mahal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his daughter, Chelsea, visited the site of the
cremation of Mohandas K. Gandhi, the spiritual leader of modern
India, scattering rose petals over the flower-decked black marble
memorial.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
