<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOLYLAND-BAPTISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE VIEWS SITE JORDAN CLAIMS IS THAT OF JESUS' BAPTISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (With POPE-HOLYLAND) 
(jt) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   se  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WADI AL KHARRAR, Jordan _ Pope John Paul II on Tuesday visited a
desolate wind-swept plain here near the Jordan River, a site where
Jordan claims Jesus was baptized.
</P>
<P>
   Jordanians took the pope's visit here as a coup, giving
something of a seal of approval to their site. ``This is a
confirmation of the baptismal site,'' said Akel Bitalji, the
minister of tourism and antiquities. ``This is the authentic
site.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday the pope, at the behest of Yasser Arafat, is
also making a brief stop at a site that also claims to be the
baptismal site _ in the West Bank, directly across the Jordan
River. Israeli officials are upgrading that site, after long
neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Buffeted by sandy gusts of wind, the pope stood under the arch
of a restored Byzantine church as he conducted the ceremony.
Invoking the scriptural depiction of John the Baptist as ``a voice
crying in the wilderness,'' he said, ``Here at the River Jordan, I
too lift up my heart in prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope's visit here, along with an earlier Mass attended by
nearly 40,000 people at Amman's municipal stadium, provided a shot
in the arm for Jordan's tiny Christian community _ less than 5
percent of the country's population, which is overwhelmingly
Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Jordan people don't even talk about Christianity,''
said Najwa Ghannoum, 27. ``But with the pope here, they talk about
us on television, and that is very good.''
</P>
<P>
   At the stadium, ecstatic followers, many of whom arrived in the
early hours, mobbed the pope's car as it slowly circled the stadium
track and as he waved to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Israeli-controlled site, the Jordanian site was
neglected during years of conflict; it was a mine-filled military
frontier where tanks were positioned. After the signing of the
Israeli-Jordanian peace treaty in 1994 and the redeployment of
Jordanian forces along the border, the area was surveyed by
archaeologists, excavated and partly restored.
</P>
<P>
   Situated at a spring-fed tributary of the Jordan near a hill
venerated in Christian tradition as the site of the prophet's
Elijah's fiery ascent to heaven, Wadi al Kharrar was the site of
several Byzantine churches commemorating the baptism.
</P>
<P>
   The partly restored remains of two churches and a monastery, as
well as a mosaic floor and baptismal pools from the Roman period,
are visible at the site today.
</P>
<P>
   The discoveries of pottery shards, coins and oil lamps from the
first century, along with subsequent travelers' accounts of
churches and baptismal shrines, all indicate that it was the
trans-Jordanian Bethany in the wilderness where John the Baptist
lived, Dr. Muhammad Waheeb, the archaeologist in charge of the
project, said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
