<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN SACHS REPORTS SURGE IN REVENUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs Group, the big investment banking firm, reported
Tuesday that a surge in revenue from trading stocks, bonds, oil and
other commodities pushed its first-quarter net income to $887
million, or $1.76 a diluted share, easily surpassing analysts'
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings, for the three months through Feb. 25, were 67
percent higher than the $532 million Goldman reported for the
period of the previous year, when the firm was still a private
partnership.
</P>
<P>
   On average, analysts had been expecting Goldman to earn $1.48 a
share. Investors bid up the firm's shares to $118.25, a gain of
$4.8125, in trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when Goldman executives were marketing shares in the
firm to investors, they insisted that the firm would become less
dependent on unpredictable trading revenue. But Goldman, which went
public in May, derived just as much of its revenue _ about 45
percent _ from trading and principal investments last quarter as it
did a year before.
</P>
<P>
   Net revenue, revenue after interest expense, from trading and
principal investments jumped 54 percent, to $2.1 billion in the
quarter. Revenue from investment banking, one of the less volatile
businesses that Goldman hopes will account for a bigger share of
its revenue, rose 37 percent, to $1.24 billion, but as a share of
total revenue, it declined slightly. All told, revenue rose 50
percent from a year before, to $4.49 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth consecutive quarter, Goldman reported a return on
equity of more than 30 percent. That is significantly higher than
the 20 percent return the firm told investors it would shoot for,
and David Viniar, Goldman's chief financial officer, cautioned them
against getting accustomed to such stellar returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers were very good across all the businesses, but the
real kicker came from trading,'' said Joan Solotar, an analyst at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette who has been recommending Goldman's
stock. ``What people are concerned about is the sustainability of
those revenues. It would be naive to say they are not volatile.''
</P>
<P>
   Viniar said the firm is ``not going to shrink trading.''
Instead, it plans to build its investment banking and money
management operations around the world so that they grow faster
than the trading operations. ``That is still our plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The firm is financing that growth with the capital it raised
through its $3.6 billion initial stock offering. Many of Goldman's
current employees and former partners received shares of stock that
they could not sell for a year.
</P>
<P>
   In two months, about 50 million shares owned by those people and
two big institutional investors will be available for sale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
