<SLUG> BC-USAIRWAYS-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTICIPATING WALKOUT BY FLIGHT ATTENDANTS, US AIRWAYS MAY SHUT
DOWN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Mass., Pa., Fla., Ill.)   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 10,000 unionized flight attendants at US Airways are
threatening an unusual walkout this Saturday, saying they will
disrupt flights on 49 of the airline's busiest routes.
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants want to maximize pressure on the company
with a strategy that they have dubbed CHAOS _ Create Havoc Around
Our System.
</P>
<P>
   In response, US Airways, the nation's sixth-largest airline,
plans to take an unusual step of its own, saying that unless a
contract is reached by Saturday, it will suspend all operations,
rather than let the flight attendants whipsaw the company and its
customers.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the airline said, ``CHAOS by any name is CHAOS,
and US Airways will not operate under the threat of constant
disruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Any decision by US Air to shut down operations, industry experts
said, would be the first time that any airline closed itself down
in the face of a job action.
</P>
<P>
   Suspending operations would inconvenience the 150,000 passengers
US Air flies each day and would create the greatest disruption in
the eastern third of the nation, where the airline controls 36
percent of the regional market. Such a shutdown would affect
flights ranging from US Air's LaGuardia shuttle to Boston and
Washington as well as the company's routes to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In another unusual twist, the company has promised to continue
paying its 30,000 workers who are not flight attendants for as long
as is feasible during a shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   The union is barred from taking any job action until a mandatory
30-day cooling off period ends at 12:01 a.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The strike threat is already hurting the airline, with travel
agents reporting that they are steering consumers to other airlines
and that many US Airways passengers have switched their
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who are completely canceling their trips,''
said Helene Singer, owner of Singer Travel in Reading, Pa. ``We're
advising people that US Air will not be flying, and people are
rebooking on other airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   After seeking a refund on her US Air flight scheduled for Friday
night, Rita Gance, a nurse from Reading, Pa., reluctantly canceled
a trip to visit her mother in West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really disappointed,'' she said. ``I looked at tickets at
other airlines, but the prices were ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Wolf, the company's chairman, and Rakesh Gangwal, its
chief executive, have joined top union officials in Washington this
week for intense negotiations, helped by the National Mediation
Board.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side was willing to predict the likelihood of a strike.
But union officials said flight attendants, borrowing a page from
the partial subway and air strikes often carried out by European
transportation unions, were ready to disrupt the 49 routes by
picketing or not showing up for work.
</P>
<P>
   The union has listed 49 routes it says it will disrupt, saying
it will not target every flight on those routes, but would instead
keep the company guessing about which flights would be affected.
Among the routes listed are are New York/LaGuardia-Orlando, New
York/LaGuardia-Tampa, Boston-Orlando, Pittsburgh-Chicago/O'Hare and
Philadelphia-San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Nagin, the airline's executive vice president and
general counsel, said the company felt compelled to shut its
operations because it was worried that the union action would
strand or delay thousands of passengers and that customers would
lose hard-earned confidence in the airline. ``We are not going to
subject our customers to the uncertainty of chaos,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nagin said the 49 designated routes accounted for 21 percent of
the airline's 2,000 daily flights, but would affect passengers on
many other flights because of the airline's hub-and-spoke system.
The union has indicated that it would expand its action beyond the
49 routes if the dispute dragged on.
</P>
<P>
   The company faults the Association of Flight Attendants for
rejecting a contract formula similar to those accepted by the
airline's pilots, mechanics and other main unions.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to reduce what industry analysts say are the
highest costs per seat mile among major airlines, US Airways is
demanding that the flight attendants accept a formula that would
link the attendants' pay to the average of their counterparts at
the nation's four largest airlines plus 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the flight attendants, whose contract expired in 1996,
assert that the airline's version of a parity formula would cut
their pay and fringe benefits by 5 percent. Union officials say the
other unions had a chance to help define their parity formula,
while the flight attendants have not been given that opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are pretty angry at the company,'' said Cynthia Kain, a
union spokeswoman. ``They feel these are good economic times and
they're being left behind.
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants have not had a raise since 1996 and their
annual pay ranges from $17,145 to $36,918.
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants are in a tight spot because many workers
in US Air's other unions are questioning why the attendants would
refuse to accept the formula they accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the employee groups represented by the other unions at the
company have entered into an agreement based on this concept, and
we think it's a fair solution and an important factor in enabling
US Airways to be competitive in a very competitive industry,''
Nagin said.
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants' CHAOS strategy has been carried out once
before, when sporadic job actions forced the cancellation of a half
dozen Alaska Airline flights in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1999, a pilots' sickout by pilots created havoc for
American Airlines. At the peak of the 10-day sickout, one fourth of
the airline's 9,200 pilots called in sick, forcing the company to
cancel more than half of its 2,250 daily flights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
