<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECON-REPORT-NYT &LR;      03-21 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TRADE DEFICIT JUMPS TO RECORD $28 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (mcd) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Swollen by a huge bill for foreign oil and a
voracious spending spree by prosperous American consumers, the
nation's trade deficit jumped to a record $28 billion in January,
the Commerce Department reported Tuesday. Exports sagged, breaking
a streak of seven consecutive advances.
</P>
<P>
   The latest deficit, $3.4 billion above the December level and 25
percent larger than the 1999 monthly average, suggested that the
booming American economy is still overwhelming the forces that
would narrow this imbalance, mainly a rebound in the economic
performance of other nations that buy American goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. economy continues to grow more quickly than its
trading partners _ and oil prices have gone up a lot,'' said
Catherine L. Mann, senior fellow at the Institute for International
Economics in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the Federal Reserve announced its fifth interest-rate
increase since June in an effort to prevent overly rapid growth,
which ran at a 5.9 percent annual pace in the final three months of
the year, from driving up inflation.
</P>
<P>
   William C. Dudley, a senior economist at Goldman Sachs, said he
had been prepared to raise his gross domestic product estimate for
this quarter but decided after digesting Tuesday's figures to stick
with a still rapid rate of 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The widening in the January gap between what the United States
buys from abroad and what it sells there occurred on both sides of
the equation. Imports jumped $1.9 billion, to a record $112.1
billion, while exports fell $1.5 billion after expanding every
month since May.
</P>
<P>
   Economists expressed no alarm about the results, which have
repeatedly been weak for January in recent years, suggesting more
than the usual imprecision in the way the Commerce Department
adjusts the data for recurring seasonal swings. But they did
express concern about the decline in exports, which if sustained
could cast doubt on the strength of economic recovery from the
Asian financial crisis of 1997-1998. Japan, for example, slipped
back into a recession in the October-December 1999 quarter and
continues to show mixed signals about recovering in the current
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The American deficit with Japan did shrink in January, to $5.6
billion from $7 billion, but the deficit with China climbed to $6
billion from $5.6 billion. Figures on trade with individual
countries are not adjusted for seasonal variation.
</P>
<P>
   With China back as the No. 1 source of the American deficit _
perhaps now on a sustained basis _ it may be a bit harder for the
Clinton administration to persuade Congress to grant it normal
trade relations on a permanent basis as part of a deal under which
the United States would support China's admission to the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Falling exports and rising imports contributed about equally to
the widening gap with China.
</P>
<P>
   The deficit with Asia's newly industrialized economies _ Hong
Kong, South Korea, Singapore and Taiwan, widened to $2.5 billion in
January from $1.8 billion in December, while it narrowed with
Western Europe to $3.6 billion from $3.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The trade gap with Canada, the biggest U.S. trading partner,
jumped to a record $4.3 billion from $3.4 billion, and the deficit
with Mexico, the other member of the North American Free Trade
Agreement, doubled to $1.8 billion, the report showed.
</P>
<P>
   As for oil, the import bill leaped to a record $7.9 billion,
more than double the $3.5 billion of January 1999, when prices had
fallen so sharply that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries collaborated with non-OPEC producers to curtail
production to raise prices.
</P>
<P>
   Both the volume and price of oil imports rose for the month,
with the per-barrel price put at $23.18, the highest since the eve
of the Persian Gulf War in December 1990, when it hit $25.75. The
December 1999 price was $22.67.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has been lobbying intensely for a production
increase by OPEC, which is to meet next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Besides importing $919 million more oil, the United States
raised its purchases of foreign cars by $677 million and its
purchases of computers, telecommunications gear and other capital
goods by $207 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Department, on revision, narrowed the overall American trade
deficit for December by $900 million, to $24.6 billion from the
$25.5 billion originally reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
