<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3963 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-SUV-SAFETY-BOS &LR;      03-21 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUV-SAFETY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUV MAKERS WORKING TO MAKE THEM SAFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alarmed by the damage sport-utility vehicles do to other cars in
accidents, auto makers are redesigning the heavy, high-riding
vehicles to make them less dangerous to other motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers say they are working on modifications that will
make SUVs lighter and lower so that accidents with ordinary
passenger cars damage the impact-absorbing frames of smaller
vehicles rather than the fragile cabins, where passengers are more
likely to be hurt. Some manufacturers are redesigning stiff steel
beams to crumple more easily so that the heavier, truck-like
vehicles absorb more of the blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years people have been buying these big, hulking SUVs
partly because they're going to win in a crash,'' said David Cole,
director of the University of Michigan's Office for the Study of
Automotive Transportation. ``But with so many of these things on
the road, people are starting to be concerned about what happens to
the other guy.''
</P>
<P>
   By far the most popular class of automobile, SUVs now account
for nearly half of all car sales in the United States. And as
off-roading luxury cars, they generate large profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to mess with a good thing, automakers have railed
for years against accusations that SUVs cause more injuries than
other cars. But pressure has mounted as studies show they do. A
federal study published last year estimated SUVs caused nearly
1,000 unnecessary deaths a year in crashes with other vehicles,
largely because of design problems.
</P>
<P>
   The movement by all major manufacturers to reduce SUVs'
destructive potential on the road comes as regulatory agencies
including the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration as
well as Congress threatened to impose regulations on the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of rumbling in Washington right now, and every
one of the manufacturers is going to be as proactive as they can to
avoid having somebody else set rules for them,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, which makes Chevrolet, Cadillac, and Oldsmobile,
already has lowered the clearance of its Chevy Suburban by two
inches and lightened it by 250 pounds, starting with 1998 models.
Those changes were motivated both by safety concerns and customer
complaints about gas mileage and difficulty getting in and out of
such tall vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, automakers say they want to preserve the look and feel of
a truck, which is a main reason many customers buy sport-utility
vehicles. So they are working on changes that don't affect ground
clearance. One option industry sources say is likely to be common
is a suspension that automatically raises the vehicle for rough,
off-road travel and lowers it again for highway driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to design a vehicle that acts like a truck so you can
take it off the road,'' said Terry Rhadigan, a GM spokesman. ``At
the same time, you want to have some of the characteristics of a
car for regular driving, not only for impact compatibility but also
for fuel economy and handling.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the changes won't start showing up until the 2002
models, automakers say. GM plans to make its 2002 Oldsmobile
Bravada, GMC Envoy, and Chevrolet Blazer with steel rails up to two
inches lower inside their underbodies than in current versions.
Ford Motor plans to do the same for its Explorer, Expedition, and
Lincoln Navigator over the next two years, and DaimlerChrysler is
making several changes to the front end of its Durango.
</P>
<P>
   Similar changes are being contemplated for SUVs made by foreign
automakers, including Toyota, Mitsubishi, and Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   Some smaller SUVs, such as Jeep Wrangler and Jeep Cherokee, are
not likely to change since they are considered less dangerous to
other vehicles, industry insiders said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
