<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RAPBROWN-SHOOTING-ART     03-21 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPBROWN-SHOOTING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-TIME CIVIL RIGHTS LEADER SOUGHT HELP FROM THOSE HE ONCE HELPED
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT1, 2, 12 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the law came for him again, 33 years after he
first went underground, the man who was once called H. Rap Brown
had returned to Lowndes County in Alabama, where his life and those
of so many others began to change in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Once, he was one of scores of youthful volunteers who worked
there registering voters, building the foundation of the civil
rights movement with names as diverse as Stokely Carmichael, Huey
Newton, John Lewis, Julian Bond, Bob Mants. They scattered in a
whirlwind of philosophies and fates, some distinguished, some
disgraced. Brown, as the chairman of the Student Nonviolent
Coordinating Committee, became one of the most provocative of black
radicals, associating with leaders of the Black Panther party and
eventually landing in prison on armed robbery charges in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But by Monday night, Brown, 56, long since paroled and now known
as Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, was back in Lowndes for a very different
reason. He had fled there from his home in Atlanta and was huddling
in an isolated rural shed, accused of firing a high-powered assault
rifle on Thursday night at two Atlanta sheriff's deputies, one of
whom died from blood loss. When he fired on U.S. marshals who were
pursuing him near the small town of White Hall, they released
police dogs into the field, and he was on the move again.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, at about 10:30 p.m. Monday, John Williams, a
250-pound Lowndes County Sheriff's deputy known as ``Big John,''
saw him cross a railroad track about a quarter mile from the shed.
He was walking slowly, trying to look like an ordinary citizen, but
Williams recognized him, brought him down to the ground and
shackled him. H. Rap Brown was in custody once again.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoon, after standing before a federal magistrate
in Montgomery to be turned over to Georgia authorities, he looked
at a reporter in the courtroom and uttered a familiar sentiment:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a government conspiracy,'' he said as he was led away.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, J.L. Chestnut, told reporters that Al-Amin denied
shooting anyone and would fight extradition to Georgia. (Gov. Don
Siegelman's office said he would sign the extradition papers as
soon as he received them from Georgia on Wednesday morning.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been fighting the system since he was 16 years old, and
the system has been trying to kill him,'' said Chestnut, one of the
first black lawyers in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes after the court hearing, the FBI announced that it
had found near the railroad tracks a .223 Ruger high-powered rifle
matching the description of the one used to kill Fulton County
Sheriff's deputy Ricky Kinchen and wound Deputy Aldranon English.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of law-enforcement officers and well-wishers attended
Kinchen's funeral on Tuesday at the Jackson Memorial Baptist Church
in northwest Atlanta. In a 2-hour service punctuated by emotional
renditions of gospel songs, Kinchen _ who, along with English, was
black _ was eulogized as a model deputy before he was killed at the
age of 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what the assignment, Ricky was always dedicated to
the mission,'' said Maj. Michael Cooke, Kinchen's supervisor. ``He
was as tough as nails when he needed to be and never shied away
from a field confrontation. He was certainly the type of deputy
that you would want to cover your back if you got into a tight
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances of Al-Amin's return to Lowndes County came as
a sorrowful shock to many of the people who worked beside him
registering voters 35 years ago. Some could not believe that the
man who spent the last 25 years as a non-violent Muslim cleric in
the West End of Atlanta would explode in a seemingly unprovoked
blaze of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so hard to get people to register back then, but he was
good at it, very persuasive,'' said John Jackson, the mayor of
White Hall, who has known Al-Amin since the 1960s. ``And lately
when I've talked to him, he always seemed calm, never violent. It's
just hard to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   But others remembered his impatience with the slow process of
civil disobedience and peaceful change, which eventually led him
away from the mainstream civil rights movement and into the world
of fury and fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this frustration, this growing sense of
discontent,'' said Rep. John Lewis, once a leader of the Student
Nonviolent Coordinating Committee and now a Democratic House member
from Atlanta. ``So many young people come down to Lowndes with the
idea that they could change people in a day or a week, that they
could liberate the natives in one summer. They had a different
mindset about the tempo of change. I don't know _ this is just one
of the saddest tales I've witnessed in the history of the
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The SNCC volunteer students were drawn to the impoverished
county of Lowndes because more than 85 percent of its population
was black, yet there was not one black registered voter. Most of
the blacks were sharecroppers, and registering usually meant that
the white landowner evicted them from their farms, sending many to
live in makeshift tent cities, one of which used to exist a few
blocks from where Al-Amin was captured. The students knocked on
doors and tried to persuade wary residents to take back their
county.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It was slow work, and it took courage for those people to
register,'' said John Hulett, an organizer who worked with Al-Amin
and is now a probate judge in Lowndes. ``Those were the days of
poll taxes and literacy tests, and people would just turn up shot
to death.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-60s, the political party that the students willed
into being _ known as the Lowndes County Freedom Party _ chose for
its symbol a black panther, a more aggressive representation than
the elephant used by the Republicans or the rooster used by the
all-white state Democratic party. A few years later, when Newton
and others left Lowndes for California, they decided to use the
same symbol for their party, which was far more militant than the
Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin converted to Islam in 1971 while imprisoned in New York
for an armed robbery tha ended his years underground. He moved to
Atlanta five years later when he was paroled. Islam does not have
ordained clergy or divinity schools, so when he formed his own
mosque in the West End of Atlanta, the congregation named him imam,
or prayer leader. He later became nationally prominent in promoting
the growth of Islam in cities around the country, and at one point
headed Atlanta's Council of Imams.
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting on Thursday, investigators were at first
unaware of his old political connection to Lowndes County, instead
tracing him back to White Hall through an automobile registration.
Bill Imfeld, the FBI's special agent in charge of the lower half of
Alabama, said agents found Al-Amin had a Toyota 4Runner registered
in White Hall, and soon learned of his old ties. They spent most of
the weekend knocking on doors in the town of 1,800 people and
looking for his car, turning up little until three federal marshals
were fired upon Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   There remain several unanswered questions. English has insisted
to investigators that he fired on Al-Amin during the Atlanta
shooting, hitting him in the middle of his body. The police found a
blood trail leading from the site to a nearby vacant house. But
paramedics who examined Al-Amin on Tuesday said he had no injuries.
Al-Amin was wearing a bullet-proof vest when he was captured, but
investigators said it was an old model, and were surprised that it
might have deflected a direct shot.
</P>
<P>
   And beyond the overarching question of why Al-Amin may have
exploded after 25 years, there is the persistent question of why he
returned to Lowndes, where he would inevitably have been traced.
The sheriff's department said he had apparently been staying in the
home of a friend, Sahib Abdul Salaam, and Sheriff Willie Vaughner
speculated that he believed he could hide in a rural county with
little police presence.
</P>
<P>
   But to Wayne Flynt, a prominent history professor at Auburn
University and an expert on the early civil rights movement,
Al-Amin hoped to receive help from the same people he had once
helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people there haven't followed his career,'' Flynt said.
``But they're suspicious of the police, and they knew Rap Brown as
one of their own. All they knew was, at a critical time, when
people were being killed and they were terrified, Rap Brown came
there and befriended them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-PATIENT-RIGHTS-NYT &LR;      03-21 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATIENT-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN OFFERS COMPROMISE TO SOLVE DEADLOCK ON PATIENTS' RIGHTS
LEGISLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the House and the Senate deadlocked on
legislation to define patients' rights, an influential congressman
proposed a compromise Tuesday on one of the biggest issues in
dispute: How many Americans should be protected by new federal
standards?
</P>
<P>
   The proposal came from Rep. Charlie Norwood, co-author of the
bill passed by the House last October.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood, a Georgia Republican widely viewed as a champion of
patients' rights, said he still believed that all Americans with
health insurance should have the protections of federal law to
guarantee access to medical specialists, emergency care and other
services.
</P>
<P>
   In a major concession to the Senate, Norwood said Tuesday that
he could accept the Senate's position setting federal standards for
a much smaller group of people, provided that Congress also
clarified the states' authority to regulate insurance for everyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``This arrangement would ensure that all Americans have access
to patient protections through either federal or state law,''
Norwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood said the House bill would protect 169 million people
with private health insurance. By contrast, he said, many of the
basic consumer protections in the Senate bill would apply only to
56 million people in group health plans regulated by the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans said they had limited the scope of their bill
because they did not want to usurp the states' authority to
regulate insurance. If that is true, Norwood said, the Republicans
should have no objections to his proposal to clarify the states'
authority to protect patients. In fact, he said, when states have
tried to set standards for health insurance and managed health
care, they have often been challenged in court by insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood's proposal puts pressure on Senate Republicans to
justify the limited scope of the bill passed by the Senate last
July. Under that bill, as under Norwood's proposed compromise, most
people in health maintenance organizations would have to look to
the states, not to the federal government, for protection.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate negotiators have been meeting for about three
weeks and have reached agreement on a few issues.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Osterberg, a spokeswoman for Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma,
the assistant Republican leader, said: ``Senator Nickles will not
have a comment on the Norwood proposal. He's not going to negotiate
in the press. The conferees are making progress toward a strong
patient's bill of rights, and they will continue to forge ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Timothy S. Jost, an expert on health law at Ohio State
University, said he doubted that many people would want the
solution Norwood proposed. But Jost said: ``It forces the Senate
conferees to confront honestly what they are proposing. It may be
useful in driving the Senate toward adopting something closer to
the House position, which calls for comprehensive regulation of
employee health benefit plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard I. Smith, vice president of the American Association of
Health Plans, scorned Norwood's proposal, saying it could expose
HMO's to ``unrestricted liability'' in lawsuits filed by patients.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John D. Dingell of Michigan, the main Democratic sponsor of
the House bill, said: ``Charlie Norwood is simply asking if the
Senate really knows what it is doing. I have the same question.''
</P>
<P>
   James P. Manley, a spokesman for Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., said Norwood's proposal ``helps expose the hypocrisy of
the Senate Republican position.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Republicans really supported states' rights, Manley said,
they would make it easier for employer-sponsored health plans to be
sued in state court under state law, as many Democrats want. A 1974
federal law, the Employee Retirement Income Security Act, has made
it difficult for patients to win such lawsuits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
