<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE WOULD NOT PUSH FOR A NEW INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As part of an administration that has been under
constant investigation, Democratic presidential contender Al Gore
said Tuesday that he would not push for a new independent counsel
law, arguing ``I don't sense any great public demand for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, whom Republicans contended should have been
the target of a special prosecutor's probe for his fund-raising
activities, made it clear that he did not regret the expiration of
the law that triggered the long-running Whitewater investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress already decided to do away with it,'' he said. ``I
think Congress spoke loudly and clearly in a bipartisan voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also touched on a range of issues likely to come up in the
campaign against Republican George W. Bush and cited liberal Texas
columnist Molly Ivins to back up his suggestion that the governor
lacks the experience to be president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also stated his support for a Clinton administration
proposal to phase out the gasoline additive MTBE, which is
manufactured in the Houston area.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law, which was signed by Clinton, has
become a sore point among Democrats who contend that it has been
used to conduct open-ended witch hunts and for Republicans who
allege it has been selectively and politically applied to
administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Congress declined to reauthorize the law that was the
basis for the appointment of a series of controversial special
prosecutors charged with probing Clinton administration activities.
</P>
<P>
   The most wide-ranging and most criticized probe was Kenneth
Starr's investigation of a series of alleged wrongdoings including
the Clintons' involvement in an Arkansas development deal called
Whitewater and the president's affair with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Starr's successor, Robert Ray, issued the first of
several reports on the matters under investigation. Ray concluded
that no deliberate wrongdoing had occurred regarding the
administration's use of FBI files on several prominent Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore dodged an independent counsel review after Attorney General
Janet Reno decided that the vice president's fund-raising
activities during the 1996 presidential election did not warrant
additional investigation. Reno's decision sparked an uproar among
congressional Republicans, particularly after it was revealed that
a number of high-ranking officials, including FBI director Louis
Freeh, had lobbied for a special prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   But many Republicans have been reluctant to push for the
reauthorization of an independent counsel law, which they believe
was also used unfairly to harass GOP presidents.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Democratic and Republican lawmakers also say they
would like to devise a way of probing administrative wrongdoing
that is more narrowly focused and less expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would be willing to consider other options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an open mind on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also said he wasn't bothered by criticism leveled at him by
Republicans that, even as he calls for campaign-finance reform, he
continues to raise money, including the unregulated ``soft money,''
which the vice president says he wants to eliminate. The vice
president is scheduled to attend Democratic National Committee
fund-raisers Friday in Houston, where the party is expected to
raise soft money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you have to unilaterally disarm in order to
advocate reform,'' he said during the interview conducted after a
fund-raiser on the Upper East Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he will continue to inject the issue of whether Bush
has the experience to be in the White House into the presidential
contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've raised the question, and I think it is invited by the
economic plan he has put forward,'' Gore said in reference to
Bush's large tax cut proposal, which the vice president claims will
drain the projected federal surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president did not directly address whether Bush's stint
as governor was adequate training for the White House. But to drive
home his point he paraphrased others, including Austin-based
columnist Ivins, who has just written a humorous and critical book
about Bush titled ``Shrub.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As for his office, you know I think five years as governor is
worth a good deal,'' he said. ``Now Molly Ivins says the office of
governor in Texas is the fifth most powerful statewide position.
And the Republican author of a proposed amendment to the Texas
constitution says that among all 50 states, it has by far the
weakest and least consequential governor's office. But it is not
for me to pass judgment on the nature of his experience and how it
bears on the qualifications for the office he now seeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore added, ``but I think that when he puts forth economic
proposals like the one he has, it is bound to focus people's
attention on what in the world is behind that and does he have the
experience to be president. Let's take a look.''
</P>
<P>
   One factor Gore said that shouldn't be considered in the
presidential race are high school and college grades and test
scores. Last weekend The Washington Post revealed that Gore was a
classic underachiever who scored far better than Bush on the SATs
but whose grades at St. Alban's prep school and Harvard were uneven
and rarely stellar.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, annoyed at the unauthorized release of his college and
high school transcripts, said he did not think they were relevant
to the presidential contest. ``I sure don't,'' he said. Referring
to the transcripts, he repeated several times, ``I refused to
release them.''
</P>
<P>
   On a policy matter, the vice president also said he supported
the phasing out of MTBE, a move that could have a substantial
economic impact in Houston, which is the center of production for
the fuel additive.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Environmental Protection Agency Commissioner Carol
Browner said she would ask Congress to change the Clean Air Act of
1990 to urge the substitution of corn-based ethanol instead for
MTBE, or methyl tertiary butyl ether. Environmental officials said
that while MTBE helps reduce air pollution, it has seeped into
water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Gore praised Browner's plan, calling it a ``road map to maximize
environmental and economic benefits for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislative road map recommended yesterday, if followed,
will allow us to phase out MTBE with all deliberate speed to limit
water pollution problems associated with it, while at the same time
avoiding regional spikes in the gasoline prices and promoting use
of alternative fuels, principally ethanol, in a way that enhances
air quality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also acknowledged that rising gas prices will
be an issue in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is already on people's minds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think what we need is tough diplomacy to bring the
OPEC price down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore added that other steps included ``the management of
strategic petroleum reserves to mitigate price increases, regional
storage reserves, and domestic drilling and production incentives
and incentives for alternative sources of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
