<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3968 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-ART-324&AMP;ADD     03-21 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-ART-324&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DISMISSES LAWSUIT REQUESTING ASYLUM HEARING FOR CUBAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT37 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By RICK BRAGG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The effort by the Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez to
prevent his return to his father in Cuba was stymied Tuesday when a
federal judge dismissed a lawsuit requesting a political asylum
hearing for the 6-year-old boy, concluding that the long, bitter
legal battle is not in Elian's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge K. Michael Moore ruled here Tuesday that
only Attorney General Janet Reno could grant Elian asylum. In
Washington on Tuesday, Reno said she would not grant the child
asylum and said he should be promptly returned to his father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, in Cardenas, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do everything that should be done after proper
consultation to insure that the child is reunited with his father
in an orderly, fair and prompt way,'' said Reno in a news
conference Tuesday. ``It is time for this little boy to move on
with life at his father's side.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the boy's Miami relatives said late Tuesday that
they had already filed an appeal with the 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals. They also requested that the court delay the boy's
return pending the outcome of any appeal, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was found floating off the Florida coast on
Thanksgiving, the sole survivor of an attempt to reach the United
States in which his mother had perished.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Elian's Miami relatives Tuesday refused to
acknowledge defeat. ``We are confident,'' said Kendall Coffey, a
lawyer for the family.
</P>
<P>
   But, experts on child custody and immigration who have followed
this international custody battle said the lawyers are just trying
to put a brave face on what appears to be a sound defeat for
Elian's Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is terminal,'' said David Abraham, a professor of
immigration law at the University of Miami. He said the ruling cut
through a sideshow of international politics that had obfuscated
what should have been a simple custody case.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Moore, who did not rule from the bench but posted his decision
on the Internet, affirmed the government's assertion that Elian's
father, not Elian himself, must speak for the child's legal rights.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-year-old is too young to understand the legal questions in
such a case, the judge said. While Moore concluded that the
relatives' lawsuit was well intended, he wrote, ``Each passing day
is another day lost between Juan Gonzalez and his son.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lawyers for Elian's relatives continued their fight
to keep him here, appealing the decision to the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Atlanta. The appeal argues that U.S.
immigration laws do not exclude children from asking for asylum.
</P>
<P>
   If they have to, they will take Elian's case to the Supreme
Court, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian has not yet had his day in court,'' said Spencer Eig,
one of eight lawyers representing Lazaro Gonzalez, the boy's great
uncle and temporary guardian.
</P>
<P>
   He and other lawyers said they were still hopeful that Elian
could somehow win an asylum hearing, saying that U.S. immigration
laws allow any ``alien'' to apply for asylum, even children. ``Any
alien means Elian,'' said Coffey.
</P>
<P>
   But, to exclude the father as the boy's legal representative,
the judge ruled, would have required proof that he abused the
child. There was no such proof, the judge ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's father, who had said he did not trust ``corrupt''
American courts, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban government issued a cautious statement: ``We must
analyze with serenity and calm the apparently positive news,
without underestimating the obstacles and difficulties still
necessary to overcome in order to achieve the kidnapped boy's
return to Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, where about 40 people demonstrated peacefully outside
Lazaro Gonzalez's house in Little Havana, it was a momentous but
oddly quiet day in an emotional saga.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference outside the federal courthouse in downtown
Miami, Marisleysis Gonzalez, Elian's cousin, said: ``I'm
overwhelmed. I have faith, and I will keep my faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen found Elian floating on an inner tube off the coast of
Fort Lauderdale last November. His mother, Elizabet Brotons, and 10
others were killed when their boat capsized on a crossing from
Cuba. Elian quickly became a symbol of freedom in Miami's Cuban
American community and the prize in a tug of war between Fidel
Castro, the Cuban president, and anti-Castro groups here.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's face began appearing on T-shirts and posters in the
United States and on billboards in Cuba. People marched on both
sides of the Florida Straits, while in the United States
politicians took sides and held news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   In January, in a decision approved by Reno and endorsed by
President Bill Clinton, the immigration service ordered that Elian
be returned to his father, even though Gonzalez had refused to come
to Miami to ask for his son's return in court. Elian's relatives
here countered with the lawsuit demanding an asylum hearing as
Cuban Americans marched through the streets, clogging traffic and
shouting their displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, even though the news was perhaps even worse for
them, Cuban American leaders said they planned no demonstrations
and would await the final legal outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect the judge's decision,'' said Luis Felipe Rojas,
press secretary for Movimiento Democracia, which had organized
previous demonstrations. Rojas said those demonstrations had been
organized to demand that Elian's case be heard by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Many Miamians, including some in the Cuban American community,
said the January demonstrations damaged the sophisticated,
cosmopolitan image to which Miami aspires. And business owners
worried that television images of the demonstrations _ including
one in which a frustrated motorist drove his car through a line of
hand-holding protesters _ could damage the city's tourist trade.
</P>
<P>
   In what could only be described as a strange distraction
Tuesday, a live rooster crowed from a tree outside the federal
courthouse in downtown Miami as reporters, photographers and
television news crews gathered for a noon news conference.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, it is not unusual for relatives of people on trial to
sacrifice a chicken or other animal outside the courthouses in a
Santeria or other religious ceremony, for luck. The rooster, some
people here said, may have somehow escaped such a sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a handful of disappointed Cuban Americans said the judge
had erred in his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no respect for Elian's rights,'' said Jorge
Gonzalez, who pitched a tent outside the Miami-Dade County
Courthouse in January and went on a hunger strike with two other
men to protest the immigration service's decision to send Elian
home.
</P>
<P>
   Only in Miami, said Abraham, would such a simple case become so
murky and yet so spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's ruling, Abraham said, ``brings us back to the core of
the case _ that a 6-yar-old is spoken for by the surviving parent,
unless that parent is incompetent.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, he said, prevents relatives around the world from
using this case as an excuse to simply keep visiting children and
ignore a parent's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it highly unlikely the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals
will overturn it,'' said Abraham. ``You can't deny the law of the
land when it suits you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
