<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON JOINS CITIES' PUSH FOR GUN-SAFETY STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Adding to pressure on the firearms industry to keep
children and criminals from using guns, Boston officials will
announce Wednesday that the city will give preferential treatment
in awarding contracts to gun companies that voluntarily agree to
abide by sweeping gun safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes after the federal government brokered a deal
with Springfield-based Smith &AMP; Wesson last week to put child-proof
safety latches on its new guns, install ``smart gun'' technology to
prevent unauthorized usage, and to refuse to sell its weapons at
gun shows unless buyers of all guns at the shows passed background
checks.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development, a driving force
behind the settlement, is trying to get other gun manufacturers to
follow the lead of Smith &AMP; Wesson, the nation's biggest gun
company.
</P>
<P>
   HUD announced over the weekend that it would give preferential
consideration in the awarding of gun purchase contracts to
companies that agree to abide by tenets of the Smith &AMP; Wesson deal.
</P>
<P>
   Boston will add its name to a list of cities making the same
demand of their gun contractors, Merita Hopkins, the city's
corporation counsel, confirmed in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In a competitive marketplace, ``it could be quite effective'' in
bringing other gun manufacturers on board, Hopkins said. ``What
we're doing is encouraging folks to make a preference.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins said she did not know how much contract money is
involved. The police department buys its guns ``according to
need,'' she said, and there is ``not a regular purchase every
year.'' The last purchase the city made was from Glock Inc., based
in Smyrna, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Glock will not sign the gun-control agreement signed by Smith &AMP;
Wesson, Glock officials told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The deal-breaker was the creation of an outside ``oversight
commission,'' made up of local, state, and federal officials, that
would supervise the gun manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission is an absurd concept,'' said Paul Jannuzzo,
vice president and general counsel of the company, a unit of Glock
GmbH of Austria. ``It's overly broad. It's more powerful than any
regulatory agency.''
</P>
<P>
   The Smith &AMP; Wesson deal _ a settlement to end lawsuits by dozens
of cities and counties nationwide _ imposed unprecedented
restrictions on the company's gun designs, marketing, and sales
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from installing the safety latches, Smith &AMP; Wesson agreed
to add a second, secret code onto their pistols to help law
enforcement officials trace the guns. The firm also agreed not to
market guns to appeal to children or criminals. For example, the
company cannot advertise a gun as ``fingerprint-proof.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson agreed not to sell a large-capacity magazine and
said it would force buyers to wait two weeks before purchasing
multiple guns, a move that allows law enforcement officials to
track suspicious purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was met with derision by gun-control opponents and
other gun manufacturers. So far, no other gun makers have signed on
to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of lost contracts is meant to step up the pressure on
the nation's other firearms manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo's order on Saturday affects purchases
made by the nation's 3,200 public housing authorities. Cuomo also
encouraged the authorities to apply the same requirement to private
subcontractors that provide security at housing developments. A HUD
spokeswoman said she did not know how much contract money is at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   The idea came after New York Attorney General Eliot Spitzer
broached the strategy last week. He said he had persuaded several
mayors in New York state to agree to refuse contracts to gun
companies that do not abide by the Smith &AMP; Wesson restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said there were some legal problems in outright refusal of
a contract. Instead, Cuomo, along with the mayors of Detroit,
Miami-Dade, and Atlanta, decided to simply give ``preferential''
consideration to acquiescent gun makers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
