<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANGLADESH-TERROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRORIST THREAT ALTERED CLINTON PLAN TO VISIT BANGLADESHI
VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl) 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. officials said Tuesday that President
Clinton's plan to visit a Bangladeshi village this week was
canceled after a terrorist threat possibly linked to Osama bin
Laden, the Saudi exile who has been accused of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. intelligence officials received information late last week
that terrorists were considering a possible attack on Clinton and
his entourage, a U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Secret Service called off Clinton's 28-mile
helicopter trip from Dhaka, the Bangladeshi capital, to the rural
village of Joypura.
</P>
<P>
   One official said that Clinton's helicopter was to have flown
over a heavily wooded area, where it would be easy for an attacker
to hide with a shoulder-launched missile. But officials declined to
say whether that was the specific threat.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden, whom the FBI recently added to its most-wanted list,
is suspected of masterminding the deadly 1998 bombings of two U.S.
embassies in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
   He is believed to be living in Afghanistan under the protection
of the fundamentalist Taliban, who control most of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
