<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-POPE-HOLYLAND-PALS-AR     03-21 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOLYLAND-PALS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOYHOOD PALS IN POLAND, READY FOR THE REUNION
</HEADLINE>
  (With POPE-HOLYLAND) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT35 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NETANYA, Israel _ Yosef Bienenstock, who had survived eight
death camps during the Holocaust because of his skills as a
handyman, finally returned to Poland to get his little brother's
bones in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Tuning out his emotions, he traveled straight to the Jewish
cemetery in the small town of Wadowice, where he grew up next door
to Lolek, a brainy Catholic kid who always let Yosef copy his
homework. Lolek was the nickname for Karol Wojtyla, now Pope John
Paul II, 79, who is six months younger than Bienenstock, 80.
</P>
<P>
   Bienenstock had prepared himself for the tin tombstone he knew
to be on his brother's grave. Of the 10 people in their family,
only he and this one brother, Romek, had survived the Nazi camps.
But his brother died of starvation, fatigue and heartsickness days
after making his way back to their hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Mysteriously, from the grave, there rose a marble monument to
his little brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can this be?'' Bienenstock said he asked the gravekeeper.
The gravekeeper explained that the pope had visited, and seeing the
pathetic grave marker for his former neighbor, had quietly ordered
a new one that did him justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of man he is,'' Bienenstock, a retired
clockmaker, said during an interview Monday in the lush garden
behind his seaside house. ``He grew up with us and he never forgot
us. That's why he demanded from the Christian world to understand
that the Jews of today cannot be held responsible for the
crucifixion. That's why he called the Holocaust an enormity. That's
why he goes to Jewish synagogues and to Jewish cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand what more people want from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bienenstock is a compact, wry man who dresses in sweater vests
and neckties, unusually formal for an Israeli. He was one of
several elderly Jews from the pope's hometown invited to meet with
him on Thursday at the Yad Vashem Holocaust memorial. Of the 2,500
Jews in Wadowice during the pope's childhood _ about a quarter of
the town _ only 80 outlived the Holocaust. Now about 20 are still
alive, 16 in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Before the visit, Bienenstock said he did not know if he would
survive the excitement until the reunion with his boyhood buddy.
Over the years, Bienenstock said, he had considered requesting an
audience with the pope at the Vatican, but he decided to wait,
believing that one day the pope would come to him in Israel, and it
would mean that much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lived in the house of a Jew,'' Bienenstock said of the pope
as a boy. ``It was a long-term rental. On the one side was a
church. On the other was us, the Jews. He was in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``From age zero, we used to play together _ marbles and soccer,
but the soccer ball was made of rags. In soccer, his ability wasn't
the greatest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always was the goalie, and the balls would whistle by him
into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to laugh a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very good, very quiet kid. I was a little terror. At
night, I used to run over and he'd let me copy his homework. For a
period at school, we shared a bench, which was very profitable for
me. I hope they don't cancel my degrees for saying so.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was known to be a genius, not that we ever thought he would
become pope or anything. We treated him the way he treated us,
always with gentleness. When we were bigger, he went to gymnasium
and I went to yeshiva. So what? We still continued. We were
religious Jews but we spoke Polish, and the only difference between
him and us were the holy days and Friday nights, when we spoke
Yiddish.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Germans entered their town after the war began, Karol
Wojtyla was already away at the university. Bienenstock said he
would not detail the degradation he suffered except to offer one
example, from the first days, before they were sent to camps. One
of his older brothers was a rabbi, he said, and a German officer
ordered Bienenstock to chop off the brother's beard and cut off his
side-curls. With an ax.
</P>
<P>
   As Bienenstock described his childhood, his petite wife, Tonya,
sat by his side when she was not jumping up to water plants, fetch
drinks or find letters that testified to her husband's career of
volunteerism. They met at a concentration camp. One day,
Bienenstock, who was in charge of unclogging the toilets, found a
gold wedding band in the muck of a latrine. He said he cleaned it
off and gave it to her. ``If we survive, and if I can find you,
with this ring, I will thee wed,'' he said he told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be pretty,'' said Mrs. Bienenstock, who still is.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wasn't ugly, really,'' her husband said. ``And I could
have chosen anybody. The girls really liked me, for some reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The camps that Bienenstock passed through formed a grim
itinerary, from Dachau to Sachsenhausen to Auschwitz. He is
convinced that he survived because he was an expert tinkerer, whom
the camp directors used to call ``the magician'' and page over the
loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope, at the time, was 19 years old, a student,'' he said.
``Who would have given him a second look in those days? What could
he have done to stop the wickedness? Personally, I don't think he
should apologize at all. It really pains me to hear all the
nonsense in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have no idea how much he has done. His recognition of
the Holocaust _ given all those Holocaust deniers _ his recognition
of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are lucky to have him. I know. I see in his old face the
face of the little boy, the little big-hearted boy. I personally
think they couldn't have chosen a more human person for a pope than
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the marble marker at his brother's grave, Bienenstock
decided to carry through on his plans. He gave the cemetery guard a
bottle of vodka and sent him away. With the help of his daughter, a
young Israeli who was a junior diplomat, he disinterred Romek. They
found little more than small bones, but they packed them all in a
suitcase, and with the help of his daughter's diplomatic passport,
smuggled them out of Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Romek Bienenstock's tombstone is more humble, made of local
stone, basalt. But it is close-by in Netanya. And its inscription,
from the book of Jeremiah, reads: ``And I shall raise you from your
graves, my people, and I shall bring you to the land of Israel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
