<SLUG> BC-NORTEL-CORETEK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTEL PUT UP $1.4 BLLION FOR CORETEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dramatizing the superheated market for optical
networking technology, CoreTek Inc., a 120-person company that has
not even begun making its marquee product, was snapped up by Nortel
Networks for $1.4 billion in stock Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal brings to nearly $8 billion the amount spent by Nortel
since January to grab optical networking start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   It's battling Lucent Technologies Inc., Cisco Systems Inc., and
other telecommunications giants to maintain its dominance in the
exploding market for systems to handle ever more Internet traffic
over fiber-optic networks.
</P>
<P>
   CoreTek, Nortel executives said, is a key piece of their plan to
develop a fully optical version of the Internet in which data move
from computer to computer in pulses of light _ without ever getting
slowed down by being converted to electricity to pass through
conventional routers and switches.
</P>
<P>
   CoreTek, founded in 1994 by Parviz Tayebati, a 39-year-old
Iranian immigrant who became a US citizen in December, has recorded
small sales of specialty optical gear.
</P>
<P>
   But it was prized by Nortel for technology that it is still
developing, called ``tunable lasers.'' They can vastly increase the
capacity of networks besieged by booming Internet traffic, while
lowering operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds crazy to give up $1 billion for a company that's not
even making anything yet,'' said Alex Benik, a Yankee Group optical
networking analyst. ``But for Nortel it makes sense, and down the
road could be worth tens of billions'' in increased market
capitalization, if CoreTek helps it to dominate optical networking.
It's widely estimated that optical networking will be a $50 billion
market within four years.
</P>
<P>
   Already this year, Nortel, based in Brampton, Ontario, has
closed a $3.25 billion stock acquisition of Qtera Corp., whose
technology increases the distance that optical signals can be sent
without regeneration.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Nortel said it would spend $3.25 billion in stock for
the optical switch maker Xros Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are critical technologies, and if you're fortunate
enough to have the stock currency to play in the game, you should
be going full steam ahead,'' said Patrick Houghton, an analyst at
Sutro &AMP; Co. in San Francisco, referring to Nortel's stock, which
this week hit a 52-week high. It closed Tuesday at $129.50, up
$3.3125.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, technologies have been developed to transmit
far more data over existing fiber-optic lines by transmitting data
in several different wavelengths _ literally, different colors of
light _ over a single line.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel is marketing a system that carries up to 160 wavelengths
on one line, so that owners of big global networks such as MCI
WorldCom Inc., Global Crossing Ltd., and AT&AMP;T Corp. can cram far
more Net traffic onto existing lines without having to spend
billions of dollars to lay more cable.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, however, network operators must install a different
type of laser for every color of light being generated to transmit
data. CoreTek's technology would slash costs by allowing a generic
unit to generate multiple colors.
</P>
<P>
   It would also improve traffic flow by allowing data being sent
in one wavelength to be converted to another and reducing or
eliminating the need to convert data from light to electricity to
pass through conventional routers and switches.
</P>
<P>
   Tayebati has a doctorate in quantum mathematics from the
University of Southern California and worked for five years in
optical computing at Foster-Miller of Waltham, an applied
commercial and defense research firm, before founding CoreTek.
</P>
<P>
   Along with wireless Net access, optical networking is one of the
hottest fields in telecommunications. In barely six months, Wall
Street's enthusiasm for the sector has rocketed two Massachusetts
optical networking concerns, Sycamore Networks Inc. of Chelmsford
and Akamai Technologies Inc. of Cambridge, into the top five among
Massachusetts companies, by stock market valuation.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel's $1.4 billion acquisition price represents a jackpot for
CoreTek's venture capital financiers, including Broadview
International LLC of Waltham, Mass. that collectively have put $26
million into the company.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen months ago, CoreTek got $6 million in funding from a
group that included Adams Capital Management and Hillman Co., both
of Pittsburgh, and Patricof &AMP; Co. of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Oak Investment Partners of Palo Alto, Calif., put
in $12 million as part of a $20 million second round of funding,
with undisclosed, smaller stakes added by Broadview, Adams,
Hillman, and JK&AMP;B Capital of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Officials would not say what share of the $1.4 billion in Nortel
stock will go to Broadview and other venture backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made out well, and employees made out well,'' said the
marketing vice president for
</P>
<P>
   CoreTek, Tom Dudley. All 120 employees have some stock options,
he added. The company's real estate consists of a modest
60,000-square-foot building in Wilmington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Mumford, president of Nortel Optical Networks, said
CoreTek's laser-tuning devices are ``clearly ahead'' of products
that Nortel is selling now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is magic in what they do,'' Mumford said.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel will issue 8.9 million shares of its stock for all
outstanding CoreTek shares when the deal closes this spring, with
$361 million of the purchase price contingent on CoreTek's meeting
milestones for product development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
