<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-ISRAEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE SETS FOOT IN `BLESSED LAND' OF ISRAEL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CECILE S. HOLMES 
and DEBORAH HORAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Pope John Paul II arrived in what he called ``this
blessed land'' of Israel on Tuesday, beginning the first official
visit by a Roman Catholic pontiff to the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is with profound emotion that I set foot in the land where
God chose to pitch his tent and made it possible for man to
encounter him more directly,'' the pope said in English after
landing at Ben Gurion International Airport in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this year of the 2,000th anniversary of the birth of Jesus
Christ, it has been my strong personal desire to come here and to
pray in the most important places which, from ancient times, have
seen God's interventions, the wonders he has done.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every top Israeli official was on hand to welcome the
79-year-old pontiff after his short flight from Jordan, where he
celebrated Mass earlier in the day and visited a site where some
scholars say Jesus was baptized. The pope later flew by helicopter
to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul's arrival in Israel marked the first time in 36 years
that a pope has visited the region. Pope Paul VI made an unofficial
visit in 1964, long before the Vatican and the Jewish state
established diplomatic relations, but he never publicly mentioned
Israel's name.
</P>
<P>
   After landing at the Tel Aviv airport Tuesday, John Paul, who
suffers from Parkinson's disease, slowly descended the steps of his
Royal Jordanian jet, his white skullcap blowing off in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Three youngsters representing the faiths of Islam, Judaism and
Christianity participated in the welcoming ceremony. The children,
who live in Jesus' boyhood town of Nazareth, held up a bowl of
Israeli soil, which John Paul touched with his lips.
</P>
<P>
   Greeting the pontiff were Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
President Ezer Weizman as well as Muslim leaders and Christian
dignitaries. One woman bowed her head and kissed the pontiff's ring
in a traditional Catholic gesture of respect.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul noted changes that have come to the Vatican-Israeli
relationship, including the Holy See's diplomatic recognition of
the Jewish state in 1993. The pontiff called his pilgrimage ``a
tribute to the three religious traditions, which coexist in this
land.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray that my visit will serve to encourage and increase
interreligious dialogue and induce Jews, Christians and Muslims to
seek in their respective beliefs ... the motivation and the
perseverance to work for the peace and justice which the peoples of
the Holy Land do not yet have.
</P>
<P>
   ``May peace be God's gift to the land he chooses as his own.
Shalom,'' the pope said, using the traditional Hebrew greeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican has stressed the spiritual quality of the pope's
journey. To many in the region, however, his visit is laden with
political significance.
</P>
<P>
   During his tour, which concludes Sunday, John Paul will meet
with Israeli and Palestinian leaders; celebrate Mass in areas
controlled by both groups; and speak privately and publicly with
Jewish, Christian and Muslim religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, his itinerary calls for a visit to Bethlehem, the
Palestinian-controlled West Bank town where Jesus is believed to
have been born. John Paul is to meet with Palestinian President
Yasser Arafat, celebrate Mass at Manger Square and stop at a
Palestinian refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   The pope will also spend time in Jerusalem, the ancient city
revered by Christians, Jews and Muslims. Palestinians hope to
establish the capital of their future state in the eastern part of
the city. Israelis consider all of Jerusalem their eternal capital.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks to John Paul on Tuesday, Weizman called Jerusalem
``the heart of the Jewish people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is what gives us our spiritual inspiration,'' he said.
``Jerusalem is the city of eternity, a city that has been
reunified. It is the city of the judges of Israel, the kings of
Israel and the prophets of Israel, the capital and source of pride
of the state of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   From Tel Aviv, the pope flew to Jerusalem, where he was greeted
by Mayor Ehud Olmert.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, John Paul celebrated Mass in a soccer stadium
in Amman, Jordan, before a crowd of 50,000 flag-waving supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open your doors to Christ'' proclaimed the neon scoreboard.
Choirs from Iraq and Lebanon as well as Jordan performed, and 2,000
children received Holy Communion for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``His pilgrimage is a spiritual blessing, and besides that, a
good testimony that our country is the Holy Land,'' said the Rev.
Nabil Haddad, a Jordanian Catholic priest. ``It will encourage the
faithful to come to Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope also visited the site alongside a stream that feeds
into the Jordan River where, according to some scholars, Jesus was
baptized by John the Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   Many Muslims in Jordan believe their country will benefit from
the papal visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't all boil down to tourism and the economy,'' said
Susan Afanah, the Muslim director of Jordan Satellite Television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to change the image that everywhere in the
Middle East, they are intolerant of Christians. Christians have
existed in the Arab world even before Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, in Jordan, we have never had any problems,'' she said.
``That's what's important to show the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
