<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-CONDOMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN TO DISTRIBUTE CONDOMS TO TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAURIA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The United Nations is hoping a condom a day will help
keep AIDS away from its peacekeepers in Africa _ and prevent them
from spreading it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeepers arriving on recently authorized peace missions in
Sierra Leone and the Congo are to be issued one latex condom per
day after the United States pressured the Security Council earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The US ambassador to the United Nations, Richard Holbrooke, made
acquired immune deficiency syndrome in Africa the focus of a
Security Council meeting in January. He said that UN peacekeepers
were spreading the deadly disease in the very countries they were
sent to protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``All too often the sad truth is that, at times, in trying to
solve one problem, such as preventing a war or containing conflict,
UN peacekeepers contribute unintentionally to another serious
problem, the spread of AIDS,'' Holbrooke told a congressional panel
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   UN officials are trying to portray their decision to buy and
distribute condoms to their troops as unrelated to American
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously appreciate the added emphasis that Ambassador
Holbrooke has given to the issue . . . but we had been looking at
this issue in a more consolidated fashion for quite some time,''
said a senior UN official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations says it has tried to address the problem
since 1995. It has issued manuals to peacekeepers explaining the
importance of using condoms.
</P>
<P>
   Until now the United Nations has reimbursed national governments
that distributed condoms to their own troops on UN missions. Now
the United Nations will pay for the one-a-day condoms directly out
of the UN peacekeeping budget and make them available to all their
troops.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations budget committee is expected to approve the
expenditure later this week for the 16,000 peacekeepers the United
Nations is sending to Sierra Leone and the Congo. It is expected to
cost $10 per man every month, or nearly $2 million a year for those
two missions.
</P>
<P>
   Extra condoms will be given to the local health authorities, the
UN official said.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations says it keeps no statistics on the number of
its peacekeepers who contract the disease or were found responsible
for spreading it. UN spokesman Fred Eckhard acknowledged that
``because UN civilian and military personnel in peacekeeping or
humanitarian operations can be exposed to the dangers of
contracting or spreading AIDS, the United Nations has been stepping
up preventative measures.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior official said he could neither confirm nor deny
reports that several Croatian women contracted AIDS from UN troops.
Another UN official said on condition of anonymity that Croatia had
demanded that peacekeepers be tested before they were deployed in
eastern Slavonia in 1992. ``We said no and privately told them they
should get their own people tested to protect our troops,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations cannot demand mandatory AIDS testing from its
peacekeepers, he added. ``That's in line with the canon of our
human rights conventions. Even if you knew (a peacekeeper) was HIV
positive you cannot discriminate.''
</P>
<P>
   UN officials say the new condom policy is not meant to be seen
as encouragement for peacekeepers to visit prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years there have been some highly publicized cases: a
band of Bulgarian peacekeepers were embroiled in gunfight in a
Cambodian brothel, Italian blue helmets in Mozambique were accused
of paying girls as young as 12 for sex and UN troops were found
visiting Muslim women in a house of prostitution near Sarajevo run
by a Serb militiaman during the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   A US official said Washington is pleased with the United
Nations' decision. ``Ambassador Holbrooke found when he went to
Africa last year that peacekeepers were getting and spreading AIDS
and he made an issue of it,'' he said. ``Naturally any kind of
preventive measure that can help we welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   After American pressure, the Security Council has agreed to
mention the AIDS issue in all resolutions establishing or renewing
peacekeeping missions. It calls for efforts to ``sensitize
peacekeeping personnel in the prevention and control of HIV/AIDS
and other communicable diseases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
