u a BC-DIABETES-DRUG-NYT &LR;      03-21 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIABETES-DRUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIABETES DRUG LINKED TO LIVER FAILURE IS REMOVED FROM MARKET
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story has been added to the New York Times front page) 
(sw) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration announced on Tuesday evening
that Rezulin, a diabetes drug linked to liver failure, would be
removed from the market immediately.
</P>
<P>
   About half a million Americans are now taking the drug, and the
agency urged them not to stop without first contacting their
doctors to obtain another treatment for their diabetes. Rezulin,
also known by the generic name troglitazone, has been prescribed to
lower blood sugar in people with Type 2, or adult-onset, diabetes,
the most common form of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, manufactured by Parke-Davis, a division of the
Warner-Lambert Co. of Morris Plains, N.J., had been criticized by
consumer safety groups and generated negative news reports during
the last year, because in rare instances it caused serious liver
damage and death.
</P>
<P>
   Since its introduction in March 1997, Rezulin has been linked to
90 cases of liver failure, resulting in 63 deaths and 10 liver
transplants. Three of the transplant recipients died. Ten other
patients recovered from severe liver failure, and 10 others are
still suffering from that condition.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of cases of liver failure was small compared with
the 1.9 million people who have taken the drug at one time or
another, and the FDA initially decided to keep Rezulin on the
market despite the risk, because it had a unique mode of action and
did help many patients.
</P>
<P>
   When Rezulin was marketed in 1997, it was the first in a class
of drugs that lowered blood sugar by making the body more sensitive
to insulin, the hormone that regulates blood sugar levels. In 1999,
the FDA approved two other drugs in the same class, Actos, marketed
by Eli Lilly &AMP; Co. and Takeda Chemical Industries, and Avandia,
made by SmithKline Beecham PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Janet Woodcock, director of the FDA's Center for Drug
Evaluation and Research, said that the agency had changed its
position on Rezulin because data on the two newer drugs showed them
to be safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that they don't pose the kind of liver
toxicity that Rezulin does,'' Woodcock said. She said that the
newer drugs might also cause liver abnormalities, but that they
were not as risky as Rezulin.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Murray Lumpkin, deputy director of the evaluation center,
said that if the two newer drugs had not become available, the FDA
probably would have left Rezulin on the market, because it was
important to have a drug of its type available.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now we have other products that can give patients the same
benefit without having to assume that risk,'' Lumpkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Corr, president of research and development for
Warner-Lambert/Parke-Davis, said, ``This certainly did take us by
surprise. We still believe that the benefits outweigh the risks and
that this drug produces enormous benefits for patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Corr said the company would write letters to doctors telling
them that Rezulin was taken off the market, but he said he did not
know whether patients would be given refunds for leftover supplies
of the drug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
