<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-JERUSALEM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE ARRIVES IN JERUSALEM AMID COMPETING CLAIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Pope John Paul II's historic pilgrimage through the
``history of salvation'' arrived Tuesday in this ancient city
revered as holy by Jews, Christians, and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   The spiritual significance embodied in the stone ramparts of
Jerusalem's Old City has also made it the most fought-over plot of
land in history, a struggle that continues today with rival
Palestinian and Israeli claims to the city as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he landed here, these intense and competing claims to
Jerusalem _ political and spiritual _ were boiling to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   When the Pope touched ground in an Israeli Blackhawk helicopter
as the sun set over the city, he was greeted in a welcoming
ceremony that included the song ``Jerusalem of Gold,'' an Israeli
anthem that celebrates the capture of historically Arab East
Jerusalem in the 1967 Six Day War.
</P>
<P>
   And President Ezer Weizman, in his welcoming speech, pointedly
referred to Jerusalem as ``the capital of the state of Israel . . .
the heart of the Jewish people throughout all the generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Palestinian Liberation Organization's minister
for Jerusalem affairs, Faisal Husseini, issued an appeal signed by
Palestinian political, religious, and academic leaders calling on
the Holy See ``to intervene to lift the siege of Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope, in turn, said he had come with a message of
coexistence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know how urgent is the need for peace and justice, not
for Israel alone, but for the entire region,'' said the pontiff.
``May peace be God's gift to the land he chose as his own.'' He
concluded with the Hebrew word for peace, ``Shalom.''
</P>
<P>
   By setting foot here at this critical juncture in the peace
process, the Pope inevitably entangled himself and the church in
the political struggle for the future of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The status of the city is perhaps the most deeply emotional
issue for Palestinian and Israeli negotiators gathering this week
in Washington to negotiate a framework for a final peace plan that
both sides have agreed to reach by September.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Michael McGarry, rector of the Vatican's Tantour Ecumenical
Institute in Jerusalem, said the pope's spiritual pilgrimage _
which will take him to Bethlehem, Nazareth, the Galilee, and
Jerusalem _ inevitably crosses paths with the real world politics
of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field is seeded with landmines all over the place, but we
would have to say the status of Jerusalem is by far the most
explosive,'' said McGarry.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians see East Jerusalem and the Old City, which
Israel captured from Jordan in 1967 and later annexed, as the
capital of a future state. Israel says Jerusalem has been the
eternal and indivisible capital of the Jewish people through
thousands of years, and it will never relinquish control of it.
</P>
<P>
   For Jews, the Herodian stones of the Western Wall, all that
remains after the destruction of the Second Temple by the Romans in
AD 70, is a symbol of their faith, and what they see as the miracle
of their return after 2,000 years in the diaspora.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians are overwhelmingly Muslim but include a small
Christian minority, and Jerusalem is holy to both faiths. The third
most significant holy shrine in Islam sits atop the Temple Mount.
It is the Dome of the Rock, the golden symbol of the site where
Muslims believe the prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   For Christians, Jerusalem is the site of their most somber
shrine, the Holy Sepulchre, where it is believed Jesus was
crucified, buried, and rose again.
</P>
<P>
   On his scheduled route to Bethlehem Wednesday, the Pope will see
the Palestinian symbols of their claim to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   As he drives through the streets of East Jerusalem, where he is
staying in the Latin Patriarchate's guest home on the Mount of
Olives, the pontiff is likely to see Palestinian flags flying on
rooftops and out of windows. Israeli municipal workers have been
busy trying to take them down, but they kept going back up.
</P>
<P>
   In Bethlehem and the West Bank, streets were lined with posters
showing Yasser Arafat shaking hands with the Pope against an
altered background of the Dome of the Rock and church spires of the
Old City. They proclaim ``Welcome to Palestine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican's official position on Jerusalem was set out in an
accord signed by the Holy See and the PLO on Feb. 15. The document
rejected as ``morally and legally unacceptable'' unilateral
decisions or actions that would alter the status of Jerusalem _
wording widely seen as reference to Israel's annexation of East
Jerusalem and its continued construction of settlements ringing the
city.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican-PLO accord also called for an internationally
guaranteed statute to protect religious rights in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has rejected the call for ``international guarantees''
and Foreign Minister David Levy labeled it a ``regretful
intervention'' in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Emil Jarjoui, a Palestinian legislator and the head of the
Palestinian Authority's ministerial committee for church affairs,
said the Vatican document simply reiterated positions on Jerusalem
held by the United Nations for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement and this visit by the Pope are very important
as a way to remind the world that Jerusalem is the spiritual center
for all of us of all three faiths, and it should not be
unilaterally controlled by only one body,'' said Jarjoui.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
