u w BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-NYT &LR;      03-21 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEST DELAY PUSHES BACK CLINTON'S DECISION ON MISSILE DEFENSE
SYSTEM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon announced Tuesday that it will delay
by two months the next, decisive test of national missile defense
technology, likely pushing back to October President Clinton's
decision on whether to deploy the system.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new schedule, this third test of the system meant to
shield the United States against a limited missile attack will be
conducted on June 26. The delay will allow the military to correct
mistakes that led to the failure of its last test in January,
according to Lt. Gen. Ronald T. Kadish, director of the Ballistic
Missile Defense Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking a very prudent approach to a high-risk
schedule,'' he said in announcing the new timetable Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That schedule has come under increasing attack within the
Pentagon and from scientists, diplomats and members of Congress
from both parties who worry that the timetable is based on
political rather than technological considerations.
</P>
<P>
   The administration set the goal of building a system of 100
missile interceptors in Alaska by 2005 to defend against the threat
of a limited missile attack from a country like North Korea. That
requires letting contracts for construction by October or November.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the administration is asking Russia to amend
the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty, which forbids a national
missile defense system. If the Russians continue to refuse to make
those changes, the United States must give a six-month warning that
it plans to violate the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president wants to pour concrete in May 2001, he has to
tell the Russians by November that he will break the treaty,'' said
Stephen Young, deputy director of the Coalition to Reduce Nuclear
dangers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the next test must succeed in order for the
Pentagon to meet its own standards for advising the president that
the missile-defense technology will work.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the delay, Secretary of Defense William Cohen will
give his recommendation to the president by August, the Pentagon
said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the president is no longer planning to make his
final decision this summer, but will delay it until October,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been the strongest force behind the push for a
complicated missile defense system that is a scaled-down version of
the ``Star Wars'' defense system originally proposed by President
Ronald Reagan. Cost estimates for the system range from $13 billion
to $40 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But even some Democrats have encouraged Clinton to make a
decision in favor of the system, both out of national security
concerns and to prevent Republicans from accusing the Democrats of
being soft on defense in the upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
   But with growing doubts that the technology will be sufficiently
tested to make such a decision by the autumn, supporters of
deployment have joined opponents in asking Clinton to postpone a
decision. European allies also question why a decision has to be
made now, and argue against the national missile defense system
because it would kill the ABM treaty, which they view as a
cornerstone of arms control.
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming June test will be the third attempt to demonstrate
that a missile fired into space can hit a mock warhead propelled by
another missile. In the first test of the system in October, the
missile hit the warhead but received help reaching the target from
a decoy that was supposed to confuse it.
</P>
<P>
   The failure in January of the second test was attributed to a
leak in a pipe that carried the frigid nitrogen gas which cools the
infrared sensors needed to guide the missile in the last minutes of
the flight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3986 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MCCAIN-SENATE-ART-NYT     03-21 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-SENATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN RETURNS TO THE SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT25 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was not John McCain the fiery maverick railing
on the floor of the Senate Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Arizona Republican who put condemnations of the
corrupting power of big money at the center of his losing
presidential bid used his much anticipated reappearance in the
chamber to speak mostly about the Western deployment in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans eager for rapproachment, it was only toward the
end of his solitary 15 minutes in the Senate that McCain referred
to the presidential run that at one point looked as if it could
topple the front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not burden my colleagues with a full discussion of how
I spent my time away and what I learned from my experience,''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke briefly of his gratitude toward the American people and
of their desire for change. ``I intend to do what I can, working
with my Congressional colleagues, Republicans and Democrats, to
help bring about the changes to practices and institutions of our
democracy that they want and deserve,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These reforms, Mr. President, are not ends in themselves. They
are a means to a much more important end. They are intended to
sustain America's pride in the way we govern overselves.''
</P>
<P>
   If it seemed oblique and low key, it was intended that way. With
reconciliation in mind, both McCain and Republican leaders were
playing down their differences in part by giving the widest
possible meaning to the word reform. McCain was welcomed back to
the weekly Senate Republican lunch with a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to hordes of waiting reporters after the lunch, Sen.
Trent Lott, the majority leader, attributed McCain's strong run in
the primaries to his ``emphasis on duty and honor and sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   Of reform, the Mississippi Republican said: ``Reform is bigger
than just campaign finance reform. Reform is about reforming
education in America to make it more productive and to have our
schools safe and drug free. It's about reforming the tax code.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who now plans to use his national prominence to try to
help Republicans keep their congressional majority, told reporters
that the candidates he stumps for should be ``committed to my
agenda for reform.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said they did not need to agree with his call to ban the
unlimited unregulated donations to political parties known as soft
money.
</P>
<P>
   He saved his harsh words for Vice President Al Gore, when asked
what he thought of the presumptive Democratic nominee's efforts to
compare himself to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   He said that if Gore was serious, he should unilaterally
renounce soft money fund-raising. He called for the vice president
to ``see that a full and complete investigation takes place of the
incredible abuses of the institutions of government and every
ethical standard concerning campaign finances that were
orchestrated by the Clinton-Gore campaign in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   In the House, an official of the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee said Democrats had compiled a list of
Republicans in competitive districts who had not voted for the
House version of McCain's campaign finance bill, in order to see if
McCain stumped for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We point out the hypocrisy,'' said Erik Smith, a spokesman for
the campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was invited to address House Republicans at their own
caucus on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Though McCain said he wanted the day to be as much like business
as usual as possible, there were signs of his new celebrity. As he
walked out of the subway beneath the Capitol, tourists and staffers
broke into spontaneous applause and called out ``our hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Though reporters knew when McCain was going to speak, he did not
give his colleagues much warning. So it was a Democrat, Sen.
Barbara Boxer of California, who introduced him as she finished her
own speech calling for gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the senator who has done such an amazing job in the
presidential race back on the floor,'' she said, ``I welcome him
back. The issues he raised I thought were vital to be raised.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he had enjoyed his time in her state and added, ``I
hope that we can get some rebate from the numerous campaign
commercials that we purchased in her state.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Boxer left. Except for Sen. Michael B. Enzi, the Wyoming
Republican who was presiding, not a senator was in the chamber as
McCain spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Sen. Harry Reid of Nevada, the assistant minority
leader, came to the floor. He walked across the aisle to talk to
McCain when he finished speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans did not even seem to know McCain had returned
until they were met by throngs of reporters outside their
closed-door lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, is he back today?'' Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, asked.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, the Alaska Republican who runs the
Appropriations Committee, said cheerily, ``John doesn't bother
me.'' He added, ``I'm sort of sad to see him come back, because I
think I'm the meanest man in town right now.''
</P>
<P>
   At the lunch, Lott, who has often tangled with McCain, welcomed
him to a standing ovation. Two other Republican senators, Don
Nickles of Oklahoma and Larry E. Craig of Idaho also had kind
words. And so did Jim Nicholson, the chairman of the Republican
National Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
