<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3988 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-TOBACCO-NEXT-N     03-21 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-TOBACCO-NEXT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: DESPITE VICTORY, TOBACCO INDUSTRY IS STILL WAITING TO
EXHALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With SCOTUS-TOBACCO, SCOTUS-TOBACCO-REACT) 
(DW) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court decided Tuesday to keep the tobacco
industry alive. But its condition remains critical and the court's
decision sets the stage for another congressional showdown on
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The court rejected the Clinton administration's claim that the
federal Food and Drug Administration had the authority to regulate
cigarettes and nicotine, a victory for the industry that helped
raise the price of tobacco company stocks, which have been
languishing for months.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision comes as cigarette makers are bracing for a
possibly devastating verdict in Florida, where a jury is hearing a
class-action case brought on behalf of smokers there. Analysts have
said that the jury may award tens of billions in punitive damages
against tobacco companies, forcing some producers, if not all, into
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette executives also awoke to Tuesday's ruling after a bad
night. A San Francisco jury held late Monday that Philip Morris and
R.J. Reynolds Tobacco must pay $1.72 million in compensatory
damages to a former smoker there. That same jury is considering
punitive damages, and a decision is expected shortly.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the Supreme Court's decision kicks tobacco
regulation back into an arena where both cigarette makers and their
opponents appear to agree it belongs: Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But just what lawmakers will do with an issue they have
approached with the same unease as gun control is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that this is going to happen,'' said Dr. David
Kessler, the former commissioner of the Food and Drug
Administration who moved to regulate tobacco. ``It's just a
question of when.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., supported a broad tobacco
bill that among other things would have created a special
regulatory category for tobacco under the drug agency. But that
bill was opposed by the tobacco industry because it was costly and
did not give cigarette makers the legal protections they sought.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for McCain said Tuesday that he did not have any
immediate reaction to the Supreme Court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Philip Morris, the nation's largest cigarette
producer, said it would back federal regulation of tobacco through
Congress if it was not classified as a ``drug'' by the Food and
Drug Administration. The producer, like other cigarette companies,
said Tuesday that it was pleased with the court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Parrish, the senior vice president of Philip Morris, said
that the cigarette maker still backed regulation in areas like
youth marketing, disclosure of the hazards of tobacco products and
research intended to produce cigarettes that may be less dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that we went to members of Congress and met with
them privately to tell them we are serious about this,'' Parrish
said.
</P>
<P>
   One person involved with tobacco litigation said that Parrish
had met in recent months with several top Republican leaders,
including Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi and Rep. Tom DeLay of
Texas. Parrish declined to comment. A spokesman for DeLay confirmed
that DeLay had met with Parrish. Lott's office did not return a
telephone call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   There is general agreement that Congressional action on a
tobacco bill is unlikely this year, and the makeup of the White
House and Congress after the fall election may determine any bill's
shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I have talked to has said there are just not that
many legislative days left in session to get things down,'' Parrish
said.
</P>
<P>
   As a campaign issue, tobacco control traditionally has carried
little weight with voters. Still, Vice President Al Gore said
Tuesday that he favored regulation of tobacco by the Food and Drug
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   And in a statement, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas said he
advocated strict laws intended to prevent teen-agers from smoking
and added that ``tobacco regulation should be made by Congress and
state legislatures.''
</P>
<P>
   For cigarette makers, the problem is not only a legislative one
but a legal one.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, while the gun producer Smith &AMP; Wesson averted some
legal woes by agreeing to change some product designs and business
practices to settle some lawsuits, the prospect of that option for
tobacco companies ranges from remote to nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, cigarette makers already have agreed to pay $246
billion to states over the next two decades to settle lawsuits
brought by state attorneys general seeking to recover health care
costs.
</P>
<P>
   But that accord did not cover either cases brought by individual
smokers, like the one decided on Monday by the jury in San
Francisco. And more important, it did not cover class-action
lawsuits like the Florida case.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Florida case represents a group of smokers that may
include 300,000 people or more, some analysts have speculated that
an award of punitive damages against the industry this spring could
be astronomical.
</P>
<P>
   To appeal that award, producers may have to post a bond equal to
it. Faced with that option, some companies may choose to file for
bankruptcy, a step that would freeze all litigation against them,
several analysts and lawyers have said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the bond is high, many if not all of the tobacco companies
may not be in the position to post,'' John Coffee, a law professor
at Columbia University, said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   That worst-case scenario, as industry officials refer to it, is
a small possibility. But it is real. Indeed, those who looked to
the Supreme Court for many years for the final word on the tobacco
industry's fate are making preparations in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette companies have persuaded several tobacco-producing
states to enact laws or consider proposals that would let them
appeal the Florida decision and protect assets like cigarette
plants from seizure if they are not able to post a bond.
</P>
<P>
   State officials, who would see billions in settlement funds
imperiled if bankruptcies occurred, are also taking steps.
</P>
<P>
   This week, they are expected to hire a legal expert to represent
states as creditors in bankruptcy court. Just in case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
