r s BC-BKC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     03-21 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUSTACHY WILL BE PREPARED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry Eustachy likes to remind his Iowa State players, those who
will meet UCLA in the NCAA's Midwest Regional semifinal Thursday,
that they may be the worst judge of their own talents.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks from personal experience. As a guard at Arcadia High
School in the early '70s, he would watch taped-delay broadcasts of
Bruins games on KTLA and imagine himself playing at Pauley Pavilion
for John Wooden.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a player in the country who didn't want to go to
UCLA,'' said the Iowa State coach, ``especially if you lived in Los
Angeles. I watched that team through its march to 10 titles. I
still get chills up my spine thinking about their tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is how close I was to playing for UCLA: I was a
non-scholarship player at Citrus College, the eighth man (on a JC
team). That's why I tell my kids not to evaluate themselves,
because I thought I should have been at UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   So instead of pondering his dream, Eustachy did all of the
things necessary to make himself a good basketball coach. He
finished his career at Citrus, transferred to Long Beach State, and
earned a bachelor's degree in the credentialed P.E./coaching
program.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he moved to Belmont Shore and started taking classes
at L.B. State, he had put playing behind him. Tex Winter was the
49ers' coach then, and teams like Texas, Cincinnati, Oklahoma
State, Duke, North Carolina and Marquette were on the schedule. ``I
didn't even attempt to make the team,'' Eustachy said. ``I didn't
want the bad news of being cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Good player or not, Eustachy has developed into an excellent
coach. His current Cyclone team set a school record for wins in a
season (31), and one more win will put the school into its first
NCAA regional final since 1944, when it was an eight-team tourney
and the NIT was the big deal in college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   In 10 seasons as a head coach, Eustachy has never had a losing
season. He had three winning seasons at Idaho, including a 24-8
mark in 1993, and five at Utah State, where he was Big West coach
of the year twice (1995, 1998) and took the Aggies to the 1998 NCAA
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Three coaches have been a major influence in Eustachy's life:
Neil Edwards, his Citrus coach who also gave him his first coaching
job; Tim Floyd, the Chicago Bulls coach who hired him at Idaho and
then recommended him for the Idaho and Iowa State jobs; and another
former coach, Bob Boyd, who hired him off a recommendation from
Edwards and also has a background with UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd was the USC coach (1967-79) during eight of UCLA's 10 title
seasons. Boyd's Trojans handed UCLA its only loss in 1969 and one
of its two losses in 1970. His 1971 USC team went 24-2, with its
only two losses to the Bruins, but second-place teams didn't get
NCAA invitations back then.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd gave Eustachy his first Division I job as an unpaid
assistant on his 1981-82 Mississippi State staff. Floyd became a
grad assistant a year later and Boyd's top aide his third, but that
first year was memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Eustachy lived with Boyd in Starkville and worked as a waiter in
a seafood restaurant when he wasn't at practice. ``It was always
interesting when the players came in to eat,'' Eustachy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a true volunteer,'' Boyd said. ``We had an old southern
gentleman as athletic director, and he said I could have a
volunteer assistant as long as it doesn't cost the department one
cent. That's exactly the way he came.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I first noted about Larry is that he was a very good
teacher. I (immediately) felt comfortable assigning him a coaching
station. He had the ability to communicate and hold the attention
of the kids. As a recruiter, the kids were always comfortable
talking to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those early days, I think I was helpful. But his success
isn't happening by chance. He's responsible for it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Eustachy landed the Utah State job, he again reached out to
Boyd, then retired in Palm Springs, and hired him as an assistant
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the world's oldest restricted-earnings coach,'' Boyd
said. ``It was a great deal for me. I wasn't doing anything at the
time, and I got a one-year contract at $1,000 a month, plus a place
to stay and insurance just for being there from mid-October to the
start of the tournaments. I used the insurance for angioplasty.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd and his wife Betty will make the trip to Auburn Hills,
Michigan, to see the Iowa State- &QL; 
UCLA game. The only warning he would give UCLA is to expect to see
a better team than the Maryland squad the Bruins just humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be any lobs Thursday,'' said Boyd of Iowa State.
``His team is very conscious of its responsibility. That's how they
win and stay in games. They get back on defense, guard you all the
time, and rebound. There's nothing complicated about what Larry
does. They just do all the important things right.''
</P>
<P>
   Eustachy isn't taking anything for granted, not his own team's
success to this point or UCLA's 11 losses prior to their current
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, they're playing as good as anyone,'' Eustachy said.
``If we don't play good transition defense, we could be out of the
game in the first five minutes. There isn't one thing where we can
say `do this and we'll win the game.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It no longer may be Wooden on the sidelines and 10 titles in 12
years, but Eustachy knows a tingling spine when he feels one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2125EST &QL; 
