<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S.-CHINA TALKS CENTER ON STATUS OF TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (subs for rewriting and additional details, mainly to recast lede,
include additional Holbrooke quotes and add that 5 top U.S.
officials will visit China)  
(bl) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A senior U.S. official said Tuesday that in two days
of intensive talks, Chinese leaders had demonstrated a ``cautious
and prudent'' approach toward the new administration in Taiwan and
seemed anxious to explore what the election outcome meant for the
complicated relationship among China, the United States and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed that the next nine weeks are critical,'' said
Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. envoy to the United Nations, adding
that there would be five cabinet-level officials visiting Beijing
in the space of a month.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's trip, which was planned before the election Saturday
of an independence-leaning candidate as Taiwan's new president, was
supposed to focus on the United Nations, and that was discussed for
several hours. But Holbrooke said that Chinese officials, who have
made few public comments on the election victory of Chen Shui-bian,
quickly turned the discussion to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese made it clear to us that the central issue in
Sino-U.S. relations from their point of view was Taiwan,'' said
Holbrooke, who was joined on the trip by Stanley Roth, the State
Department's top official on East Asia.
</P>
<P>
   During the Taiwan presidential campaign, China mounted a
menacing verbal campaign against Chen, and reiterated its position
that it would fight to block formal independence.
</P>
<P>
   But Holbrooke on Tuesday praised the ``cautious and prudent
approach that the Chinese emphasized in their discussions'' with
his delegation, focusing on diplomatic rather than military
solutions. ``The Chinese are fully mindful of the historical
significance of what happened in Taiwan and that it is both an
opportunity and a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are completely mindful of the historical significance of
the phase we're in now, and so are we,'' he said. ``And this is
reflected in the intensification of contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke met with several senior Chinese officials, including
President Jiang Zemin, who extended a scheduled 30-minute meeting
to two and a half hours. The talks also touched on human rights,
China's entry to the World Trade Organization and normalizing
China's trade status. Holbrooke said the national security adviser,
Sandy Berger, will arrive next week to take up the discussions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
