<HEADLINE>
3 FIRMS INVEST $40 MILLION IN NEW YORK TIMES CO.'S DIGITAL UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Times Co., which plans a public offering
of a new class of stock in its Internet business division this
spring, said Tuesday that three venture capital firms had invested
$40 million in the division, Times Company Digital.
</P>
<P>
   The investors are Flatiron Partners, Highland Capital Partners
and Chase Capital Partners, a unit of Chase Manhattan Bank. The
firms acquired three-year debt that will be convertible _ after the
offering _ into the Times Co.'s new Class C shares, which will
track the performance of Times Company Digital. Details about the
investment, including the interest rate to be paid on the debt and
the conversion price for the shares, were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Colonna, managing partner of Flatiron Partners, and Daniel
Nova, managing general partner of Highland Capital Partners, also
agreed to join a new advisory board for the digital division, The
Times Co. said. Other members of the board from outside the company
are Red Burns, the chairwoman of the interactive telecommunications
program at New York University, and Mark Walsh, the chief executive
of VerticalNet Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the advisory board from The Times Co. are Arthur
Sulzberger Jr., chairman; Russell T. Lewis, president and chief
executive; Howell Raines, editorial page editor of The New York
Times; and Martin A. Nisenholtz, the chief executive of the digital
division.
</P>
<P>
   The company filed a registration statement for the stock with
the Securities and Exchange Commission on Jan. 28, but the offering
cannot be made until it is cleared by the SEC and approved by
shareholders at a meeting scheduled for April 27.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
