<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TALKING TO THE SPITTOONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the road, throngs fought to get near John
McCain. In the deserted Senate chamber Tuesday, he gave a speech
about Kosovo to 99 empty mahogany desks and a few brass spittoons.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder he was feeling nostalgic, or ``shmaltzy and overly
sentimental,'' as he put it, about his zany revolution and his
runaway bus.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as much fun excoriating the Washington establishment
when you're back in its bosom.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator told the press the time of his speech, but
did not give fellow senators much notice. He didn't even bring
along his ``bodyguards,'' as the handful of senators who supported
his campaign are known, despite the fact that they were all in his
office before the speech.
</P>
<P>
   He needed the imagery to be just right for his latest high-wire
act: He wants to return to the Republican fold but also keep his
distance and maintain his romantic image as the lonely rebel.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, his campaign aides _ John Weaver, Todd Harris and
Lanny Wiles _ looked down intently from the half-filled visitors'
gallery. McCain's speechwriter and co-author of his best-selling
Vietnam memoir, Mark Salter, sat behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Was this bland little address the kickoff for McCain 2004 or, as
it might be known, ``Speed 2''?
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be extremely tricky. ``It's important that I not
give the appearance of being just one of those guys who sounds good
on the campaign trail but then goes back to business as usual,'' he
said in an interview in his office.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not think ``the magic,'' the ``Wallenda high-wire
act'' of his ``happy band'' could be re-created. But he does not
want to behave in a way that will let down all the McCainiacs who
said to him: ``I was never involved before and I will never be
involved again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a fragile thing,'' he mused.
</P>
<P>
   He insists he does not want to be the vice president to the man
he referred to throughout the 30-minute interview merely as ``he.''
</P>
<P>
   Put aside the fact that McCain wants to ban the soft money that
W. is counting on to catapult him to the White House. Put aside the
lingering animosity about low Bush campaign tactics. (One of the
toughest moments of his campaign, McCain said, was not lashing out
at W.'s outrageous breast cancer ad: ``I had to keep a tight rein
on my emotions.'')
</P>
<P>
   Even put aside Bush's arrogant attitude toward McCain in a New
York Times interview, which the senator read in a fax version that
came to his thatched hut in Bora-Bora. ``I guess I was a bit
surprised,'' he said of W.'s comments.
</P>
<P>
   There is still another problem. ``I'm 63,'' the senator says,
wincing. ``I'll be 64 in August.'' If he were Bush's vice
president, he might be 71 by the time he got to run. ``Ronald
Reagan was an exception, but in general, I think guys that old
should be getting out of politics, not running for president of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   But if W. loses with another running mate _ ``There's Tom Ridge,
John Engler, Christie Whitman _ he should pick someone from a swing
state,'' McCain suggests brightly _ the party might turn in
desperation to their rebel.
</P>
<P>
   So the senator has cooled his rhetoric on campaign finance
reform for the moment, perhaps hoping to save it as an issue for
later.
</P>
<P>
   The iconic has turned ironic: after running an idealistic
campaign to curb the corrupting influence of money on American
politics, McCain will use his new cachet to try to inject more cash
into American politics.
</P>
<P>
   Although he plans to keep fighting for campaign finance reform,
he is the GOP's new money magnet. Republicans who winced every time
he opened his mouth on the campaign trail are now salivating at the
prospect of having him headline their fund-raisers to raise money
so they can hold onto their majorities in Congress and further
thwart campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   The high priest of lower spending is even forming a PAC, a
personal fund-raising machine, to round up bucks to get his
anti-money message across. He defends himself: ``I will campaign
for people but I won't have anything to do with soft-money
events.'' The PAC, he says, ``will help us formulate an agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   And plugging a reform agenda in the coming years might come in
handy _ just in case the Wallendas have an encore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
