<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-BACHELOR-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLS SCORES WITH GOALS, NOT YET WITH FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The debut of the 2000 season last weekend for Major League
Soccer wasn't 100 percent sparkling, but it seemed to help polish
off some tarnish the league has accumulated after four years.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, the first game on the docket proved to be a
thriller, rekindling a fierce rivalry from last year's physical
playoff series between the Chicago Fire and the Burn. Just as it
did last season, the Burn refused to lose, dousing the Fire, 4-2,
Saturday in a game that included 47 total fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was what I thought was probably one of the best opening
games in MLS,'' said MLS executive vice president Ivan Gazidis.
``It was a terrific game, and there were a lot of positives that
came out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another bright spot were the debuts of the Fire's Bulgarian
standout Hristo Stoitchov and 17-year-old prodigy DaMarcus Beasley,
both among the influx of newcomers the league has high hopes for
this season. Stoitchov scored both of Chicago's goals, and Beasley
appeared to have no trouble adjusting to the physical level of MLS.
</P>
<P>
   That game helped boost the league average to 4.26 goals for the
four season openers. It's too early to speculate whether that
output will continue for 31 more games, but those are promising
early figures for keeping the offensive-minded fan base happy,
especially considering that the average goals-per-game for last
season was 2.86.
</P>
<P>
   But those numbers don't make up for some others, namely an
average attendance of 14,571. That's on par for the season average
over the past three years, but less than last season's opening
average of 16,042 in five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in line with what we expected,'' Gazidis said. ``It's
very early to be opening our season. It's what we tend to have with
games this early in March. Attendance has never been that high, but
we tend to build in early April and May.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's full slate of games should help, with the rematch
of MLS Cup '99 between defending champion D.C. United and the Los
Angeles Galaxy expected to be a big draw. There is also the
much-anticipated debut of German superstar Lothar Matthaus with the
MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the scope of this season, the perspective appears
cautiously optimistic for the future of the league. Word in Los
Angeles is that the Galaxy intends to build a 25,000-seat
soccer-specific stadium and training center for the men's and
women's national teams. In Chicago, Fire general manager Peter Wilt
has expressed interest in revamping Soldier Field.
</P>
<P>
   Those are significant developments because many believe the
future of soccer in the United States hinges on teams having their
own facilities. Currently, Columbus Crew Stadium is the only
soccer-specific stadium in the United States. GRAZIANI HONORED
</P>
<P>
   Burn forward Ariel Graziani picked up right where he left off
last season, scoring two goals in the Burn's 4-2 victory against
Chicago and earning MLS Player of the Week.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani, who played with Ecuadorian select team Emelec during
the off-season, had four goals and one assist in eight games with
the Burn last season. WOUNDED RAPIDS
</P>
<P>
   Colorado won't be limping as heavily as it has throughout most
of the preseason when it comes to Dallas on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rapids were hit hard by injury at the end of last year,
which Colorado woefully finished with a league-record 679 minutes
without a goal. And the roster was still black and blue for most of
the preseason. Five of 10 regular field starters missed Saturday's
season-opening loss against Los Angeles, but midfielders Anders
Limpar (hamstring) and Joey DiGiamarino (groin) could see their
first action of the season against the Burn in Saturday's 7:30 p.m.
match at the Cotton Bowl. THEY'RE G-R-R-REAT?
</P>
<P>
   The Burn's new home jersey and red shorts, which were unveiled
Saturday at the Cotton Bowl, come with a price: a smiling Tony the
Tiger logo on the front, as well as the Kellogg's logo spread
across the back.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg's has replaced AT&AMP;T as one of the league's major
corporate sponsors this season. But it's doubtful that a cheerful
cartoon Tiger on the front left corner of their shorts will have
many players saying how ``g-r-r-reat'' the new unis are. `STOICHOV'
GONE
</P>
<P>
   It seems the league has seen the last of Bulgarian international
Hristo Stoichov, one of MLS' marquee international players who made
his debut last week. But Hristo Stoitchov is here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   At his request, Stoitchov added the second ``T'' to his name
last week, and the league honored his request on Monday. His name
was spelled without the ``T'' during the 1994 World Cup played in
the United States and during his peak years with Barcelona of the
Spanish first division. ZARCO BACK
</P>
<P>
   Burn defender Jorge Rodriguez, who had been one of two holdouts
in the league this season but returned last week, played the final
eight minutes in the Burn's season opener against Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   A contingent of Burn fans expressed support for Rodriguez with
signs that read ``Zarco,'' his nickname, which means ``green-eyed
one'' in Spanish. The supporters staged a small walkout at the
Cotton Bowl during the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Coach David Dir does not plan to start Rodriguez until he has
reached a negotiation regarding his contract with the league. HEAT
GETS NEW COACH
</P>
<P>
   The North Texas Heat, a Dallas-based women's semipro team, will
be coached this year by Jim Benedek. Benedek has played
professionally in several countries and was coach for SMU from 1974
to 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat, which won the Division II championship of the United
Soccer League's last season, opens its season Sunday, May 7,
against the Denver Diamonds.
SPOTLIGHT ON:
BURN COACH EMOTIONAL ABOUT HICKS' DEPARTURE
</P>
<P>
   Last week's Burn season kickoff luncheon turned surprisingly
sentimental when coach Dave Dir gave an emotional speech for
outgoing president and general manager Billy Hicks, who is leaving
to take a position with the World Wrestling Federation's startup
XFL.
</P>
<P>
   A comment from Hicks during his own speech gave some perspective
to the development of soccer in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody had mentioned to me, ``Isn't it risky to leave soccer
for football?''' said Hicks, who begins his new position Monday.''I
thought it really showed how far it has come here, that in Dallas,
Texas, somebody could use that phrase.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks has been the Burn's only general manager since the
league's inception in 1996 and was one of the initial figures in
bringing a soccer franchise to Dallas. Dir remains as the only MLS
coach still with the same team from his first season.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hicks' departure) is really hard for me personally,'' Dir
said. ``People really don't know how we met or how this all came
about, but we had some grand plans for the league and for where
soccer is going. We had them when he came in, and, from that
standpoint, we wanted to bring a team to Dallas that would
encompass everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the league likes what it has seen of Dir's
contributions to that vision. He was expected to sign a three-year
contract this week.
</P>
<P>
   MLS executive vice president Ivan Gazidis said the league is not
rushing the decision on Hicks' successor. At this point, all three
of the Burn's vice presidents _ Paul Mott (operations and
administration), John Alper (sales) and Andy Swift (marketing and
broadcasting) _ have been recommended by Hicks as internal
candidates.
nn
</P>
