<HEADER>
A4001 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JAVA-PUPPET-THEATER-A     03-21 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAVA-PUPPET-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAMA IN JAVA, WHERE PUPPETS OWN THE STAGE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT32-34 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By JAMIE JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CIREBON, Indonesia _ In Japan, a master of the Noh drama may be
declared a living national treasure and supported for life. In the
West, classical theater is fostered by government subsidies (though
leaner and meaner now than they used to be) and private
philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in Java, the world's most populous island and the political
and cultural center of Indonesia, the traditional drama still
mainly survives the way it has for centuries: by popular demand.
Itinerant puppeteers, known as dalangs, travel from village to
village, performing the ancient tales of gods and demons, heroes
and fools, for anyone with the wherewithal to hire them.
</P>
<P>
   In most cultures, puppets imitate human actors; in Java, the
reverse is true. The traditional dramas have always been performed
with puppets; indeed, the Indonesian word for puppet, wayang, is
used to denote the various forms of the drama. When a piece is
performed by people, for example, it is called the wayang orang _
literally, a human puppet show.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known form of drama in Java is the wayang kulit, the
shadow-puppet theater, performed with flat puppets made of leather
whose shadows are cast on a white cloth hanging between the
puppeteer and the audience. The wayang kulit remains a popular
entertainment throughout the island.
</P>
<P>
   Another form is the wayang golek, presented on a wooden stage
with three-dimensional rod puppets carved from wood and elaborately
painted and costumed. Its popularity has begun to decline as newer
forms of entertainment seduce young audiences.
</P>
<P>
   One regional variety of the wayang golek, the wayang cepak,
known for its distinctive style of puppet carving, is particularly
imperiled, although it has been performed continuously in the
countryside around the city of Cirebon in West Java for at least
700 years, and perhaps for centuries longer than that. Cirebon was
the seat of an ancient Islamic kingdom, and the region's culture is
distinct from that of the rest of the island.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, Ann Kumar, a historian on the faculty of the
Australian National University in Canberra, commissioned a
performance of the wayang cepak, which was documented by a video
crew from the Lontar Foundation, a Jakarta-based group devoted to
preserving traditional Indonesian culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wayang cepak,'' Kumar said, ``is one genre among many in a
rich theatrical tradition which is no longer flourishing as it once
did. The performers are getting older, many are dying, and this
endangers the continuity of the art form.''
</P>
<P>
   She paid the dalang, Warsad Darya, one of the most accomplished
of the surviving wayang cepak masters, his usual fee of $110 for
the customary six-hour extravaganza of dance and theater,
accompanied by a gamelan, a traditional orchestra of bamboo and
bronze percussion instruments, and a singer. Some famous dalangs
can command thousands of dollars, but in rural area around Cirebon,
where Warsad lives, the fee is a lot of money for most of his
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Most performances of the wayang cepak serve a ritualistic
purpose, as the night's entertainment for a wedding or a boy's
circumcision, which in Muslim Java is a ceremony for pre-adolescent
boys, somewhat similar in religious significance to a confirmation
or bar mitzvah. This particular performance took place in Warsad's
workshop in the village of Gadingan, deep in the countryside of
West Java.
</P>
<P>
   The stage, a pair of stout banana trunks, was flanked by a
brilliant array of 130 puppets, all carved and painted by Warsad.
They were costumed in lustrous silk and satin, and adorned with
glittering spangles, bugles and beads. A fluorescent tube, mounted
on a beam overhead and shaded by a pink curtain, cast a soft light.
From the beam dangled offerings to the ancient pre-Muslim gods of
Java: pineapples, pumpkins, passion fruit, bottles of soda and
beer, cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   An evening of the wayang cepak begins at 9 o'clock. The puppet
drama is often preceded by a short dance performance. After a
clangorous overture by the gamelan, a 15-year-old girl came out in
front of the stage and impersonated several characters from the
wayang, wearing masks and scarves and moving with grace or
heavy-limbed power, as the character demanded.
</P>
<P>
   Then Warsad, seated on the floor behind the stage, began to work
his magic; no other word suffices. The puppets floated across the
stage, their heads and arms manipulated from below by slender rods.
An aristocratic lady rushed into view, tossing her head fretfully
and flailing her arms as the dalang crooned her cry of distress.
Having said her piece, she was pinned to one of the banana trunks
by the point at the end of the puppet rod, her arms still raised
beseechingly.
</P>
<P>
   A handsome prince entered, striding purposefully, his virile,
confident voice offering her solace. The puppets were subtly lit by
the fluorescent light overhead and from below the stage. One by
one, the characters were introduced and planted in their places,
carrying on complex conversations, punctuated by songs, which
propel an enormously complicated plot.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the dramas of the wayang are based on Javanese versions
of the great Hindu epics, the Mahabharata and the Ramayana, relics
of the Majapahit empire that flourished in Java in the 14th
century. The drama that Kumar requested, however, is from a cycle
of indigenous Javanese legends about a mythical king named Panji,
from the pre-Muslim era. Kumar likens the Panji stories to the
British romances about King Arthur, peopled by larger-than-life
heroes who bravely triumph over all obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   The version performed at Warsad's workshop was about Panji's
search for his true love, Candra Kirana, a picaresque tale in which
he encounters one vicissitude after another, involving many
disguises (frequently in cross-dress) and mistaken identities. As
in many national epics, the tale promotes correct religious and
ethical behavior as well as validating the hierarchical structure
of a feudal society and fostering respect for the aristocracy
embodied by the noble Panji.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible for scholars to say exactly how long the wayang
cepak versions of the Panji tales have been performed in the
Cirebon area, but the dramatic tradition is among the oldest
surviving in the world, contemporary with the mystery plays of
Europe and the Japanese Noh. The legends themselves are certainly
much older, dating as long ago as 2,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   ThE Panji myth was exported throughout Southeast Asia. Kumar
said that Javanese immigrants carried the Panji tales as far away
as Japan, where, she believes, they became the basis of ``The Tale
of Genji'' by Lady Murasaki Shikibu. Kumar's views are
controversial, but she has marshaled evidence that she maintains
supports them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
