<SLUG> BC-BKC-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REASONS ABOUND WHY MIHM WILL RETURN FOR SENIOR SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talked to a friend on the phone after I got back from Salt Lake
City. Like millions of others, he had watched a lot of basketball
on television during the first two rounds of the NCAA Tournament.
But his first question was not about the games or a projection
about the Final Four or the eventual national champion.
</P>
<P>
   It was about Texas' junior center Chris Mihm.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' he said, ``was that Chris Mihm's ride off into the
sunset?''
</P>
<P>
   Lot of opinions abound concerning Mihm's decision about whether
to return for his senior year. The subject is one of constant
debate among the writers who regularly cover the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   After Texas' underachieving loss to LSU in the second round of
the West Region, one regular changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a feeling,'' he said, believing Mihm would declare for
the June NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   I've got no more insight than he does. But my opinion more than
ever is that Mihm stays for a final season. I don't believe the
sunset that Mihm rode off into Saturday was the one of his
choosing. I don't believe that Chris wants the final impression of
his career to be that of LSU's Stromile Swift rejecting a
crunch-time shot in the lane. I don't believe Mihm is the kind of
guy who likes to leave a job unfinished.
</P>
<P>
   I might be wrong about how important any of that is to him, but
if he leaves, his collegiate career will remain an unfinished
symphony.
</P>
<P>
   UT coach Rick Barnes spoke in Salt Lake of the legacy that Mihm
could leave at Texas and for Texas high school basketball. Barnes
never says something without design, and those words linger in
connection with Mihm's understandably distended performance in the
final game of his junior season.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing how fickle fans are, Texas' contingent will not look
favorably on Mihm if he bails out _ especially since his return,
when coupled with the addition of a scorer such as transfer Maurice
Evans, bodes favorably on the Longhorns' chances of again having
one of the Big 12's best teams next season, and a shot at making
some noise in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do know this,'' Barnes said. ``If Chris comes back, he will
enjoy his senior season a lot more than he did this one, because no
one will be asking him all the time about his future.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mihm or no, Barnes isn't backing off about his feelings
concerning the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be a different team next year, no matter what
Chris does,'' Barnes said. ``But I want our fans to continue to get
excited about this program. I want to raise expectations. I'm
disappointed that we didn't go farther in the tournament this year,
but getting there is a great accomplishment no matter what people
say. It's not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he wants the Longhorns to run more next year and
believes he will have the team to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Junior college point guard Fredie Williams likely will run the
attack with Darren Kelly and Evans playing more offensive roles.
Barnes hopes that Lawrence Williams will make the same kind of
progress that Will Clay did between his junior and senior seasons,
and that Roosevelt Brown can be a defensive stopper. Chris Owens
could be much better and even more of a force inside, where help is
on the way from Duncanville's 6-foot-9 forward Brian Boddicker,
6-10 center Jason Klotz of state-champion Klein Forest and 6-8 prep
school forward James Thomas. Brandon Mouton of Lafayette (La.) St.
Thomas More is a 6-5 swingman who could also add scoring punch.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Texas will play one of the nation's top schedules. The
Longhorns will be in the Preseason NIT. With two slots yet open,
they will play Illinois, Utah and Connecticut at home. Chances are
good that one of the two remaining openings will be filled by a
television deal, meaning another name opponent. Texas will also go
to Arizona next season, as well at playing an ESPN game at South
Florida and fulfilling the last game of the Houston series at
Hofheinz Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to stay good,'' Barnes promised. Without
qualification. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
