<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4003 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JAVA-PUPPET-THEATER-A     03-21 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAVA-PUPPET-THEATER-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CIREBON, Indonesia: supports them.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the drama's end, Warsad had 10 puppets sharing the stage,
Panji and Candra Kirana reunited and all the court rejoicing.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Cohen, an American scholar of the wayang and a dalang
himself who has been living in Cirebon for eight years, said:
``Warsad is very smart, but illiterate, and I think that has helped
him to master the repertoire. He knows more than 100 dramas.
Literate dalangs are hindered in their command of the repertoire
because they try to stick with a set written version of the text,
whereas Warsad is more improvisatory.''
</P>
<P>
   Warsad, who is self-taught, has been supporting himself as a
puppeteer for 36 years, since he was 24. Before the performance,
his wife spread bamboo mats on the floor of their home and served
dinner to the assembled musicians and visitors. As he watched the
group fortify itself with fried chicken, vegetable soup and rice,
Warsad talked about his life as a dalang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty or thirty years ago, I performed as many as 150
performances a year,'' he said. ``In 1980 it began to decline. This
year I did 50.'' Warsad was referring to the fact that contemporary
forms of entertainment are superseding the wayang cepak theater in
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   A jaunty, compactly built man scarcely more than 5 feet tall, he
has the sunny countenance and self-confident air of an artist at
the top of his profession. ``It's in my nature to be a dalang,'' he
said. ``In the beginning, I had no teacher, no texts, no puppets. I
borrowed a set of puppets, and when the owner took them back, I
learned how to carve my own.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the puppets he uses in his own performances, he
also carves them to sell to collectors and other dalangs; he
estimates that he has carved, painted and costumed 2,000 puppets in
his life.
</P>
<P>
   Another source of income is the rental of a series of
fantastical, brilliantly colored carriages of mythological animals
for children, which he carved and painted a few years ago. Called
kereta, they are hired by families celebrating a ritual, a wedding
or, more often, a circumcision ceremony: the child and his friends
ride on the bizarre beasts, surrounded by puppet coachmen, pulled
through the village by horses.
</P>
<P>
   How is it that such an ancient, deep-rooted dramatic tradition
as the wayang cepak is in decline? Kumar said one reason it is
endangered is precisely because of the popular nature of the drama:
``There's a grass-roots interest in the theater here. It's not
patronized by rich people, and the artists are very much at the
mercy of the economy. After the crop failed here two years in a
row, there was a mass emigration to find work.''
</P>
<P>
   Warsad is one of the few people involved in the theater in the
Cirebon region who supports himself entirely by his work as a
performing artist; most of the members of his gamelan, for example,
are rice farmers or motorcycle-taxi drivers, who put in a full day
of work that begins a few hours after the end of the performance.
</P>
<P>
   The producer of the video, John McGlynn, who has lived in
Indonesia for 24 years and is a founder and director of the Lontar
Foundation, also blames the decline of the wayang cepak on the
island's inexorable urbanization. ``The theater is village-based,
and while its magic remains strong, the audience is dwindling,'' he
said. ``How do you keep the kids in the village after they've seen
the city lights? For young people who are working long hours in
sweatshops, malls and factories, discos, drugs and electronic
arcades provide a more visceral relief than does a slow-paced
wayang performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the competition comes from glamorous outside sources.
New forms of entertainment are developing in Java using traditional
idioms. Cohen, the American scholar, said the latest craze in
Cirebon is something called the organ tunggal, in which a
singer-dancer performs traditionally flavored numbers to the loud
accompaniment of a keyboard synthesizer _ rural Java's answer to
the lounge singer. Cohen said that enthusiasts of this new
entertainment sometimes become frenzied, and that fights break out.
</P>
<P>
   When Warsad's performance began, almost everyone in the village
turned out to see the dance and the beginning of the show, but an
hour or two later, most of the members of the audience were old
men. The young people had drifted to an impromptu gathering 100
yards down the lane. (It is only fair to point out, though, that a
cepak performance without a ritual connection _ a drama staged
simply to be videotaped by foreign scholars _ is perhaps something
that the people of Gadingan would not find compelling.)
</P>
<P>
   Warsad seemed undaunted. ``Two of my great-grandfathers were
dalangs,'' he said, ``but the intervening two generations were not.
I was urged by the people in the community to take up the wayang
cepak. It was considered a good thing to preserve the traditions of
our ancestors.''
</P>
<P>
   You won't hear him talking about the decline of the art: he is
too busy teaching the repertory to one of his sons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2134EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
