<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4004 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-DUKE-BATTIER-HNS &LR;      03-21 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-BATTIER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Chris Kennedy is an associate athletic director in charge of
academic counseling for Duke athletes. When new student-athletes
come to Duke, Kennedy meets with them to make sure they are on the
right scholastic path at the prestigious university.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took only one day for Kennedy to realize he didn't have to
worry about Shane Battier.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy went home that night and received the typical, ``How was
your day?'' question from his wife, Ana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good,'' Kennedy said. ``I just met a kid who is going
to be the president someday.''
</P>
<P>
   Battier is an impressive young man, whether he's leading the
Blue Devils to the Sweet 16, discussing the tenets of Buddhism (he
is a religion major) or giving his theories on the American
political process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane is an exceptional person,'' said Duke coach Mike
Krzyzewski. ``He has a dynamic personality, and he is very
disciplined. Once he sets his mind to accomplish something, he
devises a plan to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Battier, a 6-8 junior forward, made a plan before this season
began to help the top-ranked Blue Devils stay among the elite teams
in the nation, despite their losing four key players from last
season's team that lost to Connecticut in the NCAA championship
game. The plan appears to be working, because top-seeded Duke will
play Florida on Friday in the East Regional semifinals at Syracuse,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The key element to Battier's plan was to make himself more of an
offensive threat, which he has done this season by averaging 17.3
points per game. That's something the team didn't need from him
when it had offensive stars like Elton Brand and Trajan Langdon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sad to see them go,'' Battier said. ``But at the same
time, I saw it as an opportunity to step out of my role-player
shadow. There really wasn't any epiphany. I just started to realize
I was as good as any of the guys in this program. That's why I came
to Duke _ to be a premier player.''
</P>
<P>
   Battier (pronounced BAT-tee-ay) also came to Duke because he
knew it would help him prepare for his future after basketball.
Some people have compared him to Bill Bradley, a former NBA star
and New Jersey senator whom Battier idolizes. Battier was
disappointed when Bradley dropped out of the presidential race
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great role model for me,'' Battier said. ``I've tried
to read as much about him as I could. Even when he was in high
school, you could tell he was destined for bigger things than
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has noticed the same thing in Battier. Bradley wrote
Battier a letter last spring, asking Battier if he would work for
Bradley on the campaign trail during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about it,'' Battier said. ``But with everything I
was doing, it was going to take up too much of my time, and I
wouldn't be able to work on basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could have done it. As a politician, Sen. Bradley has
tried to get the pulse of the American public, and he's the first
person in a long time that really has tried to tap into that pulse.
As a basketball player, he was very cerebral. He made himself a
great individual player by being the best team player he could
be.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of Battier. He has made a point this
season of helping two freshman starters _ center Carlos Boozer and
point guard Jason Williams _ and two other freshmen who contribute
off the bench _ guard Mike Dunleavy Jr. and center Nick Horvath.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn things just being around Shane,'' Horvath said.
``You learn from all your teammates, but Shane is special because
of the way he carries himself and his maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   Battier has stood out from the crowd for a long time, and it
wasn't because he was taller than everyone else. He grew up in
suburban Detroit and attended Country Day private school, making a
perfect score on the entrance exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew early on that Shane was advanced,'' said Ed Battier,
Shane's father. ``But I don't think we did anything extra for him.
He always has surprised us.''
</P>
<P>
   One big surprise came last summer in Chicago while Shane was
working in the marketing department for McDonald's. He chose that
job over traveling with Bradley because it gave him more time to
practice basketball. His parents agreed, but they were stunned one
night when they saw him on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flipping channels, and there was Shane on WGN,'' Ed
Battier said. ``He was part of a panel discussion with Bill
Bradley, Phil Jackson and Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   Battier admits he would love to follow Bradley's path _ Rhodes
scholar, NBA career, politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see myself in politics,'' Battier said. ``I think it
would be great to represent the people, but I think I have a very
idealistic view of government at this point. Hopefully, that won't
be corrupted. I really have no idea where life is going to take
me.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, he hopes it takes him to a national championship, which
is four victories away. If Battier plays the way he did in a
victory over Kansas on Sunday, he might get his wish. Battier had a
career-high eight blocks, along with 21 points and eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane Battier may be the most alert and aware defensive player
I've ever seen,'' said Kansas coach Roy Williams. ``And he can
guard any player, no matter what size that player is.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Basketball Coaches named Battier the
Defensive Player of the Year last season, an award he likely will
earn again this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane is an amazing help-side defensive player,'' Krzyzewski
said. ``He moves as the ball moves, which enables him to make great
defensive plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Great defensive players have to constantly think ahead, which
Battier says sometimes can be a negative for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my biggest fault is I don't take enough time to enjoy
the moment,'' Battier said. ``I'm always looking toward the next
day rather than watching the sunset. I have a lot of plans for my
future, but if we win the championship, I'm going to sit back and
enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
