A4005 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-SOUTH-UNC22-COX     03-21 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-UNC22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carolina's Cota wants reason to smile
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ed Cota smiles. People have seen it. Though he
can win a staredown with Mount Rushmore, he's been known, on
occasion and with proper inducement, to crack one.
</P>
<P>
   When his North Carolina Tar Heels came back from a double-digit
deficit at home against Duke to nearly steal the basketball game,
there was Cota, placid as can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He acts like that was expected,'' said teammate Kris Lang, the
talkative sophomore forward. ``Even if we win the national
championship, he might not crack a smile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely right,'' Cota said when told of Lang's
comments. ``That's the expectation I have of the team. I'm happy
for our freshmen and sophomores, who haven't been to a Final Four,
but I want to win the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy, but I'm not happy. That comes from being there
before. My freshman year I might have been jumping for joy.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Cota started at point guard for the Tar Heels, leading a
group that also had Antawn Jamison and NBA wunderkind Vince Carter
to the Final Four, where the Heels lost to Arizona in the
semifinals. The 6-foot-2-inch, 200-pounder from Brooklyn earned ACC
rookie-of-the-year honors that year and followed it with
second-team All-ACC honors his sophomore and junior years.
</P>
<P>
   Cota's senior season started on a down note when he and teammate
Terrence Newby were among four people charged with assault stemming
from an on-campus altercation following a Halloween party. The
trial date was delayed late last month, and the charge remains
pending.
</P>
<P>
   As the Heels stumbled to an 18-12 regular-season record and lost
in the first round of the ACC tournament to Wake Forest, they were
the focus of unbridled criticism by fans and media used to winning
and winning big. Cota was a frequent target, with critics
questioning his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pay any attention to that,'' Cota said. ``I knew I was
doing a good job. Before the season everybody was hyping me up.
When things went bad, I had to take the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest criticism was that I wasn't a leader and Coach
(Bill) Guthridge was a good coach. That comes with a tough season.
People have to point fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he's a great leader,'' Lang said of Cota.
``Everybody else does, too. Just because he's not vocal, doesn't
show a lot of emotion on his face, doesn't mean he's not a great
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Shooting guard Joseph Forte arrived on campus this year with
startling offensive skills but some uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed was a big influence on me,'' Forte said. ``He was always
talking with me, saying, `Joe, slow down. Joe, they're looking for
you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Forte, though, couldn't get him to say much more: ``My big thing
when I came here was that I wanted to MAKE him talk to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cota finished the season strongly, notching double digits in
assists in three of the last five games. With 10 against Missouri
in a first-round South subregional game in Birmingham, Ala., on
Friday and seven in the second-round win over top-seeded Stanford
on Sunday, Cota pushed his career total to 1,010, making him only
the third NCAA Division I-A player to have more than 1,000. Bobby
Hurley of Duke and Chris Corchionne of North Carolina State are the
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen anyone as accurate and creative as Cota,'' Wake
Forest Coach Dave Odom told The Charlotte Observer in early March.
``In terms of creativity, this kid stands alone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be there in good times and bad,'' Cota said. ``I
did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
