<HEADER>
A4011 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-TIGER-BOY-HNS &LR;      03-21 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIGER-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY WHO HAD ARM RIPPED OFF BY TIGER ON RIGHT PATH TO RECOVERY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ark.) 
 
By LISA TEACHEY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Jayton Tidwell, the 4-year-old Arkansas boy whose arm
was surgically reattached after being ripped off by a pet tiger,
has passed the second hurdle in his recovery, staving off possible
life-threatening infections, doctors said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   His surgical team at Memorial Hermann Children's Hospital now
speculates the boy's arm may have been severed by the tiger's paw.
Initially, they thought the 400-pound tiger had bitten the boy
after the child stuck his arm in its cage last Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jayton's doing fantastic right now,'' said Dr. Mark Henry, one
of the doctor's who performed the procedure last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the limb on to stay on? Yes it is,'' Henry said. ``Is the
limb on without infection? Yes it is. His arm is on and it's going
to be staying on.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Jayton may need further surgeries to improve muscle
function and the appearance of his arm, Henry said, this injury
should not be a long-term handicap for the child.
</P>
<P>
   The boy passed the first milestone within hours of the
reattachment surgery when blood circulation was restored to his
severed arm.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday Jayton remained on a ventilator because his vocal
chords and throat were swollen. But he was awake.
</P>
<P>
   Jayton's right arm remains in a splint and he has no movement or
sensation in it, Henry said. Over the next six months the nerves
should begin growing and then doctors will be able to determine if
the level of function in the arm is acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   If not, another surgery will be performed where muscles from his
legs will be transplanted to his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Henry said the child could be functioning normally in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``His final reconstructive results should enable him to go out
and to participate in any activity whether it's artistic or
athletic or otherwise,'' Henry said. ``The exact way in which he
carries out that participation will undoubtedly not be exactly the
same as his peers. But he should not be excluded from anything
based on this injury.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure exactly how Jayton was injured. Jayton, who lives
in Arkansas, was spending spring break with his father in Brazoria
County. The accident happened when they went to visit relatives in
the Channelview area to see the tiger Jayton's uncle, Larry
Tidwell, had caged in his back yard.
</P>
<P>
   While the family gathered for pictures in the living room,
Jayton apparently slipped outside and stuck his hand in the tiger's
cage.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County regulations do not prohibit ownership of wild pets
as long as the cage has a permit from the county. Larry Tidwell's
tiger cage did not, and he was fined $500 for the misdemeanor
violation and ordered to make minor changes to the cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our suspicion that in review that the arm was probably
not bitten off. But it was probably swatted off with a single
stroke of the paw,'' Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County, which includes most of Houston, has 3.2 million
people and is the largest county in Texas. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; There were no clearly identifiable teeth marks where the limb
was severed so it was hard to tell exactly what happened, Henry
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the accident, Harris County Commissioners Court
asked the county attorney's office and the Animal Control Division
Tuesday to review the county's 2-year-old exotic animal guidelines
in an attempt to ban all exotic animals within 1,000 feet of a
residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe we ought to get them out of residential areas,''
County Judge Robert Eckels said after Tuesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Eckels said he expects the county's animal control director,
Dawn Blackmar, and Assistant County Attorney Roberta Lloyd, to
return to Commissioners Court in about a month with recommendations
on how to strengthen the exotic animal guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Henry estimated Jayton's medical expenses, including
rehabilitation, could exceed $500,000. Henry said he would treat
the child without pay but did not know if other doctors and
therapists would.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The family has set up two funds to cover the medical costs.
</P>
<P>
   The first is at a local bank: Jayton Tidwell Fund c/o Southwest
Bank of Texas, P.O. Box 27459, Houston, 77027-27549, account number
0003142175.
</P>
<P>
   The other is in Arkansas: Jayton Medical Fund c/o First Arkansas
Bank, 1804 N. First, Jacksonville, Ark., 72076
</P>
