<SLUG> BC-DESGRIPPES-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: IMAGE FIRM CREATING NEW IDENTITY FOR ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: in references to d/g(ASTERISK), please replace (ASTERISK)
with the typographical symbol, no parentheses)  
(bl) 
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A low-profile international design and image firm,
Desgrippes Gobe &AMP; Associates, which has high-profile clients like
Air France, Coca-Cola and The Limited, is creating a new identity
for a client it has known forever: itself.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old, 165-person agency, which had $25 million in
revenue last year, will be renamed d/g(ASTERISK) (the asterisk
represents a star) effective April 4 as part of a campaign to
heighten awareness of the agency's services.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has headquarters in Paris and New York and
offices in Brussels, Tokyo and Seoul, South Korea, has also created
a logo made up of four symbols that represent its disciplines: a
star represents its marketing and design expertise; a bull's eye
with the letter ``C'' at the center represents the firm's
consulting practice; a building represents its architectural
expertise; and an eye represents its interactive capabilities. The
campaign also includes a redesigned Web site at www.dga.com.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Gobe, president of the New York office, said Desgrippes
Gobe had decided to rename itself because it found that although
its original name ``reflected the identity of the founding
designers, it was not always easy to pronounce or remember.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It also failed to communicate our evolution into an
international organization and our capabilities,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Central to d/g(ASTERISK)'s work is its concept of emotional
branding, which involves analyzing the visual and emotional
responses a good or service generates. For a brand to be
successful, it believes an emotional bond must be developed between
the buyer and the product. The agency uses its research to develop
strategies that clarify or solidify the images of its clients'
brands, which strengthen that bond.
</P>
<P>
   Companies whose brands d/g(ASTERISK) has helped revamp include
Brooks Brothers, Reebok, Intimate Brands' Victoria's Secret and
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch. Ann Taylor hired the agency to design its
flagship store in Manhattan; among d/g(ASTERISK)'s innovations were
a dressing room fitted with business equipment and a central
staircase in the front of the store, designed to create a home-like
feeling. In addition, d/g(ASTERISK) has done more traditional image
consulting for companies like Coca-Cola. During the Atlanta
Olympics, it designed a can for Coke that featured the word
``always'' in five languages.
</P>
<P>
   One of the agency's newest image consulting clients is Ohio
State University, for which it is developing a vision for a
university of the future. And it is coming up with a new identity
for Air France, involving aircraft interiors, uniforms and redesign
of the airline's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Branding is also central to d/g(ASTERISK)'s interactive
strategy. Gobe, for one, expects the Internet-driven economy
ultimately will be driven by brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers will be empowered to make their own decisions, set
their own price, design their own product,'' he said. ``They'll be
able to create or break the reputation of a company, through chat
rooms, in just five minutes. Word of mouth will become global, not
local.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, there was a delay between the introduction of a
product and consumers' response to it,'' Gobe added. ``Now
companies will get immediate feedback.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Levine, who heads up the agency's consulting practice,
said the four main elements of traditional offline retailing today
are entertainment, information, personal service and ease; he
suggested all four will ultimately have to be ``reconfigured and
translated for the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   When this occurs, he predicted ``bricks-and-mortar retailers
will have to raise the bar as well, to make the live shopping
experience more special.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency's branding theories, particularly as they apply to
the Internet, generally won the support of Clive Chajet, a New
York-based consultant who was once chairman of Lippincott &AMP;
Margulies, a leading brand and corporate identity firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the future on the Internet belongs to
established, recognized brands because the transaction between the
seller and buyer will be direct,'' he said. ``There will be no
sales person telling you how wonderful the product is. So all
products will have to be presold. Brands will be known and
understood for what they offer.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Jim Nail, a senior analyst at Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass., questioned d/g(ASTERISK)'s emphasis on emotions
in e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, brands on the Web are all about how quick and easy it
is for a consumer to find what he's looking for; d/g(ASTERISK) is
going about it backward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offline, you can't deliver an experience to someone until they
walk through the door of your store,'' he added. ``Emotional
branding is used to try to draw people to the store in expectation
of delivery of the brand's promise. But online, the delivery of
that promise is one click away. So the emphasis has to be on
delivering that satisfying experience first. Out of that experience
comes the emotional connection to the brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Chajet questioned d/g(ASTERISK)'s decision to change its name to
initials, eliminating the names of its two founders. ``Adopting
initials as a corporate name is a passport to anonymity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roger van den Bergh, a New York-based designer specializing in
corporate and brand identity, also called this move risky because
``in their 29 years in business, everyone knows them as Desgrippes
Gobe. I'm not sure this will help their long-term name
recognition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
