<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S LEFT FOR LAKERS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A season chock full of highs and notably short on
lows has left the Los Angeles Lakers to once again manufacture
challenges for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They returned home Tuesday having gone 4-1 on their last
significant road trip of the season; having won 22 of their past 23
games; having beaten two of the top teams in the East (New York,
Miami); and having improved their record on the second night of
back-to-backs to 19-1.
</P>
<P>
   With their sights firmly set on the NBA Finals, the Lakers also
improved to 4-1 against the East's top three teams _ the Pacers,
Knicks and Heat.
</P>
<P>
   What to do for an encore? With 14 games left, the Lakers realize
finding new challenges is an ongoing effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be,'' Rick Fox said. ``You know, at certain times
this year we've been our (own) biggest challenge, and we've
responded to it. Outside of the Washington game, I can't see an
opportunity where we let ourselves down. We go home, and no more
big road trips to be challenged with, but a couple teams we're
going to have to beat to go anywhere in this league out of the
West.''
</P>
<P>
   The schedule is relatively friendly, with eight home games and
six on the road. But 10 of the 14 opponents are playoff-bound, and
the Lakers will find a few more statement games.
</P>
<P>
   They have road dates at Sacramento and San Antonio _ two places
they haven't won this season, against their potential first and
second-round opponents. They'll also play host to the Knicks, their
possible Finals opponent, and try for the season sweep.
</P>
<P>
   They also have a pair of games against Phoenix and one each
against Seattle and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   If form holds, the Lakers (56-12) will finish with 67 or 68
wins, which would be second best in franchise history, behind only
the 69-13 record posted by the 1971-72 team that won the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The goal now, Fox said, is ``re-establishment of our strength
and our play of the whole season, re-establishing that with the
rest of the season here, the remaining teams that we'll face will
be playoff teams in a lot of cases, and setting a tone that we want
to be playing even better ball than we've been playing going into
the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Amplified: The Lakers got their first experience with the NBA's
use of boom microphones near the bench Sunday in New York. Coach
Phil Jackson is still opposed to the idea _ and at times had
assistant Jim Cleamons shoo away the mike man _ but generally felt
``it went all right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an intrusion, there's no doubt about it,'' Jackson
said. ``We didn't talk as much as perhaps we would have talked if
we had the freedom. A lot of stuff I write out on the (dry-erase)
boards anyway, so I just pointed to it and said, `We're going to
run that the next time down.' ... So the guys got the idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
