<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOISE-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLD THE PHONE. BETTER YET, BLOW IT TO SMITHEREENS.  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The season's final performance of Strauss's
``Rosenkavalier'' at the Metropolitan Opera last month was one of
those inspired evenings when everything goes beautifully for
reasons no one can explain. The principals sang splendidly: Susan
Graham as Octavian, Heidi Grant Murphy as Sophie, and Renee
Fleming, who brought her poignant voice and subtle intensity to the
role of the Marschallin.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the last scene, came the almost inevitable disruption:
a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Ms. Fleming began the sublime opening melody of the
great final trio; just as, comforted by the shimmering sound of the
orchestra, she floated her voice to a soft high B flat on the word
``lieb'' (``beloved''); just as she was taking listeners to a
transcendent place that was, in fact, painfully deep within each of
us, a cell phone belonging to someone in a pricey seat rang. In an
instant, the intrusive jangle dragged us right back to reality:
another winter's night in New York, where oblivious people go to
the opera. Soon we would have to deal with slush and subways,
arrive home and think about the next day's work.
</P>
<P>
   From what seemed the darting of her eyes, Ms. Fleming heard that
jarring sustained ring. If she had stopped singing, signaled James
Levine in the orchestra pit to halt the performance and asked the
owner of that phone to take the call in the lobby, most of us would
have applauded. Instead, she redoubled her concentration and kept
on singing, gloriously.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often, a critic feels compelled to write a crabby
column about the rudeness of audience members. Such columns seldom
do much good, but at least the critic feels better. The traditional
disruptions, like coughing, will always be with us. But although
colds afflict us all, the kind of unabashed hacking that you hear
from people who don't even seem to be trying to control themselves
has to be a passive-aggressive expression of boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Some irritants are particularly exasperating because they are so
preventable. Why would a woman choose to adorn her wrist with a
clinking set of bracelets when she goes to the opera, so that every
time she fidgets in her seat or tinkers with her Met Titles she
becomes a human wind chime?
</P>
<P>
   Crinkling plastic bags drive me nuts. People, presumably music
lovers, show up fresh from shopping and settle into their seats
with plastic bags full of goodies, often CDs. They place the bags
on their laps and blithely lay their hands on top of them.
</P>
<P>
   Don't they hear the rustling that results every time they shift
positions? If some day one of you bag clingers is seated near Row L
at the Met and a tall guy with thinning brown hair approaches
before the opera to ask that you please place your plastic bag
beneath your seat, it's me.
</P>
<P>
   The cell phone represents a new level of intrusiveness. So far
this season, it has been the rare concert or opera I've attended
during which at least one didn't ring. Two went off, a few rings
each, during the soprano Barbara Bonney's lovely recital at Alice
Tully Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Last season at Carnegie Hall, as the tenor Ian Bostridge sang
Britten's Serenade for Tenor, Horn and Strings with Neville
Marriner and the Academy of St. Martin-in-the-Fields, a cell phone
rang forth playing the first notes of Mozart's G minor Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   I think the reason people forget to turn the things off (and you
can only assume that no one leaves them on intentionally) is that
we are getting hooked on feeling reachable at all times, in case
something comes along that might be a tiny bit more interesting
than whatever we are doing just now.
</P>
<P>
   Every day you see more and more people on the street having cell
phone chats as they walk. So much for just strolling, for being
silently present amid the vibrant urban busyness.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any place to detach ourselves from the electronic
network we are wired into, to take an exit from the information
superhighway, it's the opera house and the concert hall. There, for
a few precious hours, you can leave the rest of your life on the
other side of the closed lobby door and enjoy the natural sound of
great live music.
</P>
<P>
   You know that a problem has become pervasive when television
commercials start poking fun at it. A new one depicts a
chesty-voiced Brunnhilde in helmet and breastplate who, outraged by
the interruption of a cell phone, stops singing and heaves her
spear at the offender, zapping his phone to bits. In the next
scene, another operagoer has a new two-way pager with a silent
keypad, which allows him to ``stay in touch without disturbing
anyone.'' The depressing assumption behind the pitch is that
staying in touch while attending the opera is a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   What is to be done? The last two times I attended concerts at
Alice Tully Hall, an official appeared onstage before the
performance to remind us to turn off beepers and cell phones. Both
times, the announcement was greeted with supportive applause. Both
times, cell phones went off, each time during the second half of
the concert, suggesting that the owners had used their phones
during intermission and forgotten to turn them off again.
</P>
<P>
   What next? Metal detectors? A rule requiring cell phones to be
checked in the lobby? A vigilant Brunnhilde at every event with her
spear readied for ambush? I say, whatever it takes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0378 </DOCNO>
