<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-1STLDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTORNEYS TO APPEAL JUDGE'S RULING IN CUBAN BOY'S CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (sub for minor editing) 
 
By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attorneys for 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez filed a notice of appeal
hours after a Miami federal judge Tuesday paved the way for the boy
to be reunited with his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   A quick, two-line notice of appeal was filed late Tuesday with
the 11th U.S. Circuit of Appeals Court, said Linda Osberg-Braun, an
attorney for the Miami family.
</P>
<P>
   She said the appeal was filed to stop U.S. immigration officials
from taking the boy from his great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, with
whom the boy has been living since his rescue off the coast of Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., four months ago. Elian was found floating on an
inner-tube on Thanksgiving Day after an ill-fated boat journey from
Cuba that took his mother's life. Elian was among three survivors
on a boat that capsized
</P>
<P>
   ``We're communicating with the (U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service) directly, and we're very hopeful that they
will respect Elian's appeal rights,'' Osberg-Braun said. ``They
have not confirmed one way or another what they intend to do or
will intend to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling Tuesday, U.S. District Judge K. Michael Moore
upheld a decision by INS Commissioner Doris Meissner to return
Elian to his father, Juan Gonzalez. Moore ruled that only the U.S.
attorney general can grant political asylum to keep the boy in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the boy's Miami family had argued that the federal
agency had unjustly denied Elian his right to apply for political
asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased that the court has sustained our judgment that
Elian should be reunited with his father. The court's decision
reaffirms our position that only Elian's father can speak for his
son on federal immigration matters,'' U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   How or when the reunification takes place, however, remains
unclear. When pressed, Reno would say only that federal authorities
will move promptly to return the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say what will happen, except that we're going to
review the matter with the U.S. attorney's office, with the Miami
office of immigration and naturalization and with every one here to
plan how we may orderly achieve this reunification in an orderly
way,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department and INS officials declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to play this out publicly. We're just not,''
said Carole Florman, Justice Department spokeswoman. ``These are
not details that we feel ought to be shared with the general public
at this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ruling was the latest turn in a four-month political
and international tug-of-war between Elian's family in Cuba and his
relatives in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Cuban-exile community has rallied around Elian, lifting
him as a symbol of hard-fought freedom, whose mother died in a
desperate attempt to provide a better life for her son in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, President Fidel Castro has organized massive
demonstrations demanding the boy's return.
</P>
<P>
   Though Elian's supporters in Miami have questioned the sincerity
of his father's claims in light of his refusal to come to the
United to retrieve the boy, Gonzalez has called the boy almost
daily from Cuba, where he works at a resort hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Gonzalez has derailed attempts by family members in
Miami to seek political asylum for the boy by demanding that those
applications be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   The INS decision to return the boy was based on two interviews
by an INS officer with Juan Gonzalez in December. As a result of
the meetings, the INS determined that Gonzalez was a fit father who
had maintained a relationship with his son after his separation
from the boy's mother.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing his ruling, Moore said Elian's great uncle Lazaro had
the right to seek legal action on the boy's behalf and that the
court had limited jurisdiction in the case. He also stated that
Elian's attorneys could proceed with the lawsuit to determine if
the INS violated the boy's right to due process.
</P>
<P>
   A state court hearing to determine custody for the boy is
pending. On Jan. 10, a Florida state court granted Lazaro Gonzalez
limited legal authority.
</P>
<P>
   Osberg-Braun said the state court remains an option, but hopes
the appeal negates the need to go that route.
</P>
<P>
   However, George Martinez, a federal law expert and law professor
at Southern Methodist University in Dallas, said Elian's attorneys
no longer have the option of a state court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal law is supreme and a state court cannot contradict a
federal court on that issue,'' Martinez said. ``The state court
should be pre-empted by the federal court decision.''
</P>
<P>
   For supporters of Elian's family in Cuba, news of the ruling
came as a relief.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Edgar, general secretary of the National Council of the
Churches of Christ in the USA, a New York-based group that has been
working with Elian's family in Cuba, said he was ``delighted, but
not surprised'' by the judge's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only wish it had come sooner. Elian should have been home
before Christmas,'' he said. ``If a parent is loving, caring and
not abusive, a child should be with his or her parent, and Juan
Miguel Gonzalez is a loving father.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush issued a short
statement from his campaign headquarters in Austin, Texas, saying
the true wishes of Elian's father are still unclear. The elder
Gonzalez should be allowed to come to the United States to speak
his mind, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I urge Attorney General Janet Reno to reconsider her plans to
send Elian back to Cuba, back to the place his mother died trying
to escape,'' the Texas governor said. ``This case should be decided
by a Florida family court, which will protect the best interests of
Elian, not by a Clinton-Gore Justice Department whose record of
putting politics ahead of the law does not inspire confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign stop in New York City, Vice President Al Gore, the
expected Democratic presidential nominee, said, ``I think that what
we still need is a full and fair court hearing based on due process
where all parties can present the facts.``
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that the ``father is not free to speak his true
mind,'' and said ``This child should never have been put in a
position where the choice was between freedom or his father ...The
real fault here lies with Fidel Castro.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
