<SLUG> BC-CONDOMS-MEDICINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PRODUCTS, INCLUDING CONDOMS, TO GET STATE TAX BREAK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The 39-year-old state sales tax on
nonprescription drugs will become extinct Saturday, a change that
could save Texas shoppers an estimated $161 million a year when
they buy items such as cough syrup, aspirin, vitamins _ and
condoms.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that condoms are on the list of soon-to-be exempt items
was rekindling debate over birth control and whether the state
should promote it.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservatives lamented the fact that lawmakers who voted
last year to end the 6.25-percent sales tax on over-the-counter
medications used such broad criteria that _ inadvertently or not _
they exempted condoms from the levy.
</P>
<P>
   One group, the Texas Eagle Forum, claimed the exemption will
foster promiscuity. But proponents of family planning were hailing
the arrival of tax-free condoms, citing their role in preventing
sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential candidate who
has said that abstinence should be promoted to teen-agers, proposed
the tax break during his re-election campaign in 1998 and didn't
want it to cover condoms, said his spokeswoman, Linda Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   State tax collectors said they will have no choice but to extend
the exemption to prophylactics beginning Saturday because the 1999
law applies to all 100,000 nonprescription products that carry a
``National Drug Code,'' or NDC, issued by the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The exemption was contained in the same tax-break legislation
that granted consumers a sales tax holiday on clothing last summer.
As originally proposed by Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, Senate Bill
441 would have exempted only children's nonprescription medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, signed into law by Bush, was expanded to include adult
over-the-counter medicines during negotiations with the Texas
House. The change that extended the exemption to adult medicines
was proposed by Rep. Brian McCall, R-Plano.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just said `over-the-counter medications,''' McCall said
Tuesday, denying there was any orchestrated move to promote
condoms. He said it was ``never contemplated, in any legislative
discussions that I was part of, that condoms would or would not be
part of the definition.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to other lawmakers said there were discussions about
whether to specify which drugs or products the exemption should
cover, but for simplicity the lawmakers decided to use the FDA
coding system. At the time, supporters said the codes would at
least preclude tax breaks for herbal and folk remedies that were
not sanctioned by the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   As approved, the exemption will apply to a wide range of items,
including allergy treatments, cold remedies, dandruff products,
medicated dental products, eye-care products, sedatives, sunburn
remedies, antacids, laxatives and wound-care dressings. But as an
example of how precise the FDA codes are, the exemption applies to
antiperspirants but not regular deodorant.
</P>
<P>
   The April 1 effective date for the exemption was set later than
other tax breaks in the same legislation in order to delay its
negative fiscal impact.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
