<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4024 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-MIAMI-HNS &LR;      03-21 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIAMI-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
At some point, nearly every college basketball team has to go
through a rebuilding process. For Leonard Hamilton and the
University of Miami, it went a little deeper. The program had to be
resuscitated.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hurricanes dropped basketball in 1971 because of dwindling
attendance and mounting financial losses. There was no team until
1985, when the program was revived.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1998, the Hurricanes had played a grand total of one NCAA
Tournament game, losing to Western Kentucky in 1960. That pre-dated
even the brief golden era of Rick Barry, who led the 1962-65 Miami
teams to a 65-16 record. Because of probation resulting from
recruiting violations, Barry's teams were shut out of the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But 35 years after Barry, Hamilton and the Hurricanes are
putting Miami on the basketball map again. Long perceived as merely
a football school, Miami beat Arkansas and Ohio State last week to
advance to the Sweet 16 for the first time in school history. The
Hurricanes will play Tulsa on Friday night at the South Regional in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, we are swimming in uncharted waters, and it feels
kind of good,'' said Hamilton. ``Each time we win a game, each time
we take a step forward, we are making history for our program.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton came to Miami from Oklahoma State in 1990, a curious
career choice that has worked out for the best. He left a solid
program in what was then the Big Eight for Miami, which was about
to enter the rugged Big East.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Foster got the program off the deck from 1985-90,
compiling a respectable 78-71 record while the Hurricanes played as
an independent. When Hamilton arrived in 1990, he knew that going
to the Big East in 1991 meant things were going to get worse before
they got better.
</P>
<P>
   In his first four seasons, the Hurricanes were 34-80 overall. In
the first three seasons in the Big East, they went 1-17, 7-11 and
0-18. Moreover, no one seemed to notice. Playing off-campus at
Miami Arena, the Hurricanes averaged about 3,000 fans per game
during Hamilton's first four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   There were times, certainly, when Hamilton wondered why he had
come to a football-oriented university to play losing basketball in
front of scant crowds. To his credit, Hamilton not only stayed with
the program, he turned it into one of the more impressive success
stories in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to try not to reinvent the wheel,'' said Hamilton.
``I talked to a lot of other coaches who were successful to try to
figure out how they got their programs to that point. I feel we've
made a lot of progress each year, but I feel we still have a long
way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing about the job at Miami is that each and every
day, you feel there's something you can do to make the program
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami has improved steadily since the 0-18 Big East disaster in
1993-94. The Hurricanes went 13-3 and shared the regular-season
conference title this season. Over the last two years, they are
28-6 in the conference, the best in the Big East. Over the last
four years, the record is 48-22, second-best in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes have gone further in the NCAA Tournament this
year (they were eliminated by Purdue in the second round last year)
despite the loss of All-America forward Tim James, a first-round
draft pick of the Miami Heat in 1999. The Sweet 16-bound Hurricanes
are led by three seniors _ center Mario Bland and guards Johnny
Hemsley and Vernon Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   Hemsley is a cool 3-point shooter (9-of-19 in the first two
games of the NCAAs) and the team's leading scorer at 18.3 points
per game, while Jennings is a point guard who averages nearly seven
assists. At 6-6 and 265 pounds, Bland is a cement block in the
middle of the lane.
</P>
<P>
   Since the trio came to Miami in 1996, the Hurricanes are 80-40
and have been to the NCAA Tournament three straight seasons. They
have played a big part in building Miami's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came in as a freshman, it was known as a football
school, no question,'' said Bland, who is from Jackson, Miss. ``We
were out to change that. It took some time, but we're getting
there. I'm not saying how far we can go, but if we play good
defense and execute on offense, we can win a few more.''
</P>
<P>
   That would put the Hurricanes in the Final Four, which would
certainly validate the program and perhaps even draw some fans in
Miami. Despite playing solid basketball the last few seasons, the
Hurricanes averaged only 3,995 at home this year. At the first two
rounds of the NCAA Tournament last weekend, only about 500 Miami
fans made the trip to Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   The home crowds could increase if a proposed on-campus arena is
built, but the Hurricanes understand it's an uphill battle getting
attention for basketball at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt all along we could be a good basketball team, but
we've been reminded all along the way we believe more in ourselves
than the general public,'' said Hamilton. ``So we're constantly
feeling like we have to overcome another challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always appear to be the underdogs. There are just things
that keep you motivated all the time. We want to see how high we
can go.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Hurricanes have raised the national awareness of
their program _ for better or worse. As Jennings said after
Sunday's win, it's doubtful many bracketologists predicted Miami
would beat Ohio State in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We messed up a lot of people's brackets,'' Jennings said. ``I
think only Miami fans had us penciled in this far. We made a lot of
people upset instead of getting ourselves upset.''
</P>
<P>
