<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fed Raises Interest Rates in Effort to Slow Economy
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve clamped down a bit more on the economy,
raising interest rates by a quarter-point in an effort to prevent
an outbreak of inflation. It was the Fed's fifth quarter-point rate
increase since June. The move was no surprise to economists and
investors, who had heard repeated hints over the last month from
Alan Greenspan, the central bank's chairman, that he intended to
stick to his policy of raising rates in small, steady steps until
the economy slows.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market shrugged off the news and moved higher. The Dow
Jones industrial average gained 227.10 points, to 10,907.34. The
Nasdaq composite index rose 101.68 points, to 4,711.68. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed 37.24 points, to
1,493.87.
</P>
<P>
   Profit Rises 67 Percent at Goldman Sachs
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs Group reported that a surge in revenue from
trading stocks, bonds, oil and other commodities pushed its fiscal
first-quarter net income up 67 percent, easily surpassing analysts'
expectations. The earnings were $887 million, compared with $532
million in the period a year earlier, when the firm was still a
private partnership. Investors bid up the shares to $118.25, a gain
of $4.8125.
</P>
<P>
   White House Loses Tobacco Ruling
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court dealt a sharp blow to the Clinton
administration's efforts to curb smoking, ruling 5-4 that the Food
and Drug Administration had never received authority from Congress
to regulate tobacco products. The decision hands the question of
national tobacco regulation back to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   January Trade Deficit Hit Record
</P>
<P>
   Swollen by a huge bill for foreign oil and a voracious spending
spree by prosperous consumers, the nation's trade deficit jumped to
a record $28 billion in January.
</P>
<P>
   Auto Business for Minorities Formed
</P>
<P>
   Roy Roberts, a former General Motors executive, announced that
he had formed M-Xchange.com, an Internet company intended to make
it easier for the largest American companies to buy parts and
supplies from minority-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
   No Resume Truths Are Self-Evident
</P>
<P>
   In today's tight job market, a lot of companies risk hiring
disasters when they fail to verify information that job seekers
submit. Even recruiters of senior-level managers confess that the
frantic competition for talent can blind them to danger signs.
</P>
<P>
   BASF to Buy American Home Unit
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products agreed to sell its struggling
agricultural business to BASF, the German chemicals giant, for $3.8
billion in cash _ a move that added to speculation that the drug
company will try again to find a corporate mate. But John Stafford,
the chief executive of American Home Products, said the company,
which has failed to complete three proposed mergers in the last two
years, was not looking for another partner.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration announced that Rezulin, a
diabetes drug linked to liver failure, would be removed from the
market immediately. The drug is made by Parke-Davis, a division of
Warner-Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee, Tea, but No Protein?
</P>
<P>
   The spectacularly popular high-protein, low-carbohydrates diet
has not caught up with the airlines' food services yet, leaving
some passengers munching on cereal instead of eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Sale of Stake in Mitsubishi Seen
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler is in the final stage of talks with Mitsubishi
about acquiring 33.4 percent of the Japanese automaker, and an
announcement could come by the end of this week, executives close
to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Unions Call for Rover Protests
</P>
<P>
   British labor unions called for a huge demonstration on April 1
to protest the thousands of job losses expected from the BMW sale
of the money-losing Rover Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
