<HEADLINE>
GORE SLAMS BUSH OVER STANCE ON `STATISTICAL SAMPLING' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Claiming it hurts minorities, Democrat Al Gore
Tuesday slammed his Republican presidential rival George W. Bush
for joining other Republicans in endorsing only traditional methods
of counting people in the census.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and other Democrats have argued that to get a better handle
on the number of traditionally undercounted populations in the
country, the Census Bureau should rely on a technique called
``statistical sampling'' that relies on educated estimates to count
those groups who are the most difficult to reach with regular
counting methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is ridiculous to believe that the most accurate way to
count everybody is to send people out with a clipboard and
pencil,'' Gore said at a community center in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush spokesman Scott McClellan charged that it is Democrats
who are playing politics by trying to use a different census method
to gain a political advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton-Gore administration has a history of using
government agencies to further Democratic political goals,'' said
McClellan. ``Governor Bush believes we should count everyone. Al
Gore's attacks ignore a Supreme Court ruling that we must conduct
an actual head count, not use statistical guesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled last year that federal law does not
allow use of any method other than a head count to apportion
congressional seats among the states. The high court did not rule,
however, on use of sampling in other matters, such as
redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   Statistical sampling aims to minimize undercounts by making a
detailed survey of people in sample regions, then using that data
to assume characteristics about people in other regions with
similar demographics.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also charged that Bush had not heeded the advice of his own
advisers, citing a 1997 report by the Texas office of State-Federal
Relations, which concluded that ``all sides in the census debate
concede that traditional methods of calculation ... will never
provide a full and accurate portrait of the U.S. population.''
</P>
<P>
   The report states, ``at issue is how to correct what everyone
acknowledges is an undercount and specifically an undercount of
certain populations, most often urban populations.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that in the 1990 census about a half million Texans
were not counted, a majority of them Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is ignoring the advice of his own office in Texas about
what is in the best interest of the people of Texas,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president suggested that Bush was capitulating to the
Republican National Committee which has said that a change in
census techniques that increases the number of traditionally
Democratic minorities would hinder their efforts to carve out more
GOP congressional and state legislative districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say to Governor Bush if you really believe every
American counts it is time to stand up the political operatives in
your own party and support a census that counts every American,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan did not dispute that the Texas office of State-Federal
Relations questioned the accuracy of the current census methods in
its 1997 report. However, he said the report did not recommend a
specific alternative, such as statistical sampling.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that subsequent reports by the office slightly softened
the census language changing ``all sides in the census debate
concede'' to ``many in the census debate believe that the
traditional methods of calculation ... will never provide a full
and accurate portrait of the U.S population.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush appoints the director of the Office of State-Federal
Relations and sits on a three-member advisory board which oversees
its work. That board also includes Texas' lieutenant governor Rick
Perry, a Rep/Y[Z,X7,Cand \YX-Y9 K$h[YHR+W. HTW$SX7e1
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
