<HEADER>
A4030 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      03-21 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: AIRLINES LAG IN MEETING DEMAND FOR HIGH-PROTEIN
FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: In P(CENTS), replace (CENTS) with the typographical
symbol, no parentheses)  
(duplication notice: also sent with `f' code) 
(bl) 
 By JOE SHARKEY    c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody in his right mind is actually enthusiastic when that
service cart starts inching down the aisle with the flight
attendants passing out the meals with their frightening
soup-kitchen cheeriness. But it was 8:30 a.m., and back in the last
row of steerage I was getting hungry in that first hour of the haul
from New York to Dallas. Not hungry enough for Special K, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``No eggs?'' I asked the flight attendant.
</P>
<P>
   She shook her head, smiled and explained that the eggs were all
gone by about halfway down the aisle. Cereal was all that was left.
``The Atkins diet,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Now, about a third of the people I know are or have been in the
last six months on some variation of the spectacularly popular
high-protein, low-carbohydrate diets that are often referred to
generically as the Atkins diet, after one of the more popular
programs.
</P>
<P>
   You would think the airlines' food service might start
reflecting the fact that there has been a significant shift in the
American diet toward more protein and less carbohydrates. (Some
evidence: Last year, beef consumption rose 3 percent in the United
States, reversing a 20-year decline, and the beef industry said the
low-carb diets were partly responsible for the change). But
companies that supply in-flight meals say that they haven't been
asked to modify menus and, for instance, eliminate those puffy
muffins for a chunk of cheese _ perhaps because the diets are
considered to be fads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen it so far,'' said Bob Rosar, the corporate
executive chef at Dobbs International Services, a unit of Gate
Gourmet International, which supplies over 140 million meals a year
for more than 100 airlines. Rosar, who said that he had lost four
pounds during a brief period on a high-protein, low-carb diet, said
that if there was any shift in airline-food menus, it was toward
more vegetarian meals and away from meat _ largely the result of
pressure from European customers. Also, American business
travelers, especially those in the premium seats, are ``letting it
known that they expect a certain type of quality in the meals,'' he
said. ``Gone are the days of beef stew and mystery-meat entrees.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Michaela Kiesel, a senior vice president at LSG
Lufthansa Service Holding AG, another major supplier of airline
meals, said that frequent flyers are increasingly making it clear
that ``food quality is an important factor on which a decision in
choosing an airline is based,'' but that so far there has been no
clamor from the airlines for low-carb meals in particular.
</P>
<P>
   That may be because airlines aren't famous for listening to
their customers. Hotels, on the other hand, have their ears closer
to the ground in the area of customer service. One chain, Loews
Hotels, is introducing next month a new high-protein, low-carb menu
line called P(CENTS). The menu items, which will appear in
restaurants in all 15 Loews hotels, reflect surveys showing that
``25 percent of our customers are adhering to some form of a
high-protein, low-carbohydrate diet,'' said Emily Kanders, a Loews
representative.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines reflecting food tastes? ``Hah!'' said Clark Wolf, the
food and restaurant consultant for Loews and a man who travels
about 180 days of the year. ``Airlines could save a lot of money
and make a lot of friends by refraining from attempting to cook.
Just give me a hunk of cheese and an apple, please.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he had the airlines out of his system, Wolf explained that
he was a proponent of the high-protein, low-carb diets, especially
to avoid gastric distress when traveling, because ``with these
foods, there's less going on in your tummy.''
</P>
<P>
   The new diets have been gaining in popularity for about two
years. ``But last fall, it became audible across the country,'' he
said. ``We were getting the same requests in all of our
restaurants'' for grilled chicken, beef and fish, with perhaps a
small green salad. ``And cheese,'' he added. ``Cheese courses are
back big time.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf, 49, who is 6 feet 1 inch tall and weighs 171 pounds, said
he decided to suggest to Loews officials that they introduce the
new menu line after he gathered 30 of the chain's executive chefs
and food directors at an annual conference in Miami Beach last
November. They went restaurant-hopping one night and ``we all
noticed that everybody was being very careful about carbs; I knew
that this was something we needed to be paying attention to.''
</P>
<P>
   Business travelers are especially likely to be watching their
carbohydrate consumption, he said. ``It's almost like a club. You
see someone these days who's a major business traveler who isn't a
size 54, and you say, `Low carbs, high protein, huh?'''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf isn't an Atkins zealot by any means. There is considerable
evidence even beyond common nutritional sense that a prolonged diet
high in animal fats is not wise. But many travelers have learned
the virtues of the occasional spell of high-protein and
low-carbohydrate eating.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are eating this way you don't have to make a big
production out of being on a diet,'' Kanders said, explaining why
the P(CENTS) menu items are designed to appeal to business
travelers who might be hosting other business people while on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Besides weight watching, the current prosperity is also driving
some of the menu modifications, Wolf said. ``After the '87 crash,
potatoes got bigger on the plate while the protein shrank. Now,
people are asking for spotted blue prawns. They want veal scampi
from the north coast of Italy. They want Kobe beef. Good beef is
definitely in style.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
