<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SWEEPS THROUGH NEW JERSEY PICKING UP ENDORSEMENTS AND
DOLLARS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENGLEWOOD, N.J. _ Vice President Al Gore swept into Bill
Bradley's home state Tuesday and received the endorsements of top
allies of his vanquished foe, welcoming them into his continuing
march toward unifying the Democratic party for the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   At Baumgart's Restaurant here in this New York City suburb, Gore
embraced the Bradley allies, including Doug Berman, Bradley's
campaign chairman, Richard Codey, minority leader of the state
senate and Bradley's New Jersey chairman, Brendan Byrne, the former
governor, and assorted others, saying he wanted to ``make all of
them feel completely and totally welcome in an effort that is going
to carry the banner that both of us believe in forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman, addressing the nearly 40 officials who were standing
with Gore in the dining room here, said: ``Intra-family fights can
seem pretty intense at times.'' But he added: ``I am strong in my
support for the vice president,'' who, he said, ``will fight for
the important things,'' including abortion rights and education.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who is on vacation and was not here Tuesday, dropped
out of the Democratic presidential race on March 9 after winning no
primaries. During the campaign he said Gore represented
``entrenched power'' and had run a negative campaign that had
distorted his record. But in announcing his withdrawal he said he
would support Gore, although he did not release his delegates.
Aides to both men expect that at some point, the two will hold a
joint appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore called Tuesday's get-together ``a great gathering of unity
and common purpose'' and went out of his way to say that he had
learned a lot from Bradley _ comments that stood in contrast to
those of Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican nominee,
who said last week that his rival, Sen. John McCain, had not
brought anything new to light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot from the dialogue and the debates that we
had,'' Gore said. Gore, who also used to call Bradley a quitter for
retiring from the Senate in 1996 and ridiculed him as an academic
rather than a realist, credited him Tuesday with bringing racial
issues, health care and campaign finance to the top of the
election-year agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lifted high the banner of campaign finance reform, and I
admire his persistence and stamina in pushing that issue to the
forefront,'' Gore added.
</P>
<P>
   Gore crammed the endorsement session in between fund-raising
events here and in Manhattan, holding three events that brought him
at least $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is in a frantic swirl to reach the $33.8 million limit that
he can raise before the August convention, and he is nearly there.
As soon as he reaches that amount for his own campaign, he will
concentrate on helping the Democratic National Committee raise its
goal of $100 million for the fall election.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Tuesday's events, the vice president plans to
pick up money later this week in Cincinnati, Detroit and Houston.
He has two lunches scheduled for Wednesday in Washington, D.C., for
the Democratic National Committee, where he expects to raise
$700,000 as he shuttles between two rooms in the same hotel.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   But his activities are somewhat incongruous, coming as he has
begun to portray himself as an apostle of reform, chastened by his
zealous fundraising in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   His first event Tuesday was a luncheon at the Upper East Side
home of John and Janet Wallach. He is a former investment banker
and the couple founded Seeds for Peace, a program that seeks to
bring Israeli and Palestinian children together. About 30 people
(``solicitors'' in campaign finance jargon) brought $5,000 each and
dined on sesame-seared salmon and pistachio mousse with the vice
president at small tables set up in the Wallach's living room.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question about what his priorities would be if
he were president, Gore discussed education, cleaning up the
environment, improving health care and changing the campaign
finance system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaign finance reform is a priority because I believe our
system is greatly in need of the changes that can put the people
back in the driver's seat in our democracy,'' he told his
listeners.
</P>
<P>
   He then drove in his motorcade to the restaurant here, and then
attended two more fundraisers. He raised about $100,000 at the home
of James and Joyce Demetrakis, who work in real estate, and about
$200,000 at the home of Mark Frankel, a venture capitalist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
