<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4034 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ZAMPA-OPERA-ART-2TAKE     03-21 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAMPA-OPERA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENOR AS VILLAIN: QUAINT NOTION, BUT CAN IT WORK TODAY?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT31 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Matthew Gurewitsch writes about the arts for The Wall Street
Journal and other publications.  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stone guests make grim company. Ask Don Giovanni. Or
Zampa, the pirate king in Ferdinand Herold's opera by that name. As
Mount Etna erupts in the background (the scene is in Sicily), the
scoundrel ends up crushed in the embrace of the statue of Alice
Manfredi, a 16-year-old Florentine he seduced and abandoned a
decade before the curtain rises.
</P>
<P>
   His fate had begun to look dire in the finale of the second of
three acts, when the statue refused to surrender a wedding ring he
had impiously slipped on its finger. In the meantime he prudently
had the stone maiden tossed in the sea. To no avail, and her
show-stopping revenge well justifies the opera's alternative title,
``La Fiancee de Marbre,'' or ``The Marble Bride,'' even though _
unlike her booming fatherly counterpart in Mozart _ Alice utters
not a sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zampa,'' introduced to wild acclaim at the Opera-Comique in
Paris in 1831, remained a fixture in France, Italy and Germany
through the 19th century. Today the overture is the sole excerpt
that enjoys any name recognition, and that only barely. A whirlwind
potpourri of infectious tunes from the opera, it displays
orchestration of a zest and finesse that bring to mind Weber,
Mendelssohn and Berlioz.
</P>
<P>
   On April 3, at Alice Tully Hall, a concert revival by L'Opera
Francais de New York _ with narration written and delivered by the
composer's descendant Alexander Herold replacing the original
spoken dialogue _ restores the subsequent action in what is said to
be the opera's first New York hearing in more than a hundred years.
</P>
<P>
   Tracey Welborn sings the title role of the rake and swaggerer, a
tenor whose lines spike up to high D flat but hover on occasion
around low G, dangerous and difficult territory. Isabel
Bayrakdarian, the rising lyric soprano, appears as Camille, whose
virtue catches his heart off guard. Yves Abel, the company's
co-founder and artistic director, conducts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Textbooks say that the true Romantics were the Germans,'' Abel
said recently from Chicago, where he was conducting Donizetti's
``Elisir d'Amore.'' ``As I began to dig, I saw _ not true! The true
Romantics were the people living and working in Paris during the
Terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a time when all the old rules were being broken.
Composers were free to use strange harmonies, to divorce themselves
from traditional librettos about gods and nymphs frolicking in
magic forests. `Zampa' is later, but it comes out of that world.
Musically, it combines the heroic French grand opera style of the
Opera with the lighter musical-theater style of the Opera-Comique.
And there's the bel canto influence of the Theatre des Italiens,
where they performed Donizetti, Bellini and Rossini. Dramatically,
like many other pieces of the time, it's amazingly Goyaesque: full
of blood, murder, love, raw emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting nationality aside, the description suggests Verdi in the
early phase from, say, ``Ernani'' to ``I Masnadieri'' or ``Luisa
Miller.'' But to ears accustomed to Italianate passion, the
pre-eminent characteristic of the score of ``Zampa'' is its
lightness, its balanced, even balletic, grace. By the standards of
``Don Giovanni'' or of Weber's milestone of Romanticism ``Der
Freischutz,'' which preceded ``Zampa'' by a decade, Herold's
incursions of the demonic are mild.
</P>
<P>
   The mercurial Romantic spirit Abel speaks of shows in restless
shifts between major and minor, in meter and in tempo, but the
strophic or otherwise repetitive numbers the composer favors tend
to spin in place rather than propel the plot. Still, the freshness
and variety of the melodies are a constant delight. Listeners could
catch themselves tapping their toes and (God forbid) even humming
along. Realism was the last thing on the composer's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days, the sets and costumes told you everything you
needed to know,'' the very lively family spokesman said early this
month from his home in the Spanish town of Valencia, with Rossini's
``Pietra del Paragone'' blaring in the background. ``Opera was a
lot of people gussied up singing to the audience. Nowadays people
expect dramatic coherency and naturalism. In `Zampa,' that's not
part of the equation at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the company is advertising a ``concert performance,'' the
playbill lists Herold not only as narrator but also as director. In
that capacity, he had a tentative notion _ as yet untested _ of
putting the singers in 1830s concert dress rather than in
theatrical costumes suitable to their characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evening dress is certainly preferable to capes and bandanas,''
Herold reasoned. ``The challenge of the performance is to make the
opera true to itself and intelligible for us. It's the same as when
we perform Shakespeare today. It makes no sense to do Shakespeare
on the moon or on roller skates. What the plays are about is what
Shakespeare wrote. What Herold wrote is what we've got to do, on
its own terms. We should have a certain suggestion of the early
19th century. It will be easier to believe in the piece if what
we're watching is antique people doing something antique.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   No sidestepping the story, in other words. It involves (in
addition to the characters already mentioned) the upright Alphonse,
to whom Camille is initially engaged, and the offstage figure of
Camille's rich merchant father, captured by Zampa and marked for
death unless she gives Zampa her hand in marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the marble bride at last intervenes, Zampa is
revealed to be the long-lost brother of Alphonse, his rival: shades
of ``Il Trovatore,'' years in the future. (The chorus of cheerful,
clueless townsfolk and frolicsome pirates anticipates Gilbert and
Sullivan.) In a buffo subplot, Camille's presumptively widowed
confidante discovers in one of Zampa's lieutenants her long-lost
husband, giving rise to a deliciously ambivalent recognition scene.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from melodiously anguished duets, Camille's role includes
a ballad recounting the tale of Alice Manfredi. In its simpler way,
the set piece functions much as the heroine's ghost story early in
Donizetti's ``Lucia di Lammermoor,'' another Romantic touchstone.
Does Bayrakdarian sense a parallel?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Camille sings in French,'' she replied from her home in
Toronto. ``Can we make a comparison when the pieces are in
different languages? Italian has a completely different flavor. In
`Zampa,' the ballad is like a folk song. Singing it, I wouldn't
concern myself to make every note as developed and pearl-like as
Donizetti would require. I don't think it's meant to be dug into
for deeper meanings. As I look at the score, what I see is a very
French economy of means. There's not a lot of extra or complicated
harmony, but when it comes, it really makes a point. All the singer
has to do is respond to that, and it becomes beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Zampa's hold on the imagination of his contemporaries
notwithstanding, his character may today be harder to put across.
The drama calls for a latter-day Don Giovanni, brute and seducer.
Don Giovanni, of course, is a bass or baritone, possessed of all
the demonic macho potential inherent in the lower vocal register.
</P>
<P>
   As a romantic tenor, Zampa automatically appears in a more
tractable, more civilized light. The refrain of his aria _ as
buoyant as it is boyish _ conjures up a scamp rather than a
scoundrel, the nimble lothario of some forgotten operetta.
</P>
<P>
   Among tenor parts, Zampa perhaps anticipates the Duke of Mantua,
in ``Rigoletto,'' who, disarmed by Gilda's innocence, feels the
stirrings of a love of which his past frivolity and selfishness
have left him incapable. But such a view leaves a great deal
unaccounted for. What is Zampa's blackmail of another man's bride
but a villain's gratuitous show of power? Abel and Welborn see
ambiguity not only in the libretto but also in the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's such bravura in what Zampa sings,'' said Welborn,
tracked down in Virginia while minding two rambunctious young sons.
``He takes himself and his attractions seriously, but he also
laughs at himself, which is part of his appeal. He's definitely
attracted to Camille. She's very modest and discreet. I don't think
he's ever met anyone like her before. He relishes his power, but he
falls in love. Power and love _ I'd like to strive to show both.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
