<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WAYWARD-STATUES-ART-N     03-21 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAYWARD-STATUES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A CROWDED CITY, MANY STATUES ELBOWED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT29 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mcd) 
 By BARBARA STEWART    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Less than a decade after carting the four-story-high
Golden Boy and its global pedestal from Manhattan to Basking Ridge,
N.J., AT&AMP;T officials have acknowledged what might have seemed
obvious to some:
</P>
<P>
   Gleefully brandishing thunderbolts, with muscles more clearly
defined than Sylvester Stallone's in his Rocky days, Golden Boy _ a
k a, the Genius of Electricity and, later, the Spirit of
Communications _ is an Art Deco classic and an icon of New York,
where it had stood since it was created in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   The statue currently stands on a closely cropped lawn in front
of one of the company's cookie-cutter corporate buildings, his
gilded posterior level with a row of windows.
</P>
<P>
   Finding Golden Boy a home in New York is proving to be a
formidable task. But, on a smaller scale, the city has grappled
with this problem before. In the mid-1980s, the board of TriBeCa's
small, pristine Washington Market Park refused to accept a statue
of Mohandas K. Gandhi; and some residents around Union Square Park,
where it currently stands, objected, too. Also in the 1980's, the
placement in the Bronx of a statue of a young man with a pit bull
stirred up such anger that it was eventually moved to Socrates
Sculpture Park in Queens. And it has taken six years for the New
York Road Runners Club and the city to agree on a site for a statue
of Fred Lebow, founder of the New York City marathon.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is willing to donate Golden Boy and the cost of its upkeep
to the Parks Department, said Gary A. Morgenstern, an AT&AMP;T
spokesman. And Henry J. Stern, the parks commissioner, said in an
interview Tuesday: ``I want it a lot. It's classic _ of sculpture
or kitsch, whatever you think. It's a very significant American
piece. It's a treasure and it would be fun to have.''
</P>
<P>
   But where in downtown Manhattan, the center of commerce, is
there a park that is large enough for a statue that is 24 feet
tall, not counting the 21-foot-tall pedestal, with a 12-foot
wingspan and legs that stretch for 7 feet, a statue whose
fingernails are 2 inches long?
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, this problem might seem far from
insurmountable. And at second glance, it might seem that New York
City should accept the gift immediately. But finding a home for
even more ordinary statues, smaller and less dramatic, is often
delicate and difficult. And the size, age and flamboyance of Golden
Boy makes it especially tough.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there are other statues around the city that need
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago, four 100-year-old bronze eagles surrounding the
main obelisk of the Prison Ship Martyrs monument in Fort Green,
Brooklyn, were removed after being severely damaged by vandals.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the eagles now stand sentinel outside the doors of
Stern's office at the Arsenel, the Parks headquarters, on the east
side of Central Park. Two are stored in a room nearby. Some Fort
Green residents want them back, said Bob Evans, president of
Community Board 2. Others, afraid of further vandalism, say they
should stay at the Arsenal, where they are out of sight, but safe.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said there are plans to return the eagles to the monument,
which is being renovated, when and if the city can find a way to
keep them safe.
</P>
<P>
   And the city and the New York Road Runners Club recently agreed
to move the life-size statue of the group's founder, Lebow, to the
east side of Central Park, in the 90s, near the club headquarters.
For some four years, the statue of Lebow, who died in 1994, has
been nestled in the bushes near Tavern on the Green, on the west
side of the park, near the finish line of the New York Marathon.
Some club members preferred that the Lebow statue stay there, while
others wanted it closer to the clubhouse. But even though the
factions have come to an agreement, the Lebow statue will not be
moved to its new home until a renovation of the park along the east
90's is completed.
</P>
<P>
   A newly proposed statue of Sojourner Truth, the former slave and
freedom fighter, faced another problem: many neighborhoods wanted
it.
</P>
<P>
   The statue will show Sojourner Truth holding a Bible at the
start of a preaching tour covering hundreds of miles. It is to
stand in Columbia Park in Brooklyn, on Tillary and Court Streets,
which she passed through when she began preaching. It will be
bronze and cost about $1.5 million, said Julius O. Pearse, an
omsbudsman with the National Negro Business and Professional
Women's Club Inc., which is building the statue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of emotion around it,'' Pearse said. When word
got around, several local community organizations wanted it in
their neighborhoods, he said. But the Cadman Plaza-Columbia Park
area was historically correct, as well as near the courthouse and
therefore a well-traveled spot for ``a patron saint of
abolitionists,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But finding a home for Golden Boy is proving as difficult as
finding an $800 one-bedroom in Chelsea. The directors of the first
site approached by the city, Washington Market Park in TriBeCa, on
Chambers and Greenwich Streets, rejected the offer out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's huge,'' said Kathryn Freed, a city councilwoman who was
instrumental in creating the two-acre park from a vacant lot in the
1970's. ``This is a little park. It would have totally dominated
the whole thing. This is a little green park that is intensely used
by whole community. People come out and sit. Kids run around. The
idea of plunking down a big statue _ I don't care how gorgeous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parks,'' she continued, ``should be green things, not gold
things. Clearly, whoever thought of us is someone who doesn't like
parks.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said he has a few sites in mind, all downtown, where AT&AMP;T
was headquartered for so long. He will not reveal them. ``I don't
want to get mired in contention,'' he said. ``People kvetch about
statues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
