<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4042 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NIETZSCHE-THEATER-2TA     03-21 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIETZSCHE-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO IS THAT MAN POSING AS RICHARD FOREMAN?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has Richard Foreman found his alter ego at last? Could it be
that the poor mad philosopher Friedrich Nietzsche is the perfect
analogue for the playwright and director, who for more than 30
years has been breaking the boundaries of theater to combine the
surreal, the disordered, the mysterious and, sometimes, the just
plain nutty?
</P>
<P>
   This year is the centenary of Nietzsche's death, and he is the
subject of Foreman's new play, ``Bad Boy Nietzsche!,'' which runs
through April 30 at his Ontological-Hysteric Theater at St. Mark's
Church in Manhattan. ``Nietzsche was a sweet, retiring nebbish like
me,'' Foreman, 62, said recently. ``I identified with him
completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his SoHo loft and looking a bit like a balding basset
hound, Foreman was surrounded by strange objects. There was a toy
lamb and a parrot; a horsehead from his production of ``The
Threepenny Opera''; an assemblage of a snake and the Pope on a bed
of nails staring at each other, by Foreman's wife, Kate Manheim, an
artist. There was Manheim's new work, images taken from a
19th-century gynecological textbook on venereal diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1987, after she was struck by a mysterious illness that
caused her severe pain, Manheim was Foreman's leading stage
interpreter, and scattered through the loft are cardboard and
balsa-wood valentines he has made for her, one a train with the
words ``Richard Loves Kate'' on it and the figure of Foreman
leaning out the window.
</P>
<P>
   But dominating the space and lining every wall are Foreman's
10,000 books. He is widely read in European intellectual history:
Theodor Adorno, Walter Benjamin, Jacques Lacan. And, of course,
Nietzsche. But ``it was the image of Nietzsche holding his head and
having an idea, as an icon of a hermitlike intellectual, that
dominated me as much as his specific ideas,'' Foreman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad Boy Nietzsche!'' is in many ways typical Foreman: ropes
strung across the stage, optometrists' letters, a clear plexiglass
wall separating the audience from the performers. The actors wear
headsets with microphones and funny hats. But this is the first
time that Foreman has based a play on a historical figure.
</P>
<P>
   Nietzsche, born in 1844 in Rocken, near Leipzig, is widely
regarded as one of the foremost influences on contemporary
philosophy, and as a precursor of existentialism and
post-structuralism. In ``The Birth of Tragedy,'' published in 1872,
he questioned the foundations of Western rationalism as exemplified
by Socrates and the plays of Euripides, espousing a new kind of
morality, one based on the mastery of the passions, not their
extirpation through religion.
</P>
<P>
   In his best-known work, ``Thus Spake Zarathustra,'' published in
1883-85, Nietzsche wrote of the death of God and the will to power,
and developed his notion of the Superman, a figure who celebrates
life on earth, rather than as it is sanctified in the hereafter.
</P>
<P>
   For the young Nietzsche, his friend Richard Wagner was the
perfect exemplar of passion and will combined in the artist, the
authentic heir to the Greek tragedians. But Nietzsche broke with
Wagner over the composer's anti-Semitism, his manipulativeness and
the cult he had inspired at Bayreuth.
</P>
<P>
   Grand as Nietzsche's ideas were, the philosopher led a lonely
life. His father, a Lutheran pastor, died when his son was 4, and
Nietzsche's childhood was dominated by women. He was said to have
contracted syphilis in a brothel as a student, and suffered from
migraines and stomach pains.
</P>
<P>
   His one great love was the writer and psychoanalyst Lou
Andreas-Salome, but their relationship was chaste, and she did not
return his affection. She later became the mistress of the poet
Rainer Maria Rilke.
</P>
<P>
   In 1889 Nietzsche suffered a breakdown. At first he raved,
singing wildly, banging on his piano, tearing off his clothes in
the street. He wrote letters to friends and the courts of Europe
announcing that he was Dionysus and ``the Crucified.'' Gradually,
he withdrew, until, near the end, he was barely aware of the world.
``Nietzsche lies upstairs all day dressed in a flannel gown,'' his
friend Peter Gast wrote in 1894. ``He does not look bad, has grown
very quiet and gazes ahead with a dreamy and very questioning
expression. ... He hardly recognizes me anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   After Nietzsche's death, his ideas were distorted and
discredited through his sister Elisabeth, a Hitler supporter, and
they became identified with Nazism. But in the late 1960s and early
'70s, a new generation of interpreters found in Nietzsche an icon
who questioned established morality. And in recent years, he has
undergone another resurgence, becoming a hero to post-modernist
thinkers and artists, including Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   Like all of Foreman's productions, ``Bad Boy Nietzsche!'' defies
easy description. At the center is a Nietzsche-like figure, played
by Gary Wilmes with a big mustache, a white gown and nightcap. It
was an image, Foreman said, inspired by accounts of the mad
philosopher being coaxed onto a train to go to a clinic and being
told he was going to meet a prince. Like many Foreman characters,
this one is a timid soul picked upon by the world, especially, in
this case, by a character called the Cruel Man, a drawling Kevin
Hurley wearing a schoolgirl's pleated skirt on suspenders over his
shirt and pants. ``He's the kind of person against me and Nietzsche
and all people like us,'' Foreman said.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of Nietzsche's anguished world is a character
known as the Child, a rather sexual creature played by an adult,
Sarah Louise Lilley. ``I have read bits and pieces of things you
write, Nietzsche,'' she says in a Marilyn Monroe-like voice, ``so I
imagined you big and strong, with eyes on fire. Is it possible _
maybe you aren't the real Nietzsche?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And, typical of Foreman, there is a dominatrix-like figure, this
one with rouged nipples, called the Beautiful Woman, played by
Juliana Francis and inspired somewhat, Foreman said, by
Andreas-Salome.
</P>
<P>
   Threaded through the work are excerpts from Nietzsche's letters
and doggerel. ``After you discover me, you find me. The difficulty
now is to lose me,'' says Wilmes as Nietzsche, in words from one of
the philosopher's letters after his breakdown. ``I write on paper,
write on wall,'' the character says at another point, ``with
foolish heart a foolish scrawl.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreman said he made a conscious decision not to use Nietzsche's
philosophical writings. ``His reality came through. It was like
doodling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anything more boring than to see a Tom
Stoppard type of play,'' Foreman said, referring to Stoppard's
historically based dramas.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Foreman prefers to free associate with history
rather than to anchor his dramas in a real time and place. (In his
review of ``Bad Boy Nietzsche!'' in The New York Times, Ben
Brantley praised Foreman for not making obvious decisions, such as
refraining from using the music of Wagner and Strauss, two
composers associated with the title character.)
</P>
<P>
   The play contains images that refer directly to the
philosopher's life. At one point, the character Nietzsche throws
his arms around a stuffed horse, a reference to an incident in 1889
when the real Nietzsche saw a horse being beaten and tried to help
it, which precipitated his final breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's make a test,'' the Child says to the stage Nietzsche,
her voice insinuating. ``Suppose I climb up to that little horse
dangling from the ceiling and start beating it and beating it and
beating it _ would you protect that poor little horse?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Guess,'' replies Nietzsche, sounding as if he is saying
``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   In another image from life, the Beautiful Woman whips Nietzsche
as he pulls a cart. In 1882, Andreas-Salome persuaded Nietzsche and
his friend Paul Ree to live in a menage a trois without sex, an
arrangement that quickly broke apart. A photograph from the time
shows the two men pulling a cart containing Andreas-Salome, who is
whipping them as if they were horses. Ree smiles at the joke.
Nietzsche looks beyond, dogged and hurt. ``Whip me, sir, and you
whip my horse,'' the character of Nietzsche says in the play.
``Remember _ I'll pay you very well.''
</P>
<P>
   But like all his plays, ``Bad Boy Nietzsche!'' is primarily
Foreman's fantasy. ``Have some slices of this holy bread which
trembles in expectation,'' the character of Nietzsche says. ``There
are jewels, valuable jewels in this bread.'' The characters soon
confuse the words ``jewels'' and ``Jews,'' a reference, Foreman
said, to Nietzsche's Christian background, the communion wafer and
the incorrect charges of anti-Semitism against him.
</P>
<P>
   In one sequence, a cardboard boat sails across the stage and the
character of Nietzsche suddenly finds himself in China. This is an
allusion to the fact that ``his ideas turned the world upside
down,'' Foreman said. He added that the image also came from his
own childhood, when he would pass a toy boat resting on ice in a
fish store window on Manhattan's Upper West Side.
</P>
<P>
   The play ends on a decidedly different note from Foreman's
previous work. Most often, his heroes begin as slightly grandiose
figures and in the end are defeated. Toward the end of ``Bad Boy
Nietzsche!'' the philosopher sequesters himself in a tanklike
structure onstage. ``I'm never coming out,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The other characters begin beating the horse. In fact, says the
Child, they can beat the horse as much as they like, ``Right, Mr.
Nietzsche? Right? Right?''
</P>
<P>
   But as they do, Nietzsche emerges from the tank. ``You lied to
us, Mr. Nietzsche,'' the Child cries. ``You said you were never
coming out.''
</P>
<P>
   The character of Nietzsche replies: ``Yes, but how is that
possible? Because I never lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreman offered an explanation for the line: ``Nietzsche locked
himself inside his madness, but he did come back. His philosophy is
now dominant in the Western world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2211EST &QL; 
