A4044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WEB-SUPPLIER-MINORITY     03-21 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-SUPPLIER-MINORITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER GM EXECUTIVE FORMS WEB SITE FOR MINORITY-OWNED BUSINESS
SUPPLIERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ A former General Motors executive announced Tuesday
that he had formed an Internet company that would aim to make it
easier for the largest American companies to buy parts and supplies
from minority-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to ensure that minority businesses are not left behind
in the migration to online marketplaces,'' said Roy S. Roberts, the
chairman, chief executive and half-owner of M-Xchange.com, a
business-to-business Internet company, and a former group vice
president of GM.
</P>
<P>
   His Web site will seek to provide one-stop shopping for
companies in any industry looking to buy products and services from
companies owned by racial minorities or women. ``We want to take
all businesses and expose them to minority businesses,'' Roberts
said. ``You can't get that today.''
</P>
<P>
   The start-up company has the backing of the Rev. Jesse Jackson,
who was on hand Tuesday to promote M-Xchange.com with a message to
largely white corporate America: ``There is nothing you want to
procure that we cannot supply.'' For several years, Jackson has
campaigned through his Wall Street Project to bring mainstream
investments to minority companies and communities nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Auto executives as well as minority-owned companies were
enthusiastic about the new company.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers in Detroit will probably be big customers, said Bud
Liebler, vice president for marketing at DaimlerChrysler. ``It
would be something that all three of the companies and a lot of
companies beyond the automotive industry may have a need for,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Minority-owned companies are eager to sign up. ``There is no
question that business-to-business connectivity is going to be a
highway to the future and all companies need to understand how to
use that new channel, and minority companies in particular,'' said
Melvin Brown, owner of ChemPak Inc., a company based in Westland,
Mich., that sells industrial cleaning products primarily to the
auto and health care industries.
</P>
<P>
   M-Xchange.com is expected to begin service in mid-July, said
Roberts, 60, who was General Motors' highest-ranking black
executive before he retired in February. His white co-founder, Gary
Wasserman, 50, owns 49 percent of M-Xchange.com, and is its
president.
</P>
<P>
   Many details of the business remain to be determined. Its
headquarters will be in Detroit, Roberts said. As it seeks to grow
quickly, it will probably consider selling shares to the public.
Suppliers listing themselves on the Internet exchange will probably
pay M-Xchange.com an undetermined fee. Companies that use the Web
site to hire suppliers will probably account for most of the Web
site's revenue and are likely to pay a percentage of the contract
they award to the Internet matchmaking service.
</P>
<P>
   M-Xchange.com estimated that by 2003, mainstream companies will
buy about $135 billion, or 5 percent of total business-to-business
e-commerce purchases, from minority-owned suppliers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
