<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4047 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AL-AMIN-MAIN22-COX     03-21 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AL-AMIN-MAIN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feds hid for two days before taking Al-Amin
 &HT;    By Jack Warner and Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For two days, federal agents in Alabama watched Jamil
Abdullah Al-Amin, waiting for the right moment.
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred miles to the northeast, Atlanta police and the
Fulton County sheriff's fugitive squad kept following leads in the
metro area, so as not to tip their hand.
</P>
<P>
   By the time agents decided to take Al-Amin, they had as many as
150 Georgia, Alabama and federal officers surrounding the shack
outside White Hall, in rural Alabama, where he was hiding.
</P>
<P>
   During his initial court appearance Tuesday in Montgomery, Ala.,
after his arrest Monday night ended a massive manhunt, Al-Amin
looked at a reporter and said quietly: ``It's a government
conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The 56-year-old Muslim cleric formerly known as H. Rap Brown, a
member of the Black Panthers in the late 1960s, is accused of
gunning down two Fulton County deputy sheriffs who were trying to
serve him with a warrant near his West End home in Atlanta on
Thursday night. One deputy died.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Orlando Whitehead, chief of the Fulton sheriff's fugitive
squad, said leaders of the agencies hunting for Al-Amin met at FBI
headquarters in Atlanta on Saturday after undercover agents sent to
Alabama on a tip spotted him.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents have said one of the clues that led authorities
to Alabama was a green Toyota 4-Runner registered in White Hall in
Al-Amin's name.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead said officers feared a sudden cessation of the search
in Atlanta would lead anyone watching the operation to suspect that
Al-Amin's hideout had been discovered.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, after FBI agents and U.S. deputy marshals determined
where Al-Amin was hiding, they summoned FBI SWAT teams from Mobile,
Montgomery and Atlanta to secure a wide perimeter around the
tumbledown shack, which was about 100 yards through the woods from
the nearest habitation, Whitehead said.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday afternoon, ``we had maybe 120-150 people around the
place,'' Whitehead said. When the word was given, officers began
closing in on the shack.
</P>
<P>
   As they approached, Al-Amin came out and spotted a group of
deputy marshals, Whitehead said. ``He fired two or three shots at
them, and then ran into the woods,'' Whitehead said.
</P>
<P>
   The woods were quickly surrounded and dog handlers from the
Alabama Department of Corrections brought in six of their
man-tracking beagles, Whitehead said. Controlled by two handlers
and followed by three heavily armed FBI SWAT officers, the dogs
plunged into the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Overhead, an Alabama Air National Guard helicopter with FLIR _
Forward-Looking Infrared Radar _ hovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dogs picked up his scent real quick,'' Whitehead said.
``You could hear 'em baying and yipping for maybe 40 minutes. And
then the handlers radioed in that the beagles indicated `we're
right on top of him.'''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Al-Amin walked out of the woods unarmed and
surrendered to the dogs' handlers and FBI agents. He was wearing a
bulletproof vest, Whitehead said.
</P>
<P>
   A weapon believed to have been used to fire at the officers who
captured him, a .223 caliber Ruger, was found on the side of a road
nearby, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   It has not been determined whether the weapon is the assault
rifle used to kill Fulton County Deputy Ricky Kinchen, 35, and
wound his partner, Deputy Aldranon English, 28.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours before the officers moved in on Al-Amin's shack, six
people _ four adults and two children, all in Muslim headgear _
arrived in a black Cadillac to visit the fugitive. The Cadillac
belongs to Sahid Abdulah Salaam, a friend of Al-Amin's, said
Lowndes County Sheriff Willie Vaughner. Salaam rents a house near
the shack where Al-Amin was hiding.
</P>
<P>
   When the visitors left, officers allowed them to get out of
sight and earshot of the shack before stopping the car and
detaining them, Whitehead said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Redding Pitt in Montgomery said no charges have
been filed against Salaam and the three other adults in the
Cadillac Seville. Pitt would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   In court Tuesday, Al-Amin wore tan sandals, gray sweatpants with
the pockets pulled out and a gray thermal underwear shirt. He was
represented by Selma attorney J. L. Chestnut, who said Al-Amin will
fight attempts to extradite him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next step is for the governor of Georgia to request his
extradition, and then we'll see how the Alabama governor
responds,'' Chestnut said. ``If I know anything about the Alabama
governor, he'll sign it, and we will fight it. Somebody said the
governor of Alabama expected the warrant to arrive tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard spoke with Alabama
officials and said his office will seek an indictment against
Al-Amin this week.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether Cobb County police will drop charges
against Al-Amin for impersonating a police officer. Al-Amin's
failure to appear in court to answer that charge prompted the
Fulton deputies to try to arrest him near his Atlanta home last
Thursday. They were gunned down in the attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The initial Cobb County charge stemmed from a May 31, 1999,
traffic stop during which Al-Amin was charged with theft by
receiving a stolen auto and no proof of insurance. Al-Amin was
driving a stolen Ford Explorer, but told police he had purchased
the car earlier that month. When he pulled out his wallet, Al-Amin
had a police badge. He told the officer he was a cop, a police
report said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, White Hall Mayor John Jackson said he had appointed
Al-Amin an auxiliary police officer in the tiny town. But Jackson
said the appointment was made on June 1, 1999 _ the day after
Al-Amin was arrested by Cobb police.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb County District Attorney Pat Head said he was aware Al-Amin
had planned to claim he was an auxiliary police officer as part of
his defense in the charge of impersonating an officer.
</P>
<P>
   But Head said Al-Amin's criminal past might have presented a
problem there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell me how a convicted felon could be a police officer?''
Head said. ``If they want to come in and prove that he's a
legitimate police officer then that's a defense. I don't know any
legitimate police agency that hires convicted felons. Maybe Alabama
law is different.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writers Rhonda Cook, Ralph
Ellis, Brad Schrade and Ernie Suggs contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
