<SLUG> BC-SWIMMER-CRASH22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olympic swimmer dies in Florida car crash
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Giovanni Linscheer's friends say the
former Olympic and All-America swimmer was a rising engineer who
took time to counsel high school athletes. They can't understand
why he would drive the wrong way down Interstate 95.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've replayed how it could happen. We're dumbfounded,'' Rob
Feliciano, Linscheer's former Delray Beach roommate, said Tuesday.
``But we're focused on helping his grieving family.'' Florida
Highway Patrol officials say Linscheer, 29, slammed head-on into a
car driven by telephone technician Waldemar Derby, Jr., 30, of
Jupiter, on I-95 early Sunday, killing both. State driving records
show Linscheer, who recently moved from Delray Beach to
Jacksonville, had 16 traffic tickets, including four for speeding
and two for reckless driving.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch-born Linscheer was twice named All-America while at
the University of Florida and competed for the South American
country of Suriname at the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona, Spain, and
in the 1996 games in Atlanta, his brother, Enrico, said Tuesday
from Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   Linscheer attended UF from 1990 to 1994, earning a bachelor's
degree in civil engineering in August 1997, university officials
said. He graduated with honors from the Bolles School, a private
high school in Jacksonville, which won the swimming state
championship in 1989 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Two witnesses told investigators they saw Linscheer's Mitsubishi
Montero sports utility vehicle going south in the northbound lane
about 4:30 a.m. Sunday just before it crashed into Derby's
Chevrolet van, Florida Highway Patrol Lt. Pembrook Burrows said.
</P>
<P>
   Both bodies were too burned to be recognizable, Burrows said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities on Tuesday had not yet determined why Linscheer was
going the wrong way, whether either driver was speeding, or whether
alcohol or the wet weather contributed to the crash, Burrows said.
</P>
<P>
   Services for Linscheer will be 4 p.m. today at St. Coleman
Catholic Church in Pompano Beach. Funeral arrangements for Derby
were unavailable Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post staff researcher Lynne Palombo contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
