<SLUG> BC-USAIRWAYS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A US Airways shutdown may clip travelers' wings
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If US Airways shuts down at 12:01 a.m.
Saturday _ as it threatens to do if it can't negotiate a contract
with its 10,000 unionized flight attendants _ travel to the
Northeast from West Palm Beach and Fort Lauderdale could become a
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding seating on other airlines will be difficult because
the load factors are so high here this time of year,'' said Jim
Reynolds, a spokesman for the Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood
International Airport. ``Depending on the destination and the date
and time, it could be a problem to book on another airline.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Waters, spokeswoman for Palm Beach International Airport,
said a shutdown would mean ``an awful lot of passengers concerned
about how they are going to get to their destination.''
</P>
<P>
   US Airways offers direct flights to Baltimore, Boston,
Charlotte, N.C.; Hartford, Conn.; New York; Philadelphia;
Pittsburgh; and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The airline and its affiliates, US Airways Express and MetroJet,
are the second-largest carrier at PBIA, behind Delta Air Lines. The
US Airways trio had 19 percent of passenger traffic and 33 daily
departures in January.
</P>
<P>
   At Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood, US Airways and affiliates are a
close third to Delta and Southwest Airlines. They had nearly 12
percent of passenger traffic and 30 daily departures.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways has not said whether it has made arrangements for
other airlines to honor its tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should there be a shutdown, we will make every effort to
accommodate customers,'' spokesman Rick Weintraub said.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of Flight Attendants has been working without a
contract for three years. After months of federal mediation,
negotiations reached an impasse last month. Mediators called a
30-day cooling-off period, which ends Saturday. The two sides are
grappling over pay, pensions, work rules and job security.
</P>
<P>
   Using a method it calls ``parity plus 1 percent,'' the company
wants to evaluate its flight attendants' pay and work rules in
relation to those at the four top airlines. The company says its
other unions have accepted the method in their contract talks.
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants' union says the company's proposal
actually undercuts attendants' pay by 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said no way. This is a profitable airline,'' said union
spokesman Jeff Zack.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways posted net income of $197 million, or $2.64 a share,
on sales of $8.6 billion in 1999, compared to net income of $538
million, or $5.60 a share, on sales of $8.7 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants have said they wouldn't stage a mass walkout.
Instead, they would target specific flights without notice.
</P>
<P>
   They call the campaign Chaos, for Create Havoc Around Our
System. In response, US Airways Chairman Stephen Wolf threatened a
shutdown to avoid targeted walkouts.
</P>
<P>
   The shutdown would include US Airways and MetroJet, but not US
Airways Express, which makes short-haul flights to Tallahassee and
other Florida destinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If US Airways were to try to operate a schedule under such
conditions, in which we would not know from hour to hour which
flights the (union) would strike, our customers would lose all
confidence,'' Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
