<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-PHILHARMONIC-$ADV26-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GREAT ORCHESTRA DANCING PAST THE GRAVEYARD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ Dvorak Hall in the Rudolfinum, the home
of the Czech Philharmonic on a crook of Smetana's Moldau River, is,
like this city itself, a small treasure.
</P>
<P>
   The stage, below a commanding pipe organ, projects into an
auditorium mutedly colorful in grays and tans. Magnificent columns,
beginning at balcony level, tower above on three sides, giving a
sense of height and grandeur. That upper chamber provides light,
from high windows during the day and chandeliers at night, and a
rich, reverberant acoustic.
</P>
<P>
   But the overriding impression occurs at orchestra level, where
the room seems a jewel box, with elegantly decorated walls snugly
enclosing most of the 1,000 seats, and that impression is one of
smallness and intimacy. (Alice Tully Hall, by comparison, has 1,100
seats.)
</P>
<P>
   One of fragility, even, for how can a historically great
international orchestra continue to function in the highly charged
world economy of a new century from such a tiny, antiquated base?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the size of the hall, which was completed in 1885, used
by the parliament of Czechoslovakia from 1919 to 1939 and
beautifully reconstructed from 1989 to 1992, may be the least of
the orchestra's problems. For one thing, the philharmonic spends
relatively little time there. Like many other financially
challenged performing-arts institutions in the emerging capitalist
nations of Eastern Europe, the Czech Philharmonic has found the
grass greener abroad. It performs about half of its 100 or so
concerts a year on the road.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday afternoon, led by its chief conductor, Vladimir
Ashkenazy, the orchestra gives the first of three concerts at Avery
Fisher Hall, having just completed two weeks of touring in Florida
and California. These concerts, the Philharmonic's first in New
York since 1996, present mostly Bohemian or Czech music and are
part of Lincoln Center's Prague Festival, which celebrates the 10th
anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, a few months past. The
festival began Saturday with a symposium on Prague's rich cultural
history.
</P>
<P>
   Touring is far from the whole solution, however, and not only
because of the wear and tear it exacts on players and staff. As a
state institution in a nation embroiled in an awkward transition to
a market economy, the Czech Philharmonic has suffered a drastic
reduction in subsidies in recent years but still labors under
burdensome restrictions on how it can raise money and spend what it
raises. It cannot, for example, unilaterally increase the salaries
of players, who by any reasonable standard are cruelly underpaid.
</P>
<P>
   Crisis, to be sure, is nothing new to the Czech Philharmonic,
which was formed by members of the National Theater Opera Orchestra
and gave its first concert in 1896, conducted by Antonin Dvorak in
the Rudolfinum. Indeed, the second chapter in a published history
of the Philharmonic is titled ``Krize,'' with reference to a strike
that resulted in the dismissal of the players by the theater in
1901 and the establishment of a shaky independent organization.
</P>
<P>
   Yet through it all, including artistic misdirections compounding
the financial woes of the last decade, the orchestra has maintained
not only an excellent standard of performance but also something of
its local character: a particularly rustic, woody cluck in the
woodwinds, incisive playing from the brasses, a dark depth to the
strings. The woodwinds are notable more for the individuality of
their colors than for their blend.
</P>
<P>
   If any orchestra dances better, it can only be the Vienna
Philharmonic, which may at the moment have more reason to do so.
All this, at least, to judge from limited recent experience: two
concerts and a rehearsal in Dvorak Hall, including repertory to be
performed in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The characteristic sound of an orchestra, in many instances
already a casualty of the jet age and the resultant
interchangeability of players as well as maestros, is something
that seems to worry critics and connoisseurs these days more than
conductors. Engaged around the globe and at least marginally
influenced by recent notions of period performance practice,
conductors tend to prefer versatility: a shifting sonority
appropriate in weight and coloration to the composer or work in
question rather than a sound boasting local color. Ashkenazy is no
exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are aware of their sound,'' he said of the Czech players.
``But the repertory requires a certain type of sound. That's why
more and more orchestras sound the same. Maybe there's some kind of
margin where you can retain a certain sound and still play the
repertory as it should be played.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashkenazy, at 62, is the ultimate musical cosmopolite. He left
Russia in 1963 as an acclaimed pianist and now lives near Lucerne,
Switzerland, with his family. After stints as principal guest
conductor of the Cleveland Orchestra, music director of the Royal
Philharmonic Orchestra in London and chief conductor of the Berlin
Radio Symphony Orchestra (now the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester
Berlin), he took over the Czech Philharmonic in 1998, picking up
after a series of podium misadventures.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the players, newly free to elect their leaders, voted
to hire Gerd Albrecht as principal conductor rather than extend the
contract of Jiri Belohlavek, who had taken over the year before.
Albrecht, a German, thus became the first non-Czech maestro in the
Philharmonic's storied history. The orchestra's fame was built and
sustained during the long, successive tenures of four conductors,
each a major figure internationally: Vaclav Talich from 1918 to
1934, Rafael Kubelik to 1950, Karel Ancerl to 1968 and Vaclav
Neumann to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Part of the players' thinking about Albrecht, apparently, was
that with his international contacts, he would attract more
recording projects for the orchestra. But as it happened, the
classical-record business was on the verge of a worldwide meltdown.
Albrecht, who took over in 1993 after Belohlavek's angry exit,
himself resigned in a fit of pique in 1996. Although no one would
say much about Albrecht's term or his departure, the circumstances
were obviously not happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two camps,'' said Petr Kristian, a veteran
violinist, ``half and half.'' Albrecht, who had done much Czech
music with the orchestra before, including Dvorak operas, suddenly
seemed less interested in it, and some players are said to have
found him highhanded in manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was destructive for the orchestra when he left in the
middle of his contract,'' Ashkenazy said. After Albrecht's
departure, the gap was filled jointly by Vladimir Valek, Sir
Charles Mackerras and Ken-Ichiro Kobayashi. Valek, as permanent
guest conductor, led tours celebrating the orchestra's centennial,
including one in the United States in 1996. Ashkenazy first
conducted the orchestra in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In his own conducting career, Ashkenazy ran into a situation in
1994 somewhat like Belohlavek's. Without consulting Ashkenazy, the
Royal Philharmonic, which he had led since 1986 and with which he
had open-ended plans extending to 1997, made an offer to a
successor, Daniele Gatti. Ashkenazy resigned immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Though widely experienced by now, he has not yet achieved the
universal respect as a podium technician or interpreter that he
enjoys as a pianist. (He will be heard in both functions Monday
evening, playing and conducting Mozart's great D minor Concerto.)
But many players respond to his innate musicality, evidently the
Czechs among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a good musician,'' said Jaroslav Halir, a young
trumpeter. Kristian seconded that opinion, adding that Ashkenazy,
because of his Slavic Russian roots, is sympathetic to the
orchestra's tradition and style. ( Ashkenazy rehearses the
orchestra in English, when, that is, the musical terminology itself
is not Italian.)
</P>
<P>
   And he offers advantages beyond his musicianship. ``With his
connections, he can bring in many soloists and good conductors,''
Kristian said. ``The level has improved in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Another invaluable asset, not unrelated: Ashkenazy has brought
along his powerful manager, Jasper Parrott, who is based in London.
Parrott, a longtime friend and collaborator of the conductor's,
wrote the biography ``Ashkenazy: Beyond Frontiers'' in 1985 with
Ashkenazy's help. Parrott's father, Cecil Parrott, was the British
ambassador to Czechoslovakia from 1960 to 1966, a writer about
music, the author of a biography of Jaroslav Hasek and a translator
of Hasek's ``Good Soldier Svejk.''
</P>
<P>
   Parrott has been using his own diplomatic and managerial skills
on the orchestra's behalf. For one thing, he is working with
Ashkenazy for changes in legislation and governmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Czech Republic is in some ways worse off, because it
started out better,'' Parrott said of the various Eastern European
countries still adjusting to life after communism. ``The attempt to
liberalize after the revolution was largely a fraud. It sort of
avoided problems and made things look good. Five years ago
everything hit the buffers, and it became clear how little
fundamental reform there had been. The Poles made much more
rational reforms, and now Hungary has, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult for institutions in the Czech Republic to
benefit from entrepreneurial activities. Museums and
performing-arts institutions are treated in the same way as
everybody else, and they've all done badly. It's sort of equal
misery for everybody, so nobody has gone bust.''
</P>
<P>
   Parrott has also been helping the orchestra's administration _
the managing director, Jiri Kovar, and the new intendant, Eva
Sedlakova _ develop a modern management style based on Western
models.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech Philharmonic administers the Rudolfinum as a whole,
with its performance halls and art gallery. Kovar was said to be
occupied with legal matters during a reporter's brief visit and
thus unavailable. Sedlakova was put forward as the one who runs the
orchestra day to day.
</P>
<P>
   For an American, nosing around in the Czech Philharmonic's
finances is depressing business. The overall institution's annual
budget amounts to less than $4 million. The players' average
salary, Sedlakova said, is 12,000 Czech crowns a month, which comes
to about $4,000 a year. Although comparisons at such a level are
almost beside the point, the average salary in the Vienna
Philharmonic was said last year to be $59,000, and the
(italics)starting(end italics) salary in top American orchestras
hovers near six digits.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
