<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN SLAYINGS AT TEXAS CARWASH ARRESTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By DOMINGO RAMIREZ JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ A SWAT team rushed a northeast Dallas house on
Tuesday and arrested a fired carwash employee accused of fatally
shooting his former boss and four other former co-workers and
critically injuring another on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wayne Harris, 28, of the Dallas suburb of Irving, who has
a felony record, offered no resistance, police said. Harris is
expected to be charged with capital murder, said David Tull, an
Irving police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Police continued to withhold most information about the
shootings, including the type of weapon used, whether it was found,
where the victims were shot and where their bodies were found.
</P>
<P>
   They also were silent about motive. The Associated Press
reported that a relative of one victim said that all of the
victims' wallets were missing.
</P>
<P>
   Harris had been fired from the Mi-T-Fine Car Wash on Friday
after he was arrested on suspicion of indecent exposure at the
carwash, according to officials at Lew Sterrett Justice Center in
Dallas. According to an Irving police report, Harris had exposed
himself while performing a sexual act.
</P>
<P>
   He was released from jail Sunday after posting $500 bail.
</P>
<P>
   A carwash employee said that Harris was at the business on
Sunday and asked for a free car wash, the AP said. He was refused.
</P>
<P>
   An employee told investigators that Harris was at the carwash
Monday morning, seconds before the employee found the victims
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Police launched a massive manhunt for Harris. They would not say
what led them to the Dallas house where he was apprehended about
10:35 a.m. CST on Tuesday, nor would they comment on whether
anything was confiscated there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other people were in the house, but he was the only one
arrested,'' Tull said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said that Harris also is a suspect in the disappearance
of Sandy Scott, 37, of Irving. Harris was seen with Scott shortly
before she disappeared Nov. 29, Tull said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was an acquaintance,'' Tull said. ``He was questioned
several times by investigators, but he has never been arrested in
connection with her disappearance.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott's family members and her former husband said on Tuesday
that they fear she is dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling is not good,'' said Michael Wright, Scott's
ex-husband. ``I expect the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   The lone survivor of Monday's shooting, which police said may
have been a botched robbery, is Octavio Ramos, 36, of Irving. He
was in critical condition at Parkland Memorial Hospital in Dallas,
a hospital spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The employees who died at the scene were identified as cashier
Rhoda Wheeler, 45, of Irving; assistant manager Dennis Lee, 48, of
Irving; and supervisor Agustin Villasenor, 36, of Arlington, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Villasenor's brother, Benjamin Villasenor, 32, of Irving, and
Roberto Jimenez Jr., 15, also of Irving, died later at Parkland
Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the shooting occurred between 7:30 and 7:40 a.m. The
carwash usually opens at 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were found about 7:40 a.m., police said.
</P>
<P>
   While police investigated, friends and relatives of the victims
visited the car wash. Rain and thunder didn't keep friends,
co-workers and carwash clients from bringing flowers and messages
for the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit too close to home,'' Gladys Arnaud, a cashier at
another Mi-T-Fine Car Wash in Irving, said as she placed daisies
and red carnations in front of the car wash where the shootings
took place.
</P>
<P>
   Many employees wore black ribbons to remember their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Harris had served almost eight years in prison for burglary
convictions in 1991, state records show.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most Texas prisoners in the early to mid-1990s, he served
almost his entire sentence, with few days credited for good
behavior, Texas Department of Criminal Justice spokesman Glen
Castlebury said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this guy had really applied himself in prison, he should
have been out ... in three years,'' Castlebury said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was moved several times among prison units, another
unusual occurrence in the Texas system, Castlebury said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris went to prison Sept. 25, 1991, and was released May 3
last year, records show. He was placed on parole _ also called
mandatory supervision _ for the remainder of his sentence and was
discharged June 27. He had since been unsupervised, Castlebury
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dallas suburb of Garland, where Harris grew up, he was
charged in two burglaries, Garland police spokesman Joel Bettes
said.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1990, Harris was arrested after a burglary at an auto
parts store, police said. In May 1991, he was arrested after police
investigating a burglary found him and another man hiding in nearby
bushes, Bettes said.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1991, Harris was charged with another burglary in a
Dallas County warrant.
</P>
<P>
   He pleaded guilty to all the charges and was sent to prison,
Bettes said.
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Gordon Dickson contributed to this report. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
