r s BC-CAR-MARTIN-BGN-TEX     03-21 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MARTIN-BGN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODD BODINE HAS CURE FOR MARTIN'S DOMINATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ With victories in three of four starts, Mark
Martin is threatening to turn his final season in NASCAR's Busch
Grand National Series into an impromptu ``Victory Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   How can anybody stop Martin?
</P>
<P>
   ``Put him in an equal race car. You want to hear it, I told
ya,'' series regular Todd Bodine said during a one-day media tour
at Texas Motor Speedway on Tuesday. ``Mark Martin is a tremendous
race-car driver, there's no question about that. But right now,
he's got a tremendous aerodynamic advantage and a substantial
horsepower advantage on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The BGN series is scheduled to make its lone appearance on TMS'
1.5-mile quadoval during the Albertson's 300 on April 1. It will be
the final appearance at TMS in a Busch car for Martin, winner of
the first BGN race here in 1997. Martin plans to confine his racing
to Winston Cup beginning in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, the BGN series' all-time victory leader with 43, drives
the Busch version of the 2000 Ford Taurus. Bodine drives the BGN
version of the 2000 Chevrolet Monte Carlo. NASCAR officials, Bodine
said, need to give the BGN Monte Carlo the same two-inch extension
to the bottom of its front valance that was granted the Winston Cup
version of the car before the Cracker Barrel 500 at Atlanta Motor
Speedway on March 12.
</P>
<P>
   The extension cured a chronic ``aero push'' problem on the front
end of the Monte Carlo, allowing it to carry speed through the
corners. In the first race after the rule change, seven-time Cup
champion Dale Earnhardt gave the 2000 Chevy its first victory in a
side-by-side sprint to the finish over Bobby Labonte's Pontiac
Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
   BGN points leader Matt Kenseth, Martin's Winston Cup teammate at
Roush Racing, won the Busch season-opener at the Daytona
International Speedway in a 2000 Chevy. Martin did not compete in
that event but has clicked off BGN victories at North Carolina
Speedway, AMS and Darlington. In the BGN race he entered but did
not win, Martin finished second to Roush stablemate Jeff Burton and
his Taurus at Las Vegas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Bodine, a 36-year-old native of Chemung, N.Y., is third in
series points heading into the Cheez-It 250 at Bristol Motor
Speedway on Saturday. Bodine said a critical factor being
overlooked is that the 9.5:1 compression ratio, 358 cubic-inch V-8
engines in Busch cars crank out approximately 200 fewer horsepower
than their Cup counterparts (720 HP to 520).
</P>
<P>
   ``And the Taurus, in terms of numbers, is 30 horsepower better
aerodynamically,'' said Bodine, driver of the No. 66 Phillips 66
Chevy. ``It takes 30 less horsepower to push it at the same speed
it takes a Monte Carlo. So that advantage, along with the
horsepower advantage along with the valance advantage ... you're
just not going to beat those Tauruses right now in Busch Grand
National.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4055 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CZECH-PHILHARMONIC-3R     03-21 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-PHILHARMONIC-3RDTAKE-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PRAGUE, Czech Republic: six digits.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Czech players' average salary corresponds to that of the
citizenry as a whole and is regulated to do so. ``The budget for
salaries is fixed,'' Sedlakova said. ``It is not possible to
increase salaries even for very good players.''
</P>
<P>
   State subsidies have declined steadily to about $1.3 million a
year. ``The subsidy now covers one-third of the budget,'' Sedlakova
said, ``and we still have the same regulations as if it were
subsidized 100 percent.'' Sponsorship from corporations like the
Investment and Postal Bank and Skoda Auto amounts to perhaps
$300,000. The rest has to be earned through ticket sales and tours.
</P>
<P>
   At least the players do not have to buy their own instruments.
They may use those of the institution, and Sedlakova said the
majority do. The players stand to make additional money by
moonlighting, playing chamber music or recording film music, and
Kristian said all do. A few, he added, also teach.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sums are pathetic, and even given a relatively low
cost of living in Prague, such a scale puts the orchestra at a
clear disadvantage in the international market for top musicians.
Of the 120 players, Ashkenazy said, only one is not Czech, and that
one is Slovakian. Here, to find a silver lining, is a reason the
orchestra has been able to retain some of its old character.
</P>
<P>
   And its old habits. Only five players are women: three
violinists, who joined the orchestra in recent years, and (the
classic dodge) two harpists. ``It totally changed the atmosphere of
the orchestra when women came in,'' Sedlakova said, declining to
elaborate much. ``It just changed. The building is not built to
separate men and women. There are few rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty in attracting players from outside the Czech
Republic has by no means been killing, obviously, since native
players have been good enough to lift the orchestra to its present
level. The worse problem is the converse: keeping the best Czech
players from accepting foreign opportunities, which are sure to
increase when the Czech Republic enters the European Union, perhaps
in 2003. Ashkenazy cited the case of a young Czech horn player who
eluded the orchestra's grasp, which he fears may become typical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not yet destructive, but it might be,'' he said. ``The
playing itself is still at a very high level, but the morale is not
so good. The players sit there with their arms folded, thinking we
will do something for them, because that's the way it was under
communism.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashkenazy seems to be trying his best to help. ``It takes a lot
of time and energy meeting with important people to find solutions,
meeting with this minister, that minister,'' he said. ``But if we
ever get to the point where we can do with our money what we like,
then we'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no one would specify Ashkenazy's salary, Parrott said
that ``his fees are substantially below his international level,
but they are at least honorable.'' He is maintaining most of the
busy schedule to which he was already committed elsewhere before
coming to the aid of the orchestra. He spends six or seven weeks a
season with the Czech Philharmonic in Prague, he said, and another
six or seven weeks on tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if he could be here more,'' Sedlakova said.
She pointed out that although he had not yet taken part in player
auditions, in which he is supposed to have a vote, she hoped he
might make one next month for an opening in the horn section.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when he (italics)is(end italics) here he does his
utmost,'' she added. ``The time of conductors like Ancerl and
Neumann is another world. Even if we had a very good Czech
conductor, he would mostly be abroad. The main thing is to be in
touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashkenazy says he hopes to spend more time in Prague, and he is
not in any case trying to drum up new business. ``I don't like to
guest-conduct so much,'' said this most self-effacing maestro (if
that is not in fact an oxymoron). ``I'm too shy. I like to
establish relationships.'' His contract with the Czech Philharmonic
runs until next year, and an extension is being negotiated,
doubtless with understandable caution on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We mustn't be too pessimistic,'' Ashkenazy said of the many
difficulties still ahead of him and the orchestra. ``We can't
predict everything. But it would be a shame to lose a great
orchestra, because you (italics)might(end italics) lose it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
