<P>
   (NYT36) PHILADELPHIA -- March 21, 2000 -- SCOTUS-TOBACCO-2 --
The Supreme Court on Tuesday dealt a sharp blow to the Clinton
administration's effort to curb smoking, ruling 5 to 4 that the
Food and Drug Administration had never received authority from
Congress to regulate tobacco products. The decision, rejecting
rules proposed by the agency in 1995 to restrict the marketing of
cigarettes to children and teenagers, hands the question of
national tobacco regulation back to Congress. Justice Stephen G.
Breyer wrote that the FDA had authority over tobacco as a public
health matter. (Laura Pedrick/The New York Times)
