<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     03-21 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT VISOR DEBATE IN HOCKEY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hockey advertises itself as the world's fastest game, but the
safety of its players has always come slowly, if not reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   Goaltenders never wore a mask until 1959, when Jacques Plante
returned to the ice wearing one after having several stitches to
close a facial wound from a sizzling puck. When helmets were made
mandatory in 1979 for players entering the National Hockey League,
established players, notably Craig MacTavish, were allowed to
finish their careers without a helmet if they so preferred.
</P>
<P>
   And even after the 23-year-old defenseman Bryan Berard's
frightful eye injury on March 11, most NHL players continue to
spurn a protective plastic eye visor.
</P>
<P>
   Berard, accidentally struck in the right eye by the stick-blade
of Ottawa's Marian Hossa, underwent exploratory surgery Tuesday at
Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center. If he doesn't regain his
sight in that eye, his career is over; the NHL does not allow a
player to risk losing his sight in both eyes.
</P>
<P>
   You would think that several of Berard's teammates on the
Toronto Maple Leafs would have hurried to put on a visor in order
to protect themselves from a similar injury, but only one did,
Sergei Berezin; three others have worn a visor all season _ Yanic
Perreault, Nikolai Antropov and Alyn McCauley.
</P>
<P>
   In the great visor debate, the other Maple Leafs and most NHL
players think that a visor is either too hot, too foggy or too
cumbersome, if not too sissified. As if they were exempt from a
stick in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Although the NHL office, according to Frank Brown, its vice
president for media relations, ``would be happy'' to discuss the
mandatory use of visors with the NHL Players Association, the union
position is that wearing a visor should be up to each player.
</P>
<P>
   The union's director of business relations, Mike Gartner, the
fifth-leading career goal scorer with 708 in 19 seasons, endorses
that stance even though he wore a visor most of his career after a
serious eye injury; he couldn't see out of his left eye for two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the benefits of a visor far outweigh the risks, but I
believe in a player's choice,'' Gartner has said. ``Hockey in
itself is a dangerous game even if you were to go out there in full
body armor.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ken Dryden, the Hall of Fame goaltender of another era who
is now the Maple Leafs' president, predicted that eventually ``the
visor will happen'' throughout the NHL, just as helmets and
goaltenders' masks happened, and that more players will use visors
in training camp next September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they will be willing to wear a visor after thinking it
over during the summer,'' Dryden said.
</P>
<P>
   Dryden remembered that it took two or three seasons after Plante
pioneered the mask before another NHL goaltender, Terry Sawchuk,
wore a mask.
</P>
<P>
   Other goaltenders of that era complained that a mask was too
heavy, too hot, too restrictive of their vision _ not that
different from the later complaints about a helmet and the current
complaints about a visor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a 12-year-old goaltender without a mask when Plante wore
the mask for the first time,'' Dryden said. ``I didn't wear a mask
until 1965, my freshman year at Cornell, when I had to wear one.
And years later the helmet to the other players was like the mask
to the goaltenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as they had to wear a helmet, they found out it wasn't
so bad after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 New Jersey Devils who wear a visor, six are from
Europe, where a visor is mandatory in some countries. After
Berard's injury, the Devils' young John Madden put on a visor but
found it too distracting.
</P>
<P>
   Only five Rangers, notably Brian Leetch, regularly wear a visor.
John MacLean is also wearing one following a recent eye injury.
Theo Fleury has worn one occasionally. Mathieu Schneider wore a
visor at two Garden games last week after Berard's injury but on
the road over the weekend, he didn't like the way it fit his blue
road helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Two Islanders, Olli Jokinen and Dmitri Nabokov, have worn visors
since Berard's injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Berard incident definitely opened my eyes,'' said Jokinen,
who wore a visor in his native Finland. ``I don't care if people
call me chicken. My sight and my career are more important.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the great visor debate, too many NHL players' eyes are
still closed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
