<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4059 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      03-21 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Gerry Hunsicker has orchestrated blockbuster
deals and kept the Astros on top in the National League Central
despite limited resources.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But ask him about the toughest decision he has had to make since
taking over as the Astros' general manager prior to the 1996
season, and he'll tell you it's staring him right in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Seven infielders, six outfielders or three catchers? That's the
dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   All three totals would represent one more player than normally
carried on a conventional 25-man roster. But the Astros' success
over the past few years has not come without a few gambles or
unconventional means of getting the job done.
</P>
<P>
   Managing the roster is Hunsicker's primary task at this time of
year. To the casual fan, the six weeks of spring training is an
exercise designed to determine the best 25 players in camp, those
worthy of a spot on the opening-day roster.
</P>
<P>
   But with apologies to purists, opening day is a bit overrated.
Fact is, few teams actually leave spring training with their best
25 players. Inevitably, circumstances dictate that at least a
couple of worthy candidates start the season in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   In the Astros' case, those players could include the likes of
Glen Barker and Mitch Meluskey. Both belong in the majors, but
neither is assured of a spot because they still have options and
are competing against players who are out of options. Players who
are out of options must clear waivers before they can be sent to
the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be a couple of people who don't make this
team who haven't done anything to play themselves off the club,''
Hunsicker said. ``It's really going to come down to what areas we
want to protect the most, which weapons we think are most valuable.
Part of it is evaluating how (manager) Larry (Dierker) manages _
the moves he likes to make, what he likes to do and how people will
be utilized.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the players the Astros decide to begin the season
with might not be the same players taking the field in September.
They used 36 players last season, mainly because injuries forced
them to use the disabled list 16 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be lucky to get out of April with the 25 guys we leave
here with,'' Dierker said. ``It's not how you start; it's how you
finish that counts. To me, depth doesn't end with the 25th man on
the big-league roster. It ends with the 10th guy at Triple-A. You'd
like to have all of the positions backed up. Regardless of where
the depth is spread out, it's still important.''
</P>
<P>
   It's up to Hunsicker to make certain that depth is available.
When it looks like the Astros have too many outfielders because
Daryle Ward and Lance Berkman are not in the starting lineup, it's
because Hunsicker knows how quickly injuries can change the face of
a team.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker could have traded either player 10 times over, but
doing so would have significantly weakened the Astros' overall
depth.
</P>
<P>
   Ward will be on the opening-day roster as the Astros' fourth
outfielder, and Hunsicker said it's possible that both Barker and
Matt Mieske _ the two players competing for what was believed to be
the final spot in the outfield _ will make the team.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker also said opening the season with three catchers is a
possibility, although it's something the club never has done under
the current regime. Tony Eusebio and Paul Bako appear to be locks,
although Meluskey's spring has been impossible to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the final decision, it will be made with the idea of
controlling inventory in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been agonizing over this decision as much as any decision
since I've been here,'' Hunsicker said. ``You can make a case for
all of the options. We're going to have to make some tough
decisions, but either way I think we're going to be OK as far as
depth.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
