<P>
   (NYT46) NEW YORK -- March 21, 2000 -- NY-CHURCH-VANDALISM --
Since Sept. 26, Catholics across Brooklyn have watched with
consternation and sadness as the faces of statues have been
shattered, their arms and hands torn off, in front of churches,
convents, a Knights of Columbus hall and even a private house.
Evidence that might lead to a suspect, though, has been scant.
Statues of St. Francis of Assisi, left, and the Virgin Mary that
have recently been vandalized. (Steve Berman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT45) UNDATED -- March 21, 2000 -- ARTIST-LAWSUIT-5 -- In
voluminous papers filed in a London court Tuesday, lawyers for
Bacon's estate charged, among other accusations, that the
Marlborough Gallery looted tens of millions of dollars from the
British artist, who died in 1992. An invoice for the sale of this
painting, ``Study from the Human Body,'' 1983, by Bacon, shows the
work was sold by the Marlborough Gallery in December of that year
for $250,000, but had been purchased from Bacon by the gallery
seven months earlier for $70,823. Georgianna Gibbs, a spokeswoman
for Marlborough London, said that Bacon's relationship with the
gallery was not a passive one and that the artist was aware of the
gallery's activities and transactions on his behalf. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT44) UNDATED -- March 21, 2000 -- ARTIST-LAWSUIT-4 -- In
voluminous papers filed in a London court Tuesday, lawyers for the
estate of Francis Bacon charged that the Marlborough Gallery looted
tens of millions of dollars from the British artist. Records show
that the Marlborough Gallery underpaid Bacon in transactions
regarding his ``Statue and Figures in a Street,'' 1983. Georgianna
Gibbs, a spokeswoman for Marlborough London, said that Bacon's
relationship with the gallery was not a passive one and that the
artist was aware of the gallery's activities and transactions on
his behalf. (The New York Times)
