<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4064 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-DIABETES-DRUG-1STLD-W     03-21 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIABETES-DRUG-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIABETES DRUG LINKED TO LIVER FAILURE TO BE REMOVED FROM MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for additional details throughout; story grows by about 300
words)  
 (Eds: This story has been added to the New York Times front page)  
 (sw)  
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration announced Tuesday evening that
Rezulin, a diabetes drug linked to liver failure, would be removed
from the market immediately.
</P>
<P>
   About half a million Americans are now taking the drug, and the
FDA urged them not to stop without first contacting their doctors
to obtain other treatment, including two recently approved safer
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Rezulin, also known by the generic name troglitazone, has been
prescribed to lower blood sugar in people with Type 2, or
adult-onset, diabetes, the most common form of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, which is manufactured by Parke-Davis, a division of
Warner-Lambert Co. of Morris Plains, N.J., had been criticized by
consumer safety groups and generated negative news reports during
the last year, because in rare instances it caused serious liver
damage and death.
</P>
<P>
   Since its introduction in March 1997, Rezulin has been linked to
90 cases of liver failure, resulting in 63 deaths and necessitating
10 liver transplants, according to the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the transplant recipients died. Ten other patients
recovered from severe liver failure, and 10 others are still
suffering from that condition.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of cases of liver failure was small compared with
the 1.9 million people who have taken the drug at one time or
another, and the FDA initially decided to keep Rezulin on the
market despite the risk, because it had a unique mode of action and
did help many patients.
</P>
<P>
   When Rezulin was marketed in 1997, it was the first in a class
of drugs that lowered blood sugar by making the body more sensitive
to insulin, the hormone that regulates blood sugar levels. In 1999,
the FDA approved two other drugs in the same class, Actos, marketed
by Eli Lilly &AMP; Co. and Takeda Chemical Industries, and Avandia,
made by SmithKline Beecham PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Rezulin was the subject of a contentious FDA hearing a year ago,
in response to reports of 43 cases of liver failure, including 28
deaths. That hearing, which drew an overflow crowd of doctors,
patients, drug company executives and consumer advocates, resulted
in a decision to leave the drug on the market, but with the
recommendations that it be used only when other therapies did not
work, and that its label carry strong warnings about potential
liver toxicity and the need for regular blood tests.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Janet Woodcock, director of the Center for Drug Evaluation
and Research at the FDA, said the agency had changed its position
on Rezulin because data on the two newer drugs showed them to be
safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that they don't pose the kind of liver
toxicity that Rezulin does,'' Woodcock said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the newer drugs might also cause liver abnormalities,
but were not as risky as Rezulin.
</P>
<P>
   Patients taking Actos and Avandia, like those on Rezulin, are
told that they must have regular liver tests so that they can stop
taking the drug if abnormalities show up.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Murray Lumpkin, deputy director of the evaluation center,
said that if the two newer drugs had not become available, the FDA
would probably have left Rezulin on the market, because it was
important to have a drug of its type available.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now we have other products that can give patients the same
benefit without having to assume that risk,'' Lumpkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Corr, president of research and development for
Warner-Lambert/Parke-Davis, said, ``This certainly did take us by
surprise. We still believe that the benefits outweigh the risks and
that this drug produces enormous benefits for patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Corr said the company would write letters to doctors telling
them that Rezulin was taken off the market, but he said he did not
know whether patients would be given refunds for leftover supplies
of the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Rezulin in 1999 totaled $773 million, according to IMS
Health, a company that tracks the drug industry. Avandia had sales
of $133 million that year, its first year on the market. Actos had
$60 million in sales. But by February of this year, doctors had
begun writing more prescriptions for Avandia than for Rezulin.
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials said they were still reviewing allegations made
last week by Public Citizen's Health Research Group, a consumer
safety group, claiming that Parke-Davis knew of the drug's liver
toxicity before it was approved, but delayed compiling and sending
that information to the FDA until after Rezulin was marketed. The
company said the allegations were false. Public Citizen has been
calling for Rezulin's recall for more than a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
