<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-MAIN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ruling reaffirms right of Elian's father to decide boy's future
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat and Monika Gonzalez Mesa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Family members fighting to keep Elian Gonzalez in the
United States lost a critical decision Tuesday when a federal judge
ruled that U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno was on solid ground
when she ordered the 6-year-old boy returned to his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Reno acted within her authority when she denied Elian the right
to apply for political asylum, U.S. District Judge K. Michael Moore
said in a 50-page order that reaffirmed the father's right to
decide the boy's future.
</P>
<P>
   Moore made a plainly worded appeal that Elian's interests be
placed above all others, saying ``each passing day is another day
lost between Juan Gonzalez and his son.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami remained calm Tuesday, unlike the explosive street
demonstrations that followed the federal government's January
announcement that Elian would be returned to his father, a hotel
worker who lives near the Varadero resort on Cuba's north coast.
Elian's mother drowned during her sea journey to bring her son to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Grim-faced relatives told reporters in Miami on Tuesday they
will now rely on faith to keep the boy in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to lose. We're going to keep praying,'' Lazaro
Gonzalez, the boy's great-uncle who filed the lawsuit seeking
asylum for Elian, told about 25 supporters who waited throughout
the afternoon outside his home, still adorned with Christmas
lights. The supporters held open a 14-foot Cuban flag and
alternated between protest chants against President Clinton and
support chants for Elian. They prayed and sang the Cuban national
anthem.
</P>
<P>
   About 6 p.m. Lazaro Gonzalez returned with Elian, who smiled,
held up both hands way above his head and waved at the crowd before
shyly running to the fence outside the modest home.
</P>
<P>
   To discourage a sudden deportation of Elian, his attorneys filed
an appeal just before 5 p.m. to challenge Moore's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she is evaluating whether the INS will return Elian to
Cuba before appeals are exhausted, adding that it's her goal to
reunite the boy with his father as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for this little boy, who has been through so much,
to move on with his life at his father's side,'' Reno told
reporters. She declined to reveal when and how a reunification
would take place, but said it would be ``orderly, fair and
prompt.''
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization Service spokesman Russ Bergeron
said the agency was beginning ``to move forward on the process''
for returning the boy. ``There could be any number of options
involved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If appeals drag on for months, immigration experts say Elian
might qualify under a controversial U.S. law that allows Cubans to
apply for permanent residency after spending a year on U.S. soil.
Elian would be eligible Nov. 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say the government has a victory, but it might
be a pyrrhic victory because of the period of time under the Cuban
Adjustment Act,'' said Bernard Perlmutter, director of the
University of Miami's Children and Youth Law Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   While family members said they would accept a court ruling on
Elian's fate, one of their attorneys said Moore's three-hour
hearing March 9 was not sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian has not had his day in court,'' said Spencer Eig, an
attorney for Lazaro Gonzalez. ``But today's ruling gives us hope
that after we complete the entire legal process, including appeals
and reconsiderations, he just may.''
</P>
<P>
   Another attorney says the failure of the boy's father to
retrieve his son is suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 3 1/2 months he has not come for his child,'' said
Kendall Coffey, the former U.S. attorney for South Florida who is
working with the Miami family. ``We assume that if by now he has
not come it is either because he cannot come or he will not come.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys appealed Moore's decision to the 11th Circuit
Court of Appeals in Atlanta and said they would go to the U.S.
Supreme Court if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But the INS routinely deports undocumented immigrants who lose
lower court decisions unless the appeals court issues an order to
suspend actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family's appeal does not stay the judge's order,'' said
Ira Kurzban, a prominent immigration attorney in Miami. ``In
comparable situations, the attorney general will simply deport
somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore said Elian cannot claim he was denied his constitutional
rights because he was not legally admitted into the United States
as an immigrant. While most Cubans intercepted at sea are
repatriated, Elian was transported to a hospital for humanitarian
reasons and was allowed a temporary stay until his immigration
status could be determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian's recorded past is a profile of survival and courage in
the face of adversity and the loss of his mother at sea,'' Moore
wrote in his decision. ``His future will undoubtedly unfold in due
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, where mass demonstrations for Elian's return have been
a weekly routine since December, newscasters Tuesday advised Cubans
``not to fall into false optimism or excessive hope'' over the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the ruling, Moore's entire decision was posted
on the Web site for Cuba's Communist Party newspaper Granma under a
daily update on the ``kidnapping of Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling renewed political debate in Washington over the boy's
fate.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Connie Mack (R-Fla.), who has sponsored a bill to grant
Elian American citizenship, said he was ``disappointed in the
federal court's decision and (Reno's) judgment in denying a
political asylum hearing to a boy who survived the seas in an
escape of an oppressive regime.'' An aide to Mack said no decision
had been made on whether to revive the citizenship bill, which has
been languishing since the courts became involved in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum (R-Fla.), who filed a companion citizenship
bill in the House, said the court's decision ``leaves no recourse
except for Congress to take the matter out of the hands of the INS
and allow this child's case to be decided by a custody hearing in a
Florida state court ... which can only happen now if Elian is
granted U.S. citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for House Government Reform Committee Chairman Dan
Burton (R-Ind.), who had subpoenaed Elian in January in an attempt
to thwart any sudden effort to return him to Cuba, said there were
no plans to have the boy testify before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush on Tuesday
suggested custody of Elian be decided by a state court, ``not by a
Clinton-Gore Justice Department whose record of putting politics
ahead of the law does not inspire confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   A family judge in Miami-Dade County awarded temporary legal
custody of Elian to Lazaro Gonzalez but has not taken further
action. Moore said in his decision that he had no comment on the
state court, which is not binding on INS decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban exile radio stations in Miami lamented Tuesday's events
while protest organizers prepared to meet this morning to discuss
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martyrdom can happen while you are still living,'' said Jose
Basulto, president of Brothers to the Rescue, one of the groups in
January's protests. ``That's what he's going to become if he goes
back _ a posterchild for Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for an anti-Castro group in West Palm Beach that
contributed to the Gonzalez family defense fund said Elian would be
subject to repression and indoctrination if returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would go back into the hands of the devil, which is Fidel
Castro,'' said Franciso Tabernilla, secretary of Pro-Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But some U.S. officials think allowing Elian to stay could
disrupt efforts to recover American children pirated abroad by a
foreign parent.
</P>
<P>
   Mary A. Ryan, assistant secretary of state for consular affairs,
said in a sworn statement cited in Elian's case that failure to
reunite Elian with his father will weaken the ability of American
parents and their government in their bid to have these children
returned home.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post staff writer Larry Lipman, free-lance writer
Siobhan Morrissey and The Associated Press contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
