<P>
   (NYT40) NEW YORK -- March 21, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
TV-WONDERLAND -- Peter Berg is the creator and sometime writer and
director of ``Wonderland,'' a new ABC drama set in a psychiatric
hospital. Berg, 37, said the idea for the show had been tugging at
him for years. The question is whether a drama about psychiatric
patients and their doctors will prove simply too unsettling to
network audinces accustomed to sitcom humor and twentysomething
angst. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) NEW YORK -- March 21, 2000 -- GORE -- Vice President Al
Gore visited Lenox Hill Neighborhood House in Manhattan on Tuesday
to talk about the census count. The 3- and 4-year-olds drew
pictures of their families and discussed them with Gore. (Ruby
Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) MIAMI -- March 21, 2000 -- CUBAN-BOY-2 -- The effort by
the Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez to prevent his return to his
father in Cuba was stymied Tuesday when a federal judge dismissed a
lawsuit requesting a poltical asylum hearing for the 6-year-old
boy, concluding that the long, bitter legal battle is not in
Elian's best interest. The boy's Miami relatives left the Miami
Federal Courthouse on Tuesday. From left, Lazaro Gonzalez, great
uncle, Marisleysis Gonzalez, great aunt, and Delfin Gonzalez, great
uncle. (Greg Lovett/The Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) MIAMI -- March 21, 2000 -- CUBAN-BOY -- The effort by
the Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez to prevent his return to his
father in Cuba was stymied Tuesday when a federal judge dismissed a
lawsuit requesting a poltical asylum hearing for the 6-year-old
boy, concluding that the long, bitter legal battle is not in
Elian's best interest. Margarita Hernandez, a missionary, led a
prayer in front of Elian's relatives' home in Miami on Tuesday for
those who want him to remain in the United States. (Laura
Kleinhenz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) PHILADELPHIA -- March 21, 2000 -- SCOTUS-TOBACCO-2 --
The Supreme Court on Tuesday dealt a sharp blow to the Clinton
administration's effort to curb smoking, ruling 5 to 4 that the
Food and Drug Administration had never received authority from
Congress to regulate tobacco products. The decision, rejecting
rules proposed by the agency in 1995 to restrict the marketing of
cigarettes to children and teenagers, hands the question of
national tobacco regulation back to Congress. Justice Stephen G.
Breyer wrote that the FDA had authority over tobacco as a public
health matter. (Laura Pedrick/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NETANYA, Israel -- March 21, 2000 -- POPE-HOLYLAND-PALS
-- Yosef Bienenstock, 80, at his brother's relocated grave in
Israel. Bienenstock's family had lived in the Polish town of
Wadowice, where they grew up next door to Lolek, a brainy Catholic
kid who went on to become Pope John Paul II. Bienenstock returned
to get his little brother's bones in 1992. Expecting a tin
tombstone, he found a marble monument in its place. ``How can this
be?'' he asked the gravekeeper, who explained that the pope had
visited, and had quietly replaced his former neighbor's pathetic
grave marker. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) GADINGAN, Indonesia -- March 21, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MARCH 26 -- JAVA-PUPPET-THEATER-3 -- In Java, the world's most
populous island and the political and cultural center of Indonesia,
the traditional drama still mainly survives the way it has for
centuries: by popular demand. Itinerant puppeteers, known as
dalangs, travel from village to village, performing the ancient
tales of gods and demons, heroes and fools, for anyone with the
wherewithal to hire them. Warsad Darya, one of the most
accomplished of the surviving wayang cepak masters, with one of the
carriages he has carved and painted. (Jamie James/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) GADINGAN, Indonesia -- March 21, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MARCH 26 -- JAVA-PUPPET-THEATER-2 -- In most cultures, puppets
imitate human actors; in Java and the neighboring island of Bali,
the reverse is true. The traditional dramas have always been
performed with puppets; indeed, the Indonesian word for puppet,
wayang, is used to denote the various forms of the drama. A crowd
of puppet characters in the tradition of wayang cepak awaited the
spotlight in Gadingan, on Java. (Lontar Foundation/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) GADINGAN, Indonesia -- March 21, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MARCH 26 -- JAVA-PUPPET-THEATER-1 -- In Java, the world's most
populous island and the political and cultural center of Indonesia,
the traditional drama still mainly survives the way it has for
centuries: by popular demand. Itinerant puppeteers, known as
dalangs, travel from village to village, performing the ancient
tales of gods and demons, heroes and fools, for anyone with the
wherewithal to hire them. Warsad Darya worked his stick puppets
during a performance in Gadingan. (Lontar Foundation/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) UNDATED -- March 21, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
ZAMPA-OPERA-B&AMP;W -- Ferdinand Herrold's opera, ``Zampa,'' was
introduced to wild acclaim at the Opera-Comique in Paris in 1831,
and remained a fixture in European opera houses throughout the 19th
century. On April 3, at Alice Tully Hall, a concert revival by
L'Opera Francais de New York restores the work in what is said to
be the opera's first New York airing in more than a hundred years.
In an illustration from a 19th-century score, Zampa, the pirate,
confronts the fateful statue. (Bibliotheque Musicale Illustree/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) PORT WASHINGTON, N.Y. -- March 21, 2000 --
ROMANIAN-PRIZEWINNER -- Last week, Viviana Risca of Paul D.
Schreiber High School in Port Washington won the nationwide Intel
Science Talent Search (and a $100,000 scholarship) with a project
that encoded a secret message within a strand of DNA. Risca, 17,
first became ``a research groupie'' on the day in ninth grade in
which DNA was explained to her. ``I hell in love with biology,''
she said. (Vic DeLucia/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) BASKING RIDGE, N.J. -- March 21, 2000 -- WAYWARD-STATUES
-- Sixteen years after carting the 4-story-high Golden Boy on his
global pedestal from Manhattan to Basking Ridge, AT&AMP;T officials
have acknowledged what might, to some, have seemed obvious. Golden
Boy belongs in New York City, where he lived since he was created
as a symbol of AT&AMP;T in 1916. Golden Boy -- aka, the Spirit of
Communication, and the Genius of Electricity -- is too dramatic and
too big for quiet suburban life. (Normon Y. Lono/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) TAIPEI, Taiwan -- March 21, 2000 -- TAIWAN-POLITICS-2 --
Less than a week after an opposition candidate was elected
president of Taiwan, ending more than 50 years of Nationalist rule,
the mood here varies from outright jubilation to guarded relief.
``Chen Shui-bian's victory is a great step, but I feel my wish has
been compromised,'' said Koo Kwang-ming, 74, who spent decades in
exile in Japan promoting his Taiwan Independence Union while under
indictment at home for treason. (Erik Eckholm/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) TAIPEI, Taiwan -- March 21, 2000 -- TAIWAN-POLITICS-1 --
Less than a week after an opposition candidate was elected
president of Taiwan, ending more than 50 years of Nationalist rule,
the mood here varies from guarded relief to outright jubilation.
``My dream has come true,'' said Hsieh Tsung-min, 64, an early hero
of the democracy and independence movement on the island. Hsieh was
convicted of treason in 1964 for drafting a ``Declaration for the
Taiwanese People,'' and spent more than 11 torture-filled years in
prison. (Erik Eckholm/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) TEL AVIV, Israel -- March 21, 2000 -- POPE-HOLYLAND-2 --
With Israel's Prime Minister Ehud Barak at right, Pope John Paul II
was helped by Israeli President Ezer Weizman on Tuesday as they
walked from the plane that brought the pope for a six day
pilgrimage to the Holy Land - the first official visit by a Roman
Catholic pope to Israel. The pope declared after landing in Tel
Aviv that he felt ``deep emotion'' on setting foot ``in the land
where God chose to pitch his tent.'' (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- March 21, 2000 -- MCCAIN-SENATE -- Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., talks to reporters on Capitol Hill, Tuesday.
With little warning to his colleagues, McCain wandered alone into
the Senate this morning to deliver his first speech since he
withdrew from the presidential campaign. But instead of delivering
condemnations of soft money in Washington politics, the hallmarks
of his unsuccessful race for the Republican presidential
nomination, McCain instead chose to talk about his assessment of
the NATO deployment in Kosovo. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- March 21, 2000 -- SCOTUS-TOBACCO -- The
Supreme Court on Tuesday dealt a sharp if not entirely unexpected
blow to the Clinton Administration's effort to curb smoking, ruling
5 to 4 that the Food and Drug Administration had never received
authority from Congress to regulate tobacco products. The decision,
rejecting rules proposed by the agency in 1995 to restrict the
marketing of cigarettes to children and teenagers, hands the
question of national tobacco regulation back to Congress. Smokers
on a break outside a Manhattan office building. (Angel Franco/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- March 21, 2000 -- DOTCOM-MANAGE -- Wenda
Harris Millard is executive vice president of DoubleClick, a
company that tracks consumers' use of the Internet. ``I am a media
junkie,'' she said. ``This is what I eat for breakfast and snack on
at midnight. There hasn't been a new medium in 50 years, and the
Internet is beyond a medium - it's a marketplace. So the idea of
being right smack in the middle of inventing a new medium, how much
better could it get?'' (Philip Greenberg/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) CHICAGO -- March 21, 2000 -- JOFFREY-BALLET -- Five
years after severe financial problems pointed to the possible
demise of one of America's most popular ballet troupes, its move
from New York (involving a legal reorganization and name change
from Joffrey Ballet to Joffrey Ballet of Chicago) offers a lesson
in rescue strategy. ``I'm a Chicagoan,'' said Gerald Arpino,
artistic director of the the troupe and a longtime resident of
Greenwich Village, with a straight face, adding convincingly, ``I
gave up my apartment in New York.'' (Todd Buchanan/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- March 21, 2000 -- AIDA-PASCAL -- Adam
Pascal, who plays the Egyptian warrior Radames in Disney's musical
``Aida,'' will also have a collection of his rock songs released
over the Internet. ``This record is the first time I've allowed
myself to write music purely, without trying to direct it to a
certain audience,'' he said. ``Whether people like it or not, I
feel a huge sense of accomplishment.'' (Sara Krulwich/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- March 21, 2000 -- JERUSALEM-FILM-REVIEW --
Jaffa Road in the early 1900s, in Ron Havilio's ``Fragments:
Jerusalem,'' a six-hour film being shown at the New Directors/New
Films series Wednesday through April 6. The film captures the
history of Jerusalem, where Havilio was born in 1950, and mixes it
with the history of his own family, which traces its history there
for centuries. The result is worthy and ambitious but somewhat
soporific. (Film Society of Lincoln Center/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) MICKLETON, England -- March 21, 2000 --
ENGLISH-PUDDINGS-3 -- In Britain, a fabulous array of soft, warm,
sweet puddings - so many that a resourceful Mum could easily turn
out a different one every day of the month - light up childhood
mealtimes and linger in adult memory. The Sussex Pond pudding got
its name because the juice of a lemon steamed within it forms a
tiny ``pond.'' The lemon itself emerges soft enough to cut with a
fork. (Jonathan Player/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) MICKLETON, England -- March 21, 2000 --
ENGLISH-PUDDINGS-2 -- In Britain, pudding is the quintessential
nursery food, comforting to both body and spirit, and you will find
it on the menus of proletarian pubs and elitist clubs alike.
Spotted dick (aka spotted dog) pudding from the Pudding Club at
Three Ways House in Mickleton - started in 1985 by a bunch of
die-hard chauvinists determined to beat back the assault of frozen
supermarket Black Forest gateaux. (Jonathan Player/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) MICKLETON, England -- March 21, 2000 --
ENGLISH-PUDDINGS-1 -- In Britain, a fabulous array of soft, warm,
sweet puddings light up childhood mealtimes and linger reassuringly
decades later in the memories of 50-somethings and 60-somethings.
Nichola Parkinson with sticky toffee pudding at the Sharrow Bay
Country House Hotel. Spongelike, with fragments of crust here and
there, the pudding is bathed in a viscous butterscotch sauce, with
ice-cold cream poured over the whole shooting match at the last
minute. (Jonathan Player/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- March 21, 2000 -- WINE-TALK -- In the past
few years about 20 places calling themselves wine bars have opened
in New York, some to considerable acclaim. Enoteca, the wine bar at
I Trulli, sells only Italian wines. (Thomas Dallal/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- March 21, 2000 -- KITCHEN-WARES -- A
shallow, heavy-steel crepe pan is the perfect tool for making a
thin potato tart, above. After being browned on the stove and
finished off in the oven, the crispy tart slides easily out of the
pan, below. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- March 21, 2000 -- SOUR-ORANGE -- On the
surface, it is not one of nature's most beautiful creations: a
bumpy, blotchy thick skin encasing a pale, seedy yellow pulp. The
beauty of a sour orange is revealed in the kitchen, where its
spicy, flowery fragrance is like no other citrus. It can adapt to a
wide range of cuisines, melding savory and sweet flavors and
perking them up with an exotic, fruity tang. (Tony Cenicola/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- March 21, 2000 -- MEAT-RAVIOLI -- Of 52
restaurants informally surveyed in Manhattan, only eight served
meat ravioli - and not one of them was in Little Italy. ``In Italy
I learn the authentic way,'' said Gianni Garavelli, with a pan of
his version of the hard to find treat at Bravo Gianni, his
restaurant on the Upper East Side. ``I make for my family, but it's
a very laborious dish.'' (Carol Halebian/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MONTGOMERY, Ala. -- March 21, 2000 -- AL-AMIN-MAIN-3-COX
-- Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, formerly known as H. Rap Brown, is led
from the local jail to federal court for his arraignment, Tuesday.
Three days after he was accused of shooting to death of a sheriff's
deputy near downtown Atlanta, the former civil rights leader was
arrested Monday night in an Alabama field after an exchange of
gunfire. (Ben Gray/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MUCHEKE, Zimbabwe -- March 21, 2000 --
AFRICA-AIDSORPHANS-5-COX -- Tinashe Cami has known for some time
that he's not healthy. He's on the verge of 16, yet he is so small
and frail that he could easily be mistaken for 10 or 11. A recent
test shows he is HIV-positive. Having lost both his mother and the
woman he came to regard as an aunt to AIDS. he feels fortunate
because a local group pays for his school fees and uniform. His
aunt's sister allows him to remain in the house, where he has lived
the nine years since his mother's death. ``I want to be a soldier
and a teacher,'' he says about his future. (Seamus Conlan/The Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MBARE, Zimbabwe -- March 21, 2000 --
AFRICA-AIDSORPHANS-4-COX --Nomsa Mwale, 12, center, with her
siblings, from left, Garikai, 9; Shonia, 10; and Betina, 8, in a
one-room shed in the backyard of their late grandparentsU house.
Nomsa's father died of AIDS in 1998. Six months ago, her mother
followed him. Their life is a frenzy of survival guided by little
more than the advice given by their mother as she prepared her
children for their journey without her. (Seamus Conlan/The Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MUTOKO, Zimbabwe -- March 21, 2000 --
AFRICA-AIDSORPHANS-3-COX -- Jean Cornneck, known as Momma Jean,
holds a two-month old baby which was dropped off at her orphanage,
the Mother of Peace home. More than half the AIDS orphans in the
country end up under the care of their grandparents or orphanages
with little support or assistance from the government. At the home,
volunteers have built a dozen cottages for its residents and
Corneck tries to make the facility self-sufficient by farming. Some
80 children are taken cared of at the home. (Seamus Conlan/The Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MUTOKO, Zimbabwe -- March 21, 2000 --
AFRICA-AIDSORPHANS-2-COX -- More than half the AIDS orphans in the
country end up under the care of their grandparents or orphanages
with little support or assistance from the government. At the
Mother of Peace home run by Jean Cornneck volunteers have built a
dozen cottages for its residents and Corneck tries to make the
facility self-sufficient by farming. Some 80 children are taken
cared of at the home. (Seamus Conlan/The Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MBARE, Zimbabwe -- March 21, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH
26 -- AFRICA-AIDSORPHANS-1-COX -- Lina Smoke, 88, with her
four-year old grandson Terrence, in a shack just outside the
Zimbabwean capital which has been her home for 20 years. Two years
ago, Terrence and his three siblings came to her after their mother
died of AIDS. Their father was already dead from an AIDS-related
illness. More than half the AIDS orphans in the country end up
under the care of their grandmothers. As little support and
assistance as there is for AIDS orphans, there is even less for
grandmothers like Smoke. (Seamus Conlan/The Cox News Service) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) TEL AVIV, Israel -- March 21, 2000 -- POPE-HOLYLAND --
With a flourish of trumpets and the reading of biblical psalms, an
aging, ailing Pope John Paul II on Tuesday began the first official
visit by a Roman Catholic pontiff to the Jewish state. Israeli
President Ezer Weizman, sixth from right, and his wife, Reuma,
stand with John Paul, second from right, and Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak, during arriavl ceremonies at Ben Gurion airport near
Tel Aviv late Tuesday. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- March 21, 2000 -- REAGAN-ALZHEIMERS-COX --
Maureen Reagan, daughter of former President Ronald Reagan, as she
listens to the testimony of a patient suffering from Alzheimer's
disease before the Senate Appropriations subcommittee on health,
Tuesday. During her testimony before the committee, Reagan said
more money is needed to help combat Alzheimer's disease which has
ravaged her father and will strike even more Americans as the
population ages. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) TYRINGHAM, Mass. -- March 21, 2000 -- TECHNO-GILDER --
From his home in the Berkshires, George Gilder has built top
credentials as a ``futurist'' and technology analyst. Now, he has a
ult-like following for the Gilder Technology Report, his monthly
analysis of trends in the computer and networking sectors. (Lane
Turner/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) DETROIT -- March 21, 2000 -- GUNS-SAFETY -- A coalition
of major American cities, searching for a way prevent a drive to
improve gun safety from stalling, intend to use their combined
buying power to try to force the nation's gun manufacturers to
follow the lead of Smith &AMP; Wesson and sign onto last week's
landmark pack that requires new handgun safety devices. Atlanta,
Miami, Detroit and nearly a dozen other major cities are scheduled
to announce their effort Wednesday in Washington. Detroit police
academy cadets during a roll call in this 1997 file photo.
(Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WHITE HALL, Ala. -- March 21, 2000 -- -AL-AMIN-MAIN-2-COX
-- Agents with the Federal Bureau of Investigation on a field
Tuesday near where Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, formerly known as H. Rap
