<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4072 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DAIMLER-MITSUBISHI-NY     03-21 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIMLER-MITSUBISHI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMLERCHRYSLER-MITSUBISHI TALKS ADVANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (mcd) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN with KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler A.G. is in the final stage of talks with
Mitsubishi Motors Corp. about acquiring 33.4 percent of the
Japanese automobile maker, and an announcement could come by the
end of this week, executives close to the talks said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   While it remains unclear how much DaimlerChrysler would pay for
Mitsubishi, based on the company's market capitalization, the deal
would be worth about $1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A DaimlerChrysler deal with Mitsubishi illustrates the
German-American auto giant's desire to gain a foothold in Asia,
where much of the global growth in auto sales is expected over the
next decade. Presently, Asia represents just 3 percent of
DaimlerChrysler's sales.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal with Mitsubishi also reflects the increasingly
difficult problems faced by some of the weaker Japanese automakers,
which now find they must reach out to foreign partners to be
competitive. Renault of France purchased a 34 percent stake in the
Nissan Motor Co. a year ago, for example, and Ford Motor has
strengthened its management control over Mazda.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's chief executive, Jurgen E. Schrempp, hinted at
a deal with an Asian auto company at a news conference Tuesday in
Sindelfingen, Germany, to introduce a new Mercedes C-Class sedan.
``If we see opportunities in Asia, we will grasp them,'' he said.
``I assume this will take place very soon.'' To some extent, the
proposed alliance illustrates the success of DaimlerChrysler in the
American market, which is the world's most profitable, and the
failure of Mitsubishi in the same market.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler faces fierce competition and narrow profit
margins in Europe, while Mitsubishi is stuck with a domestic market
in Japan that has shrunk by nearly half over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   But while DaimlerChrysler has prospered in the United States,
partly through its acquisition of the Chrysler Corp. but also by
designing popular Mercedes cars and sport utility vehicles,
Mitsubishi has floundered with a tiny market share, little brand
awareness and a sexual harassment scandal three years ago that
distracted management.
</P>
<P>
   Honda and Toyota have been able to balance the weakness of their
home market with profits in the United States, where Honda has 9.8
percent of the market and Toyota 10.2 percent. But Mitsubishi had
to offer deep discounts to even capture 2.3 percent of the market
last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
