<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-BIOTECH </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Biotech Rebound Forecast  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Leading analysts detected signs of a rebound in biotech stocks
yesterday after a disastrous slide caused in part by misplaced
fears that political leaders were intent on curtailing gene
patents.
<P>
   ``Buyers are telling us they sense a bottom out there,'' said
Tom Dietz, analyst with Pacific Growth Equities in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech stocks, which had tripled in recent months, began losing
ground earlier this month, a decline that reached near panic
proportions last week after President Clinton and British Prime
Minister Tony Blair made statements about gene patents that spooked
the market.
</P>
<P>
   The sector's rise and fall is mirrored by the 200 stocks in the
Nasdaq biotech stock index, which peaked at 1,597 on March 6 _ more
than three times its April 19th close of 427 _ only to plummet to
1,073 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, however, this index gained 1 percent to close at
1,102, and though the gain seems anemic, Jim McCamant, editor of
the Medical Technology Stock Letter, said intraday trading suggests
the sector has hit bottom.
</P>
<P>
   McCamant said many stocks overcame big dips in early trading
yesterday to end the day with gains, as bargain hunters returned.
Among the firms that benefited from this trend were Fremont's
Abgenix Inc., which sank as low as $150 but managed to close up
$1.88 at $201.38. Incyte Pharmaceuticals also sank to $90, but
ended the day at $118.53, a 10 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a classic kind of turn,'' McCamant said. ``Whenever
you get strong volatility on the downside, and a big bounce, that's
the signal.''
</P>
<P>
   The market gave other signs it was warming to biotech. Mountain
View's Aclara Biosystems, which went public yesterday at $21, ended
the day at $30. The company makes chips that automate lab
experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Aclara's performance should embolden other biotech
IPOs _ as many as 50 are lined up. Dietz, the Pacific Equities
analyst, said he will be watching two IPOs scheduled for later this
week. Intermune Pharmaceuticals and IntraBiotics Pharmaceuticals
both have biotech products in late stage clinical trials, and Dietz
thinks their success will signal biotech is back.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these hopeful signs, there were still some negative
indicators yesterday. The BioCentury 100, an index compiled by the
trade newsletter in San Carlos, dropped 3 percent yesterday &LR; .
However, BioCentury Publisher Dave Flores said yesterday's loss was
certainly preferable to the 13 percent beating the index took on
Monday, and its 18 percent loss last week.
</P>
<P>
   Flores wasn't ready to declare a rebound. ``The biotech sector
doesn't have a lot of experience with volatility,'' Flores said.
``We'll have to wait longer to figure out whether this is the
bottom, or whether we'll continue to fluctuate, and if so, by how
much.''
</P>
<P>
   One point seemed clear. Last week's plunge was exacerbated by an
exodus of momentum investors, who poured into biotech in January
and February, inflating the bubble. Robert Adler, president of AMG
Services, the mutual fund tracking firm, said money flowed out of
biotech and health care funds last week _ for the first time this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a lot of the mo-mo money move out,'' said Dietz.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent slide, the Nasdaq biotech stock index is
still up 25 percent so far this year, compared with a 16 percent
rise in the overall Nasdaq composite and a 5 percent decline in the
Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Tom Abate at abate (AT) sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
