<HEADER>
A4078 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-H1B-H1B_SFCHRON &LR;      03-21 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-H1B-H1B </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Visa Quota Met for Overseas Workers  &HT;     By Carrie Kirby 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Bay Area employers lost one way of filling technology job
openings yesterday when the Immigration and Naturalization Service
stopped accepting new applications for H-1B visas, the permits that
allow foreign nationals with college degrees to work in the United
States.
<P>
   The agency has already received enough applications to fill this
year's quota of 115,000 visas. Last year, visa availability ran out
in June.
</P>
<P>
   Several bills have been introduced in Congress seeking to
increase the H-1B quota to as much as 200,000 for fiscal year 2001.
But even if the bills become law, the new quotas won't go into
effect until the fiscal year begins on October 1 _ leaving
worker-hungry technology companies high and dry for six months.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard, which employs between 500 and 800 H-1B workers,
is trying to hire 2,700 people for mostly technical jobs in its
U.S. locations. Not being able to hire foreign candidates will hurt
hiring efforts and could possibly damage the company's
profitability, said HP spokeswoman Mary Dee Beall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the best-qualified candidate is American, you can't
fill the job for six months. Some of our product cycles are as
short as six months,'' Beall said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from leaving positions open, HP may consider hiring
foreign applicants to a work at one of the company's overseas
locations and keeping them there ``until the quota is restored,''
Beall said.
</P>
<P>
   In a more radical solution, ``We could move the job overseas,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems is also considering employing foreign nationals
at overseas locations instead of at its Palo Alto headquarters.
However, since  &LR; because many of the foreign workers Sun wants to
hire are already in the United States _ as students or recent
graduates of U.S. universities _ Sun has to pay the price of
relocating the hires to overseas locations, about $200,000 per
employee, said Heidi Wilson, the company's corporate immigration
manager.
</P>
<P>
   While giant companies such as Sun and HP make the most noise
pushing for more H-1B workers by hiring lobbyists to push for
changes in the law, small Internet startups feel the pinch, too.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Greene, chief executive and president of Emeryville's
HealthCentral.com, joined the technology lobbying group TechNet
mainly because he believes something needs to be done about the
shortage of high-tech workers. HealthCentral.com publishes
health-related content for consumers, and the company also creates
customized Web interfaces that help hospitals and other large
medical organizations communicate with their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Greene said the company has had to turn away projects because he
doesn't have enough staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now starting to talk to overseas companies to contract
(programming and Web design) work out,'' said Greene, who has one
H-1B employee.
</P>
<P>
   One company that stands to benefit from the halt in visas is
ITSquare.com, a San Jose Web company that helps companies outsource
software design projects. About 25 percent of the design companies
that bid on jobs at ITSquare.com are based outside the United
States, but U.S. companies who buy their services don't have to
deal with visa hassles because they're not hiring anyone _ they're
just contracting for their services.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine months since the company's launch, it has helped
mostly dot-coms and other startups outsource their software work.
But in the past week, CEO Harvi Sachar said he received phone calls
from three large Bay Area companies _ which he would not name _ who
said they were interested in using ITSquare.com's service because
H-1B visas would be unavailable for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ubiquitous assertion from technology companies that
skilled workers are a scarce commodity right now, some critics
allege that companies such as Sun and HP are passing over qualified
American applicants, especially older computer programmers who
could easily be retrained to fill the open jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have a shortage of applicants,'' said Norman
Matloff, a professor of computer science at the University of
California at Davis who wrote a paper titled ``Debunking the Myth
of a Desperate Software Labor Shortage.''
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, Matloff said, technology companies interview
only about 10 percent of job applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies would have no trouble filling their open
jobs if they let experienced tech workers learn new skills on the
job instead of searching for applicants with the exact skills
required, such as knowledge of the Java programming language,
Matloff said.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the local companies contacted for this story planned
to respond to the end of the H-1B quota by training more American
citizens or residents to fill open jobs. Instead, they stressed
that the positions usually filled by H-1B workers usually require a
doctorate or other hard-to-find qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at ckirby (AT) sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
