<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0429 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4080 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SCAM-SCAM_SFCHRON &LR;      03-21 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCAM-SCAM </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Lawsuit Shows Risks for Small Firms Trying to Get Online  &HT;     By Carolyn Said 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Natasha Becker can take nuts, spices, flour and eggs and whip out a
Russian sherry teacake to die for. But ask her to combine bits and
bytes to create a Web site and she'd be lost.
<P>
   So when the San Mateo resident wanted to move her cake business,
Sweet Temptations, to the Internet, she said she paid $5,000 to a
company that promised it would set up, advertise and operate a Web
site for her business, plus teach her how to run a successful
storefront online. She said the company, Fortune Financial Systems,
never came through with anything more than two days of training.
</P>
<P>
   Now Becker, along with several other entrepreneurs who signed up
for the package, is suing Fortune Financial. Her tale illustrates a
maxim of every gold rush: Just because you bought a map doesn't
mean you'll find the mother lode.
</P>
<P>
   The 20 or so entrepreneurs who signed up for the Fortune
Financial package all have small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't much out there right now for the really small
businesses'' who need outside help to get online and get seen by
prospective customers, said Leslie Lundquist, author of ``Selling
Online for Dummies'' from IDG Books. Companies providing Web
services ``go for larger companies that have more money to spend on
this kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Packages for small-business owners who want to get in on the
Internet mania are proliferating, said Pat Wallace, chief executive
of the San Francisco area Better Business Bureau. ``You see these
seminars advertised constantly in the paper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of merchants who know the Internet is there,
know it's probably the future, but don't know how or what to do
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker fit that profile. So she attended a free seminar in May,
where Fortune Financial pitched her on the $5,000 package. After
paying up, she went to a two-day workshop in June, then spent
months calling Fortune Financial and its various subsidiaries to
find out when they would deliver the hands-on assistance. She said
she rarely got through or was brushed off.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in September, desperate to get her Web site up before
the holidays, Becker paid hundreds of dollars more to other
contractors to get online _ she's at &LR;  www.sweettemptme.com &LR;  _ and
to advertise the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how many bottles of Pepto Bismol I drank
because of the stress these people put me through,'' Becker said.
``I had to refinance my home to stay in business.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortune Financial, a holding company traded over the counter as
a penny stock, moved from Nevada to Florida during the months
Becker was dealing with them. Troy Sheffield, who handles investor
relations for the company, said it is being closed down and has
already shuttered the subsidiaries _ Internet Success System,
Markcomm Productions, Bizz-e and Power Communications _ that
operated its seminars and Web services business ``because of some
problems like that'' experienced by Becker.
</P>
<P>
   He referred specific questions about the lawsuit to company
investors, who said they could not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Experts warn business owners to stop and check the credentials
of anyone offering courses and services before they buy. Consumers
can call the BBB in the state where the company's headquarters are
to see if complaints have been filed against it; if it's a
franchise, they can call the state franchise board. ``Really do
your homework,'' Wallace said. ``Ask for a ton of information.''
</P>
<P>
   But Becker thought Fortune Financial was a safe bet because its
brochures said it was working with Success magazine, a publication
that has been in business since 1891.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made me feel extremely comfortable'' about signing up for
the package, she said. ``The big kahuna was we'd get all this
advertising, all this exposure in Success magazine. But it turned
out that while we were at the seminar, Success magazine was filing
for Chapter 11.''
</P>
<P>
   After seeking bankruptcy protection in May, Success magazine
sold its assets to a Raleigh, N.C., venture capital firm that
recently resumed publication. A spokesman said the magazine has
received 30 or 40 inquiries from people who took the seminars and
were left dangling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very strongly that the previous owners strained the
credibility of the publication by going into these kind of
alliances,'' said Ripley Hotch, the new editor in chief. ``I can't
help but regard (the seminar operators) as fly-by-night people who
make all kinds of promises and don't keep them.''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson is: ``Work with reputable firms, do your research,''
Lundquist said. She suggested several firms, such as Verio,
VerticalNet, SmartAge and ViaWeb.com, that specialize in getting
new businesses online.
</P>
<P>
   ``A small business could even get away with using sites like
Tripod and Lycos that let you make your own personal home page,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, from the BBB, said there are warning signs to help
guard against fraudulent businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``One red flag is asking for payment up front. You should pay
for something when you get it. We get complaints when people have
paid big bucks up front and got nothing _ and by then, it's too
late. The (fraudulent businesses) are out of town.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no statistics on how often companies offering seminars
or services fail to deliver what they've promised. People who
attended the Fortune Financial workshop in San Mateo said they were
told that the firm held seminars almost every weekend in locations
around the country. ``If they only did this to 1,000 people, that's
$5 million right there,'' said Ray Asper, a manufacturers
representative in San Mateo who attended the seminar with Becker
and is also suing Fortune Financial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to be on the Internet,'' but not everyone knows
how to actually do it, said Marie Weiner of Cotchett, Pitre &AMP;
Simon, the Burlingame law firm handling the case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
E-mail Carolyn Said at csaid(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
