A4081 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GROW-GROW_SFCHRON &LR;      03-21 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Book Gives Some Tips on Avoiding IRS Audits 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Is there a checklist a business can use to lessen its chances of
being audited by the IRS?
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR; a  &LR; A: With four weeks to go before filing your tax returns, your
question is timely for individuals as well as businesses.
</P>
<P>
   A recent book by tax attorney Frederick Daily, ``Surviving an
IRS Tax Audit'' (Nolo.com, $24.95), discusses what attracts an IRS
examination of your tax returns and what you can do to lessen the
odds and improve the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Daily mentions these warning flags to the IRS:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Comparative size of a deduction to the rest of the return &LR; . For
example, $19,000 of mortgage interest on a return showing just
$18,000 of income or $32,000 of unreimbursed employee expense on a
return showing income of $17,500.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; An item that is out of character for the taxpayer &LR; . For example,
a plumber claiming expenses related to a business plane or a
65-year-old taxpayer claiming four minor dependent children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; An item reported in the wrong place. &LR;  For example, $2,000 of
credit card interest deducted along with business expenses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Evidence of intent to mislead the IRS. &LR;  For example, incomplete
forms or missing information such as the ``occupation'' box left
blank.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; High gross income. &LR;  The more your income exceeds $100,000, the
likelier an audit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Self-employment. &LR;  The IRS targets those who are in business for
themselves four times more often than wage earners. That's because
the self-employed are basically on the honor system and don't
receive W-2 forms stating their income.
</P>
<P>
   Another author, Professor Amir Aczel, studied 1,200 audit cases
and discovered that self-employed people filing Schedule C are
often audited when they claim expenses of more than 63 percent of
their gross receipts but seldom audited when their deductions are
less than 52 percent of gross receipts.
</P>
<P>
   Nolo's Web site (www.nolo.com) also offers tax audit tips as
part of its online answers to more than 800 frequently asked legal
questions.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guaranteed way to audit-proof your filing, but Daily
and Nolo.com offer these suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Prepare your tax return by computer. &LR;  A neat, computer-prepared
return looks more official to the IRS classifiers and fits the IRS
bias favoring computer processing. Most professional tax preparers
use computers, and there are some good PC and Macintosh programs
such as Intuit's TurboTax and MacInTax that you can use to prepare
your own return.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; If you can't use a computer, print carefully. &LR;  A messy return
_ cross-outs, sloppy handwriting, smudges _ suggests you are
careless and disorganized and almost begs to be audited.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Don't use round numbers for deductions. &LR;  For example, $1,000 or
$12,000 instead of $978 or $12,127. It's an indication that you are
estimating things rather than keeping good records.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Back up your expenses.  &LR; If you claim large deductions for unusual
items, such as an earthquake or fire loss, attach documentary proof
to the back of your tax return. Copies of repair receipts, canceled
checks, insurance reports and pictures are advisable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Avoid filing an income tax return with a Schedule C, Profit
or &LR;  &UR; Loss for Business, that reports a net loss from a
small-business &LR; 
 &UR; venture. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Report side-job income as other income on line 22 of your
tax &LR;  &UR; return. &LR;  Try this only if the income is relatively small and
you are not claiming any business deductions against it.
Technically, side-job income is usually reported on Schedule C,
Profit or Loss from Business. But filing a Schedule C undoubtedly
increases your audit chances.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Don't use electronic filing or the IRS preprinted address &LR;  &UR; label
on your tax return.  &LR; These enable the IRS to get your return into
the processing cycle, including the audit cycle, more quickly.
However, using electronic filing or the label usually means that
any refund will come faster. If you expect a refund but fear an
audit, you'll have to weigh the pros and cons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
More Audit Advice
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: If you are audited by the IRS, what are the odds of getting
through without paying any additional taxes?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Nolo.com reports the odds are poor and getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 15 percent of audit victims pay nothing (other than
their personal legal and accounting expenses). Thanks to its
sophisticated computer selection process, the IRS is more likely
than ever to win cash from its targets. The agency audits about as
many taxpayers as 10 or 15 years ago, but it is recovering four
times as much money.
</P>
<P>
   If you are audited, there are ways to limit the damage. For
starters, Daily suggests seeking a delay in filing your 1999 return
because the IRS might otherwise immediately expand its audit to
include your latest figures.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of filing, you can get IRS Form 4868 and return it by
April 15 to obtain an automatic extension to file by August 15. If
the audit is still going on in August, request a second extension
on IRS Form 2688 and file it by August 15. If the second extension
is granted, you will have until October 15 to file your return. If
the audit is still alive on October 15, Daily says consider not
filing your return until the audit is completed.
</P>
<P>
   As long as you have paid all the taxes due and have no
fraudulent intent, you won't incur any penalties or interest for
not meeting the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO TAXES: &QL; 
In a recent story on San Francisco's ``transient merchants'' tax, I
mentioned taxes that local businesses pay to the city. Locally
licensed businesses pay a tax of either 1.5 percent of payroll
expenses or $1.23 to $3 for every $1,000 of gross receipts,
whichever is higher.
</P>
<P>
   However, city Treasurer Susan Leal tells us that only 1 out of 9
of the city's approximately 70,000 businesses pays either of these
taxes. Small businesses can file for an exemption if their payroll
or gross receipts tax liability is less than $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs (AT) sfgate.com, or
to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
