<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4082 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BRAUN-PHOTOGS-ART-2TA     03-21 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAUN-PHOTOGS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A WORLDLY EYE FOR SALES AS WELL AS BEAUTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26)  
 (af)  
 By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Commercial and utilitarian objects feel perfectly at home in art
these days, whether copied, adapted or merely taken over: Jeff
Koons's basketballs, Robert Gober's sinks, Mike Kelly's stuffed
toys. On their own, however, outside the ennobling frame of a
gallery or the design wing of a museum, no one would mistake them
for works of art.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't need a PhD to recognize metaphorical speech if
someone remarked about a basketball, ``Now (italics)that's(end
italics) a work of art.''
</P>
<P>
   In the current environment, which defines art as almost
anything, museums and galleries also display commercial arts like
advertising, illustrations and cartoons, raising their social
status, too. For a long while such wage labor was not considered
proper company for saints and prophets like Monet and Picasso, who
dared starvation to realize their visions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet photography, which was itself excluded from the company of
art for years, is such a porous medium that commercial work crossed
the boundaries even in the early years. The photographer's
intentions can be so fully concealed by the images themselves that
certain images quickly broke through lines thought to be hard and
fast.
</P>
<P>
   The interplay of aesthetic and commercial concerns in the 19th
century is vividly set forth in ``Image and Enterprise: The
Photographs of Adolphe Braun,'' at the Rhode Island School of
Design in Providence through April 22 and at the Cleveland Museum
of Art from June 18 through Aug. 27. The first American show to
examine Braun's career, it features 100 of his photographs, along
with related material.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Maureen C. O'Brien, the curator of painting and
sculpture at the school's museum, and Mary Bergstein, associate
professor of art and architectural history at the school, the show
opens a large window on work that is not well known.
</P>
<P>
   Braun's photographs are sometimes stunning and sometimes more
technically than aesthetically accomplished. The exemplary catalog
places his achievements and his career within various historical
contexts, including 19th-century industrial design and painting,
the rise of art reproductions, and the commercialization of
photography in France in response to technological and social
change. It is good to be reminded of the many forces impinging on
photography, not the least of them the photographer's need to earn
a living.
</P>
<P>
   Braun (1812-1877) was a highly successful textile designer who
lived most of his life in Mulhouse, an industrial center in Alsace
specializing in the printing of luxury fabrics and wallpaper. In
1842 he published his own lithographs of flowers as design models
for decorative arts. Taking up photography seriously only in 1851,
he presented an album of 300 flower photographs in Paris three
years later; it is these for which he is principally known today.
</P>
<P>
   Large and positively luscious, in succulent shades of brown with
perfectly plain backgrounds and no visible supports or containers,
these are not conventional still lifes or vanitas pictures but
simply flowers in all their creamy fullness, rather casually
arranged, with random linear stems and intricate meshes of leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteenth-century painters (who may have been influenced by
Braun's flower photographs) have made this kind of picture
familiar, so it comes as a surprise to discover that he did not
mean to make art but to make models for textile, wallpaper and
porcelain designers. His unwilting blossoms were more likely to end
up as patterns on the chaise longue than framed on the wall above
it.
</P>
<P>
   It was anticipated from the beginning that photography would be
of service to the arts, including the industrial arts. Braun
himself made the first textile designs in history based on
photographs, and the show displays fabrics printed with floral
designs derived from photographic examples.
</P>
<P>
   The mastery of his camera work, however, soon reaped accolades
usually reserved for art, and Braun quickly acquired a reputation
as one of the leading photographers of his day. Though he did not
remain at this summit, he did sustain a successful commercial
career, adjusting his subject matter to the prevailing trade winds.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the subjects of art, from gods to duchesses, nudes
to sailing ships, have been largely determined by patrons and
markets. Photography could no more afford to be an exception than
any other medium. Braun went on to photograph landscape
extensively, most notably views at dizzy heights in the Alps. The
growth of railroad travel and increased leisure time had whetted
the public's appetite for travel images, even for those who
traveled only from their armchairs.
</P>
<P>
   Occasional Alpine views, like a profile of the Staubbach
waterfall plunging off a cliff in a stream so transparent another
cliff is visible through the water, are as romantic and glorious as
anyone could wish. (A couple of these pictures strongly prefigure
the work of Ansel Adams, who probably did not know them.)
</P>
<P>
   Other landscapes and pictures of Alsatian monuments are quite
well done but seldom exceptional. If the market dictated the
subject, the photographer's skill still dictated the results.
Nadar, after all, was a commercial portraitist, and Atget
advertised ``documents for artists,'' but no one now doubts their
creative powers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Format and technique also took their cues from the market, as
well as from new technologies. Braun branched out into stereographs
when they became fashionable, and perfected landscape panoramas
once he sensed there was an audience for them. His panoramas are
unusually clear, the details and textures rendered with perfect
fidelity, but what sometimes raises them to the rarefied level of
gorgeous is his adoption, in 1866, and unsurpassed mastery of the
carbon transfer process.
</P>
<P>
   This was a printing technique that used permanent dyes or inks,
eliminating a tendency to fade that made some purchasers hesitant.
Carbon prints could be produced in different shades as well,
widening their appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Braun photographed the regional costumes of the various Swiss
cantons and a few images of farm animals as travel mementos or
references for artists. He also took pictures of the devastation of
the Franco-Prussian war, which cost the French Alsace and Lorraine.
The humiliated French made icons of his allegorical portraits of
two women personifying the lost regions; these were even reproduced
on plates, one of which is in the show.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs on china (and other materials) were common mementos
in the 19th century and more common today; think of the millions of
souvenir plates and cups with happy pictures of Prince Charles and
Diana, Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   When Braun tried to turn himself into an artist, as he did
admirably in eight unusually large carbon prints of hunting
trophies, he succeeded artistically but evidently failed
commercially. The photographs of trophies, images of dead game and
hunting accouterments in the vein of 17th-century still-life
paintings, are virtual tours de force of clarity, composition and
tone. They were as large (32 by 24 inches) and just about as
expensive as small paintings and were marketed as dining room
decorations. Apparently, though, they could not compete with
full-color paintings.
</P>
<P>
   He forged a more successful connection to art, and rendered it a
true service, with reproductions of works in museums. In 1867, when
he first published photographs of master drawings, most of the
leading drawing collections were unknown to all but a few scholars,
and the art treasures of the world were still seen chiefly in
engraved reproductions. The carbon process could give the
appearance of red chalk or of graphite on blue-tinted paper; the
photographs look astonishingly like original drawings.
</P>
<P>
   The catalog reports that they made reproductive engravings
obsolete, and that because they revealed mistakes and changes
nearly invisible in faded drawings they were considered better
records of the artist's intention than the originals. Voila!
Photography outdoes art on its own turf.
</P>
<P>
   Braun also photographed sculptures and paintings at about the
time the brothers Alinari were doing so in Italy, and the two
bodies of work became the standard references in museums, libraries
and art schools (not to mention personal travel albums) for close
to a hundred years. They helped establish the discipline of art
history and the foundations of Andre Malraux's ``museum without
walls.''
</P>
<P>
   Art reproductions answered the call of many industrialized
nations to introduce masses of people to art as a means of raising
the level of taste. In 1869, Braun's son and others had taken
pictures of the Sistine ceiling in which that distant and dimly
lighted masterpiece was introduced to the world at large for
virtually the first time; they even revealed some features that had
been invisible before.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Braun's photographs were available to students at the
Rhode Island School of Design when it opened in 1878, and they are
still in the picture files today.
</P>
<P>
   The studio continued under Braun's name for years after he died,
but in his lifetime it had already become so highly organized a
commercial venture that many of his pictures were probably taken by
others. Like Mathew Brady, Braun employed a number of photographers
whom he oversaw but who went out into the field without him and
took photographs that were published under his well-known name.
</P>
<P>
   This practice, a kind of industrialized division of labor, was
one step on a path from Raphael and Rubens, who let assistants do
parts of their paintings, to Warhol, who phoned in instructions for
a painting he would sign.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when technology was making both images and information
available on a scale never seen before, the medium was rapidly
commercialized and organized, much as the Internet has expanded
from science to retail in a few short years. Money talks, and
neither art nor information services would be so rude as not to
listen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
