<HEADLINE>
CONTEST GIVES BRACKET LOSERS ANOTHER SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 ON THE NET-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the 1980s throwbacks who had Indiana, Nevada-Las Vegas,
Kentucky and Louisville as their Final Four selections, another
opportunity for office-pool glory is online.
</P>
<P>
   For another week, Sandbox.com has continued its partnership with
CNNSI.com and Rivals.com to launch a contest for all those who
bombed in their original bracket entries. Before the tournament,
Sandbox.com introduced a contest for a $10 million first prize to
anyone who picked all 63 NCAA men's tournament games.
</P>
<P>
   The new points-based contest offers prizes to the top 10
entrants who can select winners of the remaining 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's universal; everyone bombed,'' said Amy Sasser,
spokeswoman for CNNSI.com. ``My brackets are blown, that's for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Those looking for tips can try ESPN.com, which has culled the
findings of the more than 590,000 who entered its NCAA Men's
Tournament Challenge. According to entrants in the largest online
contest, Michigan State has a 33 percent chance of winning the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Segreti, a weather forecaster stationed at Vance Air
Force Base in Enid, Okla., who won last year's ESPN.com contest
after predicting winners of 46 of the 63 games, won't be so lucky
this year. Segreti picked Temple to defeat Iowa State in the title
game.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Segreti, he can now try the Sandbox.com contest.
BYTES
</P>
<P>
   _ TRY A NOTARY INSTEAD: About a month ago, RealLegends.com had
an interesting idea: authenticate online memorabilia with a
DNA-based identification system. According to a news release from
the Vista, Calif., company, the system employs ``fingerprint
matching and imaging, DNA extractions, unique binary data and
signature data.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how this DNA system _ especially DNA extractions _ would
have worked isn't clear, but Bruce Regis, the company's chief
executive officer, said the concept was scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, it was a little bit hard to get sports celebrities to
agree to fingerprint their items,'' Regis said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the company plans to do authenticate its memorabilia a more
practical way _ by using a notary and a camera. Regis said the Los
Angeles Lakers' Kobe Bryant has agreed to be the first sports
figure to use the RealLegends.com process of authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   _ GOING POOF: Rangers fans who have had a grudge against their
American League West rivals, the Seattle Mariners, should find some
satisfaction from watching the Kingdome be demolished this week.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:30 a.m. Sunday, Microsoft plans to air live video of the
implosion on its WindowsMedia.com site
(www.windowsmedia.com/preview/kingdome). It's even available in
3-D, but it's probably too late to order the $30 enhanced-viewing
kits.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, Wash.-based Microsoft announced that it has teamed with
Isee3D of Montreal and Controlled Demolition, the contractor in
charge of demolishing the Kingdome, to present the event to online
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   New River Media of Washington, D.C., which specializes in
stereoscopic imaging for streaming video, is producing the footage.
Online viewers can get an inside glimpse of the Dome collapsing
with a remote camera that will probably get smashed during the
implosion.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also has packaged footage of 25 other implosions to
its archives. Users can even e-mail an ``implosion to a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BITS: PGATour.com and USANetwork.com plans video streaming
coverage Thursday and Friday from The Players Championship
competitors struggling with the famed No. 17 at the Tournament
Players Club at Sawgrass in Ponte Vedra, Fla. ... As part of a
promotion for its NHL Championship 2000 game, Fox Sports
Interactive plans to host Dallas Stars center Mike Modano for a
chat starting at 5 p.m. Thursday ... AthletesDirect is offering 175
Mickey Mantle baseball trading cards valued at more than $150,000
for auction on eBay. The 10-day auction concludes Friday. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
