<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-NEWS-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS: 3 APOLOGIES
</P>
<P>
   The government apologized to Jews, Gypsies and Indonesians for a
``chilly'' official response in the past to their claims to
property seized during and after World War II. Prime Minister Wim
Kok said the government had to face up to ``mistakes and
shortcomings'' made in the 1940s and offered $180 million, in
addition to past restitutions, to the Central Jewish Congress.
Gypsies received an extra $13 million. Indonesians who sided with
the Dutch during Indonesia's fight for independence in 1949 were
offered $110 million.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: BERTELSMANN JOINS FUND
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann, the German media company that owns Random House,
said it would contribute to a $5 billion fund to compensate
Nazi-era slave and forced laborers, but declined to say how much.
The company is in the process of revising its corporate history in
the light of evidence that it did not, as it previously contended,
oppose Hitler's regime. Contentious talks on how the fund should be
divided will resume Wednesday. .
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS: CROAT HANDED OVER
</P>
<P>
   A Bosnian Croat accused of war crimes was handed over to the
United Nations tribunal in The Hague, where he arrived with a
psychiatrist and other medical personnel. Mladen Naletelic, 54, a
former military commander, was indicted for persecution, torture
and murder of Muslims in Bosnia in 1993 and 1994. The new Croatian
leadership, in contrast to past governments, accepted tribunal
doctors' findings that he was well enough to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: ORANGEMEN IN DUBLIN
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland's Orange Order, whose summer parades of men in
bowler hats and orange sashes regularly plunge the province into
turmoil, has been invited by Dublin officials to march there in
May. ``We have the right of free assembly here,'' Lord Mayor Mary
Freehill said. A Sinn Fein spokesman compared Freehill's action to
``the state governor inviting the Ku Klux Klan to march in
Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   ELSEWHERE AROUND THE WORLD
</P>
<P>
   CHILE: PINOCHET IN HOSPITAL
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet, 84, entered a clinic for tests after
fainting in his residence outside Santiago. The clinic would not
comment on the condition of the former dictator, who returned to
Chile on March 3 after spending 16 months under house arrest
outside London on a Spanish warrant charging him with human rights
violations.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: EX-AIDE ADMITS HARASSMENT
</P>
<P>
   The former governor of Osaka, Japan's second-largest city,
admitted for the first time in court that he had groped a
21-year-old campaign worker last year. Until now, Isamu Yamada, a
former comedian who still uses his stage name, Knock Yokoyama, had
denied accusations of sexual harassment while agreeing to pay a
large civil settlement. Yokoyama resigned after his indictment for
sexual molestation.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: ALBRIGHT REBUKED
</P>
<P>
   In its latest response to Washington's decision to ease economic
sanctions, the Foreign Ministry rebuked Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright and other officials for a ``lack of honesty''
and ``ignorance of the geography of the region.'' The statement
appeared aimed less at the moves announced by Albright than at
remarks she made later in India that made note of divisions over
policy toward the United States between Iran's democratic reform
movement and a hard-line faction associated with the ruling
clerics.
</P>
</TEXT>
