<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' RACE FOR SECOND BASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ The Anaheim Angels starting job at second base
has been narrowed down to a competition between Scott Spiezio and
Trent Durrington, with Pat Kelly holding an outside chance.
</P>
<P>
   Spiezio is a more-established hitter and has power. Durrington
has more defensive range and is faster. Kelly probably has a better
blend of all talents but has been slowed by a sore shoulder and
hasn't been able to play much.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly had two hits in Tuesday's 12-3 loss to the Chicago White
Sox at Tucson Electric Park, but he also couldn't get anything on a
couple of throws that resulted in infield singles. He'll get an
opportunity to show manager Mike Scioscia what he can do in the
final week of Cactus League play but needs to show he's healthy
more than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of them gives us a little different package,''
Scioscia said. ``Durrington is an exciting player with a lot of
range, but he's still developing, especially offensively. Spiezio
is much further along offensively and he has power. He doesn't have
as much range as Durrington, but he has sure hands. And both turn
the double play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive back: You'll have to excuse Tim Salmon for being a
little sensitive when it came to talking about his sore back.
Salmon, after all, has been slowed by injuries the past two years
and doesn't want to dwell on it.
</P>
<P>
   He was limited to a DH role nearly all of 1998 because of a torn
ligament in the arch of his foot. And last season, he played in
only 98 games because of a badly sprained left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   So the simple question, ``How's your back?'' elicits an
understandable response: ``I'm not going to talk to you guys about
my back. I don't want to make it turn into a big deal. I've had it
before. Sometimes, you take too many swings.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon likes to get as much work during spring training as
possible because it helps him get off to a fast start once the
season begins. Wednesday he missed his third game in a row because
of his back, but he took batting practice in the indoor batting
cage Tuesday and is expected to return to the lineup today against
the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   He's having a good spring, hitting .464 (13 for 28) with four
homers and 11 RBI in 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Bafflingly bad: Pitcher Scott Schoeneweis gave up nine runs and
11 hits in 4 innings Tuesday but was ``baffled'' by his
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ahead of every hitter,'' Schoeneweis said. ``I hit my
spot every time except the last pitch (a home run by Chris
Singleton). That was my only mistake as far as I'm concerned. I
threw my pitches where I wanted to. They hit the ball on the ground
almost every time. That's what I'm supposed to do as a sinker-ball
pitcher. I just ran out of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great sinker,'' Scioscia said. ``Those ground balls
turned into seeing-eye hits. The results obviously weren't what we
wanted, but you have to look at the number of quality pitches he
threw.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though his spring ERA rose from 2.25 to 6.48, Schoeneweis
is on track to win a spot in the starting rotation. But he couldn't
help but wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I have the luxury of giving up nine runs in a
game,'' he said. ``I'm not Ken Hill, I don't have a lot of years in
the game. But I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Can he rebound?: Today is a big day for Todd Greene. Greene
caught five innings of Tuesday's game, but if he is going to make
the squad as a third catcher, he needs to be able to bounce back
and be ready to play again today. Greene, who has had two surgeries
on his right shoulder, hasn't been able to catch back-to-back days
yet this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to help us he needs to be able to catch on a regular
basis,'' Scioscia said. ``It can't be a situation where he needs
two or three days after after he catches. You always like to have a
bat like his off the bench, but I don't know if we can afford to do
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
