<SLUG> BC-BOWLING-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET MILLIONAIRES BUY BOWLING TOUR, FOLLOWING LATEST TREND 
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   and LENA WILLIAMS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pro bowlers have long been the Everymen of the nation's lanes,
blue-collar practitioners of a low-tech sport.
</P>
<P>
   But a very high-tech thing happened Tuesday: three entrepreneurs
with software and Internet pedigrees announced a deal to invest $5
million to prepare the Professional Bowlers Association for a
future in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing made too much sense,'' said Chris Peters, a former
vice president of Microsoft and a devout bowler. ``We see it as a
diamond in the rough, a turnaround opportunity people were missing.
We were so excited we hoped nobody else would figure it out. We had
to get this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters and his partners _ Mike Slade, the former president of
Starwave, the creator of elaborate Web sites, and Rob Glaser, the
chairman of RealNetworks, which makes software to send audio and
video on the Internet _ plan to revive the PBA Tour's moribund
marketing and public relations, and zip up its television
production with the expectation of Webcasting the tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tech play is combining the TV and the Internet,'' Peters
said.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of buying the nonprofit PBA from its 2,800 members _
including paying off about $2 million in debts and raising annual
prize money by $1 million to $5 million _ is cheap. Investing $15
million or $20 million more for the long term is a fortune for the
PBA but pennies compared with the $175 million paid last week by
the YankeeNets to buy the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   But the eager involvement of three high-tech wizards
demonstrates an evolution in sports ownership. The beer barons,
shipbuilders and bankers who who owned franchises are giving way to
a new breed with huge caches of new money. Glaser, whose
RealNetworks stock is worth $954 million, built a two-lane bowling
alley in the basement of his company's Seattle headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Cuban, a billionaire through Broadcast.com, spent $280
million to buy the doormat Dallas Mavericks. Ted Leonsis, a top
America Online executive, and a group of partners spent $200
million to buy the Washington Capitals and stakes in the Washington
Capitals and the MCI Center. He lured Michael Jordan to buy a
piece, then placed him in charge of the Wizards' operations.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday, Patrick McEnroe, the retired tennis player with a
somewhat famous brother, John, was awarded the ninth World Team
Tennis franchise, one that will play in East Quogue, as the New
York Hamptons. When the WTT last had a team in New York, the
Apples, McEnroe, 34, was a 12-year-old junior player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing something in New York is pretty expensive,'' said
McEnroe, a commentator for CBS Sports, ESPN and ``Imus in the
Morning'' on WFAN radio. ``My initial thought was the Hamptons and
the East End of Long Island. It's a good tennis community. People
are interested in tennis there.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost is hardly prohibitive: the franchise fee is $60,000,
and the typical costs of running a WTT team range from $300,000 to
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The WTT features two-man, two-women teams, with a coach. Each
match consists of five sets, with one set each of men's singles,
women's singles, men's doubles, women's doubles and mixed doubles.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe, who was raised in Douglaston, Queens, inquired about
buying a team a year ago, said Billie Jean King, the league's
founder, who hopes to expand to 16 teams and add more
player-owners. ``We've been waiting for the right owners,'' she
said. ``When Patrick called, we felt we were on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   The PBA's new owners hope they have the right strategy to return
the tour to the higher-profile days of the 1960's and 70's, when
ABC Sports carried more than 20 tournaments a year and the
announcers Chris Schenkel and Billy Welu were as renowned as the
stars Don Carter, Dick Weber and Carmen Salvino.
</P>
<P>
   Now the stars are Parker Bohn III, Chris Barnes and Walter Ray
Williams Jr.
</P>
<P>
   All PBA Tour events are seen on cable, either on ESPN or Fox
Sports Net. The ABC deal ended in 1997 after 36 years, and a
two-year foray in which the PBA paid CBS to be televised ended with
stiff losses for the tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they still get a 1 rating as a cable sports product, with
no investment at all,'' Peters said.
</P>
<P>
   Peters said the ability to capitalize on passion for bowling
among millions of everyday participants will be enhanced by
ownership of the entire sport _ with no unions, no rival owners
with separate agendas and no impediments to innovation. The buyers
took control of the national, senior and regional tours, as well as
the logos, copyrights and Web site, which gets 500,000 visits a
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about the level of control,'' he said. ``It's
the ability to make decisions very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gerberich, the PBA commissioner, who will retain his job
but share power with a new chief executive officer, said: ``We have
three of the smartest Internet guys in the world. Hopefully, people
think it will legitimize the sport and we can be more competitive
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
