A4092 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     03-21 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVIN'S SKIN TOUGH, ATTITUDE TOUGHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ Winning is a matter of life and death at
UCLA. Any illusions to the contrary that Steve Lavin harbored were
shattered one day last month when he received an e-mail threatening
his life.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wrote it made it graphically clear that if the UCLA
basketball team's NCAA Tournament appearance streak was going to
expire this year at 11, then Lavin deserved to perish, too.
</P>
<P>
   Some 400 miles to the north, Lavin's father Cap received the
same death threat, presumably for the offense of having sired his
sixth child.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the rage that must be percolating in a person for whom
any number of losing scores could trigger such a response. Clearly,
it is somebody from the same species of boorishness as the man who
got so irate over his car bumper being tapped he bounce-passed a
dog into a lane of oncoming traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Police thus far have had little success tracing the threat to
its source. So for the past few weeks, Lavin has been living with
the knowledge that the person who wishes him dead could have been
sitting in a row behind the home bench during UCLA's final four
home games of the regular season. Or waiting to shake Lavin's hand
after one of the Bruins' first two NCAA Tournament games in
Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The person could be holding a ticket to UCLA's Midwest Regional
semifinal game against Iowa State on Thursday at The Palace.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin figured he could respond in one of two ways. He could
whistle through the graveyard or make wisecracks for however much
longer this topsy-turvy season lasted. The Bruins' beleaguered
fourth-year coach chose quips to keep from quivering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the kids (on the team), when Gene Bartow was the coach
at UCLA, somebody wanted to shoot his dog. So at least they've got
the right target this time,'' Lavin said the other day, as sanguine
as you please.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it troubled him that his father was targeted, though,
frankly, Lavin wouldn't have been surprised if his dad, a retired
English teacher, had spruced up the syntax and returned the message
to its sender along with a poem or a book suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   When they first spoke of the death threat, Lavin, 35, told his
father, ``I guess whoever sent it thought the apple didn't fall far
enough from the tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the son inherited his sense of humor from his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't focus on it,'' Cap Lavin said of the threat,
dismissing it with the wave of his hand. ``I responded to it with a
sense of irony.''
</P>
<P>
   It figures that Lavin would turn to his father for answers and
not just because the elder Lavin starred at the University of San
Francisco under Pete Newell. Who better than a lover of literature
to make sense of a UCLA team that has been harder to read than
Henry James?
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, in Year 1 AD (After Baron Davis, their superlative
point guard), started the regular season 8-2, finished 6-0 and went
5-9 in between. The nadir had to be the third week in February,
otherwise known as Desert Scorn. UCLA hit the road to play the
Arizona schools and lost both games by a combined 44 points.
</P>
<P>
   Around that time some people inside Lavin's ever-broadening
social circle expressed concern that he had lost his center. They
worried that the rollover contract Lavin had received last summer
had made him very secure but also somewhat complacent.
</P>
<P>
   One friend joked about confronting him and conducting a
tough-love intervention, the way you would with loved ones who are
alcoholics or drug abusers.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin's addiction? Some will tell you it's the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   A few friends who have known him since before he became a UCLA
assistant coach to Jim Harrick in 1991 were worried earlier in the
winter that Lavin's life had become as flashy as the Bruins'
offense and was exhibiting as little substance, too.
</P>
<P>
   This was around the time that UCLA, under junior point guard
Earl Watson's direction, was gunning for quick points off the fast
break and acting acutely allergic to any play run out of a
half-court offense. The Bruins were becoming all too predictable,
but that wasn't the worst of it. In the losses at ASU and Arizona,
the Bruins had empty soda cans for hearts.
</P>
<P>
   After getting blown out at ASU, three UCLA players spent the
time set aside for shooting free throws at practice the next day
goofing around on nearby gymnastics equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Where was the discipline? The desire? If that wasn't Lavin's
most damning moment, it came the next day when the Bruins looked
lethargic in a 15-point loss at Arizona that dropped them to
seventh place in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   The death threat followed soon thereafter. Lavin had every
reason to be grim, to be glum, to come to practice every day and
castigate his players to make himself feel better. He could have
gotten physical like Indiana's Bob Knight or vulgar like Maryland's
Gary Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Lavin got metaphysical like Tony Robbins. He kept
telling his players they were this close to realizing their
``monster potential.'' Six losses in seven games hadn't shaken his
faith in them. That was the thing that finally got the players'
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was getting raked over the coals and yet he came to the gym
every day and was positive,'' said senior forward Sean Farnham.
``After a while, you start thinking, `If this man can believe in us
at our lowest point that we can accomplish anything we set out to
do, why don't we have a little more faith in each other?'''
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, the Bruins started making the extra passes.
They bought into the idea of a half-court offense and renewed their
commitment to defense.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin made some adjustments, too. He started running practices
with more of an iron fist. The kid gloves came off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took more control of practices,'' Farnham said. ``He made
sure we were doing everything precisely right. It had to be done
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's overall improvement since then has been dramatic.
During their eight-game winning streak, the Bruins have shot 49.6
percent from the field and 42.6 percent from 3-point range while
holding their opponents to 40.4 percent shooting. Contrast that
with their first 24 games when they shot 47.5 percent from the
field, 34.9 percent from beyond the arc and held their opponents to
43.2 percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   A little more attention to detail, the return of JaRon Rush and
all of the sudden Lavin is being painted with bright, broad strokes
again. You can continue to believe, as we do, that a veteran
assistant would make Lavin look even better. But it'd be ungracious
to nitpick about a coach who has led his team to three Sweet
Sixteen appearances in four seasons. Let's face it: If his name
were Henry Bibby, he'd own L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin gives the impression he's made of Teflon. But he is not.
The bad times have left an impression. There's some residue there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been the same person for four years,'' Lavin said. ``The
perception of who I am keeps changing based on wins and losses. I
haven't changed. Not really. The time, thought, energy and emotion
I bring to coaching the kids is the same. The only difference is,
I'm a little more weathered, a little more beaten up. I have a
little thicker skin. I'm a little less wide-eyed and bushy-tailed.
I have a better understanding of what the profession is all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, of course. Lavin now knows you sometimes can't win for
winning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
