A4220 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-PROJECT-FELON-KAN &LR;      03-21 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROJECT-FELON-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFORT TO CRACK DOWN ON FELONS WHO ILLEGALLY POSSESS FIREARMS IS
DECLARED A SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Law enforcement authorities and state
officials on Tuesday declared Project Felon a success, pointing to
46 federal weapons indictments and 19 guilty pleas in western
Missouri in the last five months.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan also offered new state resources to
help federal prosecutors continue its crackdown on felons who
illegally possess firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reducing violent crime deserves all the resources we can bring
to bear,'' Carnahan said on a visit to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Under Project Felon, which was announced in early October,
convicted felons who are caught with weapons are charged under
federal gun laws, which generally carry longer sentences than
similar charges in state or local courts.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Highway Patrol soon will assign two troopers to
work full-time on the program, Carnahan said. The governor also is
directing the Missouri Board of Probation and Parole to review the
status of state offenders charged under the federal program.
</P>
<P>
   If those offenders were under state supervision, their parole
could be revoked and they could be returned to state prison after
serving their federal sentences, Carnahan said.
</P>
<P>
   State corrections and parole officers also will be encouraged to
strongly remind felons that they could face harsh federal sentences
if they are arrested with a gun after their release from state
prison.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Stephen L. Hill said he appreciated the
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Project Felon is ``working very well because we in law
enforcement are working well together,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 30 percent of federal felonies charged in Kansas City
since the program was announced are related to Project Felon, court
records show. That level of commitment is paying off, said J.
Robert Switzer, special agent in charge of the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have saved lives, we are saving lives and we will continue
to save lives,'' Switzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Two cases in particular show the value of the program, Hill
said.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Kaplin Pulce, who was convicted for stealing, was
arrested Oct. 30 at a downtown haunted house when a 9 mm handgun
fell from his pocket as he was headed down a slide.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, authorities arrested John E. Francis on weapons
charges after a domestic disturbance. In 1975, Francis was
convicted of first-degree murder for killing Kansas City Police
Officer Russell D. Mestdagh after a pharmacy robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Both men have pleaded guilty and are awaiting sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month the first defendant to be sentenced as part
of the program, Theron L. Davis, received a term of seven years and
three months in prison for carrying a loaded revolver after felony
drug and burglary convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday afternoon a federal jury in Kansas City convicted
Odies Cole Jr. on a Project Felons weapons charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
