<HEADER>
A4222 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-ORIOLES-HARGROVE-     03-21 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-HARGROVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARGROVE TAKES ON FLIGHTY ORIOLES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ A five-time division-winning manager
meets a two-time payroll loser. It is not exactly the irresistible
force meeting the immovable object, but developments require
watching.
</P>
<P>
   Will Mike Hargrove conquer the highest-paid underachievers in
the history of the game, or will the Baltimore Orioles and the man
who pays them chew up and spit out yet another manager?
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove is the fifth manager the Orioles have employed during
the six-and-a-half-year ownership of Peter Angelos. They won a
division championship under Davey Johnson in 1997, but he was still
replaced by Ray Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Two seasons of folly followed. With payrolls totaling $146
million, the Orioles compiled a 157-167 record, finishing in fourth
place both seasons, ahead of only an expansion team in its first
two years, the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. For only $8 million more, the
Yankees won two World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Why was Hargrove available to assume command of this
dysfunctional outfit? Had he not managed the Cleveland Indians to
five consecutive division championships, three American League
Championship Series and two World Series appearances? Yes, but the
Yankees, and not the Indians, have won three World Series in the
past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Last October John Hart, the Indians' general manager, dispatched
Hargrove and named Charlie Manuel, the team's batting coach and
Hart's long-time friend, as the new manager. Hart said the team
needed a new voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never understand when they say something like that,'' Sandy
Alomar Jr., the Indians' catcher, said. ``They're pretty similar
guys. Mike was great with the players. I have no idea what they
mean. Maybe they mean they needed someone different in charge. When
you say a new voice, it doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart and Hargrove had long been portrayed in baseball circles as
two men co-existing, but not always happily. A person close to the
Indians said that Hart had wanted to fire Hargrove a few years ago,
but was stopped by the then owner, Richard Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he felt it was time for a change,'' Hargrove said at
the Orioles spring-training camp here. ``John and I got along. We
didn't hang out together and go places together. We'd go out to
dinner occasionally. But we got along. We disagreed on some things,
but I felt then and think now it was healthy disagreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove had hardly recovered from the shock of dismissal when
the Orioles offered him their manager's job. A man on the rebound
finds it hard to say no, especially when the suitor spends money as
liberally as Angelos does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being here,'' Hargrove said, ``I found things weren't as bad
or as chaotic as what I'd heard. There are good people throughout
the organization. The players have a tremendous work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   They have large salaries as well and that underachieving
reputation. ``I think the beauty of baseball is that every spring
last year's slate is wiped clean and you've got to make your own
imprint on the slate,'' Hargrove said.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles' 1999 slate became muddied early. They lost 12 of
their first 15 games and never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of built-in alibis last year and some guys
took advantage of them,'' B.J. Surhoff, the team's good-hitting
left fielder, said. ``There were a lot of distractions early on.
The Cuban game was a big distraction. All the talk about Ray's
status was a distraction to a lot of people. You didn't know what
was going to happen with him early on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles played two exhibition games against the Cuban team,
one in Havana late in spring training, the other in Baltimore early
in the season. The games became a distraction because the players,
for the most part, did not want to play the games, and their effort
reflected their feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove, sitting in the opposing dugout, saw a different reason
for the Orioles' problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a team that had a tendency to play really well for three
or four innings and all of a sudden for a couple innings just
completely lose their focus,'' Hargrove said. ``They'd re-gather
their focus and go on, but in that two- or three-inning spell
enough runs were scored and the damage was done to where they'd
lose the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove is trying to rectify the failure to focus. ``I came in
emphasizing the mental side of the game,'' he said. ``When there
are too many distractions, you're not concentrating and focusing on
what you're trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Many elements of the game, Hargrove added, are beyond the
players' control. ``The one thing you can control,'' he said, ``is
the mental side. You can control whether or not you make a mental
error and to be tough mentally. If you can accomplish that
consistently enough during the season, if the talent level is where
you think it is, then the talent has a chance to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove said he used the same approach in Cleveland. It
evidently worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them bought into it,'' he said. ``There are always
going to be a few who think you're full of baloney and try to drag
other people with them. But it's paid off here so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Veterans are not exempt from reminders about the importance of
having the right mental attitude, the manager said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even they may forget the intensity level that needs to be
achieved,'' he said. ``I believe at the big-league level that's the
separator between the winners and the losers because the talent is
fairly comparable.''
</P>
<P>
   The past two seasons the Orioles have been comparable to two
teams _ the Yankees in pay, the Devil Rays in finish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
