</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NUKE-SALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A-PLANT SALE IS SHROUDED IN UNCERTAINTY
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Va., Miss., Conn.)  (nk) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Power Authority's attempt to sell its two nuclear
plants remained mired in uncertainty and speculation Tuesday after
it decided late Monday to postpone choosing a buyer because of an
assortment of tax, legal and financial issues.
</P>
<P>
   As the dust settled after an unexpected 11-hour meeting on
Monday night, the biggest question was whether one of two bidders
for the Indian Point 3 plant in Westchester County, and the James
A. FitzPatrick reactor in Oswego County, on Lake Ontario, was still
involved.
</P>
<P>
   That bidder, Dominion Resources of Richmond, Va., had said that
its original offer, which it valued at $857 million, would expire
at 11:59 p.m. Monday. But as the deadline approached, the power
authority said that it was still uncomfortable with some aspects of
Dominion's proposal and that it would delay its decision until next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Dominion gave no indication of what it would do next,
saying only that ``we're considering our options,'' said Mark
Lazenby, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of hedging suggests that Dominion has not, for now,
simply abandoned its quest. If Dominion does drop out, then the
winner, by default, would be Entergy Nuclear of Jackson, Miss.,
which had submitted an offer it valued at $806 million.
</P>
<P>
   And while Carl Crawford, an Entergy spokesman, said that his
company, like the power authority, was still waiting for Dominion
to act, he said he was confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we've got a very superior offer already on the
table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is the largest sale, by far, of nuclear plants in U.S.
history. As such, what happens with these plants has implications
for electricity customers, the environment and the economy and may
well affect the structuring of deals for nuclear plants like the
two Millstone reactors for sale in Waterford, Conn., and the Indian
Point 2 plant in Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly not selling a corner cigar store,'' said
Clarence D. Rappleyea, the chairman and chief executive of the
power authority, during Monday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   At that meeting, the major sticking point was the issue of
decommissioning the plants when they are judged to be no longer
useful.
</P>
<P>
   The power authority is expected to pay for the costs of
decommissioning, and has been building a fund, now valued at $630
million, in anticipation of those obligations. By 2015, when the
licenses of both plants are to expire, that fund is expected to
stand at $1.9 billion, which is more than enough to cover the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission's projection of $1.18 billion to
decommission the plants. Anything left over would be kept by the
power authority.
</P>
<P>
   But if that fund were subject to taxes because the public power
authority sold its plants to a private entity like Entergy or
Dominion, or if that fund were to be counted as taxable income for
the new owner, then taxes would eat into that $1.9 billion. And if
that new, taxed figure were less than the NRC's $1.18 billion, the
new owner would have to make up the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Shoenholz, a spokesman for the power authority, said
Tuesday that the authority's tax lawyers had concluded that the
fund would probably remain tax-exempt. But just to make sure, the
authority wanted to see how the two bidders would handle the
possibility of unexpected taxes, and, Shoenholz said, Entergy that
had resolved the possibility satisfactorily and that Dominion had
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have the assurance that we would not have the
exposure,'' Shoenholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no matter what happens over the next few days, as
Dominion considers its options, the power authority expects that
its board of trustees will choose a winning bid at its next
meeting, on Tuesday in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be done Tuesday,'' Gerard D. DiMarco, a trustee,
said after Monday's meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
