<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4230 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-UCLA-NYT     03-21 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSH HAS BRUINS SOARING WITH HIS PASS-DUNK PLAY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JaRon Rush is such a special player to watch because there is
always the chance he will do something dynamic when UCLA has the
ball. All he has to do is make eye contact with point guard Earl
Watson, begin his ascent to the basket and then soar above the rim
to accept another lob pass and finish the play with a spectacular
dunk.
</P>
<P>
   It is a gorgeous play, the type the Bruins look for every moment
Rush is on the floor and the kind that obviously demoralizes
opponents. A dunk off a lob pass counts for 2 points, but it
definitely inflicts more psychological harm than a 15-foot jump
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a lob on a team, the crowd gets into it and
you're excited about it,'' said Rush, a 6-foot-7-inch sophomore
forward. ``The intensity picks up, your defense picks up,
everything picks up and it's hard to slow it down. That's why I
like it.''
</P>
<P>
   This athleticism, this fearless attitude and this high-flying
approach is what makes UCLA a dangerous team in the Round of 16.
Suddenly, a team whose coach figured he might be fired a month ago
and a team that barely qualified for the National Collegiate
Athletic Association tournament might be the most popular pick to
win a championship if fans could destroy their office pool sheets
and start all over again. Suddenly, the Bruins have won eight in a
row and are flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fun,'' Rush said. ``We're just out there having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding the point of UCLA's turnaround is simple. It began when
Rush returned. He was suspended by the NCAA for one and a half
seasons last Dec. 10 for accepting $200 from an agent and benefits
from an Amateur Athletic Union coach. After UCLA appealed Rush's
suspension, it was reduced from 44 games to 24. There was still
time to help salvage a tattered season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very hard lesson,'' Rush said. ``I wouldn't want to
go through it again. Obviously, it's something I won't do again.''
</P>
<P>
   With Rush back on the court, the Bruins, who had limped to a
13-11 record, are 8-0. While Rush said that he is playing at about
85 percent speed, he looked in peak condition with 14 points and
six rebounds in the 105-70 demolition of Maryland in the second
round of the Midwest Region. The Bruins made the Terrapins look
like a junior varsity team that had wandered into the gym.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA might have the deepest team in the country as 12 of the 13
players have started at least one Division I game and the 13th is a
walk-on. Watson is a confident leader who had the superb
statistical line of 17 points, 16 assists and no turnovers against
Maryland. He underwent laser surgery to seal a hole in his left
retina on Monday but expects to play on Thursday when UCLA (21-11)
opposes Iowa State (31-4) in Auburn Hills, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Kapono, a freshman, changes headbands if his touch from
the 3-point arc is off, which is rare. Jerome Moiso is a quick,
left-handed power forward who likes catching lobs and dunking as
much as Rush does. Dan Gadzurik has tendinitis in both knees, but
the 6-11 center from the Netherlands is a strong presence in the
middle. Still, of all the Bruins, Rush is the Energizer Bunny. What
he can do with his long arms, spindly legs and incredible ability
even amazes some of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rush puts pressure on the defense,'' Watson said. ``He forces
the defense to be aware of lobs at all times. He can catch it from
anywhere. I can throw it from half court and he'll still catch it.
He's got such soft hands. He jumps up in the air so high and he
doesn't care if he comes down and falls on his head. That opens up
the 3-point shot and the inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush, who has a skull with a top hat and ``No Fear'' tattooed on
his right bicep and a sinister wizard holding a basketball and
``JaRon'' on his left bicep, ditched his humility and conceded that
he did provide the wayward Bruins with a boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bring a lot of intensity and defensive pressure and a
presence on the court that teams have to play against,'' said Rush,
who is averaging 12.9 points and 5.6 rebounds in 21 minutes. ``That
opens up things for other players to get more shots.
</P>
<P>
   Once Rush was suspended, he went from playing against the best
players in the country every day to playing alone only twice a
week. Rush could not find a decent game on campus, so he
languished. He thought about playing professionally in Europe and
wondered if he should prepare to leave college for the National
Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing else I could do,'' Rush said. ``It was real
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush called it a depressing experience, but he did not let
Watson or his teammates see that side of his demeanor. He called
Watson, one of his childhood buddies from Kansas City, Mo., before
every game and wished the Bruins good luck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
