<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4232 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-GREER-TEX     03-21 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-GREER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREER COULD JOIN LIST OF LATE-BLOOMING SLUGGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Rafael Palmeiro was a line-drive hitter
during his first full five years in the big leagues, posting a high
average, scoring a lot of runs and averaging fewer than 20 home
runs a year.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he was what Rusty Greer is today.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro gradually changed, breaking through with 37 home runs
in 1993, his sixth full season. Throw out the strike year of 1994
and he has averaged 41 home runs and 122 RBI in his past six full
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He said Greer could make a similar transformation into a
high-average hitter who also has considerable power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, the guy is a better hitter than I was at that
age,'' Palmeiro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Raffy about it,'' said Greer, a career .309
hitter who averaged 19 home runs in his first five full seasons.
``According to his theory, there will be a time when it happens as
you learn about yourself over the course of time. You learn how to
look for your pitch at a certain time and try to pull it. Hopefully
it's something I can accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro did it. So too, did Carl Yastrzemski and Stan Musial,
two Hall of Fame left fielders who didn't develop their full power
potential until they reached the stage of their careers that Greer,
31, is at now.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro said he and Greer take the same basic approach at the
plate. They look for a good pitch and try to hit it hard. The
difference is there are times when Palmeiro goes to the plate
deliberately looking to hit a home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't do it every time,'' Palmeiro said. ``You might do it
50 to 75 times out of the year where you know the pitcher is going
to make a certain pitch. Sometimes it might change in an at-bat, if
you work the count in your favor. But out of 50 at-bats, you might
hit five to seven, maybe another 10 home runs. Add that onto the 20
or so Rusty hits by accident, and he could hit at least 30 in a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I hit three home runs last year on a 3-0 pitch,''
Palmeiro said. ``Why take on a 3-0 pitch when you know the pitcher
is going to give you a fat pitch? But it has to be your pitch. In
the playoffs, El Duque (Orlando Hernandez) was behind 3-0, and I
was looking for a fastball on the outer half of the plate. But he
threw a fastball inside, and I took it for a strike, then ended up
walking.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got back to the dugout, Johnny (Oates) said, Raffy, you
know you had the green light, don't you? I said, yeah but it wasn't
the pitch I was looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Yastrzemski followed a similar path as Palmeiro during his Hall
of Fame career. He hit for a high average but low power during his
first six years. Yastrzemski, a rookie in 1961, won a batting title
in 1963 but through 1966, his career-high in home runs was 20. Like
Greer, Yastrzemski was a line-drive hitter who used the entire
field.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after working extensively with Ted Williams, Yastrzemski
learned to pull more, especially in favorable counts, and he had
his breakthrough season in 1967, hitting .326 with 44 home runs and
121 RBI. He hit 40 home runs in 1969 and 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Musial didn't hit more than 19 home runs in his first five years
in the big leagues. But in 1948 he jumped to 39 home runs and
averaged 32 per year from 1948-54.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is being confident enough to be able to do that,''
said Greer, who said he never tries to hit a home run even though
he has hit some of the biggest for the Rangers in the past five
years. ``But once you're able to do that, I think it can start
snowballing.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Palmeiro: ``You look at Ken Griffey. He'll tell you he's
not a home-run hitter. But when he goes up to the plate, he can
envision a home run even before the pitcher has thrown the ball
because he's done it so many times before.''
</P>
<P>
   Yastrzemski, Musial and Greer have one thing in common. All
three hit a lot of doubles early in their careers. In the previous
four seasons before 1967, Yastrzemski averaged 38 doubles a year,
leading the league three times. Musial averaged 42 doubles in his
first five seasons. Greer has averaged 39 doubles a year for four
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shows me he's capable of hitting for more power,''
Palmeiro said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro was able to make his transformation without sacrificing
average or racking up high strikeout totals. He hit a career-high
47 home runs last year while hitting .324. He also walked 97 times
and only struck out 69 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pick my spots,'' Palmeiro said. ``I'm not a guy like (Jose)
Canseco, where's it's all or nothing. He's still a great hitter,
but if he's up there with runners at second and third, he still
going to try to pull the ball out of the ballpark. He's not going
to try and hit a line drive over second base.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro said the important thing is Greer is already a .300
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy who hits .300 can learn to hit with power,'' Palmeiro
said. ``It's almost impossible for a guy who hits for just power to
learn to hit .300.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Ivan Rodriguez had a similar breakthrough last year. A
.300 hitter the previous four seasons, Rodriguez hit .332 last year
but also went from a career-high 21 home runs in 1998 to 35. He
also drove in 113 runs which, combined with his defense, earned him
the American League's Most Valuable Player Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Pudge it was a combination of things,'' Rangers hitting
coach Rudy Jaramillo. ``His conditioning program helped make him
stronger, and his mechanics were smoother. But part of it, too, was
being more selective at the plate, looking for his pitch and
driving it.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer is among the best hitters in the game. Besides hitting
.300 or better in five of six seasons, he has scored at least 100
runs and driven in at least 100 runs in three of the past four
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But, while he remains the one of the most popular Rangers, he
has received little recognition nationally. He has not be selected
to the American League All-Star team, and honor usually reserved
for power hitters
</P>
<P>
   ``People who go to The Ballpark know what I can do,'' Greer
said. ``They know I'm going to go out there every night and perform
to the best of my ability. Not everybody can be a national name.
There are guys who are known nationally, and that's OK. I like to
blend in the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go quietly about your business, you get things
accomplished, almost like sneaking up on people. A good way to get
things done by surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Power hitters don't surprise people. Rusty Greer could in time.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
