<HEADLINE>
ATHLETES SPOTLIGHTED IN BATTERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER AND LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - It's happened again.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems to be happening all the time.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego Padres outfielder Al Martin, whose off-season home is
in the Phoenix area, was arrested Tues day, March 21, on domestic
violence charges.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Phoenix area's third incident of domestic violence
involv ing a professional sports athlete in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   One week before, Arizona Cardinals running back Mario Bates
spent a night in jail on two misdemeanor domestic violence charges.
</P>
<P>
   Former Arizona Diamondbacks pitcher Bobby Chouinard faces a more
serious charge after allegedly pulling a gun on his wife on
Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   Every few days, it seems, the na tional media report on another
professional or collegiate athlete get ting busted for beating up a
woman.
</P>
<P>
   But be careful, warns Richard Lap chick, director of
Northeastern Uni versity's Center for the Study of Sports in
Society: The prevailing public sentiment _ that college and
professional athletes are more prone to assault women _ is flat
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is not in any way with athletes,'' Lapchick said.
``The prob lem is American men.''
</P>
<P>
   Impressions of athletes are inspired by American media, he said,
which report on about two assaults weekly by sports professionals.
Each time a jock gets busted for hitting his wife or girlfriend,
Lapchick said, journal ists call in search of a trend story.
</P>
<P>
   What goes unreported, he added, are the 8,200 other batterings
and 2,014 other rapes.
</P>
<P>
   Lapchick said research clearly shows that athletes are more
likely to avoid arrest, conviction or severe penalties when they do
attack women. But that's also true of other wealthy males who can
afford good lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   He said there is truth to stereo-typi cal notions of locker-room
machismo which degrades women, and to the idea that athletes are
pampered and protected.
</P>
<P>
   Those attitudes clearly affect the romantic and sexual relations
be tween athletes and women, he added, but they don't translate
into higher rates of physical abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Lapchick said, most research ers have found that
assaults by males on females cross every professional, social,
racial and economic line.
</P>
<P>
   The O.J. Simpson murder case, more than any other, inspired
academic research and journalistic investiga tion of female assault
by high-level athletes.
</P>
<P>
   What investigators found, in most cases, was inconclusive. Some
re searchers reported evidence that jocks have a heightened
propensity for violence against women, but most said the athletic
celebrities merely got more publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Al Martin was arrested on domestic violence assault and threats
charges, both misdemeanors, while Shaun Haggerty-Martin, who claims
to be Martin's wife, was arrested for do mestic violence assault.
Both spent the night in the Scottsdale city jail and appeared
before a judge Tues day, March 21, morning.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale Police Sgt. Doug Dirren added that police are
investigating Haggerty-Martin's claim that Martin is married to
more than one woman. If so, Martin could face felony bigamy
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Haggerty-Martin also told police that Monday, March 20, wasn't
the first time she and Martin had fought. According to a police
report, she said when the two lived in Florida a couple of years
ago, he beat her severely, requiring her to go to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Since moving to Scottsdale in No vember, Haggerty-Martin added
they have had several fights, one in which Martin allegedly pinned
her to the bed, choking her and stuck the barrel of a gun in her
mouth, threatening to kill her.
</P>
<P>
   During Monday's, March 20, fight, she says Martin said, ``If you
cheat on me, lie to me, betray me, I will O.J. (you) so quick. I
will torture you. I'll tie you up and cut you and pour alcohol on
you.''
</P>
<P>
   San Diego general manager Kevin Towers said Tuesday, March 21,
he and Padres owner John Moores spent about 90 minutes with Martin
and the woman reported to be his other wife, Cathy. Towers
described Martin as ``not in a good emotional state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly don't condone domes tic violence,'' Towers said.
``It's unacceptable. But before we come down on Al, we want to get
all the facts from both sides of it before we discipline him.''
</P>
<P>
   Towers said to the best of his knowledge Haggerty-Martin is ``an
acquaintance (Martin) has known for four or five years since his
days in Pittsburgh'' and that they have ``had some problems in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Al's wife knows of her,'' Towers said. ``We did not get into
the depth of what has happened in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   After her release Tuesday, March 21, Haggerty-Martin _ who had a
large bruise on her chin _ declined to say whether Martin was still
married to his first wife.
</P>
<P>
   On the Padres' Internet site, Cathy is listed as Martin's wife
and the mother of his 8-year-old son, Bran don.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, acquired from the Pittsburgh Pirates on Feb. 23, was not
at Peoria Sports Complex on Tuesday, March 21, as the Padres won
over the Chicago Cubs. Towers said he ex pects Martin to take some
time off.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale police said they will inves tigate Haggerty-Martin's
claim of bigamy. Martin told police he at tended a ceremony with
her in Las Vegas in 1998 but did not believe it to be a real
wedding ceremony. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
