<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHURCH-VANDALISM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE PUZZLED BY ATTACKS ON CATHOLIC STATUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mcd) 
 By JUAN FORERO     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The vandalism appeared to be another in a disturbing
pattern of desecrations of Roman Catholic icons. And once more it
was in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   This time, a two-foot-high concrete statue of Jesus, its arms
detached, was discovered Tuesday morning on a patch of grass in
front of an Episcopal church in Park Slope.
</P>
<P>
   But hours later, after the police had strung crime-scene tape
and detectives had asked questions, investigators said that the
incident did not appear connected to a recent string of 11
anti-Catholic incidents in which sculptures throughout the borough
had been smashed or toppled.
</P>
<P>
   That conclusion, though, offered little comfort to Catholics
across Brooklyn, who since Sept. 26 have watched with consternation
and sadness as the faces of statues have been shattered, their arms
and hands torn off, in front of churches, convents, a Knights of
Columbus hall and even a private house.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Inspector Barbara Sicilia, the commander of the police
bias unit that has been investigating the vandalism, said
detectives believed the 11 desecrations were committed by one
individual or a group working together.
</P>
<P>
   Chips and markings from the statues have revealed, she said,
that the same ``hammer-type instrument'' and a ``chisel-type
instrument'' may have been used in all 11 previous cases.
</P>
<P>
   Sicilia said the latest incident did not appear to be connected
to the earlier ones because it did not involve a Catholic church
and because there was no mutilation of the statue. No one has
reported missing a figure of Christ like the one found Tuesday at
All Saint's Episcopal Church at 282 Seventh Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Sicilia said police officers throughout the borough have been
alerted to watch for the vandals, and patrols have been added on
weekend evenings, when most of the vandalism has taken place.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have also met with church officials and asked
parishioners to provide any tips or recollections of suspicious
activities. ``Everything that could be humanly thought of has been
done,'' Sicilia said. Evidence that might lead to a suspect,
though, has been scant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing we know is that every single one of these
attacks has been anti-Catholic,'' Sicilia said. ``What their
motivation is, what the thinking behind it is, we're open to any
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sacrilegious act,'' said Guylaine Bordes, a
longtime parishioner at St. Jerome Church on Newkirk Avenue, the
first church to report the defacing of a statue. ``It's almost like
you have a war with God, attacking him one on one.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the vandalized statues have been sculptures of the
Virgin Mary, but statues of Christ have also been defaced.
</P>
<P>
   In one incident in January at the Knights of Columbus hall in
Canarsie, a statue of Saint Pius X, who was pope from 1903 to 1914,
was decapitated. A sign found taped to the remains called the
current pope, John Paul II, ``Satan who deceives the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When it happened the first time, it was shock,'' said Msgr.
Rollin Darbouce, the pastor of Holy Cross Church, on Church Avenue,
where a 53-year-old statue of Mary was defaced last week. The
statue's face was smashed and its hands lopped off in the last act
of vandalism in the pattern. ``When it happened the second time,
it's indignation and rage and anger because you do not expect
something like that to happen in a civilized society.''
</P>
<P>
   Public officials, Catholic leaders and other concerned citizens
have offered rewards totaling $76,000 for information about the
vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one seems to have a clear explanation for the
incidents, some said they saw the vandalism as a vicious
desecration of sacred icons that was ``aimed at things that are
uniquely Catholic,'' said Patrick Scully, spokesman for the
Catholic League for Religious and Civil Rights, which monitors
anti-Catholic sentiment and actions.
</P>
<P>
   The statues ``have been there for years,'' he said, ``and they
mean a lot to people. This is an attack on people and the images
that they hold dear.''
</P>
<P>
   Louise Mottley, a parishioner at St. Francis of Assisi-St.
Blaise Church on Maple Street in East Flatbush for more than 20
years, said she and others at the church had been especially
disheartened that vandals struck their church twice.
</P>
<P>
   On the weekend of Jan. 8, someone lopped off the arms and heads
of statues of Our Lady of Fatima and St. Francis of Assisi.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on March 12, a wooden sculpture of Christ, which had been
mounted on a cross in front of the church, was found in pieces on
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts,'' Mottley said, likening the vandalism to someone
smashing photographs of her family. ``This is a part of the church.
This is what we grew up with. You cannot have a church without the
statues. This is what we know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
