<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-INTEL-WINNER-ART-N     03-21 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-INTEL-WINNER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL SCHOLARSHIP WINNER KNOWS `HARD WORK IS WHAT MATTERS'
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT30 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT WASHINGTON, N.Y. _ Don't open the refrigerator down in Room
37 in the basement of the research-minded Paul D. Schreiber High
School. What looks and smells like a science experiment going on in
there actually  &UR; is  &LR; a science experiment. But it doesn't belong to
Viviana Risca. Hers was made famous last week in Washington, where
she won the nationwide Intel Science Talent Search (and a $100,000
scholarship) with a project that encoded a secret message in a
strand of DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Except for her fanciful misconception that a computer mouse
would resemble a little gray rodent rather than a blob of plastic
(the reality, which descended in seventh-grade, was a
disappointment), Risca, a 17-year-old senior, has always been a
glutton for fact-finding. She first became ``a research groupie''
in ninth-grade, on the day a light went off in her head,
Edison-style. It happened during a class next door in Room 36 when
she figured out how DNA works: ``I fell in love with biology.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was a sophisticated student _ at her request, her
maternal grandparents read her Greek myths _ before she arrived in
New York in 1992 from Drumul Taberei, near Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
   A nervous third-grader who spoke only fragmentary English, she
was installed in the same grade, no remedial arrangements
necessary, in the Sachem district, on Long Island, just two days
after saying goodbye to her home, friends and, chaperoned by
grandma, taking her first international flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents threw me right into the waters _ they indoctrinated
me pretty early that hard work is what matters,'' says Risca. Her
parents, both engineers, left Romania ahead of her in 1991 and
pursued workaholic schedules here so that she and her younger
sister, Anca, would want for nothing, especially not a college
education.
</P>
<P>
   For Risca, a worrywart who recalls obsessing about the bill for
her college education ``ever since I was in elementary school,''
winning the top Intel prize over 39 other finalists has removed an
old stress and replaced it with new ones. Which college should she
attend, Stanford or Yale or MIT or Harvard or Princeton or ... you
get the problem. And if she goes to a science school like MIT, to
pursue a head-spinning double major in computer science and
biology, will she miss out on her second passion, the humanities?
</P>
<P>
   According to her, ``the depressing part'' of being the big
winner is this: Even $100,000 doesn't take care of the whole
enchilada anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents always tell me not to worry,'' she says in her
quick, accented English, ``but it's too late for that. I worry.
Sometimes I theorize that I should just go and be a farmer in the
Great Plains states.'' (That's a carry-over from weekend hikes in
the Carpathian Mountains with her grandparents, who taught her to
love nature.) Instead, she's on a path that carried five previous
winners of the competition to a Nobel Prize; might her
inquisitiveness take her that far?
</P>
<P>
   Hard to fathom; so is that $100,000 scholarship, which she's
still not sure she deserves. (Risca confesses that the Intel
project that impressed her most belonged to a Florida girl who,
without benefit of a mentor like hers, Dr. Carter Bancroft at Mt.
Sinai School of Medicine, created a poison for a weed that was
choking her community's fields.) ``The way she persevered, that's a
great example of a scientist following a theory to the end,'' she
says. Then again, Risca wasn't even sure she deserved the oil
paints she got one birthday: ``I'm not that good of a painter.''
</P>
<P>
   What she is sure about is the impatience that led her to ignore
the Nancy Drew books the rest of the third-graders devoured her
first season in America _ ``Once you've read one Nancy Drew, you've
read them all'' _ and sneak to the science shelf for a dose of
Isaac Asimov. Then came her determination to find the source of
pulsating variables in stars, a quest that took her to Columbia
University's physics library at 14, the same year she spent her
summer as an NYU lab intern trying to isolate a gene in a parasitic
organism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through a phase where I wanted to be a fashion
designer,'' she says. ``I had Barbie dolls, but I didn't play with
them. I made beaded outfits for them. But I outgrew it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Risca, a poetry aficionado, dresses like a '50s beatnik,
long hair pulled into a massive bun, plenty of black on black, the
hem of her jeans artfully frayed above a pair of low-top sneakers.
You were expecting, perhaps, a lab coat, horn rims, sensible
brogues, and a fistful of dissecting tools? Not for this fan of
Frost and Plath who edits her school's literary magazine when she's
not busy cooking up experiments for the contests that dot the
calendars of teen-age scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure from all over the place,'' Risca observes of the new
phenomenon of the teen-age science nerd as a hot recruiting
property. And the competitions! Her Intel booty, the scholarship
check and a laptop computer, are still in the mail, but Risca has
already entered this week's Long Island Science and Engineering
Fair at the State University of New York at Stony Brook.
</P>
<P>
   The new project is called ``Image Scale Estimation Using Genetic
Programming in Java.'' To Risca, who believes silicon chips will be
outmoded soon, Java is computer-speak, not a beverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to do with the way robots see,'' supplies Phyllis
Serfaty, a biology teacher who heads the special science research
program Risca entered in her sophomore year. ``But it's way out of
my league. That's Viviana.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
