<HEADLINE>
IOWA STATE WON'T BE BRUINS' ONLY TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ As if the UCLA Bruins don't have enough to
worry about this week with Iowa State, All-American Marcus Fizer
and the pressure of a Sweet 16 showdown, there's the small matter
of ... FINAL EXAMS.
</P>
<P>
   Winter-quarter finals are this week - both on campus and in the
Bruins' hotel near The Palace of Auburn Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always hard for quarter-system schools,'' UCLA athletic
director Peter Dalis said. ``It's a very difficult situation. But
the coaches and academic staff constantly talk to the kids about
time management.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins block time each day for study hall, tutoring and
exams. Academic counselor Mike Casillas, who works for the college
of letters and sciences, keeps the exams in sealed envelopes.
Unless time zones, practices or games conflict, the players take
exams at the same time they're administered on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, professors eschew road-trip exams and insist the
players take makeup tests when they return to campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is professor-specific,'' said associate athletic
director Betsy Stephenson, who oversees academic counseling. ``We
work with them and notify them at the beginning of each quarter
about each athlete's travel schedule. Traditionally, they're
flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the calendar, final exams usually conflict with the
second weekend of the NCAA Tournament, the Sweet 16 and Elite Eight
rounds. It's an odd way to celebrate. They returned from
Minneapolis late Saturday night, studied Sunday and Monday, then
left Tuesday morning for Auburn Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a couple finals Thursday and Friday, so I'll have to
take those on the road,'' freshman forward Jason Kapono said.
``We've got to play and take finals, so it's a full platter.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost a Cyclone: Bruins point guard Earl Watson was recruited
by former Iowa State coach Tim Floyd during his years at Washington
High in Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd is now the head coach of the Chicago Bulls, but he made a
lasting impression on Watson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iowa State was right there with UCLA from the beginning, but
I've wanted to play at UCLA since I was a kid,'' Watson said. ``I'm
proud of my decision and would never think about it again.''
</P>
<P>
   L.A. tie: Current Cyclones coach Larry Eustachy attended Arcadia
High, Citrus College and Long Beach State. Although he was a big
UCLA fan and wanted to play for coach John Wooden, he's never
wanted to coach in Westwood. He prefers the small-town pace of
Ames, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I grew up, UCLA always had tape-delayed games at 11 p.m.
on the march to 10 (NCAA) titles,'' Eustachy said. ``I remember the
days of Henry Bibby. There wasn't a player in the country who
didn't want to go to UCLA. I went to Citrus College as a
non-scholarship player - that's how close I was to UCLA. I thought
I should have played at UCLA, and I was the eighth man at a junior
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm a country boy. I grew up in L.A. and my parents live
there, but I like to live in places where you don't have prepay
gas. I like to pump and pay. Smaller towns are more my style.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
