<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES WON'T ALLOW COWBOYS TO FALL FROM NFL GRACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerry Jones had nothing to say Tuesday. Odd but true.
</P>
<P>
   When asked specifically about his old rivals, Eddie DeBartolo
and Carmen Policy, and about the ongoing tempest that swirls around
the San Francisco 49ers, the Cowboys owner took the high road and
sent word that he'd really rather not comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people that Jerry considers his `fraternity
brothers,' and he feels that any comment he might make would be
inappropriate,'' a Cowboys spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers franchise is in transition, which is a polite way of
saying their Super Bowl owner is facing a felony offense, the
family has been fighting over its $1.5 billion, and come Thursday,
a federal judge in Minneapolis is going to help decide whether the
Niners cheated the NFL salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Oh. Did I mention the 49ers finished 4-12 last year?
</P>
<P>
   The free-fall in San Francisco might not be over yet, depending
on what NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue is empowered by the judge
to do in the salary-cap scandal. The new 49ers owner, Denise
DeBartolo York, and her husband, John York, turned in the former
front office for irregularities in the contracts of quarterback
Steve Young, former tight end Brent Jones and former backup QB Jim
Druckenmiller.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, both the players' agents and the team could be fined
as much as $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   But that's only the closing credits. The better story here is
that a proud franchise with a glorious Super Bowl heritage has
somehow gone down the porcelain bowl.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're a Cowboys fan, reading each day's episode, you
have to wonder: Could the Cowboys be the next 49ers?
</P>
<P>
   The happenings of this off-season loudly suggest that there's
not a chance. Amid speculation, some of it fueled by the owner
himself, that the Cowboys would enjoy a winter of frugal, more
measured spending, Jerry Jones has wheeled and dealed and spent the
franchise back into playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's signing of defensive lineman Alonzo Spellman was but
another example. With defensive end Greg Ellis' status still
uncertain after breaking a leg, the Cowboys could not afford to see
their line further disrupted by Spellman signing with the Green Bay
Packers.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, since they meekly excused themselves from the postseason in
January, the Cowboys have lost Randall Godfrey, Kavika Pittman,
Jason Garrett and Eric Bjornson, and the departure of Deion Sanders
is imminent. But they added the most notable free agent available,
receiver Joey Galloway, and then signed cornerback Ryan McNeil and
tight end Jackie Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Count Do-Rag, the self-indulgent Sanders, the
Cowboys will go to training camp in July with more weapons on
offense and a capable fill-in for Deion in the fold.
</P>
<P>
   None of these moves will send Jones into bankruptcy court. He
has prospered financially mostly by being able to renegotiate
veterans' contracts and prorating signing bonuses. Jones has done
it with an eye toward the NFL's salary cap, both its current
ceiling and tomorrow's.
</P>
<P>
   It will be intriguing to see the particulars that spill out
Thursday in court in the 49ers' cap-cheating case. Two of the
agents involved, Leigh Steinberg and Jeff Moorad, know Jones and
the Cowboys well.
</P>
<P>
   Where Jones seemed to differ from Carmen Policy, DeBartolo's
former club president, is in knowing how much and how far to string
out the players' deferred payments. As a member of the NFL's
broadcasting committee and an oil wild-catter at heart, Jones has
correctly gauged the growth in the league's salary cap and spent
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, four of the five networks delivering NFL games
complained about declining audiences. Some owners wondered if a
prudent gesture wouldn't be giving the networks a rebate.
</P>
<P>
   Jones nearly choked. He urged the committee to swing open the
negotiations to other networks.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting eight-year, $17.6 billion deal delivers Jones and
each NFL owner $73.3 million per season. Jones has elected to turn
a significant portion of that back into signing bonuses each
season.
</P>
<P>
   The team will take a $3.2 million salary-cap hit when Sanders is
released in early June. The retirements of Daryl Johnston and
Michael Irvin would cost them another $2 million. But other than
the contracts of Troy Aikman, Emmitt Smith and Darren Woodson,
Jones will not be paying millions to a ``team'' already past its
Cowboys years. He learned that lesson when Jay Novacek, Charles
Haley and Tony Tolbert were forced to retire prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, the DeBartolos announced that a settlement had
been reached in their long and bitter feud. The sister and her
husband get the 49ers and their planned new stadium on Candlestick
Point. Eddie, the brother, gets a turn in a Baton Rouge, La.,
court, where he is soon to testify in the extortion trial of
ex-governor Edwin Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers, last time I checked, were still 4-12.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, five years ago, some of us were predicting that that
same fate awaited the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   At Valley Ranch, it has been a busy two months. But the owner
had nothing to say about that or his ``fraternity brothers''
Tuesday. He didn't have to. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0454 </DOCNO>
