<SLUG> BC-ADAM'S-MARK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROJECT EQUALITY TO OVERSEE ADAM'S MARK HOTELS' COMPLIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Adam's Mark hotel chain agreed Tuesday to settle racial
discrimination lawsuits brought by the U.S. Justice Department and
others. Project Equality, a small nonprofit agency based in Kansas
City, was chosen to monitor the hotel's compliance with the
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's Mark Hotels &AMP; Resorts, based in St. Louis, has 21
properties in 14 states, including the Adam's Mark near the Truman
Sports Complex. The company was sued last year by the government
and private plaintiffs, including the NAACP, over alleged
discriminatory practices.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations stemmed from incidents last spring in Daytona
Beach, Fla., when guests at a black college reunion alleged they
were singled out as security risks and required to wear bright
orange wristbands.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's Mark agreed to pay $4.4 million in damages to reunion
guests and $1.5 million to the state of Florida to establish
scholarships as well as hotel and hospitality management
internships at four historically black colleges.
</P>
<P>
   It was the largest and most comprehensive settlement ever of a
racial bias case involving hotels, attorneys said. The settlement
terms still must get the approval of a Florida federal district
judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adam's Mark is committed to equality and has never
intentionally done anything wrong,'' President and Chief Executive
Fred Kummer said Tuesday. ``We apologize for any actions that may
have made any of our guests feel uncomfortable or unwelcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, at a Washington news conference,
hailed the agreement as ``a model for the future'' and said Adam's
Mark ``is the first hotel chain of its kind to take such
comprehensive affirmative steps to prevent discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Kweisi Mfume, president of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, said in Baltimore that ``with this
agreement, the call for economic sanctions against the hotel chain
has been suspended.''The NAACP helped bring the private lawsuit and
has urged people to boycott the chain.
</P>
<P>
   The government selected Project Equality, a 35-year-old,
church-based nonprofit agency, to act as its compliance officer
during the four-year settlement period.
</P>
<P>
   The agency will investigate complaints, design and monitor
diversity and nondiscrimination training programs for 9,000 Adam's
Mark employees, oversee ``secret shopper'' tests to ensure
compliance, and develop a marketing plan to reach
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The monitoring role is one of the largest tasks ever undertaken
by Project Equality, said Kirk P. Perucca, its president and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   The organization conducts workplace audits and provides
diversity training for its members and others, including scores of
churches, national and regional religious organizations, the
American Federation of Teachers, the National Education Association
and the YWCA of the USA.
</P>
<P>
   It also publishes an annual buyer's guide of goods and services
that lists more than 3,000 companies that meet Project Equality's
diverse work-force standards.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's Mark hotels have been listed in the buyers guide since
1987 and last year became a $1,000 annual corporate sponsor of
Project Equality, Perucca said.
</P>
<P>
   The still-undetermined value of the Adam's Mark monitoring
contract for the government will likely dwarf Project Equality's
annual budget of around $300,000. More employees will be hired to
supplement the full-time staff of five.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new opportunity for us,'' Perucca said at a news
conference Tuesday in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the undertaking in 14 cities, Perucca said his staff was
undaunted and experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand what discrimination is all about,'' he said.
``Our goal is to make sure Adam's Mark values every guest that
walks through their doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Project Equality was retained by Adam's Mark last year in the
wake of the lawsuits to audit its policies and practices and
conduct training for workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department on Dec. 16 charged Adam's Mark with
discriminatory practices, alleging that black guests were being
charged more than whites, often for less-desirable rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The same day, the Florida attorney general filed a motion to
intervene in the NAACP's class-action lawsuit filed in May alleging
that Adam's Mark discriminated against black college reunion
visitors last April.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Adam's Mark noted Tuesday that the chain's
Daytona Beach hotel later this month will be a host location for
the annual black college reunion gathering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
