<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPEAL OF GAS TAX IS A NO-WIN SITUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congress apparently has dropped its bid to repeal the
4.3-cent-per-gallon fuel tax to help motorists pinched by rising
pump prices.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons make sense but also reveal how tax policy is often a
no-win situation for those paying the taxes.
</P>
<P>
   When the tax was imposed, it was to ameliorate record budget
deficits. The deficit problem abated, but the tax was retained to
finance transportation outlays. Proponents claim the revenue is
still needed even though much of the fuel tax money isn't being
used for its intended purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the strongest economic argument against repeal is that
it would make it easier for OPEC to keep oil prices high. Another
argument, noted in an analysis by the House Transportation
Committee, was that eliminating the tax wouldn't necessarily
translate into lower pump prices. This is especially so for this
particular tax. It isn't collected at the pump, but just after it
leaves the refinery. Thus it's highly questionable whether all the
intermediaries involved from production to pump would pass along
the savings instead of pocketing it.
</P>
<P>
   As much sense as these arguments make, they also raise a
compelling question: Why do those elected to represent our
interests devise taxes whose repeal seem to benefit everyone except
those who pay the tax?
</P>
<P>
   This tax's supporters have an answer for that question too. It
would cost us jobs and money. Repeal would mean the loss of 840,000
high-paying jobs in 2002 and 2003. Tens of millions of dollars in
spending on construction equipment and materials also would be
lost. Speaking of money, a breakdown by transport committee
analysts shows Missouri losing $460 million in highway funds in
2002 and 2003 and Kansas losing almost $217 million. All states
would lose a grand total of nearly $19 billion over those two
years.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this is the worst of all worlds. OPEC's pricing
hand is strengthened, upward of a million good jobs are lost, and
states lose infusions of billions critical to improving
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   All of which raises several other questions. What happened
before the advent of this tax? What happened after 1993 that made
this tax so critical to our well-being? Most important, why not
just cash in IOUs from the Highway Trust Fund to cover losses from
the tax's repeal?
</P>
<P>
   The trust fund, after all, has swelled from $9 billion to $24
billion since the mid-1990s. Isn't this a good time to dip into
this rainy day ``savings''?
</P>
<P>
   The committee report addresses this option by noting it would
require ``using most of the non-Social Security budget surplus for
transportation (needs).''
</P>
<P>
   What, you may ask, has the non-Social Security surplus got to do
with it? Well, this surplus is the most obvious source of funds
needed to redeem the Treasury IOUs constituting the Highway Trust
Fund. There's no real money in the fund, which means real money
must come from elsewhere in the budget to cash in the IOUs.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to the $15 billion in pump taxes collected that
were transformed into trust fund IOUs instead of paying for
transportation stuff? It was spent on general budget outlays.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, taxpaying Americans were left holding a bagful of
government debt in the form of trust fund chits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-00 2359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000321.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-21 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4254 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SPELLMAN-     03-21 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SPELLMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPELLMAN AGREES TO MULTIYEAR DEAL WITH COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ In signing defensive lineman Alonzo Spellman to
a one-year deal during training camp last year, Dallas Cowboys
owner Jerry Jones acknowledged he was taking a risk on a player
with a troubled past.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys and Spellman, 28, were rewarded for their gamble
Tuesday when the two sides came to an agreement on a new multiyear
contract. Details of the contract were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The former Ohio State star was unavailable for comment
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success he enjoyed and the contributions he made was
beyond anything I could have expected,'' Jones said. ``This is one
of the real positive sports stories about an individual being
challenged and meeting those challenges. This deal is justified in
terms of what he did for the team, how he played and how we expect
him to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement culminates a glorious comeback for Spellman. The
eight-year veteran played with the Bears from 1992-1997 before
sitting out the 1998 season after a string of bizarre off-the-field
incidents stemming from his battle with bipolar disorder, a mental
disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Spellman _ who originally chose the Cowboys because
of the support programs provided by the team's behavioral
department _ not have any problems last season, but he made a
successful move from defensive end to defensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Initially thought of as a fill-in for suspended defensive tackle
Leon Lett, Spellman played so well that Lett couldn't supplant him
as the starter when he returned midway through the season. Spellman
led the Cowboys with 22 quarterback pressures, tied for second with
five sacks and totaled 43 tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Dave Campo has been ``pleasantly surprised'' with
Spellman.. ``He was a good football player prior to getting to
Dallas,'' Campo said. But we didn't know what to expect. We are
fortunate that he has made the progress he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Spellman's presence makes the Cowboys' tackle rotation, which
also includes Lett and Chad Hennings, the strength of the defense.
Campo said Hennings and Spellman will be the starters heading into
training camp, though both will be challenged by Lett.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is also hoping Spellman can be an influence on newly
signed defensive end Dimitrius Underwood, who is trying to resume
his career after a series of troubles in 1999, including a suicide
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question in my mind that he'll be a big influence
on a guy like Dimitrius,'' Jones said. ``How could it not be? A guy
that had to resurrect his career.'' HARRIS LOOKING TO BE STARTER
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones emphasized Friday that the signing of tight end
Jackie Harris had no impact on David LaFleur's status as the
starter.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Harris would serve as a complement to LaFleur, as an
H-back.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference to introduce himself to the local media
yesterday, Harris, 32, emphasized that he chose the Cowboys over
his old team, the Tennessee Titans, because he was told he would be
given a chance to supplant the maligned LaFleur as the starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told that if you produce, then it's a job that could
be yours,'' Harris said. ``David is the starter. Either David will
be better or he won't he the starter. All I wanted was a chance to
be the starter.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Kevin Smith is in the process of turning part of his $1.885
million base salary for next season into bonus money to help the
Cowboys with the salary cap. The Cowboys are also reworking the
contracts of other players.
</P>
<P>
